time I give him the chance to be a father. Tell him God Himself sends him
this chance.вЂќ

вЂњMitya, he wonвЂ™t give it for anything.вЂќ

вЂњI know he wonвЂ™t. I know it perfectly well. Now, especially. ThatвЂ™s not
all. I know something more. Now, only a few days ago, perhaps only
yesterday he found out for the first time _in earnest_ (underline _in
earnest_) that Grushenka is really perhaps not joking, and really means to
marry me. He knows her nature; he knows the cat. And do you suppose heвЂ™s
going to give me money to help to bring that about when heвЂ™s crazy about
her himself? And thatвЂ™s not all, either. I can tell you more than that. I
know that for the last five days he has had three thousand drawn out of
the bank, changed into notes of a hundred roubles, packed into a large
envelope, sealed with five seals, and tied across with red tape. You see
how well I know all about it! On the envelope is written: вЂTo my angel,
Grushenka, when she will come to me.вЂ™ He scrawled it himself in silence
and in secret, and no one knows that the moneyвЂ™s there except the valet,
Smerdyakov, whom he trusts like himself. So now he has been expecting
Grushenka for the last three or four days; he hopes sheвЂ™ll come for the
money. He has sent her word of it, and she has sent him word that perhaps
sheвЂ™ll come. And if she does go to the old man, can I marry her after
that? You understand now why IвЂ™m here in secret and what IвЂ™m on the watch
for.вЂќ

вЂњFor her?вЂќ

вЂњYes, for her. Foma has a room in the house of these sluts here. Foma
comes from our parts; he was a soldier in our regiment. He does jobs for
them. HeвЂ™s watchman at night and goes grouseвЂђshooting in the dayвЂђtime; and
thatвЂ™s how he lives. IвЂ™ve established myself in his room. Neither he nor
the women of the house know the secretвЂ”that is, that I am on the watch
here.вЂќ

вЂњNo one but Smerdyakov knows, then?вЂќ

вЂњNo one else. He will let me know if she goes to the old man.вЂќ

вЂњIt was he told you about the money, then?вЂќ

вЂњYes. ItвЂ™s a dead secret. Even Ivan doesnвЂ™t know about the money, or
anything. The old man is sending Ivan to Tchermashnya on a two or three
daysвЂ™ journey. A purchaser has turned up for the copse: heвЂ™ll give eight
thousand for the timber. So the old man keeps asking Ivan to help him by
going to arrange it. It will take him two or three days. ThatвЂ™s what the
old man wants, so that Grushenka can come while heвЂ™s away.вЂќ

вЂњThen heвЂ™s expecting Grushenka toвЂђday?вЂќ

вЂњNo, she wonвЂ™t come toвЂђday; there are signs. SheвЂ™s certain not to come,вЂќ
cried Mitya suddenly. вЂњSmerdyakov thinks so, too. FatherвЂ™s drinking now.
HeвЂ™s sitting at table with Ivan. Go to him, Alyosha, and ask for the three
thousand.вЂќ

вЂњMitya, dear, whatвЂ™s the matter with you?вЂќ cried Alyosha, jumping up from
his place, and looking keenly at his brotherвЂ™s frenzied face. For one
moment the thought struck him that Dmitri was mad.

вЂњWhat is it? IвЂ™m not insane,вЂќ said Dmitri, looking intently and earnestly
at him. вЂњNo fear. I am sending you to father, and I know what IвЂ™m saying.
I believe in miracles.вЂќ

вЂњIn miracles?вЂќ

вЂњIn a miracle of Divine Providence. God knows my heart. He sees my
despair. He sees the whole picture. Surely He wonвЂ™t let something awful
happen. Alyosha, I believe in miracles. Go!вЂќ

вЂњI am going. Tell me, will you wait for me here?вЂќ

вЂњYes. I know it will take some time. You canвЂ™t go at him point blank. HeвЂ™s
drunk now. IвЂ™ll wait three hoursвЂ”four, five, six, seven. Only remember you
must go to Katerina Ivanovna toвЂђday, if it has to be at midnight, _with
the money or without the money_, and say, вЂHe sends his compliments to
you.вЂ™ I want you to say that verse to her: вЂHe sends his compliments to
you.вЂ™ вЂќ

вЂњMitya! And what if Grushenka comes toвЂђdayвЂ”if not toвЂђday, toвЂђmorrow, or
the next day?вЂќ

вЂњGrushenka? I shall see her. I shall rush out and prevent it.вЂќ

вЂњAnd ifвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњIf thereвЂ™s an if, it will be murder. I couldnвЂ™t endure it.вЂќ

вЂњWho will be murdered?вЂќ

вЂњThe old man. I shanвЂ™t kill her.вЂќ

вЂњBrother, what are you saying?вЂќ

вЂњOh, I donвЂ™t know.... I donвЂ™t know. Perhaps I shanвЂ™t kill, and perhaps I
shall. IвЂ™m afraid that he will suddenly become so loathsome to me with his
face at that moment. I hate his ugly throat, his nose, his eyes, his
shameless snigger. I feel a physical repulsion. ThatвЂ™s what IвЂ™m afraid of.
ThatвЂ™s what may be too much for me.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll go, Mitya. I believe that God will order things for the best, that
nothing awful may happen.вЂќ

вЂњAnd I will sit and wait for the miracle. And if it doesnвЂ™t come to passвЂ”вЂќ

Alyosha went thoughtfully towards his fatherвЂ™s house.



Chapter VI. Smerdyakov


He did in fact find his father still at table. Though there was a diningвЂђ
room in the house, the table was laid as usual in the drawingвЂђroom, which
was the largest room, and furnished with oldвЂђfashioned ostentation. The
furniture was white and very old, upholstered in old, red, silky material.
In the spaces between the windows there were mirrors in elaborate white
and gilt frames, of oldвЂђfashioned carving. On the walls, covered with
white paper, which was torn in many places, there hung two large
portraitsвЂ”one of some prince who had been governor of the district thirty
years before, and the other of some bishop, also long since dead. In the
corner opposite the door there were several ikons, before which a lamp was
lighted at nightfall ... not so much for devotional purposes as to light
the room. Fyodor Pavlovitch used to go to bed very late, at three or four
oвЂ™clock in the morning, and would wander about the room at night or sit in
an armвЂђchair, thinking. This had become a habit with him. He often slept
quite alone in the house, sending his servants to the lodge; but usually
Smerdyakov remained, sleeping on a bench in the hall.

When Alyosha came in, dinner was over, but coffee and preserves had been
served. Fyodor Pavlovitch liked sweet things with brandy after dinner.
Ivan was also at table, sipping coffee. The servants, Grigory and
Smerdyakov, were standing by. Both the gentlemen and the servants seemed
in singularly good spirits. Fyodor Pavlovitch was roaring with laughter.
Before he entered the room, Alyosha heard the shrill laugh he knew so
well, and could tell from the sound of it that his father had only reached
the goodвЂђhumored stage, and was far from being completely drunk.

вЂњHere he is! Here he is!вЂќ yelled Fyodor Pavlovitch, highly delighted at
seeing Alyosha. вЂњJoin us. Sit down. Coffee is a lenten dish, but itвЂ™s hot
and good. I donвЂ™t offer you brandy, youвЂ™re keeping the fast. But would you
like some? No; IвЂ™d better give you some of our famous liqueur. Smerdyakov,
go to the cupboard, the second shelf on the right. Here are the keys. Look
sharp!вЂќ

Alyosha began refusing the liqueur.

вЂњNever mind. If you wonвЂ™t have it, we will,вЂќ said Fyodor Pavlovitch,
beaming. вЂњBut stayвЂ”have you dined?вЂќ

вЂњYes,вЂќ answered Alyosha, who had in truth only eaten a piece of bread and
drunk a glass of kvas in the Father SuperiorвЂ™s kitchen. вЂњThough I should
be pleased to have some hot coffee.вЂќ

вЂњBravo, my darling! HeвЂ™ll have some coffee. Does it want warming? No, itвЂ™s
boiling. ItвЂ™s capital coffee: SmerdyakovвЂ™s making. My SmerdyakovвЂ™s an
artist at coffee and at fish patties, and at fish soup, too. You must come
one day and have some fish soup. Let me know beforehand.... But, stay;
didnвЂ™t I tell you this morning to come home with your mattress and pillow
and all? Have you brought your mattress? He he he!вЂќ

вЂњNo, I havenвЂ™t,вЂќ said Alyosha, smiling, too.

вЂњAh, but you were frightened, you were frightened this morning, werenвЂ™t
you? There, my darling, I couldnвЂ™t do anything to vex you. Do you know,
Ivan, I canвЂ™t resist the way he looks one straight in the face and laughs?
It makes me laugh all over. IвЂ™m so fond of him. Alyosha, let me give you
my blessingвЂ”a fatherвЂ™s blessing.вЂќ

Alyosha rose, but Fyodor Pavlovitch had already changed his mind.

вЂњNo, no,вЂќ he said. вЂњIвЂ™ll just make the sign of the cross over you, for
now. Sit still. Now weвЂ™ve a treat for you, in your own line, too. ItвЂ™ll
make you laugh. BalaamвЂ™s ass has begun talking to us hereвЂ”and how he
talks! How he talks!вЂќ

BalaamвЂ™s ass, it appeared, was the valet, Smerdyakov. He was a young man
of about four and twenty, remarkably unsociable and taciturn. Not that he
was shy or bashful. On the contrary, he was conceited and seemed to
despise everybody.

But we must pause to say a few words about him now. He was brought up by
Grigory and Marfa, but the boy grew up вЂњwith no sense of gratitude,вЂќ as
Grigory expressed it; he was an unfriendly boy, and seemed to look at the
world mistrustfully. In his childhood he was very fond of hanging cats,
and burying them with great ceremony. He used to dress up in a sheet as
though it were a surplice, and sang, and waved some object over the dead
cat as though it were a censer. All this he did on the sly, with the
greatest secrecy. Grigory caught him once at this diversion and gave him a
sound beating. He shrank into a corner and sulked there for a week. вЂњHe
doesnвЂ™t care for you or me, the monster,вЂќ Grigory used to say to Marfa,
вЂњand he doesnвЂ™t care for any one. Are you a human being?вЂќ he said,
addressing the boy directly. вЂњYouвЂ™re not a human being. You grew from the
mildew in the bathвЂђhouse.(2) ThatвЂ™s what you are.вЂќ Smerdyakov, it appeared
afterwards, could never forgive him those words. Grigory taught him to
read and write, and when he was twelve years old, began teaching him the
Scriptures. But this teaching came to nothing. At the second or third
lesson the boy suddenly grinned.

вЂњWhatвЂ™s that for?вЂќ asked Grigory, looking at him threateningly from under
his spectacles.

вЂњOh, nothing. God created light on the first day, and the sun, moon, and
stars on the fourth day. Where did the light come from on the first day?вЂќ

Grigory was thunderstruck. The boy looked sarcastically at his teacher.
There was something positively condescending in his expression. Grigory
could not restrain himself. вЂњIвЂ™ll show you where!вЂќ he cried, and gave the
boy a violent slap on the cheek. The boy took the slap without a word, but
withdrew into his corner again for some days. A week later he had his
first attack of the disease to which he was subject all the rest of his
lifeвЂ”epilepsy. When Fyodor Pavlovitch heard of it, his attitude to the boy
seemed changed at once. Till then he had taken no notice of him, though he
never scolded him, and always gave him a copeck when he met him.
Sometimes, when he was in good humor, he would send the boy something
sweet from his table. But as soon as he heard of his illness, he showed an
active interest in him, sent for a doctor, and tried remedies, but the
disease turned out to be incurable. The fits occurred, on an average, once
a month, but at various intervals. The fits varied too, in violence: some
were light and some were very severe. Fyodor Pavlovitch strictly forbade
Grigory to use corporal punishment to the boy, and began allowing him to
come upstairs to him. He forbade him to be taught anything whatever for a
time, too. One day when the boy was about fifteen, Fyodor Pavlovitch
noticed him lingering by the bookcase, and reading the titles through the
glass. Fyodor Pavlovitch had a fair number of booksвЂ”over a hundredвЂ”but no
one ever saw him reading. He at once gave Smerdyakov the key of the
bookcase. вЂњCome, read. You shall be my librarian. YouвЂ™ll be better sitting
reading than hanging about the courtyard. Come, read this,вЂќ and Fyodor
Pavlovitch gave him _Evenings in a Cottage near Dikanka_.

He read a little but didnвЂ™t like it. He did not once smile, and ended by
frowning.

вЂњWhy? IsnвЂ™t it funny?вЂќ asked Fyodor Pavlovitch.

Smerdyakov did not speak.

вЂњAnswer, stupid!вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s all untrue,вЂќ mumbled the boy, with a grin.

вЂњThen go to the devil! You have the soul of a lackey. Stay, hereвЂ™s
SmaragdovвЂ™s _Universal History_. ThatвЂ™s all true. Read that.вЂќ

But Smerdyakov did not get through ten pages of Smaragdov. He thought it
dull. So the bookcase was closed again.

Shortly afterwards Marfa and Grigory reported to Fyodor Pavlovitch that
Smerdyakov was gradually beginning to show an extraordinary
fastidiousness. He would sit before his soup, take up his spoon and look
into the soup, bend over it, examine it, take a spoonful and hold it to
the light.

вЂњWhat is it? A beetle?вЂќ Grigory would ask.

вЂњA fly, perhaps,вЂќ observed Marfa.

The squeamish youth never answered, but he did the same with his bread,
his meat, and everything he ate. He would hold a piece on his fork to the
light, scrutinize it microscopically, and only after long deliberation
decide to put it in his mouth.

вЂњAch! What fine gentlemenвЂ™s airs!вЂќ Grigory muttered, looking at him.

When Fyodor Pavlovitch heard of this development in Smerdyakov he
determined to make him his cook, and sent him to Moscow to be trained. He
spent some years there and came back remarkably changed in appearance. He
looked extraordinarily old for his age. His face had grown wrinkled,
yellow, and strangely emasculate. In character he seemed almost exactly
the same as before he went away. He was just as unsociable, and showed not
the slightest inclination for any companionship. In Moscow, too, as we
heard afterwards, he had always been silent. Moscow itself had little
interest for him; he saw very little there, and took scarcely any notice
of anything. He went once to the theater, but returned silent and
displeased with it. On the other hand, he came back to us from Moscow well
dressed, in a clean coat and clean linen. He brushed his clothes most
scrupulously twice a day invariably, and was very fond of cleaning his
smart calf boots with a special English polish, so that they shone like
mirrors. He turned out a firstвЂђrate cook. Fyodor Pavlovitch paid him a
salary, almost the whole of which Smerdyakov spent on clothes, pomade,
perfumes, and such things. But he seemed to have as much contempt for the
female sex as for men; he was discreet, almost unapproachable, with them.
Fyodor Pavlovitch began to regard him rather differently. His fits were
becoming more frequent, and on the days he was ill Marfa cooked, which did
not suit Fyodor Pavlovitch at all.

вЂњWhy are your fits getting worse?вЂќ asked Fyodor Pavlovitch, looking
askance at his new cook. вЂњWould you like to get married? Shall I find you
a wife?вЂќ

But Smerdyakov turned pale with anger, and made no reply. Fyodor
Pavlovitch left him with an impatient gesture. The great thing was that he
had absolute confidence in his honesty. It happened once, when Fyodor
Pavlovitch was drunk, that he dropped in the muddy courtyard three
hundredвЂђrouble notes which he had only just received. He only missed them
next day, and was just hastening to search his pockets when he saw the
notes lying on the table. Where had they come from? Smerdyakov had picked
them up and brought them in the day before.

вЂњWell, my lad, IвЂ™ve never met any one like you,вЂќ Fyodor Pavlovitch said
shortly, and gave him ten roubles. We may add that he not only believed in
his honesty, but had, for some reason, a liking for him, although the
young man looked as morosely at him as at every one and was always silent.
He rarely spoke. If it had occurred to any one to wonder at the time what
the young man was interested in, and what was in his mind, it would have
been impossible to tell by looking at him. Yet he used sometimes to stop
suddenly in the house, or even in the yard or street, and would stand
still for ten minutes, lost in thought. A physiognomist studying his face
would have said that there was no thought in it, no reflection, but only a
sort of contemplation. There is a remarkable picture by the painter
Kramskoy, called вЂњContemplation.вЂќ There is a forest in winter, and on a
roadway through the forest, in absolute solitude, stands a peasant in a
torn kaftan and bark shoes. He stands, as it were, lost in thought. Yet he
is not thinking; he is вЂњcontemplating.вЂќ If any one touched him he would
start and look at one as though awakening and bewildered. ItвЂ™s true he
would come to himself immediately; but if he were asked what he had been
thinking about, he would remember nothing. Yet probably he has, hidden
within himself, the impression which had dominated him during the period
of contemplation. Those impressions are dear to him and no doubt he hoards
them imperceptibly, and even unconsciously. How and why, of course, he
does not know either. He may suddenly, after hoarding impressions for many
years, abandon everything and go off to Jerusalem on a pilgrimage for his
soulвЂ™s salvation, or perhaps he will suddenly set fire to his native
village, and perhaps do both. There are a good many вЂњcontemplativesвЂќ among
the peasantry. Well, Smerdyakov was probably one of them, and he probably
was greedily hoarding up his impressions, hardly knowing why.



Chapter VII. The Controversy


But BalaamвЂ™s ass had suddenly spoken. The subject was a strange one.
Grigory had gone in the morning to make purchases, and had heard from the
shopkeeper Lukyanov the story of a Russian soldier which had appeared in
the newspaper of that day. This soldier had been taken prisoner in some
remote part of Asia, and was threatened with an immediate agonizing death
if he did not renounce Christianity and follow Islam. He refused to deny
his faith, and was tortured, flayed alive, and died, praising and
glorifying Christ. Grigory had related the story at table. Fyodor
Pavlovitch always liked, over the dessert after dinner, to laugh and talk,
if only with Grigory. This afternoon he was in a particularly goodвЂђhumored
and expansive mood. Sipping his brandy and listening to the story, he
observed that they ought to make a saint of a soldier like that, and to
take his skin to some monastery. вЂњThat would make the people flock, and
bring the money in.вЂќ

Grigory frowned, seeing that Fyodor Pavlovitch was by no means touched,
but, as usual, was beginning to scoff. At that moment Smerdyakov, who was
standing by the door, smiled. Smerdyakov often waited at table towards the
end of dinner, and since IvanвЂ™s arrival in our town he had done so every
day.

вЂњWhat are you grinning at?вЂќ asked Fyodor Pavlovitch, catching the smile
instantly, and knowing that it referred to Grigory.

вЂњWell, my opinion is,вЂќ Smerdyakov began suddenly and unexpectedly in a
loud voice, вЂњthat if that laudable soldierвЂ™s exploit was so very great
there would have been, to my thinking, no sin in it if he had on such an
emergency renounced, so to speak, the name of Christ and his own
christening, to save by that same his life, for good deeds, by which, in
the course of years to expiate his cowardice.вЂќ

вЂњHow could it not be a sin? YouвЂ™re talking nonsense. For that youвЂ™ll go
straight to hell and be roasted there like mutton,вЂќ put in Fyodor
Pavlovitch.

It was at this point that Alyosha came in, and Fyodor Pavlovitch, as we
have seen, was highly delighted at his appearance.

вЂњWeвЂ™re on your subject, your subject,вЂќ he chuckled gleefully, making
Alyosha sit down to listen.

вЂњAs for mutton, thatвЂ™s not so, and thereвЂ™ll be nothing there for this, and
there shouldnвЂ™t be either, if itвЂ™s according to justice,вЂќ Smerdyakov
maintained stoutly.

вЂњHow do you mean вЂaccording to justiceвЂ™?вЂќ Fyodor Pavlovitch cried still
more gayly, nudging Alyosha with his knee.

вЂњHeвЂ™s a rascal, thatвЂ™s what he is!вЂќ burst from Grigory. He looked
Smerdyakov wrathfully in the face.

вЂњAs for being a rascal, wait a little, Grigory Vassilyevitch,вЂќ answered
Smerdyakov with perfect composure. вЂњYouвЂ™d better consider yourself that,
once I am taken prisoner by the enemies of the Christian race, and they
demand from me to curse the name of God and to renounce my holy
christening, I am fully entitled to act by my own reason, since there
would be no sin in it.вЂќ

вЂњBut youвЂ™ve said that before. DonвЂ™t waste words. Prove it,вЂќ cried Fyodor
Pavlovitch.

вЂњSoupвЂђmaker!вЂќ muttered Grigory contemptuously.

вЂњAs for being a soupвЂђmaker, wait a bit, too, and consider for yourself,
Grigory Vassilyevitch, without abusing me. For as soon as I say to those
enemies, вЂNo, IвЂ™m not a Christian, and I curse my true God,вЂ™ then at once,
by GodвЂ™s high judgment, I become immediately and specially anathema
accursed, and am cut off from the Holy Church, exactly as though I were a
heathen, so that at that very instant, not only when I say it aloud, but
when I think of saying it, before a quarter of a second has passed, I am
cut off. Is that so or not, Grigory Vassilyevitch?вЂќ

He addressed Grigory with obvious satisfaction, though he was really
answering Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s questions, and was well aware of it, and
intentionally pretending that Grigory had asked the questions.

вЂњIvan,вЂќ cried Fyodor Pavlovitch suddenly, вЂњstoop down for me to whisper.
HeвЂ™s got this all up for your benefit. He wants you to praise him. Praise
him.вЂќ

Ivan listened with perfect seriousness to his fatherвЂ™s excited whisper.

вЂњStay, Smerdyakov, be quiet a minute,вЂќ cried Fyodor Pavlovitch once more.
вЂњIvan, your ear again.вЂќ

Ivan bent down again with a perfectly grave face.

вЂњI love you as I do Alyosha. DonвЂ™t think I donвЂ™t love you. Some brandy?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂ”But youвЂ™re rather drunk yourself,вЂќ thought Ivan, looking steadily at
his father.

He was watching Smerdyakov with great curiosity.

вЂњYouвЂ™re anathema accursed, as it is,вЂќ Grigory suddenly burst out, вЂњand how
dare you argue, you rascal, after that, ifвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t scold him, Grigory, donвЂ™t scold him,вЂќ Fyodor Pavlovitch cut him
short.

вЂњYou should wait, Grigory Vassilyevitch, if only a short time, and listen,
for I havenвЂ™t finished all I had to say. For at the very moment I become
accursed, at that same highest moment, I become exactly like a heathen,
and my christening is taken off me and becomes of no avail. IsnвЂ™t that
so?вЂќ

вЂњMake haste and finish, my boy,вЂќ Fyodor Pavlovitch urged him, sipping from
his wineвЂђglass with relish.

вЂњAnd if IвЂ™ve ceased to be a Christian, then I told no lie to the enemy
when they asked whether I was a Christian or not a Christian, seeing I had
already been relieved by God Himself of my Christianity by reason of the
thought alone, before I had time to utter a word to the enemy. And if I
have already been discharged, in what manner and with what sort of justice
can I be held responsible as a Christian in the other world for having
denied Christ, when, through the very thought alone, before denying Him I
had been relieved from my christening? If IвЂ™m no longer a Christian, then
I canвЂ™t renounce Christ, for IвЂ™ve nothing then to renounce. Who will hold
an unclean Tatar responsible, Grigory Vassilyevitch, even in heaven, for
not having been born a Christian? And who would punish him for that,
considering that you canвЂ™t take two skins off one ox? For God Almighty
Himself, even if He did make the Tatar responsible, when he dies would
give him the smallest possible punishment, I imagine (since he must be
punished), judging that he is not to blame if he has come into the world
an unclean heathen, from heathen parents. The Lord God canвЂ™t surely take a
Tatar and say he was a Christian? That would mean that the Almighty would
tell a real untruth. And can the Lord of Heaven and earth tell a lie, even
in one word?вЂќ

Grigory was thunderstruck and looked at the orator, his eyes nearly
starting out of his head. Though he did not clearly understand what was
said, he had caught something in this rigmarole, and stood, looking like a
man who has just hit his head against a wall. Fyodor Pavlovitch emptied
his glass and went off into his shrill laugh.

вЂњAlyosha! Alyosha! What do you say to that! Ah, you casuist! He must have
been with the Jesuits, somewhere, Ivan. Oh, you stinking Jesuit, who
taught you? But youвЂ™re talking nonsense, you casuist, nonsense, nonsense,
nonsense. DonвЂ™t cry, Grigory, weвЂ™ll reduce him to smoke and ashes in a
moment. Tell me this, O ass; you may be right before your enemies, but you
have renounced your faith all the same in your own heart, and you say
yourself that in that very hour you became anathema accursed. And if once
youвЂ™re anathema they wonвЂ™t pat you on the head for it in hell. What do you
say to that, my fine Jesuit?вЂќ

вЂњThere is no doubt that I have renounced it in my own heart, but there was
no special sin in that. Or if there was sin, it was the most ordinary.вЂќ

вЂњHowвЂ™s that the most ordinary?вЂќ

вЂњYou lie, accursed one!вЂќ hissed Grigory.

вЂњConsider yourself, Grigory Vassilyevitch,вЂќ Smerdyakov went on, staid and
unruffled, conscious of his triumph, but, as it were, generous to the
vanquished foe. вЂњConsider yourself, Grigory Vassilyevitch; it is said in
the Scripture that if you have faith, even as a mustard seed, and bid a
mountain move into the sea, it will move without the least delay at your
bidding. Well, Grigory Vassilyevitch, if IвЂ™m without faith and you have so
great a faith that you are continually swearing at me, you try yourself
telling this mountain, not to move into the sea for thatвЂ™s a long way off,
but even to our stinking little river which runs at the bottom of the
garden. YouвЂ™ll see for yourself that it wonвЂ™t budge, but will remain just
where it is however much you shout at it, and that shows, Grigory
Vassilyevitch, that you havenвЂ™t faith in the proper manner, and only abuse
others about it. Again, taking into consideration that no one in our day,
not only you, but actually no one, from the highest person to the lowest
peasant, can shove mountains into the seaвЂ”except perhaps some one man in
the world, or, at most, two, and they most likely are saving their souls
in secret somewhere in the Egyptian desert, so you wouldnвЂ™t find themвЂ”if
so it be, if all the rest have no faith, will God curse all the rest? that
is, the population of the whole earth, except about two hermits in the
desert, and in His wellвЂђknown mercy will He not forgive one of them? And
so IвЂ™m persuaded that though I may once have doubted I shall be forgiven
if I shed tears of repentance.вЂќ

вЂњStay!вЂќ cried Fyodor Pavlovitch, in a transport of delight. вЂњSo you do
suppose there are two who can move mountains? Ivan, make a note of it,
write it down. There you have the Russian all over!вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re quite right in saying itвЂ™s characteristic of the peopleвЂ™s faith,вЂќ
Ivan assented, with an approving smile.

вЂњYou agree. Then it must be so, if you agree. ItвЂ™s true, isnвЂ™t it,
Alyosha? ThatвЂ™s the Russian faith all over, isnвЂ™t it?вЂќ

вЂњNo, Smerdyakov has not the Russian faith at all,вЂќ said Alyosha firmly and
gravely.

вЂњIвЂ™m not talking about his faith. I mean those two in the desert, only
that idea. Surely thatвЂ™s Russian, isnвЂ™t it?вЂќ

вЂњYes, thatвЂ™s purely Russian,вЂќ said Alyosha smiling.

вЂњYour words are worth a gold piece, O ass, and IвЂ™ll give it to you toвЂђday.
But as to the rest you talk nonsense, nonsense, nonsense. Let me tell you,
stupid, that we here are all of little faith, only from carelessness,
because we havenвЂ™t time; things are too much for us, and, in the second
place, the Lord God has given us so little time, only twentyвЂђfour hours in
the day, so that one hasnвЂ™t even time to get sleep enough, much less to
repent of oneвЂ™s sins. While you have denied your faith to your enemies
when youвЂ™d nothing else to think about but to show your faith! So I
consider, brother, that it constitutes a sin.вЂќ

вЂњConstitute a sin it may, but consider yourself, Grigory Vassilyevitch,
that it only extenuates it, if it does constitute. If I had believed then
in very truth, as I ought to have believed, then it really would have been
sinful if I had not faced tortures for my faith, and had gone over to the
pagan Mohammedan faith. But, of course, it wouldnвЂ™t have come to torture
then, because I should only have had to say at that instant to the
mountain, вЂMove and crush the tormentor,вЂ™ and it would have moved and at
the very instant have crushed him like a blackвЂђbeetle, and I should have
walked away as though nothing had happened, praising and glorifying God.
But, suppose at that very moment I had tried all that, and cried to that
mountain, вЂCrush these tormentors,вЂ™ and it hadnвЂ™t crushed them, how could
I have helped doubting, pray, at such a time, and at such a dread hour of
mortal terror? And apart from that, I should know already that I could not
attain to the fullness of the Kingdom of Heaven (for since the mountain
had not moved at my word, they could not think very much of my faith up
aloft, and there could be no very great reward awaiting me in the world to
come). So why should I let them flay the skin off me as well, and to no
good purpose? For, even though they had flayed my skin half off my back,
even then the mountain would not have moved at my word or at my cry. And
at such a moment not only doubt might come over one but one might lose
oneвЂ™s reason from fear, so that one would not be able to think at all.
And, therefore, how should I be particularly to blame if not seeing my
advantage or reward there or here, I should, at least, save my skin. And
so trusting fully in the grace of the Lord I should cherish the hope that
I might be altogether forgiven.вЂќ



Chapter VIII. Over The Brandy


The controversy was over. But, strange to say, Fyodor Pavlovitch, who had
been so gay, suddenly began frowning. He frowned and gulped brandy, and it
was already a glass too much.

вЂњGet along with you, Jesuits!вЂќ he cried to the servants. вЂњGo away,
Smerdyakov. IвЂ™ll send you the gold piece I promised you toвЂђday, but be
off! DonвЂ™t cry, Grigory. Go to Marfa. SheвЂ™ll comfort you and put you to
bed. The rascals wonвЂ™t let us sit in peace after dinner,вЂќ he snapped
peevishly, as the servants promptly withdrew at his word.

вЂњSmerdyakov always pokes himself in now, after dinner. ItвЂ™s you heвЂ™s so
interested in. What have you done to fascinate him?вЂќ he added to Ivan.

вЂњNothing whatever,вЂќ answered Ivan. вЂњHeвЂ™s pleased to have a high opinion of
me; heвЂ™s a lackey and a mean soul. Raw material for revolution, however,
when the time comes.вЂќ

вЂњFor revolution?вЂќ

вЂњThere will be others and better ones. But there will be some like him as
well. His kind will come first, and better ones after.вЂќ

вЂњAnd when will the time come?вЂќ

вЂњThe rocket will go off and fizzle out, perhaps. The peasants are not very
fond of listening to these soupвЂђmakers, so far.вЂќ

вЂњAh, brother, but a BalaamвЂ™s ass like that thinks and thinks, and the
devil knows where he gets to.вЂќ

вЂњHeвЂ™s storing up ideas,вЂќ said Ivan, smiling.

вЂњYou see, I know he canвЂ™t bear me, nor any one else, even you, though you
fancy that he has a high opinion of you. Worse still with Alyosha, he
despises Alyosha. But he doesnвЂ™t steal, thatвЂ™s one thing, and heвЂ™s not a
gossip, he holds his tongue, and doesnвЂ™t wash our dirty linen in public.
He makes capital fish pasties too. But, damn him, is he worth talking
about so much?вЂќ

вЂњOf course he isnвЂ™t.вЂќ

вЂњAnd as for the ideas he may be hatching, the Russian peasant, generally
speaking, needs thrashing. That IвЂ™ve always maintained. Our peasants are
swindlers, and donвЂ™t deserve to be pitied, and itвЂ™s a good thing theyвЂ™re
still flogged sometimes. Russia is rich in birches. If they destroyed the
forests, it would be the ruin of Russia. I stand up for the clever people.
WeвЂ™ve left off thrashing the peasants, weвЂ™ve grown so clever, but they go
on thrashing themselves. And a good thing too. вЂFor with what measure ye
mete it shall be measured to you again,вЂ™ or how does it go? Anyhow, it
will be measured. But RussiaвЂ™s all swinishness. My dear, if you only knew
how I hate Russia.... That is, not Russia, but all this vice! But maybe I
mean Russia. _Tout cela cвЂ™est de la cochonnerie_.... Do you know what I
like? I like wit.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™ve had another glass. ThatвЂ™s enough.вЂќ

вЂњWait a bit. IвЂ™ll have one more, and then another, and then IвЂ™ll stop. No,
stay, you interrupted me. At Mokroe I was talking to an old man, and he
told me: вЂThereвЂ™s nothing we like so much as sentencing girls to be
thrashed, and we always give the lads the job of thrashing them. And the
girl he has thrashed toвЂђday, the young man will ask in marriage toвЂђmorrow.
So it quite suits the girls, too,вЂ™ he said. ThereвЂ™s a set of de Sades for
you! But itвЂ™s clever, anyway. Shall we go over and have a look at it, eh?
Alyosha, are you blushing? DonвЂ™t be bashful, child. IвЂ™m sorry I didnвЂ™t
stay to dinner at the SuperiorвЂ™s and tell the monks about the girls at
Mokroe. Alyosha, donвЂ™t be angry that I offended your Superior this
morning. I lost my temper. If there is a God, if He exists, then, of
course, IвЂ™m to blame, and I shall have to answer for it. But if there
isnвЂ™t a God at all, what do they deserve, your fathers? ItвЂ™s not enough to
cut their heads off, for they keep back progress. Would you believe it,
Ivan, that that lacerates my sentiments? No, you donвЂ™t believe it as I see
from your eyes. You believe what people say, that IвЂ™m nothing but a
buffoon. Alyosha, do you believe that IвЂ™m nothing but a buffoon?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I donвЂ™t believe it.вЂќ

вЂњAnd I believe you donвЂ™t, and that you speak the truth. You look sincere
and you speak sincerely. But not Ivan. IvanвЂ™s supercilious.... IвЂ™d make an
end of your monks, though, all the same. IвЂ™d take all that mystic stuff
and suppress it, once for all, all over Russia, so as to bring all the
fools to reason. And the gold and the silver that would flow into the
mint!вЂќ

вЂњBut why suppress it?вЂќ asked Ivan.

вЂњThat Truth may prevail. ThatвЂ™s why.вЂќ

вЂњWell, if Truth were to prevail, you know, youвЂ™d be the first to be robbed
and suppressed.вЂќ

вЂњAh! I dare say youвЂ™re right. Ah, IвЂ™m an ass!вЂќ burst out Fyodor
Pavlovitch, striking himself lightly on the forehead. вЂњWell, your
monastery may stand then, Alyosha, if thatвЂ™s how it is. And we clever
people will sit snug and enjoy our brandy. You know, Ivan, it must have
been so ordained by the Almighty Himself. Ivan, speak, is there a God or
not? Stay, speak the truth, speak seriously. Why are you laughing again?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™m laughing that you should have made a clever remark just now about
SmerdyakovвЂ™s belief in the existence of two saints who could move
mountains.вЂќ

вЂњWhy, am I like him now, then?вЂќ

вЂњVery much.вЂќ

вЂњWell, that shows IвЂ™m a Russian, too, and I have a Russian characteristic.
And you may be caught in the same way, though you are a philosopher. Shall
I catch you? What do you bet that IвЂ™ll catch you toвЂђmorrow. Speak, all the
same, is there a God, or not? Only, be serious. I want you to be serious
now.вЂќ

вЂњNo, there is no God.вЂќ

вЂњAlyosha, is there a God?вЂќ

вЂњThere is.вЂќ

вЂњIvan, and is there immortality of some sort, just a little, just a tiny
bit?вЂќ

вЂњThere is no immortality either.вЂќ

вЂњNone at all?вЂќ

вЂњNone at all.вЂќ

вЂњThereвЂ™s absolute nothingness then. Perhaps there is just something?
Anything is better than nothing!вЂќ

вЂњAbsolute nothingness.вЂќ

вЂњAlyosha, is there immortality?вЂќ

вЂњThere is.вЂќ

вЂњGod and immortality?вЂќ

вЂњGod and immortality. In God is immortality.вЂќ

вЂњHвЂ™m! ItвЂ™s more likely IvanвЂ™s right. Good Lord! to think what faith, what
force of all kinds, man has lavished for nothing, on that dream, and for
how many thousand years. Who is it laughing at man? Ivan! For the last
time, once for all, is there a God or not? I ask for the last time!вЂќ

вЂњAnd for the last time there is not.вЂќ

вЂњWho is laughing at mankind, Ivan?вЂќ

вЂњIt must be the devil,вЂќ said Ivan, smiling.

вЂњAnd the devil? Does he exist?вЂќ

вЂњNo, thereвЂ™s no devil either.вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s a pity. Damn it all, what wouldnвЂ™t I do to the man who first
invented God! Hanging on a bitter aspen tree would be too good for him.вЂќ

вЂњThere would have been no civilization if they hadnвЂ™t invented God.вЂќ

вЂњWouldnвЂ™t there have been? Without God?вЂќ

вЂњNo. And there would have been no brandy either. But I must take your
brandy away from you, anyway.вЂќ

вЂњStop, stop, stop, dear boy, one more little glass. IвЂ™ve hurt AlyoshaвЂ™s
feelings. YouвЂ™re not angry with me, Alyosha? My dear little Alexey!вЂќ

вЂњNo, I am not angry. I know your thoughts. Your heart is better than your
head.вЂќ

вЂњMy heart better than my head, is it? Oh, Lord! And that from you. Ivan,
do you love Alyosha?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњYou must love himвЂќ (Fyodor Pavlovitch was by this time very drunk).
вЂњListen, Alyosha, I was rude to your elder this morning. But I was
excited. But thereвЂ™s wit in that elder, donвЂ™t you think, Ivan?вЂќ

вЂњVery likely.вЂќ

вЂњThere is, there is. _Il y a du Piron lГ вЂђdedans._ HeвЂ™s a Jesuit, a Russian
one, that is. As heвЂ™s an honorable person thereвЂ™s a hidden indignation
boiling within him at having to pretend and affect holiness.вЂќ

вЂњBut, of course, he believes in God.вЂќ

вЂњNot a bit of it. DidnвЂ™t you know? Why, he tells every one so, himself.
That is, not every one, but all the clever people who come to him. He said
straight out to Governor Schultz not long ago: вЂ_Credo_, but I donвЂ™t know
in what.вЂ™ вЂќ

вЂњReally?вЂќ

вЂњHe really did. But I respect him. ThereвЂ™s something of Mephistopheles
about him, or rather of вЂThe hero of our timeвЂ™ ... Arbenin, or whatвЂ™s his
name?... You see, heвЂ™s a sensualist. HeвЂ™s such a sensualist that I should
be afraid for my daughter or my wife if she went to confess to him. You
know, when he begins telling stories.... The year before last he invited
us to tea, tea with liqueur (the ladies send him liqueur), and began
telling us about old times till we nearly split our sides.... Especially
how he once cured a paralyzed woman. вЂIf my legs were not bad I know a
dance I could dance you,вЂ™ he said. What do you say to that? вЂIвЂ™ve plenty
of tricks in my time,вЂ™ said he. He did Dernidov, the merchant, out of
sixty thousand.вЂќ

вЂњWhat, he stole it?вЂќ

вЂњHe brought him the money as a man he could trust, saying, вЂTake care of
it for me, friend, thereвЂ™ll be a police search at my place toвЂђmorrow.вЂ™ And
he kept it. вЂYou have given it to the Church,вЂ™ he declared. I said to him:
вЂYouвЂ™re a scoundrel,вЂ™ I said. вЂNo,вЂ™ said he, вЂIвЂ™m not a scoundrel, but IвЂ™m
broadвЂђminded.вЂ™ But that wasnвЂ™t he, that was some one else. IвЂ™ve muddled
him with some one else ... without noticing it. Come, another glass and
thatвЂ™s enough. Take away the bottle, Ivan. IвЂ™ve been telling lies. Why
didnвЂ™t you stop me, Ivan, and tell me I was lying?вЂќ

вЂњI knew youвЂ™d stop of yourself.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s a lie. You did it from spite, from simple spite against me. You
despise me. You have come to me and despised me in my own house.вЂќ

вЂњWell, IвЂ™m going away. YouвЂ™ve had too much brandy.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ve begged you for ChristвЂ™s sake to go to Tchermashnya for a day or two,
and you donвЂ™t go.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll go toвЂђmorrow if youвЂ™re so set upon it.вЂќ

вЂњYou wonвЂ™t go. You want to keep an eye on me. ThatвЂ™s what you want,
spiteful fellow. ThatвЂ™s why you wonвЂ™t go.вЂќ

The old man persisted. He had reached that state of drunkenness when the
drunkard who has till then been inoffensive tries to pick a quarrel and to
assert himself.

вЂњWhy are you looking at me? Why do you look like that? Your eyes look at
me and say, вЂYou ugly drunkard!вЂ™ Your eyes are mistrustful. TheyвЂ™re
contemptuous.... YouвЂ™ve come here with some design. Alyosha, here, looks
at me and his eyes shine. Alyosha doesnвЂ™t despise me. Alexey, you mustnвЂ™t
love Ivan.вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t be illвЂђtempered with my brother. Leave off attacking him,вЂќ Alyosha
said emphatically.

вЂњOh, all right. Ugh, my head aches. Take away the brandy, Ivan. ItвЂ™s the
third time IвЂ™ve told you.вЂќ

He mused, and suddenly a slow, cunning grin spread over his face.

вЂњDonвЂ™t be angry with a feeble old man, Ivan. I know you donвЂ™t love me, but
donвЂ™t be angry all the same. YouвЂ™ve nothing to love me for. You go to
Tchermashnya. IвЂ™ll come to you myself and bring you a present. IвЂ™ll show
you a little wench there. IвЂ™ve had my eye on her a long time. SheвЂ™s still
running about bareвЂђfoot. DonвЂ™t be afraid of bareвЂђfooted wenchesвЂ”donвЂ™t
despise themвЂ”theyвЂ™re pearls!вЂќ

And he kissed his hand with a smack.

вЂњTo my thinking,вЂќ he revived at once, seeming to grow sober the instant he
touched on his favorite topic. вЂњTo my thinking ... Ah, you boys! You
children, little suckingвЂђpigs, to my thinking ... I never thought a woman
ugly in my lifeвЂ”thatвЂ™s been my rule! Can you understand that? How could
you understand it? YouвЂ™ve milk in your veins, not blood. YouвЂ™re not out of
your shells yet. My rule has been that you can always find something
devilishly interesting in every woman that you wouldnвЂ™t find in any other.
Only, one must know how to find it, thatвЂ™s the point! ThatвЂ™s a talent! To
my mind there are no ugly women. The very fact that she is a woman is half
the battle ... but how could you understand that? Even in _vieilles
filles_, even in them you may discover something that makes you simply
wonder that men have been such fools as to let them grow old without
noticing them. BareвЂђfooted girls or unattractive ones, you must take by
surprise. DidnвЂ™t you know that? You must astound them till theyвЂ™re
fascinated, upset, ashamed that such a gentleman should fall in love with
such a little slut. ItвЂ™s a jolly good thing that there always are and will
be masters and slaves in the world, so there always will be a little maidвЂђ
ofвЂђallвЂђwork and her master, and you know, thatвЂ™s all thatвЂ™s needed for
happiness. Stay ... listen, Alyosha, I always used to surprise your
mother, but in a different way. I paid no attention to her at all, but all
at once, when the minute came, IвЂ™d be all devotion to her, crawl on my
knees, kiss her feet, and I always, alwaysвЂ”I remember it as though it were
toвЂђdayвЂ”reduced her to that tinkling, quiet, nervous, queer little laugh.
It was peculiar to her. I knew her attacks always used to begin like that.
The next day she would begin shrieking hysterically, and this little laugh
was not a sign of delight, though it made a very good counterfeit. ThatвЂ™s
the great thing, to know how to take every one. Once BelyavskyвЂ”he was a
handsome fellow, and richвЂ”used to like to come here and hang about
herвЂ”suddenly gave me a slap in the face in her presence. And sheвЂ”such a
mild sheepвЂ”why, I thought she would have knocked me down for that blow.
How she set on me! вЂYouвЂ™re beaten, beaten now,вЂ™ she said. вЂYouвЂ™ve taken a
blow from him. You have been trying to sell me to him,вЂ™ she said.... вЂAnd
how dared he strike you in my presence! DonвЂ™t dare come near me again,
never, never! Run at once, challenge him to a duel!вЂ™... I took her to the
monastery then to bring her to her senses. The holy Fathers prayed her
back to reason. But I swear, by God, Alyosha, I never insulted the poor
crazy girl! Only once, perhaps, in the first year; then she was very fond
of praying. She used to keep the feasts of Our Lady particularly and used
to turn me out of her room then. IвЂ™ll knock that mysticism out of her,
thought I! вЂHere,вЂ™ said I, вЂyou see your holy image. Here it is. Here I
take it down. You believe itвЂ™s miraculous, but here, IвЂ™ll spit on it
directly and nothing will happen to me for it!вЂ™... When she saw it, good
Lord! I thought she would kill me. But she only jumped up, wrung her
hands, then suddenly hid her face in them, began trembling all over and
fell on the floor ... fell all of a heap. Alyosha, Alyosha, whatвЂ™s the
matter?вЂќ

The old man jumped up in alarm. From the time he had begun speaking about
his mother, a change had gradually come over AlyoshaвЂ™s face. He flushed
crimson, his eyes glowed, his lips quivered. The old sot had gone
spluttering on, noticing nothing, till the moment when something very
strange happened to Alyosha. Precisely what he was describing in the crazy
woman was suddenly repeated with Alyosha. He jumped up from his seat
exactly as his mother was said to have done, wrung his hands, hid his face
in them, and fell back in his chair, shaking all over in an hysterical
paroxysm of sudden violent, silent weeping. His extraordinary resemblance
to his mother particularly impressed the old man.

вЂњIvan, Ivan! Water, quickly! ItвЂ™s like her, exactly as she used to be
then, his mother. Spurt some water on him from your mouth, thatвЂ™s what I
used to do to her. HeвЂ™s upset about his mother, his mother,вЂќ he muttered
to Ivan.

вЂњBut she was my mother, too, I believe, his mother. Was she not?вЂќ said
Ivan, with uncontrolled anger and contempt. The old man shrank before his
flashing eyes. But something very strange had happened, though only for a
second; it seemed really to have escaped the old manвЂ™s mind that AlyoshaвЂ™s
mother actually was the mother of Ivan too.

вЂњYour mother?вЂќ he muttered, not understanding. вЂњWhat do you mean? What
mother are you talking about? Was she?... Why, damn it! of course she was
yours too! Damn it! My mind has never been so darkened before. Excuse me,
why, I was thinking, Ivan.... He he he!вЂќ He stopped. A broad, drunken,
halfвЂђsenseless grin overspread his face.

At that moment a fearful noise and clamor was heard in the hall, there
were violent shouts, the door was flung open, and Dmitri burst into the
room. The old man rushed to Ivan in terror.

вЂњHeвЂ™ll kill me! HeвЂ™ll kill me! DonвЂ™t let him get at me!вЂќ he screamed,
clinging to the skirt of IvanвЂ™s coat.



Chapter IX. The Sensualists


Grigory and Smerdyakov ran into the room after Dmitri. They had been
struggling with him in the passage, refusing to admit him, acting on
instructions given them by Fyodor Pavlovitch some days before. Taking
advantage of the fact that Dmitri stopped a moment on entering the room to
look about him, Grigory ran round the table, closed the double doors on
the opposite side of the room leading to the inner apartments, and stood
before the closed doors, stretching wide his arms, prepared to defend the
entrance, so to speak, with the last drop of his blood. Seeing this,
Dmitri uttered a scream rather than a shout and rushed at Grigory.

вЂњThen sheвЂ™s there! SheвЂ™s hidden there! Out of the way, scoundrel!вЂќ

He tried to pull Grigory away, but the old servant pushed him back. Beside
himself with fury, Dmitri struck out, and hit Grigory with all his might.
The old man fell like a log, and Dmitri, leaping over him, broke in the
door. Smerdyakov remained pale and trembling at the other end of the room,
huddling close to Fyodor Pavlovitch.

вЂњSheвЂ™s here!вЂќ shouted Dmitri. вЂњI saw her turn towards the house just now,
but I couldnвЂ™t catch her. Where is she? Where is she?вЂќ

That shout, вЂњSheвЂ™s here!вЂќ produced an indescribable effect on Fyodor
Pavlovitch. All his terror left him.

вЂњHold him! Hold him!вЂќ he cried, and dashed after Dmitri. Meanwhile Grigory
had got up from the floor, but still seemed stunned. Ivan and Alyosha ran
after their father. In the third room something was heard to fall on the
floor with a ringing crash: it was a large glass vaseвЂ”not an expensive
oneвЂ”on a marble pedestal which Dmitri had upset as he ran past it.

вЂњAt him!вЂќ shouted the old man. вЂњHelp!вЂќ

Ivan and Alyosha caught the old man and were forcibly bringing him back.

вЂњWhy do you run after him? HeвЂ™ll murder you outright,вЂќ Ivan cried
wrathfully at his father.

вЂњIvan! Alyosha! She must be here. GrushenkaвЂ™s here. He said he saw her
himself, running.вЂќ

He was choking. He was not expecting Grushenka at the time, and the sudden
news that she was here made him beside himself. He was trembling all over.
He seemed frantic.

вЂњBut youвЂ™ve seen for yourself that she hasnвЂ™t come,вЂќ cried Ivan.

вЂњBut she may have come by that other entrance.вЂќ

вЂњYou know that entrance is locked, and you have the key.вЂќ

Dmitri suddenly reappeared in the drawingвЂђroom. He had, of course, found
the other entrance locked, and the key actually was in Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s
pocket. The windows of all the rooms were also closed, so Grushenka could
not have come in anywhere nor have run out anywhere.

вЂњHold him!вЂќ shrieked Fyodor Pavlovitch, as soon as he saw him again. вЂњHeвЂ™s
been stealing money in my bedroom.вЂќ And tearing himself from Ivan he
rushed again at Dmitri. But Dmitri threw up both hands and suddenly
clutched the old man by the two tufts of hair that remained on his
temples, tugged at them, and flung him with a crash on the floor. He
kicked him two or three times with his heel in the face. The old man
moaned shrilly. Ivan, though not so strong as Dmitri, threw his arms round
him, and with all his might pulled him away. Alyosha helped him with his
slender strength, holding Dmitri in front.

вЂњMadman! YouвЂ™ve killed him!вЂќ cried Ivan.

вЂњServe him right!вЂќ shouted Dmitri breathlessly. вЂњIf I havenвЂ™t killed him,
IвЂ™ll come again and kill him. You canвЂ™t protect him!вЂќ

вЂњDmitri! Go away at once!вЂќ cried Alyosha commandingly.

вЂњAlexey! You tell me. ItвЂ™s only you I can believe; was she here just now,
or not? I saw her myself creeping this way by the fence from the lane. I
shouted, she ran away.вЂќ

вЂњI swear sheвЂ™s not been here, and no one expected her.вЂќ

вЂњBut I saw her.... So she must ... IвЂ™ll find out at once where she is....
GoodвЂђby, Alexey! Not a word to Г†sop about the money now. But go to
Katerina Ivanovna at once and be sure to say, вЂHe sends his compliments to
you!вЂ™ Compliments, his compliments! Just compliments and farewell!
Describe the scene to her.вЂќ

Meanwhile Ivan and Grigory had raised the old man and seated him in an
armвЂђchair. His face was covered with blood, but he was conscious and
listened greedily to DmitriвЂ™s cries. He was still fancying that Grushenka
really was somewhere in the house. Dmitri looked at him with hatred as he
went out.

вЂњI donвЂ™t repent shedding your blood!вЂќ he cried. вЂњBeware, old man, beware
of your dream, for I have my dream, too. I curse you, and disown you
altogether.вЂќ

He ran out of the room.

вЂњSheвЂ™s here. She must be here. Smerdyakov! Smerdyakov!вЂќ the old man
wheezed, scarcely audibly, beckoning to him with his finger.

вЂњNo, sheвЂ™s not here, you old lunatic!вЂќ Ivan shouted at him angrily. вЂњHere,
heвЂ™s fainting! Water! A towel! Make haste, Smerdyakov!вЂќ

Smerdyakov ran for water. At last they got the old man undressed, and put
him to bed. They wrapped a wet towel round his head. Exhausted by the
brandy, by his violent emotion, and the blows he had received, he shut his
eyes and fell asleep as soon as his head touched the pillow. Ivan and
Alyosha went back to the drawingвЂђroom. Smerdyakov removed the fragments of
the broken vase, while Grigory stood by the table looking gloomily at the
floor.

вЂњShouldnвЂ™t you put a wet bandage on your head and go to bed, too?вЂќ Alyosha
said to him. вЂњWeвЂ™ll look after him. My brother gave you a terrible blowвЂ”on
the head.вЂќ

вЂњHeвЂ™s insulted me!вЂќ Grigory articulated gloomily and distinctly.

вЂњHeвЂ™s вЂinsultedвЂ™ his father, not only you,вЂќ observed Ivan with a forced
smile.

вЂњI used to wash him in his tub. HeвЂ™s insulted me,вЂќ repeated Grigory.

вЂњDamn it all, if I hadnвЂ™t pulled him away perhaps heвЂ™d have murdered him.
It wouldnвЂ™t take much to do for Г†sop, would it?вЂќ whispered Ivan to
Alyosha.

вЂњGod forbid!вЂќ cried Alyosha.

вЂњWhy should He forbid?вЂќ Ivan went on in the same whisper, with a malignant
grimace. вЂњOne reptile will devour the other. And serve them both right,
too.вЂќ

Alyosha shuddered.

вЂњOf course I wonвЂ™t let him be murdered as I didnвЂ™t just now. Stay here,
Alyosha, IвЂ™ll go for a turn in the yard. My headвЂ™s begun to ache.вЂќ

Alyosha went to his fatherвЂ™s bedroom and sat by his bedside behind the
screen for about an hour. The old man suddenly opened his eyes and gazed
for a long while at Alyosha, evidently remembering and meditating. All at
once his face betrayed extraordinary excitement.

вЂњAlyosha,вЂќ he whispered apprehensively, вЂњwhereвЂ™s Ivan?вЂќ

вЂњIn the yard. HeвЂ™s got a headache. HeвЂ™s on the watch.вЂќ

вЂњGive me that lookingвЂђglass. It stands over there. Give it me.вЂќ

Alyosha gave him a little round folding lookingвЂђglass which stood on the
chest of drawers. The old man looked at himself in it; his nose was
considerably swollen, and on the left side of his forehead there was a
rather large crimson bruise.

вЂњWhat does Ivan say? Alyosha, my dear, my only son, IвЂ™m afraid of Ivan.
IвЂ™m more afraid of Ivan than the other. YouвЂ™re the only one IвЂ™m not afraid
of....вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t be afraid of Ivan either. He is angry, but heвЂ™ll defend you.вЂќ

вЂњAlyosha, and what of the other? HeвЂ™s run to Grushenka. My angel, tell me
the truth, was she here just now or not?вЂќ

вЂњNo one has seen her. It was a mistake. She has not been here.вЂќ

вЂњYou know Mitya wants to marry her, to marry her.вЂќ

вЂњShe wonвЂ™t marry him.вЂќ

вЂњShe wonвЂ™t. She wonвЂ™t. She wonвЂ™t. She wonвЂ™t on any account!вЂќ

The old man fairly fluttered with joy, as though nothing more comforting
could have been said to him. In his delight he seized AlyoshaвЂ™s hand and
pressed it warmly to his heart. Tears positively glittered in his eyes.

вЂњThat image of the Mother of God of which I was telling you just now,вЂќ he
said. вЂњTake it home and keep it for yourself. And IвЂ™ll let you go back to
the monastery.... I was joking this morning, donвЂ™t be angry with me. My
head aches, Alyosha.... Alyosha, comfort my heart. Be an angel and tell me
the truth!вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re still asking whether she has been here or not?вЂќ Alyosha said
sorrowfully.

вЂњNo, no, no. I believe you. IвЂ™ll tell you what it is: you go to Grushenka
yourself, or see her somehow; make haste and ask her; see for yourself,
which she means to choose, him or me. Eh? What? Can you?вЂќ

вЂњIf I see her IвЂ™ll ask her,вЂќ Alyosha muttered, embarrassed.

вЂњNo, she wonвЂ™t tell you,вЂќ the old man interrupted, вЂњsheвЂ™s a rogue. SheвЂ™ll
begin kissing you and say that itвЂ™s you she wants. SheвЂ™s a deceitful,
shameless hussy. You mustnвЂ™t go to her, you mustnвЂ™t!вЂќ

вЂњNo, father, and it wouldnвЂ™t be suitable, it wouldnвЂ™t be right at all.вЂќ

вЂњWhere was he sending you just now? He shouted вЂGoвЂ™ as he ran away.вЂќ

вЂњTo Katerina Ivanovna.вЂќ

вЂњFor money? To ask her for money?вЂќ

вЂњNo. Not for money.вЂќ

вЂњHeвЂ™s no money; not a farthing. IвЂ™ll settle down for the night, and think
things over, and you can go. Perhaps youвЂ™ll meet her.... Only be sure to
come to me toвЂђmorrow in the morning. Be sure to. I have a word to say to
you toвЂђmorrow. Will you come?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњWhen you come, pretend youвЂ™ve come of your own accord to ask after me.
DonвЂ™t tell any one I told you to. DonвЂ™t say a word to Ivan.вЂќ

вЂњVery well.вЂќ

вЂњGoodвЂђby, my angel. You stood up for me, just now. I shall never forget
it. IвЂ™ve a word to say to you toвЂђmorrowвЂ”but I must think about it.вЂќ

вЂњAnd how do you feel now?вЂќ

вЂњI shall get up toвЂђmorrow and go out, perfectly well, perfectly well!вЂќ

Crossing the yard Alyosha found Ivan sitting on the bench at the gateway.
He was sitting writing something in pencil in his noteвЂђbook. Alyosha told
Ivan that their father had waked up, was conscious, and had let him go
back to sleep at the monastery.

вЂњAlyosha, I should be very glad to meet you toвЂђmorrow morning,вЂќ said Ivan
cordially, standing up. His cordiality was a complete surprise to Alyosha.

вЂњI shall be at the HohlakovsвЂ™ toвЂђmorrow,вЂќ answered Alyosha, вЂњI may be at
Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s, too, if I donвЂ™t find her now.вЂќ

вЂњBut youвЂ™re going to her now, anyway? For that вЂcompliments and
farewell,вЂ™ вЂќ said Ivan smiling. Alyosha was disconcerted.

вЂњI think I quite understand his exclamations just now, and part of what
went before. Dmitri has asked you to go to her and say that heвЂ”well, in
factвЂ”takes his leave of her?вЂќ

вЂњBrother, how will all this horror end between father and Dmitri?вЂќ
exclaimed Alyosha.

вЂњOne canвЂ™t tell for certain. Perhaps in nothing: it may all fizzle out.
That woman is a beast. In any case we must keep the old man indoors and
not let Dmitri in the house.вЂќ

вЂњBrother, let me ask one thing more: has any man a right to look at other
men and decide which is worthy to live?вЂќ

вЂњWhy bring in the question of worth? The matter is most often decided in
menвЂ™s hearts on other grounds much more natural. And as for rightsвЂ”who has
not the right to wish?вЂќ

вЂњNot for another manвЂ™s death?вЂќ

вЂњWhat even if for another manвЂ™s death? Why lie to oneself since all men
live so and perhaps cannot help living so. Are you referring to what I
said just nowвЂ”that one reptile will devour the other? In that case let me
ask you, do you think me like Dmitri capable of shedding Г†sopвЂ™s blood,
murdering him, eh?вЂќ

вЂњWhat are you saying, Ivan? Such an idea never crossed my mind. I donвЂ™t
think Dmitri is capable of it, either.вЂќ

вЂњThanks, if only for that,вЂќ smiled Ivan. вЂњBe sure, I should always defend
him. But in my wishes I reserve myself full latitude in this case. GoodвЂђby
till toвЂђmorrow. DonвЂ™t condemn me, and donвЂ™t look on me as a villain,вЂќ he
added with a smile.

They shook hands warmly as they had never done before. Alyosha felt that
his brother had taken the first step towards him, and that he had
certainly done this with some definite motive.



Chapter X. Both Together


Alyosha left his fatherвЂ™s house feeling even more exhausted and dejected
in spirit than when he had entered it. His mind too seemed shattered and
unhinged, while he felt that he was afraid to put together the disjointed
fragments and form a general idea from all the agonizing and conflicting
experiences of the day. He felt something bordering upon despair, which he
had never known till then. Towering like a mountain above all the rest
stood the fatal, insoluble question: How would things end between his
father and his brother Dmitri with this terrible woman? Now he had himself
been a witness of it, he had been present and seen them face to face. Yet
only his brother Dmitri could be made unhappy, terribly, completely
unhappy: there was trouble awaiting him. It appeared too that there were
other people concerned, far more so than Alyosha could have supposed
before. There was something positively mysterious in it, too. Ivan had
made a step towards him, which was what Alyosha had been long desiring.
Yet now he felt for some reason that he was frightened at it. And these
women? Strange to say, that morning he had set out for Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s
in the greatest embarrassment; now he felt nothing of the kind. On the
contrary, he was hastening there as though expecting to find guidance from
her. Yet to give her this message was obviously more difficult than
before. The matter of the three thousand was decided irrevocably, and
Dmitri, feeling himself dishonored and losing his last hope, might sink to
any depth. He had, moreover, told him to describe to Katerina Ivanovna the
scene which had just taken place with his father.

It was by now seven oвЂ™clock, and it was getting dark as Alyosha entered
the very spacious and convenient house in the High Street occupied by
Katerina Ivanovna. Alyosha knew that she lived with two aunts. One of
them, a woman of little education, was that aunt of her halfвЂђsister Agafya
Ivanovna who had looked after her in her fatherвЂ™s house when she came from
boardingвЂђschool. The other aunt was a Moscow lady of style and
consequence, though in straitened circumstances. It was said that they
both gave way in everything to Katerina Ivanovna, and that she only kept
them with her as chaperons. Katerina Ivanovna herself gave way to no one
but her benefactress, the generalвЂ™s widow, who had been kept by illness in
Moscow, and to whom she was obliged to write twice a week a full account
of all her doings.

When Alyosha entered the hall and asked the maid who opened the door to
him to take his name up, it was evident that they were already aware of
his arrival. Possibly he had been noticed from the window. At least,
Alyosha heard a noise, caught the sound of flying footsteps and rustling
skirts. Two or three women, perhaps, had run out of the room.

Alyosha thought it strange that his arrival should cause such excitement.
He was conducted however to the drawingвЂђroom at once. It was a large room,
elegantly and amply furnished, not at all in provincial style. There were
many sofas, lounges, settees, big and little tables. There were pictures
on the walls, vases and lamps on the tables, masses of flowers, and even
an aquarium in the window. It was twilight and rather dark. Alyosha made
out a silk mantle thrown down on the sofa, where people had evidently just
been sitting; and on a table in front of the sofa were two unfinished cups
of chocolate, cakes, a glass saucer with blue raisins, and another with
sweetmeats. Alyosha saw that he had interrupted visitors, and frowned. But
at that instant the portiГЁre was raised, and with rapid, hurrying
footsteps Katerina Ivanovna came in, holding out both hands to Alyosha
with a radiant smile of delight. At the same instant a servant brought in
two lighted candles and set them on the table.

вЂњThank God! At last you have come too! IвЂ™ve been simply praying for you
all day! Sit down.вЂќ

Alyosha had been struck by Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s beauty when, three weeks
before, Dmitri had first brought him, at Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s special
request, to be introduced to her. There had been no conversation between
them at that interview, however. Supposing Alyosha to be very shy,
Katerina Ivanovna had talked all the time to Dmitri to spare him. Alyosha
had been silent, but he had seen a great deal very clearly. He was struck
by the imperiousness, proud ease, and selfвЂђconfidence of the haughty girl.
And all that was certain, Alyosha felt that he was not exaggerating it. He
thought her great glowing black eyes were very fine, especially with her
pale, even rather sallow, longish face. But in those eyes and in the lines
of her exquisite lips there was something with which his brother might
well be passionately in love, but which perhaps could not be loved for
long. He expressed this thought almost plainly to Dmitri when, after the
visit, his brother besought and insisted that he should not conceal his
impressions on seeing his betrothed.

вЂњYouвЂ™ll be happy with her, but perhapsвЂ”not tranquilly happy.вЂќ

вЂњQuite so, brother. Such people remain always the same. They donвЂ™t yield
to fate. So you think I shanвЂ™t love her for ever.вЂќ

вЂњNo; perhaps you will love her for ever. But perhaps you wonвЂ™t always be
happy with her.вЂќ

Alyosha had given his opinion at the time, blushing, and angry with
himself for having yielded to his brotherвЂ™s entreaties and put such
вЂњfoolishвЂќ ideas into words. For his opinion had struck him as awfully
foolish immediately after he had uttered it. He felt ashamed too of having
given so confident an opinion about a woman. It was with the more
amazement that he felt now, at the first glance at Katerina Ivanovna as
she ran in to him, that he had perhaps been utterly mistaken. This time
her face was beaming with spontaneous goodвЂђnatured kindliness, and direct
warmвЂђhearted sincerity. The вЂњpride and haughtiness,вЂќ which had struck
Alyosha so much before, was only betrayed now in a frank, generous energy
and a sort of bright, strong faith in herself. Alyosha realized at the
first glance, at the first word, that all the tragedy of her position in
relation to the man she loved so dearly was no secret to her; that she
perhaps already knew everything, positively everything. And yet, in spite
of that, there was such brightness in her face, such faith in the future.
Alyosha felt at once that he had gravely wronged her in his thoughts. He
was conquered and captivated immediately. Besides all this, he noticed at
her first words that she was in great excitement, an excitement perhaps
quite exceptional and almost approaching ecstasy.

вЂњI was so eager to see you, because I can learn from you the whole
truthвЂ”from you and no one else.вЂќ

вЂњI have come,вЂќ muttered Alyosha confusedly, вЂњIвЂ”he sent me.вЂќ

вЂњAh, he sent you! I foresaw that. Now I know everythingвЂ”everything!вЂќ cried
Katerina Ivanovna, her eyes flashing. вЂњWait a moment, Alexey Fyodorovitch,
IвЂ™ll tell you why IвЂ™ve been so longing to see you. You see, I know perhaps
far more than you do yourself, and thereвЂ™s no need for you to tell me
anything. IвЂ™ll tell you what I want from you. I want to know your own last
impression of him. I want you to tell me most directly, plainly, coarsely
even (oh, as coarsely as you like!), what you thought of him just now and
of his position after your meeting with him toвЂђday. That will perhaps be
better than if I had a personal explanation with him, as he does not want
to come to me. Do you understand what I want from you? Now, tell me
simply, tell me every word of the message he sent you with (I knew he
would send you).вЂќ

вЂњHe told me to give you his complimentsвЂ”and to say that he would never
come againвЂ”but to give you his compliments.вЂќ

вЂњHis compliments? Was that what he saidвЂ”his own expression?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњAccidentally perhaps he made a mistake in the word, perhaps he did not
use the right word?вЂќ

вЂњNo; he told me precisely to repeat that word. He begged me two or three
times not to forget to say so.вЂќ

Katerina Ivanovna flushed hotly.

вЂњHelp me now, Alexey Fyodorovitch. Now I really need your help. IвЂ™ll tell
you what I think, and you must simply say whether itвЂ™s right or not.
Listen! If he had sent me his compliments in passing, without insisting on
