of everything! But if he particularly insisted on those words, if he
particularly told you not to forget to repeat them to me, then perhaps he
was in excitement, beside himself. He had made his decision and was
frightened at it. He wasnвЂ™t walking away from me with a resolute step, but
leaping headlong. The emphasis on that phrase may have been simply
bravado.вЂќ

вЂњYes, yes!вЂќ cried Alyosha warmly. вЂњI believe that is it.вЂќ

вЂњAnd, if so, heвЂ™s not altogether lost. I can still save him. Stay! Did he
not tell you anything about moneyвЂ”about three thousand roubles?вЂќ

вЂњHe did speak about it, and itвЂ™s that more than anything thatвЂ™s crushing
him. He said he had lost his honor and that nothing matters now,вЂќ Alyosha
answered warmly, feeling a rush of hope in his heart and believing that
there really might be a way of escape and salvation for his brother. вЂњBut
do you know about the money?вЂќ he added, and suddenly broke off.

вЂњIвЂ™ve known of it a long time; I telegraphed to Moscow to inquire, and
heard long ago that the money had not arrived. He hadnвЂ™t sent the money,
but I said nothing. Last week I learnt that he was still in need of money.
My only object in all this was that he should know to whom to turn, and
who was his true friend. No, he wonвЂ™t recognize that I am his truest
friend; he wonвЂ™t know me, and looks on me merely as a woman. IвЂ™ve been
tormented all the week, trying to think how to prevent him from being
ashamed to face me because he spent that three thousand. Let him feel
ashamed of himself, let him be ashamed of other peopleвЂ™s knowing, but not
of my knowing. He can tell God everything without shame. Why is it he
still does not understand how much I am ready to bear for his sake? Why,
why doesnвЂ™t he know me? How dare he not know me after all that has
happened? I want to save him for ever. Let him forget me as his betrothed.
And here he fears that he is dishonored in my eyes. Why, he wasnвЂ™t afraid
to be open with you, Alexey Fyodorovitch. How is it that I donвЂ™t deserve
the same?вЂќ

The last words she uttered in tears. Tears gushed from her eyes.

вЂњI must tell you,вЂќ Alyosha began, his voice trembling too, вЂњwhat happened
just now between him and my father.вЂќ

And he described the whole scene, how Dmitri had sent him to get the
money, how he had broken in, knocked his father down, and after that had
again specially and emphatically begged him to take his compliments and
farewell. вЂњHe went to that woman,вЂќ Alyosha added softly.

вЂњAnd do you suppose that I canвЂ™t put up with that woman? Does he think I
canвЂ™t? But he wonвЂ™t marry her,вЂќ she suddenly laughed nervously. вЂњCould
such a passion last for ever in a Karamazov? ItвЂ™s passion, not love. He
wonвЂ™t marry her because she wonвЂ™t marry him.вЂќ Again Katerina Ivanovna
laughed strangely.

вЂњHe may marry her,вЂќ said Alyosha mournfully, looking down.

вЂњHe wonвЂ™t marry her, I tell you. That girl is an angel. Do you know that?
Do you know that?вЂќ Katerina Ivanovna exclaimed suddenly with extraordinary
warmth. вЂњShe is one of the most fantastic of fantastic creatures. I know
how bewitching she is, but I know too that she is kind, firm and noble.
Why do you look at me like that, Alexey Fyodorovitch? Perhaps you are
wondering at my words, perhaps you donвЂ™t believe me? Agrafena
Alexandrovna, my angel!вЂќ she cried suddenly to some one, peeping into the
next room, вЂњcome in to us. This is a friend. This is Alyosha. He knows all
about our affairs. Show yourself to him.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ve only been waiting behind the curtain for you to call me,вЂќ said a
soft, one might even say sugary, feminine voice.

The portiГЁre was raised and Grushenka herself, smiling and beaming, came
up to the table. A violent revulsion passed over Alyosha. He fixed his
eyes on her and could not take them off. Here she was, that awful woman,
the вЂњbeast,вЂќ as Ivan had called her half an hour before. And yet one would
have thought the creature standing before him most simple and ordinary, a
goodвЂђnatured, kind woman, handsome certainly, but so like other handsome
ordinary women! It is true she was very, very goodвЂђlooking with that
Russian beauty so passionately loved by many men. She was a rather tall
woman, though a little shorter than Katerina Ivanovna, who was
exceptionally tall. She had a full figure, with soft, as it were,
noiseless, movements, softened to a peculiar overвЂђsweetness, like her
voice. She moved, not like Katerina Ivanovna, with a vigorous, bold step,
but noiselessly. Her feet made absolutely no sound on the floor. She sank
softly into a low chair, softly rustling her sumptuous black silk dress,
and delicately nestling her milkвЂђwhite neck and broad shoulders in a
costly cashmere shawl. She was twentyвЂђtwo years old, and her face looked
exactly that age. She was very white in the face, with a pale pink tint on
her cheeks. The modeling of her face might be said to be too broad, and
the lower jaw was set a trifle forward. Her upper lip was thin, but the
slightly prominent lower lip was at least twice as full, and looked
pouting. But her magnificent, abundant dark brown hair, her sableвЂђcolored
eyebrows and charming grayвЂђblue eyes with their long lashes would have
made the most indifferent person, meeting her casually in a crowd in the
street, stop at the sight of her face and remember it long after. What
struck Alyosha most in that face was its expression of childlike good
nature. There was a childlike look in her eyes, a look of childish
delight. She came up to the table, beaming with delight and seeming to
expect something with childish, impatient, and confiding curiosity. The
light in her eyes gladdened the soulвЂ”Alyosha felt that. There was
something else in her which he could not understand, or would not have
been able to define, and which yet perhaps unconsciously affected him. It
was that softness, that voluptuousness of her bodily movements, that
catlike noiselessness. Yet it was a vigorous, ample body. Under the shawl
could be seen full broad shoulders, a high, still quite girlish bosom. Her
figure suggested the lines of the Venus of Milo, though already in
somewhat exaggerated proportions. That could be divined. Connoisseurs of
Russian beauty could have foretold with certainty that this fresh, still
youthful beauty would lose its harmony by the age of thirty, would
вЂњspreadвЂќ; that the face would become puffy, and that wrinkles would very
soon appear upon her forehead and round the eyes; the complexion would
grow coarse and red perhapsвЂ”in fact, that it was the beauty of the moment,
the fleeting beauty which is so often met with in Russian women. Alyosha,
of course, did not think of this; but though he was fascinated, yet he
wondered with an unpleasant sensation, and as it were regretfully, why she
drawled in that way and could not speak naturally. She did so evidently
feeling there was a charm in the exaggerated, honeyed modulation of the
syllables. It was, of course, only a bad, underbred habit that showed bad
education and a false idea of good manners. And yet this intonation and
manner of speaking impressed Alyosha as almost incredibly incongruous with
the childishly simple and happy expression of her face, the soft, babyish
joy in her eyes. Katerina Ivanovna at once made her sit down in an armвЂђ
chair facing Alyosha, and ecstatically kissed her several times on her
smiling lips. She seemed quite in love with her.

вЂњThis is the first time weвЂ™ve met, Alexey Fyodorovitch,вЂќ she said
rapturously. вЂњI wanted to know her, to see her. I wanted to go to her, but
IвЂ™d no sooner expressed the wish than she came to me. I knew we should
settle everything togetherвЂ”everything. My heart told me soвЂ”I was begged
not to take the step, but I foresaw it would be a way out of the
difficulty, and I was not mistaken. Grushenka has explained everything to
me, told me all she means to do. She flew here like an angel of goodness
and brought us peace and joy.вЂќ

вЂњYou did not disdain me, sweet, excellent young lady,вЂќ drawled Grushenka
in her singвЂђsong voice, still with the same charming smile of delight.

вЂњDonвЂ™t dare to speak to me like that, you sorceress, you witch! Disdain
you! Here, I must kiss your lower lip once more. It looks as though it
were swollen, and now it will be more so, and more and more. Look how she
laughs, Alexey Fyodorovitch! It does oneвЂ™s heart good to see the angel.вЂќ

Alyosha flushed, and faint, imperceptible shivers kept running down him.

вЂњYou make so much of me, dear young lady, and perhaps I am not at all
worthy of your kindness.вЂќ

вЂњNot worthy! SheвЂ™s not worthy of it!вЂќ Katerina Ivanovna cried again with
the same warmth. вЂњYou know, Alexey Fyodorovitch, weвЂ™re fanciful, weвЂ™re
selfвЂђwilled, but proudest of the proud in our little heart. WeвЂ™re noble,
weвЂ™re generous, Alexey Fyodorovitch, let me tell you. We have only been
unfortunate. We were too ready to make every sacrifice for an unworthy,
perhaps, or fickle man. There was one manвЂ”one, an officer too, we loved
him, we sacrificed everything to him. That was long ago, five years ago,
and he has forgotten us, he has married. Now he is a widower, he has
written, he is coming here, and, do you know, weвЂ™ve loved him, none but
him, all this time, and weвЂ™ve loved him all our life! He will come, and
Grushenka will be happy again. For the last five years sheвЂ™s been
wretched. But who can reproach her, who can boast of her favor? Only that
bedridden old merchant, but he is more like her father, her friend, her
protector. He found her then in despair, in agony, deserted by the man she
loved. She was ready to drown herself then, but the old merchant saved
herвЂ”saved her!вЂќ

вЂњYou defend me very kindly, dear young lady. You are in a great hurry
about everything,вЂќ Grushenka drawled again.

вЂњDefend you! Is it for me to defend you? Should I dare to defend you?
Grushenka, angel, give me your hand. Look at that charming soft little
hand, Alexey Fyodorovitch! Look at it! It has brought me happiness and has
lifted me up, and IвЂ™m going to kiss it, outside and inside, here, here,
here!вЂќ

And three times she kissed the certainly charming, though rather fat, hand
of Grushenka in a sort of rapture. She held out her hand with a charming
musical, nervous little laugh, watched the вЂњsweet young lady,вЂќ and
obviously liked having her hand kissed.

вЂњPerhaps thereвЂ™s rather too much rapture,вЂќ thought Alyosha. He blushed. He
felt a peculiar uneasiness at heart the whole time.

вЂњYou wonвЂ™t make me blush, dear young lady, kissing my hand like this
before Alexey Fyodorovitch.вЂќ

вЂњDo you think I meant to make you blush?вЂќ said Katerina Ivanovna, somewhat
surprised. вЂњAh, my dear, how little you understand me!вЂќ

вЂњYes, and you too perhaps quite misunderstand me, dear young lady. Maybe
IвЂ™m not so good as I seem to you. IвЂ™ve a bad heart; I will have my own
way. I fascinated poor Dmitri Fyodorovitch that day simply for fun.вЂќ

вЂњBut now youвЂ™ll save him. YouвЂ™ve given me your word. YouвЂ™ll explain it all
to him. YouвЂ™ll break to him that you have long loved another man, who is
now offering you his hand.вЂќ

вЂњOh, no! I didnвЂ™t give you my word to do that. It was you kept talking
about that. I didnвЂ™t give you my word.вЂќ

вЂњThen I didnвЂ™t quite understand you,вЂќ said Katerina Ivanovna slowly,
turning a little pale. вЂњYou promisedвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњOh, no, angel lady, IвЂ™ve promised nothing,вЂќ Grushenka interrupted softly
and evenly, still with the same gay and simple expression. вЂњYou see at
once, dear young lady, what a willful wretch I am compared with you. If I
want to do a thing I do it. I may have made you some promise just now. But
now again IвЂ™m thinking: I may take to Mitya again. I liked him very much
onceвЂ”liked him for almost a whole hour. Now maybe I shall go and tell him
to stay with me from this day forward. You see, IвЂ™m so changeable.вЂќ

вЂњJust now you saidвЂ”something quite different,вЂќ Katerina Ivanovna whispered
faintly.

вЂњAh, just now! But, you know. IвЂ™m such a softвЂђhearted, silly creature.
Only think what heвЂ™s gone through on my account! What if when I go home I
feel sorry for him? What then?вЂќ

вЂњI never expectedвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњAh, young lady, how good and generous you are compared with me! Now
perhaps you wonвЂ™t care for a silly creature like me, now you know my
character. Give me your sweet little hand, angelic lady,вЂќ she said
tenderly, and with a sort of reverence took Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s hand.

вЂњHere, dear young lady, IвЂ™ll take your hand and kiss it as you did mine.
You kissed mine three times, but I ought to kiss yours three hundred times
to be even with you. Well, but let that pass. And then it shall be as God
wills. Perhaps I shall be your slave entirely and want to do your bidding
like a slave. Let it be as God wills, without any agreements and promises.
What a sweet handвЂ”what a sweet hand you have! You sweet young lady, you
incredible beauty!вЂќ

She slowly raised the hands to her lips, with the strange object indeed of
вЂњbeing evenвЂќ with her in kisses.

Katerina Ivanovna did not take her hand away. She listened with timid hope
to the last words, though GrushenkaвЂ™s promise to do her bidding like a
slave was very strangely expressed. She looked intently into her eyes; she
still saw in those eyes the same simpleвЂђhearted, confiding expression, the
same bright gayety.

вЂњSheвЂ™s perhaps too naГЇve,вЂќ thought Katerina Ivanovna, with a gleam of
hope.

Grushenka meanwhile seemed enthusiastic over the вЂњsweet hand.вЂќ She raised
it deliberately to her lips. But she held it for two or three minutes near
her lips, as though reconsidering something.

вЂњDo you know, angel lady,вЂќ she suddenly drawled in an even more soft and
sugary voice, вЂњdo you know, after all, I think I wonвЂ™t kiss your hand?вЂќ
And she laughed a little merry laugh.

вЂњAs you please. WhatвЂ™s the matter with you?вЂќ said Katerina Ivanovna,
starting suddenly.

вЂњSo that you may be left to remember that you kissed my hand, but I didnвЂ™t
kiss yours.вЂќ

There was a sudden gleam in her eyes. She looked with awful intentness at
Katerina Ivanovna.

вЂњInsolent creature!вЂќ cried Katerina Ivanovna, as though suddenly grasping
something. She flushed all over and leapt up from her seat.

Grushenka too got up, but without haste.

вЂњSo I shall tell Mitya how you kissed my hand, but I didnвЂ™t kiss yours at
all. And how he will laugh!вЂќ

вЂњVile slut! Go away!вЂќ

вЂњAh, for shame, young lady! Ah, for shame! ThatвЂ™s unbecoming for you, dear
young lady, a word like that.вЂќ

вЂњGo away! YouвЂ™re a creature for sale!вЂќ screamed Katerina Ivanovna. Every
feature was working in her utterly distorted face.

вЂњFor sale indeed! You used to visit gentlemen in the dusk for money once;
you brought your beauty for sale. You see, I know.вЂќ

Katerina Ivanovna shrieked, and would have rushed at her, but Alyosha held
her with all his strength.

вЂњNot a step, not a word! DonвЂ™t speak, donвЂ™t answer her. SheвЂ™ll go
awayвЂ”sheвЂ™ll go at once.вЂќ

At that instant Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s two aunts ran in at her cry, and with
them a maidвЂђservant. All hurried to her.

вЂњI will go away,вЂќ said Grushenka, taking up her mantle from the sofa.
вЂњAlyosha, darling, see me home!вЂќ

вЂњGo awayвЂ”go away, make haste!вЂќ cried Alyosha, clasping his hands
imploringly.

вЂњDear little Alyosha, see me home! IвЂ™ve got a pretty little story to tell
you on the way. I got up this scene for your benefit, Alyosha. See me
home, dear, youвЂ™ll be glad of it afterwards.вЂќ

Alyosha turned away, wringing his hands. Grushenka ran out of the house,
laughing musically.

Katerina Ivanovna went into a fit of hysterics. She sobbed, and was shaken
with convulsions. Every one fussed round her.

вЂњI warned you,вЂќ said the elder of her aunts. вЂњI tried to prevent your
doing this. YouвЂ™re too impulsive. How could you do such a thing? You donвЂ™t
know these creatures, and they say sheвЂ™s worse than any of them. You are
too selfвЂђwilled.вЂќ

вЂњSheвЂ™s a tigress!вЂќ yelled Katerina Ivanovna. вЂњWhy did you hold me, Alexey
Fyodorovitch? IвЂ™d have beaten herвЂ”beaten her!вЂќ

She could not control herself before Alyosha; perhaps she did not care to,
indeed.

вЂњShe ought to be flogged in public on a scaffold!вЂќ

Alyosha withdrew towards the door.

вЂњBut, my God!вЂќ cried Katerina Ivanovna, clasping her hands. вЂњHe! He! He
could be so dishonorable, so inhuman! Why, he told that creature what
happened on that fatal, accursed day! вЂYou brought your beauty for sale,
dear young lady.вЂ™ She knows it! Your brotherвЂ™s a scoundrel, Alexey
Fyodorovitch.вЂќ

Alyosha wanted to say something, but he couldnвЂ™t find a word. His heart
ached.

вЂњGo away, Alexey Fyodorovitch! ItвЂ™s shameful, itвЂ™s awful for me! ToвЂђ
morrow, I beg you on my knees, come toвЂђmorrow. DonвЂ™t condemn me. Forgive
me. I donвЂ™t know what I shall do with myself now!вЂќ

Alyosha walked out into the street reeling. He could have wept as she did.
Suddenly he was overtaken by the maid.

вЂњThe young lady forgot to give you this letter from Madame Hohlakov; itвЂ™s
been left with us since dinnerвЂђtime.вЂќ

Alyosha took the little pink envelope mechanically and put it, almost
unconsciously, into his pocket.



Chapter XI. Another Reputation Ruined


It was not much more than threeвЂђquarters of a mile from the town to the
monastery. Alyosha walked quickly along the road, at that hour deserted.
It was almost night, and too dark to see anything clearly at thirty paces
ahead. There were crossвЂђroads halfвЂђway. A figure came into sight under a
solitary willow at the crossвЂђroads. As soon as Alyosha reached the crossвЂђ
roads the figure moved out and rushed at him, shouting savagely:

вЂњYour money or your life!вЂќ

вЂњSo itвЂ™s you, Mitya,вЂќ cried Alyosha, in surprise, violently startled
however.

вЂњHa ha ha! You didnвЂ™t expect me? I wondered where to wait for you. By her
house? There are three ways from it, and I might have missed you. At last
I thought of waiting here, for you had to pass here, thereвЂ™s no other way
to the monastery. Come, tell me the truth. Crush me like a beetle. But
whatвЂ™s the matter?вЂќ

вЂњNothing, brotherвЂ”itвЂ™s the fright you gave me. Oh, Dmitri! FatherвЂ™s blood
just now.вЂќ (Alyosha began to cry, he had been on the verge of tears for a
long time, and now something seemed to snap in his soul.) вЂњYou almost
killed himвЂ”cursed himвЂ”and nowвЂ”hereвЂ”youвЂ™re making jokesвЂ”вЂYour money or your
life!вЂ™ вЂќ

вЂњWell, what of that? ItвЂ™s not seemlyвЂ”is that it? Not suitable in my
position?вЂќ

вЂњNoвЂ”I onlyвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњStay. Look at the night. You see what a dark night, what clouds, what a
wind has risen. I hid here under the willow waiting for you. And as GodвЂ™s
above, I suddenly thought, why go on in misery any longer, what is there
to wait for? Here I have a willow, a handkerchief, a shirt, I can twist
them into a rope in a minute, and braces besides, and why go on burdening
the earth, dishonoring it with my vile presence? And then I heard you
comingвЂ”Heavens, it was as though something flew down to me suddenly. So
there is a man, then, whom I love. Here he is, that man, my dear little
brother, whom I love more than any one in the world, the only one I love
in the world. And I loved you so much, so much at that moment that I
thought, вЂIвЂ™ll fall on his neck at once.вЂ™ Then a stupid idea struck me, to
have a joke with you and scare you. I shouted, like a fool, вЂYour money!вЂ™
Forgive my fooleryвЂ”it was only nonsense, and thereвЂ™s nothing unseemly in
my soul.... Damn it all, tell me whatвЂ™s happened. What did she say? Strike
me, crush me, donвЂ™t spare me! Was she furious?вЂќ

вЂњNo, not that.... There was nothing like that, Mitya. ThereвЂ”I found them
both there.вЂќ

вЂњBoth? Whom?вЂќ

вЂњGrushenka at Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s.вЂќ

Dmitri was struck dumb.

вЂњImpossible!вЂќ he cried. вЂњYouвЂ™re raving! Grushenka with her?вЂќ

Alyosha described all that had happened from the moment he went in to
Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s. He was ten minutes telling his story. He canвЂ™t be
said to have told it fluently and consecutively, but he seemed to make it
clear, not omitting any word or action of significance, and vividly
describing, often in one word, his own sensations. Dmitri listened in
silence, gazing at him with a terrible fixed stare, but it was clear to
Alyosha that he understood it all, and had grasped every point. But as the
story went on, his face became not merely gloomy, but menacing. He
scowled, he clenched his teeth, and his fixed stare became still more
rigid, more concentrated, more terrible, when suddenly, with incredible
rapidity, his wrathful, savage face changed, his tightly compressed lips
parted, and Dmitri Fyodorovitch broke into uncontrolled, spontaneous
laughter. He literally shook with laughter. For a long time he could not
speak.

вЂњSo she wouldnвЂ™t kiss her hand! So she didnвЂ™t kiss it; so she ran away!вЂќ
he kept exclaiming with hysterical delight; insolent delight it might have
been called, if it had not been so spontaneous. вЂњSo the other one called
her tigress! And a tigress she is! So she ought to be flogged on a
scaffold? Yes, yes, so she ought. ThatвЂ™s just what I think; she ought to
have been long ago. ItвЂ™s like this, brother, let her be punished, but I
must get better first. I understand the queen of impudence. ThatвЂ™s her all
over! You saw her all over in that handвЂђkissing, the sheвЂђdevil! SheвЂ™s
magnificent in her own line! So she ran home? IвЂ™ll goвЂ”ahвЂ”IвЂ™ll run to her!
Alyosha, donвЂ™t blame me, I agree that hanging is too good for her.вЂќ

вЂњBut Katerina Ivanovna!вЂќ exclaimed Alyosha sorrowfully.

вЂњI see her, too! I see right through her, as IвЂ™ve never done before! ItвЂ™s
a regular discovery of the four continents of the world, that is, of the
five! What a thing to do! ThatвЂ™s just like Katya, who was not afraid to
face a coarse, unmannerly officer and risk a deadly insult on a generous
impulse to save her father! But the pride, the recklessness, the defiance
of fate, the unbounded defiance! You say that aunt tried to stop her? That
aunt, you know, is overbearing, herself. SheвЂ™s the sister of the generalвЂ™s
widow in Moscow, and even more stuckвЂђup than she. But her husband was
caught stealing government money. He lost everything, his estate and all,
and the proud wife had to lower her colors, and hasnвЂ™t raised them since.
So she tried to prevent Katya, but she wouldnвЂ™t listen to her! She thinks
she can overcome everything, that everything will give way to her. She
thought she could bewitch Grushenka if she liked, and she believed it
herself: she plays a part to herself, and whose fault is it? Do you think
she kissed GrushenkaвЂ™s hand first, on purpose, with a motive? No, she
really was fascinated by Grushenka, thatвЂ™s to say, not by Grushenka, but
by her own dream, her own delusionвЂ”because it was _her_ dream, _her_
delusion! Alyosha, darling, how did you escape from them, those women? Did
you pick up your cassock and run? Ha ha ha!вЂќ

вЂњBrother, you donвЂ™t seem to have noticed how youвЂ™ve insulted Katerina
Ivanovna by telling Grushenka about that day. And she flung it in her face
just now that she had gone to gentlemen in secret to sell her beauty!
Brother, what could be worse than that insult?вЂќ

What worried Alyosha more than anything was that, incredible as it seemed,
his brother appeared pleased at Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s humiliation.

вЂњBah!вЂќ Dmitri frowned fiercely, and struck his forehead with his hand. He
only now realized it, though Alyosha had just told him of the insult, and
Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s cry: вЂњYour brother is a scoundrel!вЂќ

вЂњYes, perhaps, I really did tell Grushenka about that вЂfatal day,вЂ™ as
Katya calls it. Yes, I did tell her, I remember! It was that time at
Mokroe. I was drunk, the gypsies were singing.... But I was sobbing. I was
sobbing then, kneeling and praying to KatyaвЂ™s image, and Grushenka
understood it. She understood it all then. I remember, she cried
herself.... Damn it all! But itвЂ™s bound to be so now.... Then she cried,
but now вЂthe dagger in the heartвЂ™! ThatвЂ™s how women are.вЂќ

He looked down and sank into thought.

вЂњYes, I am a scoundrel, a thorough scoundrel!вЂќ he said suddenly, in a
gloomy voice. вЂњIt doesnвЂ™t matter whether I cried or not, IвЂ™m a scoundrel!
Tell her I accept the name, if thatвЂ™s any comfort. Come, thatвЂ™s enough.
GoodвЂђby. ItвЂ™s no use talking! ItвЂ™s not amusing. You go your way and I
mine. And I donвЂ™t want to see you again except as a last resource. GoodвЂђ
by, Alexey!вЂќ

He warmly pressed AlyoshaвЂ™s hand, and still looking down, without raising
his head, as though tearing himself away, turned rapidly towards the town.

Alyosha looked after him, unable to believe he would go away so abruptly.

вЂњStay, Alexey, one more confession to you alone!вЂќ cried Dmitri, suddenly
turning back. вЂњLook at me. Look at me well. You see here, hereвЂ”thereвЂ™s
terrible disgrace in store for me.вЂќ (As he said вЂњhere,вЂќ Dmitri struck his
chest with his fist with a strange air, as though the dishonor lay
precisely on his chest, in some spot, in a pocket, perhaps, or hanging
round his neck.) вЂњYou know me now, a scoundrel, an avowed scoundrel, but
let me tell you that IвЂ™ve never done anything before and never shall
again, anything that can compare in baseness with the dishonor which I
bear now at this very minute on my breast, here, here, which will come to
pass, though IвЂ™m perfectly free to stop it. I can stop it or carry it
through, note that. Well, let me tell you, I shall carry it through. I
shanвЂ™t stop it. I told you everything just now, but I didnвЂ™t tell you
this, because even I had not brass enough for it. I can still pull up; if
I do, I can give back the full half of my lost honor toвЂђmorrow. But I
shanвЂ™t pull up. I shall carry out my base plan, and you can bear witness
that I told you so beforehand. Darkness and destruction! No need to
explain. YouвЂ™ll find out in due time. The filthy backвЂђalley and the sheвЂђ
devil. GoodвЂђby. DonвЂ™t pray for me, IвЂ™m not worth it. And thereвЂ™s no need,
no need at all.... I donвЂ™t need it! Away!вЂќ

And he suddenly retreated, this time finally. Alyosha went towards the
monastery.

вЂњWhat? I shall never see him again! What is he saying?вЂќ he wondered
wildly. вЂњWhy, I shall certainly see him toвЂђmorrow. I shall look him up. I
shall make a point of it. What does he mean?вЂќ

                  вЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђ

He went round the monastery, and crossed the pineвЂђwood to the hermitage.
The door was opened to him, though no one was admitted at that hour. There
was a tremor in his heart as he went into Father ZossimaвЂ™s cell.

вЂњWhy, why, had he gone forth? Why had he sent him into the world? Here was
peace. Here was holiness. But there was confusion, there was darkness in
which one lost oneвЂ™s way and went astray at once....вЂќ

In the cell he found the novice Porfiry and Father PaГЇssy, who came every
hour to inquire after Father Zossima. Alyosha learnt with alarm that he
was getting worse and worse. Even his usual discourse with the brothers
could not take place that day. As a rule every evening after service the
monks flocked into Father ZossimaвЂ™s cell, and all confessed aloud their
sins of the day, their sinful thoughts and temptations; even their
disputes, if there had been any. Some confessed kneeling. The elder
absolved, reconciled, exhorted, imposed penance, blessed, and dismissed
them. It was against this general вЂњconfessionвЂќ that the opponents of
вЂњeldersвЂќ protested, maintaining that it was a profanation of the sacrament
of confession, almost a sacrilege, though this was quite a different
thing. They even represented to the diocesan authorities that such
confessions attained no good object, but actually to a large extent led to
sin and temptation. Many of the brothers disliked going to the elder, and
went against their own will because every one went, and for fear they
should be accused of pride and rebellious ideas. People said that some of
the monks agreed beforehand, saying, вЂњIвЂ™ll confess I lost my temper with
you this morning, and you confirm it,вЂќ simply in order to have something
to say. Alyosha knew that this actually happened sometimes. He knew, too,
that there were among the monks some who deeply resented the fact that
letters from relations were habitually taken to the elder, to be opened
and read by him before those to whom they were addressed.

It was assumed, of course, that all this was done freely, and in good
faith, by way of voluntary submission and salutary guidance. But, in fact,
there was sometimes no little insincerity, and much that was false and
strained in this practice. Yet the older and more experienced of the monks
adhered to their opinion, arguing that вЂњfor those who have come within
these walls sincerely seeking salvation, such obedience and sacrifice will
certainly be salutary and of great benefit; those, on the other hand, who
find it irksome, and repine, are no true monks, and have made a mistake in
entering the monasteryвЂ”their proper place is in the world. Even in the
temple one cannot be safe from sin and the devil. So it was no good taking
it too much into account.вЂќ

вЂњHe is weaker, a drowsiness has come over him,вЂќ Father PaГЇssy whispered to
Alyosha, as he blessed him. вЂњItвЂ™s difficult to rouse him. And he must not
be roused. He waked up for five minutes, sent his blessing to the
brothers, and begged their prayers for him at night. He intends to take
the sacrament again in the morning. He remembered you, Alexey. He asked
whether you had gone away, and was told that you were in the town. вЂI
blessed him for that work,вЂ™ he said, вЂhis place is there, not here, for
awhile.вЂ™ Those were his words about you. He remembered you lovingly, with
anxiety; do you understand how he honored you? But how is it that he has
decided that you shall spend some time in the world? He must have foreseen
something in your destiny! Understand, Alexey, that if you return to the
world, it must be to do the duty laid upon you by your elder, and not for
frivolous vanity and worldly pleasures.вЂќ

Father PaГЇssy went out. Alyosha had no doubt that Father Zossima was
dying, though he might live another day or two. Alyosha firmly and
ardently resolved that in spite of his promises to his father, the
Hohlakovs, and Katerina Ivanovna, he would not leave the monastery next
day, but would remain with his elder to the end. His heart glowed with
love, and he reproached himself bitterly for having been able for one
instant to forget him whom he had left in the monastery on his deathbed,
and whom he honored above every one in the world. He went into Father
ZossimaвЂ™s bedroom, knelt down, and bowed to the ground before the elder,
who slept quietly without stirring, with regular, hardly audible breathing
and a peaceful face.

Alyosha returned to the other room, where Father Zossima had received his
guests in the morning. Taking off his boots, he lay down on the hard,
narrow, leathern sofa, which he had long used as a bed, bringing nothing
but a pillow. The mattress, about which his father had shouted to him that
morning, he had long forgotten to lie on. He took off his cassock, which
he used as a covering. But before going to bed, he fell on his knees and
prayed a long time. In his fervent prayer he did not beseech God to
lighten his darkness but only thirsted for the joyous emotion, which
always visited his soul after the praise and adoration, of which his
evening prayer usually consisted. That joy always brought him light
untroubled sleep. As he was praying, he suddenly felt in his pocket the
little pink note the servant had handed him as he left Katerina
IvanovnaвЂ™s. He was disturbed, but finished his prayer. Then, after some
hesitation, he opened the envelope. In it was a letter to him, signed by
Lise, the young daughter of Madame Hohlakov, who had laughed at him before
the elder in the morning.

вЂњAlexey Fyodorovitch,вЂќ she wrote, вЂњI am writing to you without any oneвЂ™s
knowledge, even mammaвЂ™s, and I know how wrong it is. But I cannot live
without telling you the feeling that has sprung up in my heart, and this
no one but us two must know for a time. But how am I to say what I want so
much to tell you? Paper, they say, does not blush, but I assure you itвЂ™s
not true and that itвЂ™s blushing just as I am now, all over. Dear Alyosha,
I love you, IвЂ™ve loved you from my childhood, since our Moscow days, when
you were very different from what you are now, and I shall love you all my
life. My heart has chosen you, to unite our lives, and pass them together
till our old age. Of course, on condition that you will leave the
monastery. As for our age we will wait for the time fixed by the law. By
that time I shall certainly be quite strong, I shall be walking and
dancing. There can be no doubt of that.

вЂњYou see how IвЂ™ve thought of everything. ThereвЂ™s only one thing I canвЂ™t
imagine: what youвЂ™ll think of me when you read this. IвЂ™m always laughing
and being naughty. I made you angry this morning, but I assure you before
I took up my pen, I prayed before the Image of the Mother of God, and now
IвЂ™m praying, and almost crying.

вЂњMy secret is in your hands. When you come toвЂђmorrow, I donвЂ™t know how I
shall look at you. Ah, Alexey Fyodorovitch, what if I canвЂ™t restrain
myself like a silly and laugh when I look at you as I did toвЂђday. YouвЂ™ll
think IвЂ™m a nasty girl making fun of you, and you wonвЂ™t believe my letter.
And so I beg you, dear one, if youвЂ™ve any pity for me, when you come toвЂђ
morrow, donвЂ™t look me straight in the face, for if I meet your eyes, it
will be sure to make me laugh, especially as youвЂ™ll be in that long gown.
I feel cold all over when I think of it, so when you come, donвЂ™t look at
me at all for a time, look at mamma or at the window....

вЂњHere IвЂ™ve written you a loveвЂђletter. Oh, dear, what have I done? Alyosha,
donвЂ™t despise me, and if IвЂ™ve done something very horrid and wounded you,
forgive me. Now the secret of my reputation, ruined perhaps for ever, is
in your hands.

вЂњI shall certainly cry toвЂђday. GoodвЂђby till our meeting, our _awful_
meeting.вЂ”LISE.

вЂњP.S.вЂ”Alyosha! You must, must, must come!вЂ”LISE.вЂќ

Alyosha read the note in amazement, read it through twice, thought a
little, and suddenly laughed a soft, sweet laugh. He started. That laugh
seemed to him sinful. But a minute later he laughed again just as softly
and happily. He slowly replaced the note in the envelope, crossed himself
and lay down. The agitation in his heart passed at once. вЂњGod, have mercy
upon all of them, have all these unhappy and turbulent souls in Thy
keeping, and set them in the right path. All ways are Thine. Save them
according to Thy wisdom. Thou art love. Thou wilt send joy to all!вЂќ
Alyosha murmured, crossing himself, and falling into peaceful sleep.





PART II




Book IV. Lacerations



Chapter I. Father Ferapont


Alyosha was roused early, before daybreak. Father Zossima woke up feeling
very weak, though he wanted to get out of bed and sit up in a chair. His
mind was quite clear; his face looked very tired, yet bright and almost
joyful. It wore an expression of gayety, kindness and cordiality. вЂњMaybe I
shall not live through the coming day,вЂќ he said to Alyosha. Then he
desired to confess and take the sacrament at once. He always confessed to
Father PaГЇssy. After taking the communion, the service of extreme unction
followed. The monks assembled and the cell was gradually filled up by the
inmates of the hermitage. Meantime it was daylight. People began coming
from the monastery. After the service was over the elder desired to kiss
and take leave of every one. As the cell was so small the earlier visitors
withdrew to make room for others. Alyosha stood beside the elder, who was
seated again in his armвЂђchair. He talked as much as he could. Though his
voice was weak, it was fairly steady.

вЂњIвЂ™ve been teaching you so many years, and therefore IвЂ™ve been talking
aloud so many years, that IвЂ™ve got into the habit of talking, and so much
so that itвЂ™s almost more difficult for me to hold my tongue than to talk,
even now, in spite of my weakness, dear Fathers and brothers,вЂќ he jested,
looking with emotion at the group round him.

Alyosha remembered afterwards something of what he said to them. But
though he spoke out distinctly and his voice was fairly steady, his speech
was somewhat disconnected. He spoke of many things, he seemed anxious
before the moment of death to say everything he had not said in his life,
and not simply for the sake of instructing them, but as though thirsting
to share with all men and all creation his joy and ecstasy, and once more
in his life to open his whole heart.

вЂњLove one another, Fathers,вЂќ said Father Zossima, as far as Alyosha could
remember afterwards. вЂњLove GodвЂ™s people. Because we have come here and
shut ourselves within these walls, we are no holier than those that are
outside, but on the contrary, from the very fact of coming here, each of
us has confessed to himself that he is worse than others, than all men on
earth.... And the longer the monk lives in his seclusion, the more keenly
he must recognize that. Else he would have had no reason to come here.
When he realizes that he is not only worse than others, but that he is
responsible to all men for all and everything, for all human sins,
national and individual, only then the aim of our seclusion is attained.
For know, dear ones, that every one of us is undoubtedly responsible for
all men and everything on earth, not merely through the general sinfulness
of creation, but each one personally for all mankind and every individual
man. This knowledge is the crown of life for the monk and for every man.
For monks are not a special sort of men, but only what all men ought to
be. Only through that knowledge, our heart grows soft with infinite,
universal, inexhaustible love. Then every one of you will have the power
to win over the whole world by love and to wash away the sins of the world
with your tears.... Each of you keep watch over your heart and confess
your sins to yourself unceasingly. Be not afraid of your sins, even when
perceiving them, if only there be penitence, but make no conditions with
God. Again I say, Be not proud. Be proud neither to the little nor to the
great. Hate not those who reject you, who insult you, who abuse and
slander you. Hate not the atheists, the teachers of evil, the
materialistsвЂ”and I mean not only the good onesвЂ”for there are many good
ones among them, especially in our dayвЂ”hate not even the wicked ones.
Remember them in your prayers thus: Save, O Lord, all those who have none
to pray for them, save too all those who will not pray. And add: it is not
in pride that I make this prayer, O Lord, for I am lower than all men....
Love GodвЂ™s people, let not strangers draw away the flock, for if you
slumber in your slothfulness and disdainful pride, or worse still, in
covetousness, they will come from all sides and draw away your flock.
Expound the Gospel to the people unceasingly ... be not extortionate....
Do not love gold and silver, do not hoard them.... Have faith. Cling to
the banner and raise it on high.вЂќ

But the elder spoke more disconnectedly than Alyosha reported his words
afterwards. Sometimes he broke off altogether, as though to take breath,
and recover his strength, but he was in a sort of ecstasy. They heard him
with emotion, though many wondered at his words and found them obscure....
Afterwards all remembered those words.

When Alyosha happened for a moment to leave the cell, he was struck by the
general excitement and suspense in the monks who were crowding about it.
This anticipation showed itself in some by anxiety, in others by devout
solemnity. All were expecting that some marvel would happen immediately
after the elderвЂ™s death. Their suspense was, from one point of view,
almost frivolous, but even the most austere of the monks were affected by
it. Father PaГЇssyвЂ™s face looked the gravest of all.

Alyosha was mysteriously summoned by a monk to see Rakitin, who had
arrived from town with a singular letter for him from Madame Hohlakov. In
it she informed Alyosha of a strange and very opportune incident. It
appeared that among the women who had come on the previous day to receive
Father ZossimaвЂ™s blessing, there had been an old woman from the town, a
sergeantвЂ™s widow, called Prohorovna. She had inquired whether she might
pray for the rest of the soul of her son, Vassenka, who had gone to
Irkutsk, and had sent her no news for over a year. To which Father Zossima
had answered sternly, forbidding her to do so, and saying that to pray for
the living as though they were dead was a kind of sorcery. He afterwards
forgave her on account of her ignorance, and added, вЂњas though reading the
book of the futureвЂќ (this was Madame HohlakovвЂ™s expression), words of
comfort: вЂњthat her son Vassya was certainly alive and he would either come
himself very shortly or send a letter, and that she was to go home and
expect him.вЂќ And вЂњWould you believe it?вЂќ exclaimed Madame Hohlakov
enthusiastically, вЂњthe prophecy has been fulfilled literally indeed, and
more than that.вЂќ Scarcely had the old woman reached home when they gave
her a letter from Siberia which had been awaiting her. But that was not
all; in the letter written on the road from Ekaterinenburg, Vassya
informed his mother that he was returning to Russia with an official, and
that three weeks after her receiving the letter he hoped вЂњto embrace his
mother.вЂќ

Madame Hohlakov warmly entreated Alyosha to report this new вЂњmiracle of
predictionвЂќ to the Superior and all the brotherhood. вЂњAll, all, ought to
know of it!вЂќ she concluded. The letter had been written in haste, the
excitement of the writer was apparent in every line of it. But Alyosha had
no need to tell the monks, for all knew of it already. Rakitin had
commissioned the monk who brought his message вЂњto inform most respectfully
his reverence Father PaГЇssy, that he, Rakitin, has a matter to speak of
with him, of such gravity that he dare not defer it for a moment, and
humbly begs forgiveness for his presumption.вЂќ As the monk had given the
message to Father PaГЇssy before that to Alyosha, the latter found after
reading the letter, there was nothing left for him to do but to hand it to
Father PaГЇssy in confirmation of the story.

And even that austere and cautious man, though he frowned as he read the
news of the вЂњmiracle,вЂќ could not completely restrain some inner emotion.
His eyes gleamed, and a grave and solemn smile came into his lips.

вЂњWe shall see greater things!вЂќ broke from him.

вЂњWe shall see greater things, greater things yet!вЂќ the monks around
repeated.

But Father PaГЇssy, frowning again, begged all of them, at least for a
time, not to speak of the matter вЂњtill it be more fully confirmed, seeing
there is so much credulity among those of this world, and indeed this
might well have chanced naturally,вЂќ he added, prudently, as it were to
satisfy his conscience, though scarcely believing his own disavowal, a
fact his listeners very clearly perceived.

Within the hour the вЂњmiracleвЂќ was of course known to the whole monastery,
and many visitors who had come for the mass. No one seemed more impressed
by it than the monk who had come the day before from St. Sylvester, from
the little monastery of Obdorsk in the far North. It was he who had been
standing near Madame Hohlakov the previous day and had asked Father
Zossima earnestly, referring to the вЂњhealingвЂќ of the ladyвЂ™s daughter, вЂњHow
can you presume to do such things?вЂќ

He was now somewhat puzzled and did not know whom to believe. The evening
before he had visited Father Ferapont in his cell apart, behind the
apiary, and had been greatly impressed and overawed by the visit. This
Father Ferapont was that aged monk so devout in fasting and observing
silence who has been mentioned already, as antagonistic to Father Zossima
and the whole institution of вЂњelders,вЂќ which he regarded as a pernicious
and frivolous innovation. He was a very formidable opponent, although from
his practice of silence he scarcely spoke a word to any one. What made him
formidable was that a number of monks fully shared his feeling, and many
of the visitors looked upon him as a great saint and ascetic, although
they had no doubt that he was crazy. But it was just his craziness
attracted them.

Father Ferapont never went to see the elder. Though he lived in the
hermitage they did not worry him to keep its regulations, and this too
because he behaved as though he were crazy. He was seventyвЂђfive or more,
and he lived in a corner beyond the apiary in an old decaying wooden cell
which had been built long ago for another great ascetic, Father Iona, who
had lived to be a hundred and five, and of whose saintly doings many
curious stories were still extant in the monastery and the neighborhood.

Father Ferapont had succeeded in getting himself installed in this same
solitary cell seven years previously. It was simply a peasantвЂ™s hut,
though it looked like a chapel, for it contained an extraordinary number
of ikons with lamps perpetually burning before themвЂ”which men brought to
the monastery as offerings to God. Father Ferapont had been appointed to
look after them and keep the lamps burning. It was said (and indeed it was
true) that he ate only two pounds of bread in three days. The beekeeper,
who lived close by the apiary, used to bring him the bread every three
days, and even to this man who waited upon him, Father Ferapont rarely
uttered a word. The four pounds of bread, together with the sacrament
bread, regularly sent him on Sundays after the late mass by the Father
Superior, made up his weekly rations. The water in his jug was changed
every day. He rarely appeared at mass. Visitors who came to do him homage
saw him sometimes kneeling all day long at prayer without looking round.
If he addressed them, he was brief, abrupt, strange, and almost always
rude. On very rare occasions, however, he would talk to visitors, but for
the most part he would utter some one strange saying which was a complete
riddle, and no entreaties would induce him to pronounce a word in
explanation. He was not a priest, but a simple monk. There was a strange
belief, chiefly however among the most ignorant, that Father Ferapont had
communication with heavenly spirits and would only converse with them, and
so was silent with men.

The monk from Obdorsk, having been directed to the apiary by the
beekeeper, who was also a very silent and surly monk, went to the corner
where Father FerapontвЂ™s cell stood. вЂњMaybe he will speak as you are a
stranger and maybe youвЂ™ll get nothing out of him,вЂќ the beekeeper had
warned him. The monk, as he related afterwards, approached in the utmost
apprehension. It was rather late in the evening. Father Ferapont was
sitting at the door of his cell on a low bench. A huge old elm was lightly
rustling overhead. There was an evening freshness in the air. The monk
from Obdorsk bowed down before the saint and asked his blessing.

вЂњDo you want me to bow down to you, monk?вЂќ said Father Ferapont. вЂњGet up!вЂќ

The monk got up.

вЂњBlessing, be blessed! Sit beside me. Where have you come from?вЂќ

What most struck the poor monk was the fact that in spite of his strict
fasting and great age, Father Ferapont still looked a vigorous old man. He
was tall, held himself erect, and had a thin, but fresh and healthy face.
There was no doubt he still had considerable strength. He was of athletic
build. In spite of his great age he was not even quite gray, and still had
very thick hair and a full beard, both of which had once been black. His
eyes were gray, large and luminous, but strikingly prominent. He spoke
with a broad accent. He was dressed in a peasantвЂ™s long reddish coat of
coarse convict cloth (as it used to be called) and had a stout rope round
his waist. His throat and chest were bare. Beneath his coat, his shirt of
the coarsest linen showed almost black with dirt, not having been changed
for months. They said that he wore irons weighing thirty pounds under his
coat. His stockingless feet were thrust in old slippers almost dropping to
pieces.

вЂњFrom the little Obdorsk monastery, from St. Sylvester,вЂќ the monk answered
humbly, whilst his keen and inquisitive, but rather frightened little eyes
kept watch on the hermit.

вЂњI have been at your SylvesterвЂ™s. I used to stay there. Is Sylvester
well?вЂќ

The monk hesitated.

вЂњYou are a senseless lot! How do you keep the fasts?вЂќ

вЂњOur dietary is according to the ancient conventual rules. During Lent
there are no meals provided for Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. For Tuesday
and Thursday we have white bread, stewed fruit with honey, wild berries,
or salt cabbage and wholemeal stirabout. On Saturday white cabbage soup,
noodles with peas, kasha, all with hemp oil. On weekdays we have dried
fish and kasha with the cabbage soup. From Monday till Saturday evening,
six whole days in Holy Week, nothing is cooked, and we have only bread and
water, and that sparingly; if possible not taking food every day, just the
same as is ordered for first week in Lent. On Good Friday nothing is
eaten. In the same way on the Saturday we have to fast till three oвЂ™clock,
and then take a little bread and water and drink a single cup of wine. On
Holy Thursday we drink wine and have something cooked without oil or not
cooked at all, inasmuch as the Laodicean council lays down for Holy
Thursday: вЂIt is unseemly by remitting the fast on the Holy Thursday to
dishonor the whole of Lent!вЂ™ This is how we keep the fast. But what is
that compared with you, holy Father,вЂќ added the monk, growing more
confident, вЂњfor all the year round, even at Easter, you take nothing but
bread and water, and what we should eat in two days lasts you full seven.
ItвЂ™s truly marvelousвЂ”your great abstinence.вЂќ

вЂњAnd mushrooms?вЂќ asked Father Ferapont, suddenly.

вЂњMushrooms?вЂќ repeated the surprised monk.

вЂњYes. I can give up their bread, not needing it at all, and go away into
the forest and live there on the mushrooms or the berries, but they canвЂ™t
give up their bread here, wherefore they are in bondage to the devil.
Nowadays the unclean deny that there is need of such fasting. Haughty and
unclean is their judgment.вЂќ

вЂњOch, true,вЂќ sighed the monk.

вЂњAnd have you seen devils among them?вЂќ asked Ferapont.

вЂњAmong them? Among whom?вЂќ asked the monk, timidly.

вЂњI went to the Father Superior on Trinity Sunday last year, I havenвЂ™t been
since. I saw a devil sitting on one manвЂ™s chest hiding under his cassock,
only his horns poked out; another had one peeping out of his pocket with
such sharp eyes, he was afraid of me; another settled in the unclean belly
of one, another was hanging round a manвЂ™s neck, and so he was carrying him
about without seeing him.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ”can see spirits?вЂќ the monk inquired.

вЂњI tell you I can see, I can see through them. When I was coming out from
the SuperiorвЂ™s I saw one hiding from me behind the door, and a big one, a
yard and a half or more high, with a thick long gray tail, and the tip of
his tail was in the crack of the door and I was quick and slammed the
door, pinching his tail in it. He squealed and began to struggle, and I
made the sign of the cross over him three times. And he died on the spot
like a crushed spider. He must have rotted there in the corner and be
stinking, but they donвЂ™t see, they donвЂ™t smell it. ItвЂ™s a year since I
have been there. I reveal it to you, as you are a stranger.вЂќ

вЂњYour words are terrible! But, holy and blessed Father,вЂќ said the monk,
growing bolder and bolder, вЂњis it true, as they noise abroad even to
distant lands about you, that you are in continual communication with the
Holy Ghost?вЂќ

вЂњHe does fly down at times.вЂќ

вЂњHow does he fly down? In what form?вЂќ

вЂњAs a bird.вЂќ

вЂњThe Holy Ghost in the form of a dove?вЂќ

вЂњThereвЂ™s the Holy Ghost and thereвЂ™s the Holy Spirit. The Holy Spirit can
appear as other birdsвЂ”sometimes as a swallow, sometimes a goldfinch and
sometimes as a blueвЂђtit.вЂќ

вЂњHow do you know him from an ordinary tit?вЂќ

вЂњHe speaks.вЂќ

вЂњHow does he speak, in what language?вЂќ

вЂњHuman language.вЂќ

вЂњAnd what does he tell you?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, toвЂђday he told me that a fool would visit me and would ask me
unseemly questions. You want to know too much, monk.вЂќ

вЂњTerrible are your words, most holy and blessed Father,вЂќ the monk shook
his head. But there was a doubtful look in his frightened little eyes.

вЂњDo you see this tree?вЂќ asked Father Ferapont, after a pause.

вЂњI do, blessed Father.вЂќ

вЂњYou think itвЂ™s an elm, but for me it has another shape.вЂќ

вЂњWhat sort of shape?вЂќ inquired the monk, after a pause of vain
expectation.

вЂњIt happens at night. You see those two branches? In the night it is
Christ holding out His arms to me and seeking me with those arms, I see it
clearly and tremble. ItвЂ™s terrible, terrible!вЂќ

вЂњWhat is there terrible if itвЂ™s Christ Himself?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, HeвЂ™ll snatch me up and carry me away.вЂќ

вЂњAlive?вЂќ

вЂњIn the spirit and glory of Elijah, havenвЂ™t you heard? He will take me in
His arms and bear me away.вЂќ

Though the monk returned to the cell he was sharing with one of the
brothers, in considerable perplexity of mind, he still cherished at heart
a greater reverence for Father Ferapont than for Father Zossima. He was
strongly in favor of fasting, and it was not strange that one who kept so
rigid a fast as Father Ferapont should вЂњsee marvels.вЂќ His words seemed
certainly queer, but God only could tell what was hidden in those words,
and were not worse words and acts commonly seen in those who have
sacrificed their intellects for the glory of God? The pinching of the
devilвЂ™s tail he was ready and eager to believe, and not only in the
figurative sense. Besides he had, before visiting the monastery, a strong
prejudice against the institution of вЂњelders,вЂќ which he only knew of by
hearsay and believed to be a pernicious innovation. Before he had been
long at the monastery, he had detected the secret murmurings of some
shallow brothers who disliked the institution. He was, besides, a
meddlesome, inquisitive man, who poked his nose into everything. This was
why the news of the fresh вЂњmiracleвЂќ performed by Father Zossima reduced
him to extreme perplexity. Alyosha remembered afterwards how their
inquisitive guest from Obdorsk had been continually flitting to and fro
from one group to another, listening and asking questions among the monks
that were crowding within and without the elderвЂ™s cell. But he did not pay
much attention to him at the time, and only recollected it afterwards.

He had no thought to spare for it indeed, for when Father Zossima, feeling
tired again, had gone back to bed, he thought of Alyosha as he was closing
his eyes, and sent for him. Alyosha ran at once. There was no one else in
the cell but Father PaГЇssy, Father Iosif, and the novice Porfiry. The
elder, opening his weary eyes and looking intently at Alyosha, asked him
suddenly:

вЂњAre your people expecting you, my son?вЂќ

Alyosha hesitated.

вЂњHavenвЂ™t they need of you? DidnвЂ™t you promise some one yesterday to see
them toвЂђday?вЂќ

вЂњI did promiseвЂ”to my fatherвЂ”my brothersвЂ”others too.вЂќ

вЂњYou see, you must go. DonвЂ™t grieve. Be sure I shall not die without your
being by to hear my last word. To you I will say that word, my son, it
will be my last gift to you. To you, dear son, because you love me. But
now go to keep your promise.вЂќ

Alyosha immediately obeyed, though it was hard to go. But the promise that
he should hear his last word on earth, that it should be the last gift to
him, Alyosha, sent a thrill of rapture through his soul. He made haste
that he might finish what he had to do in the town and return quickly.
Father PaГЇssy, too, uttered some words of exhortation which moved and
surprised him greatly. He spoke as they left the cell together.

вЂњRemember, young man, unceasingly,вЂќ Father PaГЇssy began, without preface,
вЂњthat the science of this world, which has become a great power, has,
especially in the last century, analyzed everything divine handed down to
us in the holy books. After this cruel analysis the learned of this world
have nothing left of all that was sacred of old. But they have only
analyzed the parts and overlooked the whole, and indeed their blindness is
marvelous. Yet the whole still stands steadfast before their eyes, and the
gates of hell shall not prevail against it. Has it not lasted nineteen
centuries, is it not still a living, a moving power in the individual soul
and in the masses of people? It is still as strong and living even in the
souls of atheists, who have destroyed everything! For even those who have
renounced Christianity and attack it, in their inmost being still follow
the Christian ideal, for hitherto neither their subtlety nor the ardor of
their hearts has been able to create a higher ideal of man and of virtue
than the ideal given by Christ of old. When it has been attempted, the
result has been only grotesque. Remember this especially, young man, since
you are being sent into the world by your departing elder. Maybe,
remembering this great day, you will not forget my words, uttered from the
heart for your guidance, seeing you are young, and the temptations of the
world are great and beyond your strength to endure. Well, now go, my
orphan.вЂќ

With these words Father PaГЇssy blessed him. As Alyosha left the monastery
and thought them over, he suddenly realized that he had met a new and
unexpected friend, a warmly loving teacher, in this austere monk who had
hitherto treated him sternly. It was as though Father Zossima had
bequeathed him to him at his death, and вЂњperhaps thatвЂ™s just what had
passed between them,вЂќ Alyosha thought suddenly. The philosophic
reflections he had just heard so unexpectedly testified to the warmth of
Father PaГЇssyвЂ™s heart. He was in haste to arm the boyвЂ™s mind for conflict
with temptation and to guard the young soul left in his charge with the
strongest defense he could imagine.



Chapter II. At His FatherвЂ™s


First of all, Alyosha went to his father. On the way he remembered that
his father had insisted the day before that he should come without his
brother Ivan seeing him. вЂњWhy so?вЂќ Alyosha wondered suddenly. вЂњEven if my
father has something to say to me alone, why should I go in unseen? Most
likely in his excitement yesterday he meant to say something different,вЂќ
he decided. Yet he was very glad when Marfa Ignatyevna, who opened the
garden gate to him (Grigory, it appeared, was ill in bed in the lodge),
told him in answer to his question that Ivan Fyodorovitch had gone out two
hours ago.

вЂњAnd my father?вЂќ

вЂњHe is up, taking his coffee,вЂќ Marfa answered somewhat dryly.

Alyosha went in. The old man was sitting alone at the table wearing
slippers and a little old overcoat. He was amusing himself by looking
through some accounts, rather inattentively however. He was quite alone in
the house, for Smerdyakov too had gone out marketing. Though he had got up
early and was trying to put a bold face on it, he looked tired and weak.
His forehead, upon which huge purple bruises had come out during the
night, was bandaged with a red handkerchief; his nose too had swollen
terribly in the night, and some smaller bruises covered it in patches,
giving his whole face a peculiarly spiteful and irritable look. The old
man was aware of this, and turned a hostile glance on Alyosha as he came
in.

вЂњThe coffee is cold,вЂќ he cried harshly; вЂњI wonвЂ™t offer you any. IвЂ™ve
ordered nothing but a Lenten fish soup toвЂђday, and I donвЂ™t invite any one
to share it. Why have you come?вЂќ

вЂњTo find out how you are,вЂќ said Alyosha.

вЂњYes. Besides, I told you to come yesterday. ItвЂ™s all of no consequence.
You need not have troubled. But I knew youвЂ™d come poking in directly.вЂќ

He said this with almost hostile feeling. At the same time he got up and
looked anxiously in the lookingвЂђglass (perhaps for the fortieth time that
morning) at his nose. He began, too, binding his red handkerchief more
becomingly on his forehead.

вЂњRedвЂ™s better. ItвЂ™s just like the hospital in a white one,вЂќ he observed
sententiously. вЂњWell, how are things over there? How is your elder?вЂќ

вЂњHe is very bad; he may die toвЂђday,вЂќ answered Alyosha. But his father had
not listened, and had forgotten his own question at once.

вЂњIvanвЂ™s gone out,вЂќ he said suddenly. вЂњHe is doing his utmost to carry off
MityaвЂ™s betrothed. ThatвЂ™s what he is staying here for,вЂќ he added
maliciously, and, twisting his mouth, looked at Alyosha.

вЂњSurely he did not tell you so?вЂќ asked Alyosha.

вЂњYes, he did, long ago. Would you believe it, he told me three weeks ago?
You donвЂ™t suppose he too came to murder me, do you? He must have had some
object in coming.вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you mean? Why do you say such things?вЂќ said Alyosha, troubled.

вЂњHe doesnвЂ™t ask for money, itвЂ™s true, but yet he wonвЂ™t get a farthing from
me. I intend living as long as possible, you may as well know, my dear
Alexey Fyodorovitch, and so I need every farthing, and the longer I live,
the more I shall need it,вЂќ he continued, pacing from one corner of the
room to the other, keeping his hands in the pockets of his loose greasy
overcoat made of yellow cotton material. вЂњI can still pass for a man at
five and fifty, but I want to pass for one for another twenty years. As I
get older, you know, I shanвЂ™t be a pretty object. The wenches wonвЂ™t come
to me of their own accord, so I shall want my money. So I am saving up
more and more, simply for myself, my dear son Alexey Fyodorovitch. You may
as well know. For I mean to go on in my sins to the end, let me tell you.
For sin is sweet; all abuse it, but all men live in it, only others do it
on the sly, and I openly. And so all the other sinners fall upon me for
being so simple. And your paradise, Alexey Fyodorovitch, is not to my
taste, let me tell you that; and itвЂ™s not the proper place for a
gentleman, your paradise, even if it exists. I believe that I fall asleep
and donвЂ™t wake up again, and thatвЂ™s all. You can pray for my soul if you
like. And if you donвЂ™t want to, donвЂ™t, damn you! ThatвЂ™s my philosophy.
Ivan talked well here yesterday, though we were all drunk. Ivan is a
conceited coxcomb, but he has no particular learning ... nor education
either. He sits silent and smiles at one without speakingвЂ”thatвЂ™s what
pulls him through.вЂќ

Alyosha listened to him in silence.

вЂњWhy wonвЂ™t he talk to me? If he does speak, he gives himself airs. Your
Ivan is a scoundrel! And IвЂ™ll marry Grushenka in a minute if I want to.
For if youвЂ™ve money, Alexey Fyodorovitch, you have only to want a thing
and you can have it. ThatвЂ™s what Ivan is afraid of, he is on the watch to
prevent me getting married and thatвЂ™s why he is egging on Mitya to marry
Grushenka himself. He hopes to keep me from Grushenka by that (as though I
should leave him my money if I donвЂ™t marry her!). Besides if Mitya marries
Grushenka, Ivan will carry off his rich betrothed, thatвЂ™s what heвЂ™s
reckoning on! He is a scoundrel, your Ivan!вЂќ

вЂњHow cross you are! ItвЂ™s because of yesterday; you had better lie down,вЂќ
said Alyosha.

вЂњThere! you say that,вЂќ the old man observed suddenly, as though it had
struck him for the first time, вЂњand I am not angry with you. But if Ivan
said it, I should be angry with him. It is only with you I have good
moments, else you know I am an illвЂђnatured man.вЂќ

вЂњYou are not illвЂђnatured, but distorted,вЂќ said Alyosha with a smile.

вЂњListen. I meant this morning to get that ruffian Mitya locked up and I
donвЂ™t know now what I shall decide about it. Of course in these
fashionable days fathers and mothers are looked upon as a prejudice, but
even now the law does not allow you to drag your old father about by the
hair, to kick him in the face in his own house, and brag of murdering him
outrightвЂ”all in the presence of witnesses. If I liked, I could crush him
and could have him locked up at once for what he did yesterday.вЂќ

вЂњThen you donвЂ™t mean to take proceedings?вЂќ

вЂњIvan has dissuaded me. I shouldnвЂ™t care about Ivan, but thereвЂ™s another
thing.вЂќ

And bending down to Alyosha, he went on in a confidential halfвЂђwhisper.

вЂњIf I send the ruffian to prison, sheвЂ™ll hear of it and run to see him at
once. But if she hears that he has beaten me, a weak old man, within an
inch of my life, she may give him up and come to me.... For thatвЂ™s her
way, everything by contraries. I know her through and through! WonвЂ™t you
have a drop of brandy? Take some cold coffee and IвЂ™ll pour a quarter of a
glass of brandy into it, itвЂ™s delicious, my boy.вЂќ

вЂњNo, thank you. IвЂ™ll take that roll with me if I may,вЂќ said Alyosha, and
taking a halfpenny French roll he put it in the pocket of his cassock.
вЂњAnd youвЂ™d better not have brandy, either,вЂќ he suggested apprehensively,
looking into the old manвЂ™s face.

вЂњYou are quite right, it irritates my nerves instead of soothing them.
Only one little glass. IвЂ™ll get it out of the cupboard.вЂќ

He unlocked the cupboard, poured out a glass, drank it, then locked the
cupboard and put the key back in his pocket.

вЂњThatвЂ™s enough. One glass wonвЂ™t kill me.вЂќ

вЂњYou see you are in a better humor now,вЂќ said Alyosha, smiling.

вЂњUm! I love you even without the brandy, but with scoundrels I am a
scoundrel. Ivan is not going to TchermashnyaвЂ”why is that? He wants to spy
how much I give Grushenka if she comes. They are all scoundrels! But I
donвЂ™t recognize Ivan, I donвЂ™t know him at all. Where does he come from? He
is not one of us in soul. As though IвЂ™d leave him anything! I shanвЂ™t leave
a will at all, you may as well know. And IвЂ™ll crush Mitya like a beetle. I
squash blackвЂђbeetles at night with my slipper; they squelch when you tread
on them. And your Mitya will squelch too. _Your_ Mitya, for you love him.
Yes, you love him and I am not afraid of your loving him. But if Ivan
loved him I should be afraid for myself at his loving him. But Ivan loves
nobody. Ivan is not one of us. People like Ivan are not our sort, my boy.
They are like a cloud of dust. When the wind blows, the dust will be
gone.... I had a silly idea in my head when I told you to come toвЂђday; I
wanted to find out from you about Mitya. If I were to hand him over a
thousand or maybe two now, would the beggarly wretch agree to take himself
off altogether for five years or, better still, thirtyвЂђfive, and without
Grushenka, and give her up once for all, eh?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ”IвЂ™ll ask him,вЂќ muttered Alyosha. вЂњIf you would give him three thousand,
perhaps heвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s nonsense! You neednвЂ™t ask him now, no need! IвЂ™ve changed my mind.
It was a nonsensical idea of mine. I wonвЂ™t give him anything, not a penny,
I want my money myself,вЂќ cried the old man, waving his hand. вЂњIвЂ™ll crush
him like a beetle without it. DonвЂ™t say anything to him or else he will
begin hoping. ThereвЂ™s nothing for you to do here, you neednвЂ™t stay. Is
that betrothed of his, Katerina Ivanovna, whom he has kept so carefully
hidden from me all this time, going to marry him or not? You went to see
her yesterday, I believe?вЂќ

вЂњNothing will induce her to abandon him.вЂќ

вЂњThere you see how dearly these fine young ladies love a rake and a
scoundrel. They are poor creatures I tell you, those pale young ladies,
very different fromвЂ”Ah, if I had his youth and the looks I had then (for I
was betterвЂђlooking than he at eight and twenty) IвЂ™d have been a conquering
hero just as he is. He is a low cad! But he shanвЂ™t have Grushenka, anyway,
he shanвЂ™t! IвЂ™ll crush him!вЂќ

His anger had returned with the last words.

вЂњYou can go. ThereвЂ™s nothing for you to do here toвЂђday,вЂќ he snapped
harshly.

Alyosha went up to say goodвЂђby to him, and kissed him on the shoulder.

вЂњWhatвЂ™s that for?вЂќ The old man was a little surprised. вЂњWe shall see each
other again, or do you think we shanвЂ™t?вЂќ

вЂњNot at all, I didnвЂ™t mean anything.вЂќ

вЂњNor did I, I did not mean anything,вЂќ said the old man, looking at him.
вЂњListen, listen,вЂќ he shouted after him, вЂњmake haste and come again and
IвЂ™ll have a fish soup for you, a fine one, not like toвЂђday. Be sure to
come! Come toвЂђmorrow, do you hear, toвЂђmorrow!вЂќ

And as soon as Alyosha had gone out of the door, he went to the cupboard
again and poured out another halfвЂђglass.

вЂњI wonвЂ™t have more!вЂќ he muttered, clearing his throat, and again he locked
the cupboard and put the key in his pocket. Then he went into his bedroom,
lay down on the bed, exhausted, and in one minute he was asleep.



Chapter III. A Meeting With The Schoolboys


вЂњThank goodness he did not ask me about Grushenka,вЂќ thought Alyosha, as he
left his fatherвЂ™s house and turned towards Madame HohlakovвЂ™s, вЂњor I might
have to tell him of my meeting with Grushenka yesterday.вЂќ

Alyosha felt painfully that since yesterday both combatants had renewed
their energies, and that their hearts had grown hard again. вЂњFather is
spiteful and angry, heвЂ™s made some plan and will stick to it. And what of
Dmitri? He too will be harder than yesterday, he too must be spiteful and
angry, and he too, no doubt, has made some plan. Oh, I must succeed in
finding him toвЂђday, whatever happens.вЂќ

But Alyosha had not long to meditate. An incident occurred on the road,
which, though apparently of little consequence, made a great impression on
him. Just after he had crossed the square and turned the corner coming out
into Mihailovsky Street, which is divided by a small ditch from the High
Street (our whole town is intersected by ditches), he saw a group of
schoolboys between the ages of nine and twelve, at the bridge. They were
going home from school, some with their bags on their shoulders, others
with leather satchels slung across them, some in short jackets, others in
little overcoats. Some even had those high boots with creases round the
ankles, such as little boys spoilt by rich fathers love to wear. The whole
group was talking eagerly about something, apparently holding a council.
Alyosha had never from his Moscow days been able to pass children without
taking notice of them, and although he was particularly fond of children
of three or thereabout, he liked schoolboys of ten and eleven too. And so,
anxious as he was toвЂђday, he wanted at once to turn aside to talk to them.
He looked into their excited rosy faces, and noticed at once that all the
boys had stones in their hands. Behind the ditch some thirty paces away,
there was another schoolboy standing by a fence. He too had a satchel at
his side. He was about ten years old, pale, delicateвЂђlooking and with
sparkling black eyes. He kept an attentive and anxious watch on the other
six, obviously his schoolfellows with whom he had just come out of school,
but with whom he had evidently had a feud.

Alyosha went up and, addressing a fair, curlyвЂђheaded, rosy boy in a black
jacket, observed:

вЂњWhen I used to wear a satchel like yours, I always used to carry it on my
left side, so as to have my right hand free, but youвЂ™ve got yours on your
right side. So it will be awkward for you to get at it.вЂќ

Alyosha had no art or premeditation in beginning with this practical
remark. But it is the only way for a grownвЂђup person to get at once into
confidential relations with a child, or still more with a group of
children. One must begin in a serious, businesslike way so as to be on a
perfectly equal footing. Alyosha understood it by instinct.

вЂњBut he is leftвЂђhanded,вЂќ another, a fine healthyвЂђlooking boy of eleven,
answered promptly. All the others stared at Alyosha.

вЂњHe even throws stones with his left hand,вЂќ observed a third.

At that instant a stone flew into the group, but only just grazed the
leftвЂђhanded boy, though it was well and vigorously thrown by the boy
standing the other side of the ditch.

вЂњGive it him, hit him back, Smurov,вЂќ they all shouted. But Smurov, the
leftвЂђhanded boy, needed no telling, and at once revenged himself; he threw
a stone, but it missed the boy and hit the ground. The boy the other side
of the ditch, the pocket of whose coat was visibly bulging with stones,
flung another stone at the group; this time it flew straight at Alyosha
and hit him painfully on the shoulder.

вЂњHe aimed it at you, he meant it for you. You are Karamazov, Karamazov!вЂќ
the boys shouted, laughing. вЂњCome, all throw at him at once!вЂќ and six
stones flew at the boy. One struck the boy on the head and he fell down,
but at once leapt up and began ferociously returning their fire. Both
sides threw stones incessantly. Many of the group had their pockets full
too.

вЂњWhat are you about! ArenвЂ™t you ashamed? Six against one! Why, youвЂ™ll kill
him,вЂќ cried Alyosha.

He ran forward and met the flying stones to screen the solitary boy. Three
or four ceased throwing for a minute.

вЂњHe began first!вЂќ cried a boy in a red shirt in an angry childish voice.
вЂњHe is a beast, he stabbed Krassotkin in class the other day with a
penknife. It bled. Krassotkin wouldnвЂ™t tell tales, but he must be
thrashed.вЂќ

вЂњBut what for? I suppose you tease him.вЂќ

вЂњThere, he sent a stone in your back again, he knows you,вЂќ cried the
children. вЂњItвЂ™s you he is throwing at now, not us. Come, all of you, at
him again, donвЂ™t miss, Smurov!вЂќ and again a fire of stones, and a very
vicious one, began. The boy the other side of the ditch was hit in the
chest; he screamed, began to cry and ran away uphill towards Mihailovsky
Street. They all shouted: вЂњAha, he is funking, he is running away. Wisp of
tow!вЂќ

вЂњYou donвЂ™t know what a beast he is, Karamazov, killing is too good for
him,вЂќ said the boy in the jacket, with flashing eyes. He seemed to be the
eldest.

вЂњWhatвЂ™s wrong with him?вЂќ asked Alyosha, вЂњis he a tellвЂђtale or what?вЂќ

The boys looked at one another as though derisively.

вЂњAre you going that way, to Mihailovsky?вЂќ the same boy went on. вЂњCatch him
up.... You see heвЂ™s stopped again, he is waiting and looking at you.вЂќ

вЂњHe is looking at you,вЂќ the other boys chimed in.

вЂњYou ask him, does he like a disheveled wisp of tow. Do you hear, ask him
that!вЂќ

There was a general burst of laughter. Alyosha looked at them, and they at
him.

вЂњDonвЂ™t go near him, heвЂ™ll hurt you,вЂќ cried Smurov in a warning voice.

вЂњI shanвЂ™t ask him about the wisp of tow, for I expect you tease him with
that question somehow. But IвЂ™ll find out from him why you hate him so.вЂќ

вЂњFind out then, find out,вЂќ cried the boys, laughing.

Alyosha crossed the bridge and walked uphill by the fence, straight
towards the boy.

вЂњYouвЂ™d better look out,вЂќ the boys called after him; вЂњhe wonвЂ™t be afraid of
you. He will stab you in a minute, on the sly, as he did Krassotkin.вЂќ

The boy waited for him without budging. Coming up to him, Alyosha saw
facing him a child of about nine years old. He was an undersized weakly
boy with a thin pale face, with large dark eyes that gazed at him
vindictively. He was dressed in a rather shabby old overcoat, which he had
monstrously outgrown. His bare arms stuck out beyond his sleeves. There
was a large patch on the right knee of his trousers, and in his right boot
just at the toe there was a big hole in the leather, carefully blackened
with ink. Both the pockets of his greatвЂђcoat were weighed down with
stones. Alyosha stopped two steps in front of him, looking inquiringly at
him. The boy, seeing at once from AlyoshaвЂ™s eyes that he wouldnвЂ™t beat
him, became less defiant, and addressed him first.

вЂњI am alone, and there are six of them. IвЂ™ll beat them all, alone!вЂќ he
said suddenly, with flashing eyes.

вЂњI think one of the stones must have hurt you badly,вЂќ observed Alyosha.

вЂњBut I hit Smurov on the head!вЂќ cried the boy.

вЂњThey told me that you know me, and that you threw a stone at me on
purpose,вЂќ said Alyosha.

The boy looked darkly at him.

вЂњI donвЂ™t know you. Do you know me?вЂќ Alyosha continued.

вЂњLet me alone!вЂќ the boy cried irritably; but he did not move, as though he
were expecting something, and again there was a vindictive light in his
eyes.

вЂњVery well, I am going,вЂќ said Alyosha; вЂњonly I donвЂ™t know you and I donвЂ™t
tease you. They told me how they tease you, but I donвЂ™t want to tease you.
GoodвЂђby!вЂќ

вЂњMonk in silk trousers!вЂќ cried the boy, following Alyosha with the same
vindictive and defiant expression, and he threw himself into an attitude
of defense, feeling sure that now Alyosha would fall upon him; but Alyosha
turned, looked at him, and walked away. He had not gone three steps before
the biggest stone the boy had in his pocket hit him a painful blow in the
back.

вЂњSo youвЂ™ll hit a man from behind! They tell the truth, then, when they say
that you attack on the sly,вЂќ said Alyosha, turning round again. This time
the boy threw a stone savagely right into AlyoshaвЂ™s face; but Alyosha just
had time to guard himself, and the stone struck him on the elbow.

вЂњArenвЂ™t you ashamed? What have I done to you?вЂќ he cried.

The boy waited in silent defiance, certain that now Alyosha would attack
him. Seeing that even now he would not, his rage was like a little wild
beastвЂ™s; he flew at Alyosha himself, and before Alyosha had time to move,
the spiteful child had seized his left hand with both of his and bit his
middle finger. He fixed his teeth in it and it was ten seconds before he
let go. Alyosha cried out with pain and pulled his finger away with all
his might. The child let go at last and retreated to his former distance.
AlyoshaвЂ™s finger had been badly bitten to the bone, close to the nail; it
began to bleed. Alyosha took out his handkerchief and bound it tightly
round his injured hand. He was a full minute bandaging it. The boy stood
waiting all the time. At last Alyosha raised his gentle eyes and looked at
him.

вЂњVery well,вЂќ he said, вЂњyou see how badly youвЂ™ve bitten me. ThatвЂ™s enough,
isnвЂ™t it? Now tell me, what have I done to you?вЂќ

The boy stared in amazement.

вЂњThough I donвЂ™t know you and itвЂ™s the first time IвЂ™ve seen you,вЂќ Alyosha
went on with the same serenity, вЂњyet I must have done something to youвЂ”you
wouldnвЂ™t have hurt me like this for nothing. So what have I done? How have
I wronged you, tell me?вЂќ

Instead of answering, the boy broke into a loud tearful wail and ran away.
Alyosha walked slowly after him towards Mihailovsky Street, and for a long
time he saw the child running in the distance as fast as ever, not turning
his head, and no doubt still keeping up his tearful wail. He made up his
mind to find him out as soon as he had time, and to solve this mystery.
Just now he had not the time.



Chapter IV. At The HohlakovsвЂ™


Alyosha soon reached Madame HohlakovвЂ™s house, a handsome stone house of
two stories, one of the finest in our town. Though Madame Hohlakov spent
most of her time in another province where she had an estate, or in
Moscow, where she had a house of her own, yet she had a house in our town
too, inherited from her forefathers. The estate in our district was the
largest of her three estates, yet she had been very little in our province
before this time. She ran out to Alyosha in the hall.

вЂњDid you get my letter about the new miracle?вЂќ She spoke rapidly and
nervously.

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњDid you show it to every one? He restored the son to his mother!вЂќ

вЂњHe is dying toвЂђday,вЂќ said Alyosha.

вЂњI have heard, I know, oh, how I long to talk to you, to you or some one,
about all this. No, to you, to you! And how sorry I am I canвЂ™t see him!
The whole town is in excitement, they are all suspense. But nowвЂ”do you
know Katerina Ivanovna is here now?вЂќ

вЂњAh, thatвЂ™s lucky,вЂќ cried Alyosha. вЂњThen I shall see her here. She told me
yesterday to be sure to come and see her toвЂђday.вЂќ

вЂњI know, I know all. IвЂ™ve heard exactly what happened yesterdayвЂ”and the
atrocious behavior of thatвЂ”creature. _CвЂ™est tragique_, and if IвЂ™d been in
her place I donвЂ™t know what I should have done. And your brother Dmitri
Fyodorovitch, what do you think of him?вЂ”my goodness! Alexey Fyodorovitch,
I am forgetting, only fancy; your brother is in there with her, not that
dreadful brother who was so shocking yesterday, but the other, Ivan
Fyodorovitch, he is sitting with her talking; they are having a serious
conversation. If you could only imagine whatвЂ™s passing between them
nowвЂ”itвЂ™s awful, I tell you itвЂ™s lacerating, itвЂ™s like some incredible tale
of horror. They are ruining their lives for no reason any one can see.
They both recognize it and revel in it. IвЂ™ve been watching for you! IвЂ™ve
been thirsting for you! ItвЂ™s too much for me, thatвЂ™s the worst of it. IвЂ™ll
tell you all about it presently, but now I must speak of something else,
the most important thingвЂ”I had quite forgotten whatвЂ™s most important. Tell
me, why has Lise been in hysterics? As soon as she heard you were here,
she began to be hysterical!вЂќ

вЂњ_Maman_, itвЂ™s you who are hysterical now, not I,вЂќ LiseвЂ™s voice caroled
through a tiny crack of the door at the side. Her voice sounded as though
she wanted to laugh, but was doing her utmost to control it. Alyosha at
once noticed the crack, and no doubt Lise was peeping through it, but that
he could not see.

вЂњAnd no wonder, Lise, no wonder ... your caprices will make me hysterical
too. But she is so ill, Alexey Fyodorovitch, she has been so ill all
night, feverish and moaning! I could hardly wait for the morning and for
Herzenstube to come. He says that he can make nothing of it, that we must
wait. Herzenstube always comes and says that he can make nothing of it. As
soon as you approached the house, she screamed, fell into hysterics, and
insisted on being wheeled back into this room here.вЂќ

вЂњMamma, I didnвЂ™t know he had come. It wasnвЂ™t on his account I wanted to be
wheeled into this room.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s not true, Lise, Yulia ran to tell you that Alexey Fyodorovitch was
coming. She was on the lookвЂђout for you.вЂќ

вЂњMy darling mamma, itвЂ™s not at all clever of you. But if you want to make
up for it and say something very clever, dear mamma, youвЂ™d better tell our
honored visitor, Alexey Fyodorovitch, that he has shown his want of wit by
venturing to us after what happened yesterday and although every one is
laughing at him.вЂќ

вЂњLise, you go too far. I declare I shall have to be severe. Who laughs at
him? I am so glad he has come, I need him, I canвЂ™t do without him. Oh,
Alexey Fyodorovitch, I am exceedingly unhappy!вЂќ

вЂњBut whatвЂ™s the matter with you, mamma, darling?вЂќ

вЂњAh, your caprices, Lise, your fidgetiness, your illness, that awful night
of fever, that awful everlasting Herzenstube, everlasting, everlasting,
thatвЂ™s the worst of it! Everything, in fact, everything.... Even that
miracle, too! Oh, how it has upset me, how it has shattered me, that
miracle, dear Alexey Fyodorovitch! And that tragedy in the drawingвЂђroom,
itвЂ™s more than I can bear, I warn you. I canвЂ™t bear it. A comedy, perhaps,
not a tragedy. Tell me, will Father Zossima live till toвЂђmorrow, will he?
Oh, my God! What is happening to me? Every minute I close my eyes and see
that itвЂ™s all nonsense, all nonsense.вЂќ

вЂњI should be very grateful,вЂќ Alyosha interrupted suddenly, вЂњif you could
give me a clean rag to bind up my finger with. I have hurt it, and itвЂ™s
very painful.вЂќ

Alyosha unbound his bitten finger. The handkerchief was soaked with blood.
Madame Hohlakov screamed and shut her eyes.

вЂњGood heavens, what a wound, how awful!вЂќ

But as soon as Lise saw AlyoshaвЂ™s finger through the crack, she flung the
door wide open.

вЂњCome, come here,вЂќ she cried, imperiously. вЂњNo nonsense now! Good heavens,
why did you stand there saying nothing about it all this time? He might
have bled to death, mamma! How did you do it? Water, water! You must wash
it first of all, simply hold it in cold water to stop the pain, and keep
it there, keep it there.... Make haste, mamma, some water in a slopвЂђbasin.
But do make haste,вЂќ she finished nervously. She was quite frightened at
the sight of AlyoshaвЂ™s wound.

вЂњShouldnвЂ™t we send for Herzenstube?вЂќ cried Madame Hohlakov.

вЂњMamma, youвЂ™ll be the death of me. Your Herzenstube will come and say that
he can make nothing of it! Water, water! Mamma, for goodnessвЂ™ sake go
yourself and hurry Yulia, she is such a slowcoach and never can come
quickly! Make haste, mamma, or I shall die.вЂќ

вЂњWhy, itвЂ™s nothing much,вЂќ cried Alyosha, frightened at this alarm.

Yulia ran in with water and Alyosha put his finger in it.

вЂњSome lint, mamma, for mercyвЂ™s sake, bring some lint and that muddy
caustic lotion for wounds, whatвЂ™s it called? WeвЂ™ve got some. You know
where the bottle is, mamma; itвЂ™s in your bedroom in the rightвЂђhand
cupboard, thereвЂ™s a big bottle of it there with the lint.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll bring everything in a minute, Lise, only donвЂ™t scream and donвЂ™t
fuss. You see how bravely Alexey Fyodorovitch bears it. Where did you get
such a dreadful wound, Alexey Fyodorovitch?вЂќ

Madame Hohlakov hastened away. This was all Lise was waiting for.

вЂњFirst of all, answer the question, where did you get hurt like this?вЂќ she
asked Alyosha, quickly. вЂњAnd then IвЂ™ll talk to you about something quite
different. Well?вЂќ

Instinctively feeling that the time of her motherвЂ™s absence was precious
for her, Alyosha hastened to tell her of his enigmatic meeting with the
schoolboys in the fewest words possible. Lise clasped her hands at his
story.

вЂњHow can you, and in that dress too, associate with schoolboys?вЂќ she cried
angrily, as though she had a right to control him. вЂњYou are nothing but a
boy yourself if you can do that, a perfect boy! But you must find out for
me about that horrid boy and tell me all about it, for thereвЂ™s some
mystery in it. Now for the second thing, but first a question: does the
pain prevent you talking about utterly unimportant things, but talking
sensibly?вЂќ

вЂњOf course not, and I donвЂ™t feel much pain now.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s because your finger is in the water. It must be changed directly,
for it will get warm in a minute. Yulia, bring some ice from the cellar
and another basin of water. Now she is gone, I can speak; will you give me
the letter I sent you yesterday, dear Alexey FyodorovitchвЂ”be quick, for
mamma will be back in a minute and I donвЂ™t wantвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњI havenвЂ™t got the letter.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s not true, you have. I knew you would say that. YouвЂ™ve got it in
that pocket. IвЂ™ve been regretting that joke all night. Give me back the
letter at once, give it me.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ve left it at home.вЂќ

вЂњBut you canвЂ™t consider me as a child, a little girl, after that silly
joke! I beg your pardon for that silliness, but you must bring me the
letter, if you really havenвЂ™t got itвЂ”bring it toвЂђday, you must, you must.вЂќ

вЂњToвЂђday I canвЂ™t possibly, for I am going back to the monastery and I
shanвЂ™t come and see you for the next two daysвЂ”three or four perhapsвЂ”for
Father ZossimaвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњFour days, what nonsense! Listen. Did you laugh at me very much?вЂќ

вЂњI didnвЂ™t laugh at all.вЂќ

вЂњWhy not?вЂќ

вЂњBecause I believed all you said.вЂќ

вЂњYou are insulting me!вЂќ

вЂњNot at all. As soon as I read it, I thought that all that would come to
pass, for as soon as Father Zossima dies, I am to leave the monastery.
Then I shall go back and finish my studies, and when you reach the legal
age we will be married. I shall love you. Though I havenвЂ™t had time to
think about it, I believe I couldnвЂ™t find a better wife than you, and
Father Zossima tells me I must marry.вЂќ

вЂњBut I am a cripple, wheeled about in a chair,вЂќ laughed Lise, flushing
crimson.

вЂњIвЂ™ll wheel you about myself, but IвЂ™m sure youвЂ™ll get well by then.вЂќ

вЂњBut you are mad,вЂќ said Lise, nervously, вЂњto make all this nonsense out of
a joke! HereвЂ™s mamma, very _Г  propos_, perhaps. Mamma, how slow you always
are, how can you be so long! And hereвЂ™s Yulia with the ice!вЂќ

вЂњOh, Lise, donвЂ™t scream, above all things donвЂ™t scream. That scream drives
me ... How can I help it when you put the lint in another place? IвЂ™ve been
hunting and huntingвЂ”I do believe you did it on purpose.вЂќ

вЂњBut I couldnвЂ™t tell that he would come with a bad finger, or else perhaps
I might have done it on purpose. My darling mamma, you begin to say really
witty things.вЂќ

вЂњNever mind my being witty, but I must say you show nice feeling for
Alexey FyodorovitchвЂ™s sufferings! Oh, my dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, whatвЂ™s
killing me is no one thing in particular, not Herzenstube, but everything
together, thatвЂ™s what is too much for me.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s enough, mamma, enough about Herzenstube,вЂќ Lise laughed gayly.
вЂњMake haste with the lint and the lotion, mamma. ThatвЂ™s simply GoulardвЂ™s
water, Alexey Fyodorovitch, I remember the name now, but itвЂ™s a splendid
lotion. Would you believe it, mamma, on the way here he had a fight with
the boys in the street, and it was a boy bit his finger, isnвЂ™t he a child,
a child himself? Is he fit to be married after that? For only fancy, he
wants to be married, mamma. Just think of him married, wouldnвЂ™t it be
funny, wouldnвЂ™t it be awful?вЂќ

And Lise kept laughing her thin hysterical giggle, looking slyly at
Alyosha.

вЂњBut why married, Lise? What makes you talk of such a thing? ItвЂ™s quite
out of placeвЂ”and perhaps the boy was rabid.вЂќ

вЂњWhy, mamma! As though there were rabid boys!вЂќ

вЂњWhy not, Lise, as though I had said something stupid! Your boy might have
been bitten by a mad dog and he would become mad and bite any one near
him. How well she has bandaged it, Alexey Fyodorovitch! I couldnвЂ™t have
done it. Do you still feel the pain?вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s nothing much now.вЂќ

вЂњYou donвЂ™t feel afraid of water?вЂќ asked Lise.

вЂњCome, thatвЂ™s enough, Lise, perhaps I really was rather too quick talking
of the boy being rabid, and you pounced upon it at once Katerina Ivanovna
has only just heard that you are here, Alexey Fyodorovitch, she simply
rushed at me, sheвЂ™s dying to see you, dying!вЂќ

вЂњAch, mamma, go to them yourself. He canвЂ™t go just now, he is in too much
pain.вЂќ

вЂњNot at all, I can go quite well,вЂќ said Alyosha.

вЂњWhat! You are going away? Is that what you say?вЂќ

вЂњWell, when IвЂ™ve seen them, IвЂ™ll come back here and we can talk as much as
you like. But I should like to see Katerina Ivanovna at once, for I am
very anxious to be back at the monastery as soon as I can.вЂќ

вЂњMamma, take him away quickly. Alexey Fyodorovitch, donвЂ™t trouble to come
and see me afterwards, but go straight back to your monastery and a good
riddance. I want to sleep, I didnвЂ™t sleep all night.вЂќ

вЂњAh, Lise, you are only making fun, but how I wish you would sleep!вЂќ cried
Madame Hohlakov.

вЂњI donвЂ™t know what IвЂ™ve done.... IвЂ™ll stay another three minutes, five if
you like,вЂќ muttered Alyosha.

вЂњEven five! Do take him away quickly, mamma, he is a monster.вЂќ

вЂњLise, you are crazy. Let us go, Alexey Fyodorovitch, she is too
capricious toвЂђday. I am afraid to cross her. Oh, the trouble one has with
nervous girls! Perhaps she really will be able to sleep after seeing you.
How quickly you have made her sleepy, and how fortunate it is!вЂќ

вЂњAh, mamma, how sweetly you talk! I must kiss you for it, mamma.вЂќ

вЂњAnd I kiss you too, Lise. Listen, Alexey Fyodorovitch,вЂќ Madame Hohlakov
began mysteriously and importantly, speaking in a rapid whisper. вЂњI donвЂ™t
want to suggest anything, I donвЂ™t want to lift the veil, you will see for
yourself whatвЂ™s going on. ItвЂ™s appalling. ItвЂ™s the most fantastic farce.
She loves your brother, Ivan, and she is doing her utmost to persuade
herself she loves your brother, Dmitri. ItвЂ™s appalling! IвЂ™ll go in with
you, and if they donвЂ™t turn me out, IвЂ™ll stay to the end.вЂќ



Chapter V. A Laceration In The DrawingвЂђRoom


But in the drawingвЂђroom the conversation was already over. Katerina
Ivanovna was greatly excited, though she looked resolute. At the moment
Alyosha and Madame Hohlakov entered, Ivan Fyodorovitch stood up to take
leave. His face was rather pale, and Alyosha looked at him anxiously. For
this moment was to solve a doubt, a harassing enigma which had for some
time haunted Alyosha. During the preceding month it had been several times
suggested to him that his brother Ivan was in love with Katerina Ivanovna,
and, what was more, that he meant вЂњto carry her offвЂќ from Dmitri. Until
quite lately the idea seemed to Alyosha monstrous, though it worried him
extremely. He loved both his brothers, and dreaded such rivalry between
them. Meantime, Dmitri had said outright on the previous day that he was
glad that Ivan was his rival, and that it was a great assistance to him,
Dmitri. In what way did it assist him? To marry Grushenka? But that
Alyosha considered the worst thing possible. Besides all this, Alyosha had
till the evening before implicitly believed that Katerina Ivanovna had a
steadfast and passionate love for Dmitri; but he had only believed it till
the evening before. He had fancied, too, that she was incapable of loving
a man like Ivan, and that she did love Dmitri, and loved him just as he
was, in spite of all the strangeness of such a passion.

But during yesterdayвЂ™s scene with Grushenka another idea had struck him.
The word вЂњlacerating,вЂќ which Madame Hohlakov had just uttered, almost made
him start, because half waking up towards daybreak that night he had cried
out вЂњLaceration, laceration,вЂќ probably applying it to his dream. He had
been dreaming all night of the previous dayвЂ™s scene at Katerina
IvanovnaвЂ™s. Now Alyosha was impressed by Madame HohlakovвЂ™s blunt and
persistent assertion that Katerina Ivanovna was in love with Ivan, and
only deceived herself through some sort of pose, from вЂњselfвЂђlaceration,вЂќ
and tortured herself by her pretended love for Dmitri from some fancied
duty of gratitude. вЂњYes,вЂќ he thought, вЂњperhaps the whole truth lies in
those words.вЂќ But in that case what was IvanвЂ™s position? Alyosha felt
instinctively that a character like Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s must dominate, and
she could only dominate some one like Dmitri, and never a man like Ivan.
For Dmitri might at last submit to her domination вЂњto his own happinessвЂќ
(which was what Alyosha would have desired), but IvanвЂ”no, Ivan could not
submit to her, and such submission would not give him happiness. Alyosha
could not help believing that of Ivan. And now all these doubts and
reflections flitted through his mind as he entered the drawingвЂђroom.
Another idea, too, forced itself upon him: вЂњWhat if she loved neither of
themвЂ”neither Ivan nor Dmitri?вЂќ

It must be noted that Alyosha felt as it were ashamed of his own thoughts
and blamed himself when they kept recurring to him during the last month.
вЂњWhat do I know about love and women and how can I decide such questions?вЂќ
he thought reproachfully, after such doubts and surmises. And yet it was
impossible not to think about it. He felt instinctively that this rivalry
was of immense importance in his brothersвЂ™ lives and that a great deal
depended upon it.

вЂњOne reptile will devour the other,вЂќ Ivan had pronounced the day before,
speaking in anger of his father and Dmitri. So Ivan looked upon Dmitri as
a reptile, and perhaps had long done so. Was it perhaps since he had known
Katerina Ivanovna? That phrase had, of course, escaped Ivan unawares
yesterday, but that only made it more important. If he felt like that,
what chance was there of peace? Were there not, on the contrary, new
grounds for hatred and hostility in their family? And with which of them
was Alyosha to sympathize? And what was he to wish for each of them? He
loved them both, but what could he desire for each in the midst of these
conflicting interests? He might go quite astray in this maze, and
AlyoshaвЂ™s heart could not endure uncertainty, because his love was always
of an active character. He was incapable of passive love. If he loved any
one, he set to work at once to help him. And to do so he must know what he
was aiming at; he must know for certain what was best for each, and having
ascertained this it was natural for him to help them both. But instead of
a definite aim, he found nothing but uncertainty and perplexity on all
sides. вЂњIt was lacerating,вЂќ as was said just now. But what could he
understand even in this вЂњlacerationвЂќ? He did not understand the first word
in this perplexing maze.

Seeing Alyosha, Katerina Ivanovna said quickly and joyfully to Ivan, who
had already got up to go, вЂњA minute! Stay another minute! I want to hear
the opinion of this person here whom I trust absolutely. DonвЂ™t go away,вЂќ
she added, addressing Madame Hohlakov. She made Alyosha sit down beside
her, and Madame Hohlakov sat opposite, by Ivan.

вЂњYou are all my friends here, all I have in the world, my dear friends,вЂќ
she began warmly, in a voice which quivered with genuine tears of
suffering, and AlyoshaвЂ™s heart warmed to her at once. вЂњYou, Alexey
Fyodorovitch, were witness yesterday of that abominable scene, and saw
what I did. You did not see it, Ivan Fyodorovitch, he did. What he thought
of me yesterday I donвЂ™t know. I only know one thing, that if it were
repeated toвЂђday, this minute, I should express the same feelings again as
yesterdayвЂ”the same feelings, the same words, the same actions. You
remember my actions, Alexey Fyodorovitch; you checked me in one of themвЂќ
... (as she said that, she flushed and her eyes shone). вЂњI must tell you
that I canвЂ™t get over it. Listen, Alexey Fyodorovitch. I donвЂ™t even know
whether I still love _him_. I feel _pity_ for him, and that is a poor sign
of love. If I loved him, if I still loved him, perhaps I shouldnвЂ™t be
sorry for him now, but should hate him.вЂќ

Her voice quivered, and tears glittered on her eyelashes. Alyosha
shuddered inwardly. вЂњThat girl is truthful and sincere,вЂќ he thought, вЂњand
she does not love Dmitri any more.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s true, thatвЂ™s true,вЂќ cried Madame Hohlakov.

вЂњWait, dear. I havenвЂ™t told you the chief, the final decision I came to
during the night. I feel that perhaps my decision is a terrible oneвЂ”for
me, but I foresee that nothing will induce me to change itвЂ”nothing. It
will be so all my life. My dear, kind, everвЂђfaithful and generous adviser,
the one friend I have in the world, Ivan Fyodorovitch, with his deep
insight into the heart, approves and commends my decision. He knows it.вЂќ

вЂњYes, I approve of it,вЂќ Ivan assented, in a subdued but firm voice.

вЂњBut I should like Alyosha, too (Ah! Alexey Fyodorovitch, forgive my
calling you simply Alyosha), I should like Alexey Fyodorovitch, too, to
tell me before my two friends whether I am right. I feel instinctively
that you, Alyosha, my dear brother (for you are a dear brother to me),вЂќ
she said again ecstatically, taking his cold hand in her hot one, вЂњI
foresee that your decision, your approval, will bring me peace, in spite
of all my sufferings, for, after your words, I shall be calm and submitвЂ”I
feel that.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know what you are asking me,вЂќ said Alyosha, flushing. вЂњI only
know that I love you and at this moment wish for your happiness more than
my own!... But I know nothing about such affairs,вЂќ something impelled him
to add hurriedly.

вЂњIn such affairs, Alexey Fyodorovitch, in such affairs, the chief thing is
honor and duty and something higherвЂ”I donвЂ™t know whatвЂ”but higher perhaps
even than duty. I am conscious of this irresistible feeling in my heart,
and it compels me irresistibly. But it may all be put in two words. IвЂ™ve
already decided, even if he marries thatвЂ”creature,вЂќ she began solemnly,
вЂњwhom I never, never can forgive, _even then I will not abandon him_.
Henceforward I will never, never abandon him!вЂќ she cried, breaking into a
sort of pale, hysterical ecstasy. вЂњNot that I would run after him
continually, get in his way and worry him. Oh, no! I will go away to
another townвЂ”where you likeвЂ”but I will watch over him all my lifeвЂ”I will
watch over him all my life unceasingly. When he becomes unhappy with that
woman, and that is bound to happen quite soon, let him come to me and he
will find a friend, a sister.... Only a sister, of course, and so for
ever; but he will learn at least that that sister is really his sister,
who loves him and has sacrificed all her life to him. I will gain my
point. I will insist on his knowing me and confiding entirely in me,
without reserve,вЂќ she cried, in a sort of frenzy. вЂњI will be a god to whom
he can prayвЂ”and that, at least, he owes me for his treachery and for what
I suffered yesterday through him. And let him see that all my life I will
be true to him and the promise I gave him, in spite of his being untrue
and betraying me. I willвЂ”I will become nothing but a means for his
happiness, orвЂ”how shall I say?вЂ”an instrument, a machine for his happiness,
and that for my whole life, my whole life, and that he may see that all
his life! ThatвЂ™s my decision. Ivan Fyodorovitch fully approves me.вЂќ

She was breathless. She had perhaps intended to express her idea with more
dignity, art and naturalness, but her speech was too hurried and crude. It
was full of youthful impulsiveness, it betrayed that she was still
smarting from yesterdayвЂ™s insult, and that her pride craved satisfaction.
She felt this herself. Her face suddenly darkened, an unpleasant look came
into her eyes. Alyosha at once saw it and felt a pang of sympathy. His
brother Ivan made it worse by adding:

вЂњIвЂ™ve only expressed my own view,вЂќ he said. вЂњFrom any one else, this would
have been affected and overstrained, but from youвЂ”no. Any other woman
would have been wrong, but you are right. I donвЂ™t know how to explain it,
but I see that you are absolutely genuine and, therefore, you are right.вЂќ

вЂњBut thatвЂ™s only for the moment. And what does this moment stand for?
Nothing but yesterdayвЂ™s insult.вЂќ Madame Hohlakov obviously had not
intended to interfere, but she could not refrain from this very just
comment.

вЂњQuite so, quite so,вЂќ cried Ivan, with peculiar eagerness, obviously
annoyed at being interrupted, вЂњin any one else this moment would be only
due to yesterdayвЂ™s impression and would be only a moment. But with
Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s character, that moment will last all her life. What
for any one else would be only a promise is for her an everlasting
burdensome, grim perhaps, but unflagging duty. And she will be sustained
by the feeling of this duty being fulfilled. Your life, Katerina Ivanovna,
will henceforth be spent in painful brooding over your own feelings, your
own heroism, and your own suffering; but in the end that suffering will be
softened and will pass into sweet contemplation of the fulfillment of a
bold and proud design. Yes, proud it certainly is, and desperate in any
case, but a triumph for you. And the consciousness of it will at last be a
source of complete satisfaction and will make you resigned to everything
else.вЂќ

This was unmistakably said with some malice and obviously with intention;
even perhaps with no desire to conceal that he spoke ironically and with
intention.

вЂњOh, dear, how mistaken it all is!вЂќ Madame Hohlakov cried again.

вЂњAlexey Fyodorovitch, you speak. I want dreadfully to know what you will
say!вЂќ cried Katerina Ivanovna, and burst into tears. Alyosha got up from
the sofa.

вЂњItвЂ™s nothing, nothing!вЂќ she went on through her tears. вЂњIвЂ™m upset, I
didnвЂ™t sleep last night. But by the side of two such friends as you and
your brother I still feel strongвЂ”for I knowвЂ”you two will never desert me.вЂќ

вЂњUnluckily I am obliged to return to MoscowвЂ”perhaps toвЂђmorrowвЂ”and to leave
you for a long timeвЂ”And, unluckily, itвЂ™s unavoidable,вЂќ Ivan said suddenly.

вЂњToвЂђmorrowвЂ”to Moscow!вЂќ her face was suddenly contorted; вЂњbutвЂ”but, dear me,
how fortunate!вЂќ she cried in a voice suddenly changed. In one instant
there was no trace left of her tears. She underwent an instantaneous
transformation, which amazed Alyosha. Instead of a poor, insulted girl,
weeping in a sort of вЂњlaceration,вЂќ he saw a woman completely selfвЂђ
possessed and even exceedingly pleased, as though something agreeable had
just happened.

вЂњOh, not fortunate that I am losing you, of course not,вЂќ she corrected
herself suddenly, with a charming society smile. вЂњSuch a friend as you are
could not suppose that. I am only too unhappy at losing you.вЂќ She rushed
impulsively at Ivan, and seizing both his hands, pressed them warmly. вЂњBut
what is fortunate is that you will be able in Moscow to see auntie and
Agafya and to tell them all the horror of my present position. You can
speak with complete openness to Agafya, but spare dear auntie. You will
know how to do that. You canвЂ™t think how wretched I was yesterday and this
morning, wondering how I could write them that dreadful letterвЂ”for one can
never tell such things in a letter.... Now it will be easy for me to
write, for you will see them and explain everything. Oh, how glad I am!
But I am only glad of that, believe me. Of course, no one can take your
place.... I will run at once to write the letter,вЂќ she finished suddenly,
and took a step as though to go out of the room.

вЂњAnd what about Alyosha and his opinion, which you were so desperately
anxious to hear?вЂќ cried Madame Hohlakov. There was a sarcastic, angry note
in her voice.

вЂњI had not forgotten that,вЂќ cried Katerina Ivanovna, coming to a sudden
standstill, вЂњand why are you so antagonistic at such a moment?вЂќ she added,
with warm and bitter reproachfulness. вЂњWhat I said, I repeat. I must have
his opinion. More than that, I must have his decision! As he says, so it
shall be. You see how anxious I am for your words, Alexey Fyodorovitch....
But whatвЂ™s the matter?вЂќ

вЂњI couldnвЂ™t have believed it. I canвЂ™t understand it!вЂќ Alyosha cried
suddenly in distress.

вЂњWhat? What?вЂќ

вЂњHe is going to Moscow, and you cry out that you are glad. You said that
on purpose! And you begin explaining that you are not glad of that but
sorry to beвЂ”losing a friend. But that was acting, tooвЂ”you were playing a
partвЂ”as in a theater!вЂќ

вЂњIn a theater? What? What do you mean?вЂќ exclaimed Katerina Ivanovna,
profoundly astonished, flushing crimson, and frowning.

вЂњThough you assure him you are sorry to lose a friend in him, you persist
in telling him to his face that itвЂ™s fortunate he is going,вЂќ said Alyosha
breathlessly. He was standing at the table and did not sit down.

вЂњWhat are you talking about? I donвЂ™t understand.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t understand myself.... I seemed to see in a flash ... I know I am
not saying it properly, but IвЂ™ll say it all the same,вЂќ Alyosha went on in
the same shaking and broken voice. вЂњWhat I see is that perhaps you donвЂ™t
love Dmitri at all ... and never have, from the beginning.... And Dmitri,
too, has never loved you ... and only esteems you.... I really donвЂ™t know
how I dare to say all this, but somebody must tell the truth ... for
nobody here will tell the truth.вЂќ

вЂњWhat truth?вЂќ cried Katerina Ivanovna, and there was an hysterical ring in
her voice.

вЂњIвЂ™ll tell you,вЂќ Alyosha went on with desperate haste, as though he were
jumping from the top of a house. вЂњCall Dmitri; I will fetch himвЂ”and let
him come here and take your hand and take IvanвЂ™s and join your hands. For
youвЂ™re torturing Ivan, simply because you love himвЂ”and torturing him,
because you love Dmitri through вЂselfвЂђlacerationвЂ™вЂ”with an unreal
loveвЂ”because youвЂ™ve persuaded yourself.вЂќ

Alyosha broke off and was silent.

вЂњYou ... you ... you are a little religious idiotвЂ”thatвЂ™s what you are!вЂќ
Katerina Ivanovna snapped. Her face was white and her lips were moving
with anger.

Ivan suddenly laughed and got up. His hat was in his hand.

вЂњYou are mistaken, my good Alyosha,вЂќ he said, with an expression Alyosha
had never seen in his face beforeвЂ”an expression of youthful sincerity and
strong, irresistibly frank feeling. вЂњKaterina Ivanovna has never cared for
me! She has known all the time that I cared for herвЂ”though I never said a
word of my love to herвЂ”she knew, but she didnвЂ™t care for me. I have never
been her friend either, not for one moment; she is too proud to need my
friendship. She kept me at her side as a means of revenge. She revenged
with me and on me all the insults which she has been continually receiving
from Dmitri ever since their first meeting. For even that first meeting
has rankled in her heart as an insultвЂ”thatвЂ™s what her heart is like! She
has talked to me of nothing but her love for him. I am going now; but,
believe me, Katerina Ivanovna, you really love him. And the more he
insults you, the more you love himвЂ”thatвЂ™s your вЂlaceration.вЂ™ You love him
just as he is; you love him for insulting you. If he reformed, youвЂ™d give
him up at once and cease to love him. But you need him so as to
contemplate continually your heroic fidelity and to reproach him for
infidelity. And it all comes from your pride. Oh, thereвЂ™s a great deal of
humiliation and selfвЂђabasement about it, but it all comes from pride.... I
am too young and IвЂ™ve loved you too much. I know that I ought not to say
this, that it would be more dignified on my part simply to leave you, and
it would be less offensive for you. But I am going far away, and shall
never come back.... It is for ever. I donвЂ™t want to sit beside a
вЂlaceration.вЂ™... But I donвЂ™t know how to speak now. IвЂ™ve said
everything.... GoodвЂђby, Katerina Ivanovna; you canвЂ™t be angry with me, for
I am a hundred times more severely punished than you, if only by the fact
that I shall never see you again. GoodвЂђby! I donвЂ™t want your hand. You
have tortured me too deliberately for me to be able to forgive you at this
moment. I shall forgive you later, but now I donвЂ™t want your hand. вЂDen
Dank, Dame, begehr ich nicht,вЂ™ вЂќ he added, with a forced smile, showing,
however, that he could read Schiller, and read him till he knew him by
heartвЂ”which Alyosha would never have believed. He went out of the room
without saying goodвЂђby even to his hostess, Madame Hohlakov. Alyosha
clasped his hands.

вЂњIvan!вЂќ he cried desperately after him. вЂњCome back, Ivan! No, nothing will
induce him to come back now!вЂќ he cried again, regretfully realizing it;
вЂњbut itвЂ™s my fault, my fault. I began it! Ivan spoke angrily, wrongly.
Unjustly and angrily. He must come back here, come back,вЂќ Alyosha kept
exclaiming frantically.

Katerina Ivanovna went suddenly into the next room.

вЂњYou have done no harm. You behaved beautifully, like an angel,вЂќ Madame
Hohlakov whispered rapidly and ecstatically to Alyosha. вЂњI will do my
utmost to prevent Ivan Fyodorovitch from going.вЂќ

Her face beamed with delight, to the great distress of Alyosha, but
Katerina Ivanovna suddenly returned. She had two hundredвЂђrouble notes in
her hand.

вЂњI have a great favor to ask of you, Alexey Fyodorovitch,вЂќ she began,
addressing Alyosha with an apparently calm and even voice, as though
nothing had happened. вЂњA weekвЂ”yes, I think it was a week agoвЂ”Dmitri
Fyodorovitch was guilty of a hasty and unjust actionвЂ”a very ugly action.
There is a low tavern here, and in it he met that discharged officer, that
captain, whom your father used to employ in some business. Dmitri
Fyodorovitch somehow lost his temper with this captain, seized him by the
beard and dragged him out into the street and for some distance along it,
in that insulting fashion. And I am told that his son, a boy, quite a
child, who is at the school here, saw it and ran beside them crying and
begging for his father, appealing to every one to defend him, while every
one laughed. You must forgive me, Alexey Fyodorovitch, I cannot think
without indignation of that disgraceful action of _his_ ... one of those
actions of which only Dmitri Fyodorovitch would be capable in his anger
... and in his passions! I canвЂ™t describe it even.... I canвЂ™t find my
words. IвЂ™ve made inquiries about his victim, and find he is quite a poor
man. His name is Snegiryov. He did something wrong in the army and was
discharged. I canвЂ™t tell you what. And now he has sunk into terrible
destitution, with his familyвЂ”an unhappy family of sick children, and, I
believe, an insane wife. He has been living here a long time; he used to
work as a copying clerk, but now he is getting nothing. I thought if you
... that is I thought ... I donвЂ™t know. I am so confused. You see, I
wanted to ask you, my dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, to go to him, to find some
excuse to go to themвЂ”I mean to that captainвЂ”oh, goodness, how badly I
explain it!вЂ”and delicately, carefully, as only you know how toвЂќ (Alyosha
blushed), вЂњmanage to give him this assistance, these two hundred roubles.
He will be sure to take it.... I mean, persuade him to take it.... Or,
rather, what do I mean? You see itвЂ™s not by way of compensation to prevent
him from taking proceedings (for I believe he meant to), but simply a
token of sympathy, of a desire to assist him from me, Dmitri
FyodorovitchвЂ™s betrothed, not from himself.... But you know.... I would go
myself, but youвЂ™ll know how to do it ever so much better. He lives in Lake
Street, in the house of a woman called Kalmikov.... For GodвЂ™s sake, Alexey
Fyodorovitch, do it for me, and now ... now I am rather ... tired. GoodвЂђ
by!вЂќ

She turned and disappeared behind the portiГЁre so quickly that Alyosha had
not time to utter a word, though he wanted to speak. He longed to beg her
pardon, to blame himself, to say something, for his heart was full and he
could not bear to go out of the room without it. But Madame Hohlakov took
him by the hand and drew him along with her. In the hall she stopped him
again as before.

вЂњShe is proud, she is struggling with herself; but kind, charming,
generous,вЂќ she exclaimed, in a halfвЂђwhisper. вЂњOh, how I love her,
especially sometimes, and how glad I am again of everything! Dear Alexey
Fyodorovitch, you didnвЂ™t know, but I must tell you, that we all, allвЂ”both
her aunts, I and all of us, Lise, evenвЂ”have been hoping and praying for
nothing for the last month but that she may give up your favorite Dmitri,
who takes no notice of her and does not care for her, and may marry Ivan
FyodorovitchвЂ”such an excellent and cultivated young man, who loves her
more than anything in the world. We are in a regular plot to bring it
about, and I am even staying on here perhaps on that account.вЂќ

вЂњBut she has been cryingвЂ”she has been wounded again,вЂќ cried Alyosha.

вЂњNever trust a womanвЂ™s tears, Alexey Fyodorovitch. I am never for the
women in such cases. I am always on the side of the men.вЂќ

вЂњMamma, you are spoiling him,вЂќ LiseвЂ™s little voice cried from behind the
door.

вЂњNo, it was all my fault. I am horribly to blame,вЂќ Alyosha repeated
unconsoled, hiding his face in his hands in an agony of remorse for his
indiscretion.

вЂњQuite the contrary; you behaved like an angel, like an angel. I am ready
to say so a thousand times over.вЂќ

вЂњMamma, how has he behaved like an angel?вЂќ LiseвЂ™s voice was heard again.

вЂњI somehow fancied all at once,вЂќ Alyosha went on as though he had not
heard Lise, вЂњthat she loved Ivan, and so I said that stupid thing.... What
will happen now?вЂќ

вЂњTo whom, to whom?вЂќ cried Lise. вЂњMamma, you really want to be the death of
me. I ask you and you donвЂ™t answer.вЂќ

At the moment the maid ran in.

вЂњKaterina Ivanovna is ill.... She is crying, struggling ... hysterics.вЂќ

вЂњWhat is the matter?вЂќ cried Lise, in a tone of real anxiety. вЂњMamma, I
shall be having hysterics, and not she!вЂќ

вЂњLise, for mercyвЂ™s sake, donвЂ™t scream, donвЂ™t persecute me. At your age one
canвЂ™t know everything that grownвЂђup people know. IвЂ™ll come and tell you
everything you ought to know. Oh, mercy on us! I am coming, I am
coming.... Hysterics is a good sign, Alexey Fyodorovitch; itвЂ™s an
excellent thing that she is hysterical. ThatвЂ™s just as it ought to be. In
such cases I am always against the woman, against all these feminine tears
and hysterics. Run and say, Yulia, that IвЂ™ll fly to her. As for Ivan
FyodorovitchвЂ™s going away like that, itвЂ™s her own fault. But he wonвЂ™t go
away. Lise, for mercyвЂ™s sake, donвЂ™t scream! Oh, yes; you are not
screaming. ItвЂ™s I am screaming. Forgive your mamma; but I am delighted,
delighted, delighted! Did you notice, Alexey Fyodorovitch, how young, how
young Ivan Fyodorovitch was just now when he went out, when he said all
that and went out? I thought he was so learned, such a _savant_, and all
of a sudden he behaved so warmly, openly, and youthfully, with such
youthful inexperience, and it was all so fine, like you.... And the way he
repeated that German verse, it was just like you! But I must fly, I must
fly! Alexey Fyodorovitch, make haste to carry out her commission, and then
make haste back. Lise, do you want anything now? For mercyвЂ™s sake, donвЂ™t
keep Alexey Fyodorovitch a minute. He will come back to you at once.вЂќ

Madame Hohlakov at last ran off. Before leaving, Alyosha would have opened
the door to see Lise.

вЂњOn no account,вЂќ cried Lise. вЂњOn no account now. Speak through the door.
How have you come to be an angel? ThatвЂ™s the only thing I want to know.вЂќ

вЂњFor an awful piece of stupidity, Lise! GoodвЂђby!вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t dare to go away like that!вЂќ Lise was beginning.

вЂњLise, I have a real sorrow! IвЂ™ll be back directly, but I have a great,
great sorrow!вЂќ

And he ran out of the room.



Chapter VI. A Laceration In The Cottage


He certainly was really grieved in a way he had seldom been before. He had
rushed in like a fool, and meddled in what? In a loveвЂђaffair. вЂњBut what do
I know about it? What can I tell about such things?вЂќ he repeated to
himself for the hundredth time, flushing crimson. вЂњOh, being ashamed would
be nothing; shame is only the punishment I deserve. The trouble is I shall
certainly have caused more unhappiness.... And Father Zossima sent me to
reconcile and bring them together. Is this the way to bring them
together?вЂќ Then he suddenly remembered how he had tried to join their
hands, and he felt fearfully ashamed again. вЂњThough I acted quite
sincerely, I must be more sensible in the future,вЂќ he concluded suddenly,
and did not even smile at his conclusion.

Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s commission took him to Lake Street, and his brother
Dmitri lived close by, in a turning out of Lake Street. Alyosha decided to
go to him in any case before going to the captain, though he had a
presentiment that he would not find his brother. He suspected that he
would intentionally keep out of his way now, but he must find him anyhow.
Time was passing: the thought of his dying elder had not left Alyosha for
one minute from the time he set off from the monastery.

There was one point which interested him particularly about Katerina
IvanovnaвЂ™s commission; when she had mentioned the captainвЂ™s son, the
little schoolboy who had run beside his father crying, the idea had at
once struck Alyosha that this must be the schoolboy who had bitten his
finger when he, Alyosha, asked him what he had done to hurt him. Now
Alyosha felt practically certain of this, though he could not have said
why. Thinking of another subject was a relief, and he resolved to think no
more about the вЂњmischiefвЂќ he had done, and not to torture himself with
remorse, but to do what he had to do, let come what would. At that thought
he was completely comforted. Turning to the street where Dmitri lodged, he
felt hungry, and taking out of his pocket the roll he had brought from his
fatherвЂ™s, he ate it. It made him feel stronger.

Dmitri was not at home. The people of the house, an old cabinetвЂђmaker, his
son, and his old wife, looked with positive suspicion at Alyosha. вЂњHe
hasnвЂ™t slept here for the last three nights. Maybe he has gone away,вЂќ the
old man said in answer to AlyoshaвЂ™s persistent inquiries. Alyosha saw that
he was answering in accordance with instructions. When he asked whether he
were not at GrushenkaвЂ™s or in hiding at FomaвЂ™s (Alyosha spoke so freely on
purpose), all three looked at him in alarm. вЂњThey are fond of him, they
are doing their best for him,вЂќ thought Alyosha. вЂњThatвЂ™s good.вЂќ

At last he found the house in Lake Street. It was a decrepit little house,
sunk on one side, with three windows looking into the street, and with a
muddy yard, in the middle of which stood a solitary cow. He crossed the
yard and found the door opening into the passage. On the left of the
passage lived the old woman of the house with her old daughter. Both
seemed to be deaf. In answer to his repeated inquiry for the captain, one
of them at last understood that he was asking for their lodgers, and
pointed to a door across the passage. The captainвЂ™s lodging turned out to
be a simple cottage room. Alyosha had his hand on the iron latch to open
the door, when he was struck by the strange hush within. Yet he knew from
Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s words that the man had a family. вЂњEither they are all
asleep or perhaps they have heard me coming and are waiting for me to open
the door. IвЂ™d better knock first,вЂќ and he knocked. An answer came, but not
at once, after an interval of perhaps ten seconds.

вЂњWhoвЂ™s there?вЂќ shouted some one in a loud and very angry voice.

Then Alyosha opened the door and crossed the threshold. He found himself
in a regular peasantвЂ™s room. Though it was large, it was cumbered up with
domestic belongings of all sorts, and there were several people in it. On
the left was a large Russian stove. From the stove to the window on the
left was a string running across the room, and on it there were rags
hanging. There was a bedstead against the wall on each side, right and
left, covered with knitted quilts. On the one on the left was a pyramid of
four printвЂђcovered pillows, each smaller than the one beneath. On the
other there was only one very small pillow. The opposite corner was
screened off by a curtain or a sheet hung on a string. Behind this curtain
could be seen a bed made up on a bench and a chair. The rough square table
of plain wood had been moved into the middle window. The three windows,
which consisted each of four tiny greenish mildewy panes, gave little
light, and were close shut, so that the room was not very light and rather
stuffy. On the table was a fryingвЂђpan with the remains of some fried eggs,
a halfвЂђeaten piece of bread, and a small bottle with a few drops of vodka.

A woman of genteel appearance, wearing a cotton gown, was sitting on a
chair by the bed on the left. Her face was thin and yellow, and her sunken
cheeks betrayed at the first glance that she was ill. But what struck
Alyosha most was the expression in the poor womanвЂ™s eyesвЂ”a look of
surprised inquiry and yet of haughty pride. And while he was talking to
her husband, her big brown eyes moved from one speaker to the other with
the same haughty and questioning expression. Beside her at the window
stood a young girl, rather plain, with scanty reddish hair, poorly but
very neatly dressed. She looked disdainfully at Alyosha as he came in.
Beside the other bed was sitting another female figure. She was a very sad
sight, a young girl of about twenty, but hunchback and crippled вЂњwith
withered legs,вЂќ as Alyosha was told afterwards. Her crutches stood in the
corner close by. The strikingly beautiful and gentle eyes of this poor
girl looked with mild serenity at Alyosha. A man of fortyвЂђfive was sitting
at the table, finishing the fried eggs. He was spare, small and weakly
built. He had reddish hair and a scanty lightвЂђcolored beard, very much
like a wisp of tow (this comparison and the phrase вЂњa wisp of towвЂќ flashed
at once into AlyoshaвЂ™s mind for some reason, he remembered it afterwards).
It was obviously this gentleman who had shouted to him, as there was no
other man in the room. But when Alyosha went in, he leapt up from the
bench on which he was sitting, and, hastily wiping his mouth with a ragged
napkin, darted up to Alyosha.

вЂњItвЂ™s a monk come to beg for the monastery. A nice place to come to!вЂќ the
girl standing in the left corner said aloud. The man spun round instantly
towards her and answered her in an excited and breaking voice:

вЂњNo, Varvara, you are wrong. Allow me to ask,вЂќ he turned again to Alyosha,
вЂњwhat has brought you toвЂ”our retreat?вЂќ

Alyosha looked attentively at him. It was the first time he had seen him.
There was something angular, flurried and irritable about him. Though he
had obviously just been drinking, he was not drunk. There was
extraordinary impudence in his expression, and yet, strange to say, at the
same time there was fear. He looked like a man who had long been kept in
subjection and had submitted to it, and now had suddenly turned and was
trying to assert himself. Or, better still, like a man who wants
dreadfully to hit you but is horribly afraid you will hit him. In his
words and in the intonation of his shrill voice there was a sort of crazy
humor, at times spiteful and at times cringing, and continually shifting
from one tone to another. The question about вЂњour retreatвЂќ he had asked as
it were quivering all over, rolling his eyes, and skipping up so close to
Alyosha that he instinctively drew back a step. He was dressed in a very
shabby dark cotton coat, patched and spotted. He wore checked trousers of
an extremely light color, long out of fashion, and of very thin material.
They were so crumpled and so short that he looked as though he had grown
out of them like a boy.

вЂњI am Alexey Karamazov,вЂќ Alyosha began in reply.

вЂњI quite understand that, sir,вЂќ the gentleman snapped out at once to
assure him that he knew who he was already. вЂњI am Captain Snegiryov, sir,
but I am still desirous to know precisely what has led youвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњOh, IвЂ™ve come for nothing special. I wanted to have a word with youвЂ”if
only you allow me.вЂќ

вЂњIn that case, here is a chair, sir; kindly be seated. ThatвЂ™s what they
used to say in the old comedies, вЂkindly be seated,вЂ™ вЂќ and with a rapid
gesture he seized an empty chair (it was a rough wooden chair, not
upholstered) and set it for him almost in the middle of the room; then,
taking another similar chair for himself, he sat down facing Alyosha, so
close to him that their knees almost touched.

вЂњNikolay Ilyitch Snegiryov, sir, formerly a captain in the Russian
infantry, put to shame for his vices, but still a captain. Though I might
not be one now for the way I talk; for the last half of my life IвЂ™ve
learnt to say вЂsir.вЂ™ ItвЂ™s a word you use when youвЂ™ve come down in the
world.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s very true,вЂќ smiled Alyosha. вЂњBut is it used involuntarily or on
purpose?вЂќ

вЂњAs GodвЂ™s above, itвЂ™s involuntary, and I usenвЂ™t to use it! I didnвЂ™t use
the word вЂsirвЂ™ all my life, but as soon as I sank into low water I began
to say вЂsir.вЂ™ ItвЂ™s the work of a higher power. I see you are interested in
contemporary questions, but how can I have excited your curiosity, living
as I do in surroundings impossible for the exercise of hospitality?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ve comeвЂ”about that business.вЂќ

вЂњAbout what business?вЂќ the captain interrupted impatiently.

вЂњAbout your meeting with my brother Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ Alyosha blurted
out awkwardly.

вЂњWhat meeting, sir? You donвЂ™t mean that meeting? About my вЂwisp of tow,вЂ™
then?вЂќ He moved closer so that his knees positively knocked against
Alyosha. His lips were strangely compressed like a thread.

вЂњWhat wisp of tow?вЂќ muttered Alyosha.

вЂњHe is come to complain of me, father!вЂќ cried a voice familiar to
AlyoshaвЂ”the voice of the schoolboyвЂ”from behind the curtain. вЂњI bit his
finger just now.вЂќ The curtain was pulled, and Alyosha saw his assailant
lying on a little bed made up on the bench and the chair in the corner
under the ikons. The boy lay covered by his coat and an old wadded quilt.
He was evidently unwell, and, judging by his glittering eyes, he was in a
fever. He looked at Alyosha without fear, as though he felt he was at home
and could not be touched.

вЂњWhat! Did he bite your finger?вЂќ The captain jumped up from his chair.
вЂњWas it your finger he bit?вЂќ

вЂњYes. He was throwing stones with other schoolboys. There were six of them
against him alone. I went up to him, and he threw a stone at me and then
another at my head. I asked him what I had done to him. And then he rushed
at me and bit my finger badly, I donвЂ™t know why.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll thrash him, sir, at onceвЂ”this minute!вЂќ The captain jumped up from
his seat.

вЂњBut I am not complaining at all, I am simply telling you ... I donвЂ™t want
him to be thrashed. Besides, he seems to be ill.вЂќ

вЂњAnd do you suppose IвЂ™d thrash him? That IвЂ™d take my Ilusha and thrash him
before you for your satisfaction? Would you like it done at once, sir?вЂќ
said the captain, suddenly turning to Alyosha, as though he were going to
attack him. вЂњI am sorry about your finger, sir; but instead of thrashing
Ilusha, would you like me to chop off my four fingers with this knife here
