вЂњWonвЂ™t he? Then why are you dressed up like that?вЂќ said Rakitin, with a
venomous sneer.

вЂњDonвЂ™t taunt me with dressing up, Rakitin, you donвЂ™t know all that is in
my heart! If I choose to tear off my finery, IвЂ™ll tear it off at once,
this minute,вЂќ she cried in a resonant voice. вЂњYou donвЂ™t know what that
finery is for, Rakitin! Perhaps I shall see him and say: вЂHave you ever
seen me look like this before?вЂ™ He left me a thin, consumptive cryвЂђbaby of
seventeen. IвЂ™ll sit by him, fascinate him and work him up. вЂDo you see
what I am like now?вЂ™ IвЂ™ll say to him; вЂwell, and thatвЂ™s enough for you, my
dear sir, thereвЂ™s many a slip twixt the cup and the lip!вЂ™ That may be what
the finery is for, Rakitin.вЂќ Grushenka finished with a malicious laugh.
вЂњIвЂ™m violent and resentful, Alyosha, IвЂ™ll tear off my finery, IвЂ™ll destroy
my beauty, IвЂ™ll scorch my face, slash it with a knife, and turn beggar. If
I choose, I wonвЂ™t go anywhere now to see any one. If I choose, IвЂ™ll send
Kuzma back all he has ever given me, toвЂђmorrow, and all his money and IвЂ™ll
go out charing for the rest of my life. You think I wouldnвЂ™t do it,
Rakitin, that I would not dare to do it? I would, I would, I could do it
directly, only donвЂ™t exasperate me ... and IвЂ™ll send him about his
business, IвЂ™ll snap my fingers in his face, he shall never see me again!вЂќ

She uttered the last words in an hysterical scream, but broke down again,
hid her face in her hands, buried it in the pillow and shook with sobs.

Rakitin got up.

вЂњItвЂ™s time we were off,вЂќ he said, вЂњitвЂ™s late, we shall be shut out of the
monastery.вЂќ

Grushenka leapt up from her place.

вЂњSurely you donвЂ™t want to go, Alyosha!вЂќ she cried, in mournful surprise.
вЂњWhat are you doing to me? YouвЂ™ve stirred up my feeling, tortured me, and
now youвЂ™ll leave me to face this night alone!вЂќ

вЂњHe can hardly spend the night with you! Though if he wants to, let him!
IвЂ™ll go alone,вЂќ Rakitin scoffed jeeringly.

вЂњHush, evil tongue!вЂќ Grushenka cried angrily at him; вЂњyou never said such
words to me as he has come to say.вЂќ

вЂњWhat has he said to you so special?вЂќ asked Rakitin irritably.

вЂњI canвЂ™t say, I donвЂ™t know. I donвЂ™t know what he said to me, it went
straight to my heart; he has wrung my heart.... He is the first, the only
one who has pitied me, thatвЂ™s what it is. Why did you not come before, you
angel?вЂќ She fell on her knees before him as though in a sudden frenzy.
вЂњIвЂ™ve been waiting all my life for some one like you, I knew that some one
like you would come and forgive me. I believed that, nasty as I am, some
one would really love me, not only with a shameful love!вЂќ

вЂњWhat have I done to you?вЂќ answered Alyosha, bending over her with a
tender smile, and gently taking her by the hands; вЂњI only gave you an
onion, nothing but a tiny little onion, that was all!вЂќ

He was moved to tears himself as he said it. At that moment there was a
sudden noise in the passage, some one came into the hall. Grushenka jumped
up, seeming greatly alarmed. Fenya ran noisily into the room, crying out:

вЂњMistress, mistress darling, a messenger has galloped up,вЂќ she cried,
breathless and joyful. вЂњA carriage from Mokroe for you, Timofey the
driver, with three horses, they are just putting in fresh horses.... A
letter, hereвЂ™s the letter, mistress.вЂќ

A letter was in her hand and she waved it in the air all the while she
talked. Grushenka snatched the letter from her and carried it to the
candle. It was only a note, a few lines. She read it in one instant.

вЂњHe has sent for me,вЂќ she cried, her face white and distorted, with a wan
smile; вЂњhe whistles! Crawl back, little dog!вЂќ

But only for one instant she stood as though hesitating; suddenly the
blood rushed to her head and sent a glow to her cheeks.

вЂњI will go,вЂќ she cried; вЂњfive years of my life! GoodвЂђby! GoodвЂђby, Alyosha,
my fate is sealed. Go, go, leave me all of you, donвЂ™t let me see you
again! Grushenka is flying to a new life.... DonвЂ™t you remember evil
against me either, Rakitin. I may be going to my death! Ugh! I feel as
though I were drunk!вЂќ

She suddenly left them and ran into her bedroom.

вЂњWell, she has no thoughts for us now!вЂќ grumbled Rakitin. вЂњLetвЂ™s go, or we
may hear that feminine shriek again. I am sick of all these tears and
cries.вЂќ

Alyosha mechanically let himself be led out. In the yard stood a covered
cart. Horses were being taken out of the shafts, men were running to and
fro with a lantern. Three fresh horses were being led in at the open gate.
But when Alyosha and Rakitin reached the bottom of the steps, GrushenkaвЂ™s
bedroom window was suddenly opened and she called in a ringing voice after
Alyosha:

вЂњAlyosha, give my greetings to your brother Mitya and tell him not to
remember evil against me, though I have brought him misery. And tell him,
too, in my words: вЂGrushenka has fallen to a scoundrel, and not to you,
noble heart.вЂ™ And add, too, that Grushenka loved him only one hour, only
one short hour she loved himвЂ”so let him remember that hour all his
lifeвЂ”say, вЂGrushenka tells you to!вЂ™ вЂќ

She ended in a voice full of sobs. The window was shut with a slam.

вЂњHвЂ™m, hвЂ™m!вЂќ growled Rakitin, laughing, вЂњshe murders your brother Mitya and
then tells him to remember it all his life! What ferocity!вЂќ

Alyosha made no reply, he seemed not to have heard. He walked fast beside
Rakitin as though in a terrible hurry. He was lost in thought and moved
mechanically. Rakitin felt a sudden twinge as though he had been touched
on an open wound. He had expected something quite different by bringing
Grushenka and Alyosha together. Something very different from what he had
hoped for had happened.

вЂњHe is a Pole, that officer of hers,вЂќ he began again, restraining himself;
вЂњand indeed he is not an officer at all now. He served in the customs in
Siberia, somewhere on the Chinese frontier, some puny little beggar of a
Pole, I expect. Lost his job, they say. HeвЂ™s heard now that GrushenkaвЂ™s
saved a little money, so heвЂ™s turned up againвЂ”thatвЂ™s the explanation of
the mystery.вЂќ

Again Alyosha seemed not to hear. Rakitin could not control himself.

вЂњWell, so youвЂ™ve saved the sinner?вЂќ he laughed spitefully. вЂњHave you
turned the Magdalene into the true path? Driven out the seven devils, eh?
So you see the miracles you were looking out for just now have come to
pass!вЂќ

вЂњHush, Rakitin,вЂќ Alyosha answered with an aching heart.

вЂњSo you despise me now for those twentyвЂђfive roubles? IвЂ™ve sold my friend,
you think. But you are not Christ, you know, and I am not Judas.вЂќ

вЂњOh, Rakitin, I assure you IвЂ™d forgotten about it,вЂќ cried Alyosha, вЂњyou
remind me of it yourself....вЂќ

But this was the last straw for Rakitin.

вЂњDamnation take you all and each of you!вЂќ he cried suddenly, вЂњwhy the
devil did I take you up? I donвЂ™t want to know you from this time forward.
Go alone, thereвЂ™s your road!вЂќ

And he turned abruptly into another street, leaving Alyosha alone in the
dark. Alyosha came out of the town and walked across the fields to the
monastery.



Chapter IV. Cana Of Galilee


It was very late, according to the monastery ideas, when Alyosha returned
to the hermitage; the doorвЂђkeeper let him in by a special entrance. It had
struck nine oвЂ™clockвЂ”the hour of rest and repose after a day of such
agitation for all. Alyosha timidly opened the door and went into the
elderвЂ™s cell where his coffin was now standing. There was no one in the
cell but Father PaГЇssy, reading the Gospel in solitude over the coffin,
and the young novice Porfiry, who, exhausted by the previous nightвЂ™s
conversation and the disturbing incidents of the day, was sleeping the
deep sound sleep of youth on the floor of the other room. Though Father
PaГЇssy heard Alyosha come in, he did not even look in his direction.
Alyosha turned to the right from the door to the corner, fell on his knees
and began to pray.

His soul was overflowing but with mingled feelings; no single sensation
stood out distinctly; on the contrary, one drove out another in a slow,
continual rotation. But there was a sweetness in his heart and, strange to
say, Alyosha was not surprised at it. Again he saw that coffin before him,
the hidden dead figure so precious to him, but the weeping and poignant
grief of the morning was no longer aching in his soul. As soon as he came
in, he fell down before the coffin as before a holy shrine, but joy, joy
was glowing in his mind and in his heart. The one window of the cell was
open, the air was fresh and cool. вЂњSo the smell must have become stronger,
if they opened the window,вЂќ thought Alyosha. But even this thought of the
smell of corruption, which had seemed to him so awful and humiliating a
few hours before, no longer made him feel miserable or indignant. He began
quietly praying, but he soon felt that he was praying almost mechanically.
Fragments of thought floated through his soul, flashed like stars and went
out again at once, to be succeeded by others. But yet there was reigning
in his soul a sense of the wholeness of thingsвЂ”something steadfast and
comfortingвЂ”and he was aware of it himself. Sometimes he began praying
ardently, he longed to pour out his thankfulness and love....

But when he had begun to pray, he passed suddenly to something else, and
sank into thought, forgetting both the prayer and what had interrupted it.
He began listening to what Father PaГЇssy was reading, but worn out with
exhaustion he gradually began to doze.

вЂњ_And the third day there was a marriage in Cana of Galilee;_вЂќ read Father
PaГЇssy. вЂњ_And the mother of Jesus was there; And both Jesus was called,
and his disciples, to the marriage._вЂќ

вЂњMarriage? WhatвЂ™s that?... A marriage!вЂќ floated whirling through AlyoshaвЂ™s
mind. вЂњThere is happiness for her, too.... She has gone to the feast....
No, she has not taken the knife.... That was only a tragic phrase.... Well
... tragic phrases should be forgiven, they must be. Tragic phrases
comfort the heart.... Without them, sorrow would be too heavy for men to
bear. Rakitin has gone off to the back alley. As long as Rakitin broods
over his wrongs, he will always go off to the back alley.... But the high
road ... The road is wide and straight and bright as crystal, and the sun
is at the end of it.... Ah!... WhatвЂ™s being read?вЂќ...

вЂњ_And when they wanted wine, the mother of Jesus saith unto him, They have
no wine_вЂќ ... Alyosha heard.

вЂњAh, yes, I was missing that, and I didnвЂ™t want to miss it, I love that
passage: itвЂ™s Cana of Galilee, the first miracle.... Ah, that miracle! Ah,
that sweet miracle! It was not menвЂ™s grief, but their joy Christ visited,
He worked His first miracle to help menвЂ™s gladness.... вЂHe who loves men
loves their gladness, tooвЂ™ ... He was always repeating that, it was one of
his leading ideas.... вЂThereвЂ™s no living without joy,вЂ™ Mitya says.... Yes,
Mitya.... вЂEverything that is true and good is always full of
forgiveness,вЂ™ he used to say that, tooвЂќ ...

вЂњ_Jesus saith unto her, Woman, what has it to do with thee or me? Mine
hour is not yet come._

вЂњ_His mother saith unto the servants, Whatsoever he saith unto you, do
it_вЂќ ...

вЂњDo it.... Gladness, the gladness of some poor, very poor, people.... Of
course they were poor, since they hadnвЂ™t wine enough even at a wedding....
The historians write that, in those days, the people living about the Lake
of Gennesaret were the poorest that can possibly be imagined ... and
another great heart, that other great being, His Mother, knew that He had
come not only to make His great terrible sacrifice. She knew that His
heart was open even to the simple, artless merrymaking of some obscure and
unlearned people, who had warmly bidden Him to their poor wedding. вЂMine
hour is not yet come,вЂ™ He said, with a soft smile (He must have smiled
gently to her). And, indeed, was it to make wine abundant at poor weddings
He had come down to earth? And yet He went and did as she asked Him....
Ah, he is reading againвЂќ....

вЂњ_Jesus saith unto them, Fill the waterpots with water. And they filled
them up to the brim._

вЂњ_And he saith unto them, Draw out now and bear unto the governor of the
feast. And they bare it._

вЂњ_When the ruler of the feast had tasted the water that was made wine, and
knew not whence it was; (but the servants which drew the water knew;) the
governor of the feast called the bridegroom,_

вЂњ_And saith unto him, Every man at the beginning doth set forth good wine;
and when men have well drunk, that which is worse; but thou hast kept the
good wine until now._вЂќ

вЂњBut whatвЂ™s this, whatвЂ™s this? Why is the room growing wider?... Ah, yes
... ItвЂ™s the marriage, the wedding ... yes, of course. Here are the
guests, here are the young couple sitting, and the merry crowd and ...
Where is the wise governor of the feast? But who is this? Who? Again the
walls are receding.... Who is getting up there from the great table?
What!... He here, too? But heвЂ™s in the coffin ... but heвЂ™s here, too. He
has stood up, he sees me, he is coming here.... God!вЂќ...

Yes, he came up to him, to him, he, the little, thin old man, with tiny
wrinkles on his face, joyful and laughing softly. There was no coffin now,
and he was in the same dress as he had worn yesterday sitting with them,
when the visitors had gathered about him. His face was uncovered, his eyes
were shining. How was this, then? He, too, had been called to the feast.
He, too, at the marriage of Cana in Galilee....

вЂњYes, my dear, I am called, too, called and bidden,вЂќ he heard a soft voice
saying over him. вЂњWhy have you hidden yourself here, out of sight? You
come and join us too.вЂќ

It was his voice, the voice of Father Zossima. And it must be he, since he
called him!

The elder raised Alyosha by the hand and he rose from his knees.

вЂњWe are rejoicing,вЂќ the little, thin old man went on. вЂњWe are drinking the
new wine, the wine of new, great gladness; do you see how many guests?
Here are the bride and bridegroom, here is the wise governor of the feast,
he is tasting the new wine. Why do you wonder at me? I gave an onion to a
beggar, so I, too, am here. And many here have given only an onion
eachвЂ”only one little onion.... What are all our deeds? And you, my gentle
one, you, my kind boy, you too have known how to give a famished woman an
onion toвЂђday. Begin your work, dear one, begin it, gentle one!... Do you
see our Sun, do you see Him?вЂќ

вЂњI am afraid ... I dare not look,вЂќ whispered Alyosha.

вЂњDo not fear Him. He is terrible in His greatness, awful in His sublimity,
but infinitely merciful. He has made Himself like unto us from love and
rejoices with us. He is changing the water into wine that the gladness of
the guests may not be cut short. He is expecting new guests, He is calling
new ones unceasingly for ever and ever.... There they are bringing new
wine. Do you see they are bringing the vessels....вЂќ

Something glowed in AlyoshaвЂ™s heart, something filled it till it ached,
tears of rapture rose from his soul.... He stretched out his hands,
uttered a cry and waked up.

Again the coffin, the open window, and the soft, solemn, distinct reading
of the Gospel. But Alyosha did not listen to the reading. It was strange,
he had fallen asleep on his knees, but now he was on his feet, and
suddenly, as though thrown forward, with three firm rapid steps he went
right up to the coffin. His shoulder brushed against Father PaГЇssy without
his noticing it. Father PaГЇssy raised his eyes for an instant from his
book, but looked away again at once, seeing that something strange was
happening to the boy. Alyosha gazed for half a minute at the coffin, at
the covered, motionless dead man that lay in the coffin, with the ikon on
his breast and the peaked cap with the octangular cross, on his head. He
had only just been hearing his voice, and that voice was still ringing in
his ears. He was listening, still expecting other words, but suddenly he
turned sharply and went out of the cell.

He did not stop on the steps either, but went quickly down; his soul,
overflowing with rapture, yearned for freedom, space, openness. The vault
of heaven, full of soft, shining stars, stretched vast and fathomless
above him. The Milky Way ran in two pale streams from the zenith to the
horizon. The fresh, motionless, still night enfolded the earth. The white
towers and golden domes of the cathedral gleamed out against the sapphire
sky. The gorgeous autumn flowers, in the beds round the house, were
slumbering till morning. The silence of earth seemed to melt into the
silence of the heavens. The mystery of earth was one with the mystery of
the stars....

Alyosha stood, gazed, and suddenly threw himself down on the earth. He did
not know why he embraced it. He could not have told why he longed so
irresistibly to kiss it, to kiss it all. But he kissed it weeping, sobbing
and watering it with his tears, and vowed passionately to love it, to love
it for ever and ever. вЂњWater the earth with the tears of your joy and love
those tears,вЂќ echoed in his soul.

What was he weeping over?

Oh! in his rapture he was weeping even over those stars, which were
shining to him from the abyss of space, and вЂњhe was not ashamed of that
ecstasy.вЂќ There seemed to be threads from all those innumerable worlds of
God, linking his soul to them, and it was trembling all over вЂњin contact
with other worlds.вЂќ He longed to forgive every one and for everything, and
to beg forgiveness. Oh, not for himself, but for all men, for all and for
everything. вЂњAnd others are praying for me too,вЂќ echoed again in his soul.
But with every instant he felt clearly and, as it were, tangibly, that
something firm and unshakable as that vault of heaven had entered into his
soul. It was as though some idea had seized the sovereignty of his
mindвЂ”and it was for all his life and for ever and ever. He had fallen on
the earth a weak boy, but he rose up a resolute champion, and he knew and
felt it suddenly at the very moment of his ecstasy. And never, never, all
his life long, could Alyosha forget that minute.

вЂњSome one visited my soul in that hour,вЂќ he used to say afterwards, with
implicit faith in his words.

Within three days he left the monastery in accordance with the words of
his elder, who had bidden him вЂњsojourn in the world.вЂќ




Book VIII. Mitya



Chapter I. Kuzma Samsonov


But Dmitri, to whom Grushenka, flying away to a new life, had left her
last greetings, bidding him remember the hour of her love for ever, knew
nothing of what had happened to her, and was at that moment in a condition
of feverish agitation and activity. For the last two days he had been in
such an inconceivable state of mind that he might easily have fallen ill
with brain fever, as he said himself afterwards. Alyosha had not been able
to find him the morning before, and Ivan had not succeeded in meeting him
at the tavern on the same day. The people at his lodgings, by his orders,
concealed his movements.

He had spent those two days literally rushing in all directions,
вЂњstruggling with his destiny and trying to save himself,вЂќ as he expressed
it himself afterwards, and for some hours he even made a dash out of the
town on urgent business, terrible as it was to him to lose sight of
Grushenka for a moment. All this was explained afterwards in detail, and
confirmed by documentary evidence; but for the present we will only note
the most essential incidents of those two terrible days immediately
preceding the awful catastrophe, that broke so suddenly upon him.

Though Grushenka had, it is true, loved him for an hour, genuinely and
sincerely, yet she tortured him sometimes cruelly and mercilessly. The
worst of it was that he could never tell what she meant to do. To prevail
upon her by force or kindness was also impossible: she would yield to
nothing. She would only have become angry and turned away from him
altogether, he knew that well already. He suspected, quite correctly, that
she, too, was passing through an inward struggle, and was in a state of
extraordinary indecision, that she was making up her mind to something,
and unable to determine upon it. And so, not without good reason, he
divined, with a sinking heart, that at moments she must simply hate him
and his passion. And so, perhaps, it was, but what was distressing
Grushenka he did not understand. For him the whole tormenting question lay
between him and Fyodor Pavlovitch.

Here, we must note, by the way, one certain fact: he was firmly persuaded
that Fyodor Pavlovitch would offer, or perhaps had offered, Grushenka
lawful wedlock, and did not for a moment believe that the old voluptuary
hoped to gain his object for three thousand roubles. Mitya had reached
this conclusion from his knowledge of Grushenka and her character. That
was how it was that he could believe at times that all GrushenkaвЂ™s
uneasiness rose from not knowing which of them to choose, which was most
to her advantage.

Strange to say, during those days it never occurred to him to think of the
approaching return of the вЂњofficer,вЂќ that is, of the man who had been such
a fatal influence in GrushenkaвЂ™s life, and whose arrival she was expecting
with such emotion and dread. It is true that of late Grushenka had been
very silent about it. Yet he was perfectly aware of a letter she had
received a month ago from her seducer, and had heard of it from her own
lips. He partly knew, too, what the letter contained. In a moment of spite
Grushenka had shown him that letter, but to her astonishment he attached
hardly any consequence to it. It would be hard to say why this was.
Perhaps, weighed down by all the hideous horror of his struggle with his
own father for this woman, he was incapable of imagining any danger more
terrible, at any rate for the time. He simply did not believe in a suitor
who suddenly turned up again after five yearsвЂ™ disappearance, still less
in his speedy arrival. Moreover, in the вЂњofficerвЂ™sвЂќ first letter which had
been shown to Mitya, the possibility of his new rivalвЂ™s visit was very
vaguely suggested. The letter was very indefinite, highвЂђflown, and full of
sentimentality. It must be noted that Grushenka had concealed from him the
last lines of the letter, in which his return was alluded to more
definitely. He had, besides, noticed at that moment, he remembered
afterwards, a certain involuntary proud contempt for this missive from
Siberia on GrushenkaвЂ™s face. Grushenka told him nothing of what had passed
later between her and this rival; so that by degrees he had completely
forgotten the officerвЂ™s existence.

He felt that whatever might come later, whatever turn things might take,
his final conflict with Fyodor Pavlovitch was close upon him, and must be
decided before anything else. With a sinking heart he was expecting every
moment GrushenkaвЂ™s decision, always believing that it would come suddenly,
on the impulse of the moment. All of a sudden she would say to him: вЂњTake
me, IвЂ™m yours for ever,вЂќ and it would all be over. He would seize her and
bear her away at once to the ends of the earth. Oh, then he would bear her
away at once, as far, far away as possible; to the farthest end of Russia,
if not of the earth, then he would marry her, and settle down with her
incognito, so that no one would know anything about them, there, here, or
anywhere. Then, oh, then, a new life would begin at once!

Of this different, reformed and вЂњvirtuousвЂќ life (вЂњit must, it must be
virtuousвЂќ) he dreamed feverishly at every moment. He thirsted for that
reformation and renewal. The filthy morass, in which he had sunk of his
own free will, was too revolting to him, and, like very many men in such
cases, he put faith above all in change of place. If only it were not for
these people, if only it were not for these circumstances, if only he
could fly away from this accursed placeвЂ”he would be altogether
regenerated, would enter on a new path. That was what he believed in, and
what he was yearning for.

But all this could only be on condition of the first, the _happy_ solution
of the question. There was another possibility, a different and awful
ending. Suddenly she might say to him: вЂњGo away. I have just come to terms
with Fyodor Pavlovitch. I am going to marry him and donвЂ™t want youвЂќвЂ”and
then ... but then.... But Mitya did not know what would happen then. Up to
the last hour he didnвЂ™t know. That must be said to his credit. He had no
definite intentions, had planned no crime. He was simply watching and
spying in agony, while he prepared himself for the first, happy solution
of his destiny. He drove away any other idea, in fact. But for that ending
a quite different anxiety arose, a new, incidental, but yet fatal and
insoluble difficulty presented itself.

If she were to say to him: вЂњIвЂ™m yours; take me away,вЂќ how could he take
her away? Where had he the means, the money to do it? It was just at this
time that all sources of revenue from Fyodor Pavlovitch, doles which had
gone on without interruption for so many years, ceased. Grushenka had
money, of course, but with regard to this Mitya suddenly evinced
extraordinary pride; he wanted to carry her away and begin the new life
with her himself, at his own expense, not at hers. He could not conceive
of taking her money, and the very idea caused him a pang of intense
repulsion. I wonвЂ™t enlarge on this fact or analyze it here, but confine
myself to remarking that this was his attitude at the moment. All this may
have arisen indirectly and unconsciously from the secret stings of his
conscience for the money of Katerina Ivanovna that he had dishonestly
appropriated. вЂњIвЂ™ve been a scoundrel to one of them, and I shall be a
scoundrel again to the other directly,вЂќ was his feeling then, as he
explained after: вЂњand when Grushenka knows, she wonвЂ™t care for such a
scoundrel.вЂќ

Where then was he to get the means, where was he to get the fateful money?
Without it, all would be lost and nothing could be done, вЂњand only because
I hadnвЂ™t the money. Oh, the shame of it!вЂќ

To anticipate things: he did, perhaps, know where to get the money, knew,
perhaps, where it lay at that moment. I will say no more of this here, as
it will all be clear later. But his chief trouble, I must explain however
obscurely, lay in the fact that to have that sum he knew of, to _have the
right_ to take it, he must first restore Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s three
thousandвЂ”if not, вЂњIвЂ™m a common pickpocket, IвЂ™m a scoundrel, and I donвЂ™t
want to begin a new life as a scoundrel,вЂќ Mitya decided. And so he made up
his mind to move heaven and earth to return Katerina Ivanovna that three
thousand, and that _first of all_. The final stage of this decision, so to
say, had been reached only during the last hours, that is, after his last
interview with Alyosha, two days before, on the highвЂђroad, on the evening
when Grushenka had insulted Katerina Ivanovna, and Mitya, after hearing
AlyoshaвЂ™s account of it, had admitted that he was a scoundrel, and told
him to tell Katerina Ivanovna so, if it could be any comfort to her. After
parting from his brother on that night, he had felt in his frenzy that it
would be better вЂњto murder and rob some one than fail to pay my debt to
Katya. IвЂ™d rather every one thought me a robber and a murderer, IвЂ™d rather
go to Siberia than that Katya should have the right to say that I deceived
her and stole her money, and used her money to run away with Grushenka and
begin a new life! That I canвЂ™t do!вЂќ So Mitya decided, grinding his teeth,
and he might well fancy at times that his brain would give way. But
meanwhile he went on struggling....

Strange to say, though one would have supposed there was nothing left for
him but despairвЂ”for what chance had he, with nothing in the world, to
raise such a sum?вЂ”yet to the very end he persisted in hoping that he would
get that three thousand, that the money would somehow come to him of
itself, as though it might drop from heaven. That is just how it is with
people who, like Dmitri, have never had anything to do with money, except
to squander what has come to them by inheritance without any effort of
their own, and have no notion how money is obtained. A whirl of the most
fantastic notions took possession of his brain immediately after he had
parted with Alyosha two days before, and threw his thoughts into a tangle
of confusion. This is how it was he pitched first on a perfectly wild
enterprise. And perhaps to men of that kind in such circumstances the most
impossible, fantastic schemes occur first, and seem most practical.

He suddenly determined to go to Samsonov, the merchant who was GrushenkaвЂ™s
protector, and to propose a вЂњschemeвЂќ to him, and by means of it to obtain
from him at once the whole of the sum required. Of the commercial value of
his scheme he had no doubt, not the slightest, and was only uncertain how
Samsonov would look upon his freak, supposing he were to consider it from
any but the commercial point of view. Though Mitya knew the merchant by
sight, he was not acquainted with him and had never spoken a word to him.
But for some unknown reason he had long entertained the conviction that
the old reprobate, who was lying at deathвЂ™s door, would perhaps not at all
object now to GrushenkaвЂ™s securing a respectable position, and marrying a
man вЂњto be depended upon.вЂќ And he believed not only that he would not
object, but that this was what he desired, and, if opportunity arose, that
he would be ready to help. From some rumor, or perhaps from some stray
word of GrushenkaвЂ™s, he had gathered further that the old man would
perhaps prefer him to Fyodor Pavlovitch for Grushenka.

Possibly many of the readers of my novel will feel that in reckoning on
such assistance, and being ready to take his bride, so to speak, from the
hands of her protector, Dmitri showed great coarseness and want of
delicacy. I will only observe that Mitya looked upon GrushenkaвЂ™s past as
something completely over. He looked on that past with infinite pity and
resolved with all the fervor of his passion that when once Grushenka told
him she loved him and would marry him, it would mean the beginning of a
new Grushenka and a new Dmitri, free from every vice. They would forgive
one another and would begin their lives afresh. As for Kuzma Samsonov,
Dmitri looked upon him as a man who had exercised a fateful influence in
that remote past of GrushenkaвЂ™s, though she had never loved him, and who
was now himself a thing of the past, completely done with, and, so to say,
nonвЂђexistent. Besides, Mitya hardly looked upon him as a man at all, for
it was known to every one in the town that he was only a shattered wreck,
whose relations with Grushenka had changed their character and were now
simply paternal, and that this had been so for a long time.

In any case there was much simplicity on MityaвЂ™s part in all this, for in
spite of all his vices, he was a very simpleвЂђhearted man. It was an
instance of this simplicity that Mitya was seriously persuaded that, being
on the eve of his departure for the next world, old Kuzma must sincerely
repent of his past relations with Grushenka, and that she had no more
devoted friend and protector in the world than this, now harmless old man.

After his conversation with Alyosha, at the crossвЂђroads, he hardly slept
all night, and at ten oвЂ™clock next morning, he was at the house of
Samsonov and telling the servant to announce him. It was a very large and
gloomy old house of two stories, with a lodge and outhouses. In the lower
story lived SamsonovвЂ™s two married sons with their families, his old
sister, and his unmarried daughter. In the lodge lived two of his clerks,
one of whom also had a large family. Both the lodge and the lower story
were overcrowded, but the old man kept the upper floor to himself, and
would not even let the daughter live there with him, though she waited
upon him, and in spite of her asthma was obliged at certain fixed hours,
and at any time he might call her, to run upstairs to him from below.

This upper floor contained a number of large rooms kept purely for show,
furnished in the oldвЂђfashioned merchant style, with long monotonous rows
of clumsy mahogany chairs along the walls, with glass chandeliers under
shades, and gloomy mirrors on the walls. All these rooms were entirely
empty and unused, for the old man kept to one room, a small, remote
bedroom, where he was waited upon by an old servant with a kerchief on her
head, and by a lad, who used to sit on the locker in the passage. Owing to
his swollen legs, the old man could hardly walk at all, and was only
rarely lifted from his leather armвЂђchair, when the old woman supporting
him led him up and down the room once or twice. He was morose and taciturn
even with this old woman.

When he was informed of the arrival of the вЂњcaptain,вЂќ he at once refused
to see him. But Mitya persisted and sent his name up again. Samsonov
questioned the lad minutely: What he looked like? Whether he was drunk?
Was he going to make a row? The answer he received was: that he was sober,
but wouldnвЂ™t go away. The old man again refused to see him. Then Mitya,
who had foreseen this, and purposely brought pencil and paper with him,
wrote clearly on the piece of paper the words: вЂњOn most important business
closely concerning Agrafena Alexandrovna,вЂќ and sent it up to the old man.

After thinking a little Samsonov told the lad to take the visitor to the
drawingвЂђroom, and sent the old woman downstairs with a summons to his
younger son to come upstairs to him at once. This younger son, a man over
six foot and of exceptional physical strength, who was closelyвЂђshaven and
dressed in the European style, though his father still wore a kaftan and a
beard, came at once without a comment. All the family trembled before the
father. The old man had sent for this giant, not because he was afraid of
the вЂњcaptainвЂќ (he was by no means of a timorous temper), but in order to
have a witness in case of any emergency. Supported by his son and the
servantвЂђlad, he waddled at last into the drawingвЂђroom. It may be assumed
that he felt considerable curiosity. The drawingвЂђroom in which Mitya was
awaiting him was a vast, dreary room that laid a weight of depression on
the heart. It had a double row of windows, a gallery, marbled walls, and
three immense chandeliers with glass lusters covered with shades.

Mitya was sitting on a little chair at the entrance, awaiting his fate
with nervous impatience. When the old man appeared at the opposite door,
seventy feet away, Mitya jumped up at once, and with his long, military
stride walked to meet him. Mitya was well dressed, in a frockвЂђcoat,
buttoned up, with a round hat and black gloves in his hands, just as he
had been three days before at the elderвЂ™s, at the family meeting with his
father and brothers. The old man waited for him, standing dignified and
unbending, and Mitya felt at once that he had looked him through and
through as he advanced. Mitya was greatly impressed, too, with SamsonovвЂ™s
immensely swollen face. His lower lip, which had always been thick, hung
down now, looking like a bun. He bowed to his guest in dignified silence,
motioned him to a low chair by the sofa, and, leaning on his sonвЂ™s arm he
began lowering himself on to the sofa opposite, groaning painfully, so
that Mitya, seeing his painful exertions, immediately felt remorseful and
sensitively conscious of his insignificance in the presence of the
dignified person he had ventured to disturb.

вЂњWhat is it you want of me, sir?вЂќ said the old man, deliberately,
distinctly, severely, but courteously, when he was at last seated.

Mitya started, leapt up, but sat down again. Then he began at once
speaking with loud, nervous haste, gesticulating, and in a positive
frenzy. He was unmistakably a man driven into a corner, on the brink of
ruin, catching at the last straw, ready to sink if he failed. Old Samsonov
probably grasped all this in an instant, though his face remained cold and
immovable as a statueвЂ™s.

вЂњMost honored sir, Kuzma Kuzmitch, you have no doubt heard more than once
of my disputes with my father, Fyodor Pavlovitch Karamazov, who robbed me
of my inheritance from my mother ... seeing the whole town is gossiping
about it ... for here every oneвЂ™s gossiping of what they shouldnвЂ™t ... and
besides, it might have reached you through Grushenka ... I beg your
pardon, through Agrafena Alexandrovna ... Agrafena Alexandrovna, the lady
for whom I have the highest respect and esteem ...вЂќ

So Mitya began, and broke down at the first sentence. We will not
reproduce his speech word for word, but will only summarize the gist of
it. Three months ago, he said, he had of express intention (Mitya
purposely used these words instead of вЂњintentionallyвЂќ) consulted a lawyer
in the chief town of the province, вЂњa distinguished lawyer, Kuzma
Kuzmitch, Pavel Pavlovitch Korneplodov. You have perhaps heard of him? A
man of vast intellect, the mind of a statesman ... he knows you, too ...
spoke of you in the highest terms ...вЂќ Mitya broke down again. But these
breaks did not deter him. He leapt instantly over the gaps, and struggled
on and on.

This Korneplodov, after questioning him minutely, and inspecting the
documents he was able to bring him (Mitya alluded somewhat vaguely to
these documents, and slurred over the subject with special haste),
reported that they certainly might take proceedings concerning the village
of Tchermashnya, which ought, he said, to have come to him, Mitya, from
his mother, and so checkmate the old villain, his father ... вЂњbecause
every door was not closed and justice might still find a loophole.вЂќ In
fact, he might reckon on an additional sum of six or even seven thousand
roubles from Fyodor Pavlovitch, as Tchermashnya was worth, at least,
twentyвЂђfive thousand, he might say twentyвЂђeight thousand, in fact,
вЂњthirty, thirty, Kuzma Kuzmitch, and would you believe it, I didnвЂ™t get
seventeen from that heartless man!вЂќ So he, Mitya, had thrown the business
up, for the time, knowing nothing about the law, but on coming here was
struck dumb by a crossвЂђclaim made upon him (here Mitya went adrift again
and again took a flying leap forward), вЂњso will not you, excellent and
honored Kuzma Kuzmitch, be willing to take up all my claims against that
unnatural monster, and pay me a sum down of only three thousand?... You
see, you cannot, in any case, lose over it. On my honor, my honor, I swear
that. Quite the contrary, you may make six or seven thousand instead of
three.вЂќ Above all, he wanted this concluded that very day.

вЂњIвЂ™ll do the business with you at a notaryвЂ™s, or whatever it is ... in
fact, IвЂ™m ready to do anything.... IвЂ™ll hand over all the deeds ...
whatever you want, sign anything ... and we could draw up the agreement at
once ... and if it were possible, if it were only possible, that very
morning.... You could pay me that three thousand, for there isnвЂ™t a
capitalist in this town to compare with you, and so would save me from ...
would save me, in fact ... for a good, I might say an honorable action....
For I cherish the most honorable feelings for a certain person, whom you
know well, and care for as a father. I would not have come, indeed, if it
had not been as a father. And, indeed, itвЂ™s a struggle of three in this
business, for itвЂ™s fateвЂ”thatвЂ™s a fearful thing, Kuzma Kuzmitch! A tragedy,
Kuzma Kuzmitch, a tragedy! And as youвЂ™ve dropped out long ago, itвЂ™s a tugвЂђ
ofвЂђwar between two. IвЂ™m expressing it awkwardly, perhaps, but IвЂ™m not a
literary man. You see, IвЂ™m on the one side, and that monster on the other.
So you must choose. ItвЂ™s either I or the monster. It all lies in your
handsвЂ”the fate of three lives, and the happiness of two.... Excuse me, IвЂ™m
making a mess of it, but you understand ... I see from your venerable eyes
that you understand ... and if you donвЂ™t understand, IвЂ™m done for ... so
you see!вЂќ

Mitya broke off his clumsy speech with that, вЂњso you see!вЂќ and jumping up
from his seat, awaited the answer to his foolish proposal. At the last
phrase he had suddenly become hopelessly aware that it had all fallen
flat, above all, that he had been talking utter nonsense.

вЂњHow strange it is! On the way here it seemed all right, and now itвЂ™s
nothing but nonsense.вЂќ The idea suddenly dawned on his despairing mind.
All the while he had been talking, the old man sat motionless, watching
him with an icy expression in his eyes. After keeping him for a moment in
suspense, Kuzma Kuzmitch pronounced at last in the most positive and
chilling tone:

вЂњExcuse me, we donвЂ™t undertake such business.вЂќ

Mitya suddenly felt his legs growing weak under him.

вЂњWhat am I to do now, Kuzma Kuzmitch?вЂќ he muttered, with a pale smile. вЂњI
suppose itвЂ™s all up with meвЂ”what do you think?вЂќ

вЂњExcuse me....вЂќ

Mitya remained standing, staring motionless. He suddenly noticed a
movement in the old manвЂ™s face. He started.

вЂњYou see, sir, business of that sortвЂ™s not in our line,вЂќ said the old man
slowly. вЂњThereвЂ™s the court, and the lawyersвЂ”itвЂ™s a perfect misery. But if
you like, there is a man here you might apply to.вЂќ

вЂњGood heavens! Who is it? YouвЂ™re my salvation, Kuzma Kuzmitch,вЂќ faltered
Mitya.

вЂњHe doesnвЂ™t live here, and heвЂ™s not here just now. He is a peasant, he
does business in timber. His name is Lyagavy. HeвЂ™s been haggling with
Fyodor Pavlovitch for the last year, over your copse at Tchermashnya. They
canвЂ™t agree on the price, maybe youвЂ™ve heard? Now heвЂ™s come back again and
is staying with the priest at Ilyinskoe, about twelve versts from the
Volovya station. He wrote to me, too, about the business of the copse,
asking my advice. Fyodor Pavlovitch means to go and see him himself. So if
you were to be beforehand with Fyodor Pavlovitch and to make Lyagavy the
offer youвЂ™ve made me, he might possiblyвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњA brilliant idea!вЂќ Mitya interrupted ecstatically. вЂњHeвЂ™s the very man, it
would just suit him. HeвЂ™s haggling with him for it, being asked too much,
and here he would have all the documents entitling him to the property
itself. Ha ha ha!вЂќ

And Mitya suddenly went off into his short, wooden laugh, startling
Samsonov.

вЂњHow can I thank you, Kuzma Kuzmitch?вЂќ cried Mitya effusively.

вЂњDonвЂ™t mention it,вЂќ said Samsonov, inclining his head.

вЂњBut you donвЂ™t know, youвЂ™ve saved me. Oh, it was a true presentiment
brought me to you.... So now to this priest!вЂќ

вЂњNo need of thanks.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll make haste and fly there. IвЂ™m afraid IвЂ™ve overtaxed your strength. I
shall never forget it. ItвЂ™s a Russian says that, Kuzma Kuzmitch, a RвЂђrвЂђ
russian!вЂќ

вЂњTo be sure!вЂќ

Mitya seized his hand to press it, but there was a malignant gleam in the
old manвЂ™s eye. Mitya drew back his hand, but at once blamed himself for
his mistrustfulness.

вЂњItвЂ™s because heвЂ™s tired,вЂќ he thought.

вЂњFor her sake! For her sake, Kuzma Kuzmitch! You understand that itвЂ™s for
her,вЂќ he cried, his voice ringing through the room. He bowed, turned
sharply round, and with the same long stride walked to the door without
looking back. He was trembling with delight.

вЂњEverything was on the verge of ruin and my guardian angel saved me,вЂќ was
the thought in his mind. And if such a business man as Samsonov (a most
worthy old man, and what dignity!) had suggested this course, then ...
then success was assured. He would fly off immediately. вЂњI will be back
before night, I shall be back at night and the thing is done. Could the
old man have been laughing at me?вЂќ exclaimed Mitya, as he strode towards
his lodging. He could, of course, imagine nothing, but that the advice was
practical вЂњfrom such a business manвЂќ with an understanding of the
business, with an understanding of this Lyagavy (curious surname!). OrвЂ”the
old man was laughing at him.

Alas! The second alternative was the correct one. Long afterwards, when
the catastrophe had happened, old Samsonov himself confessed, laughing,
that he had made a fool of the вЂњcaptain.вЂќ He was a cold, spiteful and
sarcastic man, liable to violent antipathies. Whether it was the
вЂњcaptainвЂ™sвЂќ excited face, or the foolish conviction of the вЂњrake and
spendthrift,вЂќ that he, Samsonov, could be taken in by such a cockвЂђandвЂђbull
story as his scheme, or his jealousy of Grushenka, in whose name this
вЂњscapegraceвЂќ had rushed in on him with such a tale to get money which
worked on the old man, I canвЂ™t tell. But at the instant when Mitya stood
before him, feeling his legs grow weak under him, and frantically
exclaiming that he was ruined, at that moment the old man looked at him
with intense spite, and resolved to make a laughingвЂђstock of him. When
Mitya had gone, Kuzma Kuzmitch, white with rage, turned to his son and
bade him see to it that that beggar be never seen again, and never
admitted even into the yard, or else heвЂ™dвЂ”

He did not utter his threat. But even his son, who often saw him enraged,
trembled with fear. For a whole hour afterwards, the old man was shaking
with anger, and by evening he was worse, and sent for the doctor.



Chapter II. Lyagavy


So he must drive at full speed, and he had not the money for horses. He
had forty kopecks, and that was all, all that was left after so many years
of prosperity! But he had at home an old silver watch which had long
ceased to go. He snatched it up and carried it to a Jewish watchmaker who
had a shop in the marketвЂђplace. The Jew gave him six roubles for it.

вЂњAnd I didnвЂ™t expect that,вЂќ cried Mitya, ecstatically. (He was still in a
state of ecstasy.) He seized his six roubles and ran home. At home he
borrowed three roubles from the people of the house, who loved him so much
that they were pleased to give it him, though it was all they had. Mitya
in his excitement told them on the spot that his fate would be decided
that day, and he described, in desperate haste, the whole scheme he had
put before Samsonov, the latterвЂ™s decision, his own hopes for the future,
and so on. These people had been told many of their lodgerвЂ™s secrets
before, and so looked upon him as a gentleman who was not at all proud,
and almost one of themselves. Having thus collected nine roubles Mitya
sent for postingвЂђhorses to take him to the Volovya station. This was how
the fact came to be remembered and established that вЂњat midday, on the day
before the event, Mitya had not a farthing, and that he had sold his watch
to get money and had borrowed three roubles from his landlord, all in the
presence of witnesses.вЂќ

I note this fact, later on it will be apparent why I do so.

Though he was radiant with the joyful anticipation that he would at last
solve all his difficulties, yet, as he drew near Volovya station, he
trembled at the thought of what Grushenka might be doing in his absence.
What if she made up her mind toвЂђday to go to Fyodor Pavlovitch? This was
why he had gone off without telling her and why he left orders with his
landlady not to let out where he had gone, if any one came to inquire for
him.

вЂњI must, I must get back toвЂђnight,вЂќ he repeated, as he was jolted along in
the cart, вЂњand I dare say I shall have to bring this Lyagavy back here ...
to draw up the deed.вЂќ So mused Mitya, with a throbbing heart, but alas!
his dreams were not fated to be carried out.

To begin with, he was late, taking a short cut from Volovya station which
turned out to be eighteen versts instead of twelve. Secondly, he did not
find the priest at home at Ilyinskoe; he had gone off to a neighboring
village. While Mitya, setting off there with the same exhausted horses,
was looking for him, it was almost dark.

The priest, a shy and amiable looking little man, informed him at once
that though Lyagavy had been staying with him at first, he was now at
Suhoy Possyolok, that he was staying the night in the foresterвЂ™s cottage,
as he was buying timber there too. At MityaвЂ™s urgent request that he would
take him to Lyagavy at once, and by so doing вЂњsave him, so to speak,вЂќ the
priest agreed, after some demur, to conduct him to Suhoy Possyolok; his
curiosity was obviously aroused. But, unluckily, he advised their going on
foot, as it would not be вЂњmuch overвЂќ a verst. Mitya, of course, agreed,
and marched off with his yardвЂђlong strides, so that the poor priest almost
ran after him. He was a very cautious man, though not old.

Mitya at once began talking to him, too, of his plans, nervously and
excitedly asking advice in regard to Lyagavy, and talking all the way. The
priest listened attentively, but gave little advice. He turned off MityaвЂ™s
questions with: вЂњI donвЂ™t know. Ah, I canвЂ™t say. How can I tell?вЂќ and so
on. When Mitya began to speak of his quarrel with his father over his
inheritance, the priest was positively alarmed, as he was in some way
dependent on Fyodor Pavlovitch. He inquired, however, with surprise, why
he called the peasantвЂђtrader Gorstkin, Lyagavy, and obligingly explained
to Mitya that, though the manвЂ™s name really was Lyagavy, he was never
called so, as he would be grievously offended at the name, and that he
must be sure to call him Gorstkin, вЂњor youвЂ™ll do nothing with him; he
wonвЂ™t even listen to you,вЂќ said the priest in conclusion.

Mitya was somewhat surprised for a moment, and explained that that was
what Samsonov had called him. On hearing this fact, the priest dropped the
subject, though he would have done well to put into words his doubt
whether, if Samsonov had sent him to that peasant, calling him Lyagavy,
there was not something wrong about it and he was turning him into
ridicule. But Mitya had no time to pause over such trifles. He hurried,
striding along, and only when he reached Suhoy Possyolok did he realize
that they had come not one verst, nor one and a half, but at least three.
This annoyed him, but he controlled himself.

They went into the hut. The forester lived in one half of the hut, and
Gorstkin was lodging in the other, the better room the other side of the
passage. They went into that room and lighted a tallow candle. The hut was
extremely overheated. On the table there was a samovar that had gone out,
a tray with cups, an empty rum bottle, a bottle of vodka partly full, and
some halfвЂђeaten crusts of wheaten bread. The visitor himself lay stretched
at full length on the bench, with his coat crushed up under his head for a
pillow, snoring heavily. Mitya stood in perplexity.

вЂњOf course I must wake him. My business is too important. IвЂ™ve come in
such haste. IвЂ™m in a hurry to get back toвЂђday,вЂќ he said in great
agitation. But the priest and the forester stood in silence, not giving
their opinion. Mitya went up and began trying to wake him himself; he
tried vigorously, but the sleeper did not wake.

вЂњHeвЂ™s drunk,вЂќ Mitya decided. вЂњGood Lord! What am I to do? What am I to
do?вЂќ And, terribly impatient, he began pulling him by the arms, by the
legs, shaking his head, lifting him up and making him sit on the bench.
Yet, after prolonged exertions, he could only succeed in getting the
drunken man to utter absurd grunts, and violent, but inarticulate oaths.

вЂњNo, youвЂ™d better wait a little,вЂќ the priest pronounced at last, вЂњfor heвЂ™s
obviously not in a fit state.вЂќ

вЂњHeвЂ™s been drinking the whole day,вЂќ the forester chimed in.

вЂњGood heavens!вЂќ cried Mitya. вЂњIf only you knew how important it is to me
and how desperate I am!вЂќ

вЂњNo, youвЂ™d better wait till morning,вЂќ the priest repeated.

вЂњTill morning? Mercy! thatвЂ™s impossible!вЂќ

And in his despair he was on the point of attacking the sleeping man
again, but stopped short at once, realizing the uselessness of his
efforts. The priest said nothing, the sleepy forester looked gloomy.

вЂњWhat terrible tragedies real life contrives for people,вЂќ said Mitya, in
complete despair. The perspiration was streaming down his face. The priest
seized the moment to put before him, very reasonably, that, even if he
succeeded in wakening the man, he would still be drunk and incapable of
conversation. вЂњAnd your business is important,вЂќ he said, вЂњso youвЂ™d
certainly better put it off till morning.вЂќ With a gesture of despair Mitya
agreed.

вЂњFather, I will stay here with a light, and seize the favorable moment. As
soon as he wakes IвЂ™ll begin. IвЂ™ll pay you for the light,вЂќ he said to the
forester, вЂњfor the nightвЂ™s lodging, too; youвЂ™ll remember Dmitri Karamazov.
Only, Father, I donвЂ™t know what weвЂ™re to do with you. Where will you
sleep?вЂќ

вЂњNo, IвЂ™m going home. IвЂ™ll take his horse and get home,вЂќ he said,
indicating the forester. вЂњAnd now IвЂ™ll say goodвЂђby. I wish you all
success.вЂќ

So it was settled. The priest rode off on the foresterвЂ™s horse, delighted
to escape, though he shook his head uneasily, wondering whether he ought
not next day to inform his benefactor Fyodor Pavlovitch of this curious
incident, вЂњor he may in an unlucky hour hear of it, be angry, and withdraw
his favor.вЂќ

The forester, scratching himself, went back to his room without a word,
and Mitya sat on the bench to вЂњcatch the favorable moment,вЂќ as he
expressed it. Profound dejection clung about his soul like a heavy mist. A
profound, intense dejection! He sat thinking, but could reach no
conclusion. The candle burnt dimly, a cricket chirped; it became
insufferably close in the overheated room. He suddenly pictured the
garden, the path behind the garden, the door of his fatherвЂ™s house
mysteriously opening and Grushenka running in. He leapt up from the bench.

вЂњItвЂ™s a tragedy!вЂќ he said, grinding his teeth. Mechanically he went up to
the sleeping man and looked in his face. He was a lean, middleвЂђaged
peasant, with a very long face, flaxen curls, and a long, thin, reddish
beard, wearing a blue cotton shirt and a black waistcoat, from the pocket
of which peeped the chain of a silver watch. Mitya looked at his face with
intense hatred, and for some unknown reason his curly hair particularly
irritated him.

What was insufferably humiliating was, that after leaving things of such
importance and making such sacrifices, he, Mitya, utterly worn out, should
with business of such urgency be standing over this dolt on whom his whole
fate depended, while he snored as though there were nothing the matter, as
though heвЂ™d dropped from another planet.

вЂњOh, the irony of fate!вЂќ cried Mitya, and, quite losing his head, he fell
again to rousing the tipsy peasant. He roused him with a sort of ferocity,
pulled at him, pushed him, even beat him; but after five minutes of vain
exertions, he returned to his bench in helpless despair, and sat down.

вЂњStupid! Stupid!вЂќ cried Mitya. вЂњAnd how dishonorable it all is!вЂќ something
made him add. His head began to ache horribly. вЂњShould he fling it up and
go away altogether?вЂќ he wondered. вЂњNo, wait till toвЂђmorrow now. IвЂ™ll stay
on purpose. What else did I come for? Besides, IвЂ™ve no means of going. How
am I to get away from here now? Oh, the idiocy of it!вЂќ

But his head ached more and more. He sat without moving, and unconsciously
dozed off and fell asleep as he sat. He seemed to have slept for two hours
or more. He was waked up by his head aching so unbearably that he could
have screamed. There was a hammering in his temples, and the top of his
head ached. It was a long time before he could wake up fully and
understand what had happened to him.

At last he realized that the room was full of charcoal fumes from the
stove, and that he might die of suffocation. And the drunken peasant still
lay snoring. The candle guttered and was about to go out. Mitya cried out,
and ran staggering across the passage into the foresterвЂ™s room. The
forester waked up at once, but hearing that the other room was full of
fumes, to MityaвЂ™s surprise and annoyance, accepted the fact with strange
unconcern, though he did go to see to it.

вЂњBut heвЂ™s dead, heвЂ™s dead! and ... what am I to do then?вЂќ cried Mitya
frantically.

They threw open the doors, opened a window and the chimney. Mitya brought
a pail of water from the passage. First he wetted his own head, then,
finding a rag of some sort, dipped it into the water, and put it on
LyagavyвЂ™s head. The forester still treated the matter contemptuously, and
when he opened the window said grumpily:

вЂњItвЂ™ll be all right, now.вЂќ

He went back to sleep, leaving Mitya a lighted lantern. Mitya fussed about
the drunken peasant for half an hour, wetting his head, and gravely
resolved not to sleep all night. But he was so worn out that when he sat
down for a moment to take breath, he closed his eyes, unconsciously
stretched himself full length on the bench and slept like the dead.

It was dreadfully late when he waked. It was somewhere about nine oвЂ™clock.
The sun was shining brightly in the two little windows of the hut. The
curlyвЂђheaded peasant was sitting on the bench and had his coat on. He had
another samovar and another bottle in front of him. YesterdayвЂ™s bottle had
already been finished, and the new one was more than half empty. Mitya
jumped up and saw at once that the cursed peasant was drunk again,
hopelessly and incurably. He stared at him for a moment with wide opened
eyes. The peasant was silently and slyly watching him, with insulting
composure, and even a sort of contemptuous condescension, so Mitya
fancied. He rushed up to him.

вЂњExcuse me, you see ... I ... youвЂ™ve most likely heard from the forester
here in the hut. IвЂ™m Lieutenant Dmitri Karamazov, the son of the old
Karamazov whose copse you are buying.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s a lie!вЂќ said the peasant, calmly and confidently.

вЂњA lie? You know Fyodor Pavlovitch?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know any of your Fyodor Pavlovitches,вЂќ said the peasant, speaking
thickly.

вЂњYouвЂ™re bargaining with him for the copse, for the copse. Do wake up, and
collect yourself. Father Pavel of Ilyinskoe brought me here. You wrote to
Samsonov, and he has sent me to you,вЂќ Mitya gasped breathlessly.

вЂњYouвЂ™re lвЂђlying!вЂќ Lyagavy blurted out again. MityaвЂ™s legs went cold.

вЂњFor mercyвЂ™s sake! It isnвЂ™t a joke! YouвЂ™re drunk, perhaps. Yet you can
speak and understand ... or else ... I understand nothing!вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re a painter!вЂќ

вЂњFor mercyвЂ™s sake! IвЂ™m Karamazov, Dmitri Karamazov. I have an offer to
make you, an advantageous offer ... very advantageous offer, concerning
the copse!вЂќ

The peasant stroked his beard importantly.

вЂњNo, youвЂ™ve contracted for the job and turned out a scamp. YouвЂ™re a
scoundrel!вЂќ

вЂњI assure you youвЂ™re mistaken,вЂќ cried Mitya, wringing his hands in
despair. The peasant still stroked his beard, and suddenly screwed up his
eyes cunningly.

вЂњNo, you show me this: you tell me the law that allows roguery. DвЂ™you
hear? YouвЂ™re a scoundrel! Do you understand that?вЂќ

Mitya stepped back gloomily, and suddenly вЂњsomething seemed to hit him on
the head,вЂќ as he said afterwards. In an instant a light seemed to dawn in
his mind, вЂњa light was kindled and I grasped it all.вЂќ He stood, stupefied,
wondering how he, after all a man of intelligence, could have yielded to
such folly, have been led into such an adventure, and have kept it up for
almost twentyвЂђfour hours, fussing round this Lyagavy, wetting his head.

вЂњWhy, the manвЂ™s drunk, dead drunk, and heвЂ™ll go on drinking now for a
week; whatвЂ™s the use of waiting here? And what if Samsonov sent me here on
purpose? What if sheвЂ”? Oh, God, what have I done?вЂќ

The peasant sat watching him and grinning. Another time Mitya might have
killed the fool in a fury, but now he felt as weak as a child. He went
quietly to the bench, took up his overcoat, put it on without a word, and
went out of the hut. He did not find the forester in the next room; there
was no one there. He took fifty kopecks in small change out of his pocket
and put them on the table for his nightвЂ™s lodging, the candle, and the
trouble he had given. Coming out of the hut he saw nothing but forest all
round. He walked at hazard, not knowing which way to turn out of the hut,
to the right or to the left. Hurrying there the evening before with the
priest, he had not noticed the road. He had no revengeful feeling for
anybody, even for Samsonov, in his heart. He strode along a narrow forest
path, aimless, dazed, without heeding where he was going. A child could
have knocked him down, so weak was he in body and soul. He got out of the
forest somehow, however, and a vista of fields, bare after the harvest,
stretched as far as the eye could see.

вЂњWhat despair! What death all round!вЂќ he repeated, striding on and on.

He was saved by meeting an old merchant who was being driven across
country in a hired trap. When he overtook him, Mitya asked the way, and it
turned out that the old merchant, too, was going to Volovya. After some
discussion Mitya got into the trap. Three hours later they arrived. At
Volovya, Mitya at once ordered postingвЂђhorses to drive to the town, and
suddenly realized that he was appallingly hungry. While the horses were
being harnessed, an omelette was prepared for him. He ate it all in an
instant, ate a huge hunk of bread, ate a sausage, and swallowed three
glasses of vodka. After eating, his spirits and his heart grew lighter. He
flew towards the town, urged on the driver, and suddenly made a new and
вЂњunalterableвЂќ plan to procure that вЂњaccursed moneyвЂќ before evening. вЂњAnd
to think, only to think that a manвЂ™s life should be ruined for the sake of
that paltry three thousand!вЂќ he cried, contemptuously. вЂњIвЂ™ll settle it toвЂђ
day.вЂќ And if it had not been for the thought of Grushenka and of what
might have happened to her, which never left him, he would perhaps have
become quite cheerful again.... But the thought of her was stabbing him to
the heart every moment, like a sharp knife.

At last they arrived, and Mitya at once ran to Grushenka.



Chapter III. GoldвЂђMines


This was the visit of Mitya of which Grushenka had spoken to Rakitin with
such horror. She was just then expecting the вЂњmessage,вЂќ and was much
relieved that Mitya had not been to see her that day or the day before.
She hoped that вЂњplease God he wonвЂ™t come till IвЂ™m gone away,вЂќ and he
suddenly burst in on her. The rest we know already. To get him off her
hands she suggested at once that he should walk with her to SamsonovвЂ™s,
where she said she absolutely must go вЂњto settle his accounts,вЂќ and when
Mitya accompanied her at once, she said goodвЂђby to him at the gate, making
him promise to come at twelve oвЂ™clock to take her home again. Mitya, too,
was delighted at this arrangement. If she was sitting at SamsonovвЂ™s she
could not be going to Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s, вЂњif only sheвЂ™s not lying,вЂќ he
added at once. But he thought she was not lying from what he saw.

He was that sort of jealous man who, in the absence of the beloved woman,
at once invents all sorts of awful fancies of what may be happening to
her, and how she may be betraying him, but, when shaken, heartbroken,
convinced of her faithlessness, he runs back to her; at the first glance
at her face, her gay, laughing, affectionate face, he revives at once,
lays aside all suspicion and with joyful shame abuses himself for his
jealousy.

After leaving Grushenka at the gate he rushed home. Oh, he had so much
still to do that day! But a load had been lifted from his heart, anyway.

вЂњNow I must only make haste and find out from Smerdyakov whether anything
happened there last night, whether, by any chance, she went to Fyodor
Pavlovitch; ough!вЂќ floated through his mind.

Before he had time to reach his lodging, jealousy had surged up again in
his restless heart.

Jealousy! вЂњOthello was not jealous, he was trustful,вЂќ observed Pushkin.
And that remark alone is enough to show the deep insight of our great
poet. OthelloвЂ™s soul was shattered and his whole outlook clouded simply
because _his ideal was destroyed_. But Othello did not begin hiding,
spying, peeping. He was trustful, on the contrary. He had to be led up,
pushed on, excited with great difficulty before he could entertain the
idea of deceit. The truly jealous man is not like that. It is impossible
to picture to oneself the shame and moral degradation to which the jealous
man can descend without a qualm of conscience. And yet itвЂ™s not as though
the jealous were all vulgar and base souls. On the contrary, a man of
lofty feelings, whose love is pure and full of selfвЂђsacrifice, may yet
hide under tables, bribe the vilest people, and be familiar with the
lowest ignominy of spying and eavesdropping.

Othello was incapable of making up his mind to faithlessnessвЂ”not incapable
of forgiving it, but of making up his mind to itвЂ”though his soul was as
innocent and free from malice as a babeвЂ™s. It is not so with the really
jealous man. It is hard to imagine what some jealous men can make up their
mind to and overlook, and what they can forgive! The jealous are the
readiest of all to forgive, and all women know it. The jealous man can
forgive extraordinarily quickly (though, of course, after a violent
scene), and he is able to forgive infidelity almost conclusively proved,
the very kisses and embraces he has seen, if only he can somehow be
convinced that it has all been вЂњfor the last time,вЂќ and that his rival
will vanish from that day forward, will depart to the ends of the earth,
or that he himself will carry her away somewhere, where that dreaded rival
will not get near her. Of course the reconciliation is only for an hour.
For, even if the rival did disappear next day, he would invent another one
and would be jealous of him. And one might wonder what there was in a love
that had to be so watched over, what a love could be worth that needed
such strenuous guarding. But that the jealous will never understand. And
yet among them are men of noble hearts. It is remarkable, too, that those
very men of noble hearts, standing hidden in some cupboard, listening and
spying, never feel the stings of conscience at that moment, anyway, though
they understand clearly enough with their вЂњnoble heartsвЂќ the shameful
depths to which they have voluntarily sunk.

At the sight of Grushenka, MityaвЂ™s jealousy vanished, and, for an instant
he became trustful and generous, and positively despised himself for his
evil feelings. But it only proved that, in his love for the woman, there
was an element of something far higher than he himself imagined, that it
was not only a sensual passion, not only the вЂњcurve of her body,вЂќ of which
he had talked to Alyosha. But, as soon as Grushenka had gone, Mitya began
to suspect her of all the low cunning of faithlessness, and he felt no
sting of conscience at it.

And so jealousy surged up in him again. He had, in any case, to make
haste. The first thing to be done was to get hold of at least a small,
temporary loan of money. The nine roubles had almost all gone on his
expedition. And, as we all know, one canвЂ™t take a step without money. But
he had thought over in the cart where he could get a loan. He had a brace
of fine dueling pistols in a case, which he had not pawned till then
because he prized them above all his possessions.

In the вЂњMetropolisвЂќ tavern he had some time since made acquaintance with a
young official and had learnt that this very opulent bachelor was
passionately fond of weapons. He used to buy pistols, revolvers, daggers,
hang them on his wall and show them to acquaintances. He prided himself on
them, and was quite a specialist on the mechanism of the revolver. Mitya,
without stopping to think, went straight to him, and offered to pawn his
pistols to him for ten roubles. The official, delighted, began trying to
persuade him to sell them outright. But Mitya would not consent, so the
young man gave him ten roubles, protesting that nothing would induce him
to take interest. They parted friends.

Mitya was in haste; he rushed towards Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s by the back way,
to his arbor, to get hold of Smerdyakov as soon as possible. In this way
the fact was established that three or four hours before a certain event,
of which I shall speak later on, Mitya had not a farthing, and pawned for
ten roubles a possession he valued, though, three hours later, he was in
possession of thousands.... But I am anticipating. From Marya Kondratyevna
(the woman living near Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s) he learned the very disturbing
fact of SmerdyakovвЂ™s illness. He heard the story of his fall in the
cellar, his fit, the doctorвЂ™s visit, Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s anxiety; he heard
with interest, too, that his brother Ivan had set off that morning for
Moscow.

вЂњThen he must have driven through Volovya before me,вЂќ thought Dmitri, but
he was terribly distressed about Smerdyakov. вЂњWhat will happen now? WhoвЂ™ll
keep watch for me? WhoвЂ™ll bring me word?вЂќ he thought. He began greedily
questioning the women whether they had seen anything the evening before.
They quite understood what he was trying to find out, and completely
reassured him. No one had been there. Ivan Fyodorovitch had been there the
night; everything had been perfectly as usual. Mitya grew thoughtful. He
would certainly have to keep watch toвЂђday, but where? Here or at
SamsonovвЂ™s gate? He decided that he must be on the look out both here and
there, and meanwhile ... meanwhile.... The difficulty was that he had to
carry out the new plan that he had made on the journey back. He was sure
of its success, but he must not delay acting upon it. Mitya resolved to
sacrifice an hour to it: вЂњIn an hour I shall know everything, I shall
settle everything, and then, then, first of all to SamsonovвЂ™s. IвЂ™ll
inquire whether GrushenkaвЂ™s there and instantly be back here again, stay
till eleven, and then to SamsonovвЂ™s again to bring her home.вЂќ This was
what he decided.

He flew home, washed, combed his hair, brushed his clothes, dressed, and
went to Madame HohlakovвЂ™s. Alas! he had built his hopes on her. He had
resolved to borrow three thousand from that lady. And what was more, he
felt suddenly convinced that she would not refuse to lend it to him. It
may be wondered why, if he felt so certain, he had not gone to her at
first, one of his own sort, so to speak, instead of to Samsonov, a man he
did not know, who was not of his own class, and to whom he hardly knew how
to speak.

But the fact was that he had never known Madame Hohlakov well, and had
seen nothing of her for the last month, and that he knew she could not
endure him. She had detested him from the first because he was engaged to
Katerina Ivanovna, while she had, for some reason, suddenly conceived the
desire that Katerina Ivanovna should throw him over, and marry the
вЂњcharming, chivalrously refined Ivan, who had such excellent manners.вЂќ
MityaвЂ™s manners she detested. Mitya positively laughed at her, and had
once said about her that she was just as lively and at her ease as she was
uncultivated. But that morning in the cart a brilliant idea had struck
him: вЂњIf she is so anxious I should not marry Katerina IvanovnaвЂќ (and he
knew she was positively hysterical upon the subject) вЂњwhy should she
refuse me now that three thousand, just to enable me to leave Katya and
get away from her for ever. These spoilt fine ladies, if they set their
hearts on anything, will spare no expense to satisfy their caprice.
Besides, sheвЂ™s so rich,вЂќ Mitya argued.

As for his вЂњplanвЂќ it was just the same as before; it consisted of the
offer of his rights to TchermashnyaвЂ”but not with a commercial object, as
it had been with Samsonov, not trying to allure the lady with the
possibility of making a profit of six or seven thousandвЂ”but simply as a
security for the debt. As he worked out this new idea, Mitya was enchanted
with it, but so it always was with him in all his undertakings, in all his
sudden decisions. He gave himself up to every new idea with passionate
enthusiasm. Yet, when he mounted the steps of Madame HohlakovвЂ™s house he
felt a shiver of fear run down his spine. At that moment he saw fully, as
a mathematical certainty, that this was his last hope, that if this broke
down, nothing else was left him in the world, but to вЂњrob and murder some
one for the three thousand.вЂќ It was halfвЂђpast seven when he rang at the
bell.

At first fortune seemed to smile upon him. As soon as he was announced he
was received with extraordinary rapidity. вЂњAs though she were waiting for
me,вЂќ thought Mitya, and as soon as he had been led to the drawingвЂђroom,
the lady of the house herself ran in, and declared at once that she was
expecting him.

вЂњI was expecting you! I was expecting you! Though IвЂ™d no reason to suppose
you would come to see me, as you will admit yourself. Yet, I did expect
you. You may marvel at my instinct, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, but I was
convinced all the morning that you would come.вЂќ

вЂњThat is certainly wonderful, madam,вЂќ observed Mitya, sitting down limply,
вЂњbut I have come to you on a matter of great importance.... On a matter of
supreme importance for me, that is, madam ... for me alone ... and I
hastenвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњI know youвЂ™ve come on most important business, Dmitri Fyodorovitch; itвЂ™s
not a case of presentiment, no reactionary harking back to the miraculous
(have you heard about Father Zossima?). This is a case of mathematics: you
couldnвЂ™t help coming, after all that has passed with Katerina Ivanovna;
you couldnвЂ™t, you couldnвЂ™t, thatвЂ™s a mathematical certainty.вЂќ

вЂњThe realism of actual life, madam, thatвЂ™s what it is. But allow me to
explainвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњRealism indeed, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. IвЂ™m all for realism now. IвЂ™ve seen
too much of miracles. YouвЂ™ve heard that Father Zossima is dead?вЂќ

вЂњNo, madam, itвЂ™s the first time IвЂ™ve heard of it.вЂќ Mitya was a little
surprised. The image of Alyosha rose to his mind.

вЂњLast night, and only imagineвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњMadam,вЂќ said Mitya, вЂњI can imagine nothing except that IвЂ™m in a desperate
position, and that if you donвЂ™t help me, everything will come to grief,
and I first of all. Excuse me for the triviality of the expression, but
IвЂ™m in a feverвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњI know, I know that youвЂ™re in a fever. You could hardly fail to be, and
whatever you may say to me, I know beforehand. I have long been thinking
over your destiny, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, I am watching over it and studying
it.... Oh, believe me, IвЂ™m an experienced doctor of the soul, Dmitri
Fyodorovitch.вЂќ

вЂњMadam, if you are an experienced doctor, IвЂ™m certainly an experienced
patient,вЂќ said Mitya, with an effort to be polite, вЂњand I feel that if you
are watching over my destiny in this way, you will come to my help in my
ruin, and so allow me, at least to explain to you the plan with which I
have ventured to come to you ... and what I am hoping of you.... I have
come, madamвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t explain it. ItвЂ™s of secondary importance. But as for help, youвЂ™re
not the first I have helped, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. You have most likely
heard of my cousin, Madame Belmesov. Her husband was ruined, вЂhad come to
grief,вЂ™ as you characteristically express it, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. I
recommended him to take to horseвЂђbreeding, and now heвЂ™s doing well. Have
you any idea of horseвЂђbreeding, Dmitri Fyodorovitch?вЂќ

вЂњNot the faintest, madam; ah, madam, not the faintest!вЂќ cried Mitya, in
nervous impatience, positively starting from his seat. вЂњI simply implore
you, madam, to listen to me. Only give me two minutes of free speech that
I may just explain to you everything, the whole plan with which I have
come. Besides, I am short of time. IвЂ™m in a fearful hurry,вЂќ Mitya cried
hysterically, feeling that she was just going to begin talking again, and
hoping to cut her short. вЂњI have come in despair ... in the last gasp of
despair, to beg you to lend me the sum of three thousand, a loan, but on
safe, most safe security, madam, with the most trustworthy guarantees!
Only let me explainвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњYou must tell me all that afterwards, afterwards!вЂќ Madame Hohlakov with a
gesture demanded silence in her turn, вЂњand whatever you may tell me, I
know it all beforehand; IвЂ™ve told you so already. You ask for a certain
sum, for three thousand, but I can give you more, immeasurably more, I
will save you, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, but you must listen to me.вЂќ

Mitya started from his seat again.

вЂњMadam, will you really be so good!вЂќ he cried, with strong feeling. вЂњGood
God, youвЂ™ve saved me! You have saved a man from a violent death, from a
bullet.... My eternal gratitudeвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњI will give you more, infinitely more than three thousand!вЂќ cried Madame
Hohlakov, looking with a radiant smile at MityaвЂ™s ecstasy.

вЂњInfinitely? But I donвЂ™t need so much. I only need that fatal three
thousand, and on my part I can give security for that sum with infinite
gratitude, and I propose a plan whichвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњEnough, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, itвЂ™s said and done.вЂќ Madame Hohlakov cut him
short, with the modest triumph of beneficence: вЂњI have promised to save
you, and I will save you. I will save you as I did Belmesov. What do you
think of the goldвЂђmines, Dmitri Fyodorovitch?вЂќ

вЂњOf the goldвЂђmines, madam? I have never thought anything about them.вЂќ

вЂњBut I have thought of them for you. Thought of them over and over again.
I have been watching you for the last month. IвЂ™ve watched you a hundred
times as youвЂ™ve walked past, saying to myself: thatвЂ™s a man of energy who
ought to be at the goldвЂђmines. IвЂ™ve studied your gait and come to the
conclusion: thatвЂ™s a man who would find gold.вЂќ

вЂњFrom my gait, madam?вЂќ said Mitya, smiling.

вЂњYes, from your gait. You surely donвЂ™t deny that character can be told
from the gait, Dmitri Fyodorovitch? Science supports the idea. IвЂ™m all for
science and realism now. After all this business with Father Zossima,
which has so upset me, from this very day IвЂ™m a realist and I want to
devote myself to practical usefulness. IвЂ™m cured. вЂEnough!вЂ™ as Turgenev
says.вЂќ

вЂњBut, madam, the three thousand you so generously promised to lend meвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњIt is yours, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ Madame Hohlakov cut in at once. вЂњThe
money is as good as in your pocket, not three thousand, but three million,
Dmitri Fyodorovitch, in less than no time. IвЂ™ll make you a present of the
idea: you shall find goldвЂђmines, make millions, return and become a
leading man, and wake us up and lead us to better things. Are we to leave
it all to the Jews? You will found institutions and enterprises of all
sorts. You will help the poor, and they will bless you. This is the age of
railways, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. YouвЂ™ll become famous and indispensable to
the Department of Finance, which is so badly off at present. The
depreciation of the rouble keeps me awake at night, Dmitri Fyodorovitch;
people donвЂ™t know that side of meвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњMadam, madam!вЂќ Dmitri interrupted with an uneasy presentiment. вЂњI shall
indeed, perhaps, follow your advice, your wise advice, madam.... I shall
perhaps set off ... to the goldвЂђmines.... IвЂ™ll come and see you again
about it ... many times, indeed ... but now, that three thousand you so
generously ... oh, that would set me free, and if you could toвЂђday ... you
see, I havenвЂ™t a minute, a minute to lose toвЂђdayвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњEnough, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, enough!вЂќ Madame Hohlakov interrupted
emphatically. вЂњThe question is, will you go to the goldвЂђmines or not; have
you quite made up your mind? Answer yes or no.вЂќ

вЂњI will go, madam, afterwards.... IвЂ™ll go where you like ... but nowвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњWait!вЂќ cried Madame Hohlakov. And jumping up and running to a handsome
bureau with numerous little drawers, she began pulling out one drawer
after another, looking for something with desperate haste.

вЂњThe three thousand,вЂќ thought Mitya, his heart almost stopping, вЂњand at
the instant ... without any papers or formalities ... thatвЂ™s doing things
in gentlemanly style! SheвЂ™s a splendid woman, if only she didnвЂ™t talk so
much!вЂќ

вЂњHere!вЂќ cried Madame Hohlakov, running back joyfully to Mitya, вЂњhere is
what I was looking for!вЂќ

It was a tiny silver ikon on a cord, such as is sometimes worn next the
skin with a cross.

вЂњThis is from Kiev, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ she went on reverently, вЂњfrom
the relics of the Holy Martyr, Varvara. Let me put it on your neck myself,
and with it dedicate you to a new life, to a new career.вЂќ

And she actually put the cord round his neck, and began arranging it. In
extreme embarrassment, Mitya bent down and helped her, and at last he got
it under his neckвЂђtie and collar through his shirt to his chest.

вЂњNow you can set off,вЂќ Madame Hohlakov pronounced, sitting down
triumphantly in her place again.

вЂњMadam, I am so touched. I donвЂ™t know how to thank you, indeed ... for
such kindness, but ... If only you knew how precious time is to me....
That sum of money, for which I shall be indebted to your generosity....
Oh, madam, since you are so kind, so touchingly generous to me,вЂќ Mitya
exclaimed impulsively, вЂњthen let me reveal to you ... though, of course,
youвЂ™ve known it a long time ... that I love somebody here.... I have been
false to Katya ... Katerina Ivanovna I should say.... Oh, IвЂ™ve behaved
inhumanly, dishonorably to her, but I fell in love here with another woman
... a woman whom you, madam, perhaps, despise, for you know everything
already, but whom I cannot leave on any account, and therefore that three
thousand nowвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњLeave everything, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ Madame Hohlakov interrupted in
the most decisive tone. вЂњLeave everything, especially women. GoldвЂђmines
are your goal, and thereвЂ™s no place for women there. Afterwards, when you
come back rich and famous, you will find the girl of your heart in the
highest society. That will be a modern girl, a girl of education and
advanced ideas. By that time the dawning woman question will have gained
ground, and the new woman will have appeared.вЂќ

вЂњMadam, thatвЂ™s not the point, not at all....вЂќ Mitya clasped his hands in
entreaty.

вЂњYes, it is, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, just what you need; the very thing
youвЂ™re yearning for, though you donвЂ™t realize it yourself. I am not at all
opposed to the present woman movement, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. The
development of woman, and even the political emancipation of woman in the
near futureвЂ”thatвЂ™s my ideal. IвЂ™ve a daughter myself, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,
people donвЂ™t know that side of me. I wrote a letter to the author,
Shtchedrin, on that subject. He has taught me so much, so much about the
vocation of woman. So last year I sent him an anonymous letter of two
lines: вЂI kiss and embrace you, my teacher, for the modern woman.
Persevere.вЂ™ And I signed myself, вЂA Mother.вЂ™ I thought of signing myself
вЂA contemporary Mother,вЂ™ and hesitated, but I stuck to the simple
вЂMotherвЂ™; thereвЂ™s more moral beauty in that, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. And the
word вЂcontemporaryвЂ™ might have reminded him of вЂ_The Contemporary_вЂ™вЂ”a
painful recollection owing to the censorship.... Good Heavens, what is the
matter!вЂќ

вЂњMadam!вЂќ cried Mitya, jumping up at last, clasping his hands before her in
helpless entreaty. вЂњYou will make me weep if you delay what you have so
generouslyвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњOh, do weep, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, do weep! ThatвЂ™s a noble feeling ...
such a path lies open before you! Tears will ease your heart, and later on
you will return rejoicing. You will hasten to me from Siberia on purpose
to share your joy with meвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњBut allow me, too!вЂќ Mitya cried suddenly. вЂњFor the last time I entreat
you, tell me, can I have the sum you promised me toвЂђday, if not, when may
I come for it?вЂќ

вЂњWhat sum, Dmitri Fyodorovitch?вЂќ

вЂњThe three thousand you promised me ... that you so generouslyвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњThree thousand? Roubles? Oh, no, I havenвЂ™t got three thousand,вЂќ Madame
Hohlakov announced with serene amazement. Mitya was stupefied.

вЂњWhy, you said just now ... you said ... you said it was as good as in my
handsвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњOh, no, you misunderstood me, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. In that case you
misunderstood me. I was talking of the goldвЂђmines. ItвЂ™s true I promised
you more, infinitely more than three thousand, I remember it all now, but
I was referring to the goldвЂђmines.вЂќ

вЂњBut the money? The three thousand?вЂќ Mitya exclaimed, awkwardly.

вЂњOh, if you meant money, I havenвЂ™t any. I havenвЂ™t a penny, Dmitri
Fyodorovitch. IвЂ™m quarreling with my steward about it, and IвЂ™ve just
borrowed five hundred roubles from MiГјsov, myself. No, no, IвЂ™ve no money.
And, do you know, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, if I had, I wouldnвЂ™t give it to
you. In the first place I never lend money. Lending money means losing
friends. And I wouldnвЂ™t give it to you particularly. I wouldnвЂ™t give it
you, because I like you and want to save you, for all you need is the
goldвЂђmines, the goldвЂђmines, the goldвЂђmines!вЂќ

вЂњOh, the devil!вЂќ roared Mitya, and with all his might brought his fist
down on the table.

вЂњAie! Aie!вЂќ cried Madame Hohlakov, alarmed, and she flew to the other end
of the drawingвЂђroom.

Mitya spat on the ground, and strode rapidly out of the room, out of the
house, into the street, into the darkness! He walked like one possessed,
and beating himself on the breast, on the spot where he had struck himself
two days previously, before Alyosha, the last time he saw him in the dark,
on the road. What those blows upon his breast signified, _on that spot_,
and what he meant by itвЂ”that was, for the time, a secret which was known
to no one in the world, and had not been told even to Alyosha. But that
secret meant for him more than disgrace; it meant ruin, suicide. So he had
determined, if he did not get hold of the three thousand that would pay
his debt to Katerina Ivanovna, and so remove from his breast, from _that
spot on his breast_, the shame he carried upon it, that weighed on his
conscience. All this will be fully explained to the reader later on, but
now that his last hope had vanished, this man, so strong in appearance,
burst out crying like a little child a few steps from the HohlakovsвЂ™
house. He walked on, and not knowing what he was doing, wiped away his
tears with his fist. In this way he reached the square, and suddenly
became aware that he had stumbled against something. He heard a piercing
wail from an old woman whom he had almost knocked down.

вЂњGood Lord, youвЂ™ve nearly killed me! Why donвЂ™t you look where youвЂ™re
going, scapegrace?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, itвЂ™s you!вЂќ cried Mitya, recognizing the old woman in the dark. It
was the old servant who waited on Samsonov, whom Mitya had particularly
noticed the day before.

вЂњAnd who are you, my good sir?вЂќ said the old woman, in quite a different
voice. вЂњI donвЂ™t know you in the dark.вЂќ

вЂњYou live at Kuzma KuzmitchвЂ™s. YouвЂ™re the servant there?вЂќ

вЂњJust so, sir, I was only running out to ProhoritchвЂ™s.... But I donвЂ™t know
you now.вЂќ

вЂњTell me, my good woman, is Agrafena Alexandrovna there now?вЂќ said Mitya,
beside himself with suspense. вЂњI saw her to the house some time ago.вЂќ

вЂњShe has been there, sir. She stayed a little while, and went off again.вЂќ

вЂњWhat? Went away?вЂќ cried Mitya. вЂњWhen did she go?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, as soon as she came. She only stayed a minute. She only told Kuzma
Kuzmitch a tale that made him laugh, and then she ran away.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re lying, damn you!вЂќ roared Mitya.

вЂњAie! Aie!вЂќ shrieked the old woman, but Mitya had vanished.

He ran with all his might to the house where Grushenka lived. At the
moment he reached it, Grushenka was on her way to Mokroe. It was not more
than a quarter of an hour after her departure.

Fenya was sitting with her grandmother, the old cook, Matryona, in the
kitchen when вЂњthe captainвЂќ ran in. Fenya uttered a piercing shriek on
seeing him.

вЂњYou scream?вЂќ roared Mitya, вЂњwhere is she?вЂќ

But without giving the terrorвЂђstricken Fenya time to utter a word, he fell
all of a heap at her feet.

вЂњFenya, for ChristвЂ™s sake, tell me, where is she?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know. Dmitri Fyodorovitch, my dear, I donвЂ™t know. You may kill me
but I canвЂ™t tell you.вЂќ Fenya swore and protested. вЂњYou went out with her
yourself not long agoвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњShe came back!вЂќ

вЂњIndeed she didnвЂ™t. By God I swear she didnвЂ™t come back.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re lying!вЂќ shouted Mitya. вЂњFrom your terror I know where she is.вЂќ

He rushed away. Fenya in her fright was glad she had got off so easily.
But she knew very well that it was only that he was in such haste, or she
might not have fared so well. But as he ran, he surprised both Fenya and
old Matryona by an unexpected action. On the table stood a brass mortar,
with a pestle in it, a small brass pestle, not much more than six inches
long. Mitya already had opened the door with one hand when, with the
other, he snatched up the pestle, and thrust it in his sideвЂђpocket.

вЂњOh, Lord! HeвЂ™s going to murder some one!вЂќ cried Fenya, flinging up her
hands.



Chapter IV. In The Dark


Where was he running? вЂњWhere could she be except at Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s?
She must have run straight to him from SamsonovвЂ™s, that was clear now. The
whole intrigue, the whole deceit was evident.вЂќ ... It all rushed whirling
through his mind. He did not run to Marya KondratyevnaвЂ™s. вЂњThere was no
need to go there ... not the slightest need ... he must raise no alarm ...
they would run and tell directly.... Marya Kondratyevna was clearly in the
plot, Smerdyakov too, he too, all had been bought over!вЂќ

He formed another plan of action: he ran a long way round Fyodor
PavlovitchвЂ™s house, crossing the lane, running down Dmitrovsky Street,
then over the little bridge, and so came straight to the deserted alley at
the back, which was empty and uninhabited, with, on one side the hurdle
fence of a neighborвЂ™s kitchenвЂђgarden, on the other the strong high fence,
that ran all round Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s garden. Here he chose a spot,
apparently the very place, where according to the tradition, he knew
Lizaveta had once climbed over it: вЂњIf she could climb over it,вЂќ the
thought, God knows why, occurred to him, вЂњsurely I can.вЂќ He did in fact
jump up, and instantly contrived to catch hold of the top of the fence.
Then he vigorously pulled himself up and sat astride on it. Close by, in
the garden stood the bathвЂђhouse, but from the fence he could see the
lighted windows of the house too.

вЂњYes, the old manвЂ™s bedroom is lighted up. SheвЂ™s there!вЂќ and he leapt from
the fence into the garden. Though he knew Grigory was ill and very likely
Smerdyakov, too, and that there was no one to hear him, he instinctively
hid himself, stood still, and began to listen. But there was dead silence
on all sides and, as though of design, complete stillness, not the
slightest breath of wind.

вЂњAnd naught but the whispering silence,вЂќ the line for some reason rose to
his mind. вЂњIf only no one heard me jump over the fence! I think not.вЂќ
Standing still for a minute, he walked softly over the grass in the
garden, avoiding the trees and shrubs. He walked slowly, creeping
stealthily at every step, listening to his own footsteps. It took him five
minutes to reach the lighted window. He remembered that just under the
window there were several thick and high bushes of elder and whitebeam.
The door from the house into the garden on the leftвЂђhand side, was shut;
he had carefully looked on purpose to see, in passing. At last he reached
the bushes and hid behind them. He held his breath. вЂњI must wait now,вЂќ he
thought, вЂњto reassure them, in case they heard my footsteps and are
listening ... if only I donвЂ™t cough or sneeze.вЂќ

He waited two minutes. His heart was beating violently, and, at moments,
he could scarcely breathe. вЂњNo, this throbbing at my heart wonвЂ™t stop,вЂќ he
thought. вЂњI canвЂ™t wait any longer.вЂќ He was standing behind a bush in the
shadow. The light of the window fell on the front part of the bush.

вЂњHow red the whitebeam berries are!вЂќ he murmured, not knowing why. Softly
and noiselessly, step by step, he approached the window, and raised
himself on tiptoe. All Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s bedroom lay open before him. It
was not a large room, and was divided in two parts by a red screen,
вЂњChinese,вЂќ as Fyodor Pavlovitch used to call it. The word вЂњChineseвЂќ
flashed into MityaвЂ™s mind, вЂњand behind the screen, is Grushenka,вЂќ thought
Mitya. He began watching Fyodor Pavlovitch, who was wearing his new
stripedвЂђsilk dressingвЂђgown, which Mitya had never seen, and a silk cord
with tassels round the waist. A clean, dandified shirt of fine linen with
gold studs peeped out under the collar of the dressingвЂђgown. On his head
Fyodor Pavlovitch had the same red bandage which Alyosha had seen.

вЂњHe has got himself up,вЂќ thought Mitya.

His father was standing near the window, apparently lost in thought.
Suddenly he jerked up his head, listened a moment, and hearing nothing
went up to the table, poured out half a glass of brandy from a decanter
and drank it off. Then he uttered a deep sigh, again stood still a moment,
walked carelessly up to the lookingвЂђglass on the wall, with his right hand
raised the red bandage on his forehead a little, and began examining his
bruises and scars, which had not yet disappeared.

вЂњHeвЂ™s alone,вЂќ thought Mitya, вЂњin all probability heвЂ™s alone.вЂќ

Fyodor Pavlovitch moved away from the lookingвЂђglass, turned suddenly to
the window and looked out. Mitya instantly slipped away into the shadow.

вЂњShe may be there behind the screen. Perhaps sheвЂ™s asleep by now,вЂќ he
thought, with a pang at his heart. Fyodor Pavlovitch moved away from the
window. вЂњHeвЂ™s looking for her out of the window, so sheвЂ™s not there. Why
should he stare out into the dark? HeвЂ™s wild with impatience.вЂќ ... Mitya
slipped back at once, and fell to gazing in at the window again. The old
man was sitting down at the table, apparently disappointed. At last he put
his elbow on the table, and laid his right cheek against his hand. Mitya
watched him eagerly.

вЂњHeвЂ™s alone, heвЂ™s alone!вЂќ he repeated again. вЂњIf she were here, his face
would be different.вЂќ

Strange to say, a queer, irrational vexation rose up in his heart that she
was not here. вЂњItвЂ™s not that sheвЂ™s not here,вЂќ he explained to himself,
immediately, вЂњbut that I canвЂ™t tell for certain whether she is or not.вЂќ
Mitya remembered afterwards that his mind was at that moment exceptionally
clear, that he took in everything to the slightest detail, and missed no
point. But a feeling of misery, the misery of uncertainty and indecision,
was growing in his heart with every instant. вЂњIs she here or not?вЂќ The
angry doubt filled his heart, and suddenly, making up his mind, he put out
his hand and softly knocked on the window frame. He knocked the signal the
old man had agreed upon with Smerdyakov, twice slowly and then three times
more quickly, the signal that meant вЂњGrushenka is here!вЂќ

The old man started, jerked up his head, and, jumping up quickly, ran to
the window. Mitya slipped away into the shadow. Fyodor Pavlovitch opened
the window and thrust his whole head out.

вЂњGrushenka, is it you? Is it you?вЂќ he said, in a sort of trembling halfвЂђ
whisper. вЂњWhere are you, my angel, where are you?вЂќ He was fearfully
agitated and breathless.

вЂњHeвЂ™s alone.вЂќ Mitya decided.

вЂњWhere are you?вЂќ cried the old man again; and he thrust his head out
farther, thrust it out to the shoulders, gazing in all directions, right
and left. вЂњCome here, IвЂ™ve a little present for you. Come, IвЂ™ll show
you....вЂќ

вЂњHe means the three thousand,вЂќ thought Mitya.

вЂњBut where are you? Are you at the door? IвЂ™ll open it directly.вЂќ

And the old man almost climbed out of the window, peering out to the
right, where there was a door into the garden, trying to see into the
darkness. In another second he would certainly have run out to open the
door without waiting for GrushenkaвЂ™s answer.

Mitya looked at him from the side without stirring. The old manвЂ™s profile
that he loathed so, his pendent AdamвЂ™s apple, his hooked nose, his lips
that smiled in greedy expectation, were all brightly lighted up by the
slanting lamplight falling on the left from the room. A horrible fury of
hatred suddenly surged up in MityaвЂ™s heart: вЂњThere he was, his rival, the
man who had tormented him, had ruined his life!вЂќ It was a rush of that
sudden, furious, revengeful anger of which he had spoken, as though
foreseeing it, to Alyosha, four days ago in the arbor, when, in answer to
AlyoshaвЂ™s question, вЂњHow can you say youвЂ™ll kill our father?вЂќ вЂњI donвЂ™t
know, I donвЂ™t know,вЂќ he had said then. вЂњPerhaps I shall not kill him,
perhaps I shall. IвЂ™m afraid heвЂ™ll suddenly be so loathsome to me at that
moment. I hate his double chin, his nose, his eyes, his shameless grin. I
feel a personal repulsion. ThatвЂ™s what IвЂ™m afraid of, thatвЂ™s what may be
too much for me.вЂќ ... This personal repulsion was growing unendurable.
Mitya was beside himself, he suddenly pulled the brass pestle out of his
pocket.

                  вЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђвЂђ

вЂњGod was watching over me then,вЂќ Mitya himself said afterwards. At that
very moment Grigory waked up on his bed of sickness. Earlier in the
evening he had undergone the treatment which Smerdyakov had described to
Ivan. He had rubbed himself all over with vodka mixed with a secret, very
strong decoction, had drunk what was left of the mixture while his wife
repeated a вЂњcertain prayerвЂќ over him, after which he had gone to bed.
Marfa Ignatyevna had tasted the stuff, too, and, being unused to strong
drink, slept like the dead beside her husband.

But Grigory waked up in the night, quite suddenly, and, after a momentвЂ™s
reflection, though he immediately felt a sharp pain in his back, he sat up
in bed. Then he deliberated again, got up and dressed hurriedly. Perhaps
his conscience was uneasy at the thought of sleeping while the house was
unguarded вЂњin such perilous times.вЂќ Smerdyakov, exhausted by his fit, lay
motionless in the next room. Marfa Ignatyevna did not stir. вЂњThe stuffвЂ™s
been too much for the woman,вЂќ Grigory thought, glancing at her, and
groaning, he went out on the steps. No doubt he only intended to look out
from the steps, for he was hardly able to walk, the pain in his back and
his right leg was intolerable. But he suddenly remembered that he had not
locked the little gate into the garden that evening. He was the most
punctual and precise of men, a man who adhered to an unchangeable routine,
and habits that lasted for years. Limping and writhing with pain he went
down the steps and towards the garden. Yes, the gate stood wide open.
Mechanically he stepped into the garden. Perhaps he fancied something,
perhaps caught some sound, and, glancing to the left he saw his masterвЂ™s
window open. No one was looking out of it then.

вЂњWhatвЂ™s it open for? ItвЂ™s not summer now,вЂќ thought Grigory, and suddenly,
at that very instant he caught a glimpse of something extraordinary before
him in the garden. Forty paces in front of him a man seemed to be running
in the dark, a sort of shadow was moving very fast.

вЂњGood Lord!вЂќ cried Grigory beside himself, and forgetting the pain in his
back, he hurried to intercept the running figure. He took a short cut,
evidently he knew the garden better; the flying figure went towards the
bathвЂђhouse, ran behind it and rushed to the garden fence. Grigory
followed, not losing sight of him, and ran, forgetting everything. He
reached the fence at the very moment the man was climbing over it. Grigory
cried out, beside himself, pounced on him, and clutched his leg in his two
hands.

Yes, his foreboding had not deceived him. He recognized him, it was he,
the вЂњmonster,вЂќ the вЂњparricide.вЂќ

вЂњParricide!вЂќ the old man shouted so that the whole neighborhood could
hear, but he had not time to shout more, he fell at once, as though struck
by lightning.

Mitya jumped back into the garden and bent over the fallen man. In MityaвЂ™s
hands was a brass pestle, and he flung it mechanically in the grass. The
pestle fell two paces from Grigory, not in the grass but on the path, in a
most conspicuous place. For some seconds he examined the prostrate figure
before him. The old manвЂ™s head was covered with blood. Mitya put out his
hand and began feeling it. He remembered afterwards clearly, that he had
been awfully anxious to make sure whether he had broken the old manвЂ™s
skull, or simply stunned him with the pestle. But the blood was flowing
horribly; and in a moment MityaвЂ™s fingers were drenched with the hot
stream. He remembered taking out of his pocket the clean white
handkerchief with which he had provided himself for his visit to Madame
Hohlakov, and putting it to the old manвЂ™s head, senselessly trying to wipe
the blood from his face and temples. But the handkerchief was instantly
soaked with blood.

вЂњGood heavens! what am I doing it for?вЂќ thought Mitya, suddenly pulling
himself together. вЂњIf I have broken his skull, how can I find out now? And
what difference does it make now?вЂќ he added, hopelessly. вЂњIf IвЂ™ve killed
him, IвЂ™ve killed him.... YouвЂ™ve come to grief, old man, so there you must
lie!вЂќ he said aloud. And suddenly turning to the fence, he vaulted over it
into the lane and fell to runningвЂ”the handkerchief soaked with blood he
held, crushed up in his right fist, and as he ran he thrust it into the
back pocket of his coat. He ran headlong, and the few passersвЂђby who met
him in the dark, in the streets, remembered afterwards that they had met a
man running that night. He flew back again to the widow MorozovвЂ™s house.

Immediately after he had left it that evening, Fenya had rushed to the
chief porter, Nazar Ivanovitch, and besought him, for ChristвЂ™s sake, вЂњnot
to let the captain in again toвЂђday or toвЂђmorrow.вЂќ Nazar Ivanovitch
promised, but went upstairs to his mistress who had suddenly sent for him,
and meeting his nephew, a boy of twenty, who had recently come from the
country, on the way up told him to take his place, but forgot to mention
вЂњthe captain.вЂќ Mitya, running up to the gate, knocked. The lad instantly
recognized him, for Mitya had more than once tipped him. Opening the gate
at once, he let him in, and hastened to inform him with a goodвЂђhumored
smile that вЂњAgrafena Alexandrovna is not at home now, you know.вЂќ

вЂњWhere is she then, Prohor?вЂќ asked Mitya, stopping short.

вЂњShe set off this evening, some two hours ago, with Timofey, to Mokroe.вЂќ

вЂњWhat for?вЂќ cried Mitya.

вЂњThat I canвЂ™t say. To see some officer. Some one invited her and horses
were sent to fetch her.вЂќ

Mitya left him, and ran like a madman to Fenya.



Chapter V. A Sudden Resolution


She was sitting in the kitchen with her grandmother; they were both just
going to bed. Relying on Nazar Ivanovitch, they had not locked themselves
in. Mitya ran in, pounced on Fenya and seized her by the throat.

вЂњSpeak at once! Where is she? With whom is she now, at Mokroe?вЂќ he roared
furiously.

Both the women squealed.

вЂњAie! IвЂ™ll tell you. Aie! Dmitri Fyodorovitch, darling, IвЂ™ll tell you
everything directly, I wonвЂ™t hide anything,вЂќ gabbled Fenya, frightened to
death; вЂњsheвЂ™s gone to Mokroe, to her officer.вЂќ

вЂњWhat officer?вЂќ roared Mitya.

вЂњTo her officer, the same one she used to know, the one who threw her over
five years ago,вЂќ cackled Fenya, as fast as she could speak.

Mitya withdrew the hands with which he was squeezing her throat. He stood
facing her, pale as death, unable to utter a word, but his eyes showed
that he realized it all, all, from the first word, and guessed the whole
position. Poor Fenya was not in a condition at that moment to observe
whether he understood or not. She remained sitting on the trunk as she had
been when he ran into the room, trembling all over, holding her hands out
before her as though trying to defend herself. She seemed to have grown
rigid in that position. Her wideвЂђopened, scared eyes were fixed immovably
upon him. And to make matters worse, both his hands were smeared with
blood. On the way, as he ran, he must have touched his forehead with them,
wiping off the perspiration, so that on his forehead and his right cheek
were bloodвЂђstained patches. Fenya was on the verge of hysterics. The old
cook had jumped up and was staring at him like a mad woman, almost
unconscious with terror.

Mitya stood for a moment, then mechanically sank on to a chair next to
Fenya. He sat, not reflecting but, as it were, terrorвЂђstricken, benumbed.
Yet everything was clear as day: that officer, he knew about him, he knew
everything perfectly, he had known it from Grushenka herself, had known
that a letter had come from him a month before. So that for a month, for a
whole month, this had been going on, a secret from him, till the very
arrival of this new man, and he had never thought of him! But how could
he, how could he not have thought of him? Why was it he had forgotten this
officer, like that, forgotten him as soon as he heard of him? That was the
question that faced him like some monstrous thing. And he looked at this
monstrous thing with horror, growing cold with horror.

But suddenly, as gently and mildly as a gentle and affectionate child, he
began speaking to Fenya as though he had utterly forgotten how he had
scared and hurt her just now. He fell to questioning Fenya with an extreme
preciseness, astonishing in his position, and though the girl looked
wildly at his bloodвЂђstained hands, she, too, with wonderful readiness and
rapidity, answered every question as though eager to put the whole truth
and nothing but the truth before him. Little by little, even with a sort
of enjoyment, she began explaining every detail, not wanting to torment
him, but, as it were, eager to be of the utmost service to him. She
described the whole of that day, in great detail, the visit of Rakitin and
Alyosha, how she, Fenya, had stood on the watch, how the mistress had set
off, and how she had called out of the window to Alyosha to give him,
Mitya, her greetings, and to tell him вЂњto remember for ever how she had
loved him for an hour.вЂќ

Hearing of the message, Mitya suddenly smiled, and there was a flush of
color on his pale cheeks. At the same moment Fenya said to him, not a bit
afraid now to be inquisitive:

вЂњLook at your hands, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. TheyвЂ™re all over blood!вЂќ

вЂњYes,вЂќ answered Mitya mechanically. He looked carelessly at his hands and
at once forgot them and FenyaвЂ™s question.

He sank into silence again. Twenty minutes had passed since he had run in.
His first horror was over, but evidently some new fixed determination had
taken possession of him. He suddenly stood up, smiling dreamily.

вЂњWhat has happened to you, sir?вЂќ said Fenya, pointing to his hands again.
She spoke compassionately, as though she felt very near to him now in his
grief. Mitya looked at his hands again.

вЂњThatвЂ™s blood, Fenya,вЂќ he said, looking at her with a strange expression.
вЂњThatвЂ™s human blood, and my God! why was it shed? But ... Fenya ...
thereвЂ™s a fence hereвЂќ (he looked at her as though setting her a riddle),
вЂњa high fence, and terrible to look at. But at dawn toвЂђmorrow, when the
sun rises, Mitya will leap over that fence.... You donвЂ™t understand what
fence, Fenya, and, never mind.... YouвЂ™ll hear toвЂђmorrow and understand ...
and now, goodвЂђby. I wonвЂ™t stand in her way. IвЂ™ll step aside, I know how to
step aside. Live, my joy.... You loved me for an hour, remember Mityenka
Karamazov so for ever.... She always used to call me Mityenka, do you
remember?вЂќ

And with those words he went suddenly out of the kitchen. Fenya was almost
more frightened at this sudden departure than she had been when he ran in
and attacked her.

Just ten minutes later Dmitri went in to Pyotr Ilyitch Perhotin, the young
official with whom he had pawned his pistols. It was by now halfвЂђpast
eight, and Pyotr Ilyitch had finished his evening tea, and had just put
his coat on again to go to the вЂњMetropolisвЂќ to play billiards. Mitya
caught him coming out.

Seeing him with his face all smeared with blood, the young man uttered a
cry of surprise.

вЂњGood heavens! What is the matter?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ve come for my pistols,вЂќ said Mitya, вЂњand brought you the money. And
thanks very much. IвЂ™m in a hurry, Pyotr Ilyitch, please make haste.вЂќ

Pyotr Ilyitch grew more and more surprised; he suddenly caught sight of a
bundle of bankвЂђnotes in MityaвЂ™s hand, and what was more, he had walked in
holding the notes as no one walks in and no one carries money: he had them
in his right hand, and held them outstretched as if to show them.
PerhotinвЂ™s servantвЂђboy, who met Mitya in the passage, said afterwards that
he walked into the passage in the same way, with the money outstretched in
his hand, so he must have been carrying them like that even in the
streets. They were all rainbowвЂђcolored hundredвЂђrouble notes, and the
fingers holding them were covered with blood.

When Pyotr Ilyitch was questioned later on as to the sum of money, he said
that it was difficult to judge at a glance, but that it might have been
two thousand, or perhaps three, but it was a big, вЂњfatвЂќ bundle. вЂњDmitri
Fyodorovitch,вЂќ so he testified afterwards, вЂњseemed unlike himself, too;
not drunk, but, as it were, exalted, lost to everything, but at the same
time, as it were, absorbed, as though pondering and searching for
something and unable to come to a decision. He was in great haste,
answered abruptly and very strangely, and at moments seemed not at all
dejected but quite cheerful.вЂќ

вЂњBut what _is_ the matter with you? WhatвЂ™s wrong?вЂќ cried Pyotr Ilyitch,
looking wildly at his guest. вЂњHow is it that youвЂ™re all covered with
blood? Have you had a fall? Look at yourself!вЂќ

He took him by the elbow and led him to the glass.

Seeing his bloodвЂђstained face, Mitya started and scowled wrathfully.

вЂњDamnation! ThatвЂ™s the last straw,вЂќ he muttered angrily, hurriedly
changing the notes from his right hand to the left, and impulsively jerked
the handkerchief out of his pocket. But the handkerchief turned out to be
soaked with blood, too (it was the handkerchief he had used to wipe
GrigoryвЂ™s face). There was scarcely a white spot on it, and it had not
merely begun to dry, but had stiffened into a crumpled ball and could not
be pulled apart. Mitya threw it angrily on the floor.

вЂњOh, damn it!вЂќ he said. вЂњHavenвЂ™t you a rag of some sort ... to wipe my
face?вЂќ

вЂњSo youвЂ™re only stained, not wounded? YouвЂ™d better wash,вЂќ said Pyotr
Ilyitch. вЂњHereвЂ™s a washвЂђstand. IвЂ™ll pour you out some water.вЂќ

вЂњA washвЂђstand? ThatвЂ™s all right ... but where am I to put this?вЂќ

With the strangest perplexity he indicated his bundle of hundredвЂђrouble
notes, looking inquiringly at Pyotr Ilyitch as though it were for him to
decide what he, Mitya, was to do with his own money.

вЂњIn your pocket, or on the table here. They wonвЂ™t be lost.вЂќ

вЂњIn my pocket? Yes, in my pocket. All right.... But, I say, thatвЂ™s all
nonsense,вЂќ he cried, as though suddenly coming out of his absorption.
вЂњLook here, letвЂ™s first settle that business of the pistols. Give them
back to me. HereвЂ™s your money ... because I am in great need of them ...
and I havenвЂ™t a minute, a minute to spare.вЂќ

And taking the topmost note from the bundle he held it out to Pyotr
Ilyitch.

вЂњBut I shanвЂ™t have change enough. HavenвЂ™t you less?вЂќ

вЂњNo,вЂќ said Mitya, looking again at the bundle, and as though not trusting
his own words he turned over two or three of the topmost ones.

вЂњNo, theyвЂ™re all alike,вЂќ he added, and again he looked inquiringly at
Pyotr Ilyitch.

вЂњHow have you grown so rich?вЂќ the latter asked. вЂњWait, IвЂ™ll send my boy to
PlotnikovвЂ™s, they close lateвЂ”to see if they wonвЂ™t change it. Here, Misha!вЂќ
he called into the passage.

вЂњTo PlotnikovвЂ™s shopвЂ”firstвЂђrate!вЂќ cried Mitya, as though struck by an
idea. вЂњMisha,вЂќ he turned to the boy as he came in, вЂњlook here, run to
PlotnikovвЂ™s and tell them that Dmitri Fyodorovitch sends his greetings,
and will be there directly.... But listen, listen, tell them to have
champagne, three dozen bottles, ready before I come, and packed as it was
to take to Mokroe. I took four dozen with me then,вЂќ he added (suddenly
addressing Pyotr Ilyitch); вЂњthey know all about it, donвЂ™t you trouble,
Misha,вЂќ he turned again to the boy. вЂњStay, listen; tell them to put in
cheese, Strasburg pies, smoked fish, ham, caviare, and everything,
everything theyвЂ™ve got, up to a hundred roubles, or a hundred and twenty
as before.... But wait: donвЂ™t let them forget dessert, sweets, pears,
waterвЂђmelons, two or three or fourвЂ”no, one melonвЂ™s enough, and chocolate,
candy, toffee, fondants; in fact, everything I took to Mokroe before,
three hundred roublesвЂ™ worth with the champagne ... let it be just the
same again. And remember, Misha, if you are called MishaвЂ”His name is
Misha, isnвЂ™t it?вЂќ He turned to Pyotr Ilyitch again.

вЂњWait a minute,вЂќ Protr Ilyitch intervened, listening and watching him
uneasily, вЂњyouвЂ™d better go yourself and tell them. HeвЂ™ll muddle it.вЂќ

вЂњHe will, I see he will! Eh, Misha! Why, I was going to kiss you for the
commission.... If you donвЂ™t make a mistake, thereвЂ™s ten roubles for you,
run along, make haste.... ChampagneвЂ™s the chief thing, let them bring up
champagne. And brandy, too, and red and white wine, and all I had then....
They know what I had then.вЂќ

вЂњBut listen!вЂќ Pyotr Ilyitch interrupted with some impatience. вЂњI say, let
him simply run and change the money and tell them not to close, and you go
and tell them.... Give him your note. Be off, Misha! Put your best leg
forward!вЂќ

Pyotr Ilyitch seemed to hurry Misha off on purpose, because the boy
remained standing with his mouth and eyes wide open, apparently
understanding little of MityaвЂ™s orders, gazing up with amazement and
terror at his bloodвЂђstained face and the trembling bloodstained fingers
that held the notes.

вЂњWell, now come and wash,вЂќ said Pyotr Ilyitch sternly. вЂњPut the money on
the table or else in your pocket.... ThatвЂ™s right, come along. But take
off your coat.вЂќ

And beginning to help him off with his coat, he cried out again:

вЂњLook, your coatвЂ™s covered with blood, too!вЂќ

вЂњThat ... itвЂ™s not the coat. ItвЂ™s only a little here on the sleeve.... And
thatвЂ™s only here where the handkerchief lay. It must have soaked through.
I must have sat on the handkerchief at FenyaвЂ™s, and the bloodвЂ™s come
through,вЂќ Mitya explained at once with a childlike unconsciousness that
was astounding. Pyotr Ilyitch listened, frowning.

вЂњWell, you must have been up to something; you must have been fighting
with some one,вЂќ he muttered.

They began to wash. Pyotr Ilyitch held the jug and poured out the water.
Mitya, in desperate haste, scarcely soaped his hands (they were trembling,
and Pyotr Ilyitch remembered it afterwards). But the young official
insisted on his soaping them thoroughly and rubbing them more. He seemed
to exercise more and more sway over Mitya, as time went on. It may be
noted in passing that he was a young man of sturdy character.

вЂњLook, you havenвЂ™t got your nails clean. Now rub your face; here, on your
temples, by your ear.... Will you go in that shirt? Where are you going?
Look, all the cuff of your right sleeve is covered with blood.вЂќ

вЂњYes, itвЂ™s all bloody,вЂќ observed Mitya, looking at the cuff of his shirt.

вЂњThen change your shirt.вЂќ

вЂњI havenвЂ™t time. You see IвЂ™ll ...вЂќ Mitya went on with the same confiding
ingenuousness, drying his face and hands on the towel, and putting on his
coat. вЂњIвЂ™ll turn it up at the wrist. It wonвЂ™t be seen under the coat....
You see!вЂќ

вЂњTell me now, what game have you been up to? Have you been fighting with
some one? In the tavern again, as before? Have you been beating that
captain again?вЂќ Pyotr Ilyitch asked him reproachfully. вЂњWhom have you been
beating now ... or killing, perhaps?вЂќ

вЂњNonsense!вЂќ said Mitya.

вЂњWhy вЂnonsenseвЂ™?вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t worry,вЂќ said Mitya, and he suddenly laughed. вЂњI smashed an old
woman in the marketвЂђplace just now.вЂќ

вЂњSmashed? An old woman?вЂќ

вЂњAn old man!вЂќ cried Mitya, looking Pyotr Ilyitch straight in the face,
laughing, and shouting at him as though he were deaf.

вЂњConfound it! An old woman, an old man.... Have you killed some one?вЂќ

вЂњWe made it up. We had a rowвЂ”and made it up. In a place I know of. We
parted friends. A fool.... HeвЂ™s forgiven me.... HeвЂ™s sure to have forgiven
me by now ... if he had got up, he wouldnвЂ™t have forgiven meвЂќвЂ”Mitya
suddenly winkedвЂ”вЂњonly damn him, you know, I say, Pyotr Ilyitch, damn him!
DonвЂ™t worry about him! I donвЂ™t want to just now!вЂќ Mitya snapped out,
resolutely.

вЂњWhatever do you want to go picking quarrels with every one for? ... Just
as you did with that captain over some nonsense.... YouвЂ™ve been fighting
and now youвЂ™re rushing off on the spreeвЂ”thatвЂ™s you all over! Three dozen
champagneвЂ”what do you want all that for?вЂќ

вЂњBravo! Now give me the pistols. Upon my honor IвЂ™ve no time now. I should
like to have a chat with you, my dear boy, but I havenвЂ™t the time. And
thereвЂ™s no need, itвЂ™s too late for talking. WhereвЂ™s my money? Where have I
put it?вЂќ he cried, thrusting his hands into his pockets.

вЂњYou put it on the table ... yourself.... Here it is. Had you forgotten?
MoneyвЂ™s like dirt or water to you, it seems. Here are your pistols. ItвЂ™s
an odd thing, at six oвЂ™clock you pledged them for ten roubles, and now
youвЂ™ve got thousands. Two or three I should say.вЂќ

вЂњThree, you bet,вЂќ laughed Mitya, stuffing the notes into the sideвЂђpocket
of his trousers.

вЂњYouвЂ™ll lose it like that. Have you found a goldвЂђmine?вЂќ

вЂњThe mines? The goldвЂђmines?вЂќ Mitya shouted at the top of his voice and
went off into a roar of laughter. вЂњWould you like to go to the mines,
Perhotin? ThereвЂ™s a lady here whoвЂ™ll stump up three thousand for you, if
only youвЂ™ll go. She did it for me, sheвЂ™s so awfully fond of goldвЂђmines. Do
you know Madame Hohlakov?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know her, but IвЂ™ve heard of her and seen her. Did she really give
you three thousand? Did she really?вЂќ said Pyotr Ilyitch, eyeing him
dubiously.

вЂњAs soon as the sun rises toвЂђmorrow, as soon as PhЕ“bus, ever young, flies
upwards, praising and glorifying God, you go to her, this Madame Hohlakov,
and ask her whether she did stump up that three thousand or not. Try and
find out.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know on what terms you are ... since you say it so positively, I
suppose she did give it to you. YouвЂ™ve got the money in your hand, but
instead of going to Siberia youвЂ™re spending it all.... Where are you
really off to now, eh?вЂќ

вЂњTo Mokroe.вЂќ

вЂњTo Mokroe? But itвЂ™s night!вЂќ

вЂњOnce the lad had all, now the lad has naught,вЂќ cried Mitya suddenly.

вЂњHow вЂnaughtвЂ™? You say that with all those thousands!вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™m not talking about thousands. Damn thousands! IвЂ™m talking of the
female character.


    Fickle is the heart of woman
    Treacherous and full of vice;


I agree with Ulysses. ThatвЂ™s what he says.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t understand you!вЂќ

вЂњAm I drunk?вЂќ

вЂњNot drunk, but worse.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™m drunk in spirit, Pyotr Ilyitch, drunk in spirit! But thatвЂ™s enough!вЂќ

вЂњWhat are you doing, loading the pistol?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™m loading the pistol.вЂќ

Unfastening the pistolвЂђcase, Mitya actually opened the powder horn, and
carefully sprinkled and rammed in the charge. Then he took the bullet and,
before inserting it, held it in two fingers in front of the candle.

вЂњWhy are you looking at the bullet?вЂќ asked Pyotr Ilyitch, watching him
with uneasy curiosity.

вЂњOh, a fancy. Why, if you meant to put that bullet in your brain, would
you look at it or not?вЂќ

вЂњWhy look at it?вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s going into my brain, so itвЂ™s interesting to look and see what itвЂ™s
like. But thatвЂ™s foolishness, a momentвЂ™s foolishness. Now thatвЂ™s done,вЂќ he
added, putting in the bullet and driving it home with the ramrod. вЂњPyotr
Ilyitch, my dear fellow, thatвЂ™s nonsense, all nonsense, and if only you
knew what nonsense! Give me a little piece of paper now.вЂќ

вЂњHereвЂ™s some paper.вЂќ

вЂњNo, a clean new piece, writingвЂђpaper. ThatвЂ™s right.вЂќ

And taking a pen from the table, Mitya rapidly wrote two lines, folded the
paper in four, and thrust it in his waistcoat pocket. He put the pistols
in the case, locked it up, and kept it in his hand. Then he looked at
Pyotr Ilyitch with a slow, thoughtful smile.

вЂњNow, letвЂ™s go.вЂќ

вЂњWhere are we going? No, wait a minute.... Are you thinking of putting
that bullet in your brain, perhaps?вЂќ Pyotr Ilyitch asked uneasily.

вЂњI was fooling about the bullet! I want to live. I love life! You may be
sure of that. I love goldenвЂђhaired PhЕ“bus and his warm light.... Dear
Pyotr Ilyitch, do you know how to step aside?вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you mean by вЂstepping asideвЂ™?вЂќ

вЂњMaking way. Making way for a dear creature, and for one I hate. And to
let the one I hate become dearвЂ”thatвЂ™s what making way means! And to say to
them: God bless you, go your way, pass on, while IвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњWhile youвЂ”?вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s enough, letвЂ™s go.вЂќ

вЂњUpon my word. IвЂ™ll tell some one to prevent your going there,вЂќ said Pyotr
Ilyitch, looking at him. вЂњWhat are you going to Mokroe for, now?вЂќ

вЂњThereвЂ™s a woman there, a woman. ThatвЂ™s enough for you. You shut up.вЂќ

вЂњListen, though youвЂ™re such a savage IвЂ™ve always liked you.... I feel
anxious.вЂќ

вЂњThanks, old fellow. IвЂ™m a savage you say. Savages, savages! ThatвЂ™s what I
am always saying. Savages! Why, hereвЂ™s Misha! I was forgetting him.вЂќ

Misha ran in, postвЂђhaste, with a handful of notes in change, and reported
that every one was in a bustle at the PlotnikovsвЂ™; вЂњTheyвЂ™re carrying down
the bottles, and the fish, and the tea; it will all be ready directly.вЂќ
Mitya seized ten roubles and handed it to Pyotr Ilyitch, then tossed
another tenвЂђrouble note to Misha.

вЂњDonвЂ™t dare to do such a thing!вЂќ cried Pyotr Ilyitch. вЂњI wonвЂ™t have it in
my house, itвЂ™s a bad, demoralizing habit. Put your money away. Here, put
it here, why waste it? It would come in handy toвЂђmorrow, and I dare say
youвЂ™ll be coming to me to borrow ten roubles again. Why do you keep
putting the notes in your sideвЂђpocket? Ah, youвЂ™ll lose them!вЂќ

вЂњI say, my dear fellow, letвЂ™s go to Mokroe together.вЂќ

вЂњWhat should I go for?вЂќ

вЂњI say, letвЂ™s open a bottle at once, and drink to life! I want to drink,
and especially to drink with you. IвЂ™ve never drunk with you, have I?вЂќ

вЂњVery well, we can go to the вЂMetropolis.вЂ™ I was just going there.вЂќ

вЂњI havenвЂ™t time for that. LetвЂ™s drink at the PlotnikovsвЂ™, in the back
room. Shall I ask you a riddle?вЂќ

вЂњAsk away.вЂќ

Mitya took the piece of paper out of his waistcoat pocket, unfolded it and
showed it. In a large, distinct hand was written: вЂњI punish myself for my
whole life, my whole life I punish!вЂќ

вЂњI will certainly speak to some one, IвЂ™ll go at once,вЂќ said Pyotr Ilyitch,
after reading the paper.

вЂњYou wonвЂ™t have time, dear boy, come and have a drink. March!вЂќ

PlotnikovвЂ™s shop was at the corner of the street, next door but one to
Pyotr IlyitchвЂ™s. It was the largest grocery shop in our town, and by no
means a bad one, belonging to some rich merchants. They kept everything
that could be got in a Petersburg shop, grocery of all sort, wines
вЂњbottled by the brothers Eliseyev,вЂќ fruits, cigars, tea, coffee, sugar,
and so on. There were three shopвЂђassistants and two errand boys always
employed. Though our part of the country had grown poorer, the landowners
had gone away, and trade had got worse, yet the grocery stores flourished
as before, every year with increasing prosperity; there were plenty of
purchasers for their goods.

They were awaiting Mitya with impatience in the shop. They had vivid
recollections of how he had bought, three or four weeks ago, wine and
goods of all sorts to the value of several hundred roubles, paid for in
cash (they would never have let him have anything on credit, of course).
They remembered that then, as now, he had had a bundle of hundredвЂђrouble
notes in his hand, and had scattered them at random, without bargaining,
without reflecting, or caring to reflect what use so much wine and
provisions would be to him. The story was told all over the town that,
driving off then with Grushenka to Mokroe, he had вЂњspent three thousand in
one night and the following day, and had come back from the spree without
a penny.вЂќ He had picked up a whole troop of gypsies (encamped in our
neighborhood at the time), who for two days got money without stint out of
him while he was drunk, and drank expensive wine without stint. People
used to tell, laughing at Mitya, how he had given champagne to grimyвЂђ
handed peasants, and feasted the village women and girls on sweets and
Strasburg pies. Though to laugh at Mitya to his face was rather a risky
proceeding, there was much laughter behind his back, especially in the
tavern, at his own ingenuous public avowal that all he had got out of
Grushenka by this вЂњescapadeвЂќ was вЂњpermission to kiss her foot, and that
was the utmost she had allowed him.вЂќ

By the time Mitya and Pyotr Ilyitch reached the shop, they found a cart
with three horses harnessed abreast with bells, and with Andrey, the
driver, ready waiting for Mitya at the entrance. In the shop they had
almost entirely finished packing one box of provisions, and were only
waiting for MityaвЂ™s arrival to nail it down and put it in the cart. Pyotr
Ilyitch was astounded.

вЂњWhere did this cart come from in such a hurry?вЂќ he asked Mitya.

вЂњI met Andrey as I ran to you, and told him to drive straight here to the
shop. ThereвЂ™s no time to lose. Last time I drove with Timofey, but Timofey
now has gone on before me with the witch. Shall we be very late, Andrey?вЂќ

вЂњTheyвЂ™ll only get there an hour at most before us, not even that maybe. I
got Timofey ready to start. I know how heвЂ™ll go. Their pace wonвЂ™t be ours,
Dmitri Fyodorovitch. How could it be? They wonвЂ™t get there an hour
earlier!вЂќ Andrey, a lanky, redвЂђhaired, middleвЂђaged driver, wearing a fullвЂђ
skirted coat, and with a kaftan on his arm, replied warmly.

вЂњFifty roubles for vodka if weвЂ™re only an hour behind them.вЂќ

вЂњI warrant the time, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. Ech, they wonвЂ™t be half an hour
before us, let alone an hour.вЂќ

Though Mitya bustled about seeing after things, he gave his orders
strangely, as it were disconnectedly, and inconsecutively. He began a
sentence and forgot the end of it. Pyotr Ilyitch found himself obliged to
come to the rescue.

вЂњFour hundred roublesвЂ™ worth, not less than four hundred roublesвЂ™ worth,
just as it was then,вЂќ commanded Mitya. вЂњFour dozen champagne, not a bottle
