indispensable articles,вЂќ such as savories, sweets, toffee, etc. But the
main part of the goods ordered would be packed and sent off, as on the
previous occasion, in a special cart also with three horses traveling at
full speed, so that it would arrive not more than an hour later than
Dmitri Fyodorovitch himself.

вЂњNot more than an hour! Not more than an hour! And put in more toffee and
fondants. The girls there are so fond of it,вЂќ Mitya insisted hotly.

вЂњThe fondants are all right. But what do you want with four dozen of
champagne? One would be enough,вЂќ said Pyotr Ilyitch, almost angry. He
began bargaining, asking for a bill of the goods, and refused to be
satisfied. But he only succeeded in saving a hundred roubles. In the end
it was agreed that only three hundred roublesвЂ™ worth should be sent.

вЂњWell, you may go to the devil!вЂќ cried Pyotr Ilyitch, on second thoughts.
вЂњWhatвЂ™s it to do with me? Throw away your money, since itвЂ™s cost you
nothing.вЂќ

вЂњThis way, my economist, this way, donвЂ™t be angry.вЂќ Mitya drew him into a
room at the back of the shop. вЂњTheyвЂ™ll give us a bottle here directly.
WeвЂ™ll taste it. Ech, Pyotr Ilyitch, come along with me, for youвЂ™re a nice
fellow, the sort I like.вЂќ

Mitya sat down on a wicker chair, before a little table, covered with a
dirty dinnerвЂђnapkin. Pyotr Ilyitch sat down opposite, and the champagne
soon appeared, and oysters were suggested to the gentlemen. вЂњFirstвЂђclass
oysters, the last lot in.вЂќ

вЂњHang the oysters. I donвЂ™t eat them. And we donвЂ™t need anything,вЂќ cried
Pyotr Ilyitch, almost angrily.

вЂњThereвЂ™s no time for oysters,вЂќ said Mitya. вЂњAnd IвЂ™m not hungry. Do you
know, friend,вЂќ he said suddenly, with feeling, вЂњI never have liked all
this disorder.вЂќ

вЂњWho does like it? Three dozen of champagne for peasants, upon my word,
thatвЂ™s enough to make any one angry!вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s not what I mean. IвЂ™m talking of a higher order. ThereвЂ™s no order
in me, no higher order. But ... thatвЂ™s all over. ThereвЂ™s no need to grieve
about it. ItвЂ™s too late, damn it! My whole life has been disorder, and one
must set it in order. Is that a pun, eh?вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re raving, not making puns!вЂќ


    вЂњGlory be to God in Heaven,
    Glory be to God in me....


вЂњThat verse came from my heart once, itвЂ™s not a verse, but a tear.... I
made it myself ... not while I was pulling the captainвЂ™s beard,
though....вЂќ

вЂњWhy do you bring him in all of a sudden?вЂќ

вЂњWhy do I bring him in? Foolery! All things come to an end; all things are
made equal. ThatвЂ™s the long and short of it.вЂќ

вЂњYou know, I keep thinking of your pistols.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s all foolery, too! Drink, and donвЂ™t be fanciful. I love life. IвЂ™ve
loved life too much, shamefully much. Enough! LetвЂ™s drink to life, dear
boy, I propose the toast. Why am I pleased with myself? IвЂ™m a scoundrel,
but IвЂ™m satisfied with myself. And yet IвЂ™m tortured by the thought that
IвЂ™m a scoundrel, but satisfied with myself. I bless the creation. IвЂ™m
ready to bless God and His creation directly, but ... I must kill one
noxious insect for fear it should crawl and spoil life for others.... Let
us drink to life, dear brother. What can be more precious than life?
Nothing! To life, and to one queen of queens!вЂќ

вЂњLetвЂ™s drink to life and to your queen, too, if you like.вЂќ

They drank a glass each. Although Mitya was excited and expansive, yet he
was melancholy, too. It was as though some heavy, overwhelming anxiety
were weighing upon him.

вЂњMisha ... hereвЂ™s your Misha come! Misha, come here, my boy, drink this
glass to PhЕ“bus, the goldenвЂђhaired, of toвЂђmorrow morn....вЂќ

вЂњWhat are you giving it him for?вЂќ cried Pyotr Ilyitch, irritably.

вЂњYes, yes, yes, let me! I want to!вЂќ

вЂњEвЂ”ech!вЂќ

Misha emptied the glass, bowed, and ran out.

вЂњHeвЂ™ll remember it afterwards,вЂќ Mitya remarked. вЂњWoman, I love woman! What
is woman? The queen of creation! My heart is sad, my heart is sad, Pyotr
Ilyitch. Do you remember Hamlet? вЂI am very sorry, good Horatio! Alas,
poor Yorick!вЂ™ Perhaps thatвЂ™s me, Yorick? Yes, IвЂ™m Yorick now, and a skull
afterwards.вЂќ

Pyotr Ilyitch listened in silence. Mitya, too, was silent for a while.

вЂњWhat dogвЂ™s that youвЂ™ve got here?вЂќ he asked the shopman, casually,
noticing a pretty little lapвЂђdog with dark eyes, sitting in the corner.

вЂњIt belongs to Varvara Alexyevna, the mistress,вЂќ answered the clerk. вЂњShe
brought it and forgot it here. It must be taken back to her.вЂќ

вЂњI saw one like it ... in the regiment ...вЂќ murmured Mitya dreamily, вЂњonly
that one had its hind leg broken.... By the way, Pyotr Ilyitch, I wanted
to ask you: have you ever stolen anything in your life?вЂќ

вЂњWhat a question!вЂќ

вЂњOh, I didnвЂ™t mean anything. From somebodyвЂ™s pocket, you know. I donвЂ™t
mean government money, every one steals that, and no doubt you do,
too....вЂќ

вЂњYou go to the devil.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™m talking of other peopleвЂ™s money. Stealing straight out of a pocket?
Out of a purse, eh?вЂќ

вЂњI stole twenty copecks from my mother when I was nine years old. I took
it off the table on the sly, and held it tight in my hand.вЂќ

вЂњWell, and what happened?вЂќ

вЂњOh, nothing. I kept it three days, then I felt ashamed, confessed, and
gave it back.вЂќ

вЂњAnd what then?вЂќ

вЂњNaturally I was whipped. But why do you ask? Have you stolen something?вЂќ

вЂњI have,вЂќ said Mitya, winking slyly.

вЂњWhat have you stolen?вЂќ inquired Pyotr Ilyitch curiously.

вЂњI stole twenty copecks from my mother when I was nine years old, and gave
it back three days after.вЂќ

As he said this, Mitya suddenly got up.

вЂњDmitri Fyodorovitch, wonвЂ™t you come now?вЂќ called Andrey from the door of
the shop.

вЂњAre you ready? WeвЂ™ll come!вЂќ Mitya started. вЂњA few more last words
andвЂ”Andrey, a glass of vodka at starting. Give him some brandy as well!
That boxвЂќ (the one with the pistols) вЂњput under my seat. GoodвЂђby, Pyotr
Ilyitch, donвЂ™t remember evil against me.вЂќ

вЂњBut youвЂ™re coming back toвЂђmorrow?вЂќ

вЂњOf course.вЂќ

вЂњWill you settle the little bill now?вЂќ cried the clerk, springing forward.

вЂњOh, yes, the bill. Of course.вЂќ

He pulled the bundle of notes out of his pocket again, picked out three
hundred roubles, threw them on the counter, and ran hurriedly out of the
shop. Every one followed him out, bowing and wishing him good luck.
Andrey, coughing from the brandy he had just swallowed, jumped up on the
box. But Mitya was only just taking his seat when suddenly to his surprise
he saw Fenya before him. She ran up panting, clasped her hands before him
with a cry, and plumped down at his feet.

вЂњDmitri Fyodorovitch, dear good Dmitri Fyodorovitch, donвЂ™t harm my
mistress. And it was I told you all about it.... And donвЂ™t murder him, he
came first, heвЂ™s hers! HeвЂ™ll marry Agrafena Alexandrovna now. ThatвЂ™s why
heвЂ™s come back from Siberia. Dmitri Fyodorovitch, dear, donвЂ™t take a
fellow creatureвЂ™s life!вЂќ

вЂњTutвЂ”tutвЂ”tut! ThatвЂ™s it, is it? So youвЂ™re off there to make trouble!вЂќ
muttered Pyotr Ilyitch. вЂњNow, itвЂ™s all clear, as clear as daylight. Dmitri
Fyodorovitch, give me your pistols at once if you mean to behave like a
man,вЂќ he shouted aloud to Mitya. вЂњDo you hear, Dmitri?вЂќ

вЂњThe pistols? Wait a bit, brother, IвЂ™ll throw them into the pool on the
road,вЂќ answered Mitya. вЂњFenya, get up, donвЂ™t kneel to me. Mitya wonвЂ™t hurt
any one, the silly fool wonвЂ™t hurt any one again. But I say, Fenya,вЂќ he
shouted, after having taken his seat. вЂњI hurt you just now, so forgive me
and have pity on me, forgive a scoundrel.... But it doesnвЂ™t matter if you
donвЂ™t. ItвЂ™s all the same now. Now then, Andrey, look alive, fly along full
speed!вЂќ

Andrey whipped up the horses, and the bells began ringing.

вЂњGoodвЂђby, Pyotr Ilyitch! My last tear is for you!...вЂќ

вЂњHeвЂ™s not drunk, but he keeps babbling like a lunatic,вЂќ Pyotr Ilyitch
thought as he watched him go. He had half a mind to stay and see the cart
packed with the remaining wines and provisions, knowing that they would
deceive and defraud Mitya. But, suddenly feeling vexed with himself, he
turned away with a curse and went to the tavern to play billiards.

вЂњHeвЂ™s a fool, though heвЂ™s a good fellow,вЂќ he muttered as he went. вЂњIвЂ™ve
heard of that officer, GrushenkaвЂ™s former flame. Well, if he has turned
up.... Ech, those pistols! Damn it all! IвЂ™m not his nurse! Let them do
what they like! Besides, itвЂ™ll all come to nothing. TheyвЂ™re a set of
brawlers, thatвЂ™s all. TheyвЂ™ll drink and fight, fight and make friends
again. They are not men who do anything real. What does he mean by вЂIвЂ™m
stepping aside, IвЂ™m punishing myself?вЂ™ ItвЂ™ll come to nothing! HeвЂ™s shouted
such phrases a thousand times, drunk, in the taverns. But now heвЂ™s not
drunk. вЂDrunk in spiritвЂ™вЂ”theyвЂ™re fond of fine phrases, the villains. Am I
his nurse? He must have been fighting, his face was all over blood. With
whom? I shall find out at the вЂMetropolis.вЂ™ And his handkerchief was
soaked in blood.... ItвЂ™s still lying on my floor.... Hang it!вЂќ

He reached the tavern in a bad humor and at once made up a game. The game
cheered him. He played a second game, and suddenly began telling one of
his partners that Dmitri Karamazov had come in for some cash
againвЂ”something like three thousand roubles, and had gone to Mokroe again
to spend it with Grushenka.... This news roused singular interest in his
listeners. They all spoke of it, not laughing, but with a strange gravity.
They left off playing.

вЂњThree thousand? But where can he have got three thousand?вЂќ

Questions were asked. The story of Madame HohlakovвЂ™s present was received
with skepticism.

вЂњHasnвЂ™t he robbed his old father?вЂ”thatвЂ™s the question.вЂќ

вЂњThree thousand! ThereвЂ™s something odd about it.вЂќ

вЂњHe boasted aloud that he would kill his father; we all heard him, here.
And it was three thousand he talked about ...вЂќ

Pyotr Ilyitch listened. All at once he became short and dry in his
answers. He said not a word about the blood on MityaвЂ™s face and hands,
though he had meant to speak of it at first.

They began a third game, and by degrees the talk about Mitya died away.
But by the end of the third game, Pyotr Ilyitch felt no more desire for
billiards; he laid down the cue, and without having supper as he had
intended, he walked out of the tavern. When he reached the marketвЂђplace he
stood still in perplexity, wondering at himself. He realized that what he
wanted was to go to Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s and find out if anything had
happened there. вЂњOn account of some stupid nonsenseвЂ”as itвЂ™s sure to turn
outвЂ”am I going to wake up the household and make a scandal? Fooh! damn it,
is it my business to look after them?вЂќ

In a very bad humor he went straight home, and suddenly remembered Fenya.
вЂњDamn it all! I ought to have questioned her just now,вЂќ he thought with
vexation, вЂњI should have heard everything.вЂќ And the desire to speak to
her, and so find out, became so pressing and importunate that when he was
halfвЂђway home he turned abruptly and went towards the house where
Grushenka lodged. Going up to the gate he knocked. The sound of the knock
in the silence of the night sobered him and made him feel annoyed. And no
one answered him; every one in the house was asleep.

вЂњAnd I shall be making a fuss!вЂќ he thought, with a feeling of positive
discomfort. But instead of going away altogether, he fell to knocking
again with all his might, filling the street with clamor.

вЂњNot coming? Well, I will knock them up, I will!вЂќ he muttered at each
knock, fuming at himself, but at the same time he redoubled his knocks on
the gate.



Chapter VI. вЂњI Am Coming, Too!вЂќ


But Dmitri Fyodorovitch was speeding along the road. It was a little more
than twenty versts to Mokroe, but AndreyвЂ™s three horses galloped at such a
pace that the distance might be covered in an hour and a quarter. The
swift motion revived Mitya. The air was fresh and cool, there were big
stars shining in the sky. It was the very night, and perhaps the very
hour, in which Alyosha fell on the earth, and rapturously swore to love it
for ever and ever.

All was confusion, confusion, in MityaвЂ™s soul, but although many things
were goading his heart, at that moment his whole being was yearning for
her, his queen, to whom he was flying to look on her for the last time.
One thing I can say for certain; his heart did not waver for one instant.
I shall perhaps not be believed when I say that this jealous lover felt
not the slightest jealousy of this new rival, who seemed to have sprung
out of the earth. If any other had appeared on the scene, he would have
been jealous at once, and would perhaps have stained his fierce hands with
blood again. But as he flew through the night, he felt no envy, no
hostility even, for the man who had been her first lover.... It is true he
had not yet seen him.

вЂњHere there was no room for dispute: it was her right and his; this was
her first love which, after five years, she had not forgotten; so she had
loved him only for those five years, and I, how do I come in? What right
have I? Step aside, Mitya, and make way! What am I now? Now everything is
over apart from the officerвЂ”even if he had not appeared, everything would
be over ...вЂќ

These words would roughly have expressed his feelings, if he had been
capable of reasoning. But he could not reason at that moment. His present
plan of action had arisen without reasoning. At FenyaвЂ™s first words, it
had sprung from feeling, and been adopted in a flash, with all its
consequences. And yet, in spite of his resolution, there was confusion in
his soul, an agonizing confusion: his resolution did not give him peace.
There was so much behind that tortured him. And it seemed strange to him,
at moments, to think that he had written his own sentence of death with
pen and paper: вЂњI punish myself,вЂќ and the paper was lying there in his
pocket, ready; the pistol was loaded; he had already resolved how, next
morning, he would meet the first warm ray of вЂњgoldenвЂђhaired PhЕ“bus.вЂќ

And yet he could not be quit of the past, of all that he had left behind
and that tortured him. He felt that miserably, and the thought of it sank
into his heart with despair. There was one moment when he felt an impulse
to stop Andrey, to jump out of the cart, to pull out his loaded pistol,
and to make an end of everything without waiting for the dawn. But that
moment flew by like a spark. The horses galloped on, вЂњdevouring space,вЂќ
and as he drew near his goal, again the thought of her, of her alone, took
more and more complete possession of his soul, chasing away the fearful
images that had been haunting it. Oh, how he longed to look upon her, if
only for a moment, if only from a distance!

вЂњSheвЂ™s now with _him_,вЂќ he thought, вЂњnow I shall see what she looks like
with him, her first love, and thatвЂ™s all I want.вЂќ Never had this woman,
who was such a fateful influence in his life, aroused such love in his
breast, such new and unknown feeling, surprising even to himself, a
feeling tender to devoutness, to selfвЂђeffacement before her! вЂњI will
efface myself!вЂќ he said, in a rush of almost hysterical ecstasy.

They had been galloping nearly an hour. Mitya was silent, and though
Andrey was, as a rule, a talkative peasant, he did not utter a word,
either. He seemed afraid to talk, he only whipped up smartly his three
lean, but mettlesome, bay horses. Suddenly Mitya cried out in horrible
anxiety:

вЂњAndrey! What if theyвЂ™re asleep?вЂќ

This thought fell upon him like a blow. It had not occurred to him before.

вЂњIt may well be that theyвЂ™re gone to bed, by now, Dmitri Fyodorovitch.вЂќ

Mitya frowned as though in pain. Yes, indeed ... he was rushing there ...
with such feelings ... while they were asleep ... she was asleep, perhaps,
there too.... An angry feeling surged up in his heart.

вЂњDrive on, Andrey! Whip them up! Look alive!вЂќ he cried, beside himself.

вЂњBut maybe theyвЂ™re not in bed!вЂќ Andrey went on after a pause. вЂњTimofey
said they were a lot of them thereвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњAt the station?вЂќ

вЂњNot at the postingвЂђstation, but at PlastunovвЂ™s, at the inn, where they
let out horses, too.вЂќ

вЂњI know. So you say there are a lot of them? HowвЂ™s that? Who are they?вЂќ
cried Mitya, greatly dismayed at this unexpected news.

вЂњWell, Timofey was saying theyвЂ™re all gentlefolk. Two from our townвЂ”who
they are I canвЂ™t sayвЂ”and there are two others, strangers, maybe more
besides. I didnвЂ™t ask particularly. TheyвЂ™ve set to playing cards, so
Timofey said.вЂќ

вЂњCards?вЂќ

вЂњSo, maybe theyвЂ™re not in bed if theyвЂ™re at cards. ItвЂ™s most likely not
more than eleven.вЂќ

вЂњQuicker, Andrey! Quicker!вЂќ Mitya cried again, nervously.

вЂњMay I ask you something, sir?вЂќ said Andrey, after a pause. вЂњOnly IвЂ™m
afraid of angering you, sir.вЂќ

вЂњWhat is it?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, Fenya threw herself at your feet just now, and begged you not to
harm her mistress, and some one else, too ... so you see, sirвЂ” ItвЂ™s I am
taking you there ... forgive me, sir, itвЂ™s my conscience ... maybe itвЂ™s
stupid of me to speak of itвЂ”вЂќ

Mitya suddenly seized him by the shoulders from behind.

вЂњAre you a driver?вЂќ he asked frantically.

вЂњYes, sir.вЂќ

вЂњThen you know that one has to make way. What would you say to a driver
who wouldnвЂ™t make way for any one, but would just drive on and crush
people? No, a driver mustnвЂ™t run over people. One canвЂ™t run over a man.
One canвЂ™t spoil peopleвЂ™s lives. And if you have spoilt a lifeвЂ”punish
yourself.... If only youвЂ™ve spoilt, if only youвЂ™ve ruined any oneвЂ™s
lifeвЂ”punish yourself and go away.вЂќ

These phrases burst from Mitya almost hysterically. Though Andrey was
surprised at him, he kept up the conversation.

вЂњThatвЂ™s right, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, youвЂ™re quite right, one mustnвЂ™t crush
or torment a man, or any kind of creature, for every creature is created
by God. Take a horse, for instance, for some folks, even among us drivers,
drive anyhow. Nothing will restrain them, they just force it along.вЂќ

вЂњTo hell?вЂќ Mitya interrupted, and went off into his abrupt, short laugh.
вЂњAndrey, simple soul,вЂќ he seized him by the shoulders again, вЂњtell me,
will Dmitri Fyodorovitch Karamazov go to hell, or not, what do you think?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know, darling, it depends on you, for you are ... you see, sir,
when the Son of God was nailed on the Cross and died, He went straight
down to hell from the Cross, and set free all sinners that were in agony.
And the devil groaned, because he thought that he would get no more
sinners in hell. And God said to him, then, вЂDonвЂ™t groan, for you shall
have all the mighty of the earth, the rulers, the chief judges, and the
rich men, and shall be filled up as you have been in all the ages till I
come again.вЂ™ Those were His very words ...вЂќ

вЂњA peasant legend! Capital! Whip up the left, Andrey!вЂќ

вЂњSo you see, sir, who it is hellвЂ™s for,вЂќ said Andrey, whipping up the left
horse, вЂњbut youвЂ™re like a little child ... thatвЂ™s how we look on you ...
and though youвЂ™re hastyвЂђtempered, sir, yet God will forgive you for your
kind heart.вЂќ

вЂњAnd you, do you forgive me, Andrey?вЂќ

вЂњWhat should I forgive you for, sir? YouвЂ™ve never done me any harm.вЂќ

вЂњNo, for every one, for every one, you here alone, on the road, will you
forgive me for every one? Speak, simple peasant heart!вЂќ

вЂњOh, sir! I feel afraid of driving you, your talk is so strange.вЂќ

But Mitya did not hear. He was frantically praying and muttering to
himself.

вЂњLord, receive me, with all my lawlessness, and do not condemn me. Let me
pass by Thy judgment ... do not condemn me, for I have condemned myself,
do not condemn me, for I love Thee, O Lord. I am a wretch, but I love
Thee. If Thou sendest me to hell, I shall love Thee there, and from there
I shall cry out that I love Thee for ever and ever.... But let me love to
the end.... Here and now for just five hours ... till the first light of
Thy day ... for I love the queen of my soul ... I love her and I cannot
help loving her. Thou seest my whole heart.... I shall gallop up, I shall
fall before her and say, вЂYou are right to pass on and leave me. Farewell
and forget your victim ... never fret yourself about me!вЂ™ вЂќ

вЂњMokroe!вЂќ cried Andrey, pointing ahead with his whip.

Through the pale darkness of the night loomed a solid black mass of
buildings, flung down, as it were, in the vast plain. The village of
Mokroe numbered two thousand inhabitants, but at that hour all were
asleep, and only here and there a few lights still twinkled.

вЂњDrive on, Andrey, I come!вЂќ Mitya exclaimed, feverishly.

вЂњTheyвЂ™re not asleep,вЂќ said Andrey again, pointing with his whip to the
PlastunovsвЂ™ inn, which was at the entrance to the village. The six
windows, looking on the street, were all brightly lighted up.

вЂњTheyвЂ™re not asleep,вЂќ Mitya repeated joyously. вЂњQuicker, Andrey! Gallop!
Drive up with a dash! Set the bells ringing! Let all know that I have
come. IвЂ™m coming! IвЂ™m coming, too!вЂќ

Andrey lashed his exhausted team into a gallop, drove with a dash and
pulled up his steaming, panting horses at the high flight of steps.

Mitya jumped out of the cart just as the innkeeper, on his way to bed,
peeped out from the steps curious to see who had arrived.

вЂњTrifon Borissovitch, is that you?вЂќ

The innkeeper bent down, looked intently, ran down the steps, and rushed
up to the guest with obsequious delight.

вЂњDmitri Fyodorovitch, your honor! Do I see you again?вЂќ

Trifon Borissovitch was a thickвЂђset, healthy peasant, of middle height,
with a rather fat face. His expression was severe and uncompromising,
especially with the peasants of Mokroe, but he had the power of assuming
the most obsequious countenance, when he had an inkling that it was to his
interest. He dressed in Russian style, with a shirt buttoning down on one
side, and a fullвЂђskirted coat. He had saved a good sum of money, but was
for ever dreaming of improving his position. More than half the peasants
were in his clutches, every one in the neighborhood was in debt to him.
From the neighboring landowners he bought and rented lands which were
worked by the peasants, in payment of debts which they could never shake
off. He was a widower, with four grownвЂђup daughters. One of them was
already a widow and lived in the inn with her two children, his
grandchildren, and worked for him like a charwoman. Another of his
daughters was married to a petty official, and in one of the rooms of the
inn, on the wall could be seen, among the family photographs, a miniature
photograph of this official in uniform and official epaulettes. The two
younger daughters used to wear fashionable blue or green dresses, fitting
tight at the back, and with trains a yard long, on Church holidays or when
they went to pay visits. But next morning they would get up at dawn, as
usual, sweep out the rooms with a birchвЂђbroom, empty the slops, and clean
up after lodgers.

In spite of the thousands of roubles he had saved, Trifon Borissovitch was
very fond of emptying the pockets of a drunken guest, and remembering that
not a month ago he had, in twentyвЂђfour hours, made two if not three
hundred roubles out of Dmitri, when he had come on his escapade with
Grushenka, he met him now with eager welcome, scenting his prey the moment
Mitya drove up to the steps.

вЂњDmitri Fyodorovitch, dear sir, we see you once more!вЂќ

вЂњStay, Trifon Borissovitch,вЂќ began Mitya, вЂњfirst and foremost, where is
she?вЂќ

вЂњAgrafena Alexandrovna?вЂќ The innвЂђkeeper understood at once, looking
sharply into MityaвЂ™s face. вЂњSheвЂ™s here, too ...вЂќ

вЂњWith whom? With whom?вЂќ

вЂњSome strangers. One is an official gentleman, a Pole, to judge from his
speech. He sent the horses for her from here; and thereвЂ™s another with
him, a friend of his, or a fellow traveler, thereвЂ™s no telling. TheyвЂ™re
dressed like civilians.вЂќ

вЂњWell, are they feasting? Have they money?вЂќ

вЂњPoor sort of a feast! Nothing to boast of, Dmitri Fyodorovitch.вЂќ

вЂњNothing to boast of? And who are the others?вЂќ

вЂњTheyвЂ™re two gentlemen from the town.... TheyвЂ™ve come back from Tcherny,
and are putting up here. OneвЂ™s quite a young gentleman, a relative of Mr.
MiГјsov, he must be, but IвЂ™ve forgotten his name ... and I expect you know
the other, too, a gentleman called Maximov. HeвЂ™s been on a pilgrimage, so
he says, to the monastery in the town. HeвЂ™s traveling with this young
relation of Mr. MiГјsov.вЂќ

вЂњIs that all?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњStay, listen, Trifon Borissovitch. Tell me the chief thing: What of her?
How is she?вЂќ

вЂњOh, sheвЂ™s only just come. SheвЂ™s sitting with them.вЂќ

вЂњIs she cheerful? Is she laughing?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I think sheвЂ™s not laughing much. SheвЂ™s sitting quite dull. SheвЂ™s
combing the young gentlemanвЂ™s hair.вЂќ

вЂњThe PoleвЂ”the officer?вЂќ

вЂњHeвЂ™s not young, and heвЂ™s not an officer, either. Not him, sir. ItвЂ™s the
young gentleman thatвЂ™s Mr. MiГјsovвЂ™s relation ... IвЂ™ve forgotten his name.вЂќ

вЂњKalganov.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s it, Kalganov!вЂќ

вЂњAll right. IвЂ™ll see for myself. Are they playing cards?вЂќ

вЂњThey have been playing, but theyвЂ™ve left off. TheyвЂ™ve been drinking tea,
the official gentleman asked for liqueurs.вЂќ

вЂњStay, Trifon Borissovitch, stay, my good soul, IвЂ™ll see for myself. Now
answer one more question: are the gypsies here?вЂќ

вЂњYou canвЂ™t have the gypsies now, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. The authorities have
sent them away. But weвЂ™ve Jews that play the cymbals and the fiddle in the
village, so one might send for them. TheyвЂ™d come.вЂќ

вЂњSend for them. Certainly send for them!вЂќ cried Mitya. вЂњAnd you can get
the girls together as you did then, Marya especially, Stepanida, too, and
Arina. Two hundred roubles for a chorus!вЂќ

вЂњOh, for a sum like that I can get all the village together, though by now
theyвЂ™re asleep. Are the peasants here worth such kindness, Dmitri
Fyodorovitch, or the girls either? To spend a sum like that on such
coarseness and rudeness! WhatвЂ™s the good of giving a peasant a cigar to
smoke, the stinking ruffian! And the girls are all lousy. Besides, IвЂ™ll
get my daughters up for nothing, let alone a sum like that. TheyвЂ™ve only
just gone to bed, IвЂ™ll give them a kick and set them singing for you. You
gave the peasants champagne to drink the other day, eвЂ”ech!вЂќ

For all his pretended compassion for Mitya, Trifon Borissovitch had hidden
half a dozen bottles of champagne on that last occasion, and had picked up
a hundredвЂђrouble note under the table, and it had remained in his
clutches.

вЂњTrifon Borissovitch, I sent more than one thousand flying last time I was
here. Do you remember?вЂќ

вЂњYou did send it flying. I may well remember. You must have left three
thousand behind you.вЂќ

вЂњWell, IвЂ™ve come to do the same again, do you see?вЂќ

And he pulled out his roll of notes, and held them up before the
innkeeperвЂ™s nose.

вЂњNow, listen and remember. In an hourвЂ™s time the wine will arrive,
savories, pies, and sweetsвЂ”bring them all up at once. That box Andrey has
got is to be brought up at once, too. Open it, and hand champagne
immediately. And the girls, we must have the girls, Marya especially.вЂќ

He turned to the cart and pulled out the box of pistols.

вЂњHere, Andrey, letвЂ™s settle. HereвЂ™s fifteen roubles for the drive, and
fifty for vodka ... for your readiness, for your love.... Remember
Karamazov!вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™m afraid, sir,вЂќ faltered Andrey. вЂњGive me five roubles extra, but more
I wonвЂ™t take. Trifon Borissovitch, bear witness. Forgive my foolish words
...вЂќ

вЂњWhat are you afraid of?вЂќ asked Mitya, scanning him. вЂњWell, go to the
devil, if thatвЂ™s it!вЂќ he cried, flinging him five roubles. вЂњNow, Trifon
Borissovitch, take me up quietly and let me first get a look at them, so
that they donвЂ™t see me. Where are they? In the blue room?вЂќ

Trifon Borissovitch looked apprehensively at Mitya, but at once obediently
did his bidding. Leading him into the passage, he went himself into the
first large room, adjoining that in which the visitors were sitting, and
took the light away. Then he stealthily led Mitya in, and put him in a
corner in the dark, whence he could freely watch the company without being
seen. But Mitya did not look long, and, indeed, he could not see them, he
saw her, his heart throbbed violently, and all was dark before his eyes.

She was sitting sideways to the table in a low chair, and beside her, on
the sofa, was the pretty youth, Kalganov. She was holding his hand and
seemed to be laughing, while he, seeming vexed and not looking at her, was
saying something in a loud voice to Maximov, who sat the other side of the
table, facing Grushenka. Maximov was laughing violently at something. On
the sofa sat _he_, and on a chair by the sofa there was another stranger.
The one on the sofa was lolling backwards, smoking a pipe, and Mitya had
an impression of a stoutish, broadвЂђfaced, short little man, who was
apparently angry about something. His friend, the other stranger, struck
Mitya as extraordinarily tall, but he could make out nothing more. He
caught his breath. He could not bear it for a minute, he put the pistolвЂђ
case on a chest, and with a throbbing heart he walked, feeling cold all
over, straight into the blue room to face the company.

вЂњAie!вЂќ shrieked Grushenka, the first to notice him.



Chapter VII. The First And Rightful Lover


With his long, rapid strides, Mitya walked straight up to the table.

вЂњGentlemen,вЂќ he said in a loud voice, almost shouting, yet stammering at
every word, вЂњI ... IвЂ™m all right! DonвЂ™t be afraid!вЂќ he exclaimed,
вЂњIвЂ”thereвЂ™s nothing the matter,вЂќ he turned suddenly to Grushenka, who had
shrunk back in her chair towards Kalganov, and clasped his hand tightly.
вЂњI ... IвЂ™m coming, too. IвЂ™m here till morning. Gentlemen, may I stay with
you till morning? Only till morning, for the last time, in this same
room?вЂќ

So he finished, turning to the fat little man, with the pipe, sitting on
the sofa. The latter removed his pipe from his lips with dignity and
observed severely:

вЂњ_Panie_, weвЂ™re here in private. There are other rooms.вЂќ

вЂњWhy, itвЂ™s you, Dmitri Fyodorovitch! What do you mean?вЂќ answered Kalganov
suddenly. вЂњSit down with us. How are you?вЂќ

вЂњDelighted to see you, dear ... and precious fellow, I always thought a
lot of you.вЂќ Mitya responded, joyfully and eagerly, at once holding out
his hand across the table.

вЂњAie! How tight you squeeze! YouвЂ™ve quite broken my fingers,вЂќ laughed
Kalganov.

вЂњHe always squeezes like that, always,вЂќ Grushenka put in gayly, with a
timid smile, seeming suddenly convinced from MityaвЂ™s face that he was not
going to make a scene. She was watching him with intense curiosity and
still some uneasiness. She was impressed by something about him, and
indeed the last thing she expected of him was that he would come in and
speak like this at such a moment.

вЂњGood evening,вЂќ Maximov ventured blandly on the left. Mitya rushed up to
him, too.

вЂњGood evening. YouвЂ™re here, too! How glad I am to find you here, too!
Gentlemen, gentlemen, IвЂ”вЂќ (He addressed the Polish gentleman with the pipe
again, evidently taking him for the most important person present.) вЂњI
flew here.... I wanted to spend my last day, my last hour in this room, in
this very room ... where I, too, adored ... my queen.... Forgive me,
_panie_,вЂќ he cried wildly, вЂњI flew here and vowedвЂ” Oh, donвЂ™t be afraid,
itвЂ™s my last night! LetвЂ™s drink to our good understanding. TheyвЂ™ll bring
the wine at once.... I brought this with me.вЂќ (Something made him pull out
his bundle of notes.) вЂњAllow me, _panie_! I want to have music, singing, a
revel, as we had before. But the worm, the unnecessary worm, will crawl
away, and thereвЂ™ll be no more of him. I will commemorate my day of joy on
my last night.вЂќ

He was almost choking. There was so much, so much he wanted to say, but
strange exclamations were all that came from his lips. The Pole gazed
fixedly at him, at the bundle of notes in his hand; looked at Grushenka,
and was in evident perplexity.

вЂњIf my suverin lady is permittingвЂ”вЂќ he was beginning.

вЂњWhat does вЂsuverinвЂ™ mean? вЂSovereign,вЂ™ I suppose?вЂќ interrupted Grushenka.
вЂњI canвЂ™t help laughing at you, the way you talk. Sit down, Mitya, what are
you talking about? DonвЂ™t frighten us, please. You wonвЂ™t frighten us, will
you? If you wonвЂ™t, I am glad to see you ...вЂќ

вЂњMe, me frighten you?вЂќ cried Mitya, flinging up his hands. вЂњOh, pass me
by, go your way, I wonвЂ™t hinder you!...вЂќ

And suddenly he surprised them all, and no doubt himself as well, by
flinging himself on a chair, and bursting into tears, turning his head
away to the opposite wall, while his arms clasped the back of the chair
tight, as though embracing it.

вЂњCome, come, what a fellow you are!вЂќ cried Grushenka reproachfully.
вЂњThatвЂ™s just how he comes to see meвЂ”he begins talking, and I canвЂ™t make
out what he means. He cried like that once before, and now heвЂ™s crying
again! ItвЂ™s shameful! Why are you crying? _As though you had anything to
cry for!_вЂќ she added enigmatically, emphasizing each word with some
irritability.

вЂњI ... IвЂ™m not crying.... Well, good evening!вЂќ He instantly turned round
in his chair, and suddenly laughed, not his abrupt wooden laugh, but a
long, quivering, inaudible nervous laugh.

вЂњWell, there you are again.... Come, cheer up, cheer up!вЂќ Grushenka said
to him persuasively. вЂњIвЂ™m very glad youвЂ™ve come, very glad, Mitya, do you
hear, IвЂ™m very glad! I want him to stay here with us,вЂќ she said
peremptorily, addressing the whole company, though her words were
obviously meant for the man sitting on the sofa. вЂњI wish it, I wish it!
And if he goes away I shall go, too!вЂќ she added with flashing eyes.

вЂњWhat my queen commands is law!вЂќ pronounced the Pole, gallantly kissing
GrushenkaвЂ™s hand. вЂњI beg you, _panie_, to join our company,вЂќ he added
politely, addressing Mitya.

Mitya was jumping up with the obvious intention of delivering another
tirade, but the words did not come.

вЂњLetвЂ™s drink, _panie_,вЂќ he blurted out instead of making a speech. Every
one laughed.

вЂњGood heavens! I thought he was going to begin again!вЂќ Grushenka exclaimed
nervously. вЂњDo you hear, Mitya,вЂќ she went on insistently, вЂњdonвЂ™t prance
about, but itвЂ™s nice youвЂ™ve brought the champagne. I want some myself, and
I canвЂ™t bear liqueurs. And best of all, youвЂ™ve come yourself. We were
fearfully dull here.... YouвЂ™ve come for a spree again, I suppose? But put
your money in your pocket. Where did you get such a lot?вЂќ

Mitya had been, all this time, holding in his hand the crumpled bundle of
notes on which the eyes of all, especially of the Poles, were fixed. In
confusion he thrust them hurriedly into his pocket. He flushed. At that
moment the innkeeper brought in an uncorked bottle of champagne, and
glasses on a tray. Mitya snatched up the bottle, but he was so bewildered
that he did not know what to do with it. Kalganov took it from him and
poured out the champagne.

вЂњAnother! Another bottle!вЂќ Mitya cried to the innkeeper, and, forgetting
to clink glasses with the Pole whom he had so solemnly invited to drink to
their good understanding, he drank off his glass without waiting for any
one else. His whole countenance suddenly changed. The solemn and tragic
expression with which he had entered vanished completely, and a look of
something childlike came into his face. He seemed to have become suddenly
gentle and subdued. He looked shyly and happily at every one, with a
continual nervous little laugh, and the blissful expression of a dog who
has done wrong, been punished, and forgiven. He seemed to have forgotten
everything, and was looking round at every one with a childlike smile of
delight. He looked at Grushenka, laughing continually, and bringing his
chair close up to her. By degrees he had gained some idea of the two
Poles, though he had formed no definite conception of them yet.

The Pole on the sofa struck him by his dignified demeanor and his Polish
accent; and, above all, by his pipe. вЂњWell, what of it? ItвЂ™s a good thing
heвЂ™s smoking a pipe,вЂќ he reflected. The PoleвЂ™s puffy, middleвЂђaged face,
with its tiny nose and two very thin, pointed, dyed and impudentвЂђlooking
mustaches, had not so far roused the faintest doubts in Mitya. He was not
even particularly struck by the PoleвЂ™s absurd wig made in Siberia, with
loveвЂђlocks foolishly combed forward over the temples. вЂњI suppose itвЂ™s all
right since he wears a wig,вЂќ he went on, musing blissfully. The other,
younger Pole, who was staring insolently and defiantly at the company and
listening to the conversation with silent contempt, still only impressed
Mitya by his great height, which was in striking contrast to the Pole on
the sofa. вЂњIf he stood up heвЂ™d be six foot three.вЂќ The thought flitted
through MityaвЂ™s mind. It occurred to him, too, that this Pole must be the
friend of the other, as it were, a вЂњbodyguard,вЂќ and no doubt the big Pole
was at the disposal of the little Pole with the pipe. But this all seemed
to Mitya perfectly right and not to be questioned. In his mood of doglike
submissiveness all feeling of rivalry had died away.

GrushenkaвЂ™s mood and the enigmatic tone of some of her words he completely
failed to grasp. All he understood, with thrilling heart, was that she was
kind to him, that she had forgiven him, and made him sit by her. He was
beside himself with delight, watching her sip her glass of champagne. The
silence of the company seemed somehow to strike him, however, and he
looked round at every one with expectant eyes.

вЂњWhy are we sitting here though, gentlemen? Why donвЂ™t you begin doing
something?вЂќ his smiling eyes seemed to ask.

вЂњHe keeps talking nonsense, and we were all laughing,вЂќ Kalganov began
suddenly, as though divining his thought, and pointing to Maximov.

Mitya immediately stared at Kalganov and then at Maximov.

вЂњHeвЂ™s talking nonsense?вЂќ he laughed, his short, wooden laugh, seeming
suddenly delighted at somethingвЂ”вЂњha ha!вЂќ

вЂњYes. Would you believe it, he will have it that all our cavalry officers
in the twenties married Polish women. ThatвЂ™s awful rot, isnвЂ™t it?вЂќ

вЂњPolish women?вЂќ repeated Mitya, perfectly ecstatic.

Kalganov was well aware of MityaвЂ™s attitude to Grushenka, and he guessed
about the Pole, too, but that did not so much interest him, perhaps did
not interest him at all; what he was interested in was Maximov. He had
come here with Maximov by chance, and he met the Poles here at the inn for
the first time in his life. Grushenka he knew before, and had once been
with some one to see her; but she had not taken to him. But here she
looked at him very affectionately: before MityaвЂ™s arrival, she had been
making much of him, but he seemed somehow to be unmoved by it. He was a
boy, not over twenty, dressed like a dandy, with a very charming fairвЂђ
skinned face, and splendid thick, fair hair. From his fair face looked out
beautiful pale blue eyes, with an intelligent and sometimes even deep
expression, beyond his age indeed, although the young man sometimes looked
and talked quite like a child, and was not at all ashamed of it, even when
he was aware of it himself. As a rule he was very willful, even
capricious, though always friendly. Sometimes there was something fixed
and obstinate in his expression. He would look at you and listen, seeming
all the while to be persistently dreaming over something else. Often he
was listless and lazy, at other times he would grow excited, sometimes,
apparently, over the most trivial matters.

вЂњOnly imagine, IвЂ™ve been taking him about with me for the last four days,вЂќ
he went on, indolently drawling his words, quite naturally though, without
the slightest affectation. вЂњEver since your brother, do you remember,
shoved him off the carriage and sent him flying. That made me take an
interest in him at the time, and I took him into the country, but he keeps
talking such rot IвЂ™m ashamed to be with him. IвЂ™m taking him back.вЂќ

вЂњThe gentleman has not seen Polish ladies, and says what is impossible,вЂќ
the Pole with the pipe observed to Maximov.

He spoke Russian fairly well, much better, anyway, than he pretended. If
he used Russian words, he always distorted them into a Polish form.

вЂњBut I was married to a Polish lady myself,вЂќ tittered Maximov.

вЂњBut did you serve in the cavalry? You were talking about the cavalry.
Were you a cavalry officer?вЂќ put in Kalganov at once.

вЂњWas he a cavalry officer indeed? Ha ha!вЂќ cried Mitya, listening eagerly,
and turning his inquiring eyes to each as he spoke, as though there were
no knowing what he might hear from each.

вЂњNo, you see,вЂќ Maximov turned to him. вЂњWhat I mean is that those pretty
Polish ladies ... when they danced the mazurka with our Uhlans ... when
one of them dances a mazurka with a Uhlan she jumps on his knee like a
kitten ... a little white one ... and the _pan_вЂђfather and _pan_вЂђmother
look on and allow it.... They allow it ... and next day the Uhlan comes
and offers her his hand.... ThatвЂ™s how it is ... offers her his hand, he
he!вЂќ Maximov ended, tittering.

вЂњThe _pan_ is a _lajdak_!вЂќ the tall Pole on the chair growled suddenly and
crossed one leg over the other. MityaвЂ™s eye was caught by his huge greased
boot, with its thick, dirty sole. The dress of both the Poles looked
rather greasy.

вЂњWell, now itвЂ™s _lajdak_! WhatвЂ™s he scolding about?вЂќ said Grushenka,
suddenly vexed.

вЂњ_Pani_ Agrippina, what the gentleman saw in Poland were servant girls,
and not ladies of good birth,вЂќ the Pole with the pipe observed to
Grushenka.

вЂњYou can reckon on that,вЂќ the tall Pole snapped contemptuously.

вЂњWhat next! Let him talk! People talk, why hinder them? It makes it
cheerful,вЂќ Grushenka said crossly.

вЂњIвЂ™m not hindering them, _pani_,вЂќ said the Pole in the wig, with a long
look at Grushenka, and relapsing into dignified silence he sucked his pipe
again.

вЂњNo, no. The Polish gentleman spoke the truth.вЂќ Kalganov got excited
again, as though it were a question of vast import. вЂњHeвЂ™s never been in
Poland, so how can he talk about it? I suppose you werenвЂ™t married in
Poland, were you?вЂќ

вЂњNo, in the Province of Smolensk. Only, a Uhlan had brought her to Russia
before that, my future wife, with her mamma and her aunt, and another
female relation with a grownвЂђup son. He brought her straight from Poland
and gave her up to me. He was a lieutenant in our regiment, a very nice
young man. At first he meant to marry her himself. But he didnвЂ™t marry
her, because she turned out to be lame.вЂќ

вЂњSo you married a lame woman?вЂќ cried Kalganov.

вЂњYes. They both deceived me a little bit at the time, and concealed it. I
thought she was hopping; she kept hopping.... I thought it was for fun.вЂќ

вЂњSo pleased she was going to marry you!вЂќ yelled Kalganov, in a ringing,
childish voice.

вЂњYes, so pleased. But it turned out to be quite a different cause.
Afterwards, when we were married, after the wedding, that very evening,
she confessed, and very touchingly asked forgiveness. вЂI once jumped over
a puddle when I was a child,вЂ™ she said, вЂand injured my leg.вЂ™ He he!вЂќ

Kalganov went off into the most childish laughter, almost falling on the
sofa. Grushenka, too, laughed. Mitya was at the pinnacle of happiness.

вЂњDo you know, thatвЂ™s the truth, heвЂ™s not lying now,вЂќ exclaimed Kalganov,
turning to Mitya; вЂњand do you know, heвЂ™s been married twice; itвЂ™s his
first wife heвЂ™s talking about. But his second wife, do you know, ran away,
and is alive now.вЂќ

вЂњIs it possible?вЂќ said Mitya, turning quickly to Maximov with an
expression of the utmost astonishment.

вЂњYes. She did run away. IвЂ™ve had that unpleasant experience,вЂќ Maximov
modestly assented, вЂњwith a _monsieur_. And what was worse, sheвЂ™d had all
my little property transferred to her beforehand. вЂYouвЂ™re an educated
man,вЂ™ she said to me. вЂYou can always get your living.вЂ™ She settled my
business with that. A venerable bishop once said to me: вЂOne of your wives
was lame, but the other was too lightвЂђfooted.вЂ™ He he!вЂќ

вЂњListen, listen!вЂќ cried Kalganov, bubbling over, вЂњif heвЂ™s telling liesвЂ”and
he often isвЂ”heвЂ™s only doing it to amuse us all. ThereвЂ™s no harm in that,
is there? You know, I sometimes like him. HeвЂ™s awfully low, but itвЂ™s
natural to him, eh? DonвЂ™t you think so? Some people are low from selfвЂђ
interest, but heвЂ™s simply so, from nature. Only fancy, he claims (he was
arguing about it all the way yesterday) that Gogol wrote _Dead Souls_
about him. Do you remember, thereвЂ™s a landowner called Maximov in it, whom
Nozdryov thrashed. He was charged, do you remember, вЂfor inflicting bodily
injury with rods on the landowner Maximov in a drunken condition.вЂ™ Would
you believe it, he claims that he was that Maximov and that he was beaten!
Now can it be so? Tchitchikov made his journey, at the very latest, at the
beginning of the twenties, so that the dates donвЂ™t fit. He couldnвЂ™t have
been thrashed then, he couldnвЂ™t, could he?вЂќ

It was difficult to imagine what Kalganov was excited about, but his
excitement was genuine. Mitya followed his lead without protest.

вЂњWell, but if they did thrash him!вЂќ he cried, laughing.

вЂњItвЂ™s not that they thrashed me exactly, but what I mean isвЂ”вЂќ put in
Maximov.

вЂњWhat do you mean? Either they thrashed you or they didnвЂ™t.вЂќ

вЂњWhat oвЂ™clock is it, _panie_?вЂќ the Pole, with the pipe, asked his tall
friend, with a bored expression. The other shrugged his shoulders in
reply. Neither of them had a watch.

вЂњWhy not talk? Let other people talk. MustnвЂ™t other people talk because
youвЂ™re bored?вЂќ Grushenka flew at him with evident intention of finding
fault. Something seemed for the first time to flash upon MityaвЂ™s mind.
This time the Pole answered with unmistakable irritability.

вЂњ_Pani_, I didnвЂ™t oppose it. I didnвЂ™t say anything.вЂќ

вЂњAll right then. Come, tell us your story,вЂќ Grushenka cried to Maximov.
вЂњWhy are you all silent?вЂќ

вЂњThereвЂ™s nothing to tell, itвЂ™s all so foolish,вЂќ answered Maximov at once,
with evident satisfaction, mincing a little. вЂњBesides, all thatвЂ™s by way
of allegory in Gogol, for heвЂ™s made all the names have a meaning. Nozdryov
was really called Nosov, and Kuvshinikov had quite a different name, he
was called Shkvornev. Fenardi really was called Fenardi, only he wasnвЂ™t an
Italian but a Russian, and Mamsel Fenardi was a pretty girl with her
pretty little legs in tights, and she had a little short skirt with
spangles, and she kept turning round and round, only not for four hours
but for four minutes only, and she bewitched every one...вЂќ

вЂњBut what were you beaten for?вЂќ cried Kalganov.

вЂњFor Piron!вЂќ answered Maximov.

вЂњWhat Piron?вЂќ cried Mitya.

вЂњThe famous French writer, Piron. We were all drinking then, a big party
of us, in a tavern at that very fair. TheyвЂ™d invited me, and first of all
I began quoting epigrams. вЂIs that you, Boileau? What a funny getвЂђup!вЂ™ and
Boileau answers that heвЂ™s going to a masquerade, that is to the baths, he
he! And they took it to themselves, so I made haste to repeat another,
very sarcastic, well known to all educated people:


    Yes, Sappho and Phaon are we!
    But one grief is weighing on me.
    You donвЂ™t know your way to the sea!


They were still more offended and began abusing me in the most unseemly
way for it. And as illвЂђluck would have it, to set things right, I began
telling a very cultivated anecdote about Piron, how he was not accepted
into the French Academy, and to revenge himself wrote his own epitaph:


    CiвЂђgГ®t Piron qui ne fut rien,
    Pas mГЄme acadГ©micien.


They seized me and thrashed me.вЂќ

вЂњBut what for? What for?вЂќ

вЂњFor my education. People can thrash a man for anything,вЂќ Maximov
concluded, briefly and sententiously.

вЂњEh, thatвЂ™s enough! ThatвЂ™s all stupid, I donвЂ™t want to listen. I thought
it would be amusing,вЂќ Grushenka cut them short, suddenly.

Mitya started, and at once left off laughing. The tall Pole rose upon his
feet, and with the haughty air of a man, bored and out of his element,
began pacing from corner to corner of the room, his hands behind his back.

вЂњAh, he canвЂ™t sit still,вЂќ said Grushenka, looking at him contemptuously.
Mitya began to feel anxious. He noticed besides, that the Pole on the sofa
was looking at him with an irritable expression.

вЂњ_Panie!_вЂќ cried Mitya, вЂњletвЂ™s drink! and the other _pan_, too! Let us
drink.вЂќ

In a flash he had pulled three glasses towards him, and filled them with
champagne.

вЂњTo Poland, _panovie_, I drink to your Poland!вЂќ cried Mitya.

вЂњI shall be delighted, _panie_,вЂќ said the Pole on the sofa, with dignity
and affable condescension, and he took his glass.

вЂњAnd the other _pan_, whatвЂ™s his name? Drink, most illustrious, take your
glass!вЂќ Mitya urged.

вЂњPan Vrublevsky,вЂќ put in the Pole on the sofa.

Pan Vrublevsky came up to the table, swaying as he walked.

вЂњTo Poland, _panovie!_вЂќ cried Mitya, raising his glass. вЂњHurrah!вЂќ

All three drank. Mitya seized the bottle and again poured out three
glasses.

вЂњNow to Russia, _panovie_, and let us be brothers!вЂќ

вЂњPour out some for us,вЂќ said Grushenka; вЂњIвЂ™ll drink to Russia, too!вЂќ

вЂњSo will I,вЂќ said Kalganov.

вЂњAnd I would, too ... to Russia, the old grandmother!вЂќ tittered Maximov.

вЂњAll! All!вЂќ cried Mitya. вЂњTrifon Borissovitch, some more bottles!вЂќ

The other three bottles Mitya had brought with him were put on the table.
Mitya filled the glasses.

вЂњTo Russia! Hurrah!вЂќ he shouted again. All drank the toast except the
Poles, and Grushenka tossed off her whole glass at once. The Poles did not
touch theirs.

вЂњHowвЂ™s this, _panovie_?вЂќ cried Mitya, вЂњwonвЂ™t you drink it?вЂќ

Pan Vrublevsky took the glass, raised it and said with a resonant voice:

вЂњTo Russia as she was before 1772.вЂќ

вЂњCome, thatвЂ™s better!вЂќ cried the other Pole, and they both emptied their
glasses at once.

вЂњYouвЂ™re fools, you _panovie_,вЂќ broke suddenly from Mitya.

вЂњ_Panie!_вЂќ shouted both the Poles, menacingly, setting on Mitya like a
couple of cocks. Pan Vrublevsky was specially furious.

вЂњCan one help loving oneвЂ™s own country?вЂќ he shouted.

вЂњBe silent! DonвЂ™t quarrel! I wonвЂ™t have any quarreling!вЂќ cried Grushenka
imperiously, and she stamped her foot on the floor. Her face glowed, her
eyes were shining. The effects of the glass she had just drunk were
apparent. Mitya was terribly alarmed.

вЂњ_Panovie_, forgive me! It was my fault, IвЂ™m sorry. Vrublevsky, _panie_
Vrublevsky, IвЂ™m sorry.вЂќ

вЂњHold your tongue, you, anyway! Sit down, you stupid!вЂќ Grushenka scolded
with angry annoyance.

Every one sat down, all were silent, looking at one another.

вЂњGentlemen, I was the cause of it all,вЂќ Mitya began again, unable to make
anything of GrushenkaвЂ™s words. вЂњCome, why are we sitting here? What shall
we do ... to amuse ourselves again?вЂќ

вЂњAch, itвЂ™s certainly anything but amusing!вЂќ Kalganov mumbled lazily.

вЂњLetвЂ™s play faro again, as we did just now,вЂќ Maximov tittered suddenly.

вЂњFaro? Splendid!вЂќ cried Mitya. вЂњIf only the _panovie_вЂ”вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s lite, _panovie_,вЂќ the Pole on the sofa responded, as it were
unwillingly.

вЂњThatвЂ™s true,вЂќ assented Pan Vrublevsky.

вЂњLite? What do you mean by вЂliteвЂ™?вЂќ asked Grushenka.

вЂњLate, _pani_! вЂa late hourвЂ™ I mean,вЂќ the Pole on the sofa explained.

вЂњItвЂ™s always late with them. They can never do anything!вЂќ Grushenka almost
shrieked in her anger. вЂњTheyвЂ™re dull themselves, so they want others to be
dull. Before you came, Mitya, they were just as silent and kept turning up
their noses at me.вЂќ

вЂњMy goddess!вЂќ cried the Pole on the sofa, вЂњI see youвЂ™re not wellвЂђdisposed
to me, thatвЂ™s why IвЂ™m gloomy. IвЂ™m ready, _panie_,вЂќ added he, addressing
Mitya.

вЂњBegin, _panie_,вЂќ Mitya assented, pulling his notes out of his pocket, and
laying two hundredвЂђrouble notes on the table. вЂњI want to lose a lot to
you. Take your cards. Make the bank.вЂќ

вЂњWeвЂ™ll have cards from the landlord, _panie_,вЂќ said the little Pole,
gravely and emphatically.

вЂњThatвЂ™s much the best way,вЂќ chimed in Pan Vrublevsky.

вЂњFrom the landlord? Very good, I understand, letвЂ™s get them from him.
Cards!вЂќ Mitya shouted to the landlord.

The landlord brought in a new, unopened pack, and informed Mitya that the
girls were getting ready, and that the Jews with the cymbals would most
likely be here soon; but the cart with the provisions had not yet arrived.
Mitya jumped up from the table and ran into the next room to give orders,
but only three girls had arrived, and Marya was not there yet. And he did
not know himself what orders to give and why he had run out. He only told
them to take out of the box the presents for the girls, the sweets, the
toffee and the fondants. вЂњAnd vodka for Andrey, vodka for Andrey!вЂќ he
cried in haste. вЂњI was rude to Andrey!вЂќ

Suddenly Maximov, who had followed him out, touched him on the shoulder.

вЂњGive me five roubles,вЂќ he whispered to Mitya. вЂњIвЂ™ll stake something at
faro, too, he he!вЂќ

вЂњCapital! Splendid! Take ten, here!вЂќ

Again he took all the notes out of his pocket and picked out one for ten
roubles. вЂњAnd if you lose that, come again, come again.вЂќ

вЂњVery good,вЂќ Maximov whispered joyfully, and he ran back again. Mitya,
too, returned, apologizing for having kept them waiting. The Poles had
already sat down, and opened the pack. They looked much more amiable,
almost cordial. The Pole on the sofa had lighted another pipe and was
preparing to throw. He wore an air of solemnity.

вЂњTo your places, gentlemen,вЂќ cried Pan Vrublevsky.

вЂњNo, IвЂ™m not going to play any more,вЂќ observed Kalganov, вЂњIвЂ™ve lost fifty
roubles to them just now.вЂќ

вЂњThe _pan_ had no luck, perhaps heвЂ™ll be lucky this time,вЂќ the Pole on the
sofa observed in his direction.

вЂњHow much in the bank? To correspond?вЂќ asked Mitya.

вЂњThatвЂ™s according, _panie_, maybe a hundred, maybe two hundred, as much as
you will stake.вЂќ

вЂњA million!вЂќ laughed Mitya.

вЂњThe Pan Captain has heard of Pan Podvysotsky, perhaps?вЂќ

вЂњWhat Podvysotsky?вЂќ

вЂњIn Warsaw there was a bank and any one comes and stakes against it.
Podvysotsky comes, sees a thousand gold pieces, stakes against the bank.
The banker says, вЂ_Panie_ Podvysotsky, are you laying down the gold, or
must we trust to your honor?вЂ™ вЂTo my honor, _panie_,вЂ™ says Podvysotsky.
вЂSo much the better.вЂ™ The banker throws the dice. Podvysotsky wins. вЂTake
it, _panie_,вЂ™ says the banker, and pulling out the drawer he gives him a
million. вЂTake it, _panie_, this is your gain.вЂ™ There was a million in the
bank. вЂI didnвЂ™t know that,вЂ™ says Podvysotsky. вЂ_Panie_ Podvysotsky,вЂ™ said
the banker, вЂyou pledged your honor and we pledged ours.вЂ™ Podvysotsky took
the million.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s not true,вЂќ said Kalganov.

вЂњ_Panie_ Kalganov, in gentlemanly society one doesnвЂ™t say such things.вЂќ

вЂњAs if a Polish gambler would give away a million!вЂќ cried Mitya, but
checked himself at once. вЂњForgive me, _panie_, itвЂ™s my fault again, he
would, he would give away a million, for honor, for Polish honor. You see
how I talk Polish, ha ha! Here, I stake ten roubles, the knave leads.вЂќ

вЂњAnd I put a rouble on the queen, the queen of hearts, the pretty little
_panienotchka_, he he!вЂќ laughed Maximov, pulling out his queen, and, as
though trying to conceal it from every one, he moved right up and crossed
himself hurriedly under the table. Mitya won. The rouble won, too.

вЂњA corner!вЂќ cried Mitya.

вЂњIвЂ™ll bet another rouble, a вЂsingleвЂ™ stake,вЂќ Maximov muttered gleefully,
hugely delighted at having won a rouble.

вЂњLost!вЂќ shouted Mitya. вЂњA вЂdoubleвЂ™ on the seven!вЂќ

The seven too was trumped.

вЂњStop!вЂќ cried Kalganov suddenly.

вЂњDouble! Double!вЂќ Mitya doubled his stakes, and each time he doubled the
stake, the card he doubled was trumped by the Poles. The rouble stakes
kept winning.

вЂњOn the double!вЂќ shouted Mitya furiously.

вЂњYouвЂ™ve lost two hundred, _panie_. Will you stake another hundred?вЂќ the
Pole on the sofa inquired.

вЂњWhat? Lost two hundred already? Then another two hundred! All doubles!вЂќ

And pulling his money out of his pocket, Mitya was about to fling two
hundred roubles on the queen, but Kalganov covered it with his hand.

вЂњThatвЂ™s enough!вЂќ he shouted in his ringing voice.

вЂњWhatвЂ™s the matter?вЂќ Mitya stared at him.

вЂњThatвЂ™s enough! I donвЂ™t want you to play any more. DonвЂ™t!вЂќ

вЂњWhy?вЂќ

вЂњBecause I donвЂ™t. Hang it, come away. ThatвЂ™s why. I wonвЂ™t let you go on
playing.вЂќ

Mitya gazed at him in astonishment.

вЂњGive it up, Mitya. He may be right. YouвЂ™ve lost a lot as it is,вЂќ said
Grushenka, with a curious note in her voice. Both the Poles rose from
their seats with a deeply offended air.

вЂњAre you joking, _panie_?вЂќ said the short man, looking severely at
Kalganov.

вЂњHow dare you!вЂќ Pan Vrublevsky, too, growled at Kalganov.

вЂњDonвЂ™t dare to shout like that,вЂќ cried Grushenka. вЂњAh, you turkeyвЂђcocks!вЂќ

Mitya looked at each of them in turn. But something in GrushenkaвЂ™s face
suddenly struck him, and at the same instant something new flashed into
his mindвЂ”a strange new thought!

вЂњ_Pani_ Agrippina,вЂќ the little Pole was beginning, crimson with anger,
when Mitya suddenly went up to him and slapped him on the shoulder.

вЂњMost illustrious, two words with you.вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you want?вЂќ

вЂњIn the next room, IвЂ™ve two words to say to you, something pleasant, very
pleasant. YouвЂ™ll be glad to hear it.вЂќ

The little _pan_ was taken aback and looked apprehensively at Mitya. He
agreed at once, however, on condition that Pan Vrublevsky went with them.

вЂњThe bodyguard? Let him come, and I want him, too. I must have him!вЂќ cried
Mitya. вЂњMarch, _panovie_!вЂќ

вЂњWhere are you going?вЂќ asked Grushenka, anxiously.

вЂњWeвЂ™ll be back in one moment,вЂќ answered Mitya.

There was a sort of boldness, a sudden confidence shining in his eyes. His
face had looked very different when he entered the room an hour before.

He led the Poles, not into the large room where the chorus of girls was
assembling and the table was being laid, but into the bedroom on the
right, where the trunks and packages were kept, and there were two large
beds, with pyramids of cotton pillows on each. There was a lighted candle
on a small deal table in the corner. The small man and Mitya sat down to
this table, facing each other, while the huge Vrublevsky stood beside
them, his hands behind his back. The Poles looked severe but were
evidently inquisitive.

вЂњWhat can I do for you, _panie_?вЂќ lisped the little Pole.

вЂњWell, look here, _panie_, I wonвЂ™t keep you long. ThereвЂ™s money for you,вЂќ
he pulled out his notes. вЂњWould you like three thousand? Take it and go
your way.вЂќ

The Pole gazed openвЂђeyed at Mitya, with a searching look.

вЂњThree thousand, _panie_?вЂќ He exchanged glances with Vrublevsky.

вЂњThree, _panovie_, three! Listen, _panie_, I see youвЂ™re a sensible man.
Take three thousand and go to the devil, and Vrublevsky with youвЂ”dвЂ™you
hear? But, at once, this very minute, and for ever. You understand that,
_panie_, for ever. HereвЂ™s the door, you go out of it. What have you got
there, a greatвЂђcoat, a fur coat? IвЂ™ll bring it out to you. TheyвЂ™ll get the
horses out directly, and thenвЂ”goodвЂђby, _panie_!вЂќ

Mitya awaited an answer with assurance. He had no doubts. An expression of
extraordinary resolution passed over the PoleвЂ™s face.

вЂњAnd the money, _panie_?вЂќ

вЂњThe money, _panie_? Five hundred roubles IвЂ™ll give you this moment for
the journey, and as a first installment, and two thousand five hundred toвЂђ
morrow, in the townвЂ”I swear on my honor, IвЂ™ll get it, IвЂ™ll get it at any
cost!вЂќ cried Mitya.

The Poles exchanged glances again. The short manвЂ™s face looked more
forbidding.

вЂњSeven hundred, seven hundred, not five hundred, at once, this minute,
cash down!вЂќ Mitya added, feeling something wrong. вЂњWhatвЂ™s the matter,
_panie_? DonвЂ™t you trust me? I canвЂ™t give you the whole three thousand
straight off. If I give it, you may come back to her toвЂђmorrow....
Besides, I havenвЂ™t the three thousand with me. IвЂ™ve got it at home in the
town,вЂќ faltered Mitya, his spirit sinking at every word he uttered. вЂњUpon
my word, the moneyвЂ™s there, hidden.вЂќ

In an instant an extraordinary sense of personal dignity showed itself in
the little manвЂ™s face.

вЂњWhat next?вЂќ he asked ironically. вЂњFor shame!вЂќ and he spat on the floor.
Pan Vrublevsky spat too.

вЂњYou do that, _panie_,вЂќ said Mitya, recognizing with despair that all was
over, вЂњbecause you hope to make more out of Grushenka? YouвЂ™re a couple of
capons, thatвЂ™s what you are!вЂќ

вЂњThis is a mortal insult!вЂќ The little Pole turned as red as a crab, and he
went out of the room, briskly, as though unwilling to hear another word.
Vrublevsky swung out after him, and Mitya followed, confused and
crestfallen. He was afraid of Grushenka, afraid that the _pan_ would at
once raise an outcry. And so indeed he did. The Pole walked into the room
and threw himself in a theatrical attitude before Grushenka.

вЂњ_Pani_ Agrippina, I have received a mortal insult!вЂќ he exclaimed. But
Grushenka suddenly lost all patience, as though they had wounded her in
the tenderest spot.

вЂњSpeak Russian! Speak Russian!вЂќ she cried, вЂњnot another word of Polish!
You used to talk Russian. You canвЂ™t have forgotten it in five years.вЂќ

She was red with passion.

вЂњ_Pani_ AgrippinaвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњMy nameвЂ™s Agrafena, Grushenka, speak Russian or I wonвЂ™t listen!вЂќ

The Pole gasped with offended dignity, and quickly and pompously delivered
himself in broken Russian:

вЂњ_Pani_ Agrafena, I came here to forget the past and forgive it, to forget
all that has happened till toвЂђdayвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњForgive? Came here to forgive me?вЂќ Grushenka cut him short, jumping up
from her seat.

вЂњJust so, _pani_, IвЂ™m not pusillanimous, IвЂ™m magnanimous. But I was
astounded when I saw your lovers. Pan Mitya offered me three thousand, in
the other room to depart. I spat in the _panвЂ™s_ face.вЂќ

вЂњWhat? He offered you money for me?вЂќ cried Grushenka, hysterically. вЂњIs it
true, Mitya? How dare you? Am I for sale?вЂќ

вЂњ_Panie, panie!_вЂќ yelled Mitya, вЂњsheвЂ™s pure and shining, and I have never
been her lover! ThatвЂ™s a lie....вЂќ

вЂњHow dare you defend me to him?вЂќ shrieked Grushenka. вЂњIt wasnвЂ™t virtue
kept me pure, and it wasnвЂ™t that I was afraid of Kuzma, but that I might
hold up my head when I met him, and tell him heвЂ™s a scoundrel. And he did
actually refuse the money?вЂќ

вЂњHe took it! He took it!вЂќ cried Mitya; вЂњonly he wanted to get the whole
three thousand at once, and I could only give him seven hundred straight
off.вЂќ

вЂњI see: he heard I had money, and came here to marry me!вЂќ

вЂњ_Pani_ Agrippina!вЂќ cried the little Pole. вЂњIвЂ™mвЂ”a knight, IвЂ™mвЂ”a nobleman,
and not a _lajdak_. I came here to make you my wife and I find you a
different woman, perverse and shameless.вЂќ

вЂњOh, go back where you came from! IвЂ™ll tell them to turn you out and
youвЂ™ll be turned out,вЂќ cried Grushenka, furious. вЂњIвЂ™ve been a fool, a
fool, to have been miserable these five years! And it wasnвЂ™t for his sake,
it was my anger made me miserable. And this isnвЂ™t he at all! Was he like
this? It might be his father! Where did you get your wig from? He was a
falcon, but this is a gander. He used to laugh and sing to me.... And IвЂ™ve
been crying for five years, damned fool, abject, shameless I was!вЂќ

She sank back in her low chair and hid her face in her hands. At that
instant the chorus of Mokroe began singing in the room on the leftвЂ”a
rollicking dance song.

вЂњA regular Sodom!вЂќ Vrublevsky roared suddenly. вЂњLandlord, send the
shameless hussies away!вЂќ

The landlord, who had been for some time past inquisitively peeping in at
the door, hearing shouts and guessing that his guests were quarreling, at
once entered the room.

вЂњWhat are you shouting for? DвЂ™you want to split your throat?вЂќ he said,
addressing Vrublevsky, with surprising rudeness.

вЂњAnimal!вЂќ bellowed Pan Vrublevsky.

вЂњAnimal? And what sort of cards were you playing with just now? I gave you
a pack and you hid it. You played with marked cards! I could send you to
Siberia for playing with false cards, dвЂ™you know that, for itвЂ™s just the
same as false banknotes....вЂќ

And going up to the sofa he thrust his fingers between the sofa back and
the cushion, and pulled out an unopened pack of cards.

вЂњHereвЂ™s my pack unopened!вЂќ

He held it up and showed it to all in the room. вЂњFrom where I stood I saw
him slip my pack away, and put his in place of itвЂ”youвЂ™re a cheat and not a
gentleman!вЂќ

вЂњAnd I twice saw the _pan_ change a card!вЂќ cried Kalganov.

вЂњHow shameful! How shameful!вЂќ exclaimed Grushenka, clasping her hands, and
blushing for genuine shame. вЂњGood Lord, heвЂ™s come to that!вЂќ

вЂњI thought so, too!вЂќ said Mitya. But before he had uttered the words,
Vrublevsky, with a confused and infuriated face, shook his fist at
Grushenka, shouting:

вЂњYou low harlot!вЂќ

Mitya flew at him at once, clutched him in both hands, lifted him in the
air, and in one instant had carried him into the room on the right, from
which they had just come.

вЂњIвЂ™ve laid him on the floor, there,вЂќ he announced, returning at once,
gasping with excitement. вЂњHeвЂ™s struggling, the scoundrel! But he wonвЂ™t
come back, no fear of that!...вЂќ

He closed one half of the folding doors, and holding the other ajar called
out to the little Pole:

вЂњMost illustrious, will you be pleased to retire as well?вЂќ

вЂњMy dear Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ said Trifon Borissovitch, вЂњmake them give
you back the money you lost. ItвЂ™s as good as stolen from you.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t want my fifty roubles back,вЂќ Kalganov declared suddenly.

вЂњI donвЂ™t want my two hundred, either,вЂќ cried Mitya, вЂњI wouldnвЂ™t take it
for anything! Let him keep it as a consolation.вЂќ

вЂњBravo, Mitya! YouвЂ™re a trump, Mitya!вЂќ cried Grushenka, and there was a
note of fierce anger in the exclamation.

The little _pan_, crimson with fury but still mindful of his dignity, was
making for the door, but he stopped short and said suddenly, addressing
Grushenka:

вЂњ_Pani_, if you want to come with me, come. If not, goodвЂђby.вЂќ

And swelling with indignation and importance he went to the door. This was
a man of character: he had so good an opinion of himself that after all
that had passed, he still expected that she would marry him. Mitya slammed
the door after him.

вЂњLock it,вЂќ said Kalganov. But the key clicked on the other side, they had
locked it from within.

вЂњThatвЂ™s capital!вЂќ exclaimed Grushenka relentlessly. вЂњServe them right!вЂќ



Chapter VIII. Delirium


What followed was almost an orgy, a feast to which all were welcome.
Grushenka was the first to call for wine.

вЂњI want to drink. I want to be quite drunk, as we were before. Do you
remember, Mitya, do you remember how we made friends here last time!вЂќ

Mitya himself was almost delirious, feeling that his happiness was at
hand. But Grushenka was continually sending him away from her.

вЂњGo and enjoy yourself. Tell them to dance, to make merry, вЂlet the stove
and cottage danceвЂ™; as we had it last time,вЂќ she kept exclaiming. She was
tremendously excited. And Mitya hastened to obey her. The chorus were in
the next room. The room in which they had been sitting till that moment
was too small, and was divided in two by cotton curtains, behind which was
a huge bed with a puffy feather mattress and a pyramid of cotton pillows.
In the four rooms for visitors there were beds. Grushenka settled herself
just at the door. Mitya set an easy chair for her. She had sat in the same
place to watch the dancing and singing вЂњthe time before,вЂќ when they had
made merry there. All the girls who had come had been there then; the
Jewish band with fiddles and zithers had come, too, and at last the long
expected cart had arrived with the wines and provisions.

Mitya bustled about. All sorts of people began coming into the room to
look on, peasants and their women, who had been roused from sleep and
attracted by the hopes of another marvelous entertainment such as they had
enjoyed a month before. Mitya remembered their faces, greeting and
embracing every one he knew. He uncorked bottles and poured out wine for
every one who presented himself. Only the girls were very eager for the
champagne. The men preferred rum, brandy, and, above all, hot punch. Mitya
had chocolate made for all the girls, and ordered that three samovars
should be kept boiling all night to provide tea and punch for everyone to
help himself.

An absurd chaotic confusion followed, but Mitya was in his natural
element, and the more foolish it became, the more his spirits rose. If the
peasants had asked him for money at that moment, he would have pulled out
his notes and given them away right and left. This was probably why the
landlord, Trifon Borissovitch, kept hovering about Mitya to protect him.
He seemed to have given up all idea of going to bed that night; but he
drank little, only one glass of punch, and kept a sharp lookвЂђout on
MityaвЂ™s interests after his own fashion. He intervened in the nick of
time, civilly and obsequiously persuading Mitya not to give away вЂњcigars
and Rhine wine,вЂќ and, above all, money to the peasants as he had done
before. He was very indignant, too, at the peasant girls drinking liqueur,
and eating sweets.

вЂњTheyвЂ™re a lousy lot, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ he said. вЂњIвЂ™d give them a
kick, every one of them, and theyвЂ™d take it as an honorвЂ”thatвЂ™s all theyвЂ™re
worth!вЂќ

Mitya remembered Andrey again, and ordered punch to be sent out to him. вЂњI
was rude to him just now,вЂќ he repeated with a sinking, softened voice.
Kalganov did not want to drink, and at first did not care for the girlsвЂ™
singing; but after he had drunk a couple of glasses of champagne he became
extraordinarily lively, strolling about the room, laughing and praising
the music and the songs, admiring every one and everything. Maximov,
blissfully drunk, never left his side. Grushenka, too, was beginning to
get drunk. Pointing to Kalganov, she said to Mitya:

вЂњWhat a dear, charming boy he is!вЂќ

And Mitya, delighted, ran to kiss Kalganov and Maximov. Oh, great were his
hopes! She had said nothing yet, and seemed, indeed, purposely to refrain
from speaking. But she looked at him from time to time with caressing and
passionate eyes. At last she suddenly gripped his hand and drew him
vigorously to her. She was sitting at the moment in the low chair by the
door.

вЂњHow was it you came just now, eh? Have you walked in!... I was
frightened. So you wanted to give me up to him, did you? Did you really
want to?вЂќ

вЂњI didnвЂ™t want to spoil your happiness!вЂќ Mitya faltered blissfully. But
she did not need his answer.

вЂњWell, go and enjoy yourself ...вЂќ she sent him away once more. вЂњDonвЂ™t cry,
IвЂ™ll call you back again.вЂќ

He would run away, and she listened to the singing and looked at the
dancing, though her eyes followed him wherever he went. But in another
quarter of an hour she would call him once more and again he would run
back to her.

вЂњCome, sit beside me, tell me, how did you hear about me, and my coming
here yesterday? From whom did you first hear it?вЂќ

And Mitya began telling her all about it, disconnectedly, incoherently,
feverishly. He spoke strangely, often frowning, and stopping abruptly.

вЂњWhat are you frowning at?вЂќ she asked.

вЂњNothing.... I left a man ill there. IвЂ™d give ten years of my life for him
to get well, to know he was all right!вЂќ

вЂњWell, never mind him, if heвЂ™s ill. So you meant to shoot yourself toвЂђ
morrow! What a silly boy! What for? I like such reckless fellows as you,вЂќ
she lisped, with a rather halting tongue. вЂњSo you would go any length for
me, eh? Did you really mean to shoot yourself toвЂђmorrow, you stupid? No,
wait a little. ToвЂђmorrow I may have something to say to you.... I wonвЂ™t
say it toвЂђday, but toвЂђmorrow. YouвЂ™d like it to be toвЂђday? No, I donвЂ™t want
to toвЂђday. Come, go along now, go and amuse yourself.вЂќ

Once, however, she called him, as it were, puzzled and uneasy.

вЂњWhy are you sad? I see youвЂ™re sad.... Yes, I see it,вЂќ she added, looking
intently into his eyes. вЂњThough you keep kissing the peasants and
shouting, I see something. No, be merry. IвЂ™m merry; you be merry, too....
I love somebody here. Guess who it is. Ah, look, my boy has fallen asleep,
poor dear, heвЂ™s drunk.вЂќ

She meant Kalganov. He was, in fact, drunk, and had dropped asleep for a
moment, sitting on the sofa. But he was not merely drowsy from drink; he
felt suddenly dejected, or, as he said, вЂњbored.вЂќ He was intensely
depressed by the girlsвЂ™ songs, which, as the drinking went on, gradually
became coarse and more reckless. And the dances were as bad. Two girls
dressed up as bears, and a lively girl, called Stepanida, with a stick in
her hand, acted the part of keeper, and began to вЂњshow them.вЂќ

вЂњLook alive, Marya, or youвЂ™ll get the stick!вЂќ

The bears rolled on the ground at last in the most unseemly fashion, amid
roars of laughter from the closelyвЂђpacked crowd of men and women.

вЂњWell, let them! Let them!вЂќ said Grushenka sententiously, with an ecstatic
expression on her face. вЂњWhen they do get a day to enjoy themselves, why
shouldnвЂ™t folks be happy?вЂќ

Kalganov looked as though he had been besmirched with dirt.

вЂњItвЂ™s swinish, all this peasant foolery,вЂќ he murmured, moving away; вЂњitвЂ™s
the game they play when itвЂ™s light all night in summer.вЂќ

He particularly disliked one вЂњnewвЂќ song to a jaunty danceвЂђtune. It
described how a gentleman came and tried his luck with the girls, to see
whether they would love him:


    The master came to try the girls:
    Would they love him, would they not?


But the girls could not love the master:


    He would beat me cruelly
    And such love wonвЂ™t do for me.


Then a gypsy comes along and he, too, tries:


    The gypsy came to try the girls:
    Would they love him, would they not?


But they couldnвЂ™t love the gypsy either:


    He would be a thief, I fear,
    And would cause me many a tear.


And many more men come to try their luck, among them a soldier:


    The soldier came to try the girls:
    Would they love him, would they not?


But the soldier is rejected with contempt, in two indecent lines, sung
with absolute frankness and producing a furore in the audience. The song
ends with a merchant:


    The merchant came to try the girls:
    Would they love him, would they not?


And it appears that he wins their love because:


    The merchant will make gold for me
    And his queen IвЂ™ll gladly be.


Kalvanov was positively indignant.

вЂњThatвЂ™s just a song of yesterday,вЂќ he said aloud. вЂњWho writes such things
for them? They might just as well have had a railwayman or a Jew come to
try his luck with the girls; theyвЂ™d have carried all before them.вЂќ

And, almost as though it were a personal affront, he declared, on the
spot, that he was bored, sat down on the sofa and immediately fell asleep.
His pretty little face looked rather pale, as it fell back on the sofa
cushion.

вЂњLook how pretty he is,вЂќ said Grushenka, taking Mitya up to him. вЂњI was
combing his hair just now; his hairвЂ™s like flax, and so thick....вЂќ

And, bending over him tenderly, she kissed his forehead. Kalganov
instantly opened his eyes, looked at her, stood up, and with the most
anxious air inquired where was Maximov?

вЂњSo thatвЂ™s who it is you want.вЂќ Grushenka laughed. вЂњStay with me a minute.
Mitya, run and find his Maximov.вЂќ

Maximov, it appeared, could not tear himself away from the girls, only
running away from time to time to pour himself out a glass of liqueur. He
had drunk two cups of chocolate. His face was red, and his nose was
crimson; his eyes were moist and mawkishly sweet. He ran up and announced
that he was going to dance the вЂњsabotiГЁre.вЂќ

вЂњThey taught me all those wellвЂђbred, aristocratic dances when I was
little....вЂќ

вЂњGo, go with him, Mitya, and IвЂ™ll watch from here how he dances,вЂќ said
Grushenka.

вЂњNo, no, IвЂ™m coming to look on, too,вЂќ exclaimed Kalganov, brushing aside
in the most naГЇve way GrushenkaвЂ™s offer to sit with him. They all went to
look on. Maximov danced his dance. But it roused no great admiration in
any one but Mitya. It consisted of nothing but skipping and hopping,
kicking up the feet, and at every skip Maximov slapped the upturned sole
of his foot. Kalganov did not like it at all, but Mitya kissed the dancer.

вЂњThanks. YouвЂ™re tired perhaps? What are you looking for here? Would you
like some sweets? A cigar, perhaps?вЂќ

вЂњA cigarette.вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t you want a drink?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll just have a liqueur.... Have you any chocolates?вЂќ

вЂњYes, thereвЂ™s a heap of them on the table there. Choose one, my dear
soul!вЂќ

вЂњI like one with vanilla ... for old people. He he!вЂќ

вЂњNo, brother, weвЂ™ve none of that special sort.вЂќ

вЂњI say,вЂќ the old man bent down to whisper in MityaвЂ™s ear. вЂњThat girl
there, little Marya, he he! How would it be if you were to help me make
friends with her?вЂќ

вЂњSo thatвЂ™s what youвЂ™re after! No, brother, that wonвЂ™t do!вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™d do no harm to any one,вЂќ Maximov muttered disconsolately.

вЂњOh, all right, all right. They only come here to dance and sing, you
know, brother. But damn it all, wait a bit!... Eat and drink and be merry,
meanwhile. DonвЂ™t you want money?вЂќ

вЂњLater on, perhaps,вЂќ smiled Maximov.

вЂњAll right, all right....вЂќ

MityaвЂ™s head was burning. He went outside to the wooden balcony which ran
round the whole building on the inner side, overlooking the courtyard. The
fresh air revived him. He stood alone in a dark corner, and suddenly
clutched his head in both hands. His scattered thoughts came together; his
sensations blended into a whole and threw a sudden light into his mind. A
fearful and terrible light! вЂњIf IвЂ™m to shoot myself, why not now?вЂќ passed
through his mind. вЂњWhy not go for the pistols, bring them here, and here,
in this dark dirty corner, make an end?вЂќ Almost a minute he stood,
undecided. A few hours earlier, when he had been dashing here, he was
pursued by disgrace, by the theft he had committed, and that blood, that
blood!... But yet it was easier for him then. Then everything was over: he
had lost her, given her up. She was gone, for himвЂ”oh, then his death
sentence had been easier for him; at least it had seemed necessary,
inevitable, for what had he to stay on earth for?

But now? Was it the same as then? Now one phantom, one terror at least was
at an end: that first, rightful lover, that fateful figure had vanished,
leaving no trace. The terrible phantom had turned into something so small,
so comic; it had been carried into the bedroom and locked in. It would
never return. She was ashamed, and from her eyes he could see now whom she
loved. Now he had everything to make life happy ... but he could not go on
living, he could not; oh, damnation! вЂњO God! restore to life the man I
knocked down at the fence! Let this fearful cup pass from me! Lord, thou
hast wrought miracles for such sinners as me! But what, what if the old
manвЂ™s alive? Oh, then the shame of the other disgrace I would wipe away. I
would restore the stolen money. IвЂ™d give it back; IвЂ™d get it somehow....
No trace of that shame will remain except in my heart for ever! But no,
no; oh, impossible cowardly dreams! Oh, damnation!вЂќ

Yet there was a ray of light and hope in his darkness. He jumped up and
ran back to the roomвЂ”to her, to her, his queen for ever! Was not one
moment of her love worth all the rest of life, even in the agonies of
disgrace? This wild question clutched at his heart. вЂњTo her, to her alone,
to see her, to hear her, to think of nothing, to forget everything, if
only for that night, for an hour, for a moment!вЂќ Just as he turned from
the balcony into the passage, he came upon the landlord, Trifon
Borissovitch. He thought he looked gloomy and worried, and fancied he had
come to find him.

вЂњWhat is it, Trifon Borissovitch? are you looking for me?вЂќ

вЂњNo, sir.вЂќ The landlord seemed disconcerted. вЂњWhy should I be looking for
you? Where have you been?вЂќ

вЂњWhy do you look so glum? YouвЂ™re not angry, are you? Wait a bit, you shall
soon get to bed.... WhatвЂ™s the time?вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™ll be three oвЂ™clock. Past three, it must be.вЂќ

вЂњWeвЂ™ll leave off soon. WeвЂ™ll leave off.вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t mention it; it doesnвЂ™t matter. Keep it up as long as you like....вЂќ

вЂњWhatвЂ™s the matter with him?вЂќ Mitya wondered for an instant, and he ran
back to the room where the girls were dancing. But she was not there. She
was not in the blue room either; there was no one but Kalganov asleep on
the sofa. Mitya peeped behind the curtainвЂ”she was there. She was sitting
in the corner, on a trunk. Bent forward, with her head and arms on the bed
close by, she was crying bitterly, doing her utmost to stifle her sobs
that she might not be heard. Seeing Mitya, she beckoned him to her, and
when he ran to her, she grasped his hand tightly.

вЂњMitya, Mitya, I loved him, you know. How I have loved him these five
years, all that time! Did I love him or only my own anger? No, him, him!
ItвЂ™s a lie that it was my anger I loved and not him. Mitya, I was only
seventeen then; he was so kind to me, so merry; he used to sing to me....
Or so it seemed to a silly girl like me.... And now, O Lord, itвЂ™s not the
same man. Even his face is not the same; heвЂ™s different altogether. I
shouldnвЂ™t have known him. I drove here with Timofey, and all the way I was
thinking how I should meet him, what I should say to him, how we should
look at one another. My soul was faint, and all of a sudden it was just as
though he had emptied a pail of dirty water over me. He talked to me like
a schoolmaster, all so grave and learned; he met me so solemnly that I was
struck dumb. I couldnвЂ™t get a word in. At first I thought he was ashamed
to talk before his great big Pole. I sat staring at him and wondering why
I couldnвЂ™t say a word to him now. It must have been his wife that ruined
him; you know he threw me up to get married. She must have changed him
like that. Mitya, how shameful it is! Oh, Mitya, IвЂ™m ashamed, IвЂ™m ashamed
for all my life. Curse it, curse it, curse those five years!вЂќ

And again she burst into tears, but clung tight to MityaвЂ™s hand and did
not let it go.

вЂњMitya, darling, stay, donвЂ™t go away. I want to say one word to you,вЂќ she
whispered, and suddenly raised her face to him. вЂњListen, tell me who it is
I love? I love one man here. Who is that man? ThatвЂ™s what you must tell
me.вЂќ

A smile lighted up her face that was swollen with weeping, and her eyes
shone in the half darkness.

вЂњA falcon flew in, and my heart sank. вЂFool! thatвЂ™s the man you love!вЂ™
That was what my heart whispered to me at once. You came in and all grew
bright. WhatвЂ™s he afraid of? I wondered. For you were frightened; you
couldnвЂ™t speak. ItвЂ™s not them heвЂ™s afraid ofвЂ”could you be frightened of
any one? ItвЂ™s me heвЂ™s afraid of, I thought, only me. So Fenya told you,
you little stupid, how I called to Alyosha out of the window that IвЂ™d
loved Mityenka for one hour, and that I was going now to love ... another.
Mitya, Mitya, how could I be such a fool as to think I could love any one
after you? Do you forgive me, Mitya? Do you forgive me or not? Do you love
me? Do you love me?вЂќ She jumped up and held him with both hands on his
shoulders. Mitya, dumb with rapture, gazed into her eyes, at her face, at
her smile, and suddenly clasped her tightly in his arms and kissed her
passionately.

вЂњYou will forgive me for having tormented you? It was through spite I
tormented you all. It was for spite I drove the old man out of his
mind.... Do you remember how you drank at my house one day and broke the
wineвЂђglass? I remembered that and I broke a glass toвЂђday and drank вЂto my
vile heart.вЂ™ Mitya, my falcon, why donвЂ™t you kiss me? He kissed me once,
and now he draws back and looks and listens. Why listen to me? Kiss me,
kiss me hard, thatвЂ™s right. If you love, well, then, love! IвЂ™ll be your
slave now, your slave for the rest of my life. ItвЂ™s sweet to be a slave.
Kiss me! Beat me, illвЂђtreat me, do what you will with me.... And I do
deserve to suffer. Stay, wait, afterwards, I wonвЂ™t have that....вЂќ she
suddenly thrust him away. вЂњGo along, Mitya, IвЂ™ll come and have some wine,
I want to be drunk, IвЂ™m going to get drunk and dance; I must, I must!вЂќ She
tore herself away from him and disappeared behind the curtain. Mitya
followed like a drunken man.

вЂњYes, come what mayвЂ”whatever may happen now, for one minute IвЂ™d give the
whole world,вЂќ he thought. Grushenka did, in fact, toss off a whole glass
of champagne at one gulp, and became at once very tipsy. She sat down in
the same chair as before, with a blissful smile on her face. Her cheeks
were glowing, her lips were burning, her flashing eyes were moist; there
was passionate appeal in her eyes. Even Kalganov felt a stir at the heart
and went up to her.

вЂњDid you feel how I kissed you when you were asleep just now?вЂќ she said
thickly. вЂњIвЂ™m drunk now, thatвЂ™s what it is.... And arenвЂ™t you drunk? And
why isnвЂ™t Mitya drinking? Why donвЂ™t you drink, Mitya? IвЂ™m drunk, and you
donвЂ™t drink....вЂќ

вЂњI am drunk! IвЂ™m drunk as it is ... drunk with you ... and now IвЂ™ll be
drunk with wine, too.вЂќ

He drank off another glass, andвЂ”he thought it strange himselfвЂ”that glass
made him completely drunk. He was suddenly drunk, although till that
moment he had been quite sober, he remembered that. From that moment
everything whirled about him, as though he were delirious. He walked,
laughed, talked to everybody, without knowing what he was doing. Only one
persistent burning sensation made itself felt continually, вЂњlike a redвЂђhot
coal in his heart,вЂќ he said afterwards. He went up to her, sat beside her,
gazed at her, listened to her.... She became very talkative, kept calling
every one to her, and beckoned to different girls out of the chorus. When
the girl came up, she either kissed her, or made the sign of the cross
over her. In another minute she might have cried. She was greatly amused
by the вЂњlittle old man,вЂќ as she called Maximov. He ran up every minute to
kiss her hands, вЂњeach little finger,вЂќ and finally he danced another dance
to an old song, which he sang himself. He danced with special vigor to the
refrain:


    The little pig saysвЂ”umph! umph! umph!
    The little calf saysвЂ”moo, moo, moo,
    The little duck saysвЂ”quack, quack, quack,
    The little goose saysвЂ”ga, ga, ga.
    The hen goes strutting through the porch;
    TrooвЂђrooвЂђrooвЂђrooвЂђroo, sheвЂ™ll say,
    TrooвЂђrooвЂђrooвЂђrooвЂђroo, sheвЂ™ll say!


вЂњGive him something, Mitya,вЂќ said Grushenka. вЂњGive him a present, heвЂ™s
poor, you know. Ah, the poor, the insulted!... Do you know, Mitya, I shall
go into a nunnery. No, I really shall one day, Alyosha said something to
me toвЂђday that I shall remember all my life.... Yes.... But toвЂђday let us
dance. ToвЂђmorrow to the nunnery, but toвЂђday weвЂ™ll dance. I want to play
toвЂђday, good people, and what of it? God will forgive us. If I were God,
IвЂ™d forgive every one: вЂMy dear sinners, from this day forth I forgive
you.вЂ™ IвЂ™m going to beg forgiveness: вЂForgive me, good people, a silly
wench.вЂ™ IвЂ™m a beast, thatвЂ™s what I am. But I want to pray. I gave a little
onion. Wicked as IвЂ™ve been, I want to pray. Mitya, let them dance, donвЂ™t
stop them. Every one in the world is good. Every oneвЂ”even the worst of
them. The worldвЂ™s a nice place. Though weвЂ™re bad the worldвЂ™s all right.
WeвЂ™re good and bad, good and bad.... Come, tell me, IвЂ™ve something to ask
you: come here every one, and IвЂ™ll ask you: Why am I so good? You know I
am good. IвЂ™m very good.... Come, why am I so good?вЂќ

So Grushenka babbled on, getting more and more drunk. At last she
announced that she was going to dance, too. She got up from her chair,
staggering. вЂњMitya, donвЂ™t give me any more wineвЂ”if I ask you, donвЂ™t give
it to me. Wine doesnвЂ™t give peace. EverythingвЂ™s going round, the stove,
and everything. I want to dance. Let every one see how I dance ... let
them see how beautifully I dance....вЂќ

She really meant it. She pulled a white cambric handkerchief out of her
pocket, and took it by one corner in her right hand, to wave it in the
dance. Mitya ran to and fro, the girls were quiet, and got ready to break
into a dancing song at the first signal. Maximov, hearing that Grushenka
wanted to dance, squealed with delight, and ran skipping about in front of
her, humming:


    With legs so slim and sides so trim
    And its little tail curled tight.


But Grushenka waved her handkerchief at him and drove him away.

вЂњShвЂђh! Mitya, why donвЂ™t they come? Let every one come ... to look on. Call
them in, too, that were locked in.... Why did you lock them in? Tell them
IвЂ™m going to dance. Let them look on, too....вЂќ

Mitya walked with a drunken swagger to the locked door, and began knocking
to the Poles with his fist.

вЂњHi, you ... Podvysotskys! Come, sheвЂ™s going to dance. She calls you.вЂќ

вЂњ_Lajdak!_вЂќ one of the Poles shouted in reply.

вЂњYouвЂ™re a _lajdak_ yourself! YouвЂ™re a little scoundrel, thatвЂ™s what you
are.вЂќ

вЂњLeave off laughing at Poland,вЂќ said Kalganov sententiously. He too was
drunk.

вЂњBe quiet, boy! If I call him a scoundrel, it doesnвЂ™t mean that I called
all Poland so. One _lajdak_ doesnвЂ™t make a Poland. Be quiet, my pretty
boy, eat a sweetmeat.вЂќ

вЂњAch, what fellows! As though they were not men. Why wonвЂ™t they make
friends?вЂќ said Grushenka, and went forward to dance. The chorus broke into
вЂњAh, my porch, my new porch!вЂќ Grushenka flung back her head, half opened
her lips, smiled, waved her handkerchief, and suddenly, with a violent
lurch, stood still in the middle of the room, looking bewildered.

вЂњIвЂ™m weak....вЂќ she said in an exhausted voice. вЂњForgive me.... IвЂ™m weak, I
canвЂ™t.... IвЂ™m sorry.вЂќ

She bowed to the chorus, and then began bowing in all directions.

вЂњIвЂ™m sorry.... Forgive me....вЂќ

вЂњThe ladyвЂ™s been drinking. The pretty lady has been drinking,вЂќ voices were
heard saying.

вЂњThe ladyвЂ™s drunk too much,вЂќ Maximov explained to the girls, giggling.

вЂњMitya, lead me away ... take me,вЂќ said Grushenka helplessly. Mitya
pounced on her, snatched her up in his arms, and carried the precious
burden through the curtains.

вЂњWell, now IвЂ™ll go,вЂќ thought Kalganov, and walking out of the blue room,
he closed the two halves of the door after him. But the orgy in the larger
room went on and grew louder and louder. Mitya laid Grushenka on the bed
and kissed her on the lips.

вЂњDonвЂ™t touch me....вЂќ she faltered, in an imploring voice. вЂњDonвЂ™t touch me,
till IвЂ™m yours.... IвЂ™ve told you IвЂ™m yours, but donвЂ™t touch me ... spare
me.... With them here, with them close, you mustnвЂ™t. HeвЂ™s here. ItвЂ™s nasty
here....вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll obey you! I wonвЂ™t think of it ... I worship you!вЂќ muttered Mitya.
вЂњYes, itвЂ™s nasty here, itвЂ™s abominable.вЂќ

And still holding her in his arms, he sank on his knees by the bedside.

вЂњI know, though youвЂ™re a brute, youвЂ™re generous,вЂќ Grushenka articulated
with difficulty. вЂњIt must be honorable ... it shall be honorable for the
future ... and let us be honest, let us be good, not brutes, but good ...
take me away, take me far away, do you hear? I donвЂ™t want it to be here,
but far, far away....вЂќ

вЂњOh, yes, yes, it must be!вЂќ said Mitya, pressing her in his arms. вЂњIвЂ™ll
take you and weвЂ™ll fly away.... Oh, IвЂ™d give my whole life for one year
only to know about that blood!вЂќ

вЂњWhat blood?вЂќ asked Grushenka, bewildered.

вЂњNothing,вЂќ muttered Mitya, through his teeth. вЂњGrusha, you wanted to be
honest, but IвЂ™m a thief. But IвЂ™ve stolen money from Katya.... Disgrace, a
disgrace!вЂќ

вЂњFrom Katya, from that young lady? No, you didnвЂ™t steal it. Give it her
back, take it from me.... Why make a fuss? Now everything of mine is
yours. What does money matter? We shall waste it anyway.... Folks like us
are bound to waste money. But weвЂ™d better go and work the land. I want to
dig the earth with my own hands. We must work, do you hear? Alyosha said
so. I wonвЂ™t be your mistress, IвЂ™ll be faithful to you, IвЂ™ll be your slave,
IвЂ™ll work for you. WeвЂ™ll go to the young lady and bow down to her
together, so that she may forgive us, and then weвЂ™ll go away. And if she
wonвЂ™t forgive us, weвЂ™ll go, anyway. Take her her money and love me....
DonвЂ™t love her.... DonвЂ™t love her any more. If you love her, I shall
strangle her.... IвЂ™ll put out both her eyes with a needle....вЂќ

вЂњI love you. I love only you. IвЂ™ll love you in Siberia....вЂќ

вЂњWhy Siberia? Never mind, Siberia, if you like. I donвЂ™t care ... weвЂ™ll
work ... thereвЂ™s snow in Siberia.... I love driving in the snow ... and
must have bells.... Do you hear, thereвЂ™s a bell ringing? Where is that
bell ringing? There are people coming.... Now itвЂ™s stopped.вЂќ

She closed her eyes, exhausted, and suddenly fell asleep for an instant.
There had certainly been the sound of a bell in the distance, but the
ringing had ceased. Mitya let his head sink on her breast. He did not
notice that the bell had ceased ringing, nor did he notice that the songs
had ceased, and that instead of singing and drunken clamor there was
absolute stillness in the house. Grushenka opened her eyes.

вЂњWhatвЂ™s the matter? Was I asleep? Yes ... a bell ... IвЂ™ve been asleep and
dreamt I was driving over the snow with bells, and I dozed. I was with
some one I loved, with you. And far, far away. I was holding you and
kissing you, nestling close to you. I was cold, and the snow glistened....
You know how the snow glistens at night when the moon shines. It was as
though I was not on earth. I woke up, and my dear one is close to me. How
sweet that is!...вЂќ

вЂњClose to you,вЂќ murmured Mitya, kissing her dress, her bosom, her hands.
And suddenly he had a strange fancy: it seemed to him that she was looking
straight before her, not at him, not into his face, but over his head,
with an intent, almost uncanny fixity. An expression of wonder, almost of
alarm, came suddenly into her face.

вЂњMitya, who is that looking at us?вЂќ she whispered.

Mitya turned, and saw that some one had, in fact, parted the curtains and
seemed to be watching them. And not one person alone, it seemed.

He jumped up and walked quickly to the intruder.

вЂњHere, come to us, come here,вЂќ said a voice, speaking not loudly, but
firmly and peremptorily.

Mitya passed to the other side of the curtain and stood stock still. The
room was filled with people, but not those who had been there before. An
instantaneous shiver ran down his back, and he shuddered. He recognized
all those people instantly. That tall, stout old man in the overcoat and
forageвЂђcap with a cockadeвЂ”was the police captain, Mihail Makarovitch. And
that вЂњconsumptiveвЂђlookingвЂќ trim dandy, вЂњwho always has such polished
bootsвЂќвЂ”that was the deputy prosecutor. вЂњHe has a chronometer worth four
hundred roubles; he showed it to me.вЂќ And that small young man in
spectacles.... Mitya forgot his surname though he knew him, had seen him:
he was the вЂњinvestigating lawyer,вЂќ from the вЂњschool of jurisprudence,вЂќ who
had only lately come to the town. And this manвЂ”the inspector of police,
Mavriky Mavrikyevitch, a man he knew well. And those fellows with the
brass plates on, why are they here? And those other two ... peasants....
And there at the door Kalganov with Trifon Borissovitch....

вЂњGentlemen! WhatвЂ™s this for, gentlemen?вЂќ began Mitya, but suddenly, as
though beside himself, not knowing what he was doing, he cried aloud, at
the top of his voice:

вЂњI unвЂ”derвЂ”stand!вЂќ

The young man in spectacles moved forward suddenly, and stepping up to
Mitya, began with dignity, though hurriedly:

вЂњWe have to make ... in brief, I beg you to come this way, this way to the
sofa.... It is absolutely imperative that you should give an explanation.вЂќ

вЂњThe old man!вЂќ cried Mitya frantically. вЂњThe old man and his blood!... I
understand.вЂќ

And he sank, almost fell, on a chair close by, as though he had been mown
down by a scythe.

вЂњYou understand? He understands it! Monster and parricide! Your fatherвЂ™s
blood cries out against you!вЂќ the old captain of police roared suddenly,
stepping up to Mitya.

He was beside himself, crimson in the face and quivering all over.

вЂњThis is impossible!вЂќ cried the small young man. вЂњMihail Makarovitch,
Mihail Makarovitch, this wonвЂ™t do!... I beg youвЂ™ll allow me to speak. I
should never have expected such behavior from you....вЂќ

вЂњThis is delirium, gentlemen, raving delirium,вЂќ cried the captain of
police; вЂњlook at him: drunk, at this time of night, in the company of a
disreputable woman, with the blood of his father on his hands.... ItвЂ™s
delirium!...вЂќ

вЂњI beg you most earnestly, dear Mihail Makarovitch, to restrain your
feelings,вЂќ the prosecutor said in a rapid whisper to the old police
captain, вЂњor I shall be forced to resort toвЂ”вЂќ

But the little lawyer did not allow him to finish. He turned to Mitya, and
delivered himself in a loud, firm, dignified voice:

вЂњExвЂђLieutenant Karamazov, it is my duty to inform you that you are charged
with the murder of your father, Fyodor Pavlovitch Karamazov, perpetrated
this night....вЂќ

He said something more, and the prosecutor, too, put in something, but
though Mitya heard them he did not understand them. He stared at them all
with wild eyes.




Book IX. The Preliminary Investigation



Chapter I. The Beginning Of PerhotinвЂ™s Official Career


Pyotr Ilyitch Perhotin, whom we left knocking at the strong locked gates
of the widow MorozovвЂ™s house, ended, of course, by making himself heard.
Fenya, who was still excited by the fright she had had two hours before,
and too much вЂњupsetвЂќ to go to bed, was almost frightened into hysterics on
hearing the furious knocking at the gate. Though she had herself seen him
drive away, she fancied that it must be Dmitri Fyodorovitch knocking
again, no one else could knock so savagely. She ran to the houseвЂђporter,
who had already waked up and gone out to the gate, and began imploring him
not to open it. But having questioned Pyotr Ilyitch, and learned that he
wanted to see Fenya on very вЂњimportant business,вЂќ the man made up his mind
at last to open. Pyotr Ilyitch was admitted into FenyaвЂ™s kitchen, but the
girl begged him to allow the houseвЂђporter to be present, вЂњbecause of her
misgivings.вЂќ He began questioning her and at once learnt the most vital
fact, that is, that when Dmitri Fyodorovitch had run out to look for
Grushenka, he had snatched up a pestle from the mortar, and that when he
returned, the pestle was not with him and his hands were smeared with
blood.

вЂњAnd the blood was simply flowing, dripping from him, dripping!вЂќ Fenya
kept exclaiming. This horrible detail was simply the product of her
disordered imagination. But although not вЂњdripping,вЂќ Pyotr Ilyitch had
himself seen those hands stained with blood, and had helped to wash them.
Moreover, the question he had to decide was not how soon the blood had
dried, but where Dmitri Fyodorovitch had run with the pestle, or rather,
whether it really was to Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s, and how he could
satisfactorily ascertain. Pyotr Ilyitch persisted in returning to this
point, and though he found out nothing conclusive, yet he carried away a
conviction that Dmitri Fyodorovitch could have gone nowhere but to his
fatherвЂ™s house, and that therefore something must have happened there.

вЂњAnd when he came back,вЂќ Fenya added with excitement, вЂњI told him the
whole story, and then I began asking him, вЂWhy have you got blood on your
hands, Dmitri Fyodorovitch?вЂ™ and he answered that that was human blood,
and that he had just killed some one. He confessed it all to me, and
suddenly ran off like a madman. I sat down and began thinking, whereвЂ™s he
run off to now like a madman? HeвЂ™ll go to Mokroe, I thought, and kill my
mistress there. I ran out to beg him not to kill her. I was running to his
lodgings, but I looked at PlotnikovвЂ™s shop, and saw him just setting off,
and there was no blood on his hands then.вЂќ (Fenya had noticed this and
remembered it.) FenyaвЂ™s old grandmother confirmed her evidence as far as
she was capable. After asking some further questions, Pyotr Ilyitch left
the house, even more upset and uneasy than he had been when he entered it.

The most direct and the easiest thing for him to do would have been to go
straight to Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s, to find out whether anything had happened
there, and if so, what; and only to go to the police captain, as Pyotr
Ilyitch firmly intended doing, when he had satisfied himself of the fact.
But the night was dark, Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s gates were strong, and he
would have to knock again. His acquaintance with Fyodor Pavlovitch was of
the slightest, and what if, after he had been knocking, they opened to
him, and nothing had happened? Then Fyodor Pavlovitch in his jeering way
would go telling the story all over the town, how a stranger, called
Perhotin, had broken in upon him at midnight to ask if any one had killed
him. It would make a scandal. And scandal was what Pyotr Ilyitch dreaded
more than anything in the world.

Yet the feeling that possessed him was so strong, that though he stamped
his foot angrily and swore at himself, he set off again, not to Fyodor
PavlovitchвЂ™s but to Madame HohlakovвЂ™s. He decided that if she denied
having just given Dmitri Fyodorovitch three thousand roubles, he would go
straight to the police captain, but if she admitted having given him the
money, he would go home and let the matter rest till next morning.

It is, of course, perfectly evident that there was even more likelihood of
causing scandal by going at eleven oвЂ™clock at night to a fashionable lady,
a complete stranger, and perhaps rousing her from her bed to ask her an
amazing question, than by going to Fyodor Pavlovitch. But that is just how
it is, sometimes, especially in cases like the present one, with the
decisions of the most precise and phlegmatic people. Pyotr Ilyitch was by
no means phlegmatic at that moment. He remembered all his life how a
haunting uneasiness gradually gained possession of him, growing more and
more painful and driving him on, against his will. Yet he kept cursing
himself, of course, all the way for going to this lady, but вЂњI will get to
the bottom of it, I will!вЂќ he repeated for the tenth time, grinding his
teeth, and he carried out his intention.

It was exactly eleven oвЂ™clock when he entered Madame HohlakovвЂ™s house. He
was admitted into the yard pretty quickly, but, in response to his inquiry
whether the lady was still up, the porter could give no answer, except
that she was usually in bed by that time.

вЂњAsk at the top of the stairs. If the lady wants to receive you, sheвЂ™ll
receive you. If she wonвЂ™t, she wonвЂ™t.вЂќ

Pyotr Ilyitch went up, but did not find things so easy here. The footman
was unwilling to take in his name, but finally called a maid. Pyotr
Ilyitch politely but insistently begged her to inform her lady that an
official, living in the town, called Perhotin, had called on particular
business, and that if it were not of the greatest importance he would not
have ventured to come. вЂњTell her in those words, in those words exactly,вЂќ
he asked the girl.

She went away. He remained waiting in the entry. Madame Hohlakov herself
was already in her bedroom, though not yet asleep. She had felt upset ever
since MityaвЂ™s visit, and had a presentiment that she would not get through
the night without the sick headache which always, with her, followed such
excitement. She was surprised on hearing the announcement from the maid.
She irritably declined to see him, however, though the unexpected visit at
such an hour, of an вЂњofficial living in the town,вЂќ who was a total
stranger, roused her feminine curiosity intensely. But this time Pyotr
Ilyitch was as obstinate as a mule. He begged the maid most earnestly to
take another message in these very words:

вЂњThat he had come on business of the greatest importance, and that Madame
Hohlakov might have cause to regret it later, if she refused to see him
now.вЂќ

вЂњI plunged headlong,вЂќ he described it afterwards.

The maid, gazing at him in amazement, went to take his message again.
Madame Hohlakov was impressed. She thought a little, asked what he looked
like, and learned that he was вЂњvery well dressed, young and so polite.вЂќ We
may note, parenthetically, that Pyotr Ilyitch was a rather goodвЂђlooking
young man, and well aware of the fact. Madame Hohlakov made up her mind to
see him. She was in her dressingвЂђgown and slippers, but she flung a black
shawl over her shoulders. вЂњThe officialвЂќ was asked to walk into the
drawingвЂђroom, the very room in which Mitya had been received shortly
before. The lady came to meet her visitor, with a sternly inquiring
countenance, and, without asking him to sit down, began at once with the
question:

вЂњWhat do you want?вЂќ

вЂњI have ventured to disturb you, madam, on a matter concerning our common
acquaintance, Dmitri Fyodorovitch Karamazov,вЂќ Perhotin began.

But he had hardly uttered the name, when the ladyвЂ™s face showed signs of
acute irritation. She almost shrieked, and interrupted him in a fury:

вЂњHow much longer am I to be worried by that awful man?вЂќ she cried
hysterically. вЂњHow dare you, sir, how could you venture to disturb a lady
who is a stranger to you, in her own house at such an hour!... And to
force yourself upon her to talk of a man who came here, to this very
drawingвЂђroom, only three hours ago, to murder me, and went stamping out of
the room, as no one would go out of a decent house. Let me tell you, sir,
that I shall lodge a complaint against you, that I will not let it pass.
Kindly leave me at once.... I am a mother.... I ... IвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњMurder! then he tried to murder you, too?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, has he killed somebody else?вЂќ Madame Hohlakov asked impulsively.

вЂњIf you would kindly listen, madam, for half a moment, IвЂ™ll explain it all
in a couple of words,вЂќ answered Perhotin, firmly. вЂњAt five oвЂ™clock this
afternoon Dmitri Fyodorovitch borrowed ten roubles from me, and I know for
a fact he had no money. Yet at nine oвЂ™clock, he came to see me with a
bundle of hundredвЂђrouble notes in his hand, about two or three thousand
roubles. His hands and face were all covered with blood, and he looked
like a madman. When I asked him where he had got so much money, he
answered that he had just received it from you, that you had given him a
sum of three thousand to go to the goldвЂђmines....вЂќ

Madame HohlakovвЂ™s face assumed an expression of intense and painful
excitement.

вЂњGood God! He must have killed his old father!вЂќ she cried, clasping her
hands. вЂњI have never given him money, never! Oh, run, run!... DonвЂ™t say
another word! Save the old man ... run to his father ... run!вЂќ

вЂњExcuse me, madam, then you did not give him money? You remember for a
fact that you did not give him any money?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I didnвЂ™t, I didnвЂ™t! I refused to give it him, for he could not
appreciate it. He ran out in a fury, stamping. He rushed at me, but I
slipped away.... And let me tell you, as I wish to hide nothing from you
now, that he positively spat at me. Can you fancy that! But why are we
standing? Ah, sit down.вЂќ

вЂњExcuse me, I....вЂќ

вЂњOr better run, run, you must run and save the poor old man from an awful
death!вЂќ

вЂњBut if he has killed him already?вЂќ

вЂњAh, good heavens, yes! Then what are we to do now? What do you think we
must do now?вЂќ

Meantime she had made Pyotr Ilyitch sit down and sat down herself, facing
him. Briefly, but fairly clearly, Pyotr Ilyitch told her the history of
the affair, that part of it at least which he had himself witnessed. He
described, too, his visit to Fenya, and told her about the pestle. All
these details produced an overwhelming effect on the distracted lady, who
kept uttering shrieks, and covering her face with her hands....

вЂњWould you believe it, I foresaw all this! I have that special faculty,
whatever I imagine comes to pass. And how often IвЂ™ve looked at that awful
man and always thought, that man will end by murdering me. And now itвЂ™s
happened ... that is, if he hasnвЂ™t murdered me, but only his own father,
itвЂ™s only because the finger of God preserved me, and whatвЂ™s more, he was
ashamed to murder me because, in this very place, I put the holy ikon from
the relics of the holy martyr, Saint Varvara, on his neck.... And to think
how near I was to death at that minute, I went close up to him and he
stretched out his neck to me!... Do you know, Pyotr Ilyitch (I think you
said your name was Pyotr Ilyitch), I donвЂ™t believe in miracles, but that
ikon and this unmistakable miracle with me nowвЂ”that shakes me, and IвЂ™m
ready to believe in anything you like. Have you heard about Father
Zossima?... But I donвЂ™t know what IвЂ™m saying ... and only fancy, with the
ikon on his neck he spat at me.... He only spat, itвЂ™s true, he didnвЂ™t
murder me and ... he dashed away! But what shall we do, what must we do
now? What do you think?вЂќ

Pyotr Ilyitch got up, and announced that he was going straight to the
police captain, to tell him all about it, and leave him to do what he
thought fit.

вЂњOh, heвЂ™s an excellent man, excellent! Mihail Makarovitch, I know him. Of
course, heвЂ™s the person to go to. How practical you are, Pyotr Ilyitch!
How well youвЂ™ve thought of everything! I should never have thought of it
in your place!вЂќ

вЂњEspecially as I know the police captain very well, too,вЂќ observed Pyotr
Ilyitch, who still continued to stand, and was obviously anxious to escape
as quickly as possible from the impulsive lady, who would not let him say
goodвЂђby and go away.

вЂњAnd be sure, be sure,вЂќ she prattled on, вЂњto come back and tell me what
you see there, and what you find out ... what comes to light ... how
theyвЂ™ll try him ... and what heвЂ™s condemned to.... Tell me, we have no
capital punishment, have we? But be sure to come, even if itвЂ™s at three
oвЂ™clock at night, at four, at halfвЂђpast four.... Tell them to wake me, to
wake me, to shake me, if I donвЂ™t get up.... But, good heavens, I shanвЂ™t
sleep! But wait, hadnвЂ™t I better come with you?вЂќ

вЂњNвЂ”no. But if you would write three lines with your own hand, stating that
you did not give Dmitri Fyodorovitch money, it might, perhaps, be of use
... in case itвЂ™s needed....вЂќ

вЂњTo be sure!вЂќ Madame Hohlakov skipped, delighted, to her bureau. вЂњAnd you
know IвЂ™m simply struck, amazed at your resourcefulness, your good sense in
such affairs. Are you in the service here? IвЂ™m delighted to think that
youвЂ™re in the service here!вЂќ

And still speaking, she scribbled on half a sheet of notepaper the
following lines:


    IвЂ™ve never in my life lent to that unhappy man, Dmitri
    Fyodorovitch Karamazov (for, in spite of all, he is unhappy),
    three thousand roubles toвЂђday. IвЂ™ve never given him money, never:
    That I swear by all thatвЂ™s holy!

    K. HOHLAKOV.


вЂњHereвЂ™s the note!вЂќ she turned quickly to Pyotr Ilyitch. вЂњGo, save him.
ItвЂ™s a noble deed on your part!вЂќ

And she made the sign of the cross three times over him. She ran out to
accompany him to the passage.

вЂњHow grateful I am to you! You canвЂ™t think how grateful I am to you for
having come to me, first. How is it I havenвЂ™t met you before? I shall feel
flattered at seeing you at my house in the future. How delightful it is
that you are living here!... Such precision! Such practical ability!...
They must appreciate you, they must understand you. If thereвЂ™s anything I
can do, believe me ... oh, I love young people! IвЂ™m in love with young
people! The younger generation are the one prop of our suffering country.
Her one hope.... Oh, go, go!...вЂќ

But Pyotr Ilyitch had already run away or she would not have let him go so
soon. Yet Madame Hohlakov had made a rather agreeable impression on him,
which had somewhat softened his anxiety at being drawn into such an
unpleasant affair. Tastes differ, as we all know. вЂњSheвЂ™s by no means so
elderly,вЂќ he thought, feeling pleased, вЂњon the contrary I should have
taken her for her daughter.вЂќ

As for Madame Hohlakov, she was simply enchanted by the young man. вЂњSuch
sense! such exactness! in so young a man! in our day! and all that with
such manners and appearance! People say the young people of toвЂђday are no
good for anything, but hereвЂ™s an example!вЂќ etc. So she simply forgot this
вЂњdreadful affair,вЂќ and it was only as she was getting into bed, that,
suddenly recalling вЂњhow near death she had been,вЂќ she exclaimed: вЂњAh, it
is awful, awful!вЂќ

But she fell at once into a sound, sweet sleep.

I would not, however, have dwelt on such trivial and irrelevant details,
if this eccentric meeting of the young official with the by no means
elderly widow had not subsequently turned out to be the foundation of the
whole career of that practical and precise young man. His story is
remembered to this day with amazement in our town, and I shall perhaps
have something to say about it, when I have finished my long history of
the Brothers Karamazov.



Chapter II. The Alarm


Our police captain, Mihail Makarovitch Makarov, a retired lieutenantвЂђ
colonel, was a widower and an excellent man. He had only come to us three
years previously, but had won general esteem, chiefly because he вЂњknew how
to keep society together.вЂќ He was never without visitors, and could not
have got on without them. Some one or other was always dining with him; he
never sat down to table without guests. He gave regular dinners, too, on
all sorts of occasions, sometimes most surprising ones. Though the fare
was not _recherchГ©_, it was abundant. The fishвЂђpies were excellent, and
the wine made up in quantity for what it lacked in quality.

The first room his guests entered was a wellвЂђfitted billiardвЂђroom, with
pictures of English raceвЂђhorses, in black frames on the walls, an
essential decoration, as we all know, for a bachelorвЂ™s billiardвЂђroom.
There was cardвЂђplaying every evening at his house, if only at one table.
But at frequent intervals, all the society of our town, with the mammas
and young ladies, assembled at his house to dance. Though Mihail
Makarovitch was a widower, he did not live alone. His widowed daughter
lived with him, with her two unmarried daughters, grownвЂђup girls, who had
finished their education. They were of agreeable appearance and lively
character, and though every one knew they would have no dowry, they
attracted all the young men of fashion to their grandfatherвЂ™s house.

Mihail Makarovitch was by no means very efficient in his work, though he
performed his duties no worse than many others. To speak plainly, he was a
man of rather narrow education. His understanding of the limits of his
administrative power could not always be relied upon. It was not so much
that he failed to grasp certain reforms enacted during the present reign,
as that he made conspicuous blunders in his interpretation of them. This
was not from any special lack of intelligence, but from carelessness, for
he was always in too great a hurry to go into the subject.

вЂњI have the heart of a soldier rather than of a civilian,вЂќ he used to say
of himself. He had not even formed a definite idea of the fundamental
principles of the reforms connected with the emancipation of the serfs,
and only picked it up, so to speak, from year to year, involuntarily
increasing his knowledge by practice. And yet he was himself a landowner.
Pyotr Ilyitch knew for certain that he would meet some of Mihail
MakarovitchвЂ™s visitors there that evening, but he didnвЂ™t know which. As it
happened, at that moment the prosecutor, and Varvinsky, our district
doctor, a young man, who had only just come to us from Petersburg after
taking a brilliant degree at the Academy of Medicine, were playing whist
at the police captainвЂ™s. Ippolit Kirillovitch, the prosecutor (he was
really the deputy prosecutor, but we always called him the prosecutor),
was rather a peculiar man, of about five and thirty, inclined to be
consumptive, and married to a fat and childless woman. He was vain and
irritable, though he had a good intellect, and even a kind heart. It
seemed that all that was wrong with him was that he had a better opinion
of himself than his ability warranted. And that made him seem constantly
uneasy. He had, moreover, certain higher, even artistic, leanings, towards
psychology, for instance, a special study of the human heart, a special
knowledge of the criminal and his crime. He cherished a grievance on this
ground, considering that he had been passed over in the service, and being
firmly persuaded that in higher spheres he had not been properly
appreciated, and had enemies. In gloomy moments he even threatened to give
up his post, and practice as a barrister in criminal cases. The unexpected
Karamazov case agitated him profoundly: вЂњIt was a case that might well be
talked about all over Russia.вЂќ But I am anticipating.

Nikolay Parfenovitch Nelyudov, the young investigating lawyer, who had
only come from Petersburg two months before, was sitting in the next room
with the young ladies. People talked about it afterwards and wondered that
all the gentlemen should, as though intentionally, on the evening of вЂњthe
crimeвЂќ have been gathered together at the house of the executive
authority. Yet it was perfectly simple and happened quite naturally.

Ippolit KirillovitchвЂ™s wife had had toothache for the last two days, and
he was obliged to go out to escape from her groans. The doctor, from the
very nature of his being, could not spend an evening except at cards.
Nikolay Parfenovitch Nelyudov had been intending for three days past to
drop in that evening at Mihail MakarovitchвЂ™s, so to speak casually, so as
slyly to startle the eldest granddaughter, Olga Mihailovna, by showing
that he knew her secret, that he knew it was her birthday, and that she
was trying to conceal it on purpose, so as not to be obliged to give a
dance. He anticipated a great deal of merriment, many playful jests about
her age, and her being afraid to reveal it, about his knowing her secret
and telling everybody, and so on. The charming young man was a great adept
at such teasing; the ladies had christened him вЂњthe naughty man,вЂќ and he
seemed to be delighted at the name. He was extremely wellвЂђbred, however,
of good family, education and feelings, and, though leading a life of
pleasure, his sallies were always innocent and in good taste. He was
short, and delicateвЂђlooking. On his white, slender, little fingers he
always wore a number of big, glittering rings. When he was engaged in his
official duties, he always became extraordinarily grave, as though
realizing his position and the sanctity of the obligations laid upon him.
He had a special gift for mystifying murderers and other criminals of the
peasant class during interrogation, and if he did not win their respect,
he certainly succeeded in arousing their wonder.

Pyotr Ilyitch was simply dumbfounded when he went into the police
captainвЂ™s. He saw instantly that every one knew. They had positively
thrown down their cards, all were standing up and talking. Even Nikolay
Parfenovitch had left the young ladies and run in, looking strenuous and
ready for action. Pyotr Ilyitch was met with the astounding news that old
Fyodor Pavlovitch really had been murdered that evening in his own house,
murdered and robbed. The news had only just reached them in the following
manner.

Marfa Ignatyevna, the wife of old Grigory, who had been knocked senseless
near the fence, was sleeping soundly in her bed and might well have slept
till morning after the draught she had taken. But, all of a sudden she
waked up, no doubt roused by a fearful epileptic scream from Smerdyakov,
who was lying in the next room unconscious. That scream always preceded
his fits, and always terrified and upset Marfa Ignatyevna. She could never
get accustomed to it. She jumped up and ran halfвЂђawake to SmerdyakovвЂ™s
room. But it was dark there, and she could only hear the invalid beginning
to gasp and struggle. Then Marfa Ignatyevna herself screamed out and was
going to call her husband, but suddenly realized that when she had got up,
he was not beside her in bed. She ran back to the bedstead and began
groping with her hands, but the bed was really empty. Then he must have
gone outвЂ”where? She ran to the steps and timidly called him. She got no
answer, of course, but she caught the sound of groans far away in the
garden in the darkness. She listened. The groans were repeated, and it was
evident they came from the garden.

вЂњGood Lord! Just as it was with Lizaveta Smerdyastchaya!вЂќ she thought
distractedly. She went timidly down the steps and saw that the gate into
the garden was open.

вЂњHe must be out there, poor dear,вЂќ she thought. She went up to the gate
and all at once she distinctly heard Grigory calling her by name, вЂњMarfa!
Marfa!вЂќ in a weak, moaning, dreadful voice.

вЂњLord, preserve us from harm!вЂќ Marfa Ignatyevna murmured, and ran towards
the voice, and that was how she found Grigory. But she found him not by
the fence where he had been knocked down, but about twenty paces off. It
appeared later, that he had crawled away on coming to himself, and
probably had been a long time getting so far, losing consciousness several
times. She noticed at once that he was covered with blood, and screamed at
the top of her voice. Grigory was muttering incoherently:

вЂњHe has murdered ... his father murdered.... Why scream, silly ... run ...
fetch some one....вЂќ

But Marfa continued screaming, and seeing that her masterвЂ™s window was
open and that there was a candle alight in the window, she ran there and
began calling Fyodor Pavlovitch. But peeping in at the window, she saw a
fearful sight. Her master was lying on his back, motionless, on the floor.
His lightвЂђcolored dressingвЂђgown and white shirt were soaked with blood.
The candle on the table brightly lighted up the blood and the motionless
dead face of Fyodor Pavlovitch. TerrorвЂђstricken, Marfa rushed away from
the window, ran out of the garden, drew the bolt of the big gate and ran
headlong by the back way to the neighbor, Marya Kondratyevna. Both mother
and daughter were asleep, but they waked up at MarfaвЂ™s desperate and
persistent screaming and knocking at the shutter. Marfa, shrieking and
screaming incoherently, managed to tell them the main fact, and to beg for
assistance. It happened that Foma had come back from his wanderings and
was staying the night with them. They got him up immediately and all three
ran to the scene of the crime. On the way, Marya Kondratyevna remembered
that at about eight oвЂ™clock she heard a dreadful scream from their garden,
and this was no doubt GrigoryвЂ™s scream, вЂњParricide!вЂќ uttered when he
caught hold of MityaвЂ™s leg.

вЂњSome one person screamed out and then was silent,вЂќ Marya Kondratyevna
explained as she ran. Running to the place where Grigory lay, the two
women with the help of Foma carried him to the lodge. They lighted a
candle and saw that Smerdyakov was no better, that he was writhing in
convulsions, his eyes fixed in a squint, and that foam was flowing from
his lips. They moistened GrigoryвЂ™s forehead with water mixed with vinegar,
and the water revived him at once. He asked immediately:

вЂњIs the master murdered?вЂќ

Then Foma and both the women ran to the house and saw this time that not
only the window, but also the door into the garden was wide open, though
Fyodor Pavlovitch had for the last week locked himself in every night and
did not allow even Grigory to come in on any pretext. Seeing that door
open, they were afraid to go in to Fyodor Pavlovitch вЂњfor fear anything
should happen afterwards.вЂќ And when they returned to Grigory, the old man
told them to go straight to the police captain. Marya Kondratyevna ran
there and gave the alarm to the whole party at the police captainвЂ™s. She
arrived only five minutes before Pyotr Ilyitch, so that his story came,
not as his own surmise and theory, but as the direct confirmation, by a
witness, of the theory held by all, as to the identity of the criminal (a
theory he had in the bottom of his heart refused to believe till that
moment).

It was resolved to act with energy. The deputy police inspector of the
town was commissioned to take four witnesses, to enter Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s
house and there to open an inquiry on the spot, according to the regular
forms, which I will not go into here. The district doctor, a zealous man,
new to his work, almost insisted on accompanying the police captain, the
prosecutor, and the investigating lawyer.

I will note briefly that Fyodor Pavlovitch was found to be quite dead,
with his skull battered in. But with what? Most likely with the same
weapon with which Grigory had been attacked. And immediately that weapon
was found, Grigory, to whom all possible medical assistance was at once
given, described in a weak and breaking voice how he had been knocked
down. They began looking with a lantern by the fence and found the brass
pestle dropped in a most conspicuous place on the garden path. There were
no signs of disturbance in the room where Fyodor Pavlovitch was lying. But
by the bed, behind the screen, they picked up from the floor a big and
thick envelope with the inscription: вЂњA present of three thousand roubles
for my angel Grushenka, if she is willing to come.вЂќ And below had been
added by Fyodor Pavlovitch, вЂњFor my little chicken.вЂќ There were three
seals of red sealingвЂђwax on the envelope, but it had been torn open and
was empty: the money had been removed. They found also on the floor a
piece of narrow pink ribbon, with which the envelope had been tied up.

One piece of Pyotr IlyitchвЂ™s evidence made a great impression on the
prosecutor and the investigating magistrate, namely, his idea that Dmitri
Fyodorovitch would shoot himself before daybreak, that he had resolved to
do so, had spoken of it to Ilyitch, had taken the pistols, loaded them
before him, written a letter, put it in his pocket, etc. When Pyotr
Ilyitch, though still unwilling to believe in it, threatened to tell some
one so as to prevent the suicide, Mitya had answered grinning: вЂњYouвЂ™ll be
too late.вЂќ So they must make haste to Mokroe to find the criminal, before
he really did shoot himself.

вЂњThatвЂ™s clear, thatвЂ™s clear!вЂќ repeated the prosecutor in great excitement.
вЂњThatвЂ™s just the way with mad fellows like that: вЂI shall kill myself toвЂђ
morrow, so IвЂ™ll make merry till I die!вЂ™ вЂќ

The story of how he had bought the wine and provisions excited the
prosecutor more than ever.

вЂњDo you remember the fellow that murdered a merchant called Olsufyev,
gentlemen? He stole fifteen hundred, went at once to have his hair curled,
and then, without even hiding the money, carrying it almost in his hand in
the same way, he went off to the girls.вЂќ

All were delayed, however, by the inquiry, the search, and the
formalities, etc., in the house of Fyodor Pavlovitch. It all took time and
so, two hours before starting, they sent on ahead to Mokroe the officer of
the rural police, Mavriky Mavrikyevitch Schmertsov, who had arrived in the
town the morning before to get his pay. He was instructed to avoid raising
the alarm when he reached Mokroe, but to keep constant watch over the
вЂњcriminalвЂќ till the arrival of the proper authorities, to procure also
witnesses for the arrest, police constables, and so on. Mavriky
Mavrikyevitch did as he was told, preserving his incognito, and giving no
one but his old acquaintance, Trifon Borissovitch, the slightest hint of
his secret business. He had spoken to him just before Mitya met the
landlord in the balcony, looking for him in the dark, and noticed at once
a change in Trifon BorissovitchвЂ™s face and voice. So neither Mitya nor any
one else knew that he was being watched. The box with the pistols had been
carried off by Trifon Borissovitch and put in a suitable place. Only after
four oвЂ™clock, almost at sunrise, all the officials, the police captain,
the prosecutor, the investigating lawyer, drove up in two carriages, each
drawn by three horses. The doctor remained at Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s to make
a postвЂђmortem next day on the body. But he was particularly interested in
the condition of the servant, Smerdyakov.

вЂњSuch violent and protracted epileptic fits, recurring continually for
twentyвЂђfour hours, are rarely to be met with, and are of interest to
science,вЂќ he declared enthusiastically to his companions, and as they left
they laughingly congratulated him on his find. The prosecutor and the
investigating lawyer distinctly remembered the doctorвЂ™s saying that
Smerdyakov could not outlive the night.

After these long, but I think necessary explanations, we will return to
that moment of our tale at which we broke off.



Chapter III. The Sufferings Of A Soul, The First Ordeal


And so Mitya sat looking wildly at the people round him, not understanding
what was said to him. Suddenly he got up, flung up his hands, and shouted
aloud:

вЂњIвЂ™m not guilty! IвЂ™m not guilty of that blood! IвЂ™m not guilty of my
fatherвЂ™s blood.... I meant to kill him. But IвЂ™m not guilty. Not I.вЂќ

But he had hardly said this, before Grushenka rushed from behind the
curtain and flung herself at the police captainвЂ™s feet.

вЂњIt was my fault! Mine! My wickedness!вЂќ she cried, in a heartrending
voice, bathed in tears, stretching out her clasped hands towards them. вЂњHe
did it through me. I tortured him and drove him to it. I tortured that
poor old man thatвЂ™s dead, too, in my wickedness, and brought him to this!
ItвЂ™s my fault, mine first, mine most, my fault!вЂќ

вЂњYes, itвЂ™s your fault! YouвЂ™re the chief criminal! You fury! You harlot!
YouвЂ™re the most to blame!вЂќ shouted the police captain, threatening her
with his hand. But he was quickly and resolutely suppressed. The
prosecutor positively seized hold of him.

вЂњThis is absolutely irregular, Mihail Makarovitch!вЂќ he cried. вЂњYou are
positively hindering the inquiry.... YouвЂ™re ruining the case....вЂќ he
almost gasped.

вЂњFollow the regular course! Follow the regular course!вЂќ cried Nikolay
Parfenovitch, fearfully excited too, вЂњotherwise itвЂ™s absolutely
impossible!...вЂќ

вЂњJudge us together!вЂќ Grushenka cried frantically, still kneeling. вЂњPunish
us together. I will go with him now, if itвЂ™s to death!вЂќ

вЂњGrusha, my life, my blood, my holy one!вЂќ Mitya fell on his knees beside
her and held her tight in his arms. вЂњDonвЂ™t believe her,вЂќ he cried, вЂњsheвЂ™s
not guilty of anything, of any blood, of anything!вЂќ

He remembered afterwards that he was forcibly dragged away from her by
several men, and that she was led out, and that when he recovered himself
he was sitting at the table. Beside him and behind him stood the men with
metal plates. Facing him on the other side of the table sat Nikolay
Parfenovitch, the investigating lawyer. He kept persuading him to drink a
little water out of a glass that stood on the table.

вЂњThat will refresh you, that will calm you. Be calm, donвЂ™t be frightened,вЂќ
he added, extremely politely. Mitya (he remembered it afterwards) became
suddenly intensely interested in his big rings, one with an amethyst, and
another with a transparent bright yellow stone, of great brilliance. And
long afterwards he remembered with wonder how those rings had riveted his
attention through all those terrible hours of interrogation, so that he
was utterly unable to tear himself away from them and dismiss them, as
things that had nothing to do with his position. On MityaвЂ™s left side, in
the place where Maximov had been sitting at the beginning of the evening,
the prosecutor was now seated, and on MityaвЂ™s right hand, where Grushenka
had been, was a rosyвЂђcheeked young man in a sort of shabby huntingвЂђjacket,
with ink and paper before him. This was the secretary of the investigating
lawyer, who had brought him with him. The police captain was now standing
by the window at the other end of the room, beside Kalganov, who was
sitting there.

вЂњDrink some water,вЂќ said the investigating lawyer softly, for the tenth
time.

вЂњI have drunk it, gentlemen, I have ... but ... come, gentlemen, crush me,
punish me, decide my fate!вЂќ cried Mitya, staring with terribly fixed wideвЂђ
open eyes at the investigating lawyer.

вЂњSo you positively declare that you are not guilty of the death of your
father, Fyodor Pavlovitch?вЂќ asked the investigating lawyer, softly but
insistently.

вЂњI am not guilty. I am guilty of the blood of another old man but not of
my fatherвЂ™s. And I weep for it! I killed, I killed the old man and knocked
him down.... But itвЂ™s hard to have to answer for that murder with another,
a terrible murder of which I am not guilty.... ItвЂ™s a terrible accusation,
gentlemen, a knockвЂђdown blow. But who has killed my father, who has killed
him? Who can have killed him if I didnвЂ™t? ItвЂ™s marvelous, extraordinary,
impossible.вЂќ

вЂњYes, who can have killed him?вЂќ the investigating lawyer was beginning,
but Ippolit Kirillovitch, the prosecutor, glancing at him, addressed
Mitya.

вЂњYou need not worry yourself about the old servant, Grigory Vassilyevitch.
He is alive, he has recovered, and in spite of the terrible blows
inflicted, according to his own and your evidence, by you, there seems no
doubt that he will live, so the doctor says, at least.вЂќ

вЂњAlive? HeвЂ™s alive?вЂќ cried Mitya, flinging up his hands. His face beamed.
вЂњLord, I thank Thee for the miracle Thou has wrought for me, a sinner and
evildoer. ThatвЂ™s an answer to my prayer. IвЂ™ve been praying all night.вЂќ And
he crossed himself three times. He was almost breathless.

вЂњSo from this Grigory we have received such important evidence concerning
you, thatвЂ”вЂќ The prosecutor would have continued, but Mitya suddenly jumped
up from his chair.

вЂњOne minute, gentlemen, for GodвЂ™s sake, one minute; I will run to herвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњExcuse me, at this moment itвЂ™s quite impossible,вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch
almost shrieked. He, too, leapt to his feet. Mitya was seized by the men
with the metal plates, but he sat down of his own accord....

вЂњGentlemen, what a pity! I wanted to see her for one minute only; I wanted
to tell her that it has been washed away, it has gone, that blood that was
weighing on my heart all night, and that I am not a murderer now!
Gentlemen, she is my betrothed!вЂќ he said ecstatically and reverently,
looking round at them all. вЂњOh, thank you, gentlemen! Oh, in one minute
you have given me new life, new heart!... That old man used to carry me in
his arms, gentlemen. He used to wash me in the tub when I was a baby three
years old, abandoned by every one, he was like a father to me!...вЂќ

вЂњAnd so youвЂ”вЂќ the investigating lawyer began.

вЂњAllow me, gentlemen, allow me one minute more,вЂќ interposed Mitya, putting
his elbows on the table and covering his face with his hands. вЂњLet me have
a moment to think, let me breathe, gentlemen. All this is horribly
upsetting, horribly. A man is not a drum, gentlemen!вЂќ

вЂњDrink a little more water,вЂќ murmured Nikolay Parfenovitch.

Mitya took his hands from his face and laughed. His eyes were confident.
He seemed completely transformed in a moment. His whole bearing was
changed; he was once more the equal of these men, with all of whom he was
acquainted, as though they had all met the day before, when nothing had
happened, at some social gathering. We may note in passing that, on his
first arrival, Mitya had been made very welcome at the police captainвЂ™s,
but later, during the last month especially, Mitya had hardly called at
all, and when the police captain met him, in the street, for instance,
Mitya noticed that he frowned and only bowed out of politeness. His
acquaintance with the prosecutor was less intimate, though he sometimes
paid his wife, a nervous and fanciful lady, visits of politeness, without
quite knowing why, and she always received him graciously and had, for
some reason, taken an interest in him up to the last. He had not had time
to get to know the investigating lawyer, though he had met him and talked
to him twice, each time about the fair sex.

вЂњYouвЂ™re a most skillful lawyer, I see, Nikolay Parfenovitch,вЂќ cried Mitya,
laughing gayly, вЂњbut I can help you now. Oh, gentlemen, I feel like a new
man, and donвЂ™t be offended at my addressing you so simply and directly.
IвЂ™m rather drunk, too, IвЂ™ll tell you that frankly. I believe IвЂ™ve had the
honor and pleasure of meeting you, Nikolay Parfenovitch, at my kinsman
MiГјsovвЂ™s. Gentlemen, gentlemen, I donвЂ™t pretend to be on equal terms with
you. I understand, of course, in what character I am sitting before you.
Oh, of course, thereвЂ™s a horrible suspicion ... hanging over me ... if
Grigory has given evidence.... A horrible suspicion! ItвЂ™s awful, awful, I
understand that! But to business, gentlemen, I am ready, and we will make
an end of it in one moment; for, listen, listen, gentlemen! Since I know
IвЂ™m innocent, we can put an end to it in a minute. CanвЂ™t we? CanвЂ™t we?вЂќ

Mitya spoke much and quickly, nervously and effusively, as though he
positively took his listeners to be his best friends.

вЂњSo, for the present, we will write that you absolutely deny the charge
brought against you,вЂќ said Nikolay Parfenovitch, impressively, and bending
down to the secretary he dictated to him in an undertone what to write.

вЂњWrite it down? You want to write that down? Well, write it; I consent, I
give my full consent, gentlemen, only ... do you see?... Stay, stay, write
this. Of disorderly conduct I am guilty, of violence on a poor old man I
am guilty. And there is something else at the bottom of my heart, of which
I am guilty, tooвЂ”but that you need not write downвЂќ (he turned suddenly to
the secretary); вЂњthatвЂ™s my personal life, gentlemen, that doesnвЂ™t concern
you, the bottom of my heart, thatвЂ™s to say.... But of the murder of my old
father IвЂ™m not guilty. ThatвЂ™s a wild idea. ItвЂ™s quite a wild idea!... I
will prove you that and youвЂ™ll be convinced directly.... You will laugh,
gentlemen. YouвЂ™ll laugh yourselves at your suspicion!...вЂќ

вЂњBe calm, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ said the investigating lawyer evidently
trying to allay MityaвЂ™s excitement by his own composure. вЂњBefore we go on
with our inquiry, I should like, if you will consent to answer, to hear
you confirm the statement that you disliked your father, Fyodor
Pavlovitch, that you were involved in continual disputes with him. Here at
least, a quarter of an hour ago, you exclaimed that you wanted to kill
him: вЂI didnвЂ™t kill him,вЂ™ you said, вЂbut I wanted to kill him.вЂ™ вЂќ

вЂњDid I exclaim that? Ach, that may be so, gentlemen! Yes, unhappily, I did
want to kill him ... many times I wanted to ... unhappily, unhappily!вЂќ

вЂњYou wanted to. Would you consent to explain what motives precisely led
you to such a sentiment of hatred for your parent?вЂќ

вЂњWhat is there to explain, gentlemen?вЂќ Mitya shrugged his shoulders
sullenly, looking down. вЂњI have never concealed my feelings. All the town
knows about itвЂ”every one knows in the tavern. Only lately I declared them
in Father ZossimaвЂ™s cell.... And the very same day, in the evening I beat
my father. I nearly killed him, and I swore IвЂ™d come again and kill him,
before witnesses.... Oh, a thousand witnesses! IвЂ™ve been shouting it aloud
for the last month, any one can tell you that!... The fact stares you in
the face, it speaks for itself, it cries aloud, but feelings, gentlemen,
feelings are another matter. You see, gentlemenвЂќвЂ”Mitya frownedвЂ”вЂњit seems
to me that about feelings youвЂ™ve no right to question me. I know that you
are bound by your office, I quite understand that, but thatвЂ™s my affair,
my private, intimate affair, yet ... since I havenвЂ™t concealed my feelings
in the past ... in the tavern, for instance, IвЂ™ve talked to every one, so
... so I wonвЂ™t make a secret of it now. You see, I understand, gentlemen,
that there are terrible facts against me in this business. I told every
one that IвЂ™d kill him, and now, all of a sudden, heвЂ™s been killed. So it
must have been me! Ha ha! I can make allowances for you, gentlemen, I can
quite make allowances. IвЂ™m struck all of a heap myself, for who can have
murdered him, if not I? ThatвЂ™s what it comes to, isnвЂ™t it? If not I, who
can it be, who? Gentlemen, I want to know, I insist on knowing!вЂќ he
exclaimed suddenly. вЂњWhere was he murdered? How was he murdered? How, and
with what? Tell me,вЂќ he asked quickly, looking at the two lawyers.

вЂњWe found him in his study, lying on his back on the floor, with his head
battered in,вЂќ said the prosecutor.

вЂњThatвЂ™s horrible!вЂќ Mitya shuddered and, putting his elbows on the table,
hid his face in his right hand.

вЂњWe will continue,вЂќ interposed Nikolay Parfenovitch. вЂњSo what was it that
impelled you to this sentiment of hatred? You have asserted in public, I
believe, that it was based upon jealousy?вЂќ

вЂњWell, yes, jealousy. And not only jealousy.вЂќ

вЂњDisputes about money?вЂќ

вЂњYes, about money, too.вЂќ

вЂњThere was a dispute about three thousand roubles, I think, which you
claimed as part of your inheritance?вЂќ

вЂњThree thousand! More, more,вЂќ cried Mitya hotly; вЂњmore than six thousand,
more than ten, perhaps. I told every one so, shouted it at them. But I
made up my mind to let it go at three thousand. I was desperately in need
of that three thousand ... so the bundle of notes for three thousand that
I knew he kept under his pillow, ready for Grushenka, I considered as
simply stolen from me. Yes, gentlemen, I looked upon it as mine, as my own
property....вЂќ

The prosecutor looked significantly at the investigating lawyer, and had
time to wink at him on the sly.

вЂњWe will return to that subject later,вЂќ said the lawyer promptly. вЂњYou
will allow us to note that point and write it down; that you looked upon
that money as your own property?вЂќ

вЂњWrite it down, by all means. I know thatвЂ™s another fact that tells
against me, but IвЂ™m not afraid of facts and I tell them against myself. Do
you hear? Do you know, gentlemen, you take me for a different sort of man
from what I am,вЂќ he added, suddenly gloomy and dejected. вЂњYou have to deal
with a man of honor, a man of the highest honor; above allвЂ”donвЂ™t lose
sight of itвЂ”a man whoвЂ™s done a lot of nasty things, but has always been,
and still is, honorable at bottom, in his inner being. I donвЂ™t know how to
express it. ThatвЂ™s just whatвЂ™s made me wretched all my life, that I
yearned to be honorable, that I was, so to say, a martyr to a sense of
honor, seeking for it with a lantern, with the lantern of Diogenes, and
yet all my life IвЂ™ve been doing filthy things like all of us, gentlemen
... that is like me alone. That was a mistake, like me alone, me alone!...
Gentlemen, my head aches ...вЂќ His brows contracted with pain. вЂњYou see,
gentlemen, I couldnвЂ™t bear the look of him, there was something in him
ignoble, impudent, trampling on everything sacred, something sneering and
irreverent, loathsome, loathsome. But now that heвЂ™s dead, I feel
differently.вЂќ

вЂњHow do you mean?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t feel differently, but I wish I hadnвЂ™t hated him so.вЂќ

вЂњYou feel penitent?вЂќ

вЂњNo, not penitent, donвЂ™t write that. IвЂ™m not much good myself, IвЂ™m not
very beautiful, so I had no right to consider him repulsive. ThatвЂ™s what I
mean. Write that down, if you like.вЂќ

Saying this Mitya became very mournful. He had grown more and more gloomy
as the inquiry continued.

At that moment another unexpected scene followed. Though Grushenka had
been removed, she had not been taken far away, only into the room next but
one from the blue room, in which the examination was proceeding. It was a
little room with one window, next beyond the large room in which they had
danced and feasted so lavishly. She was sitting there with no one by her
but Maximov, who was terribly depressed, terribly scared, and clung to her
side, as though for security. At their door stood one of the peasants with
a metal plate on his breast. Grushenka was crying, and suddenly her grief
was too much for her, she jumped up, flung up her arms and, with a loud
wail of sorrow, rushed out of the room to him, to her Mitya, and so
unexpectedly that they had not time to stop her. Mitya, hearing her cry,
trembled, jumped up, and with a yell rushed impetuously to meet her, not
knowing what he was doing. But they were not allowed to come together,
though they saw one another. He was seized by the arms. He struggled, and
tried to tear himself away. It took three or four men to hold him. She was
seized too, and he saw her stretching out her arms to him, crying aloud as
they carried her away. When the scene was over, he came to himself again,
sitting in the same place as before, opposite the investigating lawyer,
and crying out to them:

вЂњWhat do you want with her? Why do you torment her? SheвЂ™s done nothing,
nothing!...вЂќ

The lawyers tried to soothe him. About ten minutes passed like this. At
last Mihail Makarovitch, who had been absent, came hurriedly into the
room, and said in a loud and excited voice to the prosecutor:

вЂњSheвЂ™s been removed, sheвЂ™s downstairs. Will you allow me to say one word
to this unhappy man, gentlemen? In your presence, gentlemen, in your
presence.вЂќ

вЂњBy all means, Mihail Makarovitch,вЂќ answered the investigating lawyer. вЂњIn
the present case we have nothing against it.вЂќ

вЂњListen, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, my dear fellow,вЂќ began the police captain,
and there was a look of warm, almost fatherly, feeling for the luckless
prisoner on his excited face. вЂњI took your Agrafena Alexandrovna
downstairs myself, and confided her to the care of the landlordвЂ™s
daughters, and that old fellow Maximov is with her all the time. And I
soothed her, do you hear? I soothed and calmed her. I impressed on her
that you have to clear yourself, so she mustnвЂ™t hinder you, must not
depress you, or you may lose your head and say the wrong thing in your
evidence. In fact, I talked to her and she understood. SheвЂ™s a sensible
girl, my boy, a goodвЂђhearted girl, she would have kissed my old hands,
begging help for you. She sent me herself, to tell you not to worry about
her. And I must go, my dear fellow, I must go and tell her that you are
calm and comforted about her. And so you must be calm, do you understand?
I was unfair to her; she is a Christian soul, gentlemen, yes, I tell you,
sheвЂ™s a gentle soul, and not to blame for anything. So what am I to tell
her, Dmitri Fyodorovitch? Will you sit quiet or not?вЂќ

The goodвЂђnatured police captain said a great deal that was irregular, but
GrushenkaвЂ™s suffering, a fellow creatureвЂ™s suffering, touched his goodвЂђ
natured heart, and tears stood in his eyes. Mitya jumped up and rushed
towards him.

вЂњForgive me, gentlemen, oh, allow me, allow me!вЂќ he cried. вЂњYouвЂ™ve the
heart of an angel, an angel, Mihail Makarovitch, I thank you for her. I
will, I will be calm, cheerful, in fact. Tell her, in the kindness of your
heart, that I am cheerful, quite cheerful, that I shall be laughing in a
minute, knowing that she has a guardian angel like you. I shall have done
with all this directly, and as soon as IвЂ™m free, IвЂ™ll be with her, sheвЂ™ll
see, let her wait. Gentlemen,вЂќ he said, turning to the two lawyers, вЂњnow
IвЂ™ll open my whole soul to you; IвЂ™ll pour out everything. WeвЂ™ll finish
this off directly, finish it off gayly. We shall laugh at it in the end,
shanвЂ™t we? But, gentlemen, that woman is the queen of my heart. Oh, let me
tell you that. That one thing IвЂ™ll tell you now.... I see IвЂ™m with
honorable men. She is my light, she is my holy one, and if only you knew!
Did you hear her cry, вЂIвЂ™ll go to death with youвЂ™? And what have I, a
penniless beggar, done for her? Why such love for me? How can a clumsy,
ugly brute like me, with my ugly face, deserve such love, that she is
ready to go to exile with me? And how she fell down at your feet for my
sake, just now!... and yet sheвЂ™s proud and has done nothing! How can I
help adoring her, how can I help crying out and rushing to her as I did
just now? Gentlemen, forgive me! But now, now I am comforted.вЂќ

And he sank back in his chair and, covering his face with his hands, burst
into tears. But they were happy tears. He recovered himself instantly. The
old police captain seemed much pleased, and the lawyers also. They felt
that the examination was passing into a new phase. When the police captain
went out, Mitya was positively gay.

вЂњNow, gentlemen, I am at your disposal, entirely at your disposal. And if
it were not for all these trivial details, we should understand one
another in a minute. IвЂ™m at those details again. IвЂ™m at your disposal,
gentlemen, but I declare that we must have mutual confidence, you in me
and I in you, or thereвЂ™ll be no end to it. I speak in your interests. To
business, gentlemen, to business, and donвЂ™t rummage in my soul; donвЂ™t
tease me with trifles, but only ask me about facts and what matters, and I
will satisfy you at once. And damn the details!вЂќ

So spoke Mitya. The interrogation began again.



Chapter IV. The Second Ordeal


вЂњYou donвЂ™t know how you encourage us, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, by your
readiness to answer,вЂќ said Nikolay Parfenovitch, with an animated air, and
obvious satisfaction beaming in his very prominent, shortвЂђsighted, light
gray eyes, from which he had removed his spectacles a moment before. вЂњAnd
you have made a very just remark about the mutual confidence, without
which it is sometimes positively impossible to get on in cases of such
importance, if the suspected party really hopes and desires to defend
himself and is in a position to do so. We, on our side, will do everything
in our power, and you can see for yourself how we are conducting the case.
You approve, Ippolit Kirillovitch?вЂќ He turned to the prosecutor.

вЂњOh, undoubtedly,вЂќ replied the prosecutor. His tone was somewhat cold,
compared with Nikolay ParfenovitchвЂ™s impulsiveness.

I will note once for all that Nikolay Parfenovitch, who had but lately
arrived among us, had from the first felt marked respect for Ippolit
Kirillovitch, our prosecutor, and had become almost his bosom friend. He
was almost the only person who put implicit faith in Ippolit
KirillovitchвЂ™s extraordinary talents as a psychologist and orator and in
the justice of his grievance. He had heard of him in Petersburg. On the
other hand, young Nikolay Parfenovitch was the only person in the whole
world whom our вЂњunappreciatedвЂќ prosecutor genuinely liked. On their way to
Mokroe they had time to come to an understanding about the present case.
And now as they sat at the table, the sharpвЂђwitted junior caught and
interpreted every indication on his senior colleagueвЂ™s faceвЂ”half a word, a
glance, or a wink.

вЂњGentlemen, only let me tell my own story and donвЂ™t interrupt me with
trivial questions and IвЂ™ll tell you everything in a moment,вЂќ said Mitya
excitedly.

вЂњExcellent! Thank you. But before we proceed to listen to your
communication, will you allow me to inquire as to another little fact of
great interest to us? I mean the ten roubles you borrowed yesterday at
about five oвЂ™clock on the security of your pistols, from your friend,
Pyotr Ilyitch Perhotin.вЂќ

вЂњI pledged them, gentlemen. I pledged them for ten roubles. What more?
ThatвЂ™s all about it. As soon as I got back to town I pledged them.вЂќ

вЂњYou got back to town? Then you had been out of town?вЂќ

вЂњYes, I went a journey of forty versts into the country. DidnвЂ™t you know?вЂќ

The prosecutor and Nikolay Parfenovitch exchanged glances.

вЂњWell, how would it be if you began your story with a systematic
description of all you did yesterday, from the morning onwards? Allow us,
for instance, to inquire why you were absent from the town, and just when
you left and when you came backвЂ”all those facts.вЂќ

вЂњYou should have asked me like that from the beginning,вЂќ cried Mitya,
laughing aloud, вЂњand, if you like, we wonвЂ™t begin from yesterday, but from
the morning of the day before; then youвЂ™ll understand how, why, and where
I went. I went the day before yesterday, gentlemen, to a merchant of the
town, called Samsonov, to borrow three thousand roubles from him on safe
security. It was a pressing matter, gentlemen, it was a sudden necessity.вЂќ

вЂњAllow me to interrupt you,вЂќ the prosecutor put in politely. вЂњWhy were you
in such pressing need for just that sum, three thousand?вЂќ

вЂњOh, gentlemen, you neednвЂ™t go into details, how, when and why, and why
just so much money, and not so much, and all that rigmarole. Why, itвЂ™ll
run to three volumes, and then youвЂ™ll want an epilogue!вЂќ

Mitya said all this with the goodвЂђnatured but impatient familiarity of a
man who is anxious to tell the whole truth and is full of the best
intentions.

вЂњGentlemen!вЂќвЂ”he corrected himself hurriedlyвЂ”вЂњdonвЂ™t be vexed with me for my
restiveness, I beg you again. Believe me once more, I feel the greatest
respect for you and understand the true position of affairs. DonвЂ™t think
IвЂ™m drunk. IвЂ™m quite sober now. And, besides, being drunk would be no
hindrance. ItвЂ™s with me, you know, like the saying: вЂWhen he is sober, he
is a fool; when he is drunk, he is a wise man.вЂ™ Ha ha! But I see,
gentlemen, itвЂ™s not the proper thing to make jokes to you, till weвЂ™ve had
our explanation, I mean. And IвЂ™ve my own dignity to keep up, too. I quite
understand the difference for the moment. I am, after all, in the position
of a criminal, and so, far from being on equal terms with you. And itвЂ™s
your business to watch me. I canвЂ™t expect you to pat me on the head for
what I did to Grigory, for one canвЂ™t break old menвЂ™s heads with impunity.
I suppose youвЂ™ll put me away for him for six months, or a year perhaps, in
a house of correction. I donвЂ™t know what the punishment isвЂ”but it will be
without loss of the rights of my rank, without loss of my rank, wonвЂ™t it?
So you see, gentlemen, I understand the distinction between us.... But you
must see that you could puzzle God Himself with such questions. вЂHow did
you step? Where did you step? When did you step? And on what did you
step?вЂ™ I shall get mixed up, if you go on like this, and you will put it
all down against me. And what will that lead to? To nothing! And even if
itвЂ™s nonsense IвЂ™m talking now, let me finish, and you, gentlemen, being
men of honor and refinement, will forgive me! IвЂ™ll finish by asking you,
gentlemen, to drop that conventional method of questioning. I mean,
beginning from some miserable trifle, how I got up, what I had for
breakfast, how I spat, and where I spat, and so distracting the attention
of the criminal, suddenly stun him with an overwhelming question, вЂWhom
did you murder? Whom did you rob?вЂ™ Ha ha! ThatвЂ™s your regulation method,
thatвЂ™s where all your cunning comes in. You can put peasants off their
guard like that, but not me. I know the tricks. IвЂ™ve been in the service,
too. Ha ha ha! YouвЂ™re not angry, gentlemen? You forgive my impertinence?вЂќ
he cried, looking at them with a goodвЂђnature that was almost surprising.
вЂњItвЂ™s only Mitya Karamazov, you know, so you can overlook it. It would be
inexcusable in a sensible man; but you can forgive it in Mitya. Ha ha!вЂќ

Nikolay Parfenovitch listened, and laughed too. Though the prosecutor did
not laugh, he kept his eyes fixed keenly on Mitya, as though anxious not
to miss the least syllable, the slightest movement, the smallest twitch of
any feature of his face.

вЂњThatвЂ™s how we have treated you from the beginning,вЂќ said Nikolay
Parfenovitch, still laughing. вЂњWe havenвЂ™t tried to put you out by asking
how you got up in the morning and what you had for breakfast. We began,
indeed, with questions of the greatest importance.вЂќ

вЂњI understand. I saw it and appreciated it, and I appreciate still more
your present kindness to me, an unprecedented kindness, worthy of your
noble hearts. We three here are gentlemen, and let everything be on the
footing of mutual confidence between educated, wellвЂђbred people, who have
the common bond of noble birth and honor. In any case, allow me to look
upon you as my best friends at this moment of my life, at this moment when
my honor is assailed. ThatвЂ™s no offense to you, gentlemen, is it?вЂќ

вЂњOn the contrary. YouвЂ™ve expressed all that so well, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ
Nikolay Parfenovitch answered with dignified approbation.

вЂњAnd enough of those trivial questions, gentlemen, all those tricky
questions!вЂќ cried Mitya enthusiastically. вЂњOr thereвЂ™s simply no knowing
where we shall get to! Is there?вЂќ

вЂњI will follow your sensible advice entirely,вЂќ the prosecutor interposed,
addressing Mitya. вЂњI donвЂ™t withdraw my question, however. It is now
vitally important for us to know exactly why you needed that sum, I mean
precisely three thousand.вЂќ

вЂњWhy I needed it?... Oh, for one thing and another.... Well, it was to pay
a debt.вЂќ

вЂњA debt to whom?вЂќ

вЂњThat I absolutely refuse to answer, gentlemen. Not because I couldnвЂ™t, or
because I shouldnвЂ™t dare, or because it would be damaging, for itвЂ™s all a
paltry matter and absolutely trifling, butвЂ”I wonвЂ™t, because itвЂ™s a matter
of principle: thatвЂ™s my private life, and I wonвЂ™t allow any intrusion into
my private life. ThatвЂ™s my principle. Your question has no bearing on the
case, and whatever has nothing to do with the case is my private affair. I
wanted to pay a debt. I wanted to pay a debt of honor but to whom I wonвЂ™t
say.вЂќ

вЂњAllow me to make a note of that,вЂќ said the prosecutor.

вЂњBy all means. Write down that I wonвЂ™t say, that I wonвЂ™t. Write that I
should think it dishonorable to say. Ech! you can write it; youвЂ™ve nothing
else to do with your time.вЂќ

вЂњAllow me to caution you, sir, and to remind you once more, if you are
unaware of it,вЂќ the prosecutor began, with a peculiar and stern
impressiveness, вЂњthat you have a perfect right not to answer the questions
put to you now, and we on our side have no right to extort an answer from
you, if you decline to give it for one reason or another. That is entirely
a matter for your personal decision. But it is our duty, on the other
hand, in such cases as the present, to explain and set before you the
degree of injury you will be doing yourself by refusing to give this or
that piece of evidence. After which I will beg you to continue.вЂќ

вЂњGentlemen, IвЂ™m not angry ... I ...вЂќ Mitya muttered in a rather
disconcerted tone. вЂњWell, gentlemen, you see, that Samsonov to whom I went
then ...вЂќ

We will, of course, not reproduce his account of what is known to the
reader already. Mitya was impatiently anxious not to omit the slightest
detail. At the same time he was in a hurry to get it over. But as he gave
his evidence it was written down, and therefore they had continually to
pull him up. Mitya disliked this, but submitted; got angry, though still
goodвЂђhumoredly. He did, it is true, exclaim, from time to time,
вЂњGentlemen, thatвЂ™s enough to make an angel out of patience!вЂќ Or,
вЂњGentlemen, itвЂ™s no good your irritating me.вЂќ

But even though he exclaimed he still preserved for a time his genially
expansive mood. So he told them how Samsonov had made a fool of him two
days before. (He had completely realized by now that he had been fooled.)
The sale of his watch for six roubles to obtain money for the journey was
something new to the lawyers. They were at once greatly interested, and
even, to MityaвЂ™s intense indignation, thought it necessary to write the
fact down as a secondary confirmation of the circumstance that he had
hardly a farthing in his pocket at the time. Little by little Mitya began
to grow surly. Then, after describing his journey to see Lyagavy, the
night spent in the stifling hut, and so on, he came to his return to the
town. Here he began, without being particularly urged, to give a minute
account of the agonies of jealousy he endured on GrushenkaвЂ™s account.

He was heard with silent attention. They inquired particularly into the
circumstance of his having a place of ambush in Marya KondratyevnaвЂ™s house
at the back of Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s garden to keep watch on Grushenka, and
of SmerdyakovвЂ™s bringing him information. They laid particular stress on
this, and noted it down. Of his jealousy he spoke warmly and at length,
and though inwardly ashamed at exposing his most intimate feelings to
вЂњpublic ignominy,вЂќ so to speak, he evidently overcame his shame in order
to tell the truth. The frigid severity, with which the investigating
lawyer, and still more the prosecutor, stared intently at him as he told
his story, disconcerted him at last considerably.

вЂњThat boy, Nikolay Parfenovitch, to whom I was talking nonsense about
women only a few days ago, and that sickly prosecutor are not worth my
telling this to,вЂќ he reflected mournfully. вЂњItвЂ™s ignominious. вЂBe patient,
humble, hold thy peace.вЂ™ вЂќ He wound up his reflections with that line. But
he pulled himself together to go on again. When he came to telling of his
visit to Madame Hohlakov, he regained his spirits and even wished to tell
a little anecdote of that lady which had nothing to do with the case. But
the investigating lawyer stopped him, and civilly suggested that he should
pass on to вЂњmore essential matters.вЂќ At last, when he described his
despair and told them how, when he left Madame HohlakovвЂ™s, he thought that
heвЂ™d вЂњget three thousand if he had to murder some one to do it,вЂќ they
stopped him again and noted down that he had вЂњmeant to murder some one.вЂќ
Mitya let them write it without protest. At last he reached the point in
his story when he learned that Grushenka had deceived him and had returned
from SamsonovвЂ™s as soon as he left her there, though she had said that she
would stay there till midnight.

вЂњIf I didnвЂ™t kill Fenya then, gentlemen, it was only because I hadnвЂ™t
time,вЂќ broke from him suddenly at that point in his story. That, too, was
carefully written down. Mitya waited gloomily, and was beginning to tell
how he ran into his fatherвЂ™s garden when the investigating lawyer suddenly
stopped him, and opening the big portfolio that lay on the sofa beside him
he brought out the brass pestle.

вЂњDo you recognize this object?вЂќ he asked, showing it to Mitya.

вЂњOh, yes,вЂќ he laughed gloomily. вЂњOf course I recognize it. Let me have a
look at it.... Damn it, never mind!вЂќ

вЂњYou have forgotten to mention it,вЂќ observed the investigating lawyer.

вЂњHang it all, I shouldnвЂ™t have concealed it from you. Do you suppose I
could have managed without it? It simply escaped my memory.вЂќ

вЂњBe so good as to tell us precisely how you came to arm yourself with it.вЂќ

вЂњCertainly I will be so good, gentlemen.вЂќ

And Mitya described how he took the pestle and ran.

вЂњBut what object had you in view in arming yourself with such a weapon?вЂќ

вЂњWhat object? No object. I just picked it up and ran off.вЂќ

вЂњWhat for, if you had no object?вЂќ

MityaвЂ™s wrath flared up. He looked intently at вЂњthe boyвЂќ and smiled
gloomily and malignantly. He was feeling more and more ashamed at having
told вЂњsuch peopleвЂќ the story of his jealousy so sincerely and
spontaneously.

вЂњBother the pestle!вЂќ broke from him suddenly.

вЂњBut stillвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњOh, to keep off dogs.... Oh, because it was dark.... In case anything
turned up.вЂќ

вЂњBut have you ever on previous occasions taken a weapon with you when you
went out, since youвЂ™re afraid of the dark?вЂќ

вЂњUgh! damn it all, gentlemen! ThereвЂ™s positively no talking to you!вЂќ cried
Mitya, exasperated beyond endurance, and turning to the secretary, crimson
with anger, he said quickly, with a note of fury in his voice:

вЂњWrite down at once ... at once ... вЂthat I snatched up the pestle to go
and kill my father ... Fyodor Pavlovitch ... by hitting him on the head
with it!вЂ™ Well, now are you satisfied, gentlemen? Are your minds
relieved?вЂќ he said, glaring defiantly at the lawyers.

вЂњWe quite understand that you made that statement just now through
exasperation with us and the questions we put to you, which you consider
trivial, though they are, in fact, essential,вЂќ the prosecutor remarked
dryly in reply.

вЂњWell, upon my word, gentlemen! Yes, I took the pestle.... What does one
pick things up for at such moments? I donвЂ™t know what for. I snatched it
up and ranвЂ”thatвЂ™s all. For to me, gentlemen, _passons_, or I declare I
wonвЂ™t tell you any more.вЂќ

He sat with his elbows on the table and his head in his hand. He sat
sideways to them and gazed at the wall, struggling against a feeling of
nausea. He had, in fact, an awful inclination to get up and declare that
he wouldnвЂ™t say another word, вЂњnot if you hang me for it.вЂќ

вЂњYou see, gentlemen,вЂќ he said at last, with difficulty controlling
himself, вЂњyou see. I listen to you and am haunted by a dream.... ItвЂ™s a
dream I have sometimes, you know.... I often dream itвЂ”itвЂ™s always the same
... that some one is hunting me, some one IвЂ™m awfully afraid of ... that
heвЂ™s hunting me in the dark, in the night ... tracking me, and I hide
somewhere from him, behind a door or cupboard, hide in a degrading way,
and the worst of it is, he always knows where I am, but he pretends not to
know where I am on purpose, to prolong my agony, to enjoy my terror....
ThatвЂ™s just what youвЂ™re doing now. ItвЂ™s just like that!вЂќ

вЂњIs that the sort of thing you dream about?вЂќ inquired the prosecutor.

вЂњYes, it is. DonвЂ™t you want to write it down?вЂќ said Mitya, with a
distorted smile.

вЂњNo; no need to write it down. But still you do have curious dreams.вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s not a question of dreams now, gentlemenвЂ”this is realism, this is
real life! IвЂ™m a wolf and youвЂ™re the hunters. Well, hunt him down!вЂќ

вЂњYou are wrong to make such comparisons ...вЂќ began Nikolay Parfenovitch,
with extraordinary softness.

вЂњNo, IвЂ™m not wrong, not at all!вЂќ Mitya flared up again, though his
outburst of wrath had obviously relieved his heart. He grew more goodвЂђ
humored at every word. вЂњYou may not trust a criminal or a man on trial
tortured by your questions, but an honorable man, the honorable impulses
of the heart (I say that boldly!)вЂ”no! That you must believe you have no
right indeed ... butвЂ”


    Be silent, heart,
    Be patient, humble, hold thy peace.


Well, shall I go on?вЂќ he broke off gloomily.

вЂњIf youвЂ™ll be so kind,вЂќ answered Nikolay Parfenovitch.



Chapter V. The Third Ordeal


Though Mitya spoke sullenly, it was evident that he was trying more than
ever not to forget or miss a single detail of his story. He told them how
he had leapt over the fence into his fatherвЂ™s garden; how he had gone up
to the window; told them all that had passed under the window. Clearly,
precisely, distinctly, he described the feelings that troubled him during
those moments in the garden when he longed so terribly to know whether
Grushenka was with his father or not. But, strange to say, both the
lawyers listened now with a sort of awful reserve, looked coldly at him,
asked few questions. Mitya could gather nothing from their faces.

вЂњTheyвЂ™re angry and offended,вЂќ he thought. вЂњWell, bother them!вЂќ

When he described how he made up his mind at last to make the вЂњsignalвЂќ to
his father that Grushenka had come, so that he should open the window, the
lawyers paid no attention to the word вЂњsignal,вЂќ as though they entirely
failed to grasp the meaning of the word in this connection: so much so,
that Mitya noticed it. Coming at last to the moment when, seeing his
father peering out of the window, his hatred flared up and he pulled the
pestle out of his pocket, he suddenly, as though of design, stopped short.
He sat gazing at the wall and was aware that their eyes were fixed upon
him.

вЂњWell?вЂќ said the investigating lawyer. вЂњYou pulled out the weapon and ...
and what happened then?вЂќ

вЂњThen? Why, then I murdered him ... hit him on the head and cracked his
skull.... I suppose thatвЂ™s your story. ThatвЂ™s it!вЂќ

His eyes suddenly flashed. All his smothered wrath suddenly flamed up with
extraordinary violence in his soul.

вЂњOur story?вЂќ repeated Nikolay Parfenovitch. вЂњWellвЂ”and yours?вЂќ

Mitya dropped his eyes and was a long time silent.

вЂњMy story, gentlemen? Well, it was like this,вЂќ he began softly. вЂњWhether
it was some oneвЂ™s tears, or my mother prayed to God, or a good angel
kissed me at that instant, I donвЂ™t know. But the devil was conquered. I
rushed from the window and ran to the fence. My father was alarmed and,
for the first time, he saw me then, cried out, and sprang back from the
window. I remember that very well. I ran across the garden to the fence
... and there Grigory caught me, when I was sitting on the fence.вЂќ

At that point he raised his eyes at last and looked at his listeners. They
seemed to be staring at him with perfectly unruffled attention. A sort of
paroxysm of indignation seized on MityaвЂ™s soul.

вЂњWhy, youвЂ™re laughing at me at this moment, gentlemen!вЂќ he broke off
suddenly.

вЂњWhat makes you think that?вЂќ observed Nikolay Parfenovitch.

вЂњYou donвЂ™t believe one wordвЂ”thatвЂ™s why! I understand, of course, that I
have come to the vital point. The old manвЂ™s lying there now with his skull
broken, while IвЂ”after dramatically describing how I wanted to kill him,
and how I snatched up the pestleвЂ”I suddenly run away from the window. A
romance! Poetry! As though one could believe a fellow on his word. Ha ha!
You are scoffers, gentlemen!вЂќ

And he swung round on his chair so that it creaked.

вЂњAnd did you notice,вЂќ asked the prosecutor suddenly, as though not
observing MityaвЂ™s excitement, вЂњdid you notice when you ran away from the
window, whether the door into the garden was open?вЂќ

вЂњNo, it was not open.вЂќ

вЂњIt was not?вЂќ

вЂњIt was shut. And who could open it? Bah! the door. Wait a bit!вЂќ he seemed
suddenly to bethink himself, and almost with a start:

вЂњWhy, did you find the door open?вЂќ

вЂњYes, it was open.вЂќ

вЂњWhy, who could have opened it if you did not open it yourselves?вЂќ cried
Mitya, greatly astonished.

вЂњThe door stood open, and your fatherвЂ™s murderer undoubtedly went in at
that door, and, having accomplished the crime, went out again by the same
door,вЂќ the prosecutor pronounced deliberately, as though chiseling out
each word separately. вЂњThat is perfectly clear. The murder was committed
in the room and _not through the __ window_; that is absolutely certain
from the examination that has been made, from the position of the body and
everything. There can be no doubt of that circumstance.вЂќ

Mitya was absolutely dumbfounded.

вЂњBut thatвЂ™s utterly impossible!вЂќ he cried, completely at a loss. вЂњI ... I
didnвЂ™t go in.... I tell you positively, definitely, the door was shut the
whole time I was in the garden, and when I ran out of the garden. I only
stood at the window and saw him through the window. ThatвЂ™s all, thatвЂ™s
all.... I remember to the last minute. And if I didnвЂ™t remember, it would
be just the same. I know it, for no one knew the signals except
Smerdyakov, and me, and the dead man. And he wouldnвЂ™t have opened the door
to any one in the world without the signals.вЂќ

вЂњSignals? What signals?вЂќ asked the prosecutor, with greedy, almost
hysterical, curiosity. He instantly lost all trace of his reserve and
dignity. He asked the question with a sort of cringing timidity. He
scented an important fact of which he had known nothing, and was already
filled with dread that Mitya might be unwilling to disclose it.

вЂњSo you didnвЂ™t know!вЂќ Mitya winked at him with a malicious and mocking
smile. вЂњWhat if I wonвЂ™t tell you? From whom could you find out? No one
knew about the signals except my father, Smerdyakov, and me: that was all.
Heaven knew, too, but it wonвЂ™t tell you. But itвЂ™s an interesting fact.
ThereвЂ™s no knowing what you might build on it. Ha ha! Take comfort,
gentlemen, IвЂ™ll reveal it. YouвЂ™ve some foolish idea in your hearts. You
donвЂ™t know the man you have to deal with! You have to do with a prisoner
who gives evidence against himself, to his own damage! Yes, for IвЂ™m a man
of honor and youвЂ”are not.вЂќ

The prosecutor swallowed this without a murmur. He was trembling with
impatience to hear the new fact. Minutely and diffusely Mitya told them
everything about the signals invented by Fyodor Pavlovitch for Smerdyakov.
He told them exactly what every tap on the window meant, tapped the
signals on the table, and when Nikolay Parfenovitch said that he supposed
he, Mitya, had tapped the signal вЂњGrushenka has come,вЂќ when he tapped to
his father, he answered precisely that he had tapped that signal, that
вЂњGrushenka had come.вЂќ

вЂњSo now you can build up your tower,вЂќ Mitya broke off, and again turned
away from them contemptuously.

вЂњSo no one knew of the signals but your dead father, you, and the valet
Smerdyakov? And no one else?вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch inquired once more.

вЂњYes. The valet Smerdyakov, and Heaven. Write down about Heaven. That may
be of use. Besides, you will need God yourselves.вЂќ

And they had already, of course, begun writing it down. But while they
wrote, the prosecutor said suddenly, as though pitching on a new idea:

вЂњBut if Smerdyakov also knew of these signals and you absolutely deny all
responsibility for the death of your father, was it not he, perhaps, who
knocked the signal agreed upon, induced your father to open to him, and
then ... committed the crime?вЂќ

Mitya turned upon him a look of profound irony and intense hatred. His
silent stare lasted so long that it made the prosecutor blink.

вЂњYouвЂ™ve caught the fox again,вЂќ commented Mitya at last; вЂњyouвЂ™ve got the
beast by the tail. Ha ha! I see through you, Mr. Prosecutor. You thought,
of course, that I should jump at that, catch at your prompting, and shout
with all my might, вЂAie! itвЂ™s Smerdyakov; heвЂ™s the murderer.вЂ™ Confess
thatвЂ™s what you thought. Confess, and IвЂ™ll go on.вЂќ

But the prosecutor did not confess. He held his tongue and waited.

вЂњYouвЂ™re mistaken. IвЂ™m not going to shout вЂItвЂ™s Smerdyakov,вЂ™ вЂќ said Mitya.

вЂњAnd you donвЂ™t even suspect him?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, do you suspect him?вЂќ

вЂњHe is suspected, too.вЂќ

Mitya fixed his eyes on the floor.

вЂњJoking apart,вЂќ he brought out gloomily. вЂњListen. From the very beginning,
almost from the moment when I ran out to you from behind the curtain, IвЂ™ve
had the thought of Smerdyakov in my mind. IвЂ™ve been sitting here, shouting
that IвЂ™m innocent and thinking all the time вЂSmerdyakov!вЂ™ I canвЂ™t get
Smerdyakov out of my head. In fact, I, too, thought of Smerdyakov just
now; but only for a second. Almost at once I thought, вЂNo, itвЂ™s not
Smerdyakov.вЂ™ ItвЂ™s not his doing, gentlemen.вЂќ

вЂњIn that case is there anybody else you suspect?вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch
inquired cautiously.

вЂњI donвЂ™t know any one it could be, whether itвЂ™s the hand of Heaven or
Satan, but ... not Smerdyakov,вЂќ Mitya jerked out with decision.

вЂњBut what makes you affirm so confidently and emphatically that itвЂ™s not
he?вЂќ

вЂњFrom my convictionвЂ”my impression. Because Smerdyakov is a man of the most
abject character and a coward. HeвЂ™s not a coward, heвЂ™s the epitome of all
the cowardice in the world walking on two legs. He has the heart of a
chicken. When he talked to me, he was always trembling for fear I should
kill him, though I never raised my hand against him. He fell at my feet
and blubbered; he has kissed these very boots, literally, beseeching me
вЂnot to frighten him.вЂ™ Do you hear? вЂNot to frighten him.вЂ™ What a thing to
say! Why, I offered him money. HeвЂ™s a puling chickenвЂ”sickly, epileptic,
weakвЂђmindedвЂ”a child of eight could thrash him. He has no character worth
talking about. ItвЂ™s not Smerdyakov, gentlemen. He doesnвЂ™t care for money;
he wouldnвЂ™t take my presents. Besides, what motive had he for murdering
the old man? Why, heвЂ™s very likely his son, you knowвЂ”his natural son. Do
you know that?вЂќ

вЂњWe have heard that legend. But you are your fatherвЂ™s son, too, you know;
yet you yourself told every one you meant to murder him.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s a thrust! And a nasty, mean one, too! IвЂ™m not afraid! Oh,
gentlemen, isnвЂ™t it too base of you to say that to my face? ItвЂ™s base,
because I told you that myself. I not only wanted to murder him, but I
might have done it. And, whatвЂ™s more, I went out of my way to tell you of
my own accord that I nearly murdered him. But, you see, I didnвЂ™t murder
him; you see, my guardian angel saved meвЂ”thatвЂ™s what youвЂ™ve not taken into
account. And thatвЂ™s why itвЂ™s so base of you. For I didnвЂ™t kill him, I
didnвЂ™t kill him! Do you hear, I did not kill him.вЂќ

He was almost choking. He had not been so moved before during the whole
interrogation.

вЂњAnd what has he told you, gentlemenвЂ”Smerdyakov, I mean?вЂќ he added
suddenly, after a pause. вЂњMay I ask that question?вЂќ

вЂњYou may ask any question,вЂќ the prosecutor replied with frigid severity,
вЂњany question relating to the facts of the case, and we are, I repeat,
bound to answer every inquiry you make. We found the servant Smerdyakov,
concerning whom you inquire, lying unconscious in his bed, in an epileptic
fit of extreme severity, that had recurred, possibly, ten times. The
doctor who was with us told us, after seeing him, that he may possibly not
outlive the night.вЂќ

вЂњWell, if thatвЂ™s so, the devil must have killed him,вЂќ broke suddenly from
Mitya, as though until that moment he had been asking himself: вЂњWas it
Smerdyakov or not?вЂќ

вЂњWe will come back to this later,вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch decided. вЂњNow,
wouldnвЂ™t you like to continue your statement?вЂќ

Mitya asked for a rest. His request was courteously granted. After
resting, he went on with his story. But he was evidently depressed. He was
exhausted, mortified and morally shaken. To make things worse the
prosecutor exasperated him, as though intentionally, by vexatious
interruptions about вЂњtrifling points.вЂќ Scarcely had Mitya described how,
sitting on the wall, he had struck Grigory on the head with the pestle,
while the old man had hold of his left leg, and how he had then jumped
down to look at him, when the prosecutor stopped him to ask him to
describe exactly how he was sitting on the wall. Mitya was surprised.

вЂњOh, I was sitting like this, astride, one leg on one side of the wall and
one on the other.вЂќ

вЂњAnd the pestle?вЂќ

вЂњThe pestle was in my hand.вЂќ

вЂњNot in your pocket? Do you remember that precisely? Was it a violent blow
you gave him?вЂќ

вЂњIt must have been a violent one. But why do you ask?вЂќ

вЂњWould you mind sitting on the chair just as you sat on the wall then and
showing us just how you moved your arm, and in what direction?вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re making fun of me, arenвЂ™t you?вЂќ asked Mitya, looking haughtily at
the speaker; but the latter did not flinch.

Mitya turned abruptly, sat astride on his chair, and swung his arm.

вЂњThis was how I struck him! ThatвЂ™s how I knocked him down! What more do
you want?вЂќ

вЂњThank you. May I trouble you now to explain why you jumped down, with
what object, and what you had in view?вЂќ

вЂњOh, hang it!... I jumped down to look at the man IвЂ™d hurt ... I donвЂ™t
know what for!вЂќ

вЂњThough you were so excited and were running away?вЂќ

вЂњYes, though I was excited and running away.вЂќ

вЂњYou wanted to help him?вЂќ

вЂњHelp!... Yes, perhaps I did want to help him.... I donвЂ™t remember.вЂќ

вЂњYou donвЂ™t remember? Then you didnвЂ™t quite know what you were doing?вЂќ

вЂњNot at all. I remember everythingвЂ”every detail. I jumped down to look at
him, and wiped his face with my handkerchief.вЂќ

вЂњWe have seen your handkerchief. Did you hope to restore him to
consciousness?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know whether I hoped it. I simply wanted to make sure whether he
was alive or not.вЂќ

вЂњAh! You wanted to be sure? Well, what then?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™m not a doctor. I couldnвЂ™t decide. I ran away thinking IвЂ™d killed him.
And now heвЂ™s recovered.вЂќ

вЂњExcellent,вЂќ commented the prosecutor. вЂњThank you. ThatвЂ™s all I wanted.
Kindly proceed.вЂќ

Alas! it never entered MityaвЂ™s head to tell them, though he remembered it,
that he had jumped back from pity, and standing over the prostrate figure
had even uttered some words of regret: вЂњYouвЂ™ve come to grief, old
manвЂ”thereвЂ™s no help for it. Well, there you must lie.вЂќ

The prosecutor could only draw one conclusion: that the man had jumped
back вЂњat such a moment and in such excitement simply with the object of
ascertaining whether the _only_ witness of his crime were dead; that he
must therefore have been a man of great strength, coolness, decision and
foresight even at such a moment,вЂќ ... and so on. The prosecutor was
satisfied: вЂњIвЂ™ve provoked the nervous fellow by вЂtriflesвЂ™ and he has said
more than he meant to.вЂќ

With painful effort Mitya went on. But this time he was pulled up
immediately by Nikolay Parfenovitch.

вЂњHow came you to run to the servant, Fedosya Markovna, with your hands so
covered with blood, and, as it appears, your face, too?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, I didnвЂ™t notice the blood at all at the time,вЂќ answered Mitya.

вЂњThatвЂ™s quite likely. It does happen sometimes.вЂќ The prosecutor exchanged
glances with Nikolay Parfenovitch.

вЂњI simply didnвЂ™t notice. YouвЂ™re quite right there, prosecutor,вЂќ Mitya
assented suddenly.

Next came the account of MityaвЂ™s sudden determination to вЂњstep asideвЂќ and
make way for their happiness. But he could not make up his mind to open
his heart to them as before, and tell them about вЂњthe queen of his soul.вЂќ
He disliked speaking of her before these chilly persons вЂњwho were
fastening on him like bugs.вЂќ And so in response to their reiterated
questions he answered briefly and abruptly:

вЂњWell, I made up my mind to kill myself. What had I left to live for? That
question stared me in the face. Her first rightful lover had come back,
the man who wronged her but whoвЂ™d hurried back to offer his love, after
five years, and atone for the wrong with marriage.... So I knew it was all
over for me.... And behind me disgrace, and that bloodвЂ”GrigoryвЂ™s.... What
had I to live for? So I went to redeem the pistols I had pledged, to load
them and put a bullet in my brain toвЂђmorrow.вЂќ

вЂњAnd a grand feast the night before?вЂќ

вЂњYes, a grand feast the night before. Damn it all, gentlemen! Do make
haste and finish it. I meant to shoot myself not far from here, beyond the
village, and IвЂ™d planned to do it at five oвЂ™clock in the morning. And I
had a note in my pocket already. I wrote it at PerhotinвЂ™s when I loaded my
pistols. HereвЂ™s the letter. Read it! ItвЂ™s not for you I tell it,вЂќ he added
contemptuously. He took it from his waistcoat pocket and flung it on the
table. The lawyers read it with curiosity, and, as is usual, added it to
the papers connected with the case.

вЂњAnd you didnвЂ™t even think of washing your hands at PerhotinвЂ™s? You were
not afraid then of arousing suspicion?вЂќ

вЂњWhat suspicion? Suspicion or not, I should have galloped here just the
same, and shot myself at five oвЂ™clock, and you wouldnвЂ™t have been in time
to do anything. If it hadnвЂ™t been for whatвЂ™s happened to my father, you
would have known nothing about it, and wouldnвЂ™t have come here. Oh, itвЂ™s
the devilвЂ™s doing. It was the devil murdered father, it was through the
devil that you found it out so soon. How did you manage to get here so
quick? ItвЂ™s marvelous, a dream!вЂќ

вЂњMr. Perhotin informed us that when you came to him, you held in your
hands ... your bloodвЂђstained hands ... your money ... a lot of money ... a
bundle of hundredвЂђrouble notes, and that his servantвЂђboy saw it too.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s true, gentlemen. I remember it was so.вЂќ

вЂњNow, thereвЂ™s one little point presents itself. Can you inform us,вЂќ
Nikolay Parfenovitch began, with extreme gentleness, вЂњwhere did you get so
much money all of a sudden, when it appears from the facts, from the
reckoning of time, that you had not been home?вЂќ

The prosecutorвЂ™s brows contracted at the question being asked so plainly,
but he did not interrupt Nikolay Parfenovitch.

вЂњNo, I didnвЂ™t go home,вЂќ answered Mitya, apparently perfectly composed, but
looking at the floor.

вЂњAllow me then to repeat my question,вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch went on as
though creeping up to the subject. вЂњWhere were you able to procure such a
sum all at once, when by your own confession, at five oвЂ™clock the same day
youвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњI was in want of ten roubles and pledged my pistols with Perhotin, and
then went to Madame Hohlakov to borrow three thousand which she wouldnвЂ™t
give me, and so on, and all the rest of it,вЂќ Mitya interrupted sharply.
вЂњYes, gentlemen, I was in want of it, and suddenly thousands turned up,
eh? Do you know, gentlemen, youвЂ™re both afraid now вЂwhat if he wonвЂ™t tell
us where he got it?вЂ™ ThatвЂ™s just how it is. IвЂ™m not going to tell you,
gentlemen. YouвЂ™ve guessed right. YouвЂ™ll never know,вЂќ said Mitya, chipping
out each word with extraordinary determination. The lawyers were silent
for a moment.

вЂњYou must understand, Mr. Karamazov, that it is of vital importance for us
to know,вЂќ said Nikolay Parfenovitch, softly and suavely.

вЂњI understand; but still I wonвЂ™t tell you.вЂќ

The prosecutor, too, intervened, and again reminded the prisoner that he
was at liberty to refuse to answer questions, if he thought it to his
interest, and so on. But in view of the damage he might do himself by his
silence, especially in a case of such importance asвЂ”

вЂњAnd so on, gentlemen, and so on. Enough! IвЂ™ve heard that rigmarole
before,вЂќ Mitya interrupted again. вЂњI can see for myself how important it
is, and that this is the vital point, and still I wonвЂ™t say.вЂќ

вЂњWhat is it to us? ItвЂ™s not our business, but yours. You are doing
yourself harm,вЂќ observed Nikolay Parfenovitch nervously.

вЂњYou see, gentlemen, joking apartвЂќвЂ”Mitya lifted his eyes and looked firmly
at them bothвЂ”вЂњI had an inkling from the first that we should come to
loggerheads at this point. But at first when I began to give my evidence,
it was all still far away and misty; it was all floating, and I was so
simple that I began with the supposition of mutual confidence existing
between us. Now I can see for myself that such confidence is out of the
question, for in any case we were bound to come to this cursed stumblingвЂђ
block. And now weвЂ™ve come to it! ItвЂ™s impossible and thereвЂ™s an end of it!
But I donвЂ™t blame you. You canвЂ™t believe it all simply on my word. I
understand that, of course.вЂќ

He relapsed into gloomy silence.

вЂњCouldnвЂ™t you, without abandoning your resolution to be silent about the
chief point, could you not, at the same time, give us some slight hint as
to the nature of the motives which are strong enough to induce you to
refuse to answer, at a crisis so full of danger to you?вЂќ

Mitya smiled mournfully, almost dreamily.

вЂњIвЂ™m much more goodвЂђnatured than you think, gentlemen. IвЂ™ll tell you the
reason why and give you that hint, though you donвЂ™t deserve it. I wonвЂ™t
speak of that, gentlemen, because it would be a stain on my honor. The
answer to the question where I got the money would expose me to far
greater disgrace than the murder and robbing of my father, if I had
murdered and robbed him. ThatвЂ™s why I canвЂ™t tell you. I canвЂ™t for fear of
disgrace. What, gentlemen, are you going to write that down?вЂќ

вЂњYes, weвЂ™ll write it down,вЂќ lisped Nikolay Parfenovitch.

вЂњYou ought not to write that down about вЂdisgrace.вЂ™ I only told you that
in the goodness of my heart. I neednвЂ™t have told you. I made you a present
of it, so to speak, and you pounce upon it at once. Oh, well, writeвЂ”write
what you like,вЂќ he concluded, with scornful disgust. вЂњIвЂ™m not afraid of
you and I can still hold up my head before you.вЂќ

вЂњAnd canвЂ™t you tell us the nature of that disgrace?вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch
hazarded.

The prosecutor frowned darkly.

вЂњNo, no, _cвЂ™est fini_, donвЂ™t trouble yourselves. ItвЂ™s not worth while
soiling oneвЂ™s hands. I have soiled myself enough through you as it is.
YouвЂ™re not worth itвЂ”no one is ... Enough, gentlemen. IвЂ™m not going on.вЂќ

This was said too peremptorily. Nikolay Parfenovitch did not insist
further, but from Ippolit KirillovitchвЂ™s eyes he saw that he had not given
up hope.

вЂњCan you not, at least, tell us what sum you had in your hands when you
went into Mr. PerhotinвЂ™sвЂ”how many roubles exactly?вЂќ

вЂњI canвЂ™t tell you that.вЂќ

вЂњYou spoke to Mr. Perhotin, I believe, of having received three thousand
from Madame Hohlakov.вЂќ

вЂњPerhaps I did. Enough, gentlemen. I wonвЂ™t say how much I had.вЂќ

вЂњWill you be so good then as to tell us how you came here and what you
have done since you arrived?вЂќ

вЂњOh! you might ask the people here about that. But IвЂ™ll tell you if you
like.вЂќ

He proceeded to do so, but we wonвЂ™t repeat his story. He told it dryly and
curtly. Of the raptures of his love he said nothing, but told them that he
abandoned his determination to shoot himself, owing to вЂњnew factors in the
case.вЂќ He told the story without going into motives or details. And this
time the lawyers did not worry him much. It was obvious that there was no
essential point of interest to them here.

вЂњWe shall verify all that. We will come back to it during the examination
of the witnesses, which will, of course, take place in your presence,вЂќ
said Nikolay Parfenovitch in conclusion. вЂњAnd now allow me to request you
to lay on the table everything in your possession, especially all the
money you still have about you.вЂќ

вЂњMy money, gentlemen? Certainly. I understand that that is necessary. IвЂ™m
surprised, indeed, that you havenвЂ™t inquired about it before. ItвЂ™s true I
couldnвЂ™t get away anywhere. IвЂ™m sitting here where I can be seen. But
hereвЂ™s my moneyвЂ”count itвЂ”take it. ThatвЂ™s all, I think.вЂќ

He turned it all out of his pockets; even the small changeвЂ”two pieces of
twenty copecksвЂ”he pulled out of his waistcoat pocket. They counted the
money, which amounted to eight hundred and thirtyвЂђsix roubles, and forty
copecks.

вЂњAnd is that all?вЂќ asked the investigating lawyer.

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњYou stated just now in your evidence that you spent three hundred roubles
at PlotnikovsвЂ™. You gave Perhotin ten, your driver twenty, here you lost
two hundred, then....вЂќ

Nikolay Parfenovitch reckoned it all up. Mitya helped him readily. They
recollected every farthing and included it in the reckoning. Nikolay
Parfenovitch hurriedly added up the total.

вЂњWith this eight hundred you must have had about fifteen hundred at
first?вЂќ

вЂњI suppose so,вЂќ snapped Mitya.

вЂњHow is it they all assert there was much more?вЂќ

вЂњLet them assert it.вЂќ

вЂњBut you asserted it yourself.вЂќ

вЂњYes, I did, too.вЂќ

вЂњWe will compare all this with the evidence of other persons not yet
examined. DonвЂ™t be anxious about your money. It will be properly taken
care of and be at your disposal at the conclusion of ... what is beginning
... if it appears, or, so to speak, is proved that you have undisputed
right to it. Well, and now....вЂќ

Nikolay Parfenovitch suddenly got up, and informed Mitya firmly that it
was his duty and obligation to conduct a minute and thorough search вЂњof
your clothes and everything else....вЂќ

вЂњBy all means, gentlemen. IвЂ™ll turn out all my pockets, if you like.вЂќ

And he did, in fact, begin turning out his pockets.

вЂњIt will be necessary to take off your clothes, too.вЂќ

вЂњWhat! Undress? Ugh! Damn it! WonвЂ™t you search me as I am! CanвЂ™t you?вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s utterly impossible, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. You must take off your
clothes.вЂќ

вЂњAs you like,вЂќ Mitya submitted gloomily; вЂњonly, please, not here, but
behind the curtains. Who will search them?вЂќ

вЂњBehind the curtains, of course.вЂќ

Nikolay Parfenovitch bent his head in assent. His small face wore an
expression of peculiar solemnity.



Chapter VI. The Prosecutor Catches Mitya


Something utterly unexpected and amazing to Mitya followed. He could
never, even a minute before, have conceived that any one could behave like
that to him, Mitya Karamazov. What was worst of all, there was something
humiliating in it, and on their side something вЂњsupercilious and
scornful.вЂќ It was nothing to take off his coat, but he was asked to
undress further, or rather not asked but вЂњcommanded,вЂќ he quite understood
that. From pride and contempt he submitted without a word. Several
peasants accompanied the lawyers and remained on the same side of the
curtain. вЂњTo be ready if force is required,вЂќ thought Mitya, вЂњand perhaps
for some other reason, too.вЂќ

вЂњWell, must I take off my shirt, too?вЂќ he asked sharply, but Nikolay
Parfenovitch did not answer. He was busily engaged with the prosecutor in
examining the coat, the trousers, the waistcoat and the cap; and it was
evident that they were both much interested in the scrutiny. вЂњThey make no
bones about it,вЂќ thought Mitya, вЂњthey donвЂ™t keep up the most elementary
politeness.вЂќ

вЂњI ask you for the second timeвЂ”need I take off my shirt or not?вЂќ he said,
still more sharply and irritably.

вЂњDonвЂ™t trouble yourself. We will tell you what to do,вЂќ Nikolay
Parfenovitch said, and his voice was positively peremptory, or so it
seemed to Mitya.

Meantime a consultation was going on in undertones between the lawyers.
There turned out to be on the coat, especially on the left side at the
back, a huge patch of blood, dry, and still stiff. There were bloodstains
on the trousers, too. Nikolay Parfenovitch, moreover, in the presence of
the peasant witnesses, passed his fingers along the collar, the cuffs, and
all the seams of the coat and trousers, obviously looking for
somethingвЂ”money, of course. He didnвЂ™t even hide from Mitya his suspicion
that he was capable of sewing money up in his clothes.

вЂњHe treats me not as an officer but as a thief,вЂќ Mitya muttered to
himself. They communicated their ideas to one another with amazing
frankness. The secretary, for instance, who was also behind the curtain,
fussing about and listening, called Nikolay ParfenovitchвЂ™s attention to
the cap, which they were also fingering.

вЂњYou remember Gridyenko, the copyingвЂђclerk,вЂќ observed the secretary. вЂњLast
summer he received the wages of the whole office, and pretended to have
lost the money when he was drunk. And where was it found? Why, in just
such pipings in his cap. The hundredвЂђrouble notes were screwed up in
little rolls and sewed in the piping.вЂќ

Both the lawyers remembered GridyenkoвЂ™s case perfectly, and so laid aside
MityaвЂ™s cap, and decided that all his clothes must be more thoroughly
examined later.

вЂњExcuse me,вЂќ cried Nikolay Parfenovitch, suddenly, noticing that the right
cuff of MityaвЂ™s shirt was turned in, and covered with blood, вЂњexcuse me,
whatвЂ™s that, blood?вЂќ

вЂњYes,вЂќ Mitya jerked out.

вЂњThat is, what blood? ... and why is the cuff turned in?вЂќ

Mitya told him how he had got the sleeve stained with blood looking after
Grigory, and had turned it inside when he was washing his hands at
PerhotinвЂ™s.

вЂњYou must take off your shirt, too. ThatвЂ™s very important as material
evidence.вЂќ

Mitya flushed red and flew into a rage.

вЂњWhat, am I to stay naked?вЂќ he shouted.

вЂњDonвЂ™t disturb yourself. We will arrange something. And meanwhile take off
your socks.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re not joking? Is that really necessary?вЂќ MityaвЂ™s eyes flashed.

вЂњWe are in no mood for joking,вЂќ answered Nikolay Parfenovitch sternly.

вЂњWell, if I mustвЂ”вЂќ muttered Mitya, and sitting down on the bed, he took
off his socks. He felt unbearably awkward. All were clothed, while he was
naked, and strange to say, when he was undressed he felt somehow guilty in
their presence, and was almost ready to believe himself that he was
inferior to them, and that now they had a perfect right to despise him.

вЂњWhen all are undressed, one is somehow not ashamed, but when oneвЂ™s the
only one undressed and everybody is looking, itвЂ™s degrading,вЂќ he kept
repeating to himself, again and again. вЂњItвЂ™s like a dream, IвЂ™ve sometimes
dreamed of being in such degrading positions.вЂќ It was a misery to him to
take off his socks. They were very dirty, and so were his underclothes,
and now every one could see it. And what was worse, he disliked his feet.
All his life he had thought both his big toes hideous. He particularly
loathed the coarse, flat, crooked nail on the right one, and now they
would all see it. Feeling intolerably ashamed made him, at once and
intentionally, rougher. He pulled off his shirt, himself.

вЂњWould you like to look anywhere else if youвЂ™re not ashamed to?вЂќ

вЂњNo, thereвЂ™s no need to, at present.вЂќ

вЂњWell, am I to stay naked like this?вЂќ he added savagely.

вЂњYes, that canвЂ™t be helped for the time.... Kindly sit down here for a
while. You can wrap yourself in a quilt from the bed, and I ... IвЂ™ll see
to all this.вЂќ

All the things were shown to the witnesses. The report of the search was
drawn up, and at last Nikolay Parfenovitch went out, and the clothes were
carried out after him. Ippolit Kirillovitch went out, too. Mitya was left
alone with the peasants, who stood in silence, never taking their eyes off
him. Mitya wrapped himself up in the quilt. He felt cold. His bare feet
stuck out, and he couldnвЂ™t pull the quilt over so as to cover them.
Nikolay Parfenovitch seemed to be gone a long time, вЂњan insufferable
time.вЂќ вЂњHe thinks of me as a puppy,вЂќ thought Mitya, gnashing his teeth.
вЂњThat rotten prosecutor has gone, too, contemptuous no doubt, it disgusts
him to see me naked!вЂќ

Mitya imagined, however, that his clothes would be examined and returned
to him. But what was his indignation when Nikolay Parfenovitch came back
with quite different clothes, brought in behind him by a peasant.

вЂњHere are clothes for you,вЂќ he observed airily, seeming well satisfied
with the success of his mission. вЂњMr. Kalganov has kindly provided these
for this unusual emergency, as well as a clean shirt. Luckily he had them
all in his trunk. You can keep your own socks and underclothes.вЂќ

Mitya flew into a passion.

вЂњI wonвЂ™t have other peopleвЂ™s clothes!вЂќ he shouted menacingly, вЂњgive me my
own!вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s impossible!вЂќ

вЂњGive me my own. Damn Kalganov and his clothes, too!вЂќ

It was a long time before they could persuade him. But they succeeded
somehow in quieting him down. They impressed upon him that his clothes,
being stained with blood, must be вЂњincluded with the other material
evidence,вЂќ and that they вЂњhad not even the right to let him have them now
... taking into consideration the possible outcome of the case.вЂќ Mitya at
last understood this. He subsided into gloomy silence and hurriedly
dressed himself. He merely observed, as he put them on, that the clothes
were much better than his old ones, and that he disliked вЂњgaining by the
change.вЂќ The coat was, besides, вЂњridiculously tight. Am I to be dressed up
like a fool ... for your amusement?вЂќ

They urged upon him again that he was exaggerating, that Kalganov was only
a little taller, so that only the trousers might be a little too long. But
the coat turned out to be really tight in the shoulders.

вЂњDamn it all! I can hardly button it,вЂќ Mitya grumbled. вЂњBe so good as to
tell Mr. Kalganov from me that I didnвЂ™t ask for his clothes, and itвЂ™s not
my doing that theyвЂ™ve dressed me up like a clown.вЂќ

вЂњHe understands that, and is sorry ... I mean, not sorry to lend you his
clothes, but sorry about all this business,вЂќ mumbled Nikolay Parfenovitch.

вЂњConfound his sorrow! Well, where now? Am I to go on sitting here?вЂќ

He was asked to go back to the вЂњother room.вЂќ Mitya went in, scowling with
anger, and trying to avoid looking at any one. Dressed in another manвЂ™s
clothes he felt himself disgraced, even in the eyes of the peasants, and
of Trifon Borissovitch, whose face appeared, for some reason, in the
doorway, and vanished immediately. вЂњHeвЂ™s come to look at me dressed up,вЂќ
thought Mitya. He sat down on the same chair as before. He had an absurd
nightmarish feeling, as though he were out of his mind.

вЂњWell, what now? Are you going to flog me? ThatвЂ™s all thatвЂ™s left for
you,вЂќ he said, clenching his teeth and addressing the prosecutor. He would
not turn to Nikolay Parfenovitch, as though he disdained to speak to him.

вЂњHe looked too closely at my socks, and turned them inside out on purpose
to show every one how dirty they wereвЂ”the scoundrel!вЂќ

вЂњWell, now we must proceed to the examination of witnesses,вЂќ observed
Nikolay Parfenovitch, as though in reply to MityaвЂ™s question.

вЂњYes,вЂќ said the prosecutor thoughtfully, as though reflecting on
something.

вЂњWeвЂ™ve done what we could in your interest, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ Nikolay
Parfenovitch went on, вЂњbut having received from you such an uncompromising
refusal to explain to us the source from which you obtained the money
found upon you, we are, at the present momentвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњWhat is the stone in your ring?вЂќ Mitya interrupted suddenly, as though
awakening from a reverie. He pointed to one of the three large rings
adorning Nikolay ParfenovitchвЂ™s right hand.

вЂњRing?вЂќ repeated Nikolay Parfenovitch with surprise.

вЂњYes, that one ... on your middle finger, with the little veins in it,
what stone is that?вЂќ Mitya persisted, like a peevish child.

вЂњThatвЂ™s a smoky topaz,вЂќ said Nikolay Parfenovitch, smiling. вЂњWould you
like to look at it? IвЂ™ll take it off ...вЂќ

вЂњNo, donвЂ™t take it off,вЂќ cried Mitya furiously, suddenly waking up, and
angry with himself. вЂњDonвЂ™t take it off ... thereвЂ™s no need.... Damn it!...
Gentlemen, youвЂ™ve sullied my heart! Can you suppose that I would conceal
it from you, if I had really killed my father, that I would shuffle, lie,
and hide myself? No, thatвЂ™s not like Dmitri Karamazov, that he couldnвЂ™t
do, and if I were guilty, I swear I shouldnвЂ™t have waited for your coming,
or for the sunrise as I meant at first, but should have killed myself
before this, without waiting for the dawn! I know that about myself now. I
couldnвЂ™t have learnt so much in twenty years as IвЂ™ve found out in this
accursed night!... And should I have been like this on this night, and at
this moment, sitting with you, could I have talked like this, could I have
moved like this, could I have looked at you and at the world like this, if
I had really been the murderer of my father, when the very thought of
having accidentally killed Grigory gave me no peace all nightвЂ”not from
fearвЂ”oh, not simply from fear of your punishment! The disgrace of it! And
you expect me to be open with such scoffers as you, who see nothing and
believe in nothing, blind moles and scoffers, and to tell you another
nasty thing IвЂ™ve done, another disgrace, even if that would save me from
your accusation! No, better Siberia! The man who opened the door to my
father and went in at that door, he killed him, he robbed him. Who was he?
IвЂ™m racking my brains and canвЂ™t think who. But I can tell you it was not
Dmitri Karamazov, and thatвЂ™s all I can tell you, and thatвЂ™s enough,
enough, leave me alone.... Exile me, punish me, but donвЂ™t bother me any
more. IвЂ™ll say no more. Call your witnesses!вЂќ

Mitya uttered his sudden monologue as though he were determined to be
absolutely silent for the future. The prosecutor watched him the whole
time and only when he had ceased speaking, observed, as though it were the
most ordinary thing, with the most frigid and composed air:

вЂњOh, about the open door of which you spoke just now, we may as well
inform you, by the way, now, of a very interesting piece of evidence of
the greatest importance both to you and to us, that has been given us by
Grigory, the old man you wounded. On his recovery, he clearly and
emphatically stated, in reply to our questions, that when, on coming out
to the steps, and hearing a noise in the garden, he made up his mind to go
into it through the little gate which stood open, before he noticed you
running, as you have told us already, in the dark from the open window
where you saw your father, he, Grigory, glanced to the left, and, while
noticing the open window, observed at the same time, much nearer to him,
the door, standing wide openвЂ”that door which you have stated to have been
shut the whole time you were in the garden. I will not conceal from you
that Grigory himself confidently affirms and bears witness that you must
have run from that door, though, of course, he did not see you do so with
his own eyes, since he only noticed you first some distance away in the
garden, running towards the fence.вЂќ

Mitya had leapt up from his chair halfвЂђway through this speech.

вЂњNonsense!вЂќ he yelled, in a sudden frenzy, вЂњitвЂ™s a barefaced lie. He
couldnвЂ™t have seen the door open because it was shut. HeвЂ™s lying!вЂќ

вЂњI consider it my duty to repeat that he is firm in his statement. He does
not waver. He adheres to it. WeвЂ™ve crossвЂђexamined him several times.вЂќ

вЂњPrecisely. I have crossвЂђexamined him several times,вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch
confirmed warmly.

вЂњItвЂ™s false, false! ItвЂ™s either an attempt to slander me, or the
hallucination of a madman,вЂќ Mitya still shouted. вЂњHeвЂ™s simply raving, from
loss of blood, from the wound. He must have fancied it when he came to....
HeвЂ™s raving.вЂќ

вЂњYes, but he noticed the open door, not when he came to after his
injuries, but before that, as soon as he went into the garden from the
lodge.вЂќ

вЂњBut itвЂ™s false, itвЂ™s false! It canвЂ™t be so! HeвЂ™s slandering me from
spite.... He couldnвЂ™t have seen it ... I didnвЂ™t come from the door,вЂќ
gasped Mitya.

The prosecutor turned to Nikolay Parfenovitch and said to him
impressively:

вЂњConfront him with it.вЂќ

вЂњDo you recognize this object?вЂќ

Nikolay Parfenovitch laid upon the table a large and thick official
envelope, on which three seals still remained intact. The envelope was
empty, and slit open at one end. Mitya stared at it with open eyes.

вЂњIt ... it must be that envelope of my fatherвЂ™s, the envelope that
contained the three thousand roubles ... and if thereвЂ™s inscribed on it,
allow me, вЂFor my little chickenвЂ™ ... yesвЂ”three thousand!вЂќ he shouted, вЂњdo
you see, three thousand, do you see?вЂќ

вЂњOf course, we see. But we didnвЂ™t find the money in it. It was empty, and
lying on the floor by the bed, behind the screen.вЂќ

For some seconds Mitya stood as though thunderstruck.

вЂњGentlemen, itвЂ™s Smerdyakov!вЂќ he shouted suddenly, at the top of his
voice. вЂњItвЂ™s he whoвЂ™s murdered him! HeвЂ™s robbed him! No one else knew
where the old man hid the envelope. ItвЂ™s Smerdyakov, thatвЂ™s clear, now!вЂќ

вЂњBut you, too, knew of the envelope and that it was under the pillow.вЂќ

вЂњI never knew it. IвЂ™ve never seen it. This is the first time IвЂ™ve looked
at it. IвЂ™d only heard of it from Smerdyakov.... He was the only one who
knew where the old man kept it hidden, I didnвЂ™t know ...вЂќ Mitya was
completely breathless.

вЂњBut you told us yourself that the envelope was under your deceased
fatherвЂ™s pillow. You especially stated that it was under the pillow, so
you must have known it.вЂќ

вЂњWeвЂ™ve got it written down,вЂќ confirmed Nikolay Parfenovitch.

вЂњNonsense! ItвЂ™s absurd! IвЂ™d no idea it was under the pillow. And perhaps
it wasnвЂ™t under the pillow at all.... It was just a chance guess that it
was under the pillow. What does Smerdyakov say? Have you asked him where
it was? What does Smerdyakov say? thatвЂ™s the chief point.... And I went
out of my way to tell lies against myself.... I told you without thinking
that it was under the pillow, and now youвЂ” Oh, you know how one says the
wrong thing, without meaning it. No one knew but Smerdyakov, only
Smerdyakov, and no one else.... He didnвЂ™t even tell me where it was! But
itвЂ™s his doing, his doing; thereвЂ™s no doubt about it, he murdered him,
thatвЂ™s as clear as daylight now,вЂќ Mitya exclaimed more and more
frantically, repeating himself incoherently, and growing more and more
exasperated and excited. вЂњYou must understand that, and arrest him at
once.... He must have killed him while I was running away and while
Grigory was unconscious, thatвЂ™s clear now.... He gave the signal and
father opened to him ... for no one but he knew the signal, and without
the signal father would never have opened the door....вЂќ

вЂњBut youвЂ™re again forgetting the circumstance,вЂќ the prosecutor observed,
still speaking with the same restraint, though with a note of triumph,
вЂњthat there was no need to give the signal if the door already stood open
when you were there, while you were in the garden....вЂќ

вЂњThe door, the door,вЂќ muttered Mitya, and he stared speechless at the
prosecutor. He sank back helpless in his chair. All were silent.

вЂњYes, the door!... ItвЂ™s a nightmare! God is against me!вЂќ he exclaimed,
staring before him in complete stupefaction.

вЂњCome, you see,вЂќ the prosecutor went on with dignity, вЂњand you can judge
for yourself, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. On the one hand we have the evidence of
the open door from which you ran out, a fact which overwhelms you and us.
On the other side your incomprehensible, persistent, and, so to speak,
obdurate silence with regard to the source from which you obtained the
money which was so suddenly seen in your hands, when only three hours
earlier, on your own showing, you pledged your pistols for the sake of ten
roubles! In view of all these facts, judge for yourself. What are we to
believe, and what can we depend upon? And donвЂ™t accuse us of being
вЂfrigid, cynical, scoffing people,вЂ™ who are incapable of believing in the
generous impulses of your heart.... Try to enter into our position ...вЂќ

Mitya was indescribably agitated. He turned pale.

вЂњVery well!вЂќ he exclaimed suddenly. вЂњI will tell you my secret. IвЂ™ll tell
you where I got the money!... IвЂ™ll reveal my shame, that I may not have to
blame myself or you hereafter.вЂќ

вЂњAnd believe me, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ put in Nikolay Parfenovitch, in a
voice of almost pathetic delight, вЂњthat every sincere and complete
confession on your part at this moment may, later on, have an immense
influence in your favor, and may, indeed, moreoverвЂ”вЂќ

But the prosecutor gave him a slight shove under the table, and he checked
himself in time. Mitya, it is true, had not heard him.



Chapter VII. MityaвЂ™s Great Secret. Received With Hisses


вЂњGentlemen,вЂќ he began, still in the same agitation, вЂњI want to make a full
confession: that money was _my own_.вЂќ The lawyersвЂ™ faces lengthened. That
was not at all what they expected.

вЂњHow do you mean?вЂќ faltered Nikolay Parfenovitch, вЂњwhen at five oвЂ™clock on
the same day, from your own confessionвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњDamn five oвЂ™clock on the same day and my own confession! ThatвЂ™s nothing
to do with it now! That money was my own, my own, that is, stolen by me
... not mine, I mean, but stolen by me, and it was fifteen hundred
roubles, and I had it on me all the time, all the time ...вЂќ

вЂњBut where did you get it?вЂќ

вЂњI took it off my neck, gentlemen, off this very neck ... it was here,
round my neck, sewn up in a rag, and IвЂ™d had it round my neck a long time,
itвЂ™s a month since I put it round my neck ... to my shame and disgrace!вЂќ

вЂњAnd from whom did you ... appropriate it?вЂќ

вЂњYou mean, вЂsteal itвЂ™? Speak out plainly now. Yes, I consider that I
practically stole it, but, if you prefer, I вЂappropriated it.вЂ™ I consider
I stole it. And last night I stole it finally.вЂќ

вЂњLast night? But you said that itвЂ™s a month since you ... obtained it?...вЂќ

вЂњYes. But not from my father. Not from my father, donвЂ™t be uneasy. I
didnвЂ™t steal it from my father, but from her. Let me tell you without
interrupting. ItвЂ™s hard to do, you know. You see, a month ago, I was sent
for by Katerina Ivanovna, formerly my betrothed. Do you know her?вЂќ

вЂњYes, of course.вЂќ

вЂњI know you know her. SheвЂ™s a noble creature, noblest of the noble. But
she has hated me ever so long, oh, ever so long ... and hated me with good
reason, good reason!вЂќ

вЂњKaterina Ivanovna!вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch exclaimed with wonder. The
prosecutor, too, stared.

вЂњOh, donвЂ™t take her name in vain! IвЂ™m a scoundrel to bring her into it.
Yes, IвЂ™ve seen that she hated me ... a long while.... From the very first,
even that evening at my lodging ... but enough, enough. YouвЂ™re unworthy
even to know of that. No need of that at all.... I need only tell you that
she sent for me a month ago, gave me three thousand roubles to send off to
her sister and another relation in Moscow (as though she couldnвЂ™t have
sent it off herself!) and I ... it was just at that fatal moment in my
life when I ... well, in fact, when IвЂ™d just come to love another, her,
sheвЂ™s sitting down below now, Grushenka. I carried her off here to Mokroe
then, and wasted here in two days half that damned three thousand, but the
other half I kept on me. Well, IвЂ™ve kept that other half, that fifteen
hundred, like a locket round my neck, but yesterday I undid it, and spent
it. WhatвЂ™s left of it, eight hundred roubles, is in your hands now,
Nikolay Parfenovitch. ThatвЂ™s the change out of the fifteen hundred I had
yesterday.вЂќ

вЂњExcuse me. HowвЂ™s that? Why, when you were here a month ago you spent
three thousand, not fifteen hundred, everybody knows that.вЂќ

вЂњWho knows it? Who counted the money? Did I let any one count it?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, you told every one yourself that youвЂ™d spent exactly three
thousand.вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s true, I did. I told the whole town so, and the whole town said so.
And here, at Mokroe, too, every one reckoned it was three thousand. Yet I
didnвЂ™t spend three thousand, but fifteen hundred. And the other fifteen
hundred I sewed into a little bag. ThatвЂ™s how it was, gentlemen. ThatвЂ™s
where I got that money yesterday....вЂќ

вЂњThis is almost miraculous,вЂќ murmured Nikolay Parfenovitch.

вЂњAllow me to inquire,вЂќ observed the prosecutor at last, вЂњhave you informed
any one whatever of this circumstance before, I mean that you had fifteen
hundred left about you a month ago?вЂќ

вЂњI told no one.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s strange. Do you mean absolutely no one?вЂќ

вЂњAbsolutely no one. No one and nobody.вЂќ

вЂњWhat was your reason for this reticence? What was your motive for making
such a secret of it? To be more precise: You have told us at last your
secret, in your words, so вЂdisgraceful,вЂ™ though in realityвЂ”that is, of
course, comparatively speakingвЂ”this action, that is, the appropriation of
three thousand roubles belonging to some one else, and, of course, only
for a time is, in my view at least, only an act of the greatest
recklessness and not so disgraceful, when one takes into consideration
your character.... Even admitting that it was an action in the highest
degree discreditable, still, discreditable is not вЂdisgraceful.вЂ™... Many
people have already guessed, during this last month, about the three
thousand of Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s, that you have spent, and I heard the
legend myself, apart from your confession.... Mihail Makarovitch, for
instance, had heard it, too, so that indeed, it was scarcely a legend, but
the gossip of the whole town. There are indications, too, if I am not
mistaken, that you confessed this yourself to some one, I mean that the
money was Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s, and so, itвЂ™s extremely surprising to me
that hitherto, that is, up to the present moment, you have made such an
extraordinary secret of the fifteen hundred you say you put by, apparently
connecting a feeling of positive horror with that secret.... ItвЂ™s not easy
to believe that it could cost you such distress to confess such a
secret.... You cried out, just now, that Siberia would be better than
confessing it ...вЂќ

The prosecutor ceased speaking. He was provoked. He did not conceal his
vexation, which was almost anger, and gave vent to all his accumulated
spleen, disconnectedly and incoherently, without choosing words.

вЂњItвЂ™s not the fifteen hundred thatвЂ™s the disgrace, but that I put it apart
from the rest of the three thousand,вЂќ said Mitya firmly.

вЂњWhy?вЂќ smiled the prosecutor irritably. вЂњWhat is there disgraceful, to
your thinking, in your having set aside half of the three thousand you had
discreditably, if you prefer, вЂdisgracefully,вЂ™ appropriated? Your taking
the three thousand is more important than what you did with it. And by the
way, why did you do thatвЂ”why did you set apart that half, for what
purpose, for what object did you do it? Can you explain that to us?вЂќ

вЂњOh, gentlemen, the purpose is the whole point!вЂќ cried Mitya. вЂњI put it
aside because I was vile, that is, because I was calculating, and to be
calculating in such a case is vile ... and that vileness has been going on
a whole month.вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s incomprehensible.вЂќ

вЂњI wonder at you. But IвЂ™ll make it clearer. Perhaps it really is
incomprehensible. You see, attend to what I say. I appropriate three
thousand entrusted to my honor, I spend it on a spree, say I spend it all,
and next morning I go to her and say, вЂKatya, IвЂ™ve done wrong, IвЂ™ve
squandered your three thousand,вЂ™ well, is that right? No, itвЂ™s not
rightвЂ”itвЂ™s dishonest and cowardly, IвЂ™m a beast, with no more selfвЂђcontrol
than a beast, thatвЂ™s so, isnвЂ™t it? But still IвЂ™m not a thief? Not a
downright thief, youвЂ™ll admit! I squandered it, but I didnвЂ™t steal it. Now
a second, rather more favorable alternative: follow me carefully, or I may
get confused againвЂ”my headвЂ™s going roundвЂ”and so, for the second
alternative: I spend here only fifteen hundred out of the three thousand,
that is, only half. Next day I go and take that half to her: вЂKatya, take
this fifteen hundred from me, IвЂ™m a low beast, and an untrustworthy
scoundrel, for IвЂ™ve wasted half the money, and I shall waste this, too, so
keep me from temptation!вЂ™ Well, what of that alternative? I should be a
beast and a scoundrel, and whatever you like; but not a thief, not
altogether a thief, or I should not have brought back what was left, but
have kept that, too. She would see at once that since I brought back half,
I should pay back what IвЂ™d spent, that I should never give up trying to,
that I should work to get it and pay it back. So in that case I should be
a scoundrel, but not a thief, you may say what you like, not a thief!вЂќ

вЂњI admit that there is a certain distinction,вЂќ said the prosecutor, with a
cold smile. вЂњBut itвЂ™s strange that you see such a vital difference.вЂќ

вЂњYes, I see a vital difference! Every man may be a scoundrel, and perhaps
every man is a scoundrel, but not every one can be a thief, it takes an
archвЂђscoundrel to be that. Oh, of course, I donвЂ™t know how to make these
fine distinctions ... but a thief is lower than a scoundrel, thatвЂ™s my
conviction. Listen, I carry the money about me a whole month, I may make
up my mind to give it back toвЂђmorrow, and IвЂ™m a scoundrel no longer, but I
cannot make up my mind, you see, though IвЂ™m making up my mind every day,
and every day spurring myself on to do it, and yet for a whole month I
canвЂ™t bring myself to it, you see. Is that right to your thinking, is that
right?вЂќ

вЂњCertainly, thatвЂ™s not right, that I can quite understand, and that I
donвЂ™t dispute,вЂќ answered the prosecutor with reserve. вЂњAnd let us give up
all discussion of these subtleties and distinctions, and, if you will be
so kind, get back to the point. And the point is, that you have still not
told us, altogether weвЂ™ve asked you, why, in the first place, you halved
the money, squandering one half and hiding the other? For what purpose
exactly did you hide it, what did you mean to do with that fifteen
hundred? I insist upon that question, Dmitri Fyodorovitch.вЂќ

вЂњYes, of course!вЂќ cried Mitya, striking himself on the forehead; вЂњforgive
me, IвЂ™m worrying you, and am not explaining the chief point, or youвЂ™d
understand in a minute, for itвЂ™s just the motive of it thatвЂ™s the
disgrace! You see, it was all to do with the old man, my dead father. He
was always pestering Agrafena Alexandrovna, and I was jealous; I thought
then that she was hesitating between me and him. So I kept thinking every
day, suppose she were to make up her mind all of a sudden, suppose she
were to leave off tormenting me, and were suddenly to say to me, вЂI love
you, not him; take me to the other end of the world.вЂ™ And IвЂ™d only forty
copecks; how could I take her away, what could I do? Why, IвЂ™d be lost. You
see, I didnвЂ™t know her then, I didnвЂ™t understand her, I thought she wanted
money, and that she wouldnвЂ™t forgive my poverty. And so I fiendishly
counted out the half of that three thousand, sewed it up, calculating on
it, sewed it up before I was drunk, and after I had sewn it up, I went off
to get drunk on the rest. Yes, that was base. Do you understand now?вЂќ

Both the lawyers laughed aloud.

вЂњI should have called it sensible and moral on your part not to have
squandered it all,вЂќ chuckled Nikolay Parfenovitch, вЂњfor after all what
does it amount to?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, that I stole it, thatвЂ™s what it amounts to! Oh, God, you horrify me
by not understanding! Every day that I had that fifteen hundred sewn up
round my neck, every day and every hour I said to myself, вЂYouвЂ™re a thief!
youвЂ™re a thief!вЂ™ Yes, thatвЂ™s why IвЂ™ve been so savage all this month,
thatвЂ™s why I fought in the tavern, thatвЂ™s why I attacked my father, it was
because I felt I was a thief. I couldnвЂ™t make up my mind, I didnвЂ™t dare
even to tell Alyosha, my brother, about that fifteen hundred: I felt I was
such a scoundrel and such a pickpocket. But, do you know, while I carried
it I said to myself at the same time every hour: вЂNo, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,
you may yet not be a thief.вЂ™ Why? Because I might go next day and pay back
that fifteen hundred to Katya. And only yesterday I made up my mind to
tear my amulet off my neck, on my way from FenyaвЂ™s to Perhotin. I hadnвЂ™t
been able till that moment to bring myself to it. And it was only when I
tore it off that I became a downright thief, a thief and a dishonest man
for the rest of my life. Why? Because, with that I destroyed, too, my
dream of going to Katya and saying, вЂIвЂ™m a scoundrel, but not a thief!вЂ™ Do
you understand now? Do you understand?вЂќ

вЂњWhat was it made you decide to do it yesterday?вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch
interrupted.

вЂњWhy? ItвЂ™s absurd to ask. Because I had condemned myself to die at five
oвЂ™clock this morning, here, at dawn. I thought it made no difference
whether I died a thief or a man of honor. But I see itвЂ™s not so, it turns
out that it does make a difference. Believe me, gentlemen, what has
tortured me most during this night has not been the thought that IвЂ™d
killed the old servant, and that I was in danger of Siberia just when my
love was being rewarded, and Heaven was open to me again. Oh, that did
torture me, but not in the same way: not so much as the damned
consciousness that I had torn that damned money off my breast at last and
spent it, and had become a downright thief! Oh, gentlemen, I tell you
again, with a bleeding heart, I have learnt a great deal this night. I
have learnt that itвЂ™s not only impossible to live a scoundrel, but
impossible to die a scoundrel.... No, gentlemen, one must die honest....вЂќ

Mitya was pale. His face had a haggard and exhausted look, in spite of his
being intensely excited.

вЂњI am beginning to understand you, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ the prosecutor
said slowly, in a soft and almost compassionate tone. вЂњBut all this, if
youвЂ™ll excuse my saying so, is a matter of nerves, in my opinion ... your
overwrought nerves, thatвЂ™s what it is. And why, for instance, should you
not have saved yourself such misery for almost a month, by going and
returning that fifteen hundred to the lady who had entrusted it to you?
And why could you not have explained things to her, and in view of your
position, which you describe as being so awful, why could you not have had
recourse to the plan which would so naturally have occurred to oneвЂ™s mind,
that is, after honorably confessing your errors to her, why could you not
have asked her to lend you the sum needed for your expenses, which, with
her generous heart, she would certainly not have refused you in your
distress, especially if it had been with some guarantee, or even on the
security you offered to the merchant Samsonov, and to Madame Hohlakov? I
suppose you still regard that security as of value?вЂќ

Mitya suddenly crimsoned.

вЂњSurely you donвЂ™t think me such an out and out scoundrel as that? You
canвЂ™t be speaking in earnest?вЂќ he said, with indignation, looking the
prosecutor straight in the face, and seeming unable to believe his ears.

вЂњI assure you IвЂ™m in earnest.... Why do you imagine IвЂ™m not serious?вЂќ It
was the prosecutorвЂ™s turn to be surprised.

вЂњOh, how base that would have been! Gentlemen, do you know, you are
torturing me! Let me tell you everything, so be it. IвЂ™ll confess all my
infernal wickedness, but to put you to shame, and youвЂ™ll be surprised
yourselves at the depth of ignominy to which a medley of human passions
can sink. You must know that I already had that plan myself, that plan you
spoke of, just now, prosecutor! Yes, gentlemen, I, too, have had that
thought in my mind all this current month, so that I was on the point of
deciding to go to KatyaвЂ”I was mean enough for that. But to go to her, to
tell her of my treachery, and for that very treachery, to carry it out,
for the expenses of that treachery, to beg for money from her, Katya (to
beg, do you hear, to beg), and go straight from her to run away with the
other, the rival, who hated and insulted herвЂ”to think of it! You must be
mad, prosecutor!вЂќ

вЂњMad I am not, but I did speak in haste, without thinking ... of that
feminine jealousy ... if there could be jealousy in this case, as you
assert ... yes, perhaps there is something of the kind,вЂќ said the
prosecutor, smiling.

вЂњBut that would have been so infamous!вЂќ Mitya brought his fist down on the
table fiercely. вЂњThat would have been filthy beyond everything! Yes, do
you know that she might have given me that money, yes, and she would have
given it, too; sheвЂ™d have been certain to give it, to be revenged on me,
sheвЂ™d have given it to satisfy her vengeance, to show her contempt for me,
for hers is an infernal nature, too, and sheвЂ™s a woman of great wrath. IвЂ™d
have taken the money, too, oh, I should have taken it; I should have taken
it, and then, for the rest of my life ... oh, God! Forgive me, gentlemen,
IвЂ™m making such an outcry because IвЂ™ve had that thought in my mind so
lately, only the day before yesterday, that night when I was having all
that bother with Lyagavy, and afterwards yesterday, all day yesterday, I
remember, till that happened ...вЂќ

вЂњTill what happened?вЂќ put in Nikolay Parfenovitch inquisitively, but Mitya
did not hear it.

вЂњI have made you an awful confession,вЂќ Mitya said gloomily in conclusion.
вЂњYou must appreciate it, and whatвЂ™s more, you must respect it, for if not,
if that leaves your souls untouched, then youвЂ™ve simply no respect for me,
gentlemen, I tell you that, and I shall die of shame at having confessed
it to men like you! Oh, I shall shoot myself! Yes, I see, I see already
that you donвЂ™t believe me. What, you want to write that down, too?вЂќ he
cried in dismay.

вЂњYes, what you said just now,вЂќ said Nikolay Parfenovitch, looking at him
in surprise, вЂњthat is, that up to the last hour you were still
contemplating going to Katerina Ivanovna to beg that sum from her.... I
assure you, thatвЂ™s a very important piece of evidence for us, Dmitri
Fyodorovitch, I mean for the whole case ... and particularly for you,
particularly important for you.вЂќ

вЂњHave mercy, gentlemen!вЂќ Mitya flung up his hands. вЂњDonвЂ™t write that,
anyway; have some shame. Here IвЂ™ve torn my heart asunder before you, and
you seize the opportunity and are fingering the wounds in both halves....
Oh, my God!вЂќ

In despair he hid his face in his hands.

вЂњDonвЂ™t worry yourself so, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ observed the prosecutor,
вЂњeverything that is written down will be read over to you afterwards, and
what you donвЂ™t agree to weвЂ™ll alter as you like. But now IвЂ™ll ask you one
little question for the second time. Has no one, absolutely no one, heard
from you of that money you sewed up? That, I must tell you, is almost
impossible to believe.вЂќ

вЂњNo one, no one, I told you so before, or youвЂ™ve not understood anything!
Let me alone!вЂќ

вЂњVery well, this matter is bound to be explained, and thereвЂ™s plenty of
time for it, but meantime, consider; we have perhaps a dozen witnesses
that you yourself spread it abroad, and even shouted almost everywhere
about the three thousand youвЂ™d spent here; three thousand, not fifteen
hundred. And now, too, when you got hold of the money you had yesterday,
you gave many people to understand that you had brought three thousand
with you.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™ve got not dozens, but hundreds of witnesses, two hundred witnesses,
two hundred have heard it, thousands have heard it!вЂќ cried Mitya.

вЂњWell, you see, all bear witness to it. And the word _all_ means
something.вЂќ

вЂњIt means nothing. I talked rot, and every one began repeating it.вЂќ

вЂњBut what need had you to вЂtalk rot,вЂ™ as you call it?вЂќ

вЂњThe devil knows. From bravado perhaps ... at having wasted so much
money.... To try and forget that money I had sewn up, perhaps ... yes,
that was why ... damn it ... how often will you ask me that question?
Well, I told a fib, and that was the end of it, once IвЂ™d said it, I didnвЂ™t
care to correct it. What does a man tell lies for sometimes?вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s very difficult to decide, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, what makes a man
tell lies,вЂќ observed the prosecutor impressively. вЂњTell me, though, was
that вЂamulet,вЂ™ as you call it, on your neck, a big thing?вЂќ

вЂњNo, not big.вЂќ

вЂњHow big, for instance?вЂќ

вЂњIf you fold a hundredвЂђrouble note in half, that would be the size.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™d better show us the remains of it. You must have them somewhere.вЂќ

вЂњDamnation, what nonsense! I donвЂ™t know where they are.вЂќ

вЂњBut excuse me: where and when did you take it off your neck? According to
your own evidence you didnвЂ™t go home.вЂќ

вЂњWhen I was going from FenyaвЂ™s to PerhotinвЂ™s, on the way I tore it off my
neck and took out the money.вЂќ

вЂњIn the dark?вЂќ

вЂњWhat should I want a light for? I did it with my fingers in one minute.вЂќ

вЂњWithout scissors, in the street?вЂќ

вЂњIn the marketвЂђplace I think it was. Why scissors? It was an old rag. It
was torn in a minute.вЂќ

вЂњWhere did you put it afterwards?вЂќ

вЂњI dropped it there.вЂќ

вЂњWhere was it, exactly?вЂќ

вЂњIn the marketвЂђplace, in the marketвЂђplace! The devil knows whereabouts.
What do you want to know for?вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s extremely important, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. It would be material
evidence in your favor. How is it you donвЂ™t understand that? Who helped
you to sew it up a month ago?вЂќ

вЂњNo one helped me. I did it myself.вЂќ

вЂњCan you sew?вЂќ

вЂњA soldier has to know how to sew. No knowledge was needed to do that.вЂќ

вЂњWhere did you get the material, that is, the rag in which you sewed the
money?вЂќ

вЂњAre you laughing at me?вЂќ

вЂњNot at all. And we are in no mood for laughing, Dmitri Fyodorovitch.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know where I got the rag fromвЂ”somewhere, I suppose.вЂќ

вЂњI should have thought you couldnвЂ™t have forgotten it?вЂќ

вЂњUpon my word, I donвЂ™t remember. I might have torn a bit off my linen.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s very interesting. We might find in your lodgings toвЂђmorrow the
shirt or whatever it is from which you tore the rag. What sort of rag was
it, cloth or linen?вЂќ

вЂњGoodness only knows what it was. Wait a bit.... I believe I didnвЂ™t tear
it off anything. It was a bit of calico.... I believe I sewed it up in a
cap of my landladyвЂ™s.вЂќ

вЂњIn your landladyвЂ™s cap?вЂќ

вЂњYes. I took it from her.вЂќ

вЂњHow did you get it?вЂќ

вЂњYou see, I remember once taking a cap for a rag, perhaps to wipe my pen
on. I took it without asking, because it was a worthless rag. I tore it
up, and I took the notes and sewed them up in it. I believe it was in that
very rag I sewed them. An old piece of calico, washed a thousand times.вЂќ

вЂњAnd you remember that for certain now?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know whether for certain. I think it was in the cap. But, hang
it, what does it matter?вЂќ

вЂњIn that case your landlady will remember that the thing was lost?вЂќ

вЂњNo, she wonвЂ™t, she didnвЂ™t miss it. It was an old rag, I tell you, an old
rag not worth a farthing.вЂќ

вЂњAnd where did you get the needle and thread?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll stop now. I wonвЂ™t say any more. Enough of it!вЂќ said Mitya, losing
his temper at last.

вЂњItвЂ™s strange that you should have so completely forgotten where you threw
the pieces in the marketвЂђplace.вЂќ

вЂњGive orders for the marketвЂђplace to be swept toвЂђmorrow, and perhaps
youвЂ™ll find it,вЂќ said Mitya, sneering. вЂњEnough, gentlemen, enough!вЂќ he
decided, in an exhausted voice. вЂњI see you donвЂ™t believe me! Not for a
moment! ItвЂ™s my fault, not yours. I ought not to have been so ready. Why,
why did I degrade myself by confessing my secret to you? ItвЂ™s a joke to
you. I see that from your eyes. You led me on to it, prosecutor? Sing a
hymn of triumph if you can.... Damn you, you torturers!вЂќ

He bent his head, and hid his face in his hands. The lawyers were silent.
A minute later he raised his head and looked at them almost vacantly. His
face now expressed complete, hopeless despair, and he sat mute and passive
as though hardly conscious of what was happening. In the meantime they had
to finish what they were about. They had immediately to begin examining
the witnesses. It was by now eight oвЂ™clock in the morning. The lights had
been extinguished long ago. Mihail Makarovitch and Kalganov, who had been
continually in and out of the room all the while the interrogation had
been going on, had now both gone out again. The lawyers, too, looked very
tired. It was a wretched morning, the whole sky was overcast, and the rain
streamed down in bucketfuls. Mitya gazed blankly out of the window.

вЂњMay I look out of the window?вЂќ he asked Nikolay Parfenovitch, suddenly.

вЂњOh, as much as you like,вЂќ the latter replied.

Mitya got up and went to the window.... The rain lashed against its little
greenish panes. He could see the muddy road just below the house, and
farther away, in the rain and mist, a row of poor, black, dismal huts,
looking even blacker and poorer in the rain. Mitya thought of вЂњPhЕ“bus the
goldenвЂђhaired,вЂќ and how he had meant to shoot himself at his first ray.
вЂњPerhaps it would be even better on a morning like this,вЂќ he thought with
a smile, and suddenly, flinging his hand downwards, he turned to his
вЂњtorturers.вЂќ

вЂњGentlemen,вЂќ he cried, вЂњI see that I am lost! But she? Tell me about her,
I beseech you. Surely she need not be ruined with me? SheвЂ™s innocent, you
know, she was out of her mind when she cried last night вЂItвЂ™s all my
fault!вЂ™ SheвЂ™s done nothing, nothing! IвЂ™ve been grieving over her all night
as I sat with you.... CanвЂ™t you, wonвЂ™t you tell me what you are going to
do with her now?вЂќ

вЂњYou can set your mind quite at rest on that score, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ
the prosecutor answered at once, with evident alacrity. вЂњWe have, so far,
no grounds for interfering with the lady in whom you are so interested. I
trust that it may be the same in the later development of the case.... On
the contrary, weвЂ™ll do everything that lies in our power in that matter.
Set your mind completely at rest.вЂќ

вЂњGentlemen, I thank you. I knew that you were honest, straightвЂђforward
people in spite of everything. YouвЂ™ve taken a load off my heart.... Well,
what are we to do now? IвЂ™m ready.вЂќ

вЂњWell, we ought to make haste. We must pass to examining the witnesses
without delay. That must be done in your presence and thereforeвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњShouldnвЂ™t we have some tea first?вЂќ interposed Nikolay Parfenovitch, вЂњI
think weвЂ™ve deserved it!вЂќ

They decided that if tea were ready downstairs (Mihail Makarovitch had, no
doubt, gone down to get some) they would have a glass and then вЂњgo on and
on,вЂќ putting off their proper breakfast until a more favorable
opportunity. Tea really was ready below, and was soon brought up. Mitya at
first refused the glass that Nikolay Parfenovitch politely offered him,
but afterwards he asked for it himself and drank it greedily. He looked
surprisingly exhausted. It might have been supposed from his Herculean
strength that one night of carousing, even accompanied by the most violent
emotions, could have had little effect on him. But he felt that he could
hardly hold his head up, and from time to time all the objects about him
seemed heaving and dancing before his eyes. вЂњA little more and I shall
begin raving,вЂќ he said to himself.



Chapter VIII. The Evidence Of The Witnesses. The Babe


The examination of the witnesses began. But we will not continue our story
in such detail as before. And so we will not dwell on how Nikolay
Parfenovitch impressed on every witness called that he must give his
evidence in accordance with truth and conscience, and that he would
afterwards have to repeat his evidence on oath, how every witness was
called upon to sign the protocol of his evidence, and so on. We will only
note that the point principally insisted upon in the examination was the
question of the three thousand roubles, that is, was the sum spent here,
at Mokroe, by Mitya on the first occasion, a month before, three thousand
or fifteen hundred? And again had he spent three thousand or fifteen
hundred yesterday? Alas, all the evidence given by every one turned out to
be against Mitya. There was not one in his favor, and some witnesses
introduced new, almost crushing facts, in contradiction of his, MityaвЂ™s,
story.

The first witness examined was Trifon Borissovitch. He was not in the
least abashed as he stood before the lawyers. He had, on the contrary, an
air of stern and severe indignation with the accused, which gave him an
appearance of truthfulness and personal dignity. He spoke little, and with
reserve, waited to be questioned, answered precisely and deliberately.
Firmly and unhesitatingly he bore witness that the sum spent a month
before could not have been less than three thousand, that all the peasants
about here would testify that they had heard the sum of three thousand
mentioned by Dmitri Fyodorovitch himself. вЂњWhat a lot of money he flung
away on the gypsy girls alone! He wasted a thousand, I daresay, on them
alone.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t believe I gave them five hundred,вЂќ was MityaвЂ™s gloomy comment on
this. вЂњItвЂ™s a pity I didnвЂ™t count the money at the time, but I was
drunk....вЂќ

Mitya was sitting sideways with his back to the curtains. He listened
gloomily, with a melancholy and exhausted air, as though he would say:

вЂњOh, say what you like. It makes no difference now.вЂќ

вЂњMore than a thousand went on them, Dmitri Fyodorovitch,вЂќ retorted Trifon
Borissovitch firmly. вЂњYou flung it about at random and they picked it up.
They were a rascally, thievish lot, horseвЂђstealers, theyвЂ™ve been driven
away from here, or maybe theyвЂ™d bear witness themselves how much they got
from you. I saw the sum in your hands, myselfвЂ”count it I didnвЂ™t, you
didnвЂ™t let me, thatвЂ™s true enoughвЂ”but by the look of it I should say it
was far more than fifteen hundred ... fifteen hundred, indeed! WeвЂ™ve seen
money too. We can judge of amounts....вЂќ

As for the sum spent yesterday he asserted that Dmitri Fyodorovitch had
told him, as soon as he arrived, that he had brought three thousand with
him.

вЂњCome now, is that so, Trifon Borissovitch?вЂќ replied Mitya. вЂњSurely I
didnвЂ™t declare so positively that IвЂ™d brought three thousand?вЂќ

вЂњYou did say so, Dmitri Fyodorovitch. You said it before Andrey. Andrey
himself is still here. Send for him. And in the hall, when you were
treating the chorus, you shouted straight out that you would leave your
sixth thousand hereвЂ”that is with what you spent before, we must
understand. Stepan and Semyon heard it, and Pyotr Fomitch Kalganov, too,
was standing beside you at the time. Maybe heвЂ™d remember it....вЂќ

The evidence as to the вЂњsixthвЂќ thousand made an extraordinary impression
on the two lawyers. They were delighted with this new mode of reckoning;
three and three made six, three thousand then and three now made six, that
was clear.

They questioned all the peasants suggested by Trifon Borissovitch, Stepan
and Semyon, the driver Andrey, and Kalganov. The peasants and the driver
unhesitatingly confirmed Trifon BorissovitchвЂ™s evidence. They noted down,
with particular care, AndreyвЂ™s account of the conversation he had had with
Mitya on the road: вЂњ вЂWhere,вЂ™ says he, вЂam I, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, going,
to heaven or to hell, and shall I be forgiven in the next world or not?вЂ™ вЂќ

The psychological Ippolit Kirillovitch heard this with a subtle smile, and
ended by recommending that these remarks as to where Dmitri Fyodorovitch
would go should be вЂњincluded in the case.вЂќ

Kalganov, when called, came in reluctantly, frowning and illвЂђhumored, and
he spoke to the lawyers as though he had never met them before in his
life, though they were acquaintances whom he had been meeting every day
for a long time past. He began by saying that вЂњhe knew nothing about it
and didnвЂ™t want to.вЂќ But it appeared that he had heard of the вЂњsixthвЂќ
thousand, and he admitted that he had been standing close by at the
moment. As far as he could see he вЂњdidnвЂ™t knowвЂќ how much money Mitya had
in his hands. He affirmed that the Poles had cheated at cards. In reply to
reiterated questions he stated that, after the Poles had been turned out,
MityaвЂ™s position with Agrafena Alexandrovna had certainly improved, and
that she had said that she loved him. He spoke of Agrafena Alexandrovna
with reserve and respect, as though she had been a lady of the best
society, and did not once allow himself to call her Grushenka. In spite of
the young manвЂ™s obvious repugnance at giving evidence, Ippolit
Kirillovitch examined him at great length, and only from him learnt all
the details of what made up MityaвЂ™s вЂњromance,вЂќ so to say, on that night.
Mitya did not once pull Kalganov up. At last they let the young man go,
and he left the room with unconcealed indignation.

The Poles, too, were examined. Though they had gone to bed in their room,
they had not slept all night, and on the arrival of the police officers
they hastily dressed and got ready, realizing that they would certainly be
sent for. They gave their evidence with dignity, though not without some
uneasiness. The little Pole turned out to be a retired official of the
twelfth class, who had served in Siberia as a veterinary surgeon. His name
was Mussyalovitch. Pan Vrublevsky turned out to be an uncertificated
dentist. Although Nikolay Parfenovitch asked them questions on entering
the room they both addressed their answers to Mihail Makarovitch, who was
standing on one side, taking him in their ignorance for the most important
person and in command, and addressed him at every word as вЂњPan Colonel.вЂќ
Only after several reproofs from Mihail Makarovitch himself, they grasped
that they had to address their answers to Nikolay Parfenovitch only. It
turned out that they could speak Russian quite correctly except for their
accent in some words. Of his relations with Grushenka, past and present,
Pan Mussyalovitch spoke proudly and warmly, so that Mitya was roused at
once and declared that he would not allow the вЂњscoundrelвЂќ to speak like
that in his presence! Pan Mussyalovitch at once called attention to the
word вЂњscoundrelвЂќ and begged that it should be put down in the protocol.
Mitya fumed with rage.

вЂњHeвЂ™s a scoundrel! A scoundrel! You can put that down. And put down, too,
that, in spite of the protocol I still declare that heвЂ™s a scoundrel!вЂќ he
cried.

Though Nikolay Parfenovitch did insert this in the protocol, he showed the
most praiseworthy tact and management. After sternly reprimanding Mitya,
he cut short all further inquiry into the romantic aspect of the case, and
hastened to pass to what was essential. One piece of evidence given by the
Poles roused special interest in the lawyers: that was how, in that very
room, Mitya had tried to buy off Pan Mussyalovitch, and had offered him
three thousand roubles to resign his claims, seven hundred roubles down,
and the remaining two thousand three hundred вЂњto be paid next day in the
town.вЂќ He had sworn at the time that he had not the whole sum with him at
Mokroe, but that his money was in the town. Mitya observed hotly that he
had not said that he would be sure to pay him the remainder next day in
the town. But Pan Vrublevsky confirmed the statement, and Mitya, after
thinking for a moment admitted, frowning, that it must have been as the
Poles stated, that he had been excited at the time, and might indeed have
said so.

The prosecutor positively pounced on this piece of evidence. It seemed to
establish for the prosecution (and they did, in fact, base this deduction
on it) that half, or a part of, the three thousand that had come into
MityaвЂ™s hands might really have been left somewhere hidden in the town, or
even, perhaps, somewhere here, in Mokroe. This would explain the
circumstance, so baffling for the prosecution, that only eight hundred
roubles were to be found in MityaвЂ™s hands. This circumstance had been the
one piece of evidence which, insignificant as it was, had hitherto told,
to some extent, in MityaвЂ™s favor. Now this one piece of evidence in his
favor had broken down. In answer to the prosecutorвЂ™s inquiry, where he
would have got the remaining two thousand three hundred roubles, since he
himself had denied having more than fifteen hundred, Mitya confidently
replied that he had meant to offer the вЂњlittle chap,вЂќ not money, but a
formal deed of conveyance of his rights to the village of Tchermashnya,
those rights which he had already offered to Samsonov and Madame Hohlakov.
The prosecutor positively smiled at the вЂњinnocence of this subterfuge.вЂќ

вЂњAnd you imagine he would have accepted such a deed as a substitute for
two thousand three hundred roubles in cash?вЂќ

вЂњHe certainly would have accepted it,вЂќ Mitya declared warmly. вЂњWhy, look
here, he might have grabbed not two thousand, but four or six, for it. He
would have put his lawyers, Poles and Jews, on to the job, and might have
got, not three thousand, but the whole property out of the old man.вЂќ

The evidence of Pan Mussyalovitch was, of course, entered in the protocol
in the fullest detail. Then they let the Poles go. The incident of the
cheating at cards was hardly touched upon. Nikolay Parfenovitch was too
well pleased with them, as it was, and did not want to worry them with
trifles, moreover, it was nothing but a foolish, drunken quarrel over
cards. There had been drinking and disorder enough, that night.... So the
two hundred roubles remained in the pockets of the Poles.

Then old Maximov was summoned. He came in timidly, approached with little
steps, looking very disheveled and depressed. He had, all this time, taken
refuge below with Grushenka, sitting dumbly beside her, and вЂњnow and then
heвЂ™d begin blubbering over her and wiping his eyes with a blue check
handkerchief,вЂќ as Mihail Makarovitch described afterwards. So that she
herself began trying to pacify and comfort him. The old man at once
confessed that he had done wrong, that he had borrowed вЂњten roubles in my
poverty,вЂќ from Dmitri Fyodorovitch, and that he was ready to pay it back.
To Nikolay ParfenovitchвЂ™s direct question, had he noticed how much money
Dmitri Fyodorovitch held in his hand, as he must have been able to see the
sum better than any one when he took the note from him, Maximov, in the
most positive manner, declared that there was twenty thousand.

вЂњHave you ever seen so much as twenty thousand before, then?вЂќ inquired
Nikolay Parfenovitch, with a smile.

вЂњTo be sure I have, not twenty, but seven, when my wife mortgaged my
little property. SheвЂ™d only let me look at it from a distance, boasting of
it to me. It was a very thick bundle, all rainbowвЂђcolored notes. And
Dmitri FyodorovitchвЂ™s were all rainbowвЂђcolored....вЂќ

He was not kept long. At last it was GrushenkaвЂ™s turn. Nikolay
Parfenovitch was obviously apprehensive of the effect her appearance might
have on Mitya, and he muttered a few words of admonition to him, but Mitya
bowed his head in silence, giving him to understand вЂњthat he would not
make a scene.вЂќ Mihail Makarovitch himself led Grushenka in. She entered
with a stern and gloomy face, that looked almost composed and sat down
quietly on the chair offered her by Nikolay Parfenovitch. She was very
pale, she seemed to be cold, and wrapped herself closely in her
magnificent black shawl. She was suffering from a slight feverish
chillвЂ”the first symptom of the long illness which followed that night. Her
grave air, her direct earnest look and quiet manner made a very favorable
impression on every one. Nikolay Parfenovitch was even a little bit
вЂњfascinated.вЂќ He admitted himself, when talking about it afterwards, that
only then had he seen вЂњhow handsome the woman was,вЂќ for, though he had
seen her several times before, he had always looked upon her as something
of a вЂњprovincial hetaira.вЂќ вЂњShe has the manners of the best society,вЂќ he
said enthusiastically, gossiping about her in a circle of ladies. But this
was received with positive indignation by the ladies, who immediately
called him a вЂњnaughty man,вЂќ to his great satisfaction.

As she entered the room, Grushenka only glanced for an instant at Mitya,
who looked at her uneasily. But her face reassured him at once. After the
first inevitable inquiries and warnings, Nikolay Parfenovitch asked her,
hesitating a little, but preserving the most courteous manner, on what
terms she was with the retired lieutenant, Dmitri Fyodorovitch Karamazov.
To this Grushenka firmly and quietly replied:

вЂњHe was an acquaintance. He came to see me as an acquaintance during the
last month.вЂќ To further inquisitive questions she answered plainly and
with complete frankness, that, though вЂњat timesвЂќ she had thought him
attractive, she had not loved him, but had won his heart as well as his
old fatherвЂ™s вЂњin my nasty spite,вЂќ that she had seen that Mitya was very
jealous of Fyodor Pavlovitch and every one else; but that had only amused
her. She had never meant to go to Fyodor Pavlovitch, she had simply been
laughing at him. вЂњI had no thoughts for either of them all this last
month. I was expecting another man who had wronged me. But I think,вЂќ she
said in conclusion, вЂњthat thereвЂ™s no need for you to inquire about that,
nor for me to answer you, for thatвЂ™s my own affair.вЂќ

Nikolay Parfenovitch immediately acted upon this hint. He again dismissed
the вЂњromanticвЂќ aspect of the case and passed to the serious one, that is,
to the question of most importance, concerning the three thousand roubles.
Grushenka confirmed the statement that three thousand roubles had
certainly been spent on the first carousal at Mokroe, and, though she had
not counted the money herself, she had heard that it was three thousand
from Dmitri FyodorovitchвЂ™s own lips.

вЂњDid he tell you that alone, or before some one else, or did you only hear
him speak of it to others in your presence?вЂќ the prosecutor inquired
immediately.

To which Grushenka replied that she had heard him say so before other
people, and had heard him say so when they were alone.

вЂњDid he say it to you alone once, or several times?вЂќ inquired the
prosecutor, and learned that he had told Grushenka so several times.

Ippolit Kirillovitch was very well satisfied with this piece of evidence.
Further examination elicited that Grushenka knew, too, where that money
had come from, and that Dmitri Fyodorovitch had got it from Katerina
Ivanovna.

вЂњAnd did you never, once, hear that the money spent a month ago was not
three thousand, but less, and that Dmitri Fyodorovitch had saved half that
sum for his own use?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I never heard that,вЂќ answered Grushenka.

It was explained further that Mitya had, on the contrary, often told her
that he hadnвЂ™t a farthing.

вЂњHe was always expecting to get some from his father,вЂќ said Grushenka in
conclusion.

вЂњDid he never say before you ... casually, or in a moment of irritation,вЂќ
Nikolay Parfenovitch put in suddenly, вЂњthat he intended to make an attempt
on his fatherвЂ™s life?вЂќ

вЂњAch, he did say so,вЂќ sighed Grushenka.

вЂњOnce or several times?вЂќ

вЂњHe mentioned it several times, always in anger.вЂќ

вЂњAnd did you believe he would do it?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I never believed it,вЂќ she answered firmly. вЂњI had faith in his noble
heart.вЂќ

вЂњGentlemen, allow me,вЂќ cried Mitya suddenly, вЂњallow me to say one word to
Agrafena Alexandrovna, in your presence.вЂќ

вЂњYou can speak,вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch assented.

вЂњAgrafena Alexandrovna!вЂќ Mitya got up from his chair, вЂњhave faith in God
and in me. I am not guilty of my fatherвЂ™s murder!вЂќ

Having uttered these words Mitya sat down again on his chair. Grushenka
stood up and crossed herself devoutly before the ikon. вЂњThanks be to Thee,
O Lord,вЂќ she said, in a voice thrilled with emotion, and still standing,
she turned to Nikolay Parfenovitch and added:

вЂњAs he has spoken now, believe it! I know him. HeвЂ™ll say anything as a
joke or from obstinacy, but heвЂ™ll never deceive you against his
conscience. HeвЂ™s telling the whole truth, you may believe it.вЂќ

вЂњThanks, Agrafena Alexandrovna, youвЂ™ve given me fresh courage,вЂќ Mitya
responded in a quivering voice.

As to the money spent the previous day, she declared that she did not know
what sum it was, but had heard him tell several people that he had three
thousand with him. And to the question where he got the money, she said
that he had told her that he had вЂњstolenвЂќ it from Katerina Ivanovna, and
that she had replied to that that he hadnвЂ™t stolen it, and that he must
pay the money back next day. On the prosecutorвЂ™s asking her emphatically
whether the money he said he had stolen from Katerina Ivanovna was what he
had spent yesterday, or what he had squandered here a month ago, she
declared that he meant the money spent a month ago, and that that was how
she understood him.

Grushenka was at last released, and Nikolay Parfenovitch informed her
impulsively that she might at once return to the town and that if he could
be of any assistance to her, with horses for example, or if she would care
for an escort, he ... would beвЂ”

вЂњI thank you sincerely,вЂќ said Grushenka, bowing to him, вЂњIвЂ™m going with
this old gentleman, I am driving him back to town with me, and meanwhile,
if youвЂ™ll allow me, IвЂ™ll wait below to hear what you decide about Dmitri
Fyodorovitch.вЂќ

She went out. Mitya was calm, and even looked more cheerful, but only for
a moment. He felt more and more oppressed by a strange physical weakness.
His eyes were closing with fatigue. The examination of the witnesses was,
at last, over. They proceeded to a final revision of the protocol. Mitya
got up, moved from his chair to the corner by the curtain, lay down on a
large chest covered with a rug, and instantly fell asleep.

He had a strange dream, utterly out of keeping with the place and the
time.

He was driving somewhere in the steppes, where he had been stationed long
ago, and a peasant was driving him in a cart with a pair of horses,
through snow and sleet. He was cold, it was early in November, and the
snow was falling in big wet flakes, melting as soon as it touched the
earth. And the peasant drove him smartly, he had a fair, long beard. He
was not an old man, somewhere about fifty, and he had on a gray peasantвЂ™s
smock. Not far off was a village, he could see the black huts, and half
the huts were burnt down, there were only the charred beams sticking up.
And as they drove in, there were peasant women drawn up along the road, a
lot of women, a whole row, all thin and wan, with their faces a sort of
brownish color, especially one at the edge, a tall, bony woman, who looked
forty, but might have been only twenty, with a long thin face. And in her
arms was a little baby crying. And her breasts seemed so dried up that
there was not a drop of milk in them. And the child cried and cried, and
held out its little bare arms, with its little fists blue from cold.

вЂњWhy are they crying? Why are they crying?вЂќ Mitya asked, as they dashed
gayly by.

вЂњItвЂ™s the babe,вЂќ answered the driver, вЂњthe babe weeping.вЂќ

And Mitya was struck by his saying, in his peasant way, вЂњthe babe,вЂќ and he
liked the peasantвЂ™s calling it a вЂњbabe.вЂќ There seemed more pity in it.

вЂњBut why is it weeping?вЂќ Mitya persisted stupidly, вЂњwhy are its little
arms bare? Why donвЂ™t they wrap it up?вЂќ

вЂњThe babeвЂ™s cold, its little clothes are frozen and donвЂ™t warm it.вЂќ

вЂњBut why is it? Why?вЂќ foolish Mitya still persisted.

вЂњWhy, theyвЂ™re poor people, burnt out. TheyвЂ™ve no bread. TheyвЂ™re begging
because theyвЂ™ve been burnt out.вЂќ

вЂњNo, no,вЂќ Mitya, as it were, still did not understand. вЂњTell me why it is
those poor mothers stand there? Why are people poor? Why is the babe poor?
Why is the steppe barren? Why donвЂ™t they hug each other and kiss? Why
donвЂ™t they sing songs of joy? Why are they so dark from black misery? Why
donвЂ™t they feed the babe?вЂќ

And he felt that, though his questions were unreasonable and senseless,
yet he wanted to ask just that, and he had to ask it just in that way. And
he felt that a passion of pity, such as he had never known before, was
rising in his heart, that he wanted to cry, that he wanted to do something
for them all, so that the babe should weep no more, so that the darkвЂђ
faced, driedвЂђup mother should not weep, that no one should shed tears
again from that moment, and he wanted to do it at once, at once,
regardless of all obstacles, with all the recklessness of the Karamazovs.

вЂњAnd IвЂ™m coming with you. I wonвЂ™t leave you now for the rest of my life,
IвЂ™m coming with you,вЂќ he heard close beside him GrushenkaвЂ™s tender voice,
thrilling with emotion. And his heart glowed, and he struggled forward
towards the light, and he longed to live, to live, to go on and on,
towards the new, beckoning light, and to hasten, hasten, now, at once!

вЂњWhat! Where?вЂќ he exclaimed opening his eyes, and sitting up on the chest,
as though he had revived from a swoon, smiling brightly. Nikolay
Parfenovitch was standing over him, suggesting that he should hear the
protocol read aloud and sign it. Mitya guessed that he had been asleep an
hour or more, but he did not hear Nikolay Parfenovitch. He was suddenly
struck by the fact that there was a pillow under his head, which hadnвЂ™t
been there when he had leant back, exhausted, on the chest.

вЂњWho put that pillow under my head? Who was so kind?вЂќ he cried, with a
sort of ecstatic gratitude, and tears in his voice, as though some great
kindness had been shown him.

He never found out who this kind man was; perhaps one of the peasant
witnesses, or Nikolay ParfenovitchвЂ™s little secretary, had compassionately
thought to put a pillow under his head; but his whole soul was quivering
with tears. He went to the table and said that he would sign whatever they
liked.

вЂњIвЂ™ve had a good dream, gentlemen,вЂќ he said in a strange voice, with a new
light, as of joy, in his face.



Chapter IX. They Carry Mitya Away


When the protocol had been signed, Nikolay Parfenovitch turned solemnly to
the prisoner and read him the вЂњCommittal,вЂќ setting forth, that in such a
year, on such a day, in such a place, the investigating lawyer of suchвЂђ
andвЂђsuch a district court, having examined soвЂђandвЂђso (to wit, Mitya)
accused of this and of that (all the charges were carefully written out)
and having considered that the accused, not pleading guilty to the charges
made against him, had brought forward nothing in his defense, while the
witnesses, soвЂђandвЂђso, and soвЂђandвЂђso, and the circumstances suchвЂђandвЂђsuch
testify against him, acting in accordance with suchвЂђandвЂђsuch articles of
the Statute Book, and so on, has ruled, that, in order to preclude soвЂђandвЂђ
so (Mitya) from all means of evading pursuit and judgment he be detained
in suchвЂђandвЂђsuch a prison, which he hereby notifies to the accused and
communicates a copy of this same вЂњCommittalвЂќ to the deputy prosecutor, and
so on, and so on.

In brief, Mitya was informed that he was, from that moment, a prisoner,
and that he would be driven at once to the town, and there shut up in a
very unpleasant place. Mitya listened attentively, and only shrugged his
shoulders.

вЂњWell, gentlemen, I donвЂ™t blame you. IвЂ™m ready.... I understand that
thereвЂ™s nothing else for you to do.вЂќ

Nikolay Parfenovitch informed him gently that he would be escorted at once
by the rural police officer, Mavriky Mavrikyevitch, who happened to be on
the spot....

вЂњStay,вЂќ Mitya interrupted, suddenly, and impelled by uncontrollable
feeling he pronounced, addressing all in the room:

вЂњGentlemen, weвЂ™re all cruel, weвЂ™re all monsters, we all make men weep, and
mothers, and babes at the breast, but of all, let it be settled here, now,
of all I am the lowest reptile! IвЂ™ve sworn to amend, and every day IвЂ™ve
done the same filthy things. I understand now that such men as I need a
blow, a blow of destiny to catch them as with a noose, and bind them by a
force from without. Never, never should I have risen of myself! But the
thunderbolt has fallen. I accept the torture of accusation, and my public
shame, I want to suffer and by suffering I shall be purified. Perhaps I
shall be purified, gentlemen? But listen, for the last time, I am not
guilty of my fatherвЂ™s blood. I accept my punishment, not because I killed
him, but because I meant to kill him, and perhaps I really might have
killed him. Still I mean to fight it out with you. I warn you of that.
IвЂ™ll fight it out with you to the end, and then God will decide. GoodвЂђby,
gentlemen, donвЂ™t be vexed with me for having shouted at you during the
examination. Oh, I was still such a fool then.... In another minute I
shall be a prisoner, but now, for the last time, as a free man, Dmitri
Karamazov offers you his hand. Saying goodвЂђby to you, I say it to all
men.вЂќ

His voice quivered and he stretched out his hand, but Nikolay
Parfenovitch, who happened to stand nearest to him, with a sudden, almost
nervous movement, hid his hands behind his back. Mitya instantly noticed
this, and started. He let his outstretched hand fall at once.

вЂњThe preliminary inquiry is not yet over,вЂќ Nikolay Parfenovitch faltered,
somewhat embarrassed. вЂњWe will continue it in the town, and I, for my
part, of course, am ready to wish you all success ... in your defense....
As a matter of fact, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, IвЂ™ve always been disposed to
regard you as, so to speak, more unfortunate than guilty. All of us here,
if I may make bold to speak for all, we are all ready to recognize that
you are, at bottom, a young man of honor, but, alas, one who has been
carried away by certain passions to a somewhat excessive degree....вЂќ

Nikolay ParfenovitchвЂ™s little figure was positively majestic by the time
he had finished speaking. It struck Mitya that in another minute this
вЂњboyвЂќ would take his arm, lead him to another corner, and renew their
conversation about вЂњgirls.вЂќ But many quite irrelevant and inappropriate
thoughts sometimes occur even to a prisoner when he is being led out to
execution.

вЂњGentlemen, you are good, you are humane, may I see _her_ to say вЂgoodвЂђbyвЂ™
for the last time?вЂќ asked Mitya.

вЂњCertainly, but considering ... in fact, now itвЂ™s impossible except in the
presence ofвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњOh, well, if it must be so, it must!вЂќ

Grushenka was brought in, but the farewell was brief, and of few words,
and did not at all satisfy Nikolay Parfenovitch. Grushenka made a deep bow
to Mitya.

вЂњI have told you I am yours, and I will be yours. I will follow you for
ever, wherever they may send you. Farewell; you are guiltless, though
youвЂ™ve been your own undoing.вЂќ

Her lips quivered, tears flowed from her eyes.

вЂњForgive me, Grusha, for my love, for ruining you, too, with my love.вЂќ

Mitya would have said something more, but he broke off and went out. He
was at once surrounded by men who kept a constant watch on him. At the
bottom of the steps to which he had driven up with such a dash the day
before with AndreyвЂ™s three horses, two carts stood in readiness. Mavriky
Mavrikyevitch, a sturdy, thickвЂђset man with a wrinkled face, was annoyed
about something, some sudden irregularity. He was shouting angrily. He
asked Mitya to get into the cart with somewhat excessive surliness.

вЂњWhen I stood him drinks in the tavern, the man had quite a different
face,вЂќ thought Mitya, as he got in. At the gates there was a crowd of
people, peasants, women and drivers. Trifon Borissovitch came down the
steps too. All stared at Mitya.

вЂњForgive me at parting, good people!вЂќ Mitya shouted suddenly from the
cart.

вЂњForgive us too!вЂќ he heard two or three voices.

вЂњGoodвЂђby to you, too, Trifon Borissovitch!вЂќ

But Trifon Borissovitch did not even turn round. He was, perhaps, too
busy. He, too, was shouting and fussing about something. It appeared that
everything was not yet ready in the second cart, in which two constables
were to accompany Mavriky Mavrikyevitch. The peasant who had been ordered
to drive the second cart was pulling on his smock, stoutly maintaining
that it was not his turn to go, but AkimвЂ™s. But Akim was not to be seen.
They ran to look for him. The peasant persisted and besought them to wait.

вЂњYou see what our peasants are, Mavriky Mavrikyevitch. TheyвЂ™ve no shame!вЂќ
exclaimed Trifon Borissovitch. вЂњAkim gave you twentyвЂђfive copecks the day
before yesterday. YouвЂ™ve drunk it all and now you cry out. IвЂ™m simply
surprised at your goodвЂђnature, with our low peasants, Mavriky
Mavrikyevitch, thatвЂ™s all I can say.вЂќ

вЂњBut what do we want a second cart for?вЂќ Mitya put in. вЂњLetвЂ™s start with
the one, Mavriky Mavrikyevitch. I wonвЂ™t be unruly, I wonвЂ™t run away from
you, old fellow. What do we want an escort for?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll trouble you, sir, to learn how to speak to me if youвЂ™ve never been
taught. IвЂ™m not вЂold fellowвЂ™ to you, and you can keep your advice for
another time!вЂќ Mavriky Mavrikyevitch snapped out savagely, as though glad
to vent his wrath.

Mitya was reduced to silence. He flushed all over. A moment later he felt
suddenly very cold. The rain had ceased, but the dull sky was still
overcast with clouds, and a keen wind was blowing straight in his face.

вЂњIвЂ™ve taken a chill,вЂќ thought Mitya, twitching his shoulders.

At last Mavriky Mavrikyevitch, too, got into the cart, sat down heavily,
and, as though without noticing it, squeezed Mitya into the corner. It is
true that he was out of humor and greatly disliked the task that had been
laid upon him.

вЂњGoodвЂђby, Trifon Borissovitch!вЂќ Mitya shouted again, and felt himself,
that he had not called out this time from goodвЂђnature, but involuntarily,
from resentment.

But Trifon Borissovitch stood proudly, with both hands behind his back,
and staring straight at Mitya with a stern and angry face, he made no
reply.

вЂњGoodвЂђby, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, goodвЂђby!вЂќ he heard all at once the voice of
Kalganov, who had suddenly darted out. Running up to the cart he held out
his hand to Mitya. He had no cap on.

Mitya had time to seize and press his hand.

вЂњGoodвЂђby, dear fellow! I shanвЂ™t forget your generosity,вЂќ he cried warmly.

But the cart moved and their hands parted. The bell began ringing and
Mitya was driven off.

Kalganov ran back, sat down in a corner, bent his head, hid his face in
his hands, and burst out crying. For a long while he sat like that, crying
as though he were a little boy instead of a young man of twenty. Oh, he
believed almost without doubt in MityaвЂ™s guilt.

вЂњWhat are these people? What can men be after this?вЂќ he exclaimed
incoherently, in bitter despondency, almost despair. At that moment he had
no desire to live.

вЂњIs it worth it? Is it worth it?вЂќ exclaimed the boy in his grief.





PART IV




Book X. The Boys



Chapter I. Kolya Krassotkin


It was the beginning of November. There had been a hard frost, eleven
degrees RГ©aumur, without snow, but a little dry snow had fallen on the
frozen ground during the night, and a keen dry wind was lifting and
blowing it along the dreary streets of our town, especially about the
marketвЂђplace. It was a dull morning, but the snow had ceased.

Not far from the marketвЂђplace, close to PlotnikovвЂ™s shop, there stood a
small house, very clean both without and within. It belonged to Madame
Krassotkin, the widow of a former provincial secretary, who had been dead
for fourteen years. His widow, still a niceвЂђlooking woman of thirtyвЂђtwo,
was living in her neat little house on her private means. She lived in
respectable seclusion; she was of a soft but fairly cheerful disposition.
She was about eighteen at the time of her husbandвЂ™s death; she had been
married only a year and had just borne him a son. From the day of his
death she had devoted herself heart and soul to the bringing up of her
precious treasure, her boy Kolya. Though she had loved him passionately
those fourteen years, he had caused her far more suffering than happiness.
She had been trembling and fainting with terror almost every day, afraid
he would fall ill, would catch cold, do something naughty, climb on a
chair and fall off it, and so on and so on. When Kolya began going to
school, the mother devoted herself to studying all the sciences with him
so as to help him, and go through his lessons with him. She hastened to
make the acquaintance of the teachers and their wives, even made up to
KolyaвЂ™s schoolfellows, and fawned upon them in the hope of thus saving
Kolya from being teased, laughed at, or beaten by them. She went so far
that the boys actually began to mock at him on her account and taunt him
with being a вЂњmotherвЂ™s darling.вЂќ

But the boy could take his own part. He was a resolute boy, вЂњtremendously
strong,вЂќ as was rumored in his class, and soon proved to be the fact; he
was agile, strongвЂђwilled, and of an audacious and enterprising temper. He
was good at lessons, and there was a rumor in the school that he could
beat the teacher, Dardanelov, at arithmetic and universal history. Though
he looked down upon every one, he was a good comrade and not supercilious.
He accepted his schoolfellowsвЂ™ respect as his due, but was friendly with
them. Above all, he knew where to draw the line. He could restrain himself
on occasion, and in his relations with the teachers he never overstepped
that last mystic limit beyond which a prank becomes an unpardonable breach
of discipline. But he was as fond of mischief on every possible occasion
as the smallest boy in the school, and not so much for the sake of
mischief as for creating a sensation, inventing something, something
effective and conspicuous. He was extremely vain. He knew how to make even
his mother give way to him; he was almost despotic in his control of her.
She gave way to him, oh, she had given way to him for years. The one
thought unendurable to her was that her boy had no great love for her. She
was always fancying that Kolya was вЂњunfeelingвЂќ to her, and at times,
dissolving into hysterical tears, she used to reproach him with his
coldness. The boy disliked this, and the more demonstrations of feeling
were demanded of him the more he seemed intentionally to avoid them. Yet
it was not intentional on his part but instinctiveвЂ”it was his character.
His mother was mistaken; he was very fond of her. He only disliked
вЂњsheepish sentimentality,вЂќ as he expressed it in his schoolboy language.

There was a bookcase in the house containing a few books that had been his
fatherвЂ™s. Kolya was fond of reading, and had read several of them by
himself. His mother did not mind that and only wondered sometimes at
seeing the boy stand for hours by the bookcase poring over a book instead
of going to play. And in that way Kolya read some things unsuitable for
his age.

Though the boy, as a rule, knew where to draw the line in his mischief, he
had of late begun to play pranks that caused his mother serious alarm. It
is true there was nothing vicious in what he did, but a wild mad
recklessness.

It happened that July, during the summer holidays, that the mother and son
went to another district, fortyвЂђfive miles away, to spend a week with a
distant relation, whose husband was an official at the railway station
(the very station, the nearest one to our town, from which a month later
Ivan Fyodorovitch Karamazov set off for Moscow). There Kolya began by
carefully investigating every detail connected with the railways, knowing
that he could impress his schoolfellows when he got home with his newly
acquired knowledge. But there happened to be some other boys in the place
with whom he soon made friends. Some of them were living at the station,
others in the neighborhood; there were six or seven of them, all between
twelve and fifteen, and two of them came from our town. The boys played
together, and on the fourth or fifth day of KolyaвЂ™s stay at the station, a
mad bet was made by the foolish boys. Kolya, who was almost the youngest
of the party and rather looked down upon by the others in consequence, was
moved by vanity or by reckless bravado to bet them two roubles that he
would lie down between the rails at night when the eleven oвЂ™clock train
was due, and would lie there without moving while the train rolled over
him at full speed. It is true they made a preliminary investigation, from
which it appeared that it was possible to lie so flat between the rails
that the train could pass over without touching, but to lie there was no
joke! Kolya maintained stoutly that he would. At first they laughed at
him, called him a little liar, a braggart, but that only egged him on.
What piqued him most was that these boys of fifteen turned up their noses
at him too superciliously, and were at first disposed to treat him as вЂњa
small boy,вЂќ not fit to associate with them, and that was an unendurable
insult.

And so it was resolved to go in the evening, half a mile from the station,
so that the train might have time to get up full speed after leaving the
station. The boys assembled. It was a pitchвЂђdark night without a moon. At
the time fixed, Kolya lay down between the rails. The five others who had
taken the bet waited among the bushes below the embankment, their hearts
beating with suspense, which was followed by alarm and remorse. At last
they heard in the distance the rumble of the train leaving the station.
Two red lights gleamed out of the darkness; the monster roared as it
approached.

вЂњRun, run away from the rails,вЂќ the boys cried to Kolya from the bushes,
breathless with terror. But it was too late: the train darted up and flew
past. The boys rushed to Kolya. He lay without moving. They began pulling
at him, lifting him up. He suddenly got up and walked away without a word.
Then he explained that he had lain there as though he were insensible to
frighten them, but the fact was that he really had lost consciousness, as
he confessed long after to his mother. In this way his reputation as вЂњa
desperate character,вЂќ was established for ever. He returned home to the
station as white as a sheet. Next day he had a slight attack of nervous
fever, but he was in high spirits and well pleased with himself. The
incident did not become known at once, but when they came back to the town
it penetrated to the school and even reached the ears of the masters. But
then KolyaвЂ™s mother hastened to entreat the masters on her boyвЂ™s behalf,
and in the end Dardanelov, a respected and influential teacher, exerted
himself in his favor, and the affair was ignored.

Dardanelov was a middleвЂђaged bachelor, who had been passionately in love
with Madame Krassotkin for many years past, and had once already, about a
year previously, ventured, trembling with fear and the delicacy of his
sentiments, to offer her most respectfully his hand in marriage. But she
refused him resolutely, feeling that to accept him would be an act of
treachery to her son, though Dardanelov had, to judge from certain
mysterious symptoms, reason for believing that he was not an object of
aversion to the charming but too chaste and tenderвЂђhearted widow. KolyaвЂ™s
mad prank seemed to have broken the ice, and Dardanelov was rewarded for
his intercession by a suggestion of hope. The suggestion, it is true, was
a faint one, but then Dardanelov was such a paragon of purity and delicacy
that it was enough for the time being to make him perfectly happy. He was
fond of the boy, though he would have felt it beneath him to try and win
him over, and was severe and strict with him in class. Kolya, too, kept
him at a respectful distance. He learned his lessons perfectly; he was
second in his class, was reserved with Dardanelov, and the whole class
firmly believed that Kolya was so good at universal history that he could
вЂњbeatвЂќ even Dardanelov. Kolya did indeed ask him the question, вЂњWho
founded Troy?вЂќ to which Dardanelov had made a very vague reply, referring
to the movements and migrations of races, to the remoteness of the period,
to the mythical legends. But the question, вЂњWho had founded Troy?вЂќ that
is, what individuals, he could not answer, and even for some reason
regarded the question as idle and frivolous. But the boys remained
convinced that Dardanelov did not know who founded Troy. Kolya had read of
the founders of Troy in Smaragdov, whose history was among the books in
his fatherвЂ™s bookcase. In the end all the boys became interested in the
question, who it was that had founded Troy, but Krassotkin would not tell
his secret, and his reputation for knowledge remained unshaken.

After the incident on the railway a certain change came over KolyaвЂ™s
attitude to his mother. When Anna Fyodorovna (Madame Krassotkin) heard of
her sonвЂ™s exploit, she almost went out of her mind with horror. She had
such terrible attacks of hysterics, lasting with intervals for several
days, that Kolya, seriously alarmed at last, promised on his honor that
such pranks should never be repeated. He swore on his knees before the
holy image, and swore by the memory of his father, at Madame KrassotkinвЂ™s
instance, and the вЂњmanlyвЂќ Kolya burst into tears like a boy of six. And
all that day the mother and son were constantly rushing into each otherвЂ™s
arms sobbing. Next day Kolya woke up as вЂњunfeelingвЂќ as before, but he had
become more silent, more modest, sterner, and more thoughtful.

Six weeks later, it is true, he got into another scrape, which even
brought his name to the ears of our Justice of the Peace, but it was a
scrape of quite another kind, amusing, foolish, and he did not, as it
turned out, take the leading part in it, but was only implicated in it.
But of this later. His mother still fretted and trembled, but the more
uneasy she became, the greater were the hopes of Dardanelov. It must be
noted that Kolya understood and divined what was in DardanelovвЂ™s heart
and, of course, despised him profoundly for his вЂњfeelingsвЂќ; he had in the
past been so tactless as to show this contempt before his mother, hinting
vaguely that he knew what Dardanelov was after. But from the time of the
railway incident his behavior in this respect also was changed; he did not
allow himself the remotest allusion to the subject and began to speak more
respectfully of Dardanelov before his mother, which the sensitive woman at
once appreciated with boundless gratitude. But at the slightest mention of
Dardanelov by a visitor in KolyaвЂ™s presence, she would flush as pink as a
rose. At such moments Kolya would either stare out of the window scowling,
or would investigate the state of his boots, or would shout angrily for
вЂњPerezvon,вЂќ the big, shaggy, mangy dog, which he had picked up a month
before, brought home, and kept for some reason secretly indoors, not
showing him to any of his schoolfellows. He bullied him frightfully,
teaching him all sorts of tricks, so that the poor dog howled for him
whenever he was absent at school, and when he came in, whined with
delight, rushed about as if he were crazy, begged, lay down on the ground
pretending to be dead, and so on; in fact, showed all the tricks he had
taught him, not at the word of command, but simply from the zeal of his
excited and grateful heart.

I have forgotten, by the way, to mention that Kolya Krassotkin was the boy
stabbed with a penknife by the boy already known to the reader as the son
of Captain Snegiryov. Ilusha had been defending his father when the
schoolboys jeered at him, shouting the nickname вЂњwisp of tow.вЂќ



Chapter II. Children


And so on that frosty, snowy, and windy day in November, Kolya Krassotkin
was sitting at home. It was Sunday and there was no school. It had just
struck eleven, and he particularly wanted to go out вЂњon very urgent
business,вЂќ but he was left alone in charge of the house, for it so
happened that all its elder inmates were absent owing to a sudden and
singular event. Madame Krassotkin had let two little rooms, separated from
the rest of the house by a passage, to a doctorвЂ™s wife with her two small
children. This lady was the same age as Anna Fyodorovna, and a great
friend of hers. Her husband, the doctor, had taken his departure twelve
months before, going first to Orenburg and then to Tashkend, and for the
last six months she had not heard a word from him. Had it not been for her
friendship with Madame Krassotkin, which was some consolation to the
forsaken lady, she would certainly have completely dissolved away in
tears. And now, to add to her misfortunes, Katerina, her only servant, was
suddenly moved the evening before to announce, to her mistressвЂ™s
amazement, that she proposed to bring a child into the world before
morning. It seemed almost miraculous to every one that no one had noticed
the probability of it before. The astounded doctorвЂ™s wife decided to move
Katerina while there was still time to an establishment in the town kept
by a midwife for such emergencies. As she set great store by her servant,
she promptly carried out this plan and remained there looking after her.
By the morning all Madame KrassotkinвЂ™s friendly sympathy and energy were
called upon to render assistance and appeal to some one for help in the
case.

So both the ladies were absent from home, the KrassotkinsвЂ™ servant,
Agafya, had gone out to the market, and Kolya was thus left for a time to
protect and look after вЂњthe kids,вЂќ that is, the son and daughter of the
doctorвЂ™s wife, who were left alone. Kolya was not afraid of taking care of
the house, besides he had Perezvon, who had been told to lie flat, without
moving, under the bench in the hall. Every time Kolya, walking to and fro
through the rooms, came into the hall, the dog shook his head and gave two
loud and insinuating taps on the floor with his tail, but alas! the
whistle did not sound to release him. Kolya looked sternly at the luckless
dog, who relapsed again into obedient rigidity. The one thing that
troubled Kolya was вЂњthe kids.вЂќ He looked, of course, with the utmost scorn
on KaterinaвЂ™s unexpected adventure, but he was very fond of the bereaved
вЂњkiddies,вЂќ and had already taken them a pictureвЂђbook. Nastya, the elder, a
girl of eight, could read, and Kostya, the boy, aged seven, was very fond
of being read to by her. Krassotkin could, of course, have provided more
diverting entertainment for them. He could have made them stand side by
side and played soldiers with them, or sent them hiding all over the
house. He had done so more than once before and was not above doing it, so
much so that a report once spread at school that Krassotkin played horses
with the little lodgers at home, prancing with his head on one side like a
traceвЂђhorse. But Krassotkin haughtily parried this thrust, pointing out
that to play horses with boys of oneвЂ™s own age, boys of thirteen, would
certainly be disgraceful вЂњat this date,вЂќ but that he did it for the sake
of вЂњthe kidsвЂќ because he liked them, and no one had a right to call him to
account for his feelings. The two вЂњkidsвЂќ adored him.

But on this occasion he was in no mood for games. He had very important
business of his own before him, something almost mysterious. Meanwhile
time was passing and Agafya, with whom he could have left the children,
would not come back from market. He had several times already crossed the
passage, opened the door of the lodgersвЂ™ room and looked anxiously at вЂњthe
kidsвЂќ who were sitting over the book, as he had bidden them. Every time he
opened the door they grinned at him, hoping he would come in and would do
something delightful and amusing. But Kolya was bothered and did not go
in.

At last it struck eleven and he made up his mind, once for all, that if
that вЂњdamnedвЂќ Agafya did not come back within ten minutes he should go out
without waiting for her, making вЂњthe kidsвЂќ promise, of course, to be brave
when he was away, not to be naughty, not to cry from fright. With this
idea he put on his wadded winter overcoat with its catskin fur collar,
slung his satchel round his shoulder, and, regardless of his motherвЂ™s
constantly reiterated entreaties that he would always put on goloshes in
such cold weather, he looked at them contemptuously as he crossed the hall
and went out with only his boots on. Perezvon, seeing him in his outdoor
clothes, began tapping nervously, yet vigorously, on the floor with his
tail. Twitching all over, he even uttered a plaintive whine. But Kolya,
seeing his dogвЂ™s passionate excitement, decided that it was a breach of
discipline, kept him for another minute under the bench, and only when he
had opened the door into the passage, whistled for him. The dog leapt up
like a mad creature and rushed bounding before him rapturously.

Kolya opened the door to peep at вЂњthe kids.вЂќ They were both sitting as
before at the table, not reading but warmly disputing about something. The
children often argued together about various exciting problems of life,
and Nastya, being the elder, always got the best of it. If Kostya did not
agree with her, he almost always appealed to Kolya Krassotkin, and his
verdict was regarded as infallible by both of them. This time the вЂњkidsвЂ™вЂќ
discussion rather interested Krassotkin, and he stood still in the passage
to listen. The children saw he was listening and that made them dispute
with even greater energy.

вЂњI shall never, never believe,вЂќ Nastya prattled, вЂњthat the old women find
babies among the cabbages in the kitchenвЂђgarden. ItвЂ™s winter now and there
are no cabbages, and so the old woman couldnвЂ™t have taken Katerina a
daughter.вЂќ

Kolya whistled to himself.

вЂњOr perhaps they do bring babies from somewhere, but only to those who are
married.вЂќ

Kostya stared at Nastya and listened, pondering profoundly.

вЂњNastya, how silly you are!вЂќ he said at last, firmly and calmly. вЂњHow can
Katerina have a baby when she isnвЂ™t married?вЂќ

Nastya was exasperated.

вЂњYou know nothing about it,вЂќ she snapped irritably. вЂњPerhaps she has a
husband, only he is in prison, so now sheвЂ™s got a baby.вЂќ

вЂњBut is her husband in prison?вЂќ the matterвЂђofвЂђfact Kostya inquired
gravely.

вЂњOr, I tell you what,вЂќ Nastya interrupted impulsively, completely
rejecting and forgetting her first hypothesis. вЂњShe hasnвЂ™t a husband, you
are right there, but she wants to be married, and so sheвЂ™s been thinking
of getting married, and thinking and thinking of it till now sheвЂ™s got it,
that is, not a husband but a baby.вЂќ

вЂњWell, perhaps so,вЂќ Kostya agreed, entirely vanquished. вЂњBut you didnвЂ™t
say so before. So how could I tell?вЂќ

вЂњCome, kiddies,вЂќ said Kolya, stepping into the room. вЂњYouвЂ™re terrible
people, I see.вЂќ

вЂњAnd Perezvon with you!вЂќ grinned Kostya, and began snapping his fingers
and calling Perezvon.

вЂњI am in a difficulty, kids,вЂќ Krassotkin began solemnly, вЂњand you must
help me. Agafya must have broken her leg, since she has not turned up till
now, thatвЂ™s certain. I must go out. Will you let me go?вЂќ

The children looked anxiously at one another. Their smiling faces showed
signs of uneasiness, but they did not yet fully grasp what was expected of
them.

вЂњYou wonвЂ™t be naughty while I am gone? You wonвЂ™t climb on the cupboard and
break your legs? You wonвЂ™t be frightened alone and cry?вЂќ

A look of profound despondency came into the childrenвЂ™s faces.

вЂњAnd I could show you something as a reward, a little copper cannon which
can be fired with real gunpowder.вЂќ

The childrenвЂ™s faces instantly brightened. вЂњShow us the cannon,вЂќ said
Kostya, beaming all over.

Krassotkin put his hand in his satchel, and pulling out a little bronze
cannon stood it on the table.

вЂњAh, you are bound to ask that! Look, itвЂ™s on wheels.вЂќ He rolled the toy
on along the table. вЂњAnd it can be fired off, too. It can be loaded with
shot and fired off.вЂќ

вЂњAnd it could kill any one?вЂќ

вЂњIt can kill any one; youвЂ™ve only got to aim at anybody,вЂќ and Krassotkin
explained where the powder had to be put, where the shot should be rolled
in, showing a tiny hole like a touchвЂђhole, and told them that it kicked
when it was fired.

The children listened with intense interest. What particularly struck
their imagination was that the cannon kicked.

вЂњAnd have you got any powder?вЂќ Nastya inquired.

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњShow us the powder, too,вЂќ she drawled with a smile of entreaty.

Krassotkin dived again into his satchel and pulled out a small flask
containing a little real gunpowder. He had some shot, too, in a screw of
paper. He even uncorked the flask and shook a little powder into the palm
of his hand.

вЂњOne has to be careful thereвЂ™s no fire about, or it would blow up and kill
us all,вЂќ Krassotkin warned them sensationally.

The children gazed at the powder with an aweвЂђstricken alarm that only
intensified their enjoyment. But Kostya liked the shot better.

вЂњAnd does the shot burn?вЂќ he inquired.

вЂњNo, it doesnвЂ™t.вЂќ

вЂњGive me a little shot,вЂќ he asked in an imploring voice.

вЂњIвЂ™ll give you a little shot; here, take it, but donвЂ™t show it to your
mother till I come back, or sheвЂ™ll be sure to think itвЂ™s gunpowder, and
will die of fright and give you a thrashing.вЂќ

вЂњMother never does whip us,вЂќ Nastya observed at once.

вЂњI know, I only said it to finish the sentence. And donвЂ™t you ever deceive
your mother except just this once, until I come back. And so, kiddies, can
I go out? You wonвЂ™t be frightened and cry when IвЂ™m gone?вЂќ

вЂњWe shaвЂ”all cry,вЂќ drawled Kostya, on the verge of tears already.

вЂњWe shall cry, we shall be sure to cry,вЂќ Nastya chimed in with timid
haste.

вЂњOh, children, children, how fraught with peril are your years! ThereвЂ™s no
help for it, chickens, I shall have to stay with you I donвЂ™t know how
long. And time is passing, time is passing, oogh!вЂќ

вЂњTell Perezvon to pretend to be dead!вЂќ Kostya begged.

вЂњThereвЂ™s no help for it, we must have recourse to Perezvon. _Ici_,
Perezvon.вЂќ And Kolya began giving orders to the dog, who performed all his
tricks.

He was a roughвЂђhaired dog, of medium size, with a coat of a sort of lilacвЂђ
gray color. He was blind in his right eye, and his left ear was torn. He
whined and jumped, stood and walked on his hind legs, lay on his back with
his paws in the air, rigid as though he were dead. While this last
performance was going on, the door opened and Agafya, Madame KrassotkinвЂ™s
servant, a stout woman of forty, marked with smallвЂђpox, appeared in the
doorway. She had come back from market and had a bag full of provisions in
her hand. Holding up the bag of provisions in her left hand she stood
still to watch the dog. Though Kolya had been so anxious for her return,
he did not cut short the performance, and after keeping Perezvon dead for
the usual time, at last he whistled to him. The dog jumped up and began
bounding about in his joy at having done his duty.

вЂњOnly think, a dog!вЂќ Agafya observed sententiously.

вЂњWhy are you late, female?вЂќ asked Krassotkin sternly.

вЂњFemale, indeed! Go on with you, you brat.вЂќ

вЂњBrat?вЂќ

вЂњYes, a brat. What is it to you if IвЂ™m late; if IвЂ™m late, you may be sure
I have good reason,вЂќ muttered Agafya, busying herself about the stove,
without a trace of anger or displeasure in her voice. She seemed quite
pleased, in fact, to enjoy a skirmish with her merry young master.

вЂњListen, you frivolous young woman,вЂќ Krassotkin began, getting up from the
sofa, вЂњcan you swear by all you hold sacred in the world and something
else besides, that you will watch vigilantly over the kids in my absence?
I am going out.вЂќ

вЂњAnd what am I going to swear for?вЂќ laughed Agafya. вЂњI shall look after
them without that.вЂќ

вЂњNo, you must swear on your eternal salvation. Else I shanвЂ™t go.вЂќ

вЂњWell, donвЂ™t then. What does it matter to me? ItвЂ™s cold out; stay at
home.вЂќ

вЂњKids,вЂќ Kolya turned to the children, вЂњthis woman will stay with you till
I come back or till your mother comes, for she ought to have been back
long ago. She will give you some lunch, too. YouвЂ™ll give them something,
Agafya, wonвЂ™t you?вЂќ

вЂњThat I can do.вЂќ

вЂњGoodвЂђby, chickens, I go with my heart at rest. And you, granny,вЂќ he added
gravely, in an undertone, as he passed Agafya, вЂњI hope youвЂ™ll spare their
tender years and not tell them any of your old womanвЂ™s nonsense about
Katerina. _Ici_, Perezvon!вЂќ

вЂњGet along with you!вЂќ retorted Agafya, really angry this time. вЂњRidiculous
boy! You want a whipping for saying such things, thatвЂ™s what you want!вЂќ



Chapter III. The Schoolboy


But Kolya did not hear her. At last he could go out. As he went out at the
gate he looked round him, shrugged up his shoulders, and saying вЂњIt is
freezing,вЂќ went straight along the street and turned off to the right
towards the marketвЂђplace. When he reached the last house but one before
the marketвЂђplace he stopped at the gate, pulled a whistle out of his
pocket, and whistled with all his might as though giving a signal. He had
not to wait more than a minute before a rosyвЂђcheeked boy of about eleven,
wearing a warm, neat and even stylish coat, darted out to meet him. This
was Smurov, a boy in the preparatory class (two classes below Kolya
Krassotkin), son of a wellвЂђtoвЂђdo official. Apparently he was forbidden by
his parents to associate with Krassotkin, who was well known to be a
desperately naughty boy, so Smurov was obviously slipping out on the sly.
He wasвЂ”if the reader has not forgottenвЂ”one of the group of boys who two
months before had thrown stones at Ilusha. He was the one who told Alyosha
Karamazov about Ilusha.

вЂњIвЂ™ve been waiting for you for the last hour, Krassotkin,вЂќ said Smurov
stolidly, and the boys strode towards the marketвЂђplace.

вЂњI am late,вЂќ answered Krassotkin. вЂњI was detained by circumstances. You
wonвЂ™t be thrashed for coming with me?вЂќ

вЂњCome, I say, IвЂ™m never thrashed! And youвЂ™ve got Perezvon with you?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re taking him, too?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњAh! if it were only Zhutchka!вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s impossible. ZhutchkaвЂ™s nonвЂђexistent. Zhutchka is lost in the mists
of obscurity.вЂќ

вЂњAh! couldnвЂ™t we do this?вЂќ Smurov suddenly stood still. вЂњYou see Ilusha
says that Zhutchka was a shaggy, grayish, smokyвЂђlooking dog like Perezvon.
CouldnвЂ™t you tell him this is Zhutchka, and he might believe you?вЂќ

вЂњBoy, shun a lie, thatвЂ™s one thing; even with a good objectвЂ”thatвЂ™s
another. Above all, I hope youвЂ™ve not told them anything about my coming.вЂќ

вЂњHeaven forbid! I know what I am about. But you wonвЂ™t comfort him with
Perezvon,вЂќ said Smurov, with a sigh. вЂњYou know his father, the captain,
вЂthe wisp of tow,вЂ™ told us that he was going to bring him a real mastiff
pup, with a black nose, toвЂђday. He thinks that would comfort Ilusha; but I
doubt it.вЂќ

вЂњAnd how is Ilusha?вЂќ

вЂњAh, he is bad, very bad! I believe heвЂ™s in consumption: he is quite
conscious, but his breathing! His breathingвЂ™s gone wrong. The other day he
asked to have his boots on to be led round the room. He tried to walk, but
he couldnвЂ™t stand. вЂAh, I told you before, father,вЂ™ he said, вЂthat those
boots were no good. I could never walk properly in them.вЂ™ He fancied it
was his boots that made him stagger, but it was simply weakness, really.
He wonвЂ™t live another week. Herzenstube is looking after him. Now they are
rich againвЂ”theyвЂ™ve got heaps of money.вЂќ

вЂњThey are rogues.вЂќ

вЂњWho are rogues?вЂќ

вЂњDoctors and the whole crew of quacks collectively, and also, of course,
individually. I donвЂ™t believe in medicine. ItвЂ™s a useless institution. I
mean to go into all that. But whatвЂ™s that sentimentality youвЂ™ve got up
there? The whole class seems to be there every day.вЂќ

вЂњNot the whole class: itвЂ™s only ten of our fellows who go to see him every
day. ThereвЂ™s nothing in that.вЂќ

вЂњWhat I donвЂ™t understand in all this is the part that Alexey Karamazov is
taking in it. His brotherвЂ™s going to be tried toвЂђmorrow or next day for
such a crime, and yet he has so much time to spend on sentimentality with
boys.вЂќ

вЂњThereвЂ™s no sentimentality about it. You are going yourself now to make it
up with Ilusha.вЂќ

вЂњMake it up with him? What an absurd expression! But I allow no one to
analyze my actions.вЂќ

вЂњAnd how pleased Ilusha will be to see you! He has no idea that you are
coming. Why was it, why was it you wouldnвЂ™t come all this time?вЂќ Smurov
cried with sudden warmth.

вЂњMy dear boy, thatвЂ™s my business, not yours. I am going of myself because
I choose to, but youвЂ™ve all been hauled there by Alexey KaramazovвЂ”thereвЂ™s
a difference, you know. And how do you know? I may not be going to make it
up at all. ItвЂ™s a stupid expression.вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s not Karamazov at all; itвЂ™s not his doing. Our fellows began going
there of themselves. Of course, they went with Karamazov at first. And
thereвЂ™s been nothing of that sortвЂ”no silliness. First one went, and then
another. His father was awfully pleased to see us. You know he will simply
go out of his mind if Ilusha dies. He sees that IlushaвЂ™s dying. And he
seems so glad weвЂ™ve made it up with Ilusha. Ilusha asked after you, that
was all. He just asks and says no more. His father will go out of his mind
or hang himself. He behaved like a madman before. You know he is a very
decent man. We made a mistake then. ItвЂ™s all the fault of that murderer
who beat him then.вЂќ

вЂњKaramazovвЂ™s a riddle to me all the same. I might have made his
acquaintance long ago, but I like to have a proper pride in some cases.
Besides, I have a theory about him which I must work out and verify.вЂќ

Kolya subsided into dignified silence. Smurov, too, was silent. Smurov, of
course, worshiped Krassotkin and never dreamed of putting himself on a
level with him. Now he was tremendously interested at KolyaвЂ™s saying that
he was вЂњgoing of himselfвЂќ to see Ilusha. He felt that there must be some
mystery in KolyaвЂ™s suddenly taking it into his head to go to him that day.
They crossed the marketвЂђplace, in which at that hour were many loaded
wagons from the country and a great number of live fowls. The market women
were selling rolls, cottons and threads, etc., in their booths. These
Sunday markets were naГЇvely called вЂњfairsвЂќ in the town, and there were
many such fairs in the year.

Perezvon ran about in the wildest spirits, sniffing about first one side,
then the other. When he met other dogs they zealously smelt each other
over according to the rules of canine etiquette.

вЂњI like to watch such realistic scenes, Smurov,вЂќ said Kolya suddenly.
вЂњHave you noticed how dogs sniff at one another when they meet? It seems
to be a law of their nature.вЂќ

вЂњYes; itвЂ™s a funny habit.вЂќ

вЂњNo, itвЂ™s not funny; you are wrong there. ThereвЂ™s nothing funny in nature,
however funny it may seem to man with his prejudices. If dogs could reason
and criticize us theyвЂ™d be sure to find just as much that would be funny
to them, if not far more, in the social relations of men, their
mastersвЂ”far more, indeed. I repeat that, because I am convinced that there
is far more foolishness among us. ThatвЂ™s RakitinвЂ™s ideaвЂ”a remarkable idea.
I am a Socialist, Smurov.вЂќ

вЂњAnd what is a Socialist?вЂќ asked Smurov.

вЂњThatвЂ™s when all are equal and all have property in common, there are no
marriages, and every one has any religion and laws he likes best, and all
the rest of it. You are not old enough to understand that yet. ItвЂ™s cold,
though.вЂќ

вЂњYes, twelve degrees of frost. Father looked at the thermometer just now.вЂќ

вЂњHave you noticed, Smurov, that in the middle of winter we donвЂ™t feel so
cold even when there are fifteen or eighteen degrees of frost as we do
now, in the beginning of winter, when there is a sudden frost of twelve
degrees, especially when there is not much snow. ItвЂ™s because people are
not used to it. Everything is habit with men, everything even in their
social and political relations. Habit is the great motiveвЂђpower. What a
funnyвЂђlooking peasant!вЂќ

Kolya pointed to a tall peasant, with a goodвЂђnatured countenance in a long
sheepskin coat, who was standing by his wagon, clapping together his
hands, in their shapeless leather gloves, to warm them. His long fair
beard was all white with frost.

вЂњThat peasantвЂ™s beardвЂ™s frozen,вЂќ Kolya cried in a loud provocative voice
as he passed him.

вЂњLots of peopleвЂ™s beards are frozen,вЂќ the peasant replied, calmly and
sententiously.

вЂњDonвЂ™t provoke him,вЂќ observed Smurov.

вЂњItвЂ™s all right; he wonвЂ™t be cross; heвЂ™s a nice fellow. GoodвЂђby, Matvey.вЂќ

вЂњGoodвЂђby.вЂќ

вЂњIs your name Matvey?вЂќ

вЂњYes. DidnвЂ™t you know?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I didnвЂ™t. It was a guess.вЂќ

вЂњYou donвЂ™t say so! You are a schoolboy, I suppose?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњYou get whipped, I expect?вЂќ

вЂњNothing to speak ofвЂ”sometimes.вЂќ

вЂњDoes it hurt?вЂќ

вЂњWell, yes, it does.вЂќ

вЂњEch, what a life!вЂќ The peasant heaved a sigh from the bottom of his
heart.

вЂњGoodвЂђby, Matvey.вЂќ

вЂњGoodвЂђby. You are a nice chap, that you are.вЂќ

The boys went on.

вЂњThat was a nice peasant,вЂќ Kolya observed to Smurov. вЂњI like talking to
the peasants, and am always glad to do them justice.вЂќ

вЂњWhy did you tell a lie, pretending we are thrashed?вЂќ asked Smurov.

вЂњI had to say that to please him.вЂќ

вЂњHow do you mean?вЂќ

вЂњYou know, Smurov, I donвЂ™t like being asked the same thing twice. I like
people to understand at the first word. Some things canвЂ™t be explained.
According to a peasantвЂ™s notions, schoolboys are whipped, and must be
whipped. What would a schoolboy be if he were not whipped? And if I were
to tell him we are not, heвЂ™d be disappointed. But you donвЂ™t understand
that. One has to know how to talk to the peasants.вЂќ

вЂњOnly donвЂ™t tease them, please, or youвЂ™ll get into another scrape as you
did about that goose.вЂќ

вЂњSo youвЂ™re afraid?вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t laugh, Kolya. Of course IвЂ™m afraid. My father would be awfully
cross. I am strictly forbidden to go out with you.вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t be uneasy, nothing will happen this time. Hallo, Natasha!вЂќ he
shouted to a market woman in one of the booths.

вЂњCall me Natasha! What next! My name is Marya,вЂќ the middleвЂђaged market
woman shouted at him.

вЂњI am so glad itвЂ™s Marya. GoodвЂђby!вЂќ

вЂњAh, you young rascal! A brat like you to carry on so!вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™m in a hurry. I canвЂ™t stay now. You shall tell me next Sunday.вЂќ Kolya
waved his hand at her, as though she had attacked him and not he her.

вЂњIвЂ™ve nothing to tell you next Sunday. You set upon me, you impudent young
monkey. I didnвЂ™t say anything,вЂќ bawled Marya. вЂњYou want a whipping, thatвЂ™s
what you want, you saucy jackanapes!вЂќ

There was a roar of laughter among the other market women round her.
Suddenly a man in a violent rage darted out from the arcade of shops close
by. He was a young man, not a native of the town, with dark, curly hair
and a long, pale face, marked with smallpox. He wore a long blue coat and
a peaked cap, and looked like a merchantвЂ™s clerk. He was in a state of
stupid excitement and brandished his fist at Kolya.

вЂњI know you!вЂќ he cried angrily, вЂњI know you!вЂќ

Kolya stared at him. He could not recall when he could have had a row with
the man. But he had been in so many rows in the street that he could
hardly remember them all.

вЂњDo you?вЂќ he asked sarcastically.

вЂњI know you! I know you!вЂќ the man repeated idiotically.

вЂњSo much the better for you. Well, itвЂ™s time I was going. GoodвЂђby!вЂќ

вЂњYou are at your saucy pranks again?вЂќ cried the man. вЂњYou are at your
saucy pranks again? I know, you are at it again!вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s not your business, brother, if I am at my saucy pranks again,вЂќ said
Kolya, standing still and scanning him.

вЂњNot my business?вЂќ

вЂњNo; itвЂ™s not your business.вЂќ

вЂњWhose then? Whose then? Whose then?вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s Trifon NikititchвЂ™s business, not yours.вЂќ

вЂњWhat Trifon Nikititch?вЂќ asked the youth, staring with loutish amazement
at Kolya, but still as angry as ever.

Kolya scanned him gravely.

вЂњHave you been to the Church of the Ascension?вЂќ he suddenly asked him,
with stern emphasis.

вЂњWhat Church of Ascension? What for? No, I havenвЂ™t,вЂќ said the young man,
somewhat taken aback.

вЂњDo you know Sabaneyev?вЂќ Kolya went on even more emphatically and even
more severely.

вЂњWhat Sabaneyev? No, I donвЂ™t know him.вЂќ

вЂњWell then you can go to the devil,вЂќ said Kolya, cutting short the
conversation; and turning sharply to the right he strode quickly on his
way as though he disdained further conversation with a dolt who did not
even know Sabaneyev.

вЂњStop, heigh! What Sabaneyev?вЂќ the young man recovered from his momentary
stupefaction and was as excited as before. вЂњWhat did he say?вЂќ He turned to
the market women with a silly stare.

The women laughed.

вЂњYou can never tell what heвЂ™s after,вЂќ said one of them.

вЂњWhat Sabaneyev is it heвЂ™s talking about?вЂќ the young man repeated, still
furious and brandishing his right arm.

вЂњIt must be a Sabaneyev who worked for the Kuzmitchovs, thatвЂ™s who it must
be,вЂќ one of the women suggested.

The young man stared at her wildly.

вЂњFor the Kuzmitchovs?вЂќ repeated another woman. вЂњBut his name wasnвЂ™t
Trifon. His nameвЂ™s Kuzma, not Trifon; but the boy said Trifon Nikititch,
so it canвЂ™t be the same.вЂќ

вЂњHis name is not Trifon and not Sabaneyev, itвЂ™s Tchizhov,вЂќ put in suddenly
a third woman, who had hitherto been silent, listening gravely. вЂњAlexey
Ivanitch is his name. Tchizhov, Alexey Ivanitch.вЂќ

вЂњNot a doubt about it, itвЂ™s Tchizhov,вЂќ a fourth woman emphatically
confirmed the statement.

The bewildered youth gazed from one to another.

вЂњBut what did he ask for, what did he ask for, good people?вЂќ he cried
almost in desperation. вЂњ вЂDo you know Sabaneyev?вЂ™ says he. And who the
devilвЂ™s to know who is Sabaneyev?вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™re a senseless fellow. I tell you itвЂ™s not Sabaneyev, but Tchizhov,
Alexey Ivanitch Tchizhov, thatвЂ™s who it is!вЂќ one of the women shouted at
him impressively.

вЂњWhat Tchizhov? Who is he? Tell me, if you know.вЂќ

вЂњThat tall, sniveling fellow who used to sit in the market in the summer.вЂќ

вЂњAnd whatвЂ™s your Tchizhov to do with me, good people, eh?вЂќ

вЂњHow can I tell what heвЂ™s to do with you?вЂќ put in another. вЂњYou ought to
know yourself what you want with him, if you make such a clamor about him.
He spoke to you, he did not speak to us, you stupid. DonвЂ™t you really know
him?вЂќ

вЂњKnow whom?вЂќ

вЂњTchizhov.вЂќ

вЂњThe devil take Tchizhov and you with him. IвЂ™ll give him a hiding, that I
will. He was laughing at me!вЂќ

вЂњWill give Tchizhov a hiding! More likely he will give you one. You are a
fool, thatвЂ™s what you are!вЂќ

вЂњNot Tchizhov, not Tchizhov, you spiteful, mischievous woman. IвЂ™ll give
the boy a hiding. Catch him, catch him, he was laughing at me!вЂќ

The woman guffawed. But Kolya was by now a long way off, marching along
with a triumphant air. Smurov walked beside him, looking round at the
shouting group far behind. He too was in high spirits, though he was still
afraid of getting into some scrape in KolyaвЂ™s company.

вЂњWhat Sabaneyev did you mean?вЂќ he asked Kolya, foreseeing what his answer
would be.

вЂњHow do I know? Now thereвЂ™ll be a hubbub among them all day. I like to
stir up fools in every class of society. ThereвЂ™s another blockhead, that
peasant there. You know, they say вЂthereвЂ™s no one stupider than a stupid
Frenchman,вЂ™ but a stupid Russian shows it in his face just as much. CanвЂ™t
you see it all over his face that he is a fool, that peasant, eh?вЂќ

вЂњLet him alone, Kolya. LetвЂ™s go on.вЂќ

вЂњNothing could stop me, now I am once off. Hey, good morning, peasant!вЂќ

A sturdyвЂђlooking peasant, with a round, simple face and grizzled beard,
who was walking by, raised his head and looked at the boy. He seemed not
quite sober.

вЂњGood morning, if you are not laughing at me,вЂќ he said deliberately in
reply.

вЂњAnd if I am?вЂќ laughed Kolya.

вЂњWell, a jokeвЂ™s a joke. Laugh away. I donвЂ™t mind. ThereвЂ™s no harm in a
joke.вЂќ

вЂњI beg your pardon, brother, it was a joke.вЂќ

вЂњWell, God forgive you!вЂќ

вЂњDo you forgive me, too?вЂќ

вЂњI quite forgive you. Go along.вЂќ

вЂњI say, you seem a clever peasant.вЂќ

вЂњCleverer than you,вЂќ the peasant answered unexpectedly, with the same
gravity.

вЂњI doubt it,вЂќ said Kolya, somewhat taken aback.

вЂњItвЂ™s true, though.вЂќ

вЂњPerhaps it is.вЂќ

вЂњIt is, brother.вЂќ

вЂњGoodвЂђby, peasant!вЂќ

вЂњGoodвЂђby!вЂќ

вЂњThere are all sorts of peasants,вЂќ Kolya observed to Smurov after a brief
silence. вЂњHow could I tell I had hit on a clever one? I am always ready to
recognize intelligence in the peasantry.вЂќ

In the distance the cathedral clock struck halfвЂђpast eleven. The boys made
haste and they walked as far as Captain SnegiryovвЂ™s lodging, a
considerable distance, quickly and almost in silence. Twenty paces from
the house Kolya stopped and told Smurov to go on ahead and ask Karamazov
to come out to him.

вЂњOne must sniff round a bit first,вЂќ he observed to Smurov.

вЂњWhy ask him to come out?вЂќ Smurov protested. вЂњYou go in; they will be
awfully glad to see you. WhatвЂ™s the sense of making friends in the frost
out here?вЂќ

вЂњI know why I want to see him out here in the frost,вЂќ Kolya cut him short
in the despotic tone he was fond of adopting with вЂњsmall boys,вЂќ and Smurov
ran to do his bidding.



Chapter IV. The Lost Dog


Kolya leaned against the fence with an air of dignity, waiting for Alyosha
to appear. Yes, he had long wanted to meet him. He had heard a great deal
about him from the boys, but hitherto he had always maintained an
appearance of disdainful indifference when he was mentioned, and he had
even вЂњcriticizedвЂќ what he heard about Alyosha. But secretly he had a great
longing to make his acquaintance; there was something sympathetic and
attractive in all he was told about Alyosha. So the present moment was
important: to begin with, he had to show himself at his best, to show his
independence, вЂњOr heвЂ™ll think of me as thirteen and take me for a boy,
like the rest of them. And what are these boys to him? I shall ask him
when I get to know him. ItвЂ™s a pity I am so short, though. Tuzikov is
younger than I am, yet he is half a head taller. But I have a clever face.
I am not goodвЂђlooking. I know IвЂ™m hideous, but IвЂ™ve a clever face. I
mustnвЂ™t talk too freely; if I fall into his arms all at once, he may
thinkвЂ”Tfoo! how horrible if he should thinkвЂ”!вЂќ

Such were the thoughts that excited Kolya while he was doing his utmost to
assume the most independent air. What distressed him most was his being so
short; he did not mind so much his вЂњhideousвЂќ face, as being so short. On
the wall in a corner at home he had the year before made a pencilвЂђmark to
show his height, and every two months since he anxiously measured himself
against it to see how much he had gained. But alas! he grew very slowly,
and this sometimes reduced him almost to despair. His face was in reality
by no means вЂњhideousвЂќ; on the contrary, it was rather attractive, with a
fair, pale skin, freckled. His small, lively gray eyes had a fearless
look, and often glowed with feeling. He had rather high cheekbones; small,
very red, but not very thick, lips; his nose was small and unmistakably
turned up. вЂњIвЂ™ve a regular pug nose, a regular pug nose,вЂќ Kolya used to
mutter to himself when he looked in the lookingвЂђglass, and he always left
it with indignation. вЂњBut perhaps I havenвЂ™t got a clever face?вЂќ he
sometimes thought, doubtful even of that. But it must not be supposed that
his mind was preoccupied with his face and his height. On the contrary,
however bitter the moments before the lookingвЂђglass were to him, he
quickly forgot them, and forgot them for a long time, вЂњabandoning himself
entirely to ideas and to real life,вЂќ as he formulated it to himself.

Alyosha came out quickly and hastened up to Kolya. Before he reached him,
Kolya could see that he looked delighted. вЂњCan he be so glad to see me?вЂќ
Kolya wondered, feeling pleased. We may note here, in passing, that
AlyoshaвЂ™s appearance had undergone a complete change since we saw him
last. He had abandoned his cassock and was wearing now a wellвЂђcut coat, a
soft, round hat, and his hair had been cropped short. All this was very
becoming to him, and he looked quite handsome. His charming face always
had a goodвЂђhumored expression; but there was a gentleness and serenity in
his goodвЂђhumor. To KolyaвЂ™s surprise, Alyosha came out to him just as he
was, without an overcoat. He had evidently come in haste. He held out his
hand to Kolya at once.

вЂњHere you are at last! How anxious weвЂ™ve been to see you!вЂќ

вЂњThere were reasons which you shall know directly. Anyway, I am glad to
make your acquaintance. IвЂ™ve long been hoping for an opportunity, and have
heard a great deal about you,вЂќ Kolya muttered, a little breathless.

вЂњWe should have met anyway. IвЂ™ve heard a great deal about you, too; but
youвЂ™ve been a long time coming here.вЂќ

вЂњTell me, how are things going?вЂќ

вЂњIlusha is very ill. He is certainly dying.вЂќ

вЂњHow awful! You must admit that medicine is a fraud, Karamazov,вЂќ cried
Kolya warmly.

вЂњIlusha has mentioned you often, very often, even in his sleep, in
delirium, you know. One can see that you used to be very, very dear to him
... before the incident ... with the knife.... Then thereвЂ™s another
reason.... Tell me, is that your dog?вЂќ

вЂњYes, Perezvon.вЂќ

вЂњNot Zhutchka?вЂќ Alyosha looked at Kolya with eyes full of pity. вЂњIs she
lost for ever?вЂќ

вЂњI know you would all like it to be Zhutchka. IвЂ™ve heard all about it.вЂќ
Kolya smiled mysteriously. вЂњListen, Karamazov, IвЂ™ll tell you all about it.
ThatвЂ™s what I came for; thatвЂ™s what I asked you to come out here for, to
explain the whole episode to you before we go in,вЂќ he began with
animation. вЂњYou see, Karamazov, Ilusha came into the preparatory class
last spring. Well, you know what our preparatory class isвЂ”a lot of small
boys. They began teasing Ilusha at once. I am two classes higher up, and,
of course, I only look on at them from a distance. I saw the boy was weak
and small, but he wouldnвЂ™t give in to them; he fought with them. I saw he
was proud, and his eyes were full of fire. I like children like that. And
they teased him all the more. The worst of it was he was horribly dressed
at the time, his breeches were too small for him, and there were holes in
his boots. They worried him about it; they jeered at him. That I canвЂ™t
stand. I stood up for him at once, and gave it to them hot. I beat them,
but they adore me, do you know, Karamazov?вЂќ Kolya boasted impulsively;
вЂњbut I am always fond of children. IвЂ™ve two chickens in my hands at home
nowвЂ”thatвЂ™s what detained me toвЂђday. So they left off beating Ilusha and I
took him under my protection. I saw the boy was proud. I tell you that,
the boy was proud; but in the end he became slavishly devoted to me: he
did my slightest bidding, obeyed me as though I were God, tried to copy
me. In the intervals between the classes he used to run to me at once, and
IвЂ™d go about with him. On Sundays, too. They always laugh when an older
boy makes friends with a younger one like that; but thatвЂ™s a prejudice. If
itвЂ™s my fancy, thatвЂ™s enough. I am teaching him, developing him. Why
shouldnвЂ™t I develop him if I like him? Here you, Karamazov, have taken up
with all these nestlings. I see you want to influence the younger
generationвЂ”to develop them, to be of use to them, and I assure you this
trait in your character, which I knew by hearsay, attracted me more than
anything. Let us get to the point, though. I noticed that there was a sort
of softness and sentimentality coming over the boy, and you know I have a
positive hatred of this sheepish sentimentality, and I have had it from a
baby. There were contradictions in him, too: he was proud, but he was
slavishly devoted to me, and yet all at once his eyes would flash and heвЂ™d
refuse to agree with me; heвЂ™d argue, fly into a rage. I used sometimes to
propound certain ideas; I could see that it was not so much that he
disagreed with the ideas, but that he was simply rebelling against me,
because I was cool in responding to his endearments. And so, in order to
train him properly, the tenderer he was, the colder I became. I did it on
purpose: that was my idea. My object was to form his character, to lick
him into shape, to make a man of him ... and besides ... no doubt, you
understand me at a word. Suddenly I noticed for three days in succession
he was downcast and dejected, not because of my coldness, but for
something else, something more important. I wondered what the tragedy was.
I have pumped him and found out that he had somehow got to know
Smerdyakov, who was footman to your late fatherвЂ”it was before his death,
of courseвЂ”and he taught the little fool a silly trickвЂ”that is, a brutal,
nasty trick. He told him to take a piece of bread, to stick a pin in it,
and throw it to one of those hungry dogs who snap up anything without
biting it, and then to watch and see what would happen. So they prepared a
piece of bread like that and threw it to Zhutchka, that shaggy dog thereвЂ™s
been such a fuss about. The people of the house it belonged to never fed
it at all, though it barked all day. (Do you like that stupid barking,
Karamazov? I canвЂ™t stand it.) So it rushed at the bread, swallowed it, and
began to squeal; it turned round and round and ran away, squealing as it
ran out of sight. That was IlushaвЂ™s own account of it. He confessed it to
me, and cried bitterly. He hugged me, shaking all over. He kept on
repeating вЂHe ran away squealingвЂ™: the sight of that haunted him. He was
tormented by remorse, I could see that. I took it seriously. I determined
to give him a lesson for other things as well. So I must confess I wasnвЂ™t
quite straightforward, and pretended to be more indignant perhaps than I
was. вЂYouвЂ™ve done a nasty thing,вЂ™ I said, вЂyou are a scoundrel. I wonвЂ™t
tell of it, of course, but I shall have nothing more to do with you for a
time. IвЂ™ll think it over and let you know through SmurovвЂ™вЂ”thatвЂ™s the boy
whoвЂ™s just come with me; heвЂ™s always ready to do anything for meвЂ”вЂwhether
I will have anything to do with you in the future or whether I give you up
for good as a scoundrel.вЂ™ He was tremendously upset. I must own I felt IвЂ™d
gone too far as I spoke, but there was no help for it. I did what I
thought best at the time. A day or two after, I sent Smurov to tell him
that I would not speak to him again. ThatвЂ™s what we call it when two
schoolfellows refuse to have anything more to do with one another.
Secretly I only meant to send him to Coventry for a few days and then, if
I saw signs of repentance, to hold out my hand to him again. That was my
intention. But what do you think happened? He heard SmurovвЂ™s message, his
eyes flashed. вЂTell Krassotkin from me,вЂ™ he cried, вЂthat I will throw
bread with pins to all the dogsвЂ”allвЂ”all of them!вЂ™ вЂSo heвЂ™s going in for a
little temper. We must smoke it out of him.вЂ™ And I began to treat him with
contempt; whenever I met him I turned away or smiled sarcastically. And
just then that affair with his father happened. You remember? You must
realize that he was fearfully worked up by what had happened already. The
boys, seeing IвЂ™d given him up, set on him and taunted him, shouting, вЂWisp
of tow, wisp of tow!вЂ™ And he had soon regular skirmishes with them, which
I am very sorry for. They seem to have given him one very bad beating. One
day he flew at them all as they were coming out of school. I stood a few
yards off, looking on. And, I swear, I donвЂ™t remember that I laughed; it
was quite the other way, I felt awfully sorry for him, in another minute I
would have run up to take his part. But he suddenly met my eyes. I donвЂ™t
know what he fancied; but he pulled out a penknife, rushed at me, and
struck at my thigh, here in my right leg. I didnвЂ™t move. I donвЂ™t mind
owning I am plucky sometimes, Karamazov. I simply looked at him
contemptuously, as though to say, вЂThis is how you repay all my kindness!
Do it again, if you like, IвЂ™m at your service.вЂ™ But he didnвЂ™t stab me
again; he broke down, he was frightened at what he had done, he threw away
the knife, burst out crying, and ran away. I did not sneak on him, of
course, and I made them all keep quiet, so it shouldnвЂ™t come to the ears
of the masters. I didnвЂ™t even tell my mother till it had healed up. And
the wound was a mere scratch. And then I heard that the same day heвЂ™d been
throwing stones and had bitten your fingerвЂ”but you understand now what a
state he was in! Well, it canвЂ™t be helped: it was stupid of me not to come
and forgive himвЂ”that is, to make it up with himвЂ”when he was taken ill. I
am sorry for it now. But I had a special reason. So now IвЂ™ve told you all
about it ... but IвЂ™m afraid it was stupid of me.вЂќ

вЂњOh, what a pity,вЂќ exclaimed Alyosha, with feeling, вЂњthat I didnвЂ™t know
before what terms you were on with him, or IвЂ™d have come to you long ago
to beg you to go to him with me. Would you believe it, when he was
feverish he talked about you in delirium. I didnвЂ™t know how much you were
to him! And youвЂ™ve really not succeeded in finding that dog? His father
and the boys have been hunting all over the town for it. Would you believe
it, since heвЂ™s been ill, IвЂ™ve three times heard him repeat with tears,
вЂItвЂ™s because I killed Zhutchka, father, that I am ill now. God is
punishing me for it.вЂ™ He canвЂ™t get that idea out of his head. And if the
dog were found and proved to be alive, one might almost fancy the joy
would cure him. We have all rested our hopes on you.вЂќ

вЂњTell me, what made you hope that I should be the one to find him?вЂќ Kolya
asked, with great curiosity. вЂњWhy did you reckon on me rather than any one
else?вЂќ

вЂњThere was a report that you were looking for the dog, and that you would
bring it when youвЂ™d found it. Smurov said something of the sort. WeвЂ™ve all
been trying to persuade Ilusha that the dog is alive, that itвЂ™s been seen.
The boys brought him a live hare; he just looked at it, with a faint
smile, and asked them to set it free in the fields. And so we did. His
father has just this moment come back, bringing him a mastiff pup, hoping
to comfort him with that; but I think it only makes it worse.вЂќ

вЂњTell me, Karamazov, what sort of man is the father? I know him, but what
do you make of himвЂ”a mountebank, a buffoon?вЂќ

вЂњOh, no; there are people of deep feeling who have been somehow crushed.
Buffoonery in them is a form of resentful irony against those to whom they
darenвЂ™t speak the truth, from having been for years humiliated and
intimidated by them. Believe me, Krassotkin, that sort of buffoonery is
sometimes tragic in the extreme. His whole life now is centered in Ilusha,
and if Ilusha dies, he will either go mad with grief or kill himself. I
feel almost certain of that when I look at him now.вЂќ

вЂњI understand you, Karamazov. I see you understand human nature,вЂќ Kolya
added, with feeling.

вЂњAnd as soon as I saw you with a dog, I thought it was Zhutchka you were
bringing.вЂќ

вЂњWait a bit, Karamazov, perhaps we shall find it yet; but this is
Perezvon. IвЂ™ll let him go in now and perhaps it will amuse Ilusha more
than the mastiff pup. Wait a bit, Karamazov, you will know something in a
minute. But, I say, I am keeping you here!вЂќ Kolya cried suddenly. вЂњYouвЂ™ve
no overcoat on in this bitter cold. You see what an egoist I am. Oh, we
are all egoists, Karamazov!вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t trouble; it is cold, but I donвЂ™t often catch cold. Let us go in,
though, and, by the way, what is your name? I know you are called Kolya,
but what else?вЂќ

вЂњNikolayвЂ”Nikolay Ivanovitch Krassotkin, or, as they say in official
documents, вЂKrassotkin son.вЂ™ вЂќ Kolya laughed for some reason, but added
suddenly, вЂњOf course I hate my name Nikolay.вЂќ

вЂњWhy so?вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s so trivial, so ordinary.вЂќ

вЂњYou are thirteen?вЂќ asked Alyosha.

вЂњNo, fourteenвЂ”that is, I shall be fourteen very soon, in a fortnight. IвЂ™ll
confess one weakness of mine, Karamazov, just to you, since itвЂ™s our first
meeting, so that you may understand my character at once. I hate being
asked my age, more than that ... and in fact ... thereвЂ™s a libelous story
going about me, that last week I played robbers with the preparatory boys.
ItвЂ™s a fact that I did play with them, but itвЂ™s a perfect libel to say I
did it for my own amusement. I have reasons for believing that youвЂ™ve
heard the story; but I wasnвЂ™t playing for my own amusement, it was for the
sake of the children, because they couldnвЂ™t think of anything to do by
themselves. But theyвЂ™ve always got some silly tale. This is an awful town
for gossip, I can tell you.вЂќ

вЂњBut what if you had been playing for your own amusement, whatвЂ™s the
harm?вЂќ

вЂњCome, I say, for my own amusement! You donвЂ™t play horses, do you?вЂќ

вЂњBut you must look at it like this,вЂќ said Alyosha, smiling. вЂњGrownвЂђup
people go to the theater and there the adventures of all sorts of heroes
are representedвЂ”sometimes there are robbers and battles, tooвЂ”and isnвЂ™t
that just the same thing, in a different form, of course? And young
peopleвЂ™s games of soldiers or robbers in their playtime are also art in
its first stage. You know, they spring from the growing artistic instincts
of the young. And sometimes these games are much better than performances
in the theater, the only difference is that people go there to look at the
actors, while in these games the young people are the actors themselves.
But thatвЂ™s only natural.вЂќ

вЂњYou think so? Is that your idea?вЂќ Kolya looked at him intently. вЂњOh, you
know, thatвЂ™s rather an interesting view. When I go home, IвЂ™ll think it
over. IвЂ™ll admit I thought I might learn something from you. IвЂ™ve come to
learn of you, Karamazov,вЂќ Kolya concluded, in a voice full of spontaneous
feeling.

вЂњAnd I of you,вЂќ said Alyosha, smiling and pressing his hand.

Kolya was much pleased with Alyosha. What struck him most was that he
treated him exactly like an equal and that he talked to him just as if he
were вЂњquite grown up.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll show you something directly, Karamazov; itвЂ™s a theatrical
performance, too,вЂќ he said, laughing nervously. вЂњThatвЂ™s why IвЂ™ve come.вЂќ

вЂњLet us go first to the people of the house, on the left. All the boys
leave their coats in there, because the room is small and hot.вЂќ

вЂњOh, IвЂ™m only coming in for a minute. IвЂ™ll keep on my overcoat. Perezvon
will stay here in the passage and be dead. _Ici_, Perezvon, lie down and
be dead! You see how heвЂ™s dead. IвЂ™ll go in first and explore, then IвЂ™ll
whistle to him when I think fit, and youвЂ™ll see, heвЂ™ll dash in like mad.
Only Smurov must not forget to open the door at the moment. IвЂ™ll arrange
it all and youвЂ™ll see something.вЂќ



Chapter V. By IlushaвЂ™s Bedside


The room inhabited by the family of the retired captain Snegiryov is
already familiar to the reader. It was close and crowded at that moment
with a number of visitors. Several boys were sitting with Ilusha, and
though all of them, like Smurov, were prepared to deny that it was Alyosha
who had brought them and reconciled them with Ilusha, it was really the
fact. All the art he had used had been to take them, one by one, to
Ilusha, without вЂњsheepish sentimentality,вЂќ appearing to do so casually and
without design. It was a great consolation to Ilusha in his suffering. He
was greatly touched by seeing the almost tender affection and sympathy
shown him by these boys, who had been his enemies. Krassotkin was the only
one missing and his absence was a heavy load on IlushaвЂ™s heart. Perhaps
the bitterest of all his bitter memories was his stabbing Krassotkin, who
had been his one friend and protector. Clever little Smurov, who was the
first to make it up with Ilusha, thought it was so. But when Smurov hinted
to Krassotkin that Alyosha wanted to come and see him about something, the
latter cut him short, bidding Smurov tell вЂњKaramazovвЂќ at once that he knew
best what to do, that he wanted no oneвЂ™s advice, and that, if he went to
see Ilusha, he would choose his own time for he had вЂњhis own reasons.вЂќ

That was a fortnight before this Sunday. That was why Alyosha had not been
to see him, as he had meant to. But though he waited, he sent Smurov to
him twice again. Both times Krassotkin met him with a curt, impatient
refusal, sending Alyosha a message not to bother him any more, that if he
came himself, he, Krassotkin, would not go to Ilusha at all. Up to the
very last day, Smurov did not know that Kolya meant to go to Ilusha that
morning, and only the evening before, as he parted from Smurov, Kolya
abruptly told him to wait at home for him next morning, for he would go
with him to the SnegiryovsвЂ™, but warned him on no account to say he was
coming, as he wanted to drop in casually. Smurov obeyed. SmurovвЂ™s fancy
that Kolya would bring back the lost dog was based on the words Kolya had
dropped that вЂњthey must be asses not to find the dog, if it was alive.вЂќ
When Smurov, waiting for an opportunity, timidly hinted at his guess about
the dog, Krassotkin flew into a violent rage. вЂњIвЂ™m not such an ass as to
go hunting about the town for other peopleвЂ™s dogs when IвЂ™ve got a dog of
my own! And how can you imagine a dog could be alive after swallowing a
pin? Sheepish sentimentality, thatвЂ™s what it is!вЂќ

For the last fortnight Ilusha had not left his little bed under the ikons
in the corner. He had not been to school since the day he met Alyosha and
bit his finger. He was taken ill the same day, though for a month
afterwards he was sometimes able to get up and walk about the room and
passage. But latterly he had become so weak that he could not move without
help from his father. His father was terribly concerned about him. He even
gave up drinking and was almost crazy with terror that his boy would die.
And often, especially after leading him round the room on his arm and
putting him back to bed, he would run to a dark corner in the passage and,
leaning his head against the wall, he would break into paroxysms of
violent weeping, stifling his sobs that they might not be heard by Ilusha.

Returning to the room, he would usually begin doing something to amuse and
comfort his precious boy; he would tell him stories, funny anecdotes, or
would mimic comic people he had happened to meet, even imitate the howls
and cries of animals. But Ilusha could not bear to see his father fooling
and playing the buffoon. Though the boy tried not to show how he disliked
it, he saw with an aching heart that his father was an object of contempt,
and he was continually haunted by the memory of the вЂњwisp of towвЂќ and that
вЂњterrible day.вЂќ

Nina, IlushaвЂ™s gentle, crippled sister, did not like her fatherвЂ™s
buffoonery either (Varvara had been gone for some time past to Petersburg
to study at the university). But the halfвЂђimbecile mother was greatly
diverted and laughed heartily when her husband began capering about or
performing something. It was the only way she could be amused; all the
rest of the time she was grumbling and complaining that now every one had
forgotten her, that no one treated her with respect, that she was
slighted, and so on. But during the last few days she had completely
changed. She began looking constantly at IlushaвЂ™s bed in the corner and
seemed lost in thought. She was more silent, quieter, and, if she cried,
she cried quietly so as not to be heard. The captain noticed the change in
her with mournful perplexity. The boysвЂ™ visits at first only angered her,
but later on their merry shouts and stories began to divert her, and at
last she liked them so much that, if the boys had given up coming, she
would have felt dreary without them. When the children told some story or
played a game, she laughed and clapped her hands. She called some of them
to her and kissed them. She was particularly fond of Smurov.

As for the captain, the presence in his room of the children, who came to
cheer up Ilusha, filled his heart from the first with ecstatic joy. He
even hoped that Ilusha would now get over his depression, and that that
would hasten his recovery. In spite of his alarm about Ilusha, he had not,
till lately, felt one minuteвЂ™s doubt of his boyвЂ™s ultimate recovery.

He met his little visitors with homage, waited upon them hand and foot; he
was ready to be their horse and even began letting them ride on his back,
but Ilusha did not like the game and it was given up. He began buying
little things for them, gingerbread and nuts, gave them tea and cut them
sandwiches. It must be noted that all this time he had plenty of money. He
had taken the two hundred roubles from Katerina Ivanovna just as Alyosha
had predicted he would. And afterwards Katerina Ivanovna, learning more
about their circumstances and IlushaвЂ™s illness, visited them herself, made
the acquaintance of the family, and succeeded in fascinating the halfвЂђ
imbecile mother. Since then she had been lavish in helping them, and the
captain, terrorвЂђstricken at the thought that his boy might be dying,
forgot his pride and humbly accepted her assistance.

All this time Doctor Herzenstube, who was called in by Katerina Ivanovna,
came punctually every other day, but little was gained by his visits and
he dosed the invalid mercilessly. But on that Sunday morning a new doctor
was expected, who had come from Moscow, where he had a great reputation.
Katerina Ivanovna had sent for him from Moscow at great expense, not
expressly for Ilusha, but for another object of which more will be said in
its place hereafter. But, as he had come, she had asked him to see Ilusha
as well, and the captain had been told to expect him. He hadnвЂ™t the
slightest idea that Kolya Krassotkin was coming, though he had long wished
for a visit from the boy for whom Ilusha was fretting.

At the moment when Krassotkin opened the door and came into the room, the
captain and all the boys were round IlushaвЂ™s bed, looking at a tiny
mastiff pup, which had only been born the day before, though the captain
had bespoken it a week ago to comfort and amuse Ilusha, who was still
fretting over the lost and probably dead Zhutchka. Ilusha, who had heard
three days before that he was to be presented with a puppy, not an
ordinary puppy, but a pedigree mastiff (a very important point, of
course), tried from delicacy of feeling to pretend that he was pleased.
But his father and the boys could not help seeing that the puppy only
served to recall to his little heart the thought of the unhappy dog he had
killed. The puppy lay beside him feebly moving and he, smiling sadly,
stroked it with his thin, pale, wasted hand. Clearly he liked the puppy,
but ... it wasnвЂ™t Zhutchka; if he could have had Zhutchka and the puppy,
too, then he would have been completely happy.

вЂњKrassotkin!вЂќ cried one of the boys suddenly. He was the first to see him
come in.

KrassotkinвЂ™s entrance made a general sensation; the boys moved away and
stood on each side of the bed, so that he could get a full view of Ilusha.
The captain ran eagerly to meet Kolya.

вЂњPlease come in ... you are welcome!вЂќ he said hurriedly. вЂњIlusha, Mr.
Krassotkin has come to see you!вЂќ

But Krassotkin, shaking hands with him hurriedly, instantly showed his
complete knowledge of the manners of good society. He turned first to the
captainвЂ™s wife sitting in her armвЂђchair, who was very illвЂђhumored at the
moment, and was grumbling that the boys stood between her and IlushaвЂ™s bed
and did not let her see the new puppy. With the greatest courtesy he made
her a bow, scraping his foot, and turning to Nina, he made her, as the
only other lady present, a similar bow. This polite behavior made an
extremely favorable impression on the deranged lady.

вЂњThere, you can see at once he is a young man that has been well brought
up,вЂќ she commented aloud, throwing up her hands; вЂњbut as for our other
visitors they come in one on the top of another.вЂќ

вЂњHow do you mean, mamma, one on the top of another, how is that?вЂќ muttered
the captain affectionately, though a little anxious on her account.

вЂњThatвЂ™s how they ride in. They get on each otherвЂ™s shoulders in the
passage and prance in like that on a respectable family. Strange sort of
visitors!вЂќ

вЂњBut whoвЂ™s come in like that, mamma?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, that boy came in riding on that oneвЂ™s back and this one on that
oneвЂ™s.вЂќ

Kolya was already by IlushaвЂ™s bedside. The sick boy turned visibly paler.
He raised himself in the bed and looked intently at Kolya. Kolya had not
seen his little friend for two months, and he was overwhelmed at the sight
of him. He had never imagined that he would see such a wasted, yellow
face, such enormous, feverishly glowing eyes and such thin little hands.
He saw, with grieved surprise, IlushaвЂ™s rapid, hard breathing and dry
lips. He stepped close to him, held out his hand, and almost overwhelmed,
he said:

вЂњWell, old man ... how are you?вЂќ But his voice failed him, he couldnвЂ™t
achieve an appearance of ease; his face suddenly twitched and the corners
of his mouth quivered. Ilusha smiled a pitiful little smile, still unable
to utter a word. Something moved Kolya to raise his hand and pass it over
IlushaвЂ™s hair.

вЂњNever mind!вЂќ he murmured softly to him to cheer him up, or perhaps not
knowing why he said it. For a minute they were silent again.

вЂњHallo, so youвЂ™ve got a new puppy?вЂќ Kolya said suddenly, in a most callous
voice.

вЂњYeвЂ”es,вЂќ answered Ilusha in a long whisper, gasping for breath.

вЂњA black nose, that means heвЂ™ll be fierce, a good houseвЂђdog,вЂќ Kolya
observed gravely and stolidly, as if the only thing he cared about was the
puppy and its black nose. But in reality he still had to do his utmost to
control his feelings not to burst out crying like a child, and do what he
would he could not control it. вЂњWhen it grows up, youвЂ™ll have to keep it
on the chain, IвЂ™m sure.вЂќ

вЂњHeвЂ™ll be a huge dog!вЂќ cried one of the boys.

вЂњOf course he will,вЂќ вЂњa mastiff,вЂќ вЂњlarge,вЂќ вЂњlike this,вЂќ вЂњas big as a
calf,вЂќ shouted several voices.

вЂњAs big as a calf, as a real calf,вЂќ chimed in the captain. вЂњI got one like
that on purpose, one of the fiercest breed, and his parents are huge and
very fierce, they stand as high as this from the floor.... Sit down here,
on IlushaвЂ™s bed, or here on the bench. You are welcome, weвЂ™ve been hoping
to see you a long time.... You were so kind as to come with Alexey
Fyodorovitch?вЂќ

Krassotkin sat on the edge of the bed, at IlushaвЂ™s feet. Though he had
perhaps prepared a freeвЂђandвЂђeasy opening for the conversation on his way,
now he completely lost the thread of it.

вЂњNo ... I came with Perezvon. IвЂ™ve got a dog now, called Perezvon. A
Slavonic name. HeвЂ™s out there ... if I whistle, heвЂ™ll run in. IвЂ™ve brought
a dog, too,вЂќ he said, addressing Ilusha all at once. вЂњDo you remember
Zhutchka, old man?вЂќ he suddenly fired the question at him.

IlushaвЂ™s little face quivered. He looked with an agonized expression at
Kolya. Alyosha, standing at the door, frowned and signed to Kolya not to
speak of Zhutchka, but he did not or would not notice.

вЂњWhere ... is Zhutchka?вЂќ Ilusha asked in a broken voice.

вЂњOh, well, my boy, your ZhutchkaвЂ™s lost and done for!вЂќ

Ilusha did not speak, but he fixed an intent gaze once more on Kolya.
Alyosha, catching KolyaвЂ™s eye, signed to him vigorously again, but he
turned away his eyes pretending not to have noticed.

вЂњIt must have run away and died somewhere. It must have died after a meal
like that,вЂќ Kolya pronounced pitilessly, though he seemed a little
breathless. вЂњBut IвЂ™ve got a dog, Perezvon ... A Slavonic name.... IвЂ™ve
brought him to show you.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t want him!вЂќ said Ilusha suddenly.

вЂњNo, no, you really must see him ... it will amuse you. I brought him on
purpose.... HeвЂ™s the same sort of shaggy dog.... You allow me to call in
my dog, madam?вЂќ He suddenly addressed Madame Snegiryov, with inexplicable
excitement in his manner.

вЂњI donвЂ™t want him, I donвЂ™t want him!вЂќ cried Ilusha, with a mournful break
in his voice. There was a reproachful light in his eyes.

вЂњYouвЂ™d better,вЂќ the captain started up from the chest by the wall on which
he had just sat down, вЂњyouвЂ™d better ... another time,вЂќ he muttered, but
Kolya could not be restrained. He hurriedly shouted to Smurov, вЂњOpen the
door,вЂќ and as soon as it was open, he blew his whistle. Perezvon dashed
headlong into the room.

вЂњJump, Perezvon, beg! Beg!вЂќ shouted Kolya, jumping up, and the dog stood
erect on its hindвЂђlegs by IlushaвЂ™s bedside. What followed was a surprise
to every one: Ilusha started, lurched violently forward, bent over
Perezvon and gazed at him, faint with suspense.

вЂњItвЂ™s ... Zhutchka!вЂќ he cried suddenly, in a voice breaking with joy and
suffering.

вЂњAnd who did you think it was?вЂќ Krassotkin shouted with all his might, in
a ringing, happy voice, and bending down he seized the dog and lifted him
up to Ilusha.

вЂњLook, old man, you see, blind of one eye and the left ear is torn, just
the marks you described to me. It was by that I found him. I found him
directly. He did not belong to any one!вЂќ he explained, turning quickly to
the captain, to his wife, to Alyosha and then again to Ilusha. вЂњHe used to
live in the FedotovsвЂ™ backвЂђyard. Though he made his home there, they did
not feed him. He was a stray dog that had run away from the village ... I
found him.... You see, old man, he couldnвЂ™t have swallowed what you gave
him. If he had, he must have died, he must have! So he must have spat it
out, since he is alive. You did not see him do it. But the pin pricked his
tongue, that is why he squealed. He ran away squealing and you thought
heвЂ™d swallowed it. He might well squeal, because the skin of dogsвЂ™ mouths
is so tender ... tenderer than in men, much tenderer!вЂќ Kolya cried
impetuously, his face glowing and radiant with delight. Ilusha could not
speak. White as a sheet, he gazed openвЂђmouthed at Kolya, with his great
eyes almost starting out of his head. And if Krassotkin, who had no
suspicion of it, had known what a disastrous and fatal effect such a
moment might have on the sick childвЂ™s health, nothing would have induced
him to play such a trick on him. But Alyosha was perhaps the only person
in the room who realized it. As for the captain he behaved like a small
child.

вЂњZhutchka! ItвЂ™s Zhutchka!вЂќ he cried in a blissful voice, вЂњIlusha, this is
Zhutchka, your Zhutchka! Mamma, this is Zhutchka!вЂќ He was almost weeping.

вЂњAnd I never guessed!вЂќ cried Smurov regretfully. вЂњBravo, Krassotkin! I
said heвЂ™d find the dog and here heвЂ™s found him.вЂќ

вЂњHere heвЂ™s found him!вЂќ another boy repeated gleefully.

вЂњKrassotkinвЂ™s a brick!вЂќ cried a third voice.

вЂњHeвЂ™s a brick, heвЂ™s a brick!вЂќ cried the other boys, and they began
clapping.

вЂњWait, wait,вЂќ Krassotkin did his utmost to shout above them all. вЂњIвЂ™ll
tell you how it happened, thatвЂ™s the whole point. I found him, I took him
home and hid him at once. I kept him locked up at home and did not show
him to any one till toвЂђday. Only Smurov has known for the last fortnight,
but I assured him this dog was called Perezvon and he did not guess. And
meanwhile I taught the dog all sorts of tricks. You should only see all
the things he can do! I trained him so as to bring you a wellвЂђtrained dog,
in good condition, old man, so as to be able to say to you, вЂSee, old man,
what a fine dog your Zhutchka is now!вЂ™ HavenвЂ™t you a bit of meat? HeвЂ™ll
show you a trick that will make you die with laughing. A piece of meat,
havenвЂ™t you got any?вЂќ

The captain ran across the passage to the landlady, where their cooking
was done. Not to lose precious time, Kolya, in desperate haste, shouted to
Perezvon, вЂњDead!вЂќ And the dog immediately turned round and lay on his back
with its four paws in the air. The boys laughed. Ilusha looked on with the
same suffering smile, but the person most delighted with the dogвЂ™s
performance was вЂњmamma.вЂќ She laughed at the dog and began snapping her
fingers and calling it, вЂњPerezvon, Perezvon!вЂќ

вЂњNothing will make him get up, nothing!вЂќ Kolya cried triumphantly, proud
of his success. вЂњHe wonвЂ™t move for all the shouting in the world, but if I
call to him, heвЂ™ll jump up in a minute. Ici, Perezvon!вЂќ The dog leapt up
and bounded about, whining with delight. The captain ran back with a piece
of cooked beef.

вЂњIs it hot?вЂќ Kolya inquired hurriedly, with a businessвЂђlike air, taking
the meat. вЂњDogs donвЂ™t like hot things. No, itвЂ™s all right. Look,
everybody, look, Ilusha, look, old man; why arenвЂ™t you looking? He does
not look at him, now IвЂ™ve brought him.вЂќ

The new trick consisted in making the dog stand motionless with his nose
out and putting a tempting morsel of meat just on his nose. The luckless
dog had to stand without moving, with the meat on his nose, as long as his
master chose to keep him, without a movement, perhaps for half an hour.
But he kept Perezvon only for a brief moment.

вЂњPaid for!вЂќ cried Kolya, and the meat passed in a flash from the dogвЂ™s
nose to his mouth. The audience, of course, expressed enthusiasm and
surprise.

вЂњCan you really have put off coming all this time simply to train the
dog?вЂќ exclaimed Alyosha, with an involuntary note of reproach in his
voice.

вЂњSimply for that!вЂќ answered Kolya, with perfect simplicity. вЂњI wanted to
show him in all his glory.вЂќ

вЂњPerezvon! Perezvon,вЂќ called Ilusha suddenly, snapping his thin fingers
and beckoning to the dog.

вЂњWhat is it? Let him jump up on the bed! _Ici_, Perezvon!вЂќ Kolya slapped
the bed and Perezvon darted up by Ilusha. The boy threw both arms round
his head and Perezvon instantly licked his cheek. Ilusha crept close to
him, stretched himself out in bed and hid his face in the dogвЂ™s shaggy
coat.

вЂњDear, dear!вЂќ kept exclaiming the captain. Kolya sat down again on the
edge of the bed.

вЂњIlusha, I can show you another trick. IвЂ™ve brought you a little cannon.
You remember, I told you about it before and you said how much youвЂ™d like
to see it. Well, here, IвЂ™ve brought it to you.вЂќ

And Kolya hurriedly pulled out of his satchel the little bronze cannon. He
hurried, because he was happy himself. Another time he would have waited
till the sensation made by Perezvon had passed off, now he hurried on
regardless of all consideration. вЂњYou are all happy now,вЂќ he felt, вЂњso
hereвЂ™s something to make you happier!вЂќ He was perfectly enchanted himself.

вЂњIвЂ™ve been coveting this thing for a long while; itвЂ™s for you, old man,
itвЂ™s for you. It belonged to Morozov, it was no use to him, he had it from
his brother. I swopped a book from fatherвЂ™s bookвЂђcase for it, _A Kinsman
of Mahomet or Salutary Folly_, a scandalous book published in Moscow a
hundred years ago, before they had any censorship. And Morozov has a taste
for such things. He was grateful to me, too....вЂќ

Kolya held the cannon in his hand so that all could see and admire it.
Ilusha raised himself, and, with his right arm still round the dog, he
gazed enchanted at the toy. The sensation was even greater when Kolya
announced that he had gunpowder too, and that it could be fired off at
once вЂњif it wonвЂ™t alarm the ladies.вЂќ вЂњMammaвЂќ immediately asked to look at
the toy closer and her request was granted. She was much pleased with the
little bronze cannon on wheels and began rolling it to and fro on her lap.
She readily gave permission for the cannon to be fired, without any idea
of what she had been asked. Kolya showed the powder and the shot. The
captain, as a military man, undertook to load it, putting in a minute
quantity of powder. He asked that the shot might be put off till another
time. The cannon was put on the floor, aiming towards an empty part of the
room, three grains of powder were thrust into the touchвЂђhole and a match
was put to it. A magnificent explosion followed. Mamma was startled, but
at once laughed with delight. The boys gazed in speechless triumph. But
the captain, looking at Ilusha, was more enchanted than any of them. Kolya
picked up the cannon and immediately presented it to Ilusha, together with
the powder and the shot.

вЂњI got it for you, for you! IвЂ™ve been keeping it for you a long time,вЂќ he
repeated once more in his delight.

вЂњOh, give it to me! No, give me the cannon!вЂќ mamma began begging like a
little child. Her face showed a piteous fear that she would not get it.
Kolya was disconcerted. The captain fidgeted uneasily.

вЂњMamma, mamma,вЂќ he ran to her, вЂњthe cannonвЂ™s yours, of course, but let
Ilusha have it, because itвЂ™s a present to him, but itвЂ™s just as good as
yours. Ilusha will always let you play with it; it shall belong to both of
you, both of you.вЂќ

вЂњNo, I donвЂ™t want it to belong to both of us, I want it to be mine
altogether, not IlushaвЂ™s,вЂќ persisted mamma, on the point of tears.

вЂњTake it, mother, here, keep it!вЂќ Ilusha cried. вЂњKrassotkin, may I give it
to my mother?вЂќ he turned to Krassotkin with an imploring face, as though
he were afraid he might be offended at his giving his present to some one
else.

вЂњOf course you may,вЂќ Krassotkin assented heartily, and, taking the cannon
from Ilusha, he handed it himself to mamma with a polite bow. She was so
touched that she cried.

вЂњIlusha, darling, heвЂ™s the one who loves his mamma!вЂќ she said tenderly,
and at once began wheeling the cannon to and fro on her lap again.

вЂњMamma, let me kiss your hand.вЂќ The captain darted up to her at once and
did so.

вЂњAnd I never saw such a charming fellow as this nice boy,вЂќ said the
grateful lady, pointing to Krassotkin.

вЂњAnd IвЂ™ll bring you as much powder as you like, Ilusha. We make the powder
ourselves now. Borovikov found out how itвЂ™s madeвЂ”twentyвЂђfour parts of
saltpeter, ten of sulphur and six of birchwood charcoal. ItвЂ™s all pounded
together, mixed into a paste with water and rubbed through a tammy
sieveвЂ”thatвЂ™s how itвЂ™s done.вЂќ

вЂњSmurov told me about your powder, only father says itвЂ™s not real
gunpowder,вЂќ responded Ilusha.

вЂњNot real?вЂќ Kolya flushed. вЂњIt burns. I donвЂ™t know, of course.вЂќ

вЂњNo, I didnвЂ™t mean that,вЂќ put in the captain with a guilty face. вЂњI only
said that real powder is not made like that, but thatвЂ™s nothing, it can be
made so.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know, you know best. We lighted some in a pomatum pot, it burned
splendidly, it all burnt away leaving only a tiny ash. But that was only
the paste, and if you rub it through ... but of course you know best, I
donвЂ™t know.... And BulkinвЂ™s father thrashed him on account of our powder,
did you hear?вЂќ he turned to Ilusha.

вЂњYes,вЂќ answered Ilusha. He listened to Kolya with immense interest and
enjoyment.

вЂњWe had prepared a whole bottle of it and he used to keep it under his
bed. His father saw it. He said it might explode, and thrashed him on the
spot. He was going to make a complaint against me to the masters. He is
not allowed to go about with me now, no one is allowed to go about with me
now. Smurov is not allowed to either, IвЂ™ve got a bad name with every one.
They say IвЂ™m a вЂdesperate character,вЂ™ вЂќ Kolya smiled scornfully. вЂњIt all
began from what happened on the railway.вЂќ

вЂњAh, weвЂ™ve heard of that exploit of yours, too,вЂќ cried the captain. вЂњHow
could you lie still on the line? Is it possible you werenвЂ™t the least
afraid, lying there under the train? WerenвЂ™t you frightened?вЂќ

The captain was abject in his flattery of Kolya.

вЂњNвЂ”not particularly,вЂќ answered Kolya carelessly. вЂњWhatвЂ™s blasted my
reputation more than anything here was that cursed goose,вЂќ he said,
turning again to Ilusha. But though he assumed an unconcerned air as he
talked, he still could not control himself and was continually missing the
note he tried to keep up.

вЂњAh! I heard about the goose!вЂќ Ilusha laughed, beaming all over. вЂњThey
told me, but I didnвЂ™t understand. Did they really take you to the court?вЂќ

вЂњThe most stupid, trivial affair, they made a mountain of a molehill as
they always do,вЂќ Kolya began carelessly. вЂњI was walking through the
marketвЂђplace here one day, just when theyвЂ™d driven in the geese. I stopped
and looked at them. All at once a fellow, who is an errandвЂђboy at
PlotnikovвЂ™s now, looked at me and said, вЂWhat are you looking at the geese
for?вЂ™ I looked at him; he was a stupid, moonвЂђfaced fellow of twenty. I am
always on the side of the peasantry, you know. I like talking to the
peasants.... WeвЂ™ve dropped behind the peasantsвЂ”thatвЂ™s an axiom. I believe
you are laughing, Karamazov?вЂќ

вЂњNo, Heaven forbid, I am listening,вЂќ said Alyosha with a most goodвЂђnatured
air, and the sensitive Kolya was immediately reassured.

вЂњMy theory, Karamazov, is clear and simple,вЂќ he hurried on again, looking
pleased. вЂњI believe in the people and am always glad to give them their
due, but I am not for spoiling them, that is a _sine qua non_ ... But I
was telling you about the goose. So I turned to the fool and answered, вЂI
am wondering what the goose thinks about.вЂ™ He looked at me quite stupidly,
вЂAnd what does the goose think about?вЂ™ he asked. вЂDo you see that cart
full of oats?вЂ™ I said. вЂThe oats are dropping out of the sack, and the
goose has put its neck right under the wheel to gobble them upвЂ”do you
see?вЂ™ вЂI see that quite well,вЂ™ he said. вЂWell,вЂ™ said I, вЂif that cart were
to move on a little, would it break the gooseвЂ™s neck or not?вЂ™ вЂItвЂ™d be
sure to break it,вЂ™ and he grinned all over his face, highly delighted.
вЂCome on, then,вЂ™ said I, вЂletвЂ™s try.вЂ™ вЂLetвЂ™s,вЂ™ he said. And it did not
take us long to arrange: he stood at the bridle without being noticed, and
I stood on one side to direct the goose. And the owner wasnвЂ™t looking, he
was talking to some one, so I had nothing to do, the goose thrust its head
in after the oats of itself, under the cart, just under the wheel. I
winked at the lad, he tugged at the bridle, and crack. The gooseвЂ™s neck
was broken in half. And, as luck would have it, all the peasants saw us at
that moment and they kicked up a shindy at once. вЂYou did that on
purpose!вЂ™ вЂNo, not on purpose.вЂ™ вЂYes, you did, on purpose!вЂ™ Well, they
shouted, вЂTake him to the justice of the peace!вЂ™ They took me, too. вЂYou
were there, too,вЂ™ they said, вЂyou helped, youвЂ™re known all over the
market!вЂ™ And, for some reason, I really am known all over the market,вЂќ
Kolya added conceitedly. вЂњWe all went off to the justiceвЂ™s, they brought
the goose, too. The fellow was crying in a great funk, simply blubbering
like a woman. And the farmer kept shouting that you could kill any number
of geese like that. Well, of course, there were witnesses. The justice of
the peace settled it in a minute, that the farmer was to be paid a rouble
for the goose, and the fellow to have the goose. And he was warned not to
play such pranks again. And the fellow kept blubbering like a woman. вЂIt
wasnвЂ™t me,вЂ™ he said, вЂit was he egged me on,вЂ™ and he pointed to me. I
answered with the utmost composure that I hadnвЂ™t egged him on, that I
simply stated the general proposition, had spoken hypothetically. The
justice of the peace smiled and was vexed with himself at once for having
smiled. вЂIвЂ™ll complain to your masters of you, so that for the future you
maynвЂ™t waste your time on such general propositions, instead of sitting at
your books and learning your lessons.вЂ™ He didnвЂ™t complain to the masters,
that was a joke, but the matter was noised abroad and came to the ears of
the masters. Their ears are long, you know! The classical master,
Kolbasnikov, was particularly shocked about it, but Dardanelov got me off
again. But Kolbasnikov is savage with every one now like a green ass. Did
you know, Ilusha, he is just married, got a dowry of a thousand roubles,
and his brideвЂ™s a regular fright of the first rank and the last degree.
The thirdвЂђclass fellows wrote an epigram on it:


    Astounding news has reached the class,
    Kolbasnikov has been an ass.


And so on, awfully funny, IвЂ™ll bring it to you later on. I say nothing
against Dardanelov, he is a learned man, thereвЂ™s no doubt about it. I
respect men like that and itвЂ™s not because he stood up for me.вЂќ

вЂњBut you took him down about the founders of Troy!вЂќ Smurov put in
suddenly, unmistakably proud of Krassotkin at such a moment. He was
particularly pleased with the story of the goose.

вЂњDid you really take him down?вЂќ the captain inquired, in a flattering way.
вЂњOn the question who founded Troy? We heard of it, Ilusha told me about it
at the time.вЂќ

вЂњHe knows everything, father, he knows more than any of us!вЂќ put in
Ilusha; вЂњhe only pretends to be like that, but really he is top in every
subject....вЂќ

Ilusha looked at Kolya with infinite happiness.

вЂњOh, thatвЂ™s all nonsense about Troy, a trivial matter. I consider this an
unimportant question,вЂќ said Kolya with haughty humility. He had by now
completely recovered his dignity, though he was still a little uneasy. He
felt that he was greatly excited and that he had talked about the goose,
for instance, with too little reserve, while Alyosha had looked serious
and had not said a word all the time. And the vain boy began by degrees to
have a rankling fear that Alyosha was silent because he despised him, and
thought he was showing off before him. If he dared to think anything like
that Kolya wouldвЂ”

вЂњI regard the question as quite a trivial one,вЂќ he rapped out again,
proudly.

вЂњAnd I know who founded Troy,вЂќ a boy, who had not spoken before, said
suddenly, to the surprise of every one. He was silent and seemed to be
shy. He was a pretty boy of about eleven, called Kartashov. He was sitting
near the door. Kolya looked at him with dignified amazement.

The fact was that the identity of the founders of Troy had become a secret
for the whole school, a secret which could only be discovered by reading
Smaragdov, and no one had Smaragdov but Kolya. One day, when KolyaвЂ™s back
was turned, Kartashov hastily opened Smaragdov, which lay among KolyaвЂ™s
books, and immediately lighted on the passage relating to the foundation
of Troy. This was a good time ago, but he felt uneasy and could not bring
himself to announce publicly that he too knew who had founded Troy, afraid
of what might happen and of KrassotkinвЂ™s somehow putting him to shame over
it. But now he couldnвЂ™t resist saying it. For weeks he had been longing
to.

вЂњWell, who did found it?вЂќ asked Kolya, turning to him with haughty
superciliousness. He saw from his face that he really did know and at once
made up his mind how to take it. There was, so to speak, a discordant note
in the general harmony.

вЂњTroy was founded by Teucer, Dardanus, Ilius and Tros,вЂќ the boy rapped out
at once, and in the same instant he blushed, blushed so, that it was
painful to look at him. But the boys stared at him, stared at him for a
whole minute, and then all the staring eyes turned at once and were
fastened upon Kolya, who was still scanning the audacious boy with
disdainful composure.

вЂњIn what sense did they found it?вЂќ he deigned to comment at last. вЂњAnd
what is meant by founding a city or a state? What do they do? Did they go
and each lay a brick, do you suppose?вЂќ

There was laughter. The offending boy turned from pink to crimson. He was
silent and on the point of tears. Kolya held him so for a minute.

вЂњBefore you talk of a historical event like the foundation of a
nationality, you must first understand what you mean by it,вЂќ he admonished
him in stern, incisive tones. вЂњBut I attach no consequence to these old
wivesвЂ™ tales and I donвЂ™t think much of universal history in general,вЂќ he
added carelessly, addressing the company generally.

вЂњUniversal history?вЂќ the captain inquired, looking almost scared.

вЂњYes, universal history! ItвЂ™s the study of the successive follies of
mankind and nothing more. The only subjects I respect are mathematics and
natural science,вЂќ said Kolya. He was showing off and he stole a glance at
Alyosha; his was the only opinion he was afraid of there. But Alyosha was
still silent and still serious as before. If Alyosha had said a word it
would have stopped him, but Alyosha was silent and вЂњit might be the
silence of contempt,вЂќ and that finally irritated Kolya.

вЂњThe classical languages, too ... they are simply madness, nothing more.
You seem to disagree with me again, Karamazov?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t agree,вЂќ said Alyosha, with a faint smile.

вЂњThe study of the classics, if you ask my opinion, is simply a police
measure, thatвЂ™s simply why it has been introduced into our schools.вЂќ By
degrees Kolya began to get breathless again. вЂњLatin and Greek were
introduced because they are a bore and because they stupefy the intellect.
It was dull before, so what could they do to make things duller? It was
senseless enough before, so what could they do to make it more senseless?
So they thought of Greek and Latin. ThatвЂ™s my opinion, I hope I shall
never change it,вЂќ Kolya finished abruptly. His cheeks were flushed.

вЂњThatвЂ™s true,вЂќ assented Smurov suddenly, in a ringing tone of conviction.
He had listened attentively.

вЂњAnd yet he is first in Latin himself,вЂќ cried one of the group of boys
suddenly.

вЂњYes, father, he says that and yet he is first in Latin,вЂќ echoed Ilusha.

вЂњWhat of it?вЂќ Kolya thought fit to defend himself, though the praise was
very sweet to him. вЂњI am fagging away at Latin because I have to, because
I promised my mother to pass my examination, and I think that whatever you
do, itвЂ™s worth doing it well. But in my soul I have a profound contempt
for the classics and all that fraud.... You donвЂ™t agree, Karamazov?вЂќ

вЂњWhy вЂfraudвЂ™?вЂќ Alyosha smiled again.

вЂњWell, all the classical authors have been translated into all languages,
so it was not for the sake of studying the classics they introduced Latin,
but solely as a police measure, to stupefy the intelligence. So what can
one call it but a fraud?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, who taught you all this?вЂќ cried Alyosha, surprised at last.

вЂњIn the first place I am capable of thinking for myself without being
taught. Besides, what I said just now about the classics being translated
our teacher Kolbasnikov has said to the whole of the third class.вЂќ

вЂњThe doctor has come!вЂќ cried Nina, who had been silent till then.

A carriage belonging to Madame Hohlakov drove up to the gate. The captain,
who had been expecting the doctor all the morning, rushed headlong out to
meet him. вЂњMammaвЂќ pulled herself together and assumed a dignified air.
Alyosha went up to Ilusha and began setting his pillows straight. Nina,
from her invalid chair, anxiously watched him putting the bed tidy. The
boys hurriedly took leave. Some of them promised to come again in the
evening. Kolya called Perezvon and the dog jumped off the bed.

вЂњI wonвЂ™t go away, I wonвЂ™t go away,вЂќ Kolya said hastily to Ilusha. вЂњIвЂ™ll
wait in the passage and come back when the doctorвЂ™s gone, IвЂ™ll come back
with Perezvon.вЂќ

But by now the doctor had entered, an importantвЂђlooking person with long,
dark whiskers and a shiny, shaven chin, wearing a bearskin coat. As he
crossed the threshold he stopped, taken aback; he probably fancied he had
come to the wrong place. вЂњHow is this? Where am I?вЂќ he muttered, not
removing his coat nor his peaked sealskin cap. The crowd, the poverty of
the room, the washing hanging on a line in the corner, puzzled him. The
captain, bent double, was bowing low before him.

вЂњItвЂ™s here, sir, here, sir,вЂќ he muttered cringingly; вЂњitвЂ™s here, youвЂ™ve
come right, you were coming to us...вЂќ

вЂњSneвЂђgiвЂђryov?вЂќ the doctor said loudly and pompously. вЂњMr. SnegiryovвЂ”is
that you?вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s me, sir!вЂќ

вЂњAh!вЂќ

The doctor looked round the room with a squeamish air once more and threw
off his coat, displaying to all eyes the grand decoration at his neck. The
captain caught the fur coat in the air, and the doctor took off his cap.

вЂњWhere is the patient?вЂќ he asked emphatically.



Chapter VI. Precocity


вЂњWhat do you think the doctor will say to him?вЂќ Kolya asked quickly. вЂњWhat
a repulsive mug, though, hasnвЂ™t he? I canвЂ™t endure medicine!вЂќ

вЂњIlusha is dying. I think thatвЂ™s certain,вЂќ answered Alyosha, mournfully.

вЂњThey are rogues! MedicineвЂ™s a fraud! I am glad to have made your
acquaintance, though, Karamazov. I wanted to know you for a long time. I
am only sorry we meet in such sad circumstances.вЂќ

Kolya had a great inclination to say something even warmer and more
demonstrative, but he felt ill at ease. Alyosha noticed this, smiled, and
pressed his hand.

вЂњIвЂ™ve long learned to respect you as a rare person,вЂќ Kolya muttered again,
faltering and uncertain. вЂњI have heard you are a mystic and have been in
the monastery. I know you are a mystic, but ... that hasnвЂ™t put me off.
Contact with real life will cure you.... ItвЂ™s always so with characters
like yours.вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you mean by mystic? Cure me of what?вЂќ Alyosha was rather
astonished.

вЂњOh, God and all the rest of it.вЂќ

вЂњWhat, donвЂ™t you believe in God?вЂќ

вЂњOh, IвЂ™ve nothing against God. Of course, God is only a hypothesis, but
... I admit that He is needed ... for the order of the universe and all
that ... and that if there were no God He would have to be invented,вЂќ
added Kolya, beginning to blush. He suddenly fancied that Alyosha might
think he was trying to show off his knowledge and to prove that he was
вЂњgrown up.вЂќ вЂњI havenвЂ™t the slightest desire to show off my knowledge to
him,вЂќ Kolya thought indignantly. And all of a sudden he felt horribly
annoyed.

вЂњI must confess I canвЂ™t endure entering on such discussions,вЂќ he said with
a final air. вЂњItвЂ™s possible for one who doesnвЂ™t believe in God to love
mankind, donвЂ™t you think so? Voltaire didnвЂ™t believe in God and loved
mankind?вЂќ (вЂњI am at it again,вЂќ he thought to himself.)

вЂњVoltaire believed in God, though not very much, I think, and I donвЂ™t
think he loved mankind very much either,вЂќ said Alyosha quietly, gently,
and quite naturally, as though he were talking to some one of his own age,
or even older. Kolya was particularly struck by AlyoshaвЂ™s apparent
diffidence about his opinion of Voltaire. He seemed to be leaving the
question for him, little Kolya, to settle.

вЂњHave you read Voltaire?вЂќ Alyosha finished.

вЂњNo, not to say read.... But IвЂ™ve read _Candide_ in the Russian
translation ... in an absurd, grotesque, old translation ... (At it again!
again!)вЂќ

вЂњAnd did you understand it?вЂќ

вЂњOh, yes, everything.... That is ... Why do you suppose I shouldnвЂ™t
understand it? ThereвЂ™s a lot of nastiness in it, of course.... Of course I
can understand that itвЂ™s a philosophical novel and written to advocate an
idea....вЂќ Kolya was getting mixed by now. вЂњI am a Socialist, Karamazov, I
am an incurable Socialist,вЂќ he announced suddenly, apropos of nothing.

вЂњA Socialist?вЂќ laughed Alyosha. вЂњBut when have you had time to become one?
Why, I thought you were only thirteen?вЂќ

Kolya winced.

вЂњIn the first place I am not thirteen, but fourteen, fourteen in a
fortnight,вЂќ he flushed angrily, вЂњand in the second place I am at a
complete loss to understand what my age has to do with it? The question is
what are my convictions, not what is my age, isnвЂ™t it?вЂќ

вЂњWhen you are older, youвЂ™ll understand for yourself the influence of age
on convictions. I fancied, too, that you were not expressing your own
ideas,вЂќ Alyosha answered serenely and modestly, but Kolya interrupted him
hotly:

вЂњCome, you want obedience and mysticism. You must admit that the Christian
religion, for instance, has only been of use to the rich and the powerful
to keep the lower classes in slavery. ThatвЂ™s so, isnвЂ™t it?вЂќ

вЂњAh, I know where you read that, and I am sure some one told you so!вЂќ
cried Alyosha.

вЂњI say, what makes you think I read it? And certainly no one told me so. I
can think for myself.... I am not opposed to Christ, if you like. He was a
most humane person, and if He were alive toвЂђday, He would be found in the
ranks of the revolutionists, and would perhaps play a conspicuous part....
ThereвЂ™s no doubt about that.вЂќ

вЂњOh, where, where did you get that from? What fool have you made friends
with?вЂќ exclaimed Alyosha.

вЂњCome, the truth will out! It has so chanced that I have often talked to
Mr. Rakitin, of course, but ... old Byelinsky said that, too, so they
say.вЂќ

вЂњByelinsky? I donвЂ™t remember. He hasnвЂ™t written that anywhere.вЂќ

вЂњIf he didnвЂ™t write it, they say he said it. I heard that from a ... but
never mind.вЂќ

вЂњAnd have you read Byelinsky?вЂќ

вЂњWell, no ... I havenвЂ™t read all of him, but ... I read the passage about
Tatyana, why she didnвЂ™t go off with Onyegin.вЂќ

вЂњDidnвЂ™t go off with Onyegin? Surely you donвЂ™t ... understand that
already?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, you seem to take me for little Smurov,вЂќ said Kolya, with a grin of
irritation. вЂњBut please donвЂ™t suppose I am such a revolutionist. I often
disagree with Mr. Rakitin. Though I mention Tatyana, I am not at all for
the emancipation of women. I acknowledge that women are a subject race and
must obey. _Les femmes tricottent_, as Napoleon said.вЂќ Kolya, for some
reason, smiled, вЂњAnd on that question at least I am quite of one mind with
that pseudoвЂђgreat man. I think, too, that to leave oneвЂ™s own country and
fly to America is mean, worse than meanвЂ”silly. Why go to America when one
may be of great service to humanity here? Now especially. ThereвЂ™s a
perfect mass of fruitful activity open to us. ThatвЂ™s what I answered.вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you mean? Answered whom? Has some one suggested your going to
America already?вЂќ

вЂњI must own, theyвЂ™ve been at me to go, but I declined. ThatвЂ™s between
ourselves, of course, Karamazov; do you hear, not a word to any one. I say
this only to you. I am not at all anxious to fall into the clutches of the
secret police and take lessons at the Chain bridge.


    _Long will you remember_
    _The house at the Chain bridge._


Do you remember? ItвЂ™s splendid. Why are you laughing? You donвЂ™t suppose I
am fibbing, do you?вЂќ (вЂњWhat if he should find out that IвЂ™ve only that one
number of _The Bell_ in fatherвЂ™s bookcase, and havenвЂ™t read any more of
it?вЂќ Kolya thought with a shudder.)

вЂњOh, no, I am not laughing and donвЂ™t suppose for a moment that you are
lying. No, indeed, I canвЂ™t suppose so, for all this, alas! is perfectly
true. But tell me, have you read PushkinвЂ”_Onyegin_, for instance?... You
spoke just now of Tatyana.вЂќ

вЂњNo, I havenвЂ™t read it yet, but I want to read it. I have no prejudices,
Karamazov; I want to hear both sides. What makes you ask?вЂќ

вЂњOh, nothing.вЂќ

вЂњTell me, Karamazov, have you an awful contempt for me?вЂќ Kolya rapped out
suddenly and drew himself up before Alyosha, as though he were on drill.
вЂњBe so kind as to tell me, without beating about the bush.вЂќ

вЂњI have a contempt for you?вЂќ Alyosha looked at him wondering. вЂњWhat for? I
am only sad that a charming nature such as yours should be perverted by
all this crude nonsense before you have begun life.вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t be anxious about my nature,вЂќ Kolya interrupted, not without
complacency. вЂњBut itвЂ™s true that I am stupidly sensitive, crudely
sensitive. You smiled just now, and I fancied you seemed toвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњOh, my smile meant something quite different. IвЂ™ll tell you why I smiled.
Not long ago I read the criticism made by a German who had lived in
Russia, on our students and schoolboys of toвЂђday. вЂShow a Russian
schoolboy,вЂ™ he writes, вЂa map of the stars, which he knows nothing about,
and he will give you back the map next day with corrections on it.вЂ™ No
knowledge and unbounded conceitвЂ”thatвЂ™s what the German meant to say about
the Russian schoolboy.вЂќ

вЂњYes, thatвЂ™s perfectly right,вЂќ Kolya laughed suddenly, вЂњexactly so! Bravo
the German! But he did not see the good side, what do you think? Conceit
may be, that comes from youth, that will be corrected if need be, but, on
the other hand, there is an independent spirit almost from childhood,
boldness of thought and conviction, and not the spirit of these sausage
makers, groveling before authority.... But the German was right all the
same. Bravo the German! But Germans want strangling all the same. Though
they are so good at science and learning they must be strangled.вЂќ

вЂњStrangled, what for?вЂќ smiled Alyosha.

вЂњWell, perhaps I am talking nonsense, I agree. I am awfully childish
sometimes, and when I am pleased about anything I canвЂ™t restrain myself
and am ready to talk any stuff. But, I say, we are chattering away here
about nothing, and that doctor has been a long time in there. But perhaps
heвЂ™s examining the mamma and that poor crippled Nina. I liked that Nina,
you know. She whispered to me suddenly as I was coming away, вЂWhy didnвЂ™t
you come before?вЂ™ And in such a voice, so reproachfully! I think she is
awfully nice and pathetic.вЂќ

вЂњYes, yes! Well, youвЂ™ll be coming often, you will see what she is like. It
would do you a great deal of good to know people like that, to learn to
value a great deal which you will find out from knowing these people,вЂќ
Alyosha observed warmly. вЂњThat would have more effect on you than
anything.вЂќ

вЂњOh, how I regret and blame myself for not having come sooner!вЂќ Kolya
exclaimed, with bitter feeling.

вЂњYes, itвЂ™s a great pity. You saw for yourself how delighted the poor child
was to see you. And how he fretted for you to come!вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t tell me! You make it worse! But it serves me right. What kept me
from coming was my conceit, my egoistic vanity, and the beastly
wilfullness, which I never can get rid of, though IвЂ™ve been struggling
with it all my life. I see that now. I am a beast in lots of ways,
Karamazov!вЂќ

вЂњNo, you have a charming nature, though itвЂ™s been distorted, and I quite
understand why you have had such an influence on this generous, morbidly
sensitive boy,вЂќ Alyosha answered warmly.

вЂњAnd you say that to me!вЂќ cried Kolya; вЂњand would you believe it, I
thoughtвЂ”IвЂ™ve thought several times since IвЂ™ve been hereвЂ”that you despised
me! If only you knew how I prize your opinion!вЂќ

вЂњBut are you really so sensitive? At your age! Would you believe it, just
now, when you were telling your story, I thought, as I watched you, that
you must be very sensitive!вЂќ

вЂњYou thought so? What an eye youвЂ™ve got, I say! I bet that was when I was
talking about the goose. That was just when I was fancying you had a great
contempt for me for being in such a hurry to show off, and for a moment I
quite hated you for it, and began talking like a fool. Then I fanciedвЂ”just
now, hereвЂ”when I said that if there were no God He would have to be
invented, that I was in too great a hurry to display my knowledge,
especially as I got that phrase out of a book. But I swear I wasnвЂ™t
showing off out of vanity, though I really donвЂ™t know why. Because I was
so pleased? Yes, I believe it was because I was so pleased ... though itвЂ™s
perfectly disgraceful for any one to be gushing directly they are pleased,
I know that. But I am convinced now that you donвЂ™t despise me; it was all
my imagination. Oh, Karamazov, I am profoundly unhappy. I sometimes fancy
all sorts of things, that every one is laughing at me, the whole world,
and then I feel ready to overturn the whole order of things.вЂќ

вЂњAnd you worry every one about you,вЂќ smiled Alyosha.

вЂњYes, I worry every one about me, especially my mother. Karamazov, tell
me, am I very ridiculous now?вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t think about that, donвЂ™t think of it at all!вЂќ cried Alyosha. вЂњAnd
what does ridiculous mean? IsnвЂ™t every one constantly being or seeming
ridiculous? Besides, nearly all clever people now are fearfully afraid of
being ridiculous, and that makes them unhappy. All I am surprised at is
that you should be feeling that so early, though IвЂ™ve observed it for some
time past, and not only in you. Nowadays the very children have begun to
suffer from it. ItвЂ™s almost a sort of insanity. The devil has taken the
form of that vanity and entered into the whole generation; itвЂ™s simply the
devil,вЂќ added Alyosha, without a trace of the smile that Kolya, staring at
him, expected to see. вЂњYou are like every one else,вЂќ said Alyosha, in
conclusion, вЂњthat is, like very many others. Only you must not be like
everybody else, thatвЂ™s all.вЂќ

вЂњEven if every one is like that?вЂќ

вЂњYes, even if every one is like that. You be the only one not like it. You
really are not like every one else, here you are not ashamed to confess to
something bad and even ridiculous. And who will admit so much in these
days? No one. And people have even ceased to feel the impulse to selfвЂђ
criticism. DonвЂ™t be like every one else, even if you are the only one.вЂќ

вЂњSplendid! I was not mistaken in you. You know how to console one. Oh, how
I have longed to know you, Karamazov! IвЂ™ve long been eager for this
meeting. Can you really have thought about me, too? You said just now that
you thought of me, too?вЂќ

вЂњYes, IвЂ™d heard of you and had thought of you, too ... and if itвЂ™s partly
vanity that makes you ask, it doesnвЂ™t matter.вЂќ

вЂњDo you know, Karamazov, our talk has been like a declaration of love,вЂќ
said Kolya, in a bashful and melting voice. вЂњThatвЂ™s not ridiculous, is
it?вЂќ

вЂњNot at all ridiculous, and if it were, it wouldnвЂ™t matter, because itвЂ™s
been a good thing.вЂќ Alyosha smiled brightly.

вЂњBut do you know, Karamazov, you must admit that you are a little ashamed
yourself, now.... I see it by your eyes.вЂќ Kolya smiled with a sort of sly
happiness.

вЂњWhy ashamed?вЂќ

вЂњWell, why are you blushing?вЂќ

вЂњIt was you made me blush,вЂќ laughed Alyosha, and he really did blush. вЂњOh,
well, I am a little, goodness knows why, I donвЂ™t know...вЂќ he muttered,
almost embarrassed.

вЂњOh, how I love you and admire you at this moment just because you are
rather ashamed! Because you are just like me,вЂќ cried Kolya, in positive
ecstasy. His cheeks glowed, his eyes beamed.

вЂњYou know, Kolya, you will be very unhappy in your life,вЂќ something made
Alyosha say suddenly.

вЂњI know, I know. How you know it all beforehand!вЂќ Kolya agreed at once.

вЂњBut you will bless life on the whole, all the same.вЂќ

вЂњJust so, hurrah! You are a prophet. Oh, we shall get on together,
Karamazov! Do you know, what delights me most, is that you treat me quite
like an equal. But we are not equals, no, we are not, you are better! But
we shall get on. Do you know, all this last month, IвЂ™ve been saying to
myself, вЂEither we shall be friends at once, for ever, or we shall part
enemies to the grave!вЂ™ вЂќ

вЂњAnd saying that, of course, you loved me,вЂќ Alyosha laughed gayly.

вЂњI did. I loved you awfully. IвЂ™ve been loving and dreaming of you. And how
do you know it all beforehand? Ah, hereвЂ™s the doctor. Goodness! What will
he tell us? Look at his face!вЂќ



Chapter VII. Ilusha


The doctor came out of the room again, muffled in his fur coat and with
his cap on his head. His face looked almost angry and disgusted, as though
he were afraid of getting dirty. He cast a cursory glance round the
passage, looking sternly at Alyosha and Kolya as he did so. Alyosha waved
from the door to the coachman, and the carriage that had brought the
doctor drove up. The captain darted out after the doctor, and, bowing
apologetically, stopped him to get the last word. The poor fellow looked
utterly crushed; there was a scared look in his eyes.

вЂњYour Excellency, your Excellency ... is it possible?вЂќ he began, but could
not go on and clasped his hands in despair. Yet he still gazed imploringly
at the doctor, as though a word from him might still change the poor boyвЂ™s
fate.

вЂњI canвЂ™t help it, I am not God!вЂќ the doctor answered offhand, though with
the customary impressiveness.

вЂњDoctor ... your Excellency ... and will it be soon, soon?вЂќ

вЂњYou must be prepared for anything,вЂќ said the doctor in emphatic and
incisive tones, and dropping his eyes, he was about to step out to the
coach.

вЂњYour Excellency, for ChristвЂ™s sake!вЂќ the terrorвЂђstricken captain stopped
him again. вЂњYour Excellency! but can nothing, absolutely nothing save him
now?вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s not in my hands now,вЂќ said the doctor impatiently, вЂњbut hвЂ™m!...вЂќ he
stopped suddenly. вЂњIf you could, for instance ... send ... your patient
... at once, without delayвЂќ (the words вЂњat once, without delay,вЂќ the
doctor uttered with an almost wrathful sternness that made the captain
start) вЂњto Syracuse, the change to the new beвЂђneвЂђficial climatic
conditions might possibly effectвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњTo Syracuse!вЂќ cried the captain, unable to grasp what was said.

вЂњSyracuse is in Sicily,вЂќ Kolya jerked out suddenly in explanation. The
doctor looked at him.

вЂњSicily! your Excellency,вЂќ faltered the captain, вЂњbut youвЂ™ve seenвЂќвЂ”he
spread out his hands, indicating his surroundingsвЂ”вЂњmamma and my family?вЂќ

вЂњNвЂ”no, Sicily is not the place for the family, the family should go to
Caucasus in the early spring ... your daughter must go to the Caucasus,
and your wife ... after a course of the waters in the Caucasus for her
rheumatism ... must be sent straight to Paris to the mental specialist
Lepelletier; I could give you a note to him, and then ... there might be a
changeвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњDoctor, doctor! But you see!вЂќ The captain flung wide his hands again
despairingly, indicating the bare wooden walls of the passage.

вЂњWell, thatвЂ™s not my business,вЂќ grinned the doctor. вЂњI have only told you
the answer of medical science to your question as to possible treatment.
As for the rest, to my regretвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t be afraid, apothecary, my dog wonвЂ™t bite you,вЂќ Kolya rapped out
loudly, noticing the doctorвЂ™s rather uneasy glance at Perezvon, who was
standing in the doorway. There was a wrathful note in KolyaвЂ™s voice. He
used the word apothecary instead of doctor on purpose, and, as he
explained afterwards, used it вЂњto insult him.вЂќ

вЂњWhatвЂ™s that?вЂќ The doctor flung up his head, staring with surprise at
Kolya. вЂњWhoвЂ™s this?вЂќ he addressed Alyosha, as though asking him to
explain.

вЂњItвЂ™s PerezvonвЂ™s master, donвЂ™t worry about me,вЂќ Kolya said incisively
again.

вЂњPerezvon?вЂќ(7) repeated the doctor, perplexed.

вЂњHe hears the bell, but where it is he cannot tell. GoodвЂђby, we shall meet
in Syracuse.вЂќ

вЂњWhoвЂ™s this? WhoвЂ™s this?вЂќ The doctor flew into a terrible rage.

вЂњHe is a schoolboy, doctor, he is a mischievous boy; take no notice of
him,вЂќ said Alyosha, frowning and speaking quickly. вЂњKolya, hold your
tongue!вЂќ he cried to Krassotkin. вЂњTake no notice of him, doctor,вЂќ he
repeated, rather impatiently.

вЂњHe wants a thrashing, a good thrashing!вЂќ The doctor stamped in a perfect
fury.

вЂњAnd you know, apothecary, my Perezvon might bite!вЂќ said Kolya, turning
pale, with quivering voice and flashing eyes. вЂњ_Ici_, Perezvon!вЂќ

вЂњKolya, if you say another word, IвЂ™ll have nothing more to do with you,вЂќ
Alyosha cried peremptorily.

вЂњThere is only one man in the world who can command Nikolay
KrassotkinвЂ”this is the manвЂќ; Kolya pointed to Alyosha. вЂњI obey him, goodвЂђ
by!вЂќ

He stepped forward, opened the door, and quickly went into the inner room.
Perezvon flew after him. The doctor stood still for five seconds in
amazement, looking at Alyosha; then, with a curse, he went out quickly to
the carriage, repeating aloud, вЂњThis is ... this is ... I donвЂ™t know what
it is!вЂќ The captain darted forward to help him into the carriage. Alyosha
followed Kolya into the room. He was already by IlushaвЂ™s bedside. The sick
boy was holding his hand and calling for his father. A minute later the
captain, too, came back.

вЂњFather, father, come ... we ...вЂќ Ilusha faltered in violent excitement,
but apparently unable to go on, he flung his wasted arms round his father
and Kolya, uniting them in one embrace, and hugging them as tightly as he
could. The captain suddenly began to shake with dumb sobs, and KolyaвЂ™s
lips and chin twitched.

вЂњFather, father! How sorry I am for you!вЂќ Ilusha moaned bitterly.

вЂњIlusha ... darling ... the doctor said ... you would be all right ... we
shall be happy ... the doctor ...вЂќ the captain began.

вЂњAh, father! I know what the new doctor said to you about me.... I saw!вЂќ
cried Ilusha, and again he hugged them both with all his strength, hiding
his face on his fatherвЂ™s shoulder.

вЂњFather, donвЂ™t cry, and when I die get a good boy, another one ... choose
one of them all, a good one, call him Ilusha and love him instead of
me....вЂќ

вЂњHush, old man, youвЂ™ll get well,вЂќ Krassotkin cried suddenly, in a voice
that sounded angry.

вЂњBut donвЂ™t ever forget me, father,вЂќ Ilusha went on, вЂњcome to my grave ...
and, father, bury me by our big stone, where we used to go for our walk,
and come to me there with Krassotkin in the evening ... and Perezvon ... I
shall expect you.... Father, father!вЂќ

His voice broke. They were all three silent, still embracing. Nina was
crying quietly in her chair, and at last seeing them all crying, вЂњmamma,вЂќ
too, burst into tears.

вЂњIlusha! Ilusha!вЂќ she exclaimed.

Krassotkin suddenly released himself from IlushaвЂ™s embrace.

вЂњGoodвЂђby, old man, mother expects me back to dinner,вЂќ he said quickly.
вЂњWhat a pity I did not tell her! She will be dreadfully anxious.... But
after dinner IвЂ™ll come back to you for the whole day, for the whole
evening, and IвЂ™ll tell you all sorts of things, all sorts of things. And
IвЂ™ll bring Perezvon, but now I will take him with me, because he will
begin to howl when I am away and bother you. GoodвЂђby!вЂќ

And he ran out into the passage. He didnвЂ™t want to cry, but in the passage
he burst into tears. Alyosha found him crying.

вЂњKolya, you must be sure to keep your word and come, or he will be
terribly disappointed,вЂќ Alyosha said emphatically.

вЂњI will! Oh, how I curse myself for not having come before!вЂќ muttered
Kolya, crying, and no longer ashamed of it.

At that moment the captain flew out of the room, and at once closed the
door behind him. His face looked frenzied, his lips were trembling. He
stood before the two and flung up his arms.

вЂњI donвЂ™t want a good boy! I donвЂ™t want another boy!вЂќ he muttered in a wild
whisper, clenching his teeth. вЂњIf I forget thee, Jerusalem, may my
tongueвЂ”вЂќ He broke off with a sob and sank on his knees before the wooden
bench. Pressing his fists against his head, he began sobbing with absurd
whimpering cries, doing his utmost that his cries should not be heard in
the room.

Kolya ran out into the street.

вЂњGoodвЂђby, Karamazov? Will you come yourself?вЂќ he cried sharply and angrily
to Alyosha.

вЂњI will certainly come in the evening.вЂќ

вЂњWhat was that he said about Jerusalem?... What did he mean by that?вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s from the Bible. вЂIf I forget thee, Jerusalem,вЂ™ that is, if I forget
all that is most precious to me, if I let anything take its place, then
mayвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњI understand, thatвЂ™s enough! Mind you come! _Ici_, Perezvon!вЂќ he cried
with positive ferocity to the dog, and with rapid strides he went home.




Book XI. Ivan



Chapter I. At GrushenkaвЂ™s


Alyosha went towards the cathedral square to the widow MorozovвЂ™s house to
see Grushenka, who had sent Fenya to him early in the morning with an
urgent message begging him to come. Questioning Fenya, Alyosha learned
that her mistress had been particularly distressed since the previous day.
During the two months that had passed since MityaвЂ™s arrest, Alyosha had
called frequently at the widow MorozovвЂ™s house, both from his own
inclination and to take messages for Mitya. Three days after MityaвЂ™s
arrest, Grushenka was taken very ill and was ill for nearly five weeks.
For one whole week she was unconscious. She was very much changedвЂ”thinner
and a little sallow, though she had for the past fortnight been well
enough to go out. But to Alyosha her face was even more attractive than
before, and he liked to meet her eyes when he went in to her. A look of
firmness and intelligent purpose had developed in her face. There were
signs of a spiritual transformation in her, and a steadfast, fine and
humble determination that nothing could shake could be discerned in her.
There was a small vertical line between her brows which gave her charming
face a look of concentrated thought, almost austere at the first glance.
There was scarcely a trace of her former frivolity.

It seemed strange to Alyosha, too, that in spite of the calamity that had
overtaken the poor girl, betrothed to a man who had been arrested for a
terrible crime, almost at the instant of their betrothal, in spite of her
illness and the almost inevitable sentence hanging over Mitya, Grushenka
had not yet lost her youthful cheerfulness. There was a soft light in the
once proud eyes, though at times they gleamed with the old vindictive fire
when she was visited by one disturbing thought stronger than ever in her
heart. The object of that uneasiness was the same as everвЂ”Katerina
Ivanovna, of whom Grushenka had even raved when she lay in delirium.
Alyosha knew that she was fearfully jealous of her. Yet Katerina Ivanovna
had not once visited Mitya in his prison, though she might have done it
whenever she liked. All this made a difficult problem for Alyosha, for he
was the only person to whom Grushenka opened her heart and from whom she
was continually asking advice. Sometimes he was unable to say anything.

Full of anxiety he entered her lodging. She was at home. She had returned
from seeing Mitya half an hour before, and from the rapid movement with
which she leapt up from her chair to meet him he saw that she had been
expecting him with great impatience. A pack of cards dealt for a game of
вЂњfoolsвЂќ lay on the table. A bed had been made up on the leather sofa on
the other side and Maximov lay, halfвЂђreclining, on it. He wore a dressingвЂђ
gown and a cotton nightcap, and was evidently ill and weak, though he was
smiling blissfully. When the homeless old man returned with Grushenka from
Mokroe two months before, he had simply stayed on and was still staying
with her. He arrived with her in rain and sleet, sat down on the sofa,
drenched and scared, and gazed mutely at her with a timid, appealing
smile. Grushenka, who was in terrible grief and in the first stage of
fever, almost forgot his existence in all she had to do the first halfвЂђ
hour after her arrival. Suddenly she chanced to look at him intently: he
laughed a pitiful, helpless little laugh. She called Fenya and told her to
give him something to eat. All that day he sat in the same place, almost
without stirring. When it got dark and the shutters were closed, Fenya
asked her mistress:

вЂњIs the gentleman going to stay the night, mistress?вЂќ

вЂњYes; make him a bed on the sofa,вЂќ answered Grushenka.

Questioning him more in detail, Grushenka learned from him that he had
literally nowhere to go, and that вЂњMr. Kalganov, my benefactor, told me
straight that he wouldnвЂ™t receive me again and gave me five roubles.вЂќ

вЂњWell, God bless you, youвЂ™d better stay, then,вЂќ Grushenka decided in her
grief, smiling compassionately at him. Her smile wrung the old manвЂ™s heart
and his lips twitched with grateful tears. And so the destitute wanderer
had stayed with her ever since. He did not leave the house even when she
was ill. Fenya and her grandmother, the cook, did not turn him out, but
went on serving him meals and making up his bed on the sofa. Grushenka had
grown used to him, and coming back from seeing Mitya (whom she had begun
to visit in prison before she was really well) she would sit down and
begin talking to вЂњMaximushkaвЂќ about trifling matters, to keep her from
thinking of her sorrow. The old man turned out to be a good storyвЂђteller
on occasions, so that at last he became necessary to her. Grushenka saw
scarcely any one else beside Alyosha, who did not come every day and never
stayed long. Her old merchant lay seriously ill at this time, вЂњat his last
gaspвЂќ as they said in the town, and he did, in fact, die a week after
MityaвЂ™s trial. Three weeks before his death, feeling the end approaching,
he made his sons, their wives and children, come upstairs to him at last
and bade them not leave him again. From that moment he gave strict orders
to his servants not to admit Grushenka and to tell her if she came, вЂњThe
master wishes you long life and happiness and tells you to forget him.вЂќ
But Grushenka sent almost every day to inquire after him.

вЂњYouвЂ™ve come at last!вЂќ she cried, flinging down the cards and joyfully
greeting Alyosha, вЂњand MaximushkaвЂ™s been scaring me that perhaps you
wouldnвЂ™t come. Ah, how I need you! Sit down to the table. What will you
haveвЂ”coffee?вЂќ

вЂњYes, please,вЂќ said Alyosha, sitting down at the table. вЂњI am very
hungry.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s right. Fenya, Fenya, coffee,вЂќ cried Grushenka. вЂњItвЂ™s been made a
long time ready for you. And bring some little pies, and mind they are
hot. Do you know, weвЂ™ve had a storm over those pies toвЂђday. I took them to
the prison for him, and would you believe it, he threw them back to me: he
would not eat them. He flung one of them on the floor and stamped on it.
So I said to him: вЂI shall leave them with the warder; if you donвЂ™t eat
them before evening, it will be that your venomous spite is enough for
you!вЂ™ With that I went away. We quarreled again, would you believe it?
Whenever I go we quarrel.вЂќ

Grushenka said all this in one breath in her agitation. Maximov, feeling
nervous, at once smiled and looked on the floor.

вЂњWhat did you quarrel about this time?вЂќ asked Alyosha.

вЂњI didnвЂ™t expect it in the least. Only fancy, he is jealous of the Pole.
вЂWhy are you keeping him?вЂ™ he said. вЂSo youвЂ™ve begun keeping him.вЂ™ He is
jealous, jealous of me all the time, jealous eating and sleeping! He even
took it into his head to be jealous of Kuzma last week.вЂќ

вЂњBut he knew about the Pole before?вЂќ

вЂњYes, but there it is. He has known about him from the very beginning, but
toвЂђday he suddenly got up and began scolding about him. I am ashamed to
repeat what he said. Silly fellow! Rakitin went in as I came out. Perhaps
Rakitin is egging him on. What do you think?вЂќ she added carelessly.

вЂњHe loves you, thatвЂ™s what it is: he loves you so much. And now he is
particularly worried.вЂќ

вЂњI should think he might be, with the trial toвЂђmorrow. And I went to him
to say something about toвЂђmorrow, for I dread to think whatвЂ™s going to
happen then. You say that he is worried, but how worried I am! And he
talks about the Pole! HeвЂ™s too silly! He is not jealous of Maximushka yet,
anyway.вЂќ

вЂњMy wife was dreadfully jealous over me, too,вЂќ Maximov put in his word.

вЂњJealous of you?вЂќ Grushenka laughed in spite of herself. вЂњOf whom could
she have been jealous?вЂќ

вЂњOf the servant girls.вЂќ

вЂњHold your tongue, Maximushka, I am in no laughing mood now; I feel angry.
DonвЂ™t ogle the pies. I shanвЂ™t give you any; they are not good for you, and
I wonвЂ™t give you any vodka either. I have to look after him, too, just as
though I kept an almshouse,вЂќ she laughed.

вЂњI donвЂ™t deserve your kindness. I am a worthless creature,вЂќ said Maximov,
with tears in his voice. вЂњYou would do better to spend your kindness on
people of more use than me.вЂќ

вЂњEch, every one is of use, Maximushka, and how can we tell whoвЂ™s of most
use? If only that Pole didnвЂ™t exist, Alyosha. HeвЂ™s taken it into his head
to fall ill, too, toвЂђday. IвЂ™ve been to see him also. And I shall send him
some pies, too, on purpose. I hadnвЂ™t sent him any, but Mitya accused me of
it, so now I shall send some! Ah, hereвЂ™s Fenya with a letter! Yes, itвЂ™s
from the PolesвЂ”begging again!вЂќ

Pan Mussyalovitch had indeed sent an extremely long and characteristically
eloquent letter in which he begged her to lend him three roubles. In the
letter was enclosed a receipt for the sum, with a promise to repay it
within three months, signed by Pan Vrublevsky as well. Grushenka had
received many such letters, accompanied by such receipts, from her former
lover during the fortnight of her convalescence. But she knew that the two
Poles had been to ask after her health during her illness. The first
letter Grushenka got from them was a long one, written on large notepaper
and with a big family crest on the seal. It was so obscure and rhetorical
that Grushenka put it down before she had read half, unable to make head
or tail of it. She could not attend to letters then. The first letter was
followed next day by another in which Pan Mussyalovitch begged her for a
loan of two thousand roubles for a very short period. Grushenka left that
letter, too, unanswered. A whole series of letters had followedвЂ”one every
dayвЂ”all as pompous and rhetorical, but the loan asked for, gradually
diminishing, dropped to a hundred roubles, then to twentyвЂђfive, to ten,
and finally Grushenka received a letter in which both the Poles begged her
for only one rouble and included a receipt signed by both.

Then Grushenka suddenly felt sorry for them, and at dusk she went round
herself to their lodging. She found the two Poles in great poverty, almost
destitution, without food or fuel, without cigarettes, in debt to their
landlady. The two hundred roubles they had carried off from Mitya at
Mokroe had soon disappeared. But Grushenka was surprised at their meeting
her with arrogant dignity and selfвЂђassertion, with the greatest punctilio
and pompous speeches. Grushenka simply laughed, and gave her former
admirer ten roubles. Then, laughing, she told Mitya of it and he was not
in the least jealous. But ever since, the Poles had attached themselves to
Grushenka and bombarded her daily with requests for money and she had
always sent them small sums. And now that day Mitya had taken it into his
head to be fearfully jealous.

вЂњLike a fool, I went round to him just for a minute, on the way to see
Mitya, for he is ill, too, my Pole,вЂќ Grushenka began again with nervous
haste. вЂњI was laughing, telling Mitya about it. вЂFancy,вЂ™ I said, вЂmy Pole
had the happy thought to sing his old songs to me to the guitar. He
thought I would be touched and marry him!вЂ™ Mitya leapt up swearing.... So,
there, IвЂ™ll send them the pies! Fenya, is it that little girl theyвЂ™ve
sent? Here, give her three roubles and pack a dozen pies up in a paper and
tell her to take them. And you, Alyosha, be sure to tell Mitya that I did
send them the pies.вЂќ

вЂњI wouldnвЂ™t tell him for anything,вЂќ said Alyosha, smiling.

вЂњEch! You think he is unhappy about it. Why, heвЂ™s jealous on purpose. He
doesnвЂ™t care,вЂќ said Grushenka bitterly.

вЂњOn purpose?вЂќ queried Alyosha.

вЂњI tell you you are silly, Alyosha. You know nothing about it, with all
your cleverness. I am not offended that he is jealous of a girl like me. I
would be offended if he were not jealous. I am like that. I am not
offended at jealousy. I have a fierce heart, too. I can be jealous myself.
Only what offends me is that he doesnвЂ™t love me at all. I tell you he is
jealous now _on purpose_. Am I blind? DonвЂ™t I see? He began talking to me
just now of that woman, of Katerina, saying she was this and that, how she
had ordered a doctor from Moscow for him, to try and save him; how she had
ordered the best counsel, the most learned one, too. So he loves her, if
heвЂ™ll praise her to my face, more shame to him! HeвЂ™s treated me badly
himself, so he attacked me, to make out I am in fault first and to throw
it all on me. вЂYou were with your Pole before me, so I canвЂ™t be blamed for
Katerina,вЂ™ thatвЂ™s what it amounts to. He wants to throw the whole blame on
me. He attacked me on purpose, on purpose, I tell you, but IвЂ™llвЂ”вЂќ

Grushenka could not finish saying what she would do. She hid her eyes in
her handkerchief and sobbed violently.

вЂњHe doesnвЂ™t love Katerina Ivanovna,вЂќ said Alyosha firmly.

вЂњWell, whether he loves her or not, IвЂ™ll soon find out for myself,вЂќ said
Grushenka, with a menacing note in her voice, taking the handkerchief from
her eyes. Her face was distorted. Alyosha saw sorrowfully that from being
mild and serene, it had become sullen and spiteful.

вЂњEnough of this foolishness,вЂќ she said suddenly; вЂњitвЂ™s not for that I sent
for you. Alyosha, darling, toвЂђmorrowвЂ”what will happen toвЂђmorrow? ThatвЂ™s
what worries me! And itвЂ™s only me it worries! I look at every one and no
one is thinking of it. No one cares about it. Are you thinking about it
even? ToвЂђmorrow heвЂ™ll be tried, you know. Tell me, how will he be tried?
You know itвЂ™s the valet, the valet killed him! Good heavens! Can they
condemn him in place of the valet and will no one stand up for him? They
havenвЂ™t troubled the valet at all, have they?вЂќ

вЂњHeвЂ™s been severely crossвЂђexamined,вЂќ observed Alyosha thoughtfully; вЂњbut
every one came to the conclusion it was not he. Now he is lying very ill.
He has been ill ever since that attack. Really ill,вЂќ added Alyosha.

вЂњOh, dear! couldnвЂ™t you go to that counsel yourself and tell him the whole
thing by yourself? HeвЂ™s been brought from Petersburg for three thousand
roubles, they say.вЂќ

вЂњWe gave these three thousand togetherвЂ”Ivan, Katerina Ivanovna and IвЂ”but
she paid two thousand for the doctor from Moscow herself. The counsel
Fetyukovitch would have charged more, but the case has become known all
over Russia; itвЂ™s talked of in all the papers and journals. Fetyukovitch
agreed to come more for the glory of the thing, because the case has
become so notorious. I saw him yesterday.вЂќ

вЂњWell? Did you talk to him?вЂќ Grushenka put in eagerly.

вЂњHe listened and said nothing. He told me that he had already formed his
opinion. But he promised to give my words consideration.вЂќ

вЂњConsideration! Ah, they are swindlers! TheyвЂ™ll ruin him. And why did she
send for the doctor?вЂќ

вЂњAs an expert. They want to prove that MityaвЂ™s mad and committed the
murder when he didnвЂ™t know what he was doingвЂќ; Alyosha smiled gently; вЂњbut
Mitya wonвЂ™t agree to that.вЂќ

вЂњYes; but that would be the truth if he had killed him!вЂќ cried Grushenka.
вЂњHe was mad then, perfectly mad, and that was my fault, wretch that I am!
But, of course, he didnвЂ™t do it, he didnвЂ™t do it! And they are all against
him, the whole town. Even FenyaвЂ™s evidence went to prove he had done it.
And the people at the shop, and that official, and at the tavern, too,
before, people had heard him say so! They are all, all against him, all
crying out against him.вЂќ

вЂњYes, thereвЂ™s a fearful accumulation of evidence,вЂќ Alyosha observed
grimly.

вЂњAnd GrigoryвЂ”Grigory VassilyevitchвЂ”sticks to his story that the door was
open, persists that he saw itвЂ”thereвЂ™s no shaking him. I went and talked to
him myself. HeвЂ™s rude about it, too.вЂќ

вЂњYes, thatвЂ™s perhaps the strongest evidence against him,вЂќ said Alyosha.

вЂњAnd as for MityaвЂ™s being mad, he certainly seems like it now,вЂќ Grushenka
began with a peculiarly anxious and mysterious air. вЂњDo you know, Alyosha,
IвЂ™ve been wanting to talk to you about it for a long time. I go to him
every day and simply wonder at him. Tell me, now, what do you suppose heвЂ™s
always talking about? He talks and talks and I can make nothing of it. I
fancied he was talking of something intellectual that I couldnвЂ™t
understand in my foolishness. Only he suddenly began talking to me about a
babeвЂ”that is, about some child. вЂWhy is the babe poor?вЂ™ he said. вЂItвЂ™s for
that babe I am going to Siberia now. I am not a murderer, but I must go to
Siberia!вЂ™ What that meant, what babe, I couldnвЂ™t tell for the life of me.
Only I cried when he said it, because he said it so nicely. He cried
himself, and I cried, too. He suddenly kissed me and made the sign of the
cross over me. What did it mean, Alyosha, tell me? What is this babe?вЂќ

вЂњIt must be Rakitin, whoвЂ™s been going to see him lately,вЂќ smiled Alyosha,
вЂњthough ... thatвЂ™s not RakitinвЂ™s doing. I didnвЂ™t see Mitya yesterday. IвЂ™ll
see him toвЂђday.вЂќ

вЂњNo, itвЂ™s not Rakitin; itвЂ™s his brother Ivan Fyodorovitch upsetting him.
ItвЂ™s his going to see him, thatвЂ™s what it is,вЂќ Grushenka began, and
suddenly broke off. Alyosha gazed at her in amazement.

вЂњIvanвЂ™s going? Has he been to see him? Mitya told me himself that Ivan
hasnвЂ™t been once.вЂќ

вЂњThere ... there! What a girl I am! Blurting things out!вЂќ exclaimed
Grushenka, confused and suddenly blushing. вЂњStay, Alyosha, hush! Since
IвЂ™ve said so much IвЂ™ll tell the whole truthвЂ”heвЂ™s been to see him twice,
the first directly he arrived. He galloped here from Moscow at once, of
course, before I was taken ill; and the second time was a week ago. He
told Mitya not to tell you about it, under any circumstances; and not to
tell any one, in fact. He came secretly.вЂќ

Alyosha sat plunged in thought, considering something. The news evidently
impressed him.

вЂњIvan doesnвЂ™t talk to me of MityaвЂ™s case,вЂќ he said slowly. вЂњHeвЂ™s said very
little to me these last two months. And whenever I go to see him, he seems
vexed at my coming, so IвЂ™ve not been to him for the last three weeks.
HвЂ™m!... if he was there a week ago ... there certainly has been a change
in Mitya this week.вЂќ

вЂњThere has been a change,вЂќ Grushenka assented quickly. вЂњThey have a
secret, they have a secret! Mitya told me himself there was a secret, and
such a secret that Mitya canвЂ™t rest. Before then, he was cheerfulвЂ”and,
indeed, he is cheerful nowвЂ”but when he shakes his head like that, you
know, and strides about the room and keeps pulling at the hair on his
right temple with his right hand, I know there is something on his mind
worrying him.... I know! He was cheerful before, though, indeed, he is
cheerful toвЂђday.вЂќ

вЂњBut you said he was worried.вЂќ

вЂњYes, he is worried and yet cheerful. He keeps on being irritable for a
minute and then cheerful and then irritable again. And you know, Alyosha,
I am constantly wondering at himвЂ”with this awful thing hanging over him,
he sometimes laughs at such trifles as though he were a baby himself.вЂќ

вЂњAnd did he really tell you not to tell me about Ivan? Did he say, вЂDonвЂ™t
tell himвЂ™?вЂќ

вЂњYes, he told me, вЂDonвЂ™t tell him.вЂ™ ItвЂ™s you that MityaвЂ™s most afraid of.
Because itвЂ™s a secret: he said himself it was a secret. Alyosha, darling,
go to him and find out what their secret is and come and tell me,вЂќ
Grushenka besought him with sudden eagerness. вЂњSet my mind at rest that I
may know the worst thatвЂ™s in store for me. ThatвЂ™s why I sent for you.вЂќ

вЂњYou think itвЂ™s something to do with you? If it were, he wouldnвЂ™t have
told you there was a secret.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know. Perhaps he wants to tell me, but doesnвЂ™t dare to. He warns
me. There is a secret, he tells me, but he wonвЂ™t tell me what it is.вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you think yourself?вЂќ

вЂњWhat do I think? ItвЂ™s the end for me, thatвЂ™s what I think. They all three
have been plotting my end, for KaterinaвЂ™s in it. ItвЂ™s all Katerina, it all
comes from her. She is this and that, and that means that I am not. He
tells me that beforehandвЂ”warns me. He is planning to throw me over, thatвЂ™s
the whole secret. TheyвЂ™ve planned it together, the three of themвЂ”Mitya,
Katerina, and Ivan Fyodorovitch. Alyosha, IвЂ™ve been wanting to ask you a
long time. A week ago he suddenly told me that Ivan was in love with
Katerina, because he often goes to see her. Did he tell me the truth or
not? Tell me, on your conscience, tell me the worst.вЂќ

вЂњI wonвЂ™t tell you a lie. Ivan is not in love with Katerina Ivanovna, I
think.вЂќ

вЂњOh, thatвЂ™s what I thought! He is lying to me, shameless deceiver, thatвЂ™s
what it is! And he was jealous of me just now, so as to put the blame on
me afterwards. He is stupid, he canвЂ™t disguise what he is doing; he is so
open, you know.... But IвЂ™ll give it to him, IвЂ™ll give it to him! вЂYou
believe I did it,вЂ™ he said. He said that to me, to me. He reproached me
with that! God forgive him! You wait, IвЂ™ll make it hot for Katerina at the
trial! IвЂ™ll just say a word then ... IвЂ™ll tell everything then!вЂќ

And again she cried bitterly.

вЂњThis I can tell you for certain, Grushenka,вЂќ Alyosha said, getting up.
вЂњFirst, that he loves you, loves you more than any one in the world, and
you only, believe me. I know. I do know. The second thing is that I donвЂ™t
want to worm his secret out of him, but if heвЂ™ll tell me of himself toвЂђ
day, I shall tell him straight out that I have promised to tell you. Then
IвЂ™ll come to you toвЂђday, and tell you. Only ... I fancy ... Katerina
Ivanovna has nothing to do with it, and that the secret is about something
else. ThatвЂ™s certain. It isnвЂ™t likely itвЂ™s about Katerina Ivanovna, it
seems to me. GoodвЂђby for now.вЂќ

Alyosha shook hands with her. Grushenka was still crying. He saw that she
put little faith in his consolation, but she was better for having had her
sorrow out, for having spoken of it. He was sorry to leave her in such a
state of mind, but he was in haste. He had a great many things to do
still.



Chapter II. The Injured Foot


The first of these things was at the house of Madame Hohlakov, and he
hurried there to get it over as quickly as possible and not be too late
for Mitya. Madame Hohlakov had been slightly ailing for the last three
weeks: her foot had for some reason swollen up, and though she was not in
bed, she lay all day halfвЂђreclining on the couch in her boudoir, in a
fascinating but decorous _dГ©shabillГ©_. Alyosha had once noted with
innocent amusement that, in spite of her illness, Madame Hohlakov had
begun to be rather dressyвЂ”topвЂђknots, ribbons, loose wrappers, had made
their appearance, and he had an inkling of the reason, though he dismissed
such ideas from his mind as frivolous. During the last two months the
young official, Perhotin, had become a regular visitor at the house.

Alyosha had not called for four days and he was in haste to go straight to
Lise, as it was with her he had to speak, for Lise had sent a maid to him
the previous day, specially asking him to come to her вЂњabout something
very important,вЂќ a request which, for certain reasons, had interest for
Alyosha. But while the maid went to take his name in to Lise, Madame
Hohlakov heard of his arrival from some one, and immediately sent to beg
him to come to her вЂњjust for one minute.вЂќ Alyosha reflected that it was
better to accede to the mammaвЂ™s request, or else she would be sending down
to LiseвЂ™s room every minute that he was there. Madame Hohlakov was lying
on a couch. She was particularly smartly dressed and was evidently in a
state of extreme nervous excitement. She greeted Alyosha with cries of
rapture.

вЂњItвЂ™s ages, ages, perfect ages since IвЂ™ve seen you! ItвЂ™s a whole weekвЂ”only
think of it! Ah, but you were here only four days ago, on Wednesday. You
have come to see Lise. IвЂ™m sure you meant to slip into her room on tiptoe,
without my hearing you. My dear, dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, if you only
knew how worried I am about her! But of that later, though thatвЂ™s the most
important thing, of that later. Dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, I trust you
implicitly with my Lise. Since the death of Father ZossimaвЂ”God rest his
soul!вЂќ (she crossed herself)вЂ”вЂњI look upon you as a monk, though you look
charming in your new suit. Where did you find such a tailor in these
parts? No, no, thatвЂ™s not the chief thingвЂ”of that later. Forgive me for
sometimes calling you Alyosha; an old woman like me may take liberties,вЂќ
she smiled coquettishly; вЂњbut that will do later, too. The important thing
is that I shouldnвЂ™t forget what is important. Please remind me of it
yourself. As soon as my tongue runs away with me, you just say вЂthe
important thing?вЂ™ Ach! how do I know now what is of most importance? Ever
since Lise took back her promiseвЂ”her childish promise, Alexey
FyodorovitchвЂ”to marry you, youвЂ™ve realized, of course, that it was only
the playful fancy of a sick child who had been so long confined to her
chairвЂ”thank God, she can walk now!... that new doctor Katya sent for from
Moscow for your unhappy brother, who will toвЂђmorrowвЂ”But why speak of toвЂђ
morrow? I am ready to die at the very thought of toвЂђmorrow. Ready to die
of curiosity.... That doctor was with us yesterday and saw Lise.... I paid
him fifty roubles for the visit. But thatвЂ™s not the point, thatвЂ™s not the
point again. You see, IвЂ™m mixing everything up. I am in such a hurry. Why
am I in a hurry? I donвЂ™t understand. ItвЂ™s awful how I seem growing unable
to understand anything. Everything seems mixed up in a sort of tangle. I
am afraid you are so bored you will jump up and run away, and that will be
all I shall see of you. Goodness! Why are we sitting here and no coffee?
Yulia, Glafira, coffee!вЂќ

Alyosha made haste to thank her, and said that he had only just had
coffee.

вЂњWhere?вЂќ

вЂњAt Agrafena AlexandrovnaвЂ™s.вЂќ

вЂњAt ... at that womanвЂ™s? Ah, itвЂ™s she has brought ruin on every one. I
know nothing about it though. They say she has become a saint, though itвЂ™s
rather late in the day. She had better have done it before. What use is it
now? Hush, hush, Alexey Fyodorovitch, for I have so much to say to you
that I am afraid I shall tell you nothing. This awful trial ... I shall
certainly go, I am making arrangements. I shall be carried there in my
chair; besides I can sit up. I shall have people with me. And, you know, I
am a witness. How shall I speak, how shall I speak? I donвЂ™t know what I
shall say. One has to take an oath, hasnвЂ™t one?вЂќ

вЂњYes; but I donвЂ™t think you will be able to go.вЂќ

вЂњI can sit up. Ah, you put me out! Ah! this trial, this savage act, and
then they are all going to Siberia, some are getting married, and all this
so quickly, so quickly, everythingвЂ™s changing, and at lastвЂ”nothing. All
grow old and have death to look forward to. Well, so be it! I am weary.
This Katya, _cette charmante personne_, has disappointed all my hopes. Now
she is going to follow one of your brothers to Siberia, and your other
brother is going to follow her, and will live in the nearest town, and
they will all torment one another. It drives me out of my mind. Worst of
allвЂ”the publicity. The story has been told a million times over in all the
papers in Moscow and Petersburg. Ah! yes, would you believe it, thereвЂ™s a
paragraph that I was вЂa dear friendвЂ™ of your brotherвЂ™s вЂ”вЂ”, I canвЂ™t repeat
the horrid word. Just fancy, just fancy!вЂќ

вЂњImpossible! Where was the paragraph? What did it say?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll show you directly. I got the paper and read it yesterday. Here, in
the Petersburg paper _Gossip_. The paper began coming out this year. I am
awfully fond of gossip, and I take it in, and now it pays me outвЂ”this is
what gossip comes to! Here it is, here, this passage. Read it.вЂќ

And she handed Alyosha a sheet of newspaper which had been under her
pillow.

It was not exactly that she was upset, she seemed overwhelmed and perhaps
everything really was mixed up in a tangle in her head. The paragraph was
very typical, and must have been a great shock to her, but, fortunately
perhaps, she was unable to keep her mind fixed on any one subject at that
moment, and so might race off in a minute to something else and quite
forget the newspaper.

Alyosha was well aware that the story of the terrible case had spread all
over Russia. And, good heavens! what wild rumors about his brother, about
the Karamazovs, and about himself he had read in the course of those two
months, among other equally credible items! One paper had even stated that
he had gone into a monastery and become a monk, in horror at his brotherвЂ™s
crime. Another contradicted this, and stated that he and his elder, Father
Zossima, had broken into the monastery chest and вЂњmade tracks from the
monastery.вЂќ The present paragraph in the paper _Gossip_ was under the
heading, вЂњThe Karamazov Case at Skotoprigonyevsk.вЂќ (That, alas! was the
name of our little town. I had hitherto kept it concealed.) It was brief,
and Madame Hohlakov was not directly mentioned in it. No names appeared,
in fact. It was merely stated that the criminal, whose approaching trial
was making such a sensationвЂ”retired army captain, an idle swaggerer, and
reactionary bullyвЂ”was continually involved in amorous intrigues, and
particularly popular with certain ladies вЂњwho were pining in solitude.вЂќ
One such lady, a pining widow, who tried to seem young though she had a
grownвЂђup daughter, was so fascinated by him that only two hours before the
crime she offered him three thousand roubles, on condition that he would
elope with her to the gold mines. But the criminal, counting on escaping
punishment, had preferred to murder his father to get the three thousand
rather than go off to Siberia with the middleвЂђaged charms of his pining
lady. This playful paragraph finished, of course, with an outburst of
generous indignation at the wickedness of parricide and at the lately
abolished institution of serfdom. Reading it with curiosity, Alyosha
folded up the paper and handed it back to Madame Hohlakov.

вЂњWell, that must be me,вЂќ she hurried on again. вЂњOf course I am meant.
Scarcely more than an hour before, I suggested gold mines to him, and here
they talk of вЂmiddleвЂђaged charmsвЂ™ as though that were my motive! He writes
that out of spite! God Almighty forgive him for the middleвЂђaged charms, as
I forgive him! You know itвЂ™sвЂ” Do you know who it is? ItвЂ™s your friend
Rakitin.вЂќ

вЂњPerhaps,вЂќ said Alyosha, вЂњthough IвЂ™ve heard nothing about it.вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s he, itвЂ™s he! No вЂperhapsвЂ™ about it. You know I turned him out of the
house.... You know all that story, donвЂ™t you?вЂќ

вЂњI know that you asked him not to visit you for the future, but why it
was, I havenвЂ™t heard ... from you, at least.вЂќ

вЂњAh, then youвЂ™ve heard it from him! He abuses me, I suppose, abuses me
dreadfully?вЂќ

вЂњYes, he does; but then he abuses every one. But why youвЂ™ve given him up I
havenвЂ™t heard from him either. I meet him very seldom now, indeed. We are
not friends.вЂќ

вЂњWell, then, IвЂ™ll tell you all about it. ThereвЂ™s no help for it, IвЂ™ll
confess, for there is one point in which I was perhaps to blame. Only a
little, little point, so little that perhaps it doesnвЂ™t count. You see, my
dear boyвЂќвЂ”Madame Hohlakov suddenly looked arch and a charming, though
enigmatic, smile played about her lipsвЂ”вЂњyou see, I suspect ... You must
forgive me, Alyosha. I am like a mother to you.... No, no; quite the
contrary. I speak to you now as though you were my fatherвЂ”motherвЂ™s quite
out of place. Well, itвЂ™s as though I were confessing to Father Zossima,
thatвЂ™s just it. I called you a monk just now. Well, that poor young man,
your friend, Rakitin (Mercy on us! I canвЂ™t be angry with him. I feel
cross, but not very), that frivolous young man, would you believe it,
seems to have taken it into his head to fall in love with me. I only
noticed it later. At firstвЂ”a month agoвЂ”he only began to come oftener to
see me, almost every day; though, of course, we were acquainted before. I
knew nothing about it ... and suddenly it dawned upon me, and I began to
notice things with surprise. You know, two months ago, that modest,
charming, excellent young man, Pyotr Ilyitch Perhotin, whoвЂ™s in the
service here, began to be a regular visitor at the house. You met him here
ever so many times yourself. And he is an excellent, earnest young man,
isnвЂ™t he? He comes once every three days, not every day (though I should
be glad to see him every day), and always so well dressed. Altogether, I
love young people, Alyosha, talented, modest, like you, and he has almost
the mind of a statesman, he talks so charmingly, and I shall certainly,
certainly try and get promotion for him. He is a future diplomat. On that
awful day he almost saved me from death by coming in the night. And your
friend Rakitin comes in such boots, and always stretches them out on the
carpet.... He began hinting at his feelings, in fact, and one day, as he
was going, he squeezed my hand terribly hard. My foot began to swell
directly after he pressed my hand like that. He had met Pyotr Ilyitch here
before, and would you believe it, he is always gibing at him, growling at
him, for some reason. I simply looked at the way they went on together and
laughed inwardly. So I was sitting here aloneвЂ”no, I was laid up then.
Well, I was lying here alone and suddenly Rakitin comes in, and only
fancy! brought me some verses of his own compositionвЂ”a short poem, on my
bad foot: that is, he described my foot in a poem. Wait a minuteвЂ”how did
it go?


    A captivating little foot.


It began somehow like that. I can never remember poetry. IвЂ™ve got it here.
IвЂ™ll show it to you later. But itвЂ™s a charming thingвЂ”charming; and, you
know, itвЂ™s not only about the foot, it had a good moral, too, a charming
idea, only IвЂ™ve forgotten it; in fact, it was just the thing for an album.
So, of course, I thanked him, and he was evidently flattered. IвЂ™d hardly
had time to thank him when in comes Pyotr Ilyitch, and Rakitin suddenly
looked as black as night. I could see that Pyotr Ilyitch was in the way,
for Rakitin certainly wanted to say something after giving me the verses.
I had a presentiment of it; but Pyotr Ilyitch came in. I showed Pyotr
Ilyitch the verses and didnвЂ™t say who was the author. But I am convinced
that he guessed, though he wonвЂ™t own it to this day, and declares he had
no idea. But he says that on purpose. Pyotr Ilyitch began to laugh at
once, and fell to criticizing it. вЂWretched doggerel,вЂ™ he said they were,
вЂsome divinity student must have written them,вЂ™ and with such vehemence,
such vehemence! Then, instead of laughing, your friend flew into a rage.
вЂGood gracious!вЂ™ I thought, вЂtheyвЂ™ll fly at each other.вЂ™ вЂIt was I who
wrote them,вЂ™ said he. вЂI wrote them as a joke,вЂ™ he said, вЂfor I think it
degrading to write verses.... But they are good poetry. They want to put a
monument to your Pushkin for writing about womenвЂ™s feet, while I wrote
with a moral purpose, and you,вЂ™ said he, вЂare an advocate of serfdom.
YouвЂ™ve no humane ideas,вЂ™ said he. вЂYou have no modern enlightened
feelings, you are uninfluenced by progress, you are a mere official,вЂ™ he
said, вЂand you take bribes.вЂ™ Then I began screaming and imploring them.
And, you know, Pyotr Ilyitch is anything but a coward. He at once took up
the most gentlemanly tone, looked at him sarcastically, listened, and
apologized. вЂIвЂ™d no idea,вЂ™ said he. вЂI shouldnвЂ™t have said it, if I had
known. I should have praised it. Poets are all so irritable,вЂ™ he said. In
short, he laughed at him under cover of the most gentlemanly tone. He
explained to me afterwards that it was all sarcastic. I thought he was in
earnest. Only as I lay there, just as before you now, I thought, вЂWould
it, or would it not, be the proper thing for me to turn Rakitin out for
shouting so rudely at a visitor in my house?вЂ™ And, would you believe it, I
lay here, shut my eyes, and wondered, would it be the proper thing or not.
I kept worrying and worrying, and my heart began to beat, and I couldnвЂ™t
make up my mind whether to make an outcry or not. One voice seemed to be
telling me, вЂSpeak,вЂ™ and the other вЂNo, donвЂ™t speak.вЂ™ And no sooner had
the second voice said that than I cried out, and fainted. Of course, there
was a fuss. I got up suddenly and said to Rakitin, вЂItвЂ™s painful for me to
say it, but I donвЂ™t wish to see you in my house again.вЂ™ So I turned him
out. Ah! Alexey Fyodorovitch, I know myself I did wrong. I was putting it
on. I wasnвЂ™t angry with him at all, really; but I suddenly fanciedвЂ”that
was what did itвЂ”that it would be such a fine scene.... And yet, believe
me, it was quite natural, for I really shed tears and cried for several
days afterwards, and then suddenly, one afternoon, I forgot all about it.
So itвЂ™s a fortnight since heвЂ™s been here, and I kept wondering whether he
would come again. I wondered even yesterday, then suddenly last night came
this _Gossip_. I read it and gasped. Who could have written it? He must
have written it. He went home, sat down, wrote it on the spot, sent it,
and they put it in. It was a fortnight ago, you see. But, Alyosha, itвЂ™s
awful how I keep talking and donвЂ™t say what I want to say. Ah! the words
come of themselves!вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s very important for me to be in time to see my brother toвЂђday,вЂќ
Alyosha faltered.

вЂњTo be sure, to be sure! You bring it all back to me. Listen, what is an
aberration?вЂќ

вЂњWhat aberration?вЂќ asked Alyosha, wondering.

вЂњIn the legal sense. An aberration in which everything is pardonable.
Whatever you do, you will be acquitted at once.вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you mean?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ll tell you. This Katya ... Ah! she is a charming, charming creature,
only I never can make out who it is she is in love with. She was with me
some time ago and I couldnвЂ™t get anything out of her. Especially as she
wonвЂ™t talk to me except on the surface now. She is always talking about my
health and nothing else, and she takes up such a tone with me, too. I
simply said to myself, вЂWell, so be it. I donвЂ™t careвЂ™... Oh, yes. I was
talking of aberration. This doctor has come. You know a doctor has come?
Of course, you know itвЂ”the one who discovers madmen. You wrote for him.
No, it wasnвЂ™t you, but Katya. ItвЂ™s all KatyaвЂ™s doing. Well, you see, a man
may be sitting perfectly sane and suddenly have an aberration. He may be
conscious and know what he is doing and yet be in a state of aberration.
And thereвЂ™s no doubt that Dmitri Fyodorovitch was suffering from
aberration. They found out about aberration as soon as the law courts were
reformed. ItвЂ™s all the good effect of the reformed law courts. The doctor
has been here and questioned me about that evening, about the gold mines.
вЂHow did he seem then?вЂ™ he asked me. He must have been in a state of
aberration. He came in shouting, вЂMoney, money, three thousand! Give me
three thousand!вЂ™ and then went away and immediately did the murder. вЂI
donвЂ™t want to murder him,вЂ™ he said, and he suddenly went and murdered him.
ThatвЂ™s why theyвЂ™ll acquit him, because he struggled against it and yet he
murdered him.вЂќ

вЂњBut he didnвЂ™t murder him,вЂќ Alyosha interrupted rather sharply. He felt
more and more sick with anxiety and impatience.

вЂњYes, I know it was that old man Grigory murdered him.вЂќ

вЂњGrigory?вЂќ cried Alyosha.

вЂњYes, yes; it was Grigory. He lay as Dmitri Fyodorovitch struck him down,
and then got up, saw the door open, went in and killed Fyodor Pavlovitch.вЂќ

вЂњBut why, why?вЂќ

вЂњSuffering from aberration. When he recovered from the blow Dmitri
Fyodorovitch gave him on the head, he was suffering from aberration; he
went and committed the murder. As for his saying he didnвЂ™t, he very likely
doesnвЂ™t remember. Only, you know, itвЂ™ll be better, ever so much better, if
Dmitri Fyodorovitch murdered him. And thatвЂ™s how it must have been, though
I say it was Grigory. It certainly was Dmitri Fyodorovitch, and thatвЂ™s
better, ever so much better! Oh! not better that a son should have killed
his father, I donвЂ™t defend that. Children ought to honor their parents,
and yet it would be better if it were he, as youвЂ™d have nothing to cry
over then, for he did it when he was unconscious or rather when he was
conscious, but did not know what he was doing. Let them acquit himвЂ”thatвЂ™s
so humane, and would show what a blessing reformed law courts are. I knew
nothing about it, but they say they have been so a long time. And when I
heard it yesterday, I was so struck by it that I wanted to send for you at
once. And if he is acquitted, make him come straight from the law courts
to dinner with me, and IвЂ™ll have a party of friends, and weвЂ™ll drink to
the reformed law courts. I donвЂ™t believe heвЂ™d be dangerous; besides, IвЂ™ll
invite a great many friends, so that he could always be led out if he did
anything. And then he might be made a justice of the peace or something in
another town, for those who have been in trouble themselves make the best
judges. And, besides, who isnвЂ™t suffering from aberration nowadays?вЂ”you,
I, all of us are in a state of aberration, and there are ever so many
examples of it: a man sits singing a song, suddenly something annoys him,
he takes a pistol and shoots the first person he comes across, and no one
blames him for it. I read that lately, and all the doctors confirm it. The
doctors are always confirming; they confirm anything. Why, my Lise is in a
state of aberration. She made me cry again yesterday, and the day before,
too, and toвЂђday I suddenly realized that itвЂ™s all due to aberration. Oh,
Lise grieves me so! I believe sheвЂ™s quite mad. Why did she send for you?
Did she send for you or did you come of yourself?вЂќ

вЂњYes, she sent for me, and I am just going to her.вЂќ Alyosha got up
resolutely.

вЂњOh, my dear, dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, perhaps thatвЂ™s whatвЂ™s most
important,вЂќ Madame Hohlakov cried, suddenly bursting into tears. вЂњGod
knows I trust Lise to you with all my heart, and itвЂ™s no matter her
sending for you on the sly, without telling her mother. But forgive me, I
canвЂ™t trust my daughter so easily to your brother Ivan Fyodorovitch,
though I still consider him the most chivalrous young man. But only fancy,
heвЂ™s been to see Lise and I knew nothing about it!вЂќ

вЂњHow? What? When?вЂќ Alyosha was exceedingly surprised. He had not sat down
again and listened standing.

вЂњI will tell you; thatвЂ™s perhaps why I asked you to come, for I donвЂ™t know
now why I did ask you to come. Well, Ivan Fyodorovitch has been to see me
twice, since he came back from Moscow. First time he came as a friend to
call on me, and the second time Katya was here and he came because he
heard she was here. I didnвЂ™t, of course, expect him to come often, knowing
what a lot he has to do as it is, _vous comprenez, cette affaire et la
mort terrible de votre papa_. But I suddenly heard heвЂ™d been here again,
not to see me but to see Lise. ThatвЂ™s six days ago now. He came, stayed
five minutes, and went away. And I didnвЂ™t hear of it till three days
afterwards, from Glafira, so it was a great shock to me. I sent for Lise
directly. She laughed. вЂHe thought you were asleep,вЂ™ she said, вЂand came
in to me to ask after your health.вЂ™ Of course, thatвЂ™s how it happened. But
Lise, Lise, mercy on us, how she distresses me! Would you believe it, one
night, four days ago, just after you saw her last time, and had gone away,
she suddenly had a fit, screaming, shrieking, hysterics! Why is it I never
have hysterics? Then, next day another fit, and the same thing on the
third, and yesterday too, and then yesterday that aberration. She suddenly
screamed out, вЂI hate Ivan Fyodorovitch. I insist on your never letting
him come to the house again.вЂ™ I was struck dumb at these amazing words,
and answered, вЂOn what grounds could I refuse to see such an excellent
young man, a young man of such learning too, and so unfortunate?вЂ™вЂ”for all
this business is a misfortune, isnвЂ™t it? She suddenly burst out laughing
at my words, and so rudely, you know. Well, I was pleased; I thought I had
amused her and the fits would pass off, especially as I wanted to refuse
to see Ivan Fyodorovitch anyway on account of his strange visits without
my knowledge, and meant to ask him for an explanation. But early this
morning Lise waked up and flew into a passion with Yulia and, would you
believe it, slapped her in the face. ThatвЂ™s monstrous; I am always polite
to my servants. And an hour later she was hugging YuliaвЂ™s feet and kissing
them. She sent a message to me that she wasnвЂ™t coming to me at all, and
would never come and see me again, and when I dragged myself down to her,
she rushed to kiss me, crying, and as she kissed me, she pushed me out of
the room without saying a word, so I couldnвЂ™t find out what was the
matter. Now, dear Alexey Fyodorovitch, I rest all my hopes on you, and, of
course, my whole life is in your hands. I simply beg you to go to Lise and
find out everything from her, as you alone can, and come back and tell
meвЂ”me, her mother, for you understand it will be the death of me, simply
the death of me, if this goes on, or else I shall run away. I can stand no
more. I have patience; but I may lose patience, and then ... then
something awful will happen. Ah, dear me! At last, Pyotr Ilyitch!вЂќ cried
Madame Hohlakov, beaming all over as she saw Perhotin enter the room. вЂњYou
are late, you are late! Well, sit down, speak, put us out of suspense.
What does the counsel say. Where are you off to, Alexey Fyodorovitch?вЂќ

вЂњTo Lise.вЂќ

вЂњOh, yes. You wonвЂ™t forget, you wonвЂ™t forget what I asked you? ItвЂ™s a
question of life and death!вЂќ

вЂњOf course, I wonвЂ™t forget, if I can ... but I am so late,вЂќ muttered
Alyosha, beating a hasty retreat.

вЂњNo, be sure, be sure to come in; donвЂ™t say вЂIf you can.вЂ™ I shall die if
you donвЂ™t,вЂќ Madame Hohlakov called after him, but Alyosha had already left
the room.



Chapter III. A Little Demon


Going in to Lise, he found her half reclining in the invalidвЂђchair, in
which she had been wheeled when she was unable to walk. She did not move
to meet him, but her sharp, keen eyes were simply riveted on his face.
There was a feverish look in her eyes, her face was pale and yellow.
Alyosha was amazed at the change that had taken place in her in three
days. She was positively thinner. She did not hold out her hand to him. He
touched the thin, long fingers which lay motionless on her dress, then he
sat down facing her, without a word.

вЂњI know you are in a hurry to get to the prison,вЂќ Lise said curtly, вЂњand
mammaвЂ™s kept you there for hours; sheвЂ™s just been telling you about me and
Yulia.вЂќ

вЂњHow do you know?вЂќ asked Alyosha.

вЂњIвЂ™ve been listening. Why do you stare at me? I want to listen and I do
listen, thereвЂ™s no harm in that. I donвЂ™t apologize.вЂќ

вЂњYou are upset about something?вЂќ

вЂњOn the contrary, I am very happy. IвЂ™ve only just been reflecting for the
thirtieth time what a good thing it is I refused you and shall not be your
wife. You are not fit to be a husband. If I were to marry you and give you
a note to take to the man I loved after you, youвЂ™d take it and be sure to
give it to him and bring an answer back, too. If you were forty, you would
still go on taking my loveвЂђletters for me.вЂќ

She suddenly laughed.

вЂњThere is something spiteful and yet openвЂђhearted about you,вЂќ Alyosha
smiled to her.

вЂњThe openвЂђheartedness consists in my not being ashamed of myself with you.
WhatвЂ™s more, I donвЂ™t want to feel ashamed with you, just with you.
Alyosha, why is it I donвЂ™t respect you? I am very fond of you, but I donвЂ™t
respect you. If I respected you, I shouldnвЂ™t talk to you without shame,
should I?вЂќ

вЂњNo.вЂќ

вЂњBut do you believe that I am not ashamed with you?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I donвЂ™t believe it.вЂќ

Lise laughed nervously again; she spoke rapidly.

вЂњI sent your brother, Dmitri Fyodorovitch, some sweets in prison. Alyosha,
you know, you are quite pretty! I shall love you awfully for having so
quickly allowed me not to love you.вЂќ

вЂњWhy did you send for me toвЂђday, Lise?вЂќ

вЂњI wanted to tell you of a longing I have. I should like some one to
torture me, marry me and then torture me, deceive me and go away. I donвЂ™t
want to be happy.вЂќ

вЂњYou are in love with disorder?вЂќ

вЂњYes, I want disorder. I keep wanting to set fire to the house. I keep
imagining how IвЂ™ll creep up and set fire to the house on the sly; it must
be on the sly. TheyвЂ™ll try to put it out, but itвЂ™ll go on burning. And I
shall know and say nothing. Ah, what silliness! And how bored I am!вЂќ

She waved her hand with a look of repulsion.

вЂњItвЂ™s your luxurious life,вЂќ said Alyosha, softly.

вЂњIs it better, then, to be poor?вЂќ

вЂњYes, it is better.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s what your monk taught you. ThatвЂ™s not true. Let me be rich and all
the rest poor, IвЂ™ll eat sweets and drink cream and not give any to any one
else. Ach, donвЂ™t speak, donвЂ™t say anything,вЂќ she shook her hand at him,
though Alyosha had not opened his mouth. вЂњYouвЂ™ve told me all that before,
I know it all by heart. It bores me. If I am ever poor, I shall murder
somebody, and even if I am rich, I may murder some one, perhapsвЂ”why do
nothing! But do you know, I should like to reap, cut the rye? IвЂ™ll marry
you, and you shall become a peasant, a real peasant; weвЂ™ll keep a colt,
shall we? Do you know Kalganov?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњHe is always wandering about, dreaming. He says, вЂWhy live in real life?
ItвЂ™s better to dream. One can dream the most delightful things, but real
life is a bore.вЂ™ But heвЂ™ll be married soon for all that; heвЂ™s been making
love to me already. Can you spin tops?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњWell, heвЂ™s just like a top: he wants to be wound up and set spinning and
then to be lashed, lashed, lashed with a whip. If I marry him, IвЂ™ll keep
him spinning all his life. You are not ashamed to be with me?вЂќ

вЂњNo.вЂќ

вЂњYou are awfully cross, because I donвЂ™t talk about holy things. I donвЂ™t
want to be holy. What will they do to one in the next world for the
greatest sin? You must know all about that.вЂќ

вЂњGod will censure you.вЂќ Alyosha was watching her steadily.

вЂњThatвЂ™s just what I should like. I would go up and they would censure me,
and I would burst out laughing in their faces. I should dreadfully like to
set fire to the house, Alyosha, to our house; you still donвЂ™t believe me?вЂќ

вЂњWhy? There are children of twelve years old, who have a longing to set
fire to something and they do set things on fire, too. ItвЂ™s a sort of
disease.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s not true, thatвЂ™s not true; there may be children, but thatвЂ™s not
what I mean.вЂќ

вЂњYou take evil for good; itвЂ™s a passing crisis, itвЂ™s the result of your
illness, perhaps.вЂќ

вЂњYou do despise me, though! ItвЂ™s simply that I donвЂ™t want to do good, I
want to do evil, and it has nothing to do with illness.вЂќ

вЂњWhy do evil?вЂќ

вЂњSo that everything might be destroyed. Ah, how nice it would be if
everything were destroyed! You know, Alyosha, I sometimes think of doing a
fearful lot of harm and everything bad, and I should do it for a long
while on the sly and suddenly every one would find it out. Every one will
stand round and point their fingers at me and I would look at them all.
That would be awfully nice. Why would it be so nice, Alyosha?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know. ItвЂ™s a craving to destroy something good or, as you say, to
set fire to something. It happens sometimes.вЂќ

вЂњI not only say it, I shall do it.вЂќ

вЂњI believe you.вЂќ

вЂњAh, how I love you for saying you believe me. And you are not lying one
little bit. But perhaps you think that I am saying all this on purpose to
annoy you?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I donвЂ™t think that ... though perhaps there is a little desire to do
that in it, too.вЂќ

вЂњThere is a little. I never can tell lies to you,вЂќ she declared, with a
strange fire in her eyes.

What struck Alyosha above everything was her earnestness. There was not a
trace of humor or jesting in her face now, though, in old days, fun and
gayety never deserted her even at her most вЂњearnestвЂќ moments.

вЂњThere are moments when people love crime,вЂќ said Alyosha thoughtfully.

вЂњYes, yes! You have uttered my thought; they love crime, every one loves
crime, they love it always, not at some вЂmoments.вЂ™ You know, itвЂ™s as
though people have made an agreement to lie about it and have lied about
it ever since. They all declare that they hate evil, but secretly they all
love it.вЂќ

вЂњAnd are you still reading nasty books?вЂќ

вЂњYes, I am. Mamma reads them and hides them under her pillow and I steal
them.вЂќ

вЂњArenвЂ™t you ashamed to destroy yourself?вЂќ

вЂњI want to destroy myself. ThereвЂ™s a boy here, who lay down between the
railway lines when the train was passing. Lucky fellow! Listen, your
brother is being tried now for murdering his father and every one loves
his having killed his father.вЂќ

вЂњLoves his having killed his father?вЂќ

вЂњYes, loves it; every one loves it! Everybody says itвЂ™s so awful, but
secretly they simply love it. I for one love it.вЂќ

вЂњThere is some truth in what you say about every one,вЂќ said Alyosha
softly.

вЂњOh, what ideas you have!вЂќ Lise shrieked in delight. вЂњAnd you a monk, too!
You wouldnвЂ™t believe how I respect you, Alyosha, for never telling lies.
Oh, I must tell you a funny dream of mine. I sometimes dream of devils.
ItвЂ™s night; I am in my room with a candle and suddenly there are devils
all over the place, in all the corners, under the table, and they open the
doors; thereвЂ™s a crowd of them behind the doors and they want to come and
seize me. And they are just coming, just seizing me. But I suddenly cross
myself and they all draw back, though they donвЂ™t go away altogether, they
stand at the doors and in the corners, waiting. And suddenly I have a
frightful longing to revile God aloud, and so I begin, and then they come
crowding back to me, delighted, and seize me again and I cross myself
again and they all draw back. ItвЂ™s awful fun. it takes oneвЂ™s breath away.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ve had the same dream, too,вЂќ said Alyosha suddenly.

вЂњReally?вЂќ cried Lise, surprised. вЂњI say, Alyosha, donвЂ™t laugh, thatвЂ™s
awfully important. Could two different people have the same dream?вЂќ

вЂњIt seems they can.вЂќ

вЂњAlyosha, I tell you, itвЂ™s awfully important,вЂќ Lise went on, with really
excessive amazement. вЂњItвЂ™s not the dream thatвЂ™s important, but your having
the same dream as me. You never lie to me, donвЂ™t lie now: is it true? You
are not laughing?вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s true.вЂќ

Lise seemed extraordinarily impressed and for half a minute she was
silent.

вЂњAlyosha, come and see me, come and see me more often,вЂќ she said suddenly,
in a supplicating voice.

вЂњIвЂ™ll always come to see you, all my life,вЂќ answered Alyosha firmly.

вЂњYou are the only person I can talk to, you know,вЂќ Lise began again. вЂњI
talk to no one but myself and you. Only you in the whole world. And to you
more readily than to myself. And I am not a bit ashamed with you, not a
bit. Alyosha, why am I not ashamed with you, not a bit? Alyosha, is it
true that at Easter the Jews steal a child and kill it?вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t know.вЂќ

вЂњThereвЂ™s a book here in which I read about the trial of a Jew, who took a
child of four years old and cut off the fingers from both hands, and then
crucified him on the wall, hammered nails into him and crucified him, and
afterwards, when he was tried, he said that the child died soon, within
four hours. That was вЂsoonвЂ™! He said the child moaned, kept on moaning and
he stood admiring it. ThatвЂ™s nice!вЂќ

вЂњNice?вЂќ

вЂњNice; I sometimes imagine that it was I who crucified him. He would hang
there moaning and I would sit opposite him eating pineapple _compote_. I
am awfully fond of pineapple _compote_. Do you like it?вЂќ

Alyosha looked at her in silence. Her pale, sallow face was suddenly
contorted, her eyes burned.

вЂњYou know, when I read about that Jew I shook with sobs all night. I kept
fancying how the little thing cried and moaned (a child of four years old
understands, you know), and all the while the thought of pineapple
_compote_ haunted me. In the morning I wrote a letter to a certain person,
begging him _particularly_ to come and see me. He came and I suddenly told
him all about the child and the pineapple _compote_. _All_ about it,
_all_, and said that it was nice. He laughed and said it really was nice.
Then he got up and went away. He was only here five minutes. Did he
despise me? Did he despise me? Tell me, tell me, Alyosha, did he despise
me or not?вЂќ She sat up on the couch, with flashing eyes.

вЂњTell me,вЂќ Alyosha asked anxiously, вЂњdid you send for that person?вЂќ

вЂњYes, I did.вЂќ

вЂњDid you send him a letter?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњSimply to ask about that, about that child?вЂќ

вЂњNo, not about that at all. But when he came, I asked him about that at
once. He answered, laughed, got up and went away.вЂќ

вЂњThat person behaved honorably,вЂќ Alyosha murmured.

вЂњAnd did he despise me? Did he laugh at me?вЂќ

вЂњNo, for perhaps he believes in the pineapple _compote_ himself. He is
very ill now, too, Lise.вЂќ

вЂњYes, he does believe in it,вЂќ said Lise, with flashing eyes.

вЂњHe doesnвЂ™t despise any one,вЂќ Alyosha went on. вЂњOnly he does not believe
any one. If he doesnвЂ™t believe in people, of course, he does despise
them.вЂќ

вЂњThen he despises me, me?вЂќ

вЂњYou, too.вЂќ

вЂњGood,вЂќ Lise seemed to grind her teeth. вЂњWhen he went out laughing, I felt
that it was nice to be despised. The child with fingers cut off is nice,
and to be despised is nice....вЂќ

And she laughed in AlyoshaвЂ™s face, a feverish malicious laugh.

вЂњDo you know, Alyosha, do you know, I should likeвЂ”Alyosha, save me!вЂќ She
suddenly jumped from the couch, rushed to him and seized him with both
hands. вЂњSave me!вЂќ she almost groaned. вЂњIs there any one in the world I
could tell what IвЂ™ve told you? IвЂ™ve told you the truth, the truth. I shall
kill myself, because I loathe everything! I donвЂ™t want to live, because I
loathe everything! I loathe everything, everything. Alyosha, why donвЂ™t you
love me in the least?вЂќ she finished in a frenzy.

вЂњBut I do love you!вЂќ answered Alyosha warmly.

вЂњAnd will you weep over me, will you?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњNot because I wonвЂ™t be your wife, but simply weep for me?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњThank you! ItвЂ™s only your tears I want. Every one else may punish me and
trample me under foot, every one, every one, not excepting _any one_. For
I donвЂ™t love any one. Do you hear, not any one! On the contrary, I hate
him! Go, Alyosha; itвЂ™s time you went to your brotherвЂќ; she tore herself
away from him suddenly.

вЂњHow can I leave you like this?вЂќ said Alyosha, almost in alarm.

вЂњGo to your brother, the prison will be shut; go, hereвЂ™s your hat. Give my
love to Mitya, go, go!вЂќ

And she almost forcibly pushed Alyosha out of the door. He looked at her
with pained surprise, when he was suddenly aware of a letter in his right
hand, a tiny letter folded up tight and sealed. He glanced at it and
instantly read the address, вЂњTo Ivan Fyodorovitch Karamazov.вЂќ He looked
quickly at Lise. Her face had become almost menacing.

вЂњGive it to him, you must give it to him!вЂќ she ordered him, trembling and
beside herself. вЂњToвЂђday, at once, or IвЂ™ll poison myself! ThatвЂ™s why I sent
for you.вЂќ

And she slammed the door quickly. The bolt clicked. Alyosha put the note
in his pocket and went straight downstairs, without going back to Madame
Hohlakov; forgetting her, in fact. As soon as Alyosha had gone, Lise
unbolted the door, opened it a little, put her finger in the crack and
slammed the door with all her might, pinching her finger. Ten seconds
after, releasing her finger, she walked softly, slowly to her chair, sat
up straight in it and looked intently at her blackened finger and at the
blood that oozed from under the nail. Her lips were quivering and she kept
whispering rapidly to herself:

вЂњI am a wretch, wretch, wretch, wretch!вЂќ



Chapter IV. A Hymn And A Secret


It was quite late (days are short in November) when Alyosha rang at the
prison gate. It was beginning to get dusk. But Alyosha knew that he would
be admitted without difficulty. Things were managed in our little town, as
everywhere else. At first, of course, on the conclusion of the preliminary
inquiry, relations and a few other persons could only obtain interviews
with Mitya by going through certain inevitable formalities. But later,
though the formalities were not relaxed, exceptions were made for some, at
least, of MityaвЂ™s visitors. So much so, that sometimes the interviews with
the prisoner in the room set aside for the purpose were practically
_tГЄteвЂђГ вЂђtГЄte_.

These exceptions, however, were few in number; only Grushenka, Alyosha and
Rakitin were treated like this. But the captain of the police, Mihail
Mihailovitch, was very favorably disposed to Grushenka. His abuse of her
at Mokroe weighed on the old manвЂ™s conscience, and when he learned the
whole story, he completely changed his view of her. And strange to say,
though he was firmly persuaded of his guilt, yet after Mitya was once in
prison, the old man came to take a more and more lenient view of him. вЂњHe
was a man of good heart, perhaps,вЂќ he thought, вЂњwho had come to grief from
drinking and dissipation.вЂќ His first horror had been succeeded by pity. As
for Alyosha, the police captain was very fond of him and had known him for
a long time. Rakitin, who had of late taken to coming very often to see
the prisoner, was one of the most intimate acquaintances of the вЂњpolice
captainвЂ™s young ladies,вЂќ as he called them, and was always hanging about
their house. He gave lessons in the house of the prison superintendent,
too, who, though scrupulous in the performance of his duties, was a kindвЂђ
hearted old man. Alyosha, again, had an intimate acquaintance of long
standing with the superintendent, who was fond of talking to him,
generally on sacred subjects. He respected Ivan Fyodorovitch, and stood in
awe of his opinion, though he was a great philosopher himself; вЂњselfвЂђ
taught,вЂќ of course. But Alyosha had an irresistible attraction for him.
During the last year the old man had taken to studying the Apocryphal
Gospels, and constantly talked over his impressions with his young friend.
He used to come and see him in the monastery and discussed for hours
together with him and with the monks. So even if Alyosha were late at the
prison, he had only to go to the superintendent and everything was made
easy. Besides, every one in the prison, down to the humblest warder, had
grown used to Alyosha. The sentry, of course, did not trouble him so long
as the authorities were satisfied.

When Mitya was summoned from his cell, he always went downstairs, to the
place set aside for interviews. As Alyosha entered the room he came upon
Rakitin, who was just taking leave of Mitya. They were both talking
loudly. Mitya was laughing heartily as he saw him out, while Rakitin
seemed grumbling. Rakitin did not like meeting Alyosha, especially of
late. He scarcely spoke to him, and bowed to him stiffly. Seeing Alyosha
enter now, he frowned and looked away, as though he were entirely absorbed
in buttoning his big, warm, furвЂђtrimmed overcoat. Then he began looking at
once for his umbrella.

вЂњI must mind not to forget my belongings,вЂќ he muttered, simply to say
something.

вЂњMind you donвЂ™t forget other peopleвЂ™s belongings,вЂќ said Mitya, as a joke,
and laughed at once at his own wit. Rakitin fired up instantly.

вЂњYouвЂ™d better give that advice to your own family, whoвЂ™ve always been a
slaveвЂђdriving lot, and not to Rakitin,вЂќ he cried, suddenly trembling with
anger.

вЂњWhatвЂ™s the matter? I was joking,вЂќ cried Mitya. вЂњDamn it all! They are all
like that,вЂќ he turned to Alyosha, nodding towards RakitinвЂ™s hurriedly
retreating figure. вЂњHe was sitting here, laughing and cheerful, and all at
once he boils up like that. He didnвЂ™t even nod to you. Have you broken
with him completely? Why are you so late? IвЂ™ve not been simply waiting,
but thirsting for you the whole morning. But never mind. WeвЂ™ll make up for
it now.вЂќ

вЂњWhy does he come here so often? Surely you are not such great friends?вЂќ
asked Alyosha. He, too, nodded at the door through which Rakitin had
disappeared.

вЂњGreat friends with Rakitin? No, not as much as that. Is it likelyвЂ”a pig
like that? He considers I am ... a blackguard. They canвЂ™t understand a
joke either, thatвЂ™s the worst of such people. They never understand a
joke, and their souls are dry, dry and flat; they remind me of prison
walls when I was first brought here. But he is a clever fellow, very
clever. Well, Alexey, itвЂ™s all over with me now.вЂќ

He sat down on the bench and made Alyosha sit down beside him.

вЂњYes, the trialвЂ™s toвЂђmorrow. Are you so hopeless, brother?вЂќ Alyosha said,
with an apprehensive feeling.

вЂњWhat are you talking about?вЂќ said Mitya, looking at him rather
uncertainly. вЂњOh, you mean the trial! Damn it all! Till now weвЂ™ve been
talking of things that donвЂ™t matter, about this trial, but I havenвЂ™t said
a word to you about the chief thing. Yes, the trial is toвЂђmorrow; but it
wasnвЂ™t the trial I meant, when I said it was all over with me. Why do you
look at me so critically?вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you mean, Mitya?вЂќ

вЂњIdeas, ideas, thatвЂ™s all! Ethics! What is ethics?вЂќ

вЂњEthics?вЂќ asked Alyosha, wondering.

вЂњYes; is it a science?вЂќ

вЂњYes, there is such a science ... but ... I confess I canвЂ™t explain to you
what sort of science it is.вЂќ

вЂњRakitin knows. Rakitin knows a lot, damn him! HeвЂ™s not going to be a
monk. He means to go to Petersburg. There heвЂ™ll go in for criticism of an
elevating tendency. Who knows, he may be of use and make his own career,
too. Ough! they are firstвЂђrate, these people, at making a career! Damn
ethics, I am done for, Alexey, I am, you man of God! I love you more than
any one. It makes my heart yearn to look at you. Who was Karl Bernard?вЂќ

вЂњKarl Bernard?вЂќ Alyosha was surprised again.

вЂњNo, not Karl. Stay, I made a mistake. Claude Bernard. What was he?
Chemist or what?вЂќ

вЂњHe must be a savant,вЂќ answered Alyosha; вЂњbut I confess I canвЂ™t tell you
much about him, either. IвЂ™ve heard of him as a savant, but what sort I
donвЂ™t know.вЂќ

вЂњWell, damn him, then! I donвЂ™t know either,вЂќ swore Mitya. вЂњA scoundrel of
some sort, most likely. They are all scoundrels. And Rakitin will make his
way. Rakitin will get on anywhere; he is another Bernard. Ugh, these
Bernards! They are all over the place.вЂќ

вЂњBut what is the matter?вЂќ Alyosha asked insistently.

вЂњHe wants to write an article about me, about my case, and so begin his
literary career. ThatвЂ™s what he comes for; he said so himself. He wants to
prove some theory. He wants to say вЂhe couldnвЂ™t help murdering his father,
he was corrupted by his environment,вЂ™ and so on. He explained it all to
me. He is going to put in a tinge of Socialism, he says. But there, damn
the fellow, he can put in a tinge if he likes, I donвЂ™t care. He canвЂ™t bear
Ivan, he hates him. HeвЂ™s not fond of you, either. But I donвЂ™t turn him
out, for he is a clever fellow. Awfully conceited, though. I said to him
just now, вЂThe Karamazovs are not blackguards, but philosophers; for all
true Russians are philosophers, and though youвЂ™ve studied, you are not a
philosopherвЂ”you are a low fellow.вЂ™ He laughed, so maliciously. And I said
to him, вЂ_De ideabus non est disputandum_.вЂ™ IsnвЂ™t that rather good? I can
set up for being a classic, you see!вЂќ Mitya laughed suddenly.

вЂњWhy is it all over with you? You said so just now,вЂќ Alyosha interposed.

вЂњWhy is it all over with me? HвЂ™m!... The fact of it is ... if you take it
as a whole, I am sorry to lose GodвЂ”thatвЂ™s why it is.вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you mean by вЂsorry to lose GodвЂ™?вЂќ

вЂњImagine: inside, in the nerves, in the headвЂ”that is, these nerves are
there in the brain ... (damn them!) there are sort of little tails, the
little tails of those nerves, and as soon as they begin quivering ... that
is, you see, I look at something with my eyes and then they begin
quivering, those little tails ... and when they quiver, then an image
appears ... it doesnвЂ™t appear at once, but an instant, a second, passes
... and then something like a moment appears; that is, not a momentвЂ”devil
take the moment!вЂ”but an image; that is, an object, or an action, damn it!
ThatвЂ™s why I see and then think, because of those tails, not at all
because IвЂ™ve got a soul, and that I am some sort of image and likeness.
All that is nonsense! Rakitin explained it all to me yesterday, brother,
and it simply bowled me over. ItвЂ™s magnificent, Alyosha, this science! A
new manвЂ™s arisingвЂ”that I understand.... And yet I am sorry to lose God!вЂќ

вЂњWell, thatвЂ™s a good thing, anyway,вЂќ said Alyosha.

вЂњThat I am sorry to lose God? ItвЂ™s chemistry, brother, chemistry! ThereвЂ™s
no help for it, your reverence, you must make way for chemistry. And
Rakitin does dislike God. Ough! doesnвЂ™t he dislike Him! ThatвЂ™s the sore
point with all of them. But they conceal it. They tell lies. They pretend.
вЂWill you preach this in your reviews?вЂ™ I asked him. вЂOh, well, if I did
it openly, they wonвЂ™t let it through,вЂ™ he said. He laughed. вЂBut what will
become of men then?вЂ™ I asked him, вЂwithout God and immortal life? All
things are lawful then, they can do what they like?вЂ™ вЂDidnвЂ™t you know?вЂ™ he
said laughing, вЂa clever man can do what he likes,вЂ™ he said. вЂA clever man
knows his way about, but youвЂ™ve put your foot in it, committing a murder,
and now you are rotting in prison.вЂ™ He says that to my face! A regular
pig! I used to kick such people out, but now I listen to them. He talks a
lot of sense, too. Writes well. He began reading me an article last week.
I copied out three lines of it. Wait a minute. Here it is.вЂќ

Mitya hurriedly pulled out a piece of paper from his pocket and read:

вЂњ вЂIn order to determine this question, it is above all essential to put
oneвЂ™s personality in contradiction to oneвЂ™s reality.вЂ™ Do you understand
that?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I donвЂ™t,вЂќ said Alyosha. He looked at Mitya and listened to him with
curiosity.

вЂњI donвЂ™t understand either. ItвЂ™s dark and obscure, but intellectual.
вЂEvery one writes like that now,вЂ™ he says, вЂitвЂ™s the effect of their
environment.вЂ™ They are afraid of the environment. He writes poetry, too,
the rascal. HeвЂ™s written in honor of Madame HohlakovвЂ™s foot. Ha ha ha!вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ve heard about it,вЂќ said Alyosha.

вЂњHave you? And have you heard the poem?вЂќ

вЂњNo.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ve got it. Here it is. IвЂ™ll read it to you. You donвЂ™t knowвЂ”I havenвЂ™t
told youвЂ”thereвЂ™s quite a story about it. HeвЂ™s a rascal! Three weeks ago he
began to tease me. вЂYouвЂ™ve got yourself into a mess, like a fool, for the
sake of three thousand, but IвЂ™m going to collar a hundred and fifty
thousand. I am going to marry a widow and buy a house in Petersburg.вЂ™ And
he told me he was courting Madame Hohlakov. She hadnвЂ™t much brains in her
youth, and now at forty she has lost what she had. вЂBut sheвЂ™s awfully
sentimental,вЂ™ he says; вЂthatвЂ™s how I shall get hold of her. When I marry
her, I shall take her to Petersburg and there I shall start a newspaper.вЂ™
And his mouth was simply watering, the beast, not for the widow, but for
the hundred and fifty thousand. And he made me believe it. He came to see
me every day. вЂShe is coming round,вЂ™ he declared. He was beaming with
delight. And then, all of a sudden, he was turned out of the house.
PerhotinвЂ™s carrying everything before him, bravo! I could kiss the silly
old noodle for turning him out of the house. And he had written this
doggerel. вЂItвЂ™s the first time IвЂ™ve soiled my hands with writing poetry,вЂ™
he said. вЂItвЂ™s to win her heart, so itвЂ™s in a good cause. When I get hold
of the silly womanвЂ™s fortune, I can be of great social utility.вЂ™ They have
this social justification for every nasty thing they do! вЂAnyway itвЂ™s
better than your PushkinвЂ™s poetry,вЂ™ he said, вЂfor IвЂ™ve managed to advocate
enlightenment even in that.вЂ™ I understand what he means about Pushkin, I
quite see that, if he really was a man of talent and only wrote about
womenвЂ™s feet. But wasnвЂ™t Rakitin stuck up about his doggerel! The vanity
of these fellows! вЂOn the convalescence of the swollen foot of the object
of my affectionsвЂ™вЂ”he thought of that for a title. HeвЂ™s a waggish fellow.


    A captivating little foot,
    Though swollen and red and tender!
    The doctors come and plasters put,
    But still they cannot mend her.

    Yet, вЂ™tis not for her foot I dreadвЂ”
    A theme for PushkinвЂ™s muse more fitвЂ”
    ItвЂ™s not her foot, it is her head:
    I tremble for her loss of wit!

    For as her foot swells, strange to say,
    Her intellect is on the waneвЂ”
    Oh, for some remedy I pray
    That may restore both foot and brain!


He is a pig, a regular pig, but heвЂ™s very arch, the rascal! And he really
has put in a progressive idea. And wasnвЂ™t he angry when she kicked him
out! He was gnashing his teeth!вЂќ

вЂњHeвЂ™s taken his revenge already,вЂќ said Alyosha. вЂњHeвЂ™s written a paragraph
about Madame Hohlakov.вЂќ

And Alyosha told him briefly about the paragraph in _Gossip_.

вЂњThatвЂ™s his doing, thatвЂ™s his doing!вЂќ Mitya assented, frowning. вЂњThatвЂ™s
him! These paragraphs ... I know ... the insulting things that have been
written about Grushenka, for instance.... And about Katya, too.... HвЂ™m!вЂќ

He walked across the room with a harassed air.

вЂњBrother, I cannot stay long,вЂќ Alyosha said, after a pause. вЂњToвЂђmorrow
will be a great and awful day for you, the judgment of God will be
accomplished ... I am amazed at you, you walk about here, talking of I
donвЂ™t know what ...вЂќ

вЂњNo, donвЂ™t be amazed at me,вЂќ Mitya broke in warmly. вЂњAm I to talk of that
stinking dog? Of the murderer? WeвЂ™ve talked enough of him. I donвЂ™t want to
say more of the stinking son of Stinking Lizaveta! God will kill him, you
will see. Hush!вЂќ

He went up to Alyosha excitedly and kissed him. His eyes glowed.

вЂњRakitin wouldnвЂ™t understand it,вЂќ he began in a sort of exaltation; вЂњbut
you, youвЂ™ll understand it all. ThatвЂ™s why I was thirsting for you. You
see, thereвЂ™s so much IвЂ™ve been wanting to tell you for ever so long, here,
within these peeling walls, but I havenвЂ™t said a word about what matters
most; the moment never seems to have come. Now I can wait no longer. I
must pour out my heart to you. Brother, these last two months IвЂ™ve found
in myself a new man. A new man has risen up in me. He was hidden in me,
but would never have come to the surface, if it hadnвЂ™t been for this blow
from heaven. I am afraid! And what do I care if I spend twenty years in
the mines, breaking ore with a hammer? I am not a bit afraid of thatвЂ”itвЂ™s
something else I am afraid of now: that that new man may leave me. Even
there, in the mines, underвЂђground, I may find a human heart in another
convict and murderer by my side, and I may make friends with him, for even
there one may live and love and suffer. One may thaw and revive a frozen
heart in that convict, one may wait upon him for years, and at last bring
up from the dark depths a lofty soul, a feeling, suffering creature; one
may bring forth an angel, create a hero! There are so many of them,
hundreds of them, and we are all to blame for them. Why was it I dreamed
of that вЂbabeвЂ™ at such a moment? вЂWhy is the babe so poor?вЂ™ That was a
sign to me at that moment. ItвЂ™s for the babe IвЂ™m going. Because we are all
responsible for all. For all the вЂbabes,вЂ™ for there are big children as
well as little children. All are вЂbabes.вЂ™ I go for all, because some one
must go for all. I didnвЂ™t kill father, but IвЂ™ve got to go. I accept it.
ItвЂ™s all come to me here, here, within these peeling walls. There are
numbers of them there, hundreds of them underground, with hammers in their
hands. Oh, yes, we shall be in chains and there will be no freedom, but
then, in our great sorrow, we shall rise again to joy, without which man
cannot live nor God exist, for God gives joy: itвЂ™s His privilegeвЂ”a grand
one. Ah, man should be dissolved in prayer! What should I be underground
there without God? RakitinвЂ™s laughing! If they drive God from the earth,
we shall shelter Him underground. One cannot exist in prison without God;
itвЂ™s even more impossible than out of prison. And then we men underground
will sing from the bowels of the earth a glorious hymn to God, with Whom
is joy. Hail to God and His joy! I love Him!вЂќ

Mitya was almost gasping for breath as he uttered his wild speech. He
turned pale, his lips quivered, and tears rolled down his cheeks.

вЂњYes, life is full, there is life even underground,вЂќ he began again. вЂњYou
wouldnвЂ™t believe, Alexey, how I want to live now, what a thirst for
existence and consciousness has sprung up in me within these peeling
walls. Rakitin doesnвЂ™t understand that; all he cares about is building a
house and letting flats. But IвЂ™ve been longing for you. And what is
suffering? I am not afraid of it, even if it were beyond reckoning. I am
not afraid of it now. I was afraid of it before. Do you know, perhaps I
wonвЂ™t answer at the trial at all.... And I seem to have such strength in
me now, that I think I could stand anything, any suffering, only to be
able to say and to repeat to myself every moment, вЂI exist.вЂ™ In thousands
of agoniesвЂ”I exist. IвЂ™m tormented on the rackвЂ”but I exist! Though I sit
alone on a pillarвЂ”I exist! I see the sun, and if I donвЂ™t see the sun, I
know itвЂ™s there. And thereвЂ™s a whole life in that, in knowing that the sun
is there. Alyosha, my angel, all these philosophies are the death of me.
Damn them! Brother IvanвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњWhat of brother Ivan?вЂќ interrupted Alyosha, but Mitya did not hear.

вЂњYou see, I never had any of these doubts before, but it was all hidden
away in me. It was perhaps just because ideas I did not understand were
surging up in me, that I used to drink and fight and rage. It was to
stifle them in myself, to still them, to smother them. Ivan is not
Rakitin, there is an idea in him. Ivan is a sphinx and is silent; he is
always silent. ItвЂ™s God thatвЂ™s worrying me. ThatвЂ™s the only thing thatвЂ™s
worrying me. What if He doesnвЂ™t exist? What if RakitinвЂ™s rightвЂ”that itвЂ™s
an idea made up by men? Then if He doesnвЂ™t exist, man is the chief of the
earth, of the universe. Magnificent! Only how is he going to be good
without God? ThatвЂ™s the question. I always come back to that. For whom is
man going to love then? To whom will he be thankful? To whom will he sing
the hymn? Rakitin laughs. Rakitin says that one can love humanity without
God. Well, only a sniveling idiot can maintain that. I canвЂ™t understand
it. LifeвЂ™s easy for Rakitin. вЂYouвЂ™d better think about the extension of
civic rights, or even of keeping down the price of meat. You will show
your love for humanity more simply and directly by that, than by
philosophy.вЂ™ I answered him, вЂWell, but you, without a God, are more
likely to raise the price of meat, if it suits you, and make a rouble on
every copeck.вЂ™ He lost his temper. But after all, what is goodness? Answer
me that, Alexey. Goodness is one thing with me and another with a
Chinaman, so itвЂ™s a relative thing. Or isnвЂ™t it? Is it not relative? A
treacherous question! You wonвЂ™t laugh if I tell you itвЂ™s kept me awake two
nights. I only wonder now how people can live and think nothing about it.
Vanity! Ivan has no God. He has an idea. ItвЂ™s beyond me. But he is silent.
I believe he is a freeвЂђmason. I asked him, but he is silent. I wanted to
drink from the springs of his soulвЂ”he was silent. But once he did drop a
word.вЂќ

вЂњWhat did he say?вЂќ Alyosha took it up quickly.

вЂњI said to him, вЂThen everything is lawful, if it is so?вЂ™ He frowned.
вЂFyodor Pavlovitch, our papa,вЂ™ he said, вЂwas a pig, but his ideas were
right enough.вЂ™ That was what he dropped. That was all he said. That was
going one better than Rakitin.вЂќ

вЂњYes,вЂќ Alyosha assented bitterly. вЂњWhen was he with you?вЂќ

вЂњOf that later; now I must speak of something else. I have said nothing
about Ivan to you before. I put it off to the last. When my business here
is over and the verdict has been given, then IвЂ™ll tell you something. IвЂ™ll
tell you everything. WeвЂ™ve something tremendous on hand.... And you shall
be my judge in it. But donвЂ™t begin about that now; be silent. You talk of
toвЂђmorrow, of the trial; but, would you believe it, I know nothing about
it.вЂќ

вЂњHave you talked to the counsel?вЂќ

вЂњWhatвЂ™s the use of the counsel? I told him all about it. HeвЂ™s a soft,
cityвЂђbred rogueвЂ”a Bernard! But he doesnвЂ™t believe meвЂ”not a bit of it. Only
imagine, he believes I did it. I see it. вЂIn that case,вЂ™ I asked him, вЂwhy
have you come to defend me?вЂ™ Hang them all! TheyвЂ™ve got a doctor down,
too, want to prove IвЂ™m mad. I wonвЂ™t have that! Katerina Ivanovna wants to
do her вЂdutyвЂ™ to the end, whatever the strain!вЂќ Mitya smiled bitterly.
вЂњThe cat! HardвЂђhearted creature! She knows that I said of her at Mokroe
that she was a woman of вЂgreat wrath.вЂ™ They repeated it. Yes, the facts
against me have grown numerous as the sands of the sea. Grigory sticks to
his point. GrigoryвЂ™s honest, but a fool. Many people are honest because
they are fools: thatвЂ™s RakitinвЂ™s idea. GrigoryвЂ™s my enemy. And there are
some people who are better as foes than friends. I mean Katerina Ivanovna.
I am afraid, oh, I am afraid she will tell how she bowed to the ground
after that four thousand. SheвЂ™ll pay it back to the last farthing. I donвЂ™t
want her sacrifice; theyвЂ™ll put me to shame at the trial. I wonder how I
can stand it. Go to her, Alyosha, ask her not to speak of that in the
court, canвЂ™t you? But damn it all, it doesnвЂ™t matter! I shall get through
somehow. I donвЂ™t pity her. ItвЂ™s her own doing. She deserves what she gets.
I shall have my own story to tell, Alexey.вЂќ He smiled bitterly again.
вЂњOnly ... only Grusha, Grusha! Good Lord! Why should she have such
suffering to bear?вЂќ he exclaimed suddenly, with tears. вЂњGrushaвЂ™s killing
me; the thought of herвЂ™s killing me, killing me. She was with me just
now....вЂќ

вЂњShe told me she was very much grieved by you toвЂђday.вЂќ

вЂњI know. Confound my temper! It was jealousy. I was sorry, I kissed her as
she was going. I didnвЂ™t ask her forgiveness.вЂќ

вЂњWhy didnвЂ™t you?вЂќ exclaimed Alyosha.

Suddenly Mitya laughed almost mirthfully.

вЂњGod preserve you, my dear boy, from ever asking forgiveness for a fault
from a woman you love. From one you love especially, however greatly you
may have been in fault. For a womanвЂ”devil only knows what to make of a
woman! I know something about them, anyway. But try acknowledging you are
in fault to a woman. Say, вЂI am sorry, forgive me,вЂ™ and a shower of
reproaches will follow! Nothing will make her forgive you simply and
directly, sheвЂ™ll humble you to the dust, bring forward things that have
never happened, recall everything, forget nothing, add something of her
own, and only then forgive you. And even the best, the best of them do it.
SheвЂ™ll scrape up all the scrapings and load them on your head. They are
ready to flay you alive, I tell you, every one of them, all these angels
without whom we cannot live! I tell you plainly and openly, dear boy,
every decent man ought to be under some womanвЂ™s thumb. ThatвЂ™s my
convictionвЂ”not conviction, but feeling. A man ought to be magnanimous, and
itвЂ™s no disgrace to a man! No disgrace to a hero, not even a CГ¦sar! But
donвЂ™t ever beg her pardon all the same for anything. Remember that rule
given you by your brother Mitya, whoвЂ™s come to ruin through women. No, IвЂ™d
better make it up to Grusha somehow, without begging pardon. I worship
her, Alexey, worship her. Only she doesnвЂ™t see it. No, she still thinks I
donвЂ™t love her enough. And she tortures me, tortures me with her love. The
past was nothing! In the past it was only those infernal curves of hers
that tortured me, but now IвЂ™ve taken all her soul into my soul and through
her IвЂ™ve become a man myself. Will they marry us? If they donвЂ™t, I shall
die of jealousy. I imagine something every day.... What did she say to you
about me?вЂќ

Alyosha repeated all Grushenka had said to him that day. Mitya listened,
made him repeat things, and seemed pleased.

вЂњThen she is not angry at my being jealous?вЂќ he exclaimed. вЂњShe is a
regular woman! вЂIвЂ™ve a fierce heart myself!вЂ™ Ah, I love such fierce
hearts, though I canвЂ™t bear any oneвЂ™s being jealous of me. I canвЂ™t endure
it. We shall fight. But I shall love her, I shall love her infinitely.
Will they marry us? Do they let convicts marry? ThatвЂ™s the question. And
without her I canвЂ™t exist....вЂќ

Mitya walked frowning across the room. It was almost dark. He suddenly
seemed terribly worried.

вЂњSo thereвЂ™s a secret, she says, a secret? We have got up a plot against
her, and Katya is mixed up in it, she thinks. No, my good Grushenka,
thatвЂ™s not it. You are very wide of the mark, in your foolish feminine
way. Alyosha, darling, well, here goes! IвЂ™ll tell you our secret!вЂќ

He looked round, went close up quickly to Alyosha, who was standing before
him, and whispered to him with an air of mystery, though in reality no one
could hear them: the old warder was dozing in the corner, and not a word
could reach the ears of the soldiers on guard.

вЂњI will tell you all our secret,вЂќ Mitya whispered hurriedly. вЂњI meant to
tell you later, for how could I decide on anything without you? You are
everything to me. Though I say that Ivan is superior to us, you are my
angel. ItвЂ™s your decision will decide it. Perhaps itвЂ™s you that is
superior and not Ivan. You see, itвЂ™s a question of conscience, question of
the higher conscienceвЂ”the secret is so important that I canвЂ™t settle it
myself, and IвЂ™ve put it off till I could speak to you. But anyway itвЂ™s too
early to decide now, for we must wait for the verdict. As soon as the
verdict is given, you shall decide my fate. DonвЂ™t decide it now. IвЂ™ll tell
you now. You listen, but donвЂ™t decide. Stand and keep quiet. I wonвЂ™t tell
you everything. IвЂ™ll only tell you the idea, without details, and you keep
quiet. Not a question, not a movement. You agree? But, goodness, what
shall I do with your eyes? IвЂ™m afraid your eyes will tell me your
decision, even if you donвЂ™t speak. Oo! IвЂ™m afraid! Alyosha, listen! Ivan
suggests my _escaping_. I wonвЂ™t tell you the details: itвЂ™s all been
thought out: it can all be arranged. Hush, donвЂ™t decide. I should go to
America with Grusha. You know I canвЂ™t live without Grusha! What if they
wonвЂ™t let her follow me to Siberia? Do they let convicts get married? Ivan
thinks not. And without Grusha what should I do there underground with a
hammer? I should only smash my skull with the hammer! But, on the other
hand, my conscience? I should have run away from suffering. A sign has
come, I reject the sign. I have a way of salvation and I turn my back on
it. Ivan says that in America, вЂwith the goodвЂђwill,вЂ™ I can be of more use
than underground. But what becomes of our hymn from underground? WhatвЂ™s
America? America is vanity again! And thereвЂ™s a lot of swindling in
America, too, I expect. I should have run away from crucifixion! I tell
you, you know, Alexey, because you are the only person who can understand
this. ThereвЂ™s no one else. ItвЂ™s folly, madness to others, all IвЂ™ve told
you of the hymn. TheyвЂ™ll say IвЂ™m out of my mind or a fool. I am not out of
my mind and I am not a fool. Ivan understands about the hymn, too. He
understands, only he doesnвЂ™t answerвЂ”he doesnвЂ™t speak. He doesnвЂ™t believe
in the hymn. DonвЂ™t speak, donвЂ™t speak. I see how you look! You have
already decided. DonвЂ™t decide, spare me! I canвЂ™t live without Grusha. Wait
till after the trial!вЂќ

Mitya ended beside himself. He held Alyosha with both hands on his
shoulders, and his yearning, feverish eyes were fixed on his brotherвЂ™s.

вЂњThey donвЂ™t let convicts marry, do they?вЂќ he repeated for the third time
in a supplicating voice.

Alyosha listened with extreme surprise and was deeply moved.

вЂњTell me one thing,вЂќ he said. вЂњIs Ivan very keen on it, and whose idea was
it?вЂќ

вЂњHis, his, and he is very keen on it. He didnвЂ™t come to see me at first,
then he suddenly came a week ago and he began about it straight away. He
is awfully keen on it. He doesnвЂ™t ask me, but orders me to escape. He
doesnвЂ™t doubt of my obeying him, though I showed him all my heart as I
have to you, and told him about the hymn, too. He told me heвЂ™d arrange it;
heвЂ™s found out about everything. But of that later. HeвЂ™s simply set on it.
ItвЂ™s all a matter of money: heвЂ™ll pay ten thousand for escape and give me
twenty thousand for America. And he says we can arrange a magnificent
escape for ten thousand.вЂќ

вЂњAnd he told you on no account to tell me?вЂќ Alyosha asked again.

вЂњTo tell no one, and especially not you; on no account to tell you. He is
afraid, no doubt, that youвЂ™ll stand before me as my conscience. DonвЂ™t tell
him I told you. DonвЂ™t tell him, for anything.вЂќ

вЂњYou are right,вЂќ Alyosha pronounced; вЂњitвЂ™s impossible to decide anything
before the trial is over. After the trial youвЂ™ll decide of yourself. Then
youвЂ™ll find that new man in yourself and he will decide.вЂќ

вЂњA new man, or a Bernard whoвЂ™ll decide _Г  la_ Bernard, for I believe IвЂ™m a
contemptible Bernard myself,вЂќ said Mitya, with a bitter grin.

вЂњBut, brother, have you no hope then of being acquitted?вЂќ

Mitya shrugged his shoulders nervously and shook his head. вЂњAlyosha,
darling, itвЂ™s time you were going,вЂќ he said, with a sudden haste. вЂњThereвЂ™s
the superintendent shouting in the yard. HeвЂ™ll be here directly. We are
late; itвЂ™s irregular. Embrace me quickly. Kiss me! Sign me with the cross,
darling, for the cross I have to bear toвЂђmorrow.вЂќ

They embraced and kissed.

вЂњIvan,вЂќ said Mitya suddenly, вЂњsuggests my escaping; but, of course, he
believes I did it.вЂќ

A mournful smile came on to his lips.

вЂњHave you asked him whether he believes it?вЂќ asked Alyosha.

вЂњNo, I havenвЂ™t. I wanted to, but I couldnвЂ™t. I hadnвЂ™t the courage. But I
saw it from his eyes. Well, goodвЂђby!вЂќ

Once more they kissed hurriedly, and Alyosha was just going out, when
Mitya suddenly called him back.

вЂњStand facing me! ThatвЂ™s right!вЂќ And again he seized Alyosha, putting both
hands on his shoulders. His face became suddenly quite pale, so that it
was dreadfully apparent, even through the gathering darkness. His lips
twitched, his eyes fastened upon Alyosha.

вЂњAlyosha, tell me the whole truth, as you would before God. Do you believe
I did it? Do you, do you in yourself, believe it? The whole truth, donвЂ™t
lie!вЂќ he cried desperately.

Everything seemed heaving before Alyosha, and he felt something like a
stab at his heart.

вЂњHush! What do you mean?вЂќ he faltered helplessly.

вЂњThe whole truth, the whole, donвЂ™t lie!вЂќ repeated Mitya.

вЂњIвЂ™ve never for one instant believed that you were the murderer!вЂќ broke in
a shaking voice from AlyoshaвЂ™s breast, and he raised his right hand in the
air, as though calling God to witness his words.

MityaвЂ™s whole face was lighted up with bliss.

вЂњThank you!вЂќ he articulated slowly, as though letting a sigh escape him
after fainting. вЂњNow you have given me new life. Would you believe it,
till this moment IвЂ™ve been afraid to ask you, you, even you. Well, go!
YouвЂ™ve given me strength for toвЂђmorrow. God bless you! Come, go along!
Love Ivan!вЂќ was MityaвЂ™s last word.

Alyosha went out in tears. Such distrustfulness in Mitya, such lack of
confidence even to him, to AlyoshaвЂ”all this suddenly opened before Alyosha
an unsuspected depth of hopeless grief and despair in the soul of his
unhappy brother. Intense, infinite compassion overwhelmed him instantly.
There was a poignant ache in his torn heart. вЂњLove Ivan!вЂќвЂ”he suddenly
recalled MityaвЂ™s words. And he was going to Ivan. He badly wanted to see
Ivan all day. He was as much worried about Ivan as about Mitya, and more
than ever now.



Chapter V. Not You, Not You!


On the way to Ivan he had to pass the house where Katerina Ivanovna was
living. There was light in the windows. He suddenly stopped and resolved
to go in. He had not seen Katerina Ivanovna for more than a week. But now
it struck him that Ivan might be with her, especially on the eve of the
terrible day. Ringing, and mounting the staircase, which was dimly lighted
by a Chinese lantern, he saw a man coming down, and as they met, he
recognized him as his brother. So he was just coming from Katerina
Ivanovna.

вЂњAh, itвЂ™s only you,вЂќ said Ivan dryly. вЂњWell, goodвЂђby! You are going to
her?вЂќ

вЂњYes.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t advise you to; sheвЂ™s upset and youвЂ™ll upset her more.вЂќ

A door was instantly flung open above, and a voice cried suddenly:

вЂњNo, no! Alexey Fyodorovitch, have you come from him?вЂќ

вЂњYes, I have been with him.вЂќ

вЂњHas he sent me any message? Come up, Alyosha, and you, Ivan Fyodorovitch,
you must come back, you must. Do you hear?вЂќ

There was such a peremptory note in KatyaвЂ™s voice that Ivan, after a
momentвЂ™s hesitation, made up his mind to go back with Alyosha.

вЂњShe was listening,вЂќ he murmured angrily to himself, but Alyosha heard it.

вЂњExcuse my keeping my greatcoat on,вЂќ said Ivan, going into the drawingвЂђ
room. вЂњI wonвЂ™t sit down. I wonвЂ™t stay more than a minute.вЂќ

вЂњSit down, Alexey Fyodorovitch,вЂќ said Katerina Ivanovna, though she
remained standing. She had changed very little during this time, but there
was an ominous gleam in her dark eyes. Alyosha remembered afterwards that
she had struck him as particularly handsome at that moment.

вЂњWhat did he ask you to tell me?вЂќ

вЂњOnly one thing,вЂќ said Alyosha, looking her straight in the face, вЂњthat
you would spare yourself and say nothing at the trial of whatвЂќ (he was a
little confused) вЂњ... passed between you ... at the time of your first
acquaintance ... in that town.вЂќ

вЂњAh! that I bowed down to the ground for that money!вЂќ She broke into a
bitter laugh. вЂњWhy, is he afraid for me or for himself? He asks me to
spareвЂ”whom? Him or myself? Tell me, Alexey Fyodorovitch!вЂќ

Alyosha watched her intently, trying to understand her.

вЂњBoth yourself and him,вЂќ he answered softly.

вЂњI am glad to hear it,вЂќ she snapped out maliciously, and she suddenly
blushed.

вЂњYou donвЂ™t know me yet, Alexey Fyodorovitch,вЂќ she said menacingly. вЂњAnd I
donвЂ™t know myself yet. Perhaps youвЂ™ll want to trample me under foot after
my examination toвЂђmorrow.вЂќ

вЂњYou will give your evidence honorably,вЂќ said Alyosha; вЂњthatвЂ™s all thatвЂ™s
wanted.вЂќ

вЂњWomen are often dishonorable,вЂќ she snarled. вЂњOnly an hour ago I was
thinking I felt afraid to touch that monster ... as though he were a
reptile ... but no, he is still a human being to me! But did he do it? Is
he the murderer?вЂќ she cried, all of a sudden, hysterically, turning
quickly to Ivan. Alyosha saw at once that she had asked Ivan that question
before, perhaps only a moment before he came in, and not for the first
time, but for the hundredth, and that they had ended by quarreling.

вЂњIвЂ™ve been to see Smerdyakov.... It was you, you who persuaded me that he
murdered his father. ItвЂ™s only you I believed!вЂќ she continued, still
addressing Ivan. He gave her a sort of strained smile. Alyosha started at
her tone. He had not suspected such familiar intimacy between them.

вЂњWell, thatвЂ™s enough, anyway,вЂќ Ivan cut short the conversation. вЂњI am
going. IвЂ™ll come toвЂђmorrow.вЂќ And turning at once, he walked out of the
room and went straight downstairs.

With an imperious gesture, Katerina Ivanovna seized Alyosha by both hands.

вЂњFollow him! Overtake him! DonвЂ™t leave him alone for a minute!вЂќ she said,
in a hurried whisper. вЂњHeвЂ™s mad! DonвЂ™t you know that heвЂ™s mad? He is in a
fever, nervous fever. The doctor told me so. Go, run after him....вЂќ

Alyosha jumped up and ran after Ivan, who was not fifty paces ahead of
him.

вЂњWhat do you want?вЂќ He turned quickly on Alyosha, seeing that he was
running after him. вЂњShe told you to catch me up, because IвЂ™m mad. I know
it all by heart,вЂќ he added irritably.

вЂњShe is mistaken, of course; but she is right that you are ill,вЂќ said
Alyosha. вЂњI was looking at your face just now. You look very ill, Ivan.вЂќ

Ivan walked on without stopping. Alyosha followed him.

вЂњAnd do you know, Alexey Fyodorovitch, how people do go out of their
mind?вЂќ Ivan asked in a voice suddenly quiet, without a trace of
irritation, with a note of the simplest curiosity.

вЂњNo, I donвЂ™t. I suppose there are all kinds of insanity.вЂќ

вЂњAnd can one observe that oneвЂ™s going mad oneself?вЂќ

вЂњI imagine one canвЂ™t see oneself clearly in such circumstances,вЂќ Alyosha
answered with surprise.

Ivan paused for half a minute.

вЂњIf you want to talk to me, please change the subject,вЂќ he said suddenly.

вЂњOh, while I think of it, I have a letter for you,вЂќ said Alyosha timidly,
and he took LiseвЂ™s note from his pocket and held it out to Ivan. They were
just under a lampвЂђpost. Ivan recognized the handwriting at once.

вЂњAh, from that little demon!вЂќ he laughed maliciously, and, without opening
the envelope, he tore it into bits and threw it in the air. The bits were
scattered by the wind.

вЂњSheвЂ™s not sixteen yet, I believe, and already offering herself,вЂќ he said
contemptuously, striding along the street again.

вЂњHow do you mean, offering herself?вЂќ exclaimed Alyosha.

вЂњAs wanton women offer themselves, to be sure.вЂќ

вЂњHow can you, Ivan, how can you?вЂќ Alyosha cried warmly, in a grieved
voice. вЂњShe is a child; you are insulting a child! She is ill; she is very
ill, too. She is on the verge of insanity, too, perhaps.... I had hoped to
hear something from you ... that would save her.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™ll hear nothing from me. If she is a child I am not her nurse. Be
quiet, Alexey. DonвЂ™t go on about her. I am not even thinking about it.вЂќ

They were silent again for a moment.

вЂњShe will be praying all night now to the Mother of God to show her how to
act toвЂђmorrow at the trial,вЂќ he said sharply and angrily again.

вЂњYou ... you mean Katerina Ivanovna?вЂќ

вЂњYes. Whether sheвЂ™s to save Mitya or ruin him. SheвЂ™ll pray for light from
above. She canвЂ™t make up her mind for herself, you see. She has not had
time to decide yet. She takes me for her nurse, too. She wants me to sing
lullabies to her.вЂќ

вЂњKaterina Ivanovna loves you, brother,вЂќ said Alyosha sadly.

вЂњPerhaps; but I am not very keen on her.вЂќ

вЂњShe is suffering. Why do you ... sometimes say things to her that give
her hope?вЂќ Alyosha went on, with timid reproach. вЂњI know that youвЂ™ve given
her hope. Forgive me for speaking to you like this,вЂќ he added.

вЂњI canвЂ™t behave to her as I oughtвЂ”break off altogether and tell her so
straight out,вЂќ said Ivan, irritably. вЂњI must wait till sentence is passed
on the murderer. If I break off with her now, she will avenge herself on
me by ruining that scoundrel toвЂђmorrow at the trial, for she hates him and
knows she hates him. ItвЂ™s all a lieвЂ”lie upon lie! As long as I donвЂ™t break
off with her, she goes on hoping, and she wonвЂ™t ruin that monster, knowing
how I want to get him out of trouble. If only that damned verdict would
come!вЂќ

The words вЂњmurdererвЂќ and вЂњmonsterвЂќ echoed painfully in AlyoshaвЂ™s heart.

вЂњBut how can she ruin Mitya?вЂќ he asked, pondering on IvanвЂ™s words. вЂњWhat
evidence can she give that would ruin Mitya?вЂќ

вЂњYou donвЂ™t know that yet. SheвЂ™s got a document in her hands, in MityaвЂ™s
own writing, that proves conclusively that he did murder Fyodor
Pavlovitch.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s impossible!вЂќ cried Alyosha.

вЂњWhy is it impossible? IвЂ™ve read it myself.вЂќ

вЂњThere canвЂ™t be such a document!вЂќ Alyosha repeated warmly. вЂњThere canвЂ™t
be, because heвЂ™s not the murderer. ItвЂ™s not he murdered father, not he!вЂќ

Ivan suddenly stopped.

вЂњWho is the murderer then, according to you?вЂќ he asked, with apparent
coldness. There was even a supercilious note in his voice.

вЂњYou know who,вЂќ Alyosha pronounced in a low, penetrating voice.

вЂњWho? You mean the myth about that crazy idiot, the epileptic,
Smerdyakov?вЂќ

Alyosha suddenly felt himself trembling all over.

вЂњYou know who,вЂќ broke helplessly from him. He could scarcely breathe.

вЂњWho? Who?вЂќ Ivan cried almost fiercely. All his restraint suddenly
vanished.

вЂњI only know one thing,вЂќ Alyosha went on, still almost in a whisper, вЂњ_it
wasnвЂ™t you_ killed father.вЂќ

вЂњ вЂNot youвЂ™! What do you mean by вЂnot youвЂ™?вЂќ Ivan was thunderstruck.

вЂњIt was not you killed father, not you!вЂќ Alyosha repeated firmly.

The silence lasted for half a minute.

вЂњI know I didnвЂ™t. Are you raving?вЂќ said Ivan, with a pale, distorted
smile. His eyes were riveted on Alyosha. They were standing again under a
lampвЂђpost.

вЂњNo, Ivan. YouвЂ™ve told yourself several times that you are the murderer.вЂќ

вЂњWhen did I say so? I was in Moscow.... When have I said so?вЂќ Ivan
faltered helplessly.

вЂњYouвЂ™ve said so to yourself many times, when youвЂ™ve been alone during
these two dreadful months,вЂќ Alyosha went on softly and distinctly as
before. Yet he was speaking now, as it were, not of himself, not of his
own will, but obeying some irresistible command. вЂњYou have accused
yourself and have confessed to yourself that you are the murderer and no
one else. But you didnвЂ™t do it: you are mistaken: you are not the
murderer. Do you hear? It was not you! God has sent me to tell you so.вЂќ

They were both silent. The silence lasted a whole long minute. They were
both standing still, gazing into each otherвЂ™s eyes. They were both pale.
Suddenly Ivan began trembling all over, and clutched AlyoshaвЂ™s shoulder.

вЂњYouвЂ™ve been in my room!вЂќ he whispered hoarsely. вЂњYouвЂ™ve been there at
night, when he came.... Confess ... have you seen him, have you seen him?вЂќ

вЂњWhom do you meanвЂ”Mitya?вЂќ Alyosha asked, bewildered.

вЂњNot him, damn the monster!вЂќ Ivan shouted, in a frenzy. вЂњDo you know that
he visits me? How did you find out? Speak!вЂќ

вЂњWho is _he_! I donвЂ™t know whom you are talking about,вЂќ Alyosha faltered,
beginning to be alarmed.

вЂњYes, you do know ... or how could youвЂ”? ItвЂ™s impossible that you donвЂ™t
know.вЂќ

Suddenly he seemed to check himself. He stood still and seemed to reflect.
A strange grin contorted his lips.

вЂњBrother,вЂќ Alyosha began again, in a shaking voice, вЂњI have said this to
you, because youвЂ™ll believe my word, I know that. I tell you once and for
all, itвЂ™s not you. You hear, once for all! God has put it into my heart to
say this to you, even though it may make you hate me from this hour.вЂќ

But by now Ivan had apparently regained his selfвЂђcontrol.

вЂњAlexey Fyodorovitch,вЂќ he said, with a cold smile, вЂњI canвЂ™t endure
prophets and epilepticsвЂ”messengers from God especiallyвЂ”and you know that
only too well. I break off all relations with you from this moment and
probably for ever. I beg you to leave me at this turning. ItвЂ™s the way to
your lodgings, too. YouвЂ™d better be particularly careful not to come to me
toвЂђday! Do you hear?вЂќ

He turned and walked on with a firm step, not looking back.

вЂњBrother,вЂќ Alyosha called after him, вЂњif anything happens to you toвЂђday,
turn to me before any one!вЂќ

But Ivan made no reply. Alyosha stood under the lampвЂђpost at the cross
roads, till Ivan had vanished into the darkness. Then he turned and walked
slowly homewards. Both Alyosha and Ivan were living in lodgings; neither
of them was willing to live in Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s empty house. Alyosha
had a furnished room in the house of some working people. Ivan lived some
distance from him. He had taken a roomy and fairly comfortable lodge
attached to a fine house that belonged to a wellвЂђtoвЂђdo lady, the widow of
an official. But his only attendant was a deaf and rheumatic old crone who
went to bed at six oвЂ™clock every evening and got up at six in the morning.
Ivan had become remarkably indifferent to his comforts of late, and very
fond of being alone. He did everything for himself in the one room he
lived in, and rarely entered any of the other rooms in his abode.

He reached the gate of the house and had his hand on the bell, when he
suddenly stopped. He felt that he was trembling all over with anger.
Suddenly he let go of the bell, turned back with a curse, and walked with
rapid steps in the opposite direction. He walked a mile and a half to a
tiny, slanting, wooden house, almost a hut, where Marya Kondratyevna, the
neighbor who used to come to Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s kitchen for soup and to
whom Smerdyakov had once sung his songs and played on the guitar, was now
lodging. She had sold their little house, and was now living here with her
mother. Smerdyakov, who was illвЂ”almost dyingвЂ”had been with them ever since
Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s death. It was to him Ivan was going now, drawn by a
sudden and irresistible prompting.



Chapter VI. The First Interview With Smerdyakov


This was the third time that Ivan had been to see Smerdyakov since his
return from Moscow. The first time he had seen him and talked to him was
on the first day of his arrival, then he had visited him once more, a
fortnight later. But his visits had ended with that second one, so that it
was now over a month since he had seen him. And he had scarcely heard
anything of him.

Ivan had only returned five days after his fatherвЂ™s death, so that he was
not present at the funeral, which took place the day before he came back.
The cause of his delay was that Alyosha, not knowing his Moscow address,
had to apply to Katerina Ivanovna to telegraph to him, and she, not
knowing his address either, telegraphed to her sister and aunt, reckoning
on IvanвЂ™s going to see them as soon as he arrived in Moscow. But he did
not go to them till four days after his arrival. When he got the telegram,
he had, of course, set off postвЂђhaste to our town. The first to meet him
was Alyosha, and Ivan was greatly surprised to find that, in opposition to
the general opinion of the town, he refused to entertain a suspicion
against Mitya, and spoke openly of Smerdyakov as the murderer. Later on,
after seeing the police captain and the prosecutor, and hearing the
details of the charge and the arrest, he was still more surprised at
Alyosha, and ascribed his opinion only to his exaggerated brotherly
feeling and sympathy with Mitya, of whom Alyosha, as Ivan knew, was very
fond.

By the way, let us say a word or two of IvanвЂ™s feeling to his brother
Dmitri. He positively disliked him; at most, felt sometimes a compassion
for him, and even that was mixed with great contempt, almost repugnance.
MityaвЂ™s whole personality, even his appearance, was extremely unattractive
to him. Ivan looked with indignation on Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s love for his
brother. Yet he went to see Mitya on the first day of his arrival, and
that interview, far from shaking IvanвЂ™s belief in his guilt, positively
strengthened it. He found his brother agitated, nervously excited. Mitya
had been talkative, but very absentвЂђminded and incoherent. He used violent
language, accused Smerdyakov, and was fearfully muddled. He talked
principally about the three thousand roubles, which he said had been
вЂњstolenвЂќ from him by his father.

вЂњThe money was mine, it was my money,вЂќ Mitya kept repeating. вЂњEven if I
had stolen it, I should have had the right.вЂќ

He hardly contested the evidence against him, and if he tried to turn a
fact to his advantage, it was in an absurd and incoherent way. He hardly
seemed to wish to defend himself to Ivan or any one else. Quite the
contrary, he was angry and proudly scornful of the charges against him; he
was continually firing up and abusing every one. He only laughed
contemptuously at GrigoryвЂ™s evidence about the open door, and declared
that it was вЂњthe devil that opened it.вЂќ But he could not bring forward any
coherent explanation of the fact. He even succeeded in insulting Ivan
during their first interview, telling him sharply that it was not for
people who declared that вЂњeverything was lawful,вЂќ to suspect and question
him. Altogether he was anything but friendly with Ivan on that occasion.
Immediately after that interview with Mitya, Ivan went for the first time
to see Smerdyakov.

In the railway train on his way from Moscow, he kept thinking of
Smerdyakov and of his last conversation with him on the evening before he
went away. Many things seemed to him puzzling and suspicious. But when he
gave his evidence to the investigating lawyer Ivan said nothing, for the
time, of that conversation. He put that off till he had seen Smerdyakov,
who was at that time in the hospital.

Doctor Herzenstube and Varvinsky, the doctor he met in the hospital,
confidently asserted in reply to IvanвЂ™s persistent questions, that
SmerdyakovвЂ™s epileptic attack was unmistakably genuine, and were surprised
indeed at Ivan asking whether he might not have been shamming on the day
of the catastrophe. They gave him to understand that the attack was an
exceptional one, the fits persisting and recurring several times, so that
the patientвЂ™s life was positively in danger, and it was only now, after
they had applied remedies, that they could assert with confidence that the
patient would survive. вЂњThough it might well be,вЂќ added Doctor
Herzenstube, вЂњthat his reason would be impaired for a considerable period,
if not permanently.вЂќ On IvanвЂ™s asking impatiently whether that meant that
he was now mad, they told him that this was not yet the case, in the full
sense of the word, but that certain abnormalities were perceptible. Ivan
decided to find out for himself what those abnormalities were.

At the hospital he was at once allowed to see the patient. Smerdyakov was
lying on a truckleвЂђbed in a separate ward. There was only one other bed in
the room, and in it lay a tradesman of the town, swollen with dropsy, who
was obviously almost dying; he could be no hindrance to their
conversation. Smerdyakov grinned uncertainly on seeing Ivan, and for the
first instant seemed nervous. So at least Ivan fancied. But that was only
momentary. For the rest of the time he was struck, on the contrary, by
SmerdyakovвЂ™s composure. From the first glance Ivan had no doubt that he
was very ill. He was very weak; he spoke slowly, seeming to move his
tongue with difficulty; he was much thinner and sallower. Throughout the
interview, which lasted twenty minutes, he kept complaining of headache
and of pain in all his limbs. His thin emasculate face seemed to have
become so tiny; his hair was ruffled, and his crest of curls in front
stood up in a thin tuft. But in the left eye, which was screwed up and
seemed to be insinuating something, Smerdyakov showed himself unchanged.
вЂњItвЂ™s always worth while speaking to a clever man.вЂќ Ivan was reminded of
that at once. He sat down on the stool at his feet. Smerdyakov, with
painful effort, shifted his position in bed, but he was not the first to
speak. He remained dumb, and did not even look much interested.

вЂњCan you talk to me?вЂќ asked Ivan. вЂњI wonвЂ™t tire you much.вЂќ

вЂњCertainly I can,вЂќ mumbled Smerdyakov, in a faint voice. вЂњHas your honor
been back long?вЂќ he added patronizingly, as though encouraging a nervous
visitor.

вЂњI only arrived toвЂђday.... To see the mess you are in here.вЂќ

Smerdyakov sighed.

вЂњWhy do you sigh? You knew of it all along,вЂќ Ivan blurted out.

Smerdyakov was stolidly silent for a while.

вЂњHow could I help knowing? It was clear beforehand. But how could I tell
it would turn out like that?вЂќ

вЂњWhat would turn out? DonвЂ™t prevaricate! YouвЂ™ve foretold youвЂ™d have a fit;
on the way down to the cellar, you know. You mentioned the very spot.вЂќ

вЂњHave you said so at the examination yet?вЂќ Smerdyakov queried with
composure.

Ivan felt suddenly angry.

вЂњNo, I havenвЂ™t yet, but I certainly shall. You must explain a great deal
to me, my man; and let me tell you, I am not going to let you play with
me!вЂќ

вЂњWhy should I play with you, when I put my whole trust in you, as in God
Almighty?вЂќ said Smerdyakov, with the same composure, only for a moment
closing his eyes.

вЂњIn the first place,вЂќ began Ivan, вЂњI know that epileptic fits canвЂ™t be
told beforehand. IвЂ™ve inquired; donвЂ™t try and take me in. You canвЂ™t
foretell the day and the hour. How was it you told me the day and the hour
beforehand, and about the cellar, too? How could you tell that you would
fall down the cellar stairs in a fit, if you didnвЂ™t sham a fit on
purpose?вЂќ

вЂњI had to go to the cellar anyway, several times a day, indeed,вЂќ
Smerdyakov drawled deliberately. вЂњI fell from the garret just in the same
way a year ago. ItвЂ™s quite true you canвЂ™t tell the day and hour of a fit
beforehand, but you can always have a presentiment of it.вЂќ

вЂњBut you did foretell the day and the hour!вЂќ

вЂњIn regard to my epilepsy, sir, you had much better inquire of the doctors
here. You can ask them whether it was a real fit or a sham; itвЂ™s no use my
saying any more about it.вЂќ

вЂњAnd the cellar? How could you know beforehand of the cellar?вЂќ

вЂњYou donвЂ™t seem able to get over that cellar! As I was going down to the
cellar, I was in terrible dread and doubt. What frightened me most was
losing you and being left without defense in all the world. So I went down
into the cellar thinking, вЂHere, itвЂ™ll come on directly, itвЂ™ll strike me
down directly, shall I fall?вЂ™ And it was through this fear that I suddenly
felt the spasm that always comes ... and so I went flying. All that and
all my previous conversation with you at the gate the evening before, when
I told you how frightened I was and spoke of the cellar, I told all that
to Doctor Herzenstube and Nikolay Parfenovitch, the investigating lawyer,
and itвЂ™s all been written down in the protocol. And the doctor here, Mr.
Varvinsky, maintained to all of them that it was just the thought of it
brought it on, the apprehension that I might fall. It was just then that
the fit seized me. And so theyвЂ™ve written it down, that itвЂ™s just how it
must have happened, simply from my fear.вЂќ

As he finished, Smerdyakov drew a deep breath, as though exhausted.

вЂњThen you have said all that in your evidence?вЂќ said Ivan, somewhat taken
aback. He had meant to frighten him with the threat of repeating their
conversation, and it appeared that Smerdyakov had already reported it all
himself.

вЂњWhat have I to be afraid of? Let them write down the whole truth,вЂќ
Smerdyakov pronounced firmly.

вЂњAnd have you told them every word of our conversation at the gate?вЂќ

вЂњNo, not to say every word.вЂќ

вЂњAnd did you tell them that you can sham fits, as you boasted then?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I didnвЂ™t tell them that either.вЂќ

вЂњTell me now, why did you send me then to Tchermashnya?вЂќ

вЂњI was afraid youвЂ™d go away to Moscow; Tchermashnya is nearer, anyway.вЂќ

вЂњYou are lying; you suggested my going away yourself; you told me to get
out of the way of trouble.вЂќ

вЂњThat was simply out of affection and my sincere devotion to you,
foreseeing trouble in the house, to spare you. Only I wanted to spare
myself even more. ThatвЂ™s why I told you to get out of harmвЂ™s way, that you
might understand that there would be trouble in the house, and would
remain at home to protect your father.вЂќ

вЂњYou might have said it more directly, you blockhead!вЂќ Ivan suddenly fired
up.

вЂњHow could I have said it more directly then? It was simply my fear that
made me speak, and you might have been angry, too. I might well have been
apprehensive that Dmitri Fyodorovitch would make a scene and carry away
that money, for he considered it as good as his own; but who could tell
that it would end in a murder like this? I thought that he would only
carry off the three thousand that lay under the masterвЂ™s mattress in the
envelope, and you see, heвЂ™s murdered him. How could you guess it either,
sir?вЂќ

вЂњBut if you say yourself that it couldnвЂ™t be guessed, how could I have
guessed and stayed at home? You contradict yourself!вЂќ said Ivan,
pondering.

вЂњYou might have guessed from my sending you to Tchermashnya and not to
Moscow.вЂќ

вЂњHow could I guess it from that?вЂќ

Smerdyakov seemed much exhausted, and again he was silent for a minute.

вЂњYou might have guessed from the fact of my asking you not to go to
Moscow, but to Tchermashnya, that I wanted to have you nearer, for
MoscowвЂ™s a long way off, and Dmitri Fyodorovitch, knowing you are not far
off, would not be so bold. And if anything had happened, you might have
come to protect me, too, for I warned you of Grigory VassilyevitchвЂ™s
illness, and that I was afraid of having a fit. And when I explained those
knocks to you, by means of which one could go in to the deceased, and that
Dmitri Fyodorovitch knew them all through me, I thought that you would
guess yourself that he would be sure to do something, and so wouldnвЂ™t go
to Tchermashnya even, but would stay.вЂќ

вЂњHe talks very coherently,вЂќ thought Ivan, вЂњthough he does mumble; whatвЂ™s
the derangement of his faculties that Herzenstube talked of?вЂќ

вЂњYou are cunning with me, damn you!вЂќ he exclaimed, getting angry.

вЂњBut I thought at the time that you quite guessed,вЂќ Smerdyakov parried
with the simplest air.

вЂњIf IвЂ™d guessed, I should have stayed,вЂќ cried Ivan.

вЂњWhy, I thought that it was because you guessed, that you went away in
such a hurry, only to get out of trouble, only to run away and save
yourself in your fright.вЂќ

вЂњYou think that every one is as great a coward as yourself?вЂќ

вЂњForgive me, I thought you were like me.вЂќ

вЂњOf course, I ought to have guessed,вЂќ Ivan said in agitation; вЂњand I did
guess there was some mischief brewing on your part ... only you are lying,
you are lying again,вЂќ he cried, suddenly recollecting. вЂњDo you remember
how you went up to the carriage and said to me, вЂItвЂ™s always worth while
speaking to a clever manвЂ™? So you were glad I went away, since you praised
me?вЂќ

Smerdyakov sighed again and again. A trace of color came into his face.

вЂњIf I was pleased,вЂќ he articulated rather breathlessly, вЂњit was simply
because you agreed not to go to Moscow, but to Tchermashnya. For it was
nearer, anyway. Only when I said these words to you, it was not by way of
praise, but of reproach. You didnвЂ™t understand it.вЂќ

вЂњWhat reproach?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, that foreseeing such a calamity you deserted your own father, and
would not protect us, for I might have been taken up any time for stealing
that three thousand.вЂќ

вЂњDamn you!вЂќ Ivan swore again. вЂњStay, did you tell the prosecutor and the
investigating lawyer about those knocks?вЂќ

вЂњI told them everything just as it was.вЂќ

Ivan wondered inwardly again.

вЂњIf I thought of anything then,вЂќ he began again, вЂњit was solely of some
wickedness on your part. Dmitri might kill him, but that he would stealвЂ”I
did not believe that then.... But I was prepared for any wickedness from
you. You told me yourself you could sham a fit. What did you say that
for?вЂќ

вЂњIt was just through my simplicity, and I never have shammed a fit on
purpose in my life. And I only said so then to boast to you. It was just
foolishness. I liked you so much then, and was openвЂђhearted with you.вЂќ

вЂњMy brother directly accuses you of the murder and theft.вЂќ

вЂњWhat else is left for him to do?вЂќ said Smerdyakov, with a bitter grin.
вЂњAnd who will believe him with all the proofs against him? Grigory
Vassilyevitch saw the door open. What can he say after that? But never
mind him! He is trembling to save himself.вЂќ

He slowly ceased speaking; then suddenly, as though on reflection, added:

вЂњAnd look here again. He wants to throw it on me and make out that it is
the work of my handsвЂ”IвЂ™ve heard that already. But as to my being clever at
shamming a fit: should I have told you beforehand that I could sham one,
if I really had had such a design against your father? If I had been
planning such a murder could I have been such a fool as to give such
evidence against myself beforehand? And to his son, too! Upon my word! Is
that likely? As if that could be, such a thing has never happened. No one
hears this talk of ours now, except Providence itself, and if you were to
tell of it to the prosecutor and Nikolay Parfenovitch you might defend me
completely by doing so, for who would be likely to be such a criminal, if
he is so openвЂђhearted beforehand? Any one can see that.вЂќ

вЂњWell,вЂќ and Ivan got up to cut short the conversation, struck by
SmerdyakovвЂ™s last argument. вЂњI donвЂ™t suspect you at all, and I think itвЂ™s
absurd, indeed, to suspect you. On the contrary, I am grateful to you for
setting my mind at rest. Now I am going, but IвЂ™ll come again. Meanwhile,
goodвЂђby. Get well. Is there anything you want?вЂќ

вЂњI am very thankful for everything. Marfa Ignatyevna does not forget me,
and provides me anything I want, according to her kindness. Good people
visit me every day.вЂќ

вЂњGoodвЂђby. But I shanвЂ™t say anything of your being able to sham a fit, and
I donвЂ™t advise you to, either,вЂќ something made Ivan say suddenly.

вЂњI quite understand. And if you donвЂ™t speak of that, I shall say nothing
of that conversation of ours at the gate.вЂќ

Then it happened that Ivan went out, and only when he had gone a dozen
steps along the corridor, he suddenly felt that there was an insulting
significance in SmerdyakovвЂ™s last words. He was almost on the point of
turning back, but it was only a passing impulse, and muttering,
вЂњNonsense!вЂќ he went out of the hospital.

His chief feeling was one of relief at the fact that it was not
Smerdyakov, but Mitya, who had committed the murder, though he might have
been expected to feel the opposite. He did not want to analyze the reason
for this feeling, and even felt a positive repugnance at prying into his
sensations. He felt as though he wanted to make haste to forget something.
In the following days he became convinced of MityaвЂ™s guilt, as he got to
know all the weight of evidence against him. There was evidence of people
of no importance, Fenya and her mother, for instance, but the effect of it
was almost overpowering. As to Perhotin, the people at the tavern, and at
PlotnikovвЂ™s shop, as well as the witnesses at Mokroe, their evidence
seemed conclusive. It was the details that were so damning. The secret of
the knocks impressed the lawyers almost as much as GrigoryвЂ™s evidence as
to the open door. GrigoryвЂ™s wife, Marfa, in answer to IvanвЂ™s questions,
declared that Smerdyakov had been lying all night the other side of the
partition wall. вЂњHe was not three paces from our bed,вЂќ and that although
she was a sound sleeper she waked several times and heard him moaning, вЂњHe
was moaning the whole time, moaning continually.вЂќ

Talking to Herzenstube, and giving it as his opinion that Smerdyakov was
not mad, but only rather weak, Ivan only evoked from the old man a subtle
smile.

вЂњDo you know how he spends his time now?вЂќ he asked; вЂњlearning lists of
French words by heart. He has an exerciseвЂђbook under his pillow with the
French words written out in Russian letters for him by some one, he he
he!вЂќ

Ivan ended by dismissing all doubts. He could not think of Dmitri without
repulsion. Only one thing was strange, however. Alyosha persisted that
Dmitri was not the murderer, and that вЂњin all probabilityвЂќ Smerdyakov was.
Ivan always felt that AlyoshaвЂ™s opinion meant a great deal to him, and so
he was astonished at it now. Another thing that was strange was that
Alyosha did not make any attempt to talk about Mitya with Ivan, that he
never began on the subject and only answered his questions. This, too,
struck Ivan particularly.

But he was very much preoccupied at that time with something quite apart
from that. On his return from Moscow, he abandoned himself hopelessly to
his mad and consuming passion for Katerina Ivanovna. This is not the time
to begin to speak of this new passion of IvanвЂ™s, which left its mark on
all the rest of his life: this would furnish the subject for another
novel, which I may perhaps never write. But I cannot omit to mention here
that when Ivan, on leaving Katerina Ivanovna with Alyosha, as IвЂ™ve related
already, told him, вЂњI am not keen on her,вЂќ it was an absolute lie: he
loved her madly, though at times he hated her so that he might have
murdered her. Many causes helped to bring about this feeling. Shattered by
what had happened with Mitya, she rushed on IvanвЂ™s return to meet him as
her one salvation. She was hurt, insulted and humiliated in her feelings.
And here the man had come back to her, who had loved her so ardently
before (oh! she knew that very well), and whose heart and intellect she
considered so superior to her own. But the sternly virtuous girl did not
abandon herself altogether to the man she loved, in spite of the Karamazov
violence of his passions and the great fascination he had for her. She was
continually tormented at the same time by remorse for having deserted
Mitya, and in moments of discord and violent anger (and they were
numerous) she told Ivan so plainly. This was what he had called to Alyosha
вЂњlies upon lies.вЂќ There was, of course, much that was false in it, and
that angered Ivan more than anything.... But of all this later.

He did, in fact, for a time almost forget SmerdyakovвЂ™s existence, and yet,
a fortnight after his first visit to him, he began to be haunted by the
same strange thoughts as before. ItвЂ™s enough to say that he was
continually asking himself, why was it that on that last night in Fyodor
PavlovitchвЂ™s house he had crept out on to the stairs like a thief and
listened to hear what his father was doing below? Why had he recalled that
afterwards with repulsion? Why next morning, had he been suddenly so
depressed on the journey? Why, as he reached Moscow, had he said to
himself, вЂњI am a scoundrelвЂќ? And now he almost fancied that these
tormenting thoughts would make him even forget Katerina Ivanovna, so
completely did they take possession of him again. It was just after
fancying this, that he met Alyosha in the street. He stopped him at once,
and put a question to him:

вЂњDo you remember when Dmitri burst in after dinner and beat father, and
afterwards I told you in the yard that I reserved вЂthe right to
desireвЂ™?... Tell me, did you think then that I desired fatherвЂ™s death or
not?вЂќ

вЂњI did think so,вЂќ answered Alyosha, softly.

вЂњIt was so, too; it was not a matter of guessing. But didnвЂ™t you fancy
then that what I wished was just that вЂone reptile should devour anotherвЂ™;
that is, just that Dmitri should kill father, and as soon as possible ...
and that I myself was even prepared to help to bring that about?вЂќ

Alyosha turned rather pale, and looked silently into his brotherвЂ™s face.

вЂњSpeak!вЂќ cried Ivan, вЂњI want above everything to know what you thought
then. I want the truth, the truth!вЂќ

He drew a deep breath, looking angrily at Alyosha before his answer came.

вЂњForgive me, I did think that, too, at the time,вЂќ whispered Alyosha, and
he did not add one softening phrase.

вЂњThanks,вЂќ snapped Ivan, and, leaving Alyosha, he went quickly on his way.
From that time Alyosha noticed that Ivan began obviously to avoid him and
seemed even to have taken a dislike to him, so much so that Alyosha gave
up going to see him. Immediately after that meeting with him, Ivan had not
gone home, but went straight to Smerdyakov again.



Chapter VII. The Second Visit To Smerdyakov


By that time Smerdyakov had been discharged from the hospital. Ivan knew
his new lodging, the dilapidated little wooden house, divided in two by a
passage on one side of which lived Marya Kondratyevna and her mother, and
on the other, Smerdyakov. No one knew on what terms he lived with them,
whether as a friend or as a lodger. It was supposed afterwards that he had
come to stay with them as Marya KondratyevnaвЂ™s betrothed, and was living
there for a time without paying for board or lodging. Both mother and
daughter had the greatest respect for him and looked upon him as greatly
superior to themselves.

Ivan knocked, and, on the door being opened, went straight into the
passage. By Marya KondratyevnaвЂ™s directions he went straight to the better
room on the left, occupied by Smerdyakov. There was a tiled stove in the
room and it was extremely hot. The walls were gay with blue paper, which
was a good deal used however, and in the cracks under it cockroaches
swarmed in amazing numbers, so that there was a continual rustling from
them. The furniture was very scanty: two benches against each wall and two
chairs by the table. The table of plain wood was covered with a cloth with
pink patterns on it. There was a pot of geranium on each of the two little
windows. In the corner there was a case of ikons. On the table stood a
little copper samovar with many dents in it, and a tray with two cups. But
Smerdyakov had finished tea and the samovar was out. He was sitting at the
table on a bench. He was looking at an exerciseвЂђbook and slowly writing
with a pen. There was a bottle of ink by him and a flat iron candlestick,
but with a composite candle. Ivan saw at once from SmerdyakovвЂ™s face that
he had completely recovered from his illness. His face was fresher,
fuller, his hair stood up jauntily in front, and was plastered down at the
sides. He was sitting in a partiвЂђcolored, wadded dressingвЂђgown, rather
dirty and frayed, however. He had spectacles on his nose, which Ivan had
never seen him wearing before. This trifling circumstance suddenly
redoubled IvanвЂ™s anger: вЂњA creature like that and wearing spectacles!вЂќ

Smerdyakov slowly raised his head and looked intently at his visitor
through his spectacles; then he slowly took them off and rose from the
bench, but by no means respectfully, almost lazily, doing the least
possible required by common civility. All this struck Ivan instantly; he
took it all in and noted it at onceвЂ”most of all the look in SmerdyakovвЂ™s
eyes, positively malicious, churlish and haughty. вЂњWhat do you want to
intrude for?вЂќ it seemed to say; вЂњwe settled everything then; why have you
come again?вЂќ Ivan could scarcely control himself.

вЂњItвЂ™s hot here,вЂќ he said, still standing, and unbuttoned his overcoat.

вЂњTake off your coat,вЂќ Smerdyakov conceded.

Ivan took off his coat and threw it on a bench with trembling hands. He
took a chair, moved it quickly to the table and sat down. Smerdyakov
managed to sit down on his bench before him.

вЂњTo begin with, are we alone?вЂќ Ivan asked sternly and impulsively. вЂњCan
they overhear us in there?вЂќ

вЂњNo one can hear anything. YouвЂ™ve seen for yourself: thereвЂ™s a passage.вЂќ

вЂњListen, my good fellow; what was that you babbled, as I was leaving the
hospital, that if I said nothing about your faculty of shamming fits, you
wouldnвЂ™t tell the investigating lawyer all our conversation at the gate?
What do you mean by _all_? What could you mean by it? Were you threatening
me? Have I entered into some sort of compact with you? Do you suppose I am
afraid of you?вЂќ

Ivan said this in a perfect fury, giving him to understand with obvious
intention that he scorned any subterfuge or indirectness and meant to show
his cards. SmerdyakovвЂ™s eyes gleamed resentfully, his left eye winked, and
he at once gave his answer, with his habitual composure and deliberation.
вЂњYou want to have everything aboveвЂђboard; very well, you shall have it,вЂќ
he seemed to say.

вЂњThis is what I meant then, and this is why I said that, that you, knowing
beforehand of this murder of your own parent, left him to his fate, and
that people mightnвЂ™t after that conclude any evil about your feelings and
perhaps of something else, tooвЂ”thatвЂ™s what I promised not to tell the
authorities.вЂќ

Though Smerdyakov spoke without haste and obviously controlling himself,
yet there was something in his voice, determined and emphatic, resentful
and insolently defiant. He stared impudently at Ivan. A mist passed before
IvanвЂ™s eyes for the first moment.

вЂњHow? What? Are you out of your mind?вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™m perfectly in possession of all my faculties.вЂќ

вЂњDo you suppose I _knew_ of the murder?вЂќ Ivan cried at last, and he
brought his fist violently on the table. вЂњWhat do you mean by вЂsomething
else, tooвЂ™? Speak, scoundrel!вЂќ

Smerdyakov was silent and still scanned Ivan with the same insolent stare.

вЂњSpeak, you stinking rogue, what is that вЂsomething else, tooвЂ™?вЂќ

вЂњThe вЂsomething elseвЂ™ I meant was that you probably, too, were very
desirous of your parentвЂ™s death.вЂќ

Ivan jumped up and struck him with all his might on the shoulder, so that
he fell back against the wall. In an instant his face was bathed in tears.
Saying, вЂњItвЂ™s a shame, sir, to strike a sick man,вЂќ he dried his eyes with
a very dirty blue check handkerchief and sank into quiet weeping. A minute
passed.

вЂњThatвЂ™s enough! Leave off,вЂќ Ivan said peremptorily, sitting down again.
вЂњDonвЂ™t put me out of all patience.вЂќ

Smerdyakov took the rag from his eyes. Every line of his puckered face
reflected the insult he had just received.

вЂњSo you thought then, you scoundrel, that together with Dmitri I meant to
kill my father?вЂќ

вЂњI didnвЂ™t know what thoughts were in your mind then,вЂќ said Smerdyakov
resentfully; вЂњand so I stopped you then at the gate to sound you on that
very point.вЂќ

вЂњTo sound what, what?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, that very circumstance, whether you wanted your father to be
murdered or not.вЂќ

What infuriated Ivan more than anything was the aggressive, insolent tone
to which Smerdyakov persistently adhered.

вЂњIt was you murdered him?вЂќ he cried suddenly.

Smerdyakov smiled contemptuously.

вЂњYou know of yourself, for a fact, that it wasnвЂ™t I murdered him. And I
should have thought that there was no need for a sensible man to speak of
it again.вЂќ

вЂњBut why, why had you such a suspicion about me at the time?вЂќ

вЂњAs you know already, it was simply from fear. For I was in such a
position, shaking with fear, that I suspected every one. I resolved to
sound you, too, for I thought if you wanted the same as your brother, then
the business was as good as settled and I should be crushed like a fly,
too.вЂќ

вЂњLook here, you didnвЂ™t say that a fortnight ago.вЂќ

вЂњI meant the same when I talked to you in the hospital, only I thought
youвЂ™d understand without wasting words, and that being such a sensible man
you wouldnвЂ™t care to talk of it openly.вЂќ

вЂњWhat next! Come answer, answer, I insist: what was it ... what could I
have done to put such a degrading suspicion into your mean soul?вЂќ

вЂњAs for the murder, you couldnвЂ™t have done that and didnвЂ™t want to, but as
for wanting some one else to do it, that was just what you did want.вЂќ

вЂњAnd how coolly, how coolly he speaks! But why should I have wanted it;
what grounds had I for wanting it?вЂќ

вЂњWhat grounds had you? What about the inheritance?вЂќ said Smerdyakov
sarcastically, and, as it were, vindictively. вЂњWhy, after your parentвЂ™s
death there was at least forty thousand to come to each of you, and very
likely more, but if Fyodor Pavlovitch got married then to that lady,
Agrafena Alexandrovna, she would have had all his capital made over to her
directly after the wedding, for sheвЂ™s plenty of sense, so that your parent
would not have left you two roubles between the three of you. And were
they far from a wedding, either? Not a hairвЂ™sвЂђbreadth: that lady had only
to lift her little finger and he would have run after her to church, with
his tongue out.вЂќ

Ivan restrained himself with painful effort.

вЂњVery good,вЂќ he commented at last. вЂњYou see, I havenвЂ™t jumped up, I
havenвЂ™t knocked you down, I havenвЂ™t killed you. Speak on. So, according to
you, I had fixed on Dmitri to do it; I was reckoning on him?вЂќ

вЂњHow could you help reckoning on him? If he killed him, then he would lose
all the rights of a nobleman, his rank and property, and would go off to
exile; so his share of the inheritance would come to you and your brother
Alexey Fyodorovitch in equal parts; so youвЂ™d each have not forty, but
sixty thousand each. ThereвЂ™s not a doubt you did reckon on Dmitri
Fyodorovitch.вЂќ

вЂњWhat I put up with from you! Listen, scoundrel, if I had reckoned on any
one then, it would have been on you, not on Dmitri, and I swear I did
expect some wickedness from you ... at the time.... I remember my
impression!вЂќ

вЂњI thought, too, for a minute, at the time, that you were reckoning on me
as well,вЂќ said Smerdyakov, with a sarcastic grin. вЂњSo that it was just by
that more than anything you showed me what was in your mind. For if you
had a foreboding about me and yet went away, you as good as said to me,
вЂYou can murder my parent, I wonвЂ™t hinder you!вЂ™ вЂќ

вЂњYou scoundrel! So thatвЂ™s how you understood it!вЂќ

вЂњIt was all that going to Tchermashnya. Why! You were meaning to go to
Moscow and refused all your fatherвЂ™s entreaties to go to TchermashnyaвЂ”and
simply at a foolish word from me you consented at once! What reason had
you to consent to Tchermashnya? Since you went to Tchermashnya with no
reason, simply at my word, it shows that you must have expected something
from me.вЂќ

вЂњNo, I swear I didnвЂ™t!вЂќ shouted Ivan, grinding his teeth.

вЂњYou didnвЂ™t? Then you ought, as your fatherвЂ™s son, to have had me taken to
the lockвЂђup and thrashed at once for my words then ... or at least, to
have given me a punch in the face on the spot, but you were not a bit
angry, if you please, and at once in a friendly way acted on my foolish
word and went away, which was utterly absurd, for you ought to have stayed
to save your parentвЂ™s life. How could I help drawing my conclusions?вЂќ

Ivan sat scowling, both his fists convulsively pressed on his knees.

вЂњYes, I am sorry I didnвЂ™t punch you in the face,вЂќ he said with a bitter
smile. вЂњI couldnвЂ™t have taken you to the lockвЂђup just then. Who would have
believed me and what charge could I bring against you? But the punch in
the face ... oh, IвЂ™m sorry I didnвЂ™t think of it. Though blows are
forbidden, I should have pounded your ugly face to a jelly.вЂќ

Smerdyakov looked at him almost with relish.

вЂњIn the ordinary occasions of life,вЂќ he said in the same complacent and
sententious tone in which he had taunted Grigory and argued with him about
religion at Fyodor PavlovitchвЂ™s table, вЂњin the ordinary occasions of life,
blows on the face are forbidden nowadays by law, and people have given
them up, but in exceptional occasions of life people still fly to blows,
not only among us but all over the world, be it even the fullest Republic
of France, just as in the time of Adam and Eve, and they never will leave
off, but you, even in an exceptional case, did not dare.вЂќ

вЂњWhat are you learning French words for?вЂќ Ivan nodded towards the
exerciseвЂђbook lying on the table.

вЂњWhy shouldnвЂ™t I learn them so as to improve my education, supposing that
I may myself chance to go some day to those happy parts of Europe?вЂќ

вЂњListen, monster.вЂќ IvanвЂ™s eyes flashed and he trembled all over. вЂњI am not
afraid of your accusations; you can say what you like about me, and if I
donвЂ™t beat you to death, itвЂ™s simply because I suspect you of that crime
and IвЂ™ll drag you to justice. IвЂ™ll unmask you.вЂќ

вЂњTo my thinking, youвЂ™d better keep quiet, for what can you accuse me of,
considering my absolute innocence? and who would believe you? Only if you
begin, I shall tell everything, too, for I must defend myself.вЂќ

вЂњDo you think I am afraid of you now?вЂќ

вЂњIf the court doesnвЂ™t believe all IвЂ™ve said to you just now, the public
will, and you will be ashamed.вЂќ

вЂњThatвЂ™s as much as to say, вЂItвЂ™s always worth while speaking to a sensible
man,вЂ™ eh?вЂќ snarled Ivan.

вЂњYou hit the mark, indeed. And youвЂ™d better be sensible.вЂќ

Ivan got up, shaking all over with indignation, put on his coat, and
without replying further to Smerdyakov, without even looking at him,
walked quickly out of the cottage. The cool evening air refreshed him.
There was a bright moon in the sky. A nightmare of ideas and sensations
filled his soul. вЂњShall I go at once and give information against
Smerdyakov? But what information can I give? He is not guilty, anyway. On
the contrary, heвЂ™ll accuse me. And in fact, why did I set off for
Tchermashnya then? What for? What for?вЂќ Ivan asked himself. вЂњYes, of
course, I was expecting something and he is right....вЂќ And he remembered
for the hundredth time how, on the last night in his fatherвЂ™s house, he
had listened on the stairs. But he remembered it now with such anguish
that he stood still on the spot as though he had been stabbed. вЂњYes, I
expected it then, thatвЂ™s true! I wanted the murder, I did want the murder!
Did I want the murder? Did I want it? I must kill Smerdyakov! If I donвЂ™t
dare kill Smerdyakov now, life is not worth living!вЂќ

Ivan did not go home, but went straight to Katerina Ivanovna and alarmed
her by his appearance. He was like a madman. He repeated all his
conversation with Smerdyakov, every syllable of it. He couldnвЂ™t be calmed,
however much she tried to soothe him: he kept walking about the room,
speaking strangely, disconnectedly. At last he sat down, put his elbows on
the table, leaned his head on his hands and pronounced this strange
sentence: вЂњIf itвЂ™s not Dmitri, but Smerdyakov whoвЂ™s the murderer, I share
his guilt, for I put him up to it. Whether I did, I donвЂ™t know yet. But if
he is the murderer, and not Dmitri, then, of course, I am the murderer,
too.вЂќ

When Katerina Ivanovna heard that, she got up from her seat without a
word, went to her writingвЂђtable, opened a box standing on it, took out a
sheet of paper and laid it before Ivan. This was the document of which
Ivan spoke to Alyosha later on as a вЂњconclusive proofвЂќ that Dmitri had
killed his father. It was the letter written by Mitya to Katerina Ivanovna
when he was drunk, on the very evening he met Alyosha at the crossroads on
the way to the monastery, after the scene at Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s, when
Grushenka had insulted her. Then, parting from Alyosha, Mitya had rushed
to Grushenka. I donвЂ™t know whether he saw her, but in the evening he was
at the вЂњMetropolis,вЂќ where he got thoroughly drunk. Then he asked for pen
and paper and wrote a document of weighty consequences to himself. It was
a wordy, disconnected, frantic letter, a drunken letter in fact. It was
like the talk of a drunken man, who, on his return home, begins with
extraordinary heat telling his wife or one of his household how he has
just been insulted, what a rascal had just insulted him, what a fine
fellow he is on the other hand, and how he will pay that scoundrel out;
and all that at great length, with great excitement and incoherence, with
drunken tears and blows on the table. The letter was written on a dirty
piece of ordinary paper of the cheapest kind. It had been provided by the
tavern and there were figures scrawled on the back of it. There was
evidently not space enough for his drunken verbosity and Mitya not only
filled the margins but had written the last line right across the rest.
The letter ran as follows:


    FATAL KATYA: ToвЂђmorrow I will get the money and repay your three
    thousand and farewell, woman of great wrath, but farewell, too, my
    love! Let us make an end! ToвЂђmorrow I shall try and get it from
    every one, and if I canвЂ™t borrow it, I give you my word of honor I
    shall go to my father and break his skull and take the money from
    under the pillow, if only Ivan has gone. If I have to go to
    Siberia for it, IвЂ™ll give you back your three thousand. And
    farewell. I bow down to the ground before you, for IвЂ™ve been a
    scoundrel to you. Forgive me! No, better not forgive me, youвЂ™ll be
    happier and so shall I! Better Siberia than your love, for I love
    another woman and you got to know her too well toвЂђday, so how can
    you forgive? I will murder the man whoвЂ™s robbed me! IвЂ™ll leave you
    all and go to the East so as to see no one again. Not _her_
    either, for you are not my only tormentress; she is too. Farewell!

    P.S.вЂ”I write my curse, but I adore you! I hear it in my heart. One
    string is left, and it vibrates. Better tear my heart in two! I
    shall kill myself, but first of all that cur. I shall tear three
    thousand from him and fling it to you. Though IвЂ™ve been a
    scoundrel to you, I am not a thief! You can expect three thousand.
    The cur keeps it under his mattress, in pink ribbon. I am not a
    thief, but IвЂ™ll murder my thief. Katya, donвЂ™t look disdainful.
    Dmitri is not a thief! but a murderer! He has murdered his father
    and ruined himself to hold his ground, rather than endure your
    pride. And he doesnвЂ™t love you.

    P.P.S.вЂ”I kiss your feet, farewell! P.P.P.S.вЂ”Katya, pray to God
    that some oneвЂ™ll give me the money. Then I shall not be steeped in
    gore, and if no one doesвЂ”I shall! Kill me!

    Your slave and enemy,

    D. KARAMAZOV.


When Ivan read this вЂњdocumentвЂќ he was convinced. So then it was his
brother, not Smerdyakov. And if not Smerdyakov, then not he, Ivan. This
letter at once assumed in his eyes the aspect of a logical proof. There
could be no longer the slightest doubt of MityaвЂ™s guilt. The suspicion
never occurred to Ivan, by the way, that Mitya might have committed the
murder in conjunction with Smerdyakov, and, indeed, such a theory did not
fit in with the facts. Ivan was completely reassured. The next morning he
only thought of Smerdyakov and his gibes with contempt. A few days later
he positively wondered how he could have been so horribly distressed at
his suspicions. He resolved to dismiss him with contempt and forget him.
So passed a month. He made no further inquiry about Smerdyakov, but twice
he happened to hear that he was very ill and out of his mind.

вЂњHeвЂ™ll end in madness,вЂќ the young doctor Varvinsky observed about him, and
Ivan remembered this. During the last week of that month Ivan himself
began to feel very ill. He went to consult the Moscow doctor who had been
sent for by Katerina Ivanovna just before the trial. And just at that time
his relations with Katerina Ivanovna became acutely strained. They were
like two enemies in love with one another. Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s вЂњreturnsвЂќ
to Mitya, that is, her brief but violent revulsions of feeling in his
favor, drove Ivan to perfect frenzy. Strange to say, until that last scene
described above, when Alyosha came from Mitya to Katerina Ivanovna, Ivan
had never once, during that month, heard her express a doubt of MityaвЂ™s
guilt, in spite of those вЂњreturnsвЂќ that were so hateful to him. It is
remarkable, too, that while he felt that he hated Mitya more and more
every day, he realized that it was not on account of KatyaвЂ™s вЂњreturnsвЂќ
that he hated him, but just _because he was the murderer of his father_.
He was conscious of this and fully recognized it to himself.

Nevertheless, he went to see Mitya ten days before the trial and proposed
to him a plan of escapeвЂ”a plan he had obviously thought over a long time.
He was partly impelled to do this by a sore place still left in his heart
from a phrase of SmerdyakovвЂ™s, that it was to his, IvanвЂ™s, advantage that
his brother should be convicted, as that would increase his inheritance
and AlyoshaвЂ™s from forty to sixty thousand roubles. He determined to
sacrifice thirty thousand on arranging MityaвЂ™s escape. On his return from
seeing him, he was very mournful and dispirited; he suddenly began to feel
that he was anxious for MityaвЂ™s escape, not only to heal that sore place
by sacrificing thirty thousand, but for another reason. вЂњIs it because I
am as much a murderer at heart?вЂќ he asked himself. Something very deep
down seemed burning and rankling in his soul. His pride above all suffered
cruelly all that month. But of that later....

When, after his conversation with Alyosha, Ivan suddenly decided with his
hand on the bell of his lodging to go to Smerdyakov, he obeyed a sudden
and peculiar impulse of indignation. He suddenly remembered how Katerina
Ivanovna had only just cried out to him in AlyoshaвЂ™s presence: вЂњIt was
you, you, persuaded me of hisвЂќ (that is, MityaвЂ™s) вЂњguilt!вЂќ Ivan was
thunderstruck when he recalled it. He had never once tried to persuade her
that Mitya was the murderer; on the contrary, he had suspected himself in
her presence, that time when he came back from Smerdyakov. It was _she_,
she, who had produced that вЂњdocumentвЂќ and proved his brotherвЂ™s guilt. And
now she suddenly exclaimed: вЂњIвЂ™ve been at SmerdyakovвЂ™s myself!вЂќ When had
she been there? Ivan had known nothing of it. So she was not at all so
sure of MityaвЂ™s guilt! And what could Smerdyakov have told her? What,
what, had he said to her? His heart burned with violent anger. He could
not understand how he could, half an hour before, have let those words
pass and not have cried out at the moment. He let go of the bell and
rushed off to Smerdyakov. вЂњI shall kill him, perhaps, this time,вЂќ he
thought on the way.



Chapter VIII. The Third And Last Interview With Smerdyakov


When he was halfвЂђway there, the keen dry wind that had been blowing early
that morning rose again, and a fine dry snow began falling thickly. It did
not lie on the ground, but was whirled about by the wind, and soon there
was a regular snowstorm. There were scarcely any lampвЂђposts in the part of
the town where Smerdyakov lived. Ivan strode alone in the darkness,
unconscious of the storm, instinctively picking out his way. His head
ached and there was a painful throbbing in his temples. He felt that his
hands were twitching convulsively. Not far from Marya KondratyevnaвЂ™s
cottage, Ivan suddenly came upon a solitary drunken little peasant. He was
wearing a coarse and patched coat, and was walking in zigzags, grumbling
and swearing to himself. Then suddenly he would begin singing in a husky
drunken voice:


    вЂњAch, VankaвЂ™s gone to Petersburg;
    I wonвЂ™t wait till he comes back.вЂќ


But he broke off every time at the second line and began swearing again;
then he would begin the same song again. Ivan felt an intense hatred for
him before he had thought about him at all. Suddenly he realized his
presence and felt an irresistible impulse to knock him down. At that
moment they met, and the peasant with a violent lurch fell full tilt
against Ivan, who pushed him back furiously. The peasant went flying
backwards and fell like a log on the frozen ground. He uttered one
plaintive вЂњOвЂ”oh!вЂќ and then was silent. Ivan stepped up to him. He was
lying on his back, without movement or consciousness. вЂњHe will be frozen,вЂќ
thought Ivan, and he went on his way to SmerdyakovвЂ™s.

In the passage, Marya Kondratyevna, who ran out to open the door with a
candle in her hand, whispered that Smerdyakov was very ill, вЂњItвЂ™s not that
heвЂ™s laid up, but he seems not himself, and he even told us to take the
tea away; he wouldnвЂ™t have any.вЂќ

вЂњWhy, does he make a row?вЂќ asked Ivan coarsely.

вЂњOh, dear, no, quite the contrary, heвЂ™s very quiet. Only please donвЂ™t talk
to him too long,вЂќ Marya Kondratyevna begged him. Ivan opened the door and
stepped into the room.

It was overвЂђheated as before, but there were changes in the room. One of
the benches at the side had been removed, and in its place had been put a
large old mahogany leather sofa, on which a bed had been made up, with
fairly clean white pillows. Smerdyakov was sitting on the sofa, wearing
the same dressingвЂђgown. The table had been brought out in front of the
sofa, so that there was hardly room to move. On the table lay a thick book
in yellow cover, but Smerdyakov was not reading it. He seemed to be
sitting doing nothing. He met Ivan with a slow silent gaze, and was
apparently not at all surprised at his coming. There was a great change in
his face; he was much thinner and sallower. His eyes were sunken and there
were blue marks under them.

вЂњWhy, you really are ill?вЂќ Ivan stopped short. вЂњI wonвЂ™t keep you long, I
wonвЂ™t even take off my coat. Where can one sit down?вЂќ

He went to the other end of the table, moved up a chair and sat down on
it.

вЂњWhy do you look at me without speaking? IвЂ™ve only come with one question,
and I swear I wonвЂ™t go without an answer. Has the young lady, Katerina
Ivanovna, been with you?вЂќ

Smerdyakov still remained silent, looking quietly at Ivan as before.
Suddenly, with a motion of his hand, he turned his face away.

вЂњWhatвЂ™s the matter with you?вЂќ cried Ivan.

вЂњNothing.вЂќ

вЂњWhat do you mean by вЂnothingвЂ™?вЂќ

вЂњYes, she has. ItвЂ™s no matter to you. Let me alone.вЂќ

вЂњNo, I wonвЂ™t let you alone. Tell me, when was she here?вЂќ

вЂњWhy, IвЂ™d quite forgotten about her,вЂќ said Smerdyakov, with a scornful
smile, and turning his face to Ivan again, he stared at him with a look of
frenzied hatred, the same look that he had fixed on him at their last
interview, a month before.

вЂњYou seem very ill yourself, your face is sunken; you donвЂ™t look like
yourself,вЂќ he said to Ivan.

вЂњNever mind my health, tell me what I ask you.вЂќ

вЂњBut why are your eyes so yellow? The whites are quite yellow. Are you so
worried?вЂќ He smiled contemptuously and suddenly laughed outright.

вЂњListen; IвЂ™ve told you I wonвЂ™t go away without an answer!вЂќ Ivan cried,
intensely irritated.

вЂњWhy do you keep pestering me? Why do you torment me?вЂќ said Smerdyakov,
with a look of suffering.

вЂњDamn it! IвЂ™ve nothing to do with you. Just answer my question and IвЂ™ll go
away.вЂќ

вЂњIвЂ™ve no answer to give you,вЂќ said Smerdyakov, looking down again.

вЂњYou may be sure IвЂ™ll make you answer!вЂќ

вЂњWhy are you so uneasy?вЂќ Smerdyakov stared at him, not simply with
contempt, but almost with repulsion. вЂњIs this because the trial begins toвЂђ
morrow? Nothing will happen to you; canвЂ™t you believe that at last? Go
home, go to bed and sleep in peace, donвЂ™t be afraid of anything.вЂќ

вЂњI donвЂ™t understand you.... What have I to be afraid of toвЂђmorrow?вЂќ Ivan
articulated in astonishment, and suddenly a chill breath of fear did in
fact pass over his soul. Smerdyakov measured him with his eyes.

вЂњYou donвЂ™t understand?вЂќ he drawled reproachfully. вЂњItвЂ™s a strange thing a
sensible man should care to play such a farce!вЂќ

Ivan looked at him speechless. The startling, incredibly supercilious tone
of this man who had once been his valet, was extraordinary in itself. He
had not taken such a tone even at their last interview.

вЂњI tell you, youвЂ™ve nothing to be afraid of. I wonвЂ™t say anything about
you; thereвЂ™s no proof against you. I say, how your hands are trembling!
Why are your fingers moving like that? Go home, _you_ did not murder him.вЂќ

Ivan started. He remembered Alyosha.

вЂњI know it was not I,вЂќ he faltered.

вЂњDo you?вЂќ Smerdyakov caught him up again.

Ivan jumped up and seized him by the shoulder.

вЂњTell me everything, you viper! Tell me everything!вЂќ

Smerdyakov was not in the least scared. He only riveted his eyes on Ivan
with insane hatred.

вЂњWell, it was you who murdered him, if thatвЂ™s it,вЂќ he whispered furiously.

Ivan sank back on his chair, as though pondering something. He laughed
malignantly.

вЂњYou mean my going away. What you talked about last time?вЂќ

вЂњYou stood before me last time and understood it all, and you understand
it now.вЂќ

вЂњAll I understand is that you are mad.вЂќ

вЂњArenвЂ™t you tired of it? Here we are face to face; whatвЂ™s the use of going
on keeping up a farce to each other? Are you still trying to throw it all
on me, to my face? _You_ murdered him; you are the real murderer, I was
only your instrument, your faithful servant, and it was following your
words I did it.вЂќ

вЂњ_Did_ it? Why, did you murder him?вЂќ Ivan turned cold.

Something seemed to give way in his brain, and he shuddered all over with
a cold shiver. Then Smerdyakov himself looked at him wonderingly; probably
the genuineness of IvanвЂ™s horror struck him.

вЂњYou donвЂ™t mean to say you really did not know?вЂќ he faltered
mistrustfully, looking with a forced smile into his eyes. Ivan still gazed
at him, and seemed unable to speak.


    Ach, VankaвЂ™s gone to Petersburg;
    I wonвЂ™t wait till he comes back,


suddenly echoed in his head.

вЂњDo you know, I am afraid that you are a dream, a phantom sitting before
me,вЂќ he muttered.

вЂњThereвЂ™s no phantom here, but only us two and one other. No doubt he is
here, that third, between us.вЂќ

вЂњWho is he? Who is here? What third person?вЂќ Ivan cried in alarm, looking
about him, his eyes hastily searching in every corner.

вЂњThat third is God HimselfвЂ”Providence. He is the third beside us now. Only
donвЂ™t look for Him, you wonвЂ™t find Him.вЂќ

вЂњItвЂ™s a lie that you killed him!вЂќ Ivan cried madly. вЂњYou are mad, or
teasing me again!вЂќ

Smerdyakov, as before, watched him curiously, with no sign of fear. He
could still scarcely get over his incredulity; he still fancied that Ivan
knew everything and was trying to вЂњthrow it all on him to his face.вЂќ

вЂњWait a minute,вЂќ he said at last in a weak voice, and suddenly bringing up
his left leg from under the table, he began turning up his trouser leg. He
was wearing long white stockings and slippers. Slowly he took off his
garter and fumbled to the bottom of his stocking. Ivan gazed at him, and
suddenly shuddered in a paroxysm of terror.

вЂњHeвЂ™s mad!вЂќ he cried, and rapidly jumping up, he drew back, so that he
knocked his back against the wall and stood up against it, stiff and
straight. He looked with insane terror at Smerdyakov, who, entirely
unaffected by his terror, continued fumbling in his stocking, as though he
were making an effort to get hold of something with his fingers and pull
it out. At last he got hold of it and began pulling it out. Ivan saw that
it was a piece of paper, or perhaps a roll of papers. Smerdyakov pulled it
out and laid it on the table.

вЂњHere,вЂќ he said quietly.

вЂњWhat is it?вЂќ asked Ivan, trembling.

вЂњKindly look at it,вЂќ Smerdyakov answered, still in the same low tone.

Ivan stepped up to the table, took up the roll of paper and began
unfolding it, but suddenly he drew back his fingers, as though from
contact with a loathsome reptile.

вЂњYour hands keep twitching,вЂќ observed Smerdyakov, and he deliberately
unfolded the bundle himself. Under the wrapper were three packets of
hundredвЂђrouble notes.

вЂњThey are all here, all the three thousand roubles; you need not count
them. Take them,вЂќ Smerdyakov suggested to Ivan, nodding at the notes. Ivan
sank back in his chair. He was as white as a handkerchief.

вЂњYou frightened me ... with your stocking,вЂќ he said, with a strange grin.

вЂњCan you really not have known till now?вЂќ Smerdyakov asked once more.

вЂњNo, I did not know. I kept thinking of Dmitri. Brother, brother! Ach!вЂќ He
suddenly clutched his head in both hands.

вЂњListen. Did you kill him alone? With my brotherвЂ™s help or without?вЂќ

вЂњIt was only with you, with your help, I killed him, and Dmitri
Fyodorovitch is quite innocent.вЂќ

вЂњAll right, all right. Talk about me later. Why do I keep on trembling? I
canвЂ™t speak properly.вЂќ

вЂњYou were bold enough then. You said вЂeverything was lawful,вЂ™ and how
frightened you are now,вЂќ Smerdyakov muttered in surprise. вЂњWonвЂ™t you have
some lemonade? IвЂ™ll ask for some at once. ItвЂ™s very refreshing. Only I
must hide this first.вЂќ

And again he motioned at the notes. He was just going to get up and call
at the door to Marya Kondratyevna to make some lemonade and bring it them,
but, looking for something to cover up the notes that she might not see
them, he first took out his handkerchief, and as it turned out to be very
dirty, took up the big yellow book that Ivan had noticed at first lying on
the table, and put it over the notes. The book was _The Sayings of the
Holy Father Isaac the Syrian_. Ivan read it mechanically.

вЂњI wonвЂ™t have any lemonade,вЂќ he said. вЂњTalk of me later. Sit down and tell
me how you did it. Tell me all about it.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™d better take off your greatcoat, or youвЂ™ll be too hot.вЂќ Ivan, as
though heвЂ™d only just thought of it, took off his coat, and, without
getting up from his chair, threw it on the bench.

вЂњSpeak, please, speak.вЂќ

He seemed calmer. He waited, feeling sure that Smerdyakov would tell him
_all_ about it.

вЂњHow it was done?вЂќ sighed Smerdyakov. вЂњIt was done in a most natural way,
following your very words.вЂќ

вЂњOf my words later,вЂќ Ivan broke in again, apparently with complete selfвЂђ
possession, firmly uttering his words, and not shouting as before. вЂњOnly
tell me in detail how you did it. Everything, as it happened. DonвЂ™t forget
anything. The details, above everything, the details, I beg you.вЂќ

вЂњYouвЂ™d gone away, then I fell into the cellar.вЂќ

вЂњIn a fit or in a sham one?вЂќ

вЂњA sham one, naturally. I shammed it all. I went quietly down the steps to
the very bottom and lay down quietly, and as I lay down I gave a scream,
and struggled, till they carried me out.вЂќ

вЂњStay! And were you shamming all along, afterwards, and in the hospital?вЂќ

вЂњNo, not at all. Next day, in the morning, before they took me to the
hospital, I had a real attack and a more violent one than IвЂ™ve had for
years. For two days I was quite unconscious.вЂќ

вЂњAll right, all right. Go on.вЂќ

вЂњThey laid me on the bed. I knew IвЂ™d be the other side of the partition,
for whenever I was ill, Marfa Ignatyevna used to put me there, near them.
SheвЂ™s always been very kind to me, from my birth up. At night I moaned,
but quietly. I kept expecting Dmitri Fyodorovitch to come.вЂќ

вЂњExpecting him? To come to you?вЂќ

вЂњNot to me. I expected him to come into the house, for IвЂ™d no doubt that
heвЂ™d come that night, for being without me and getting no news, heвЂ™d be
sure to come and climb over the fence, as he used to, and do something.вЂќ

вЂњAnd if he hadnвЂ™t come?вЂќ

вЂњThen nothing would have happened. I should never have brought myself to
it without him.вЂќ

вЂњAll right, all right ... speak more intelligibly, donвЂ™t hurry; above all,
donвЂ™t leave anything out!вЂќ

вЂњI expected him to kill Fyodor Pavlovitch. I thought that was certain, for
I had prepared him for it ... during the last few days.... He knew about
the knocks, that was the chief thing. With his suspiciousness and the fury
which had been growing in him all those days, he was bound to get into the
house by means of those taps. That was inevitable, so I was expecting
him.вЂќ

вЂњStay,вЂќ Ivan interrupted; вЂњif he had killed him, he would have taken the
money and carried it away; you must have considered that. What would you
have got by it afterwards? I donвЂ™t see.вЂќ

вЂњBut he would never have found the money. That was only what I told him,
that the money was under the mattress. But that wasnвЂ™t true. It had been
lying in a box. And afterwards I suggested to Fyodor Pavlovitch, as I was
the only person he trusted, to hide the envelope with the notes in the
corner behind the ikons, for no one would have guessed that place,
especially if they came in a hurry. So thatвЂ™s where the envelope lay, in
the corner behind the ikons. It would have been absurd to keep it under
the mattress; the box, anyway, could be locked. But all believe it was
under the mattress. A stupid thing to believe. So if Dmitri Fyodorovitch
had committed the murder, finding nothing, he would either have run away
in a hurry, afraid of every sound, as always happens with murderers, or he
would have been arrested. So I could always have clambered up to the ikons
and have taken away the money next morning or even that night, and it
would have all been put down to Dmitri Fyodorovitch. I could reckon upon
that.вЂќ

вЂњBut what if he did not kill him, but only knocked him down?вЂќ

вЂњIf he did not kill him, of course, I would not have ventured to take the
money, and nothing would have happened. But I calculated that he would
beat him senseless, and I should have time to take it then, and then IвЂ™d
make out to Fyodor Pavlovitch that it was no one but Dmitri Fyodorovitch
who had taken the money after beating him.вЂќ

вЂњStop ... I am getting mixed. Then it was Dmitri after all who killed him;
you only took the money?вЂќ

вЂњNo, he didnвЂ™t kill him. Well, I might as well have told you now that he
was the murderer.... But I donвЂ™t want to lie to you now, because ...
because if you really havenвЂ™t understood till now, as I see for myself,
and are not pretending, so as to throw your guilt on me to my very face,
you are still responsible for it all, since you knew of the murder and
charged me to do it, and went away knowing all about it. And so I want to
prove to your face this evening that you are the only real murderer in the
whole affair, and I am not the real murderer, though I did kill him. You
are the rightful murderer.вЂќ

вЂњWhy, why, am I a murderer? Oh, God!вЂќ Ivan cried, unable to restrain
himself at last, and forgetting that he had put off discussing himself
till the end of the conversation. вЂњYou still mean that Tchermashnya? Stay,
tell me, why did you want my consent, if you really took Tchermashnya for
consent? How will you explain that now?вЂќ

вЂњAssured of your consent, I should have known that you wouldnвЂ™t have made
an outcry over those three thousand being lost, even if IвЂ™d been
suspected, instead of Dmitri Fyodorovitch, or as his accomplice; on the
contrary, you would have protected me from others.... And when you got
your inheritance you would have rewarded me when you were able, all the
rest of your life. For youвЂ™d have received your inheritance through me,
seeing that if he had married Agrafena Alexandrovna, you wouldnвЂ™t have had
a farthing.вЂќ

вЂњAh! Then you intended to worry me all my life afterwards,вЂќ snarled Ivan.
вЂњAnd what if I hadnвЂ™t gone away then, but had informed against you?вЂќ

вЂњWhat could you have informed? That I persuaded you to go to Tchermashnya?
ThatвЂ™s all nonsense. Besides, after our conversation you would either have
gone away or have stayed. If you had stayed, nothing would have happened.
I should have known that you didnвЂ™t want it done, and should have
attempted nothing. As you went away, it meant you assured me that you
wouldnвЂ™t dare to inform against me at the trial, and that youвЂ™d overlook
my having the three thousand. And, indeed, you couldnвЂ™t have prosecuted me
afterwards, because then I should have told it all in the court; that is,
not that I had stolen the money or killed himвЂ”I shouldnвЂ™t have said
thatвЂ”but that youвЂ™d put me up to the theft and the murder, though I didnвЂ™t
consent to it. ThatвЂ™s why I needed your consent, so that you couldnвЂ™t have
cornered me afterwards, for what proof could you have had? I could always
have cornered you, revealing your eagerness for your fatherвЂ™s death, and I
tell you the public would have believed it all, and you would have been
ashamed for the rest of your life.вЂќ

вЂњWas I then so eager, was I?вЂќ Ivan snarled again.

вЂњTo be sure you were, and by your consent you silently sanctioned my doing
it.вЂќ Smerdyakov looked resolutely at Ivan. He was very weak and spoke
slowly and wearily, but some hidden inner force urged him on. He evidently
had some design. Ivan felt that.

вЂњGo on,вЂќ he said. вЂњTell me what happened that night.вЂќ

вЂњWhat more is there to tell! I lay there and I thought I heard the master
shout. And before that Grigory Vassilyevitch had suddenly got up and came
out, and he suddenly gave a scream, and then all was silence and darkness.
I lay there waiting, my heart beating; I couldnвЂ™t bear it. I got up at
last, went out. I saw the window open on the left into the garden, and I
stepped to the left to listen whether he was sitting there alive, and I
heard the master moving about, sighing, so I knew he was alive. вЂEch!вЂ™ I
thought. I went to the window and shouted to the master, вЂItвЂ™s I.вЂ™ And he
shouted to me, вЂHeвЂ™s been, heвЂ™s been; heвЂ™s run away.вЂ™ He meant Dmitri
Fyodorovitch had been. вЂHeвЂ™s killed Grigory!вЂ™ вЂWhere?вЂ™ I whispered.
вЂThere, in the corner,вЂ™ he pointed. He was whispering, too. вЂWait a bit,вЂ™
I said. I went to the corner of the garden to look, and there I came upon
Grigory Vassilyevitch lying by the wall, covered with blood, senseless. So
itвЂ™s true that Dmitri Fyodorovitch has been here, was the thought that
came into my head, and I determined on the spot to make an end of it, as
Grigory Vassilyevitch, even if he were alive, would see nothing of it, as
he lay there senseless. The only risk was that Marfa Ignatyevna might wake
up. I felt that at the moment, but the longing to get it done came over
me, till I could scarcely breathe. I went back to the window to the master
and said, вЂSheвЂ™s here, sheвЂ™s come; Agrafena Alexandrovna has come, wants
to be let in.вЂ™ And he started like a baby. вЂWhere is she?вЂ™ he fairly
gasped, but couldnвЂ™t believe it. вЂSheвЂ™s standing there,вЂ™ said I. вЂOpen.вЂ™
He looked out of the window at me, half believing and half distrustful,
but afraid to open. вЂWhy, he is afraid of me now,вЂ™ I thought. And it was
funny. I bethought me to knock on the windowвЂђframe those taps weвЂ™d agreed
upon as a signal that Grushenka had come, in his presence, before his
eyes. He didnвЂ™t seem to believe my word, but as soon as he heard the taps,
he ran at once to open the door. He opened it. I would have gone in, but
he stood in the way to prevent me passing. вЂWhere is she? Where is she?вЂ™
He looked at me, all of a tremble. вЂWell,вЂ™ thought I, вЂif heвЂ™s so
frightened of me as all that, itвЂ™s a bad look out!вЂ™ And my legs went weak
with fright that he wouldnвЂ™t let me in or would call out, or Marfa
Ignatyevna would run up, or something else might happen. I donвЂ™t remember
now, but I must have stood pale, facing him. I whispered to him, вЂWhy,
sheвЂ™s there, there, under the window; how is it you donвЂ™t see her?вЂ™ I
said. вЂBring her then, bring her.вЂ™ вЂSheвЂ™s afraid,вЂ™ said I; вЂshe was
frightened at the noise, sheвЂ™s hidden in the bushes; go and call to her
yourself from the study.вЂ™ He ran to the window, put the candle in the
window. вЂGrushenka,вЂ™ he cried, вЂGrushenka, are you here?вЂ™ Though he cried
that, he didnвЂ™t want to lean out of the window, he didnвЂ™t want to move
away from me, for he was panicвЂђstricken; he was so frightened he didnвЂ™t
dare to turn his back on me. вЂWhy, here she is,вЂ™ said I. I went up to the
window and leaned right out of it. вЂHere she is; sheвЂ™s in the bush,
laughing at you, donвЂ™t you see her?вЂ™ He suddenly believed it; he was all
of a shakeвЂ”he was awfully crazy about herвЂ”and he leaned right out of the
window. I snatched up that iron paperвЂђweight from his table; do you
remember, weighing about three pounds? I swung it and hit him on the top
of the skull with the corner of it. He didnвЂ™t even cry out. He only sank
down suddenly, and I hit him again and a third time. And the third time I
knew IвЂ™d broken his skull. He suddenly rolled on his back, face upwards,
covered with blood. I looked round. There was no blood on me, not a spot.
I wiped the paperвЂђweight, put it back, went up to the ikons, took the
money out of the envelope, and flung the envelope on the floor and the
pink ribbon beside it. I went out into the garden all of a tremble,
straight to the appleвЂђtree with a hollow in itвЂ”you know that hollow. IвЂ™d
marked it long before and put a rag and a piece of paper ready in it. I
wrapped all the notes in the rag and stuffed it deep down in the hole. And
there it stayed for over a fortnight. I took it out later, when I came out
of the hospital. I went back to my bed, lay down and thought, вЂIf Grigory
Vassilyevitch has been killed outright it may be a bad job for me, but if
he is not killed and recovers, it will be firstвЂђrate, for then heвЂ™ll bear
witness that Dmitri Fyodorovitch has been here, and so he must have killed
him and taken the money.вЂ™ Then I began groaning with suspense and
impatience, so as to wake Marfa Ignatyevna as soon as possible. At last
she got up and she rushed to me, but when she saw Grigory Vassilyevitch
was not there, she ran out, and I heard her scream in the garden. And that
set it all going and set my mind at rest.вЂќ

He stopped. Ivan had listened all the time in dead silence without
stirring or taking his eyes off him. As he told his story Smerdyakov
glanced at him from time to time, but for the most part kept his eyes
averted. When he had finished he was evidently agitated and was breathing
hard. The perspiration stood out on his face. But it was impossible to
tell whether it was remorse he was feeling, or what.

вЂњStay,вЂќ cried Ivan, pondering. вЂњWhat about the door? If he only opened the
door to you, how could Grigory have seen it open before? For Grigory saw
it before you went.вЂќ

It was remarkable that Ivan spoke quite amicably, in a different tone, not
angry as before, so if any one had opened the door at that moment and
peeped in at them, he would certainly have concluded that they were
talking peaceably about some ordinary, though interesting, subject.

вЂњAs for that door and Grigory VassilyevitchвЂ™s having seen it open, thatвЂ™s
only his fancy,вЂќ said Smerdyakov, with a wry smile. вЂњHe is not a man, I
assure you, but an obstinate mule. He didnвЂ™t see it, but fancied he had
seen it, and thereвЂ™s no shaking him. ItвЂ™s just our luck he took that
notion into his head, for they canвЂ™t fail to convict Dmitri Fyodorovitch
after that.вЂќ

вЂњListen ...вЂќ said Ivan, beginning to seem bewildered again and making an
effort to grasp something. вЂњListen. There are a lot of questions I want to
ask you, but I forget them ... I keep forgetting and getting mixed up.
Yes. Tell me this at least, why did you open the envelope and leave it
there on the floor? Why didnвЂ™t you simply carry off the envelope?... When
you were telling me, I thought you spoke about it as though it were the
right thing to do ... but why, I canвЂ™t understand....вЂќ

вЂњI did that for a good reason. For if a man had known all about it, as I
did for instance, if heвЂ™d seen those notes before, and perhaps had put
them in that envelope himself, and had seen the envelope sealed up and
addressed, with his own eyes, if such a man had done the murder, what
should have made him tear open the envelope afterwards, especially in such
desperate haste, since heвЂ™d know for certain the notes must be in the
envelope? No, if the robber had been some one like me, heвЂ™d simply have
put the envelope straight in his pocket and got away with it as fast as he
could. But itвЂ™d be quite different with Dmitri Fyodorovitch. He only knew
about the envelope by hearsay; he had never seen it, and if heвЂ™d found it,
for instance, under the mattress, heвЂ™d have torn it open as quickly as
possible to make sure the notes were in it. And heвЂ™d have thrown the
envelope down, without having time to think that it would be evidence
against him. Because he was not an habitual thief and had never directly
stolen anything before, for he is a gentleman born, and if he did bring
himself to steal, it would not be regular stealing, but simply taking what
was his own, for heвЂ™d told the whole town he meant to before, and had even
bragged aloud before every one that heвЂ™d go and take his property from
Fyodor Pavlovitch. I didnвЂ™t say that openly to the prosecutor when I was
being examined, but quite the contrary, I brought him to it by a hint, as
though I didnвЂ™t see it myself, and as though heвЂ™d thought of it himself
and I hadnвЂ™t prompted him; so that Mr. ProsecutorвЂ™s mouth positively
watered at my suggestion.вЂќ

вЂњBut can you possibly have thought of all that on the spot?вЂќ cried Ivan,
overcome with astonishment. He looked at Smerdyakov again with alarm.

вЂњMercy on us! Could any one think of it all in such a desperate hurry? It
was all thought out beforehand.вЂќ

вЂњWell ... well, it was the devil helped you!вЂќ Ivan cried again. вЂњNo, you
are not a fool, you are far cleverer than I thought....вЂќ

He got up, obviously intending to walk across the room. He was in terrible
distress. But as the table blocked his way, and there was hardly room to
pass between the table and the wall, he only turned round where he stood
and sat down again. Perhaps the impossibility of moving irritated him, as
he suddenly cried out almost as furiously as before.

вЂњListen, you miserable, contemptible creature! DonвЂ™t you understand that
if I havenвЂ™t killed you, itвЂ™s simply because I am keeping you to answer
toвЂђmorrow at the trial. God sees,вЂќ Ivan raised his hand, вЂњperhaps I, too,
was guilty; perhaps I really had a secret desire for my fatherвЂ™s ...
death, but I swear I was not as guilty as you think, and perhaps I didnвЂ™t
urge you on at all. No, no, I didnвЂ™t urge you on! But no matter, I will
give evidence against myself toвЂђmorrow at the trial. IвЂ™m determined to! I
shall tell everything, everything. But weвЂ™ll make our appearance together.
And whatever you may say against me at the trial, whatever evidence you
give, IвЂ™ll face it; I am not afraid of you. IвЂ™ll confirm it all myself!
But you must confess, too! You must, you must; weвЂ™ll go together. ThatвЂ™s
how it shall be!вЂќ

Ivan said this solemnly and resolutely and from his flashing eyes alone it
could be seen that it would be so.

вЂњYou are ill, I see; you are quite ill. Your eyes are yellow,вЂќ Smerdyakov
commented, without the least irony, with apparent sympathy in fact.

вЂњWeвЂ™ll go together,вЂќ Ivan repeated. вЂњAnd if you wonвЂ™t go, no matter, IвЂ™ll
go alone.вЂќ

Smerdyakov paused as though pondering.

вЂњThereвЂ™ll be nothing of the sort, and you wonвЂ™t go,вЂќ he concluded at last
positively.

вЂњYou donвЂ™t understand me,вЂќ Ivan exclaimed reproachfully.

вЂњYouвЂ™ll be too much ashamed, if you confess it all. And, whatвЂ™s more, it
will be no use at all, for I shall say straight out that I never said
anything of the sort to you, and that you are either ill (and it looks
like it, too), or that youвЂ™re so sorry for your brother that you are
sacrificing yourself to save him and have invented it all against me, for
youвЂ™ve always thought no more of me than if IвЂ™d been a fly. And who will
believe you, and what single proof have you got?вЂќ

вЂњListen, you showed me those notes just now to convince me.вЂќ

Smerdyakov lifted the book off the notes and laid it on one side.

вЂњTake that money away with you,вЂќ Smerdyakov sighed.

вЂњOf course, I shall take it. But why do you give it to me, if you
committed the murder for the sake of it?вЂќ Ivan looked at him with great
surprise.

вЂњI donвЂ™t want it,вЂќ Smerdyakov articulated in a shaking voice, with a
gesture of refusal. вЂњI did have an idea of beginning a new life with that
money in Moscow or, better still, abroad. I did dream of it, chiefly
because вЂall things are lawful.вЂ™ That was quite right what you taught me,
for you talked a lot to me about that. For if thereвЂ™s no everlasting God,
thereвЂ™s no such thing as virtue, and thereвЂ™s no need of it. You were right
there. So thatвЂ™s how I looked at it.вЂќ

вЂњDid you come to that of yourself?вЂќ asked Ivan, with a wry smile.

вЂњWith your guidance.вЂќ

вЂњAnd now, I suppose, you believe in God, since you are giving back the
money?вЂќ

вЂњNo, I donвЂ™t believe,вЂќ whispered Smerdyakov.

вЂњThen why are you giving it back?вЂќ

вЂњLeave off ... thatвЂ™s enough!вЂќ Smerdyakov waved his hand again. вЂњYou used
to say yourself that everything was lawful, so now why are you so upset,
too? You even want to go and give evidence against yourself.... Only
thereвЂ™ll be nothing of the sort! You wonвЂ™t go to give evidence,вЂќ
Smerdyakov decided with conviction.

вЂњYouвЂ™ll see,вЂќ said Ivan.

вЂњIt isnвЂ™t possible. You are very clever. You are fond of money, I know
that. You like to be respected, too, for youвЂ™re very proud; you are far
too fond of female charms, too, and you mind most of all about living in
undisturbed comfort, without having to depend on any oneвЂ”thatвЂ™s what you
care most about. You wonвЂ™t want to spoil your life for ever by taking such
a disgrace on yourself. You are like Fyodor Pavlovitch, you are more like
him than any of his children; youвЂ™ve the same soul as he had.вЂќ

вЂњYou are not a fool,вЂќ said Ivan, seeming struck. The blood rushed to his
face. вЂњYou are serious now!вЂќ he observed, looking suddenly at Smerdyakov
with a different expression.

вЂњIt was your pride made you think I was a fool. Take the money.вЂќ

Ivan took the three rolls of notes and put them in his pocket without
wrapping them in anything.

вЂњI shall show them at the court toвЂђmorrow,вЂќ he said.

вЂњNobody will believe you, as youвЂ™ve plenty of money of your own; you may
simply have taken it out of your cashвЂђbox and brought it to the court.вЂќ

Ivan rose from his seat.

вЂњI repeat,вЂќ he said, вЂњthe only reason I havenвЂ™t killed you is that I need
you for toвЂђmorrow, remember that, donвЂ™t forget it!вЂќ

вЂњWell, kill me. Kill me now,вЂќ Smerdyakov said, all at once looking
strangely at Ivan. вЂњYou wonвЂ™t dare do that even!вЂќ he added, with a bitter
smile. вЂњYou wonвЂ™t dare to do anything, you, who used to be so bold!вЂќ

вЂњTill toвЂђmorrow,вЂќ cried Ivan, and moved to go out.

вЂњStay a moment.... Show me those notes again.вЂќ

Ivan took out the notes and showed them to him. Smerdyakov looked at them
for ten seconds.

вЂњWell, you can go,вЂќ he said, with a wave of his hand. вЂњIvan Fyodorovitch!вЂќ
he called after him again.

вЂњWhat do you want?вЂќ Ivan turned without stopping.

вЂњGoodвЂђby!вЂќ

вЂњTill toвЂђmorrow!вЂќ Ivan cried again, and he walked out of the cottage.

The snowstorm was still raging. He walked the first few steps boldly, but
suddenly began staggering. вЂњItвЂ™s something physical,вЂќ he thought with a
grin. Something like joy was springing up in his heart. He was conscious
of unbounded resolution; he would make an end of the wavering that had so
tortured him of late. His determination was taken, вЂњand now it will not be
changed,вЂќ he thought with relief. At that moment he stumbled against
something and almost fell down. Stopping short, he made out at his feet
the peasant he had knocked down, still lying senseless and motionless. The
snow had almost covered his face. Ivan seized him and lifted him in his
arms. Seeing a light in the little house to the right he went up, knocked
at the shutters, and asked the man to whom the house belonged to help him
carry the peasant to the policeвЂђstation, promising him three roubles. The
man got ready and came out. I wonвЂ™t describe in detail how Ivan succeeded
in his object, bringing the peasant to the policeвЂђstation and arranging
for a doctor to see him at once, providing with a liberal hand for the
expenses. I will only say that this business took a whole hour, but Ivan
was well content with it. His mind wandered and worked incessantly.

вЂњIf I had not taken my decision so firmly for toвЂђmorrow,вЂќ he reflected
with satisfaction, вЂњI should not have stayed a whole hour to look after
the peasant, but should have passed by, without caring about his being
frozen. I am quite capable of watching myself, by the way,вЂќ he thought at
the same instant, with still greater satisfaction, вЂњalthough they have
decided that I am going out of my mind!вЂќ

Just as he reached his own house he stopped short, asking himself suddenly
hadnвЂ™t he better go at once to the prosecutor and tell him everything. He
decided the question by turning back to the house. вЂњEverything together
toвЂђmorrow!вЂќ he whispered to himself, and, strange to say, almost all his
gladness and selfвЂђsatisfaction passed in one instant.

As he entered his own room he felt something like a touch of ice on his
heart, like a recollection or, more exactly, a reminder, of something
agonizing and revolting that was in that room now, at that moment, and had
been there before. He sank wearily on his sofa. The old woman brought him
a samovar; he made tea, but did not touch it. He sat on the sofa and felt
giddy. He felt that he was ill and helpless. He was beginning to drop
asleep, but got up uneasily and walked across the room to shake off his
drowsiness. At moments he fancied he was delirious, but it was not illness
that he thought of most. Sitting down again, he began looking round, as
though searching for something. This happened several times. At last his
eyes were fastened intently on one point. Ivan smiled, but an angry flush
suffused his face. He sat a long time in his place, his head propped on
both arms, though he looked sideways at the same point, at the sofa that
stood against the opposite wall. There was evidently something, some
object, that irritated him there, worried him and tormented him.



Chapter IX. The Devil. IvanвЂ™s Nightmare


I am not a doctor, but yet I feel that the moment has come when I must
inevitably give the reader some account of the nature of IvanвЂ™s illness.
Anticipating events I can say at least one thing: he was at that moment on
the very eve of an attack of brain fever. Though his health had long been
affected, it had offered a stubborn resistance to the fever which in the
end gained complete mastery over it. Though I know nothing of medicine, I
venture to hazard the suggestion that he really had perhaps, by a terrible
effort of will, succeeded in delaying the attack for a time, hoping, of
course, to check it completely. He knew that he was unwell, but he loathed
the thought of being ill at that fatal time, at the approaching crisis in
his life, when he needed to have all his wits about him, to say what he
had to say boldly and resolutely and вЂњto justify himself to himself.вЂќ

He had, however, consulted the new doctor, who had been brought from
Moscow by a fantastic notion of Katerina IvanovnaвЂ™s to which I have
referred already. After listening to him and examining him the doctor came
to the conclusion that he was actually suffering from some disorder of the
brain, and was not at all surprised by an admission which Ivan had
reluctantly made him. вЂњHallucinations are quite likely in your condition,вЂќ
the doctor opined, вЂњthough it would be better to verify them ... you must
take steps at once, without a momentвЂ™s delay, or things will go badly with
you.вЂќ But Ivan did not follow this judicious advice and did not take to
his bed to be nursed. вЂњI am walking about, so I am strong enough, if I
drop, itвЂ™ll be different then, any one may nurse me who likes,вЂќ he
decided, dismissing the subject.

And so he was sitting almost conscious himself of his delirium and, as I
have said already, looking persistently at some object on the sofa against
the opposite wall. Some one appeared to be sitting there, though goodness
knows how he had come in, for he had not been in the room when Ivan came
into it, on his return from Smerdyakov. This was a person or, more
accurately speaking, a Russian gentleman of a particular kind, no longer
young, _qui faisait la cinquantaine_, as the French say, with rather long,
still thick, dark hair, slightly streaked with gray and a small pointed
beard. He was wearing a brownish reefer jacket, rather shabby, evidently
made by a good tailor though, and of a fashion at least three years old,
that had been discarded by smart and wellвЂђtoвЂђdo people for the last two
years. His linen and his long scarfвЂђlike neckвЂђtie were all such as are
worn by people who aim at being stylish, but on closer inspection his
linen was not overвЂђclean and his wide scarf was very threadbare. The
visitorвЂ™s check trousers were of excellent cut, but were too light in
color and too tight for the present fashion. His soft fluffy white hat was
out of keeping with the season.

In brief there was every appearance of gentility on straitened means. It
looked as though the gentleman belonged to that class of idle landowners
who used to flourish in the times of serfdom. He had unmistakably been, at
some time, in good and fashionable society, had once had good connections,
had possibly preserved them indeed, but, after a gay youth, becoming
gradually impoverished on the abolition of serfdom, he had sunk into the
position of a poor relation of the best class, wandering from one good old
friend to another and received by them for his companionable and
accommodating disposition and as being, after all, a gentleman who could
be asked to sit down with any one, though, of course, not in a place of
honor. Such gentlemen of accommodating temper and dependent position, who
can tell a story, take a hand at cards, and who have a distinct aversion
for any duties that may be forced upon them, are usually solitary
creatures, either bachelors or widowers. Sometimes they have children, but
if so, the children are always being brought up at a distance, at some
auntвЂ™s, to whom these gentlemen never allude in good society, seeming
ashamed of the relationship. They gradually lose sight of their children
altogether, though at intervals they receive a birthday or Christmas
letter from them and sometimes even answer it.

The countenance of the unexpected visitor was not so much goodвЂђnatured, as
accommodating and ready to assume any amiable expression as occasion might
arise. He had no watch, but he had a tortoiseвЂђshell lorgnette on a black
ribbon. On the middle finger of his right hand was a massive gold ring
with a cheap opal stone in it.

Ivan was angrily silent and would not begin the conversation. The visitor
waited and sat exactly like a poor relation who had come down from his
room to keep his host company at tea, and was discreetly silent, seeing
that his host was frowning and preoccupied. But he was ready for any
affable conversation as soon as his host should begin it. All at once his
face expressed a sudden solicitude.

вЂњI say,вЂќ he began to Ivan, вЂњexcuse me, I only mention it to remind you.
You went to SmerdyakovвЂ™s to find out about Katerina Ivanovna, but you came
away without finding out anything about her, you probably forgotвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњAh, yes,вЂќ broke from Ivan and his face grew gloomy with uneasiness. вЂњYes,
IвЂ™d forgotten ... but it doesnвЂ™t matter now, never mind, till toвЂђmorrow,вЂќ
he muttered to himself, вЂњand you,вЂќ he added, addressing his visitor, вЂњI
should have remembered that myself in a minute, for that was just what was
tormenting me! Why do you interfere, as if I should believe that you
prompted me, and that I didnвЂ™t remember it of myself?вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t believe it then,вЂќ said the gentleman, smiling amicably, вЂњwhatвЂ™s the
good of believing against your will? Besides, proofs are no help to
believing, especially material proofs. Thomas believed, not because he saw
Christ risen, but because he wanted to believe, before he saw. Look at the
spiritualists, for instance.... I am very fond of them ... only fancy,
they imagine that they are serving the cause of religion, because the
devils show them their horns from the other world. That, they say, is a
material proof, so to speak, of the existence of another world. The other
world and material proofs, what next! And if you come to that, does
proving thereвЂ™s a devil prove that thereвЂ™s a God? I want to join an
idealist society, IвЂ™ll lead the opposition in it, IвЂ™ll say I am a realist,
but not a materialist, he he!вЂќ

вЂњListen,вЂќ Ivan suddenly got up from the table. вЂњI seem to be delirious....
I am delirious, in fact, talk any nonsense you like, I donвЂ™t care! You
wonвЂ™t drive me to fury, as you did last time. But I feel somehow
ashamed.... I want to walk about the room.... I sometimes donвЂ™t see you
and donвЂ™t even hear your voice as I did last time, but I always guess what
you are prating, for itвЂ™s I, _I myself speaking, not you_. Only I donвЂ™t
know whether I was dreaming last time or whether I really saw you. IвЂ™ll
wet a towel and put it on my head and perhaps youвЂ™ll vanish into air.вЂќ

Ivan went into the corner, took a towel, and did as he said, and with a
wet towel on his head began walking up and down the room.

вЂњI am so glad you treat me so familiarly,вЂќ the visitor began.

вЂњFool,вЂќ laughed Ivan, вЂњdo you suppose I should stand on ceremony with you?
I am in good spirits now, though IвЂ™ve a pain in my forehead ... and in the
top of my head ... only please donвЂ™t talk philosophy, as you did last
time. If you canвЂ™t take yourself off, talk of something amusing. Talk
gossip, you are a poor relation, you ought to talk gossip. What a
nightmare to have! But I am not afraid of you. IвЂ™ll get the better of you.
I wonвЂ™t be taken to a madвЂђhouse!вЂќ

вЂњ_CвЂ™est charmant_, poor relation. Yes, I am in my natural shape. For what
am I on earth but a poor relation? By the way, I am listening to you and
am rather surprised to find you are actually beginning to take me for
something real, not simply your fancy, as you persisted in declaring last
timeвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњNever for one minute have I taken you for reality,вЂќ Ivan cried with a
sort of fury. вЂњYou are a lie, you are my illness, you are a phantom. ItвЂ™s
only that I donвЂ™t know how to destroy you and I see I must suffer for a
time. You are my hallucination. You are the incarnation of myself, but
only of one side of me ... of my thoughts and feelings, but only the
nastiest and stupidest of them. From that point of view you might be of
interest to me, if only I had time to waste on youвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњExcuse me, excuse me, IвЂ™ll catch you. When you flew out at Alyosha under
the lampвЂђpost this evening and shouted to him, вЂYou learnt it from _him_!
How do you know that _he_ visits me?вЂ™ you were thinking of me then. So for
one brief moment you did believe that I really exist,вЂќ the gentleman
laughed blandly.

вЂњYes, that was a moment of weakness ... but I couldnвЂ™t believe in you. I
donвЂ™t know whether I was asleep or awake last time. Perhaps I was only
dreaming then and didnвЂ™t see you really at allвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњAnd why were you so surly with Alyosha just now? He is a dear; IвЂ™ve
treated him badly over Father Zossima.вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t talk of Alyosha! How dare you, you flunkey!вЂќ Ivan laughed again.

вЂњYou scold me, but you laughвЂ”thatвЂ™s a good sign. But you are ever so much
more polite than you were last time and I know why: that great resolution
of yoursвЂ”вЂќ

вЂњDonвЂ™t speak of my resolution,вЂќ cried Ivan, savagely.

вЂњI understand, I understand, _cвЂ™est noble, cвЂ™est charmant_, you are going
to defend your brother and to sacrifice yourself ... _CвЂ™est
chevaleresque_.вЂќ

вЂњHold your tongue, IвЂ™ll kick you!вЂќ

вЂњI shanвЂ™t be altogether sorry, for then my object will be attained. If you
kick me, you must believe in my reality, for people donвЂ™t kick ghosts.
Joking apart, it doesnвЂ™t matter to me, scold if you like, though itвЂ™s
better to be a trifle more polite even to me. вЂFool, flunkey!вЂ™ what
words!вЂќ

вЂњScolding you, I scold myself,вЂќ Ivan laughed again, вЂњyou are myself,
myself, only with a different face. You just say what I am thinking ...
and are incapable of saying anything new!вЂќ

вЂњIf I am like you in my way of thinking, itвЂ™s all to my credit,вЂќ the
gentleman declared, with delicacy and dignity.

вЂњYou choose out only my worst thoughts, and whatвЂ™s more, the stupid ones.
You are stupid and vulgar. You are awfully stupid. No, I canвЂ™t put up with
you! What am I to do, what am I to do?вЂќ Ivan said through his clenched
teeth.

вЂњMy dear friend, above all things I want to behave like a gentleman and to
be recognized as such,вЂќ the visitor began in an excess of deprecating and
simpleвЂђhearted pride, typical of a poor relation. вЂњI am poor, but ... I
wonвЂ™t say very honest, but ... itвЂ™s an axiom generally accepted in society
that I am a fallen angel. I certainly canвЂ™t conceive how I can ever have
been an angel. If I ever was, it must have been so long ago that thereвЂ™s
no harm in forgetting it. Now I only prize the reputation of being a
gentlemanly person and live as I can, trying to make myself agreeable. I
love men genuinely, IвЂ™ve been greatly calumniated! Here when I stay with
you from time to time, my life gains a kind of reality and thatвЂ™s what I
